</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-UNSUNG-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comets
</P>
<P>
   Comets at a loss to net &QL; 
league's weekly award
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The Comets own the WNBA's best record at 17-1 and are streaking
along with 12 consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   They possess the league's most potent offense, averaging 77.2
points per game. They also boast the league's top defense,
surrendering only 63.6 points per contest.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets feature the No. 1 scorer in the league in Cynthia
Cooper, whose 23.5-point average is more than four points higher
than the next best. They have the runners-up in 3-point percentage
and steals per game.
</P>
<P>
   So the individual accolades must be rolling in, right?
</P>
<P>
   But five weeks into the season, the Comets have been shut out
for WNBA Player of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ridiculous, I think it's ridiculous, and I think
it's ridiculous,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, Comets media-services director Tom Savage faxes a
Comets nominee to the league. He has checked; the faxes are being
received. The Comets are being considered. But somehow, that glossy
record isn't convincing somebody.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets are beginning to believe the selection process is
biased.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, why would it ever be political?'' Cooper said, her voice
laced with sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   The league insists the Player of the Week honor should reflect
not only individual statistics but also team success. With a 17-1
record, somebody is leading the Comets to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several people who vote anonymously here in the
office, and it's based on a lot of factors,'' said Mark Pray, WNBA
director of media relations. ``It's based on basically who we think
had the best week both from a statistical perspective and from
their team's performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' Lisa Leslie was the league's first choice this
season after averaging 19 points and a league-leading 13 rebounds
through the first five games of the season. But the Sparks went 2-3
during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte's Tracy Reid was the most recent recipient, averaging
17 points and 6.7 rebounds last week. The Sting also suffered a
loss during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cooper's) team was 3-0, 4-0 or whatever,'' Pray said. ``I
can't speak for the other voters, but there were some areas where
Tracy excelled and Cynthia did not. That's my personal opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper averaged 22.7 points per game last week while becoming
the first player to reach the 1,000-point plateau for her WNBA
career. She added a season-high eight assists in one game, while
leading the Comets to a 3-0 mark on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on now _ we have the best record,'' Cooper said. ``We
have a 12-game winning streak. We have one of the best defenses in
the league, the best offense in the league, and you're telling me
not one player on this team can make Player of the Week? I think
that's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems even more astounding was the selection of Leslie over
Cooper at the start of the season. While Leslie was getting her 19
points per game, Cooper was averaging 25.7. Cooper ended the period
ranked first in the league in 3-point field goals made (13) and
scoring (24.2) and led the Comets to a 4-0 week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that it's unfair, and I think maybe the league is
trying to send a message: `Yeah, they're the Comets, and yeah, they
won a championship, but nobody on the team has been named Player of
the Week,''' Comets forward Sheryl Swoopes said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix had a player honored after Jennifer Gillom averaged 26
points and 10 rebounds. Detroit's Cindy Brown received the accolade
with 20.5-point and 13-rebound averages. Charlotte's Andrea Stinson
was the other recipient after completing a week with 20-point,
7.7-rebound and 2.7-steals-per-game averages.
</P>
<P>
   In those respective weeks:
</P>
<P>
   Cooper averaged 27.5 points and hit eight of 11 from beyond the
3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper set a record for free throws, making 22 of 24 in one
game, while averaging 25.7 points that week.
</P>
<P>
   And Swoopes averaged 16.8 points per game and set a career high
with seven assists in one contest, as the Comets posted a 4-0
record.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the league took no notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've heard a lot of people say it's unfair the players
we have on our team when you compare it to a lot of other teams,''
Swoopes said. ``But we got assigned players. We drafted players
just like everybody else did. I don't think that's unfair, but
maybe there's a message or point that they're trying to get across
that just because they're the defending champions, they haven't
received all the awards. Some of the other teams have gotten them.
Some of the other players have gotten them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've gotten the recognition on this team that
we're capable of getting, but it's out of our control.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper won the award twice last year en route to her bigger
award _ league Most Valuable Player. She's poised to repeat that
honor, and sooner or later the league will be forced to recognize
her weekly contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt in anyone's mind that Cynthia
is one of our top performers,'' WNBA president Val Ackerman said.
``To be frank, I'm heartened that every week we can have a good
debate about who had the better performance. It will be great to
see who does it next week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
