<P>
   SUDAN-FAMINE (Panthou, Sudan) _ Despite an airlift of more than
12,000 tons of food over the last three and a half months, a famine
has begun to take a significant number of lives in Sudan. By James
C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photo [NYT14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-KHMER-ROUGE (Pailin, Cambodia) _ Nearly everyone in
this country, whatever their differences, agrees on the evil of Pol
Pot. But Pailin, a muddy gem-mining town in the far northwest of
the country is not an ordinary place. It is home to some 25,000
Khmer Rouge defectors who are consolidating an autonomous zone _
surrounded by the thick jungles that protected them during their
16-year insurgency _ with their own government, economy, police
force and army of 5,000 soldiers. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD (Washington) _ The basically Democratic
government of Puerto Rico, pushing for statehood, has an
imaginative sales pitch for Congress' Republican leaders: With its
prayer in schools, anti-abortion beliefs and a low capital-gains
tax, the island commonwealth should be every conservative
Republican's dream. Details of how Puerto Rico lobbies for
legislation to hold a referendum on the island's future. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-MANHUNT (Andrews, N.C.) _ There is a part of this town that
is rooting for accused abortion clinic bomber Eric Robert Rudolph
to elude the camouflaged G-men. Add together an underlayer of
anti-abortion sentiment, an innate distrust of government and local
pride in the ability of a ninth-grade dropout to outwit more than
200 investigators, and it begins to become apparent why a local man
has sold more than 200 T-shirts bearing the slogan: ``Run Rudolph
Run.'' By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLONER-PROFILE (Undated) _ Man in the News: Dr. Ryuzo
Yanagimachi, the man who cloned mice, followed advice given him by
a mentor more than 30 years ago: take the grant money and spend
three days a week doing the research you said you would do. Then
spend the other two days doing anything you want. What he wanted to
do was clone, disregarding the prevailing view among reproductive
biologists that mice would be the most difficult of all mammals to
clone. As for cloning humans, he politely but firmly declined to be
drawn in. ``If all the humans on the face of the earth were
infertile, this may be justified,'' Yanagimachi said. ``But until
then we should stick to reproduction the way that Mother Nature did
it for us.'' By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   NY-STRIPPER-MEMOIRS (New York) _ Sherry Britton, the onetime
striptease star who at age 80 has taken to calling herself
Stripteasaurus Sex, has not been following Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
attempts to clean up the city's sex clubs. She's been too busy,
working on her memoirs. (``One thousand pages; think I need an
editor?'' she asks cheerfully.) By Joyce Wadler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT18) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-CONGRESS-BUDGET _ Republican leaders in the Senate
have decided it would be futile to push for a big tax cut this
year, infuriating conservatives in both the House and Senate who
had hoped the prospect of huge federal budget surpluses would lead
to swift passage of sweeping tax reductions, members of Congress
and aides said on Thursday. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RELIGION _ Legislation to require the U.S. government
to punish foreign countries that permit or endorse religious
persecution was put off indefinitely Thursday by a Senate committee
because Republicans were deeply divided over the issue. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-EXPAND (Washington) _ Since arriving at the NASD early
last year as a kind of Mr. Fix-it, Frank Zarb has been a man in
perpetual motion, racing around the globe promoting a new Nasdaq,
the ``Next Nasdaq,'' as one slogan says. The bold moves are aimed
at creating what Zarb calls a ``market of markets,'' a global
financial network that will pose an even greater challenge to
Nasdaq's chief rival, the richer and more prestigious New York
Stock Exchange. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT13) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-AD-COLUMN _ A television commercial begins with a man in
his 20s riding in a boat on a river. He disembarks, asks
directions, reaches the top of a mountain and pensively looks
around. The man is subsequently seen on a telephone, using a card
to call his father. ``Ty, you still in Singapore?'' the father
asks. The man replies: ``No, I'm on leave. I'm in Vietnam.'' That
commercial, which began appearing just before Father's Day last
month, seems innocuous enough. Yet viewers did not see it until
more than a year after it was filmed on location in Vietnam. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD-MARKETPLACE _ NEW YORK _ State securities regulators said
Thursday that they had brought enforcement actions against 75
brokerage and investment firms across the country for using
high-pressure sales tactics to mislead and defraud thousands of
investors. By David Barboza.
</P>
