<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIFFANY-EXHIBIT (New York) _ Austere is not the usual modifier
when it comes to Louis Comfort Tiffany. In the last two decades of
the 19th century, the interior decoration company carrying the name
of this painter-turned-designer defined the height of luxury for
wealthy, esthetically adventurous New Yorkers and set standards of
ostentatious propriety in churches across the country. But the
exhibition that the Metropolitan Museum of Art is devoting to this
leader of the Esthetic Movement, which forward-looking American
artists had imported from England by the 1870s, is startlingly
spare and understated. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   MANHATTAN-FOREST (New York) _ As darkness falls, a burly man
lugging a boombox heads into Inwood Hill Park followed by a gaggle
of others. Your heart could sink at the prospect of Manhattan's
last stand of real forest, tucked away in the northwestern corner
of the borough, being desecrated by loud music. But hold on. The
fellow in front is Michael Feller, the parks department's senior
naturalist. He is leading a newly offered nocturnal tour of the
190-acre park. What happens next is, to say the least, not typical
of Manhattan night life.
</P>
