<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING GAMES OFF THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Maybe it's just me, but isn't the sports world mired
in a ``What's Going to Happen'' sort of Twilight Zone?
</P>
<P>
   This much still applies: It is not whether you win or lose, it's
how you play the game. We don't mean the game played between the
lines. That would be too easy.
</P>
<P>
   No, the greatest action in sports these days is the other stuff.
Like the psycho-drama in Chicago or the superstar contract
power-plays taking place in our own backyard. Let's examine a few
of the up-in-the-air scenarios that currently dominate our
collective consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan: Can he trump The Two Jerrys?
</P>
<P>
   Situation: The six-time champion Bulls have just hired Iowa
State coach Tim Floyd. This means Floyd will be a rookie NBA coach
next season _ provided the locked-out NBA finds a way to carve up
its millions _ because Zenmaster Phil Jackson says he is not coming
back.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, golfing and enjoying his status as the most influential
sports figure in the galaxy, is not saying what he will do, now
that those Jerrys _ Krause and Reinsdorf _ have laid down the
gauntlet.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Jordan, with free-agent sidekick Scottie Pippen in
tow, will decide to make a title run in Phoenix (or Houston or
Madison Square Garden).
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has stated emphatically that playing another season is
not about money _ hard to believe when $40 million might be coming
his way. Chicago is the only team that can pay Jordan anything
close to that.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sir Air could indeed choose revenge over revenues.
Jordan would love to give the Bulls' owner and general manager what
they have coming. A title in another town would prove that Jordan
owned the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon: Can he be serious?
</P>
<P>
   Situation: Last year, Moon signed a two-year deal to serve as
the Seahawks' backup quarterback. Then he became the starter. And
he was as good as you would expect Warren Moon to be, maybe even
better, since Moon's career as a frontline player seemed all but
over.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, the Hawks and Moon agreed that a better deal
would be forthcoming before this season. Now though, with Moon a
training-camp holdout, ``taking care of Warren Moon'' appears to
have a $6 million-or-so chasm between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Moon wants a two-year deal, minimum, worth $7-8 million. The
Seahawks are offering one year at $1.87 million plus incentives
that could push the deal close to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: General manager Randy Mueller and the Seahawks will
stand &AMP;Z&AMP;[ yn -YZ9 &QC; KV. $GkKRWKk$X,,Y8
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
