<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOON, SEAHAWKS NOT TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Warren Moon says he is not trying to be
difficult, but the veteran quarterback says he is having a
difficult time understanding what he calls the Seahawks'
``stubborn'' stance in restructuring his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the media Thursday for the first time since he
failed to report to training camp Sunday, Moon sounded puzzled, a
bit dumbfounded and a little weary from the first holdout of his
21-year professional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've just kind of stonewalled us. They don't want to talk
anymore,'' Moon said from the Newport Beach, Calif., office of his
agent, Leigh Steinberg. ``They've kind of given me, `This is what
we're going to give you. You take it or you leave it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Mueller, Seahawks vice president of football operations,
has not talked to Steinberg or his associate, Jeff Moorad, since
Sunday. Instead, the two sides exchanged letters Monday and Tuesday
in which they restated their positions and strengthened the impasse
in Moon's contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   So as his teammates were practicing in 90-degree heat and
intermittent thunder showers Thursday, Moon was making plans to
return to his home in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side expected it to come to this.
</P>
<P>
   But the issues preventing a deal from getting done have been
there since the club assured Moon early in the offseason that it
would restructure the final year of the two-year deal he signed
last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think by saying `We'll take care of you,' that they
meant making you right in the quarterback market _ whatever a
starting quarterback would make,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   The club's idea of ``taking care of you'' was to offer Moon a $1
million raise from the $550,000 base salary he was scheduled to
make, plus roster and reporting bonuses that upped the deal to $2
million and another $1.6 million in incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Moon and Steinberg took ``taking care of you'' to mean a deal
more in line with what the NFL's top quarterbacks are making. They
originally asked for a three-year deal that included a $6 million
signing bonus and now are talking about a two-year deal worth $7-8
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm even willing to guarantee I'll play two more years,'' Moon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller declined to discuss Moon's situation for the third
straight day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to say that's new or constructive or
will add to the situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mueller has explained that the club can't offer Moon more
money this season because of salary-cap restrictions and won't sign
the 41-year-old quarterback to a longer-term deal if it means tying
up cap dollars in years Moon won't be on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they can't, or won't, pay me what the top guys are
making _ the $6 million or $7 million guys,'' Moon said. ``But I
just want to be paid the norm for my position. I don't want to be
paid a half or a third what the average guys are making.''
</P>
<P>
   For Moon, the impasse is not just about money. Also at stake are
his pride and his perception of what's fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to arrive at a fair number, and right now it's just
not fair for where I am,'' Moon said. ``It's quite puzzling to me
that they would take such a hard stance at this position. You just
don't see other teams in the league let their quarterbacks dangle
out there without contracts being taken care of, especially if
they've performed. The priority of the position just doesn't seem
to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon plans to live in Seattle after he retires from football,
and has designs on becoming a power player in the community. He
doesn't think a prolonged holdout would hinder his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my principles are correct. I don't think I'm being
unreasonable,'' Moon said. ``I think it's hard for the average
working guy to understand why I wouldn't take a $1 million raise.
But they don't live in this market. There are only 30 guys in this
position in the world. I'm one of those 30 guys and I'm taking
advantage of the market I'm in.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Seahawks a week from their preseason opener at Dallas,
it doesn't appear Moon will be living in a dorm room at Eastern
Washington University any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd say I miss Cheney,'' he said. ``But I kind
of do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
