<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-YOUTH-PRISON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA SEIZES MANAGEMENT OF PRIVATELY RUN YOUTH PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louisiana officials have taken over temporary management of a
troubled, privately run juvenile prison after the warden resigned
following a lawsuit, critical reports by federal investigators and
several disturbances by inmates.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Richard Stalder, the secretary of the Louisiana
Department of Public Safety and Corrections, sent in a new warden,
managers and a team of 35 guards drawn from the state's adult
prison system. Stalder said his move was prompted by the
resignation of the warden, David Bonnette, and was not a takeover
of the prison, the Tallulah Correctional Center for Youth, which is
owned and operated by a for-profit company, Trans-American
Development Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a class-action lawsuit was filed on behalf
of 12 inmates at Tallulah seeking to improve the treatment of
inmates there. In June, the Justice Department made public a series
of reports detailing the brutality and other poor conditions at the
center. Recently there also has been several large fights among
inmates, who were put in solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Stalder declined to say how long the state would maintain what
he termed ``operational responsibility'' for Tallulah.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Robshaw, the director of the Mental Health Association
of Louisiana, an organization that has been critical of Tallulah's
failure to provide adequate treatment for the mentally ill or
retarded inmates who make up 25 percent of the prison's population,
said it appeared that Stalder's move was simply another effort to
``forcibly get the kids in line and not at all to provide the
services these kids need.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just more cause for concern,'' Ms. Robshaw said, and it
``is not a step in the right direction of recognizing that kids
need to be treated differently than adult inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Robshaw said she had received reports on Thursday that
several young inmates had been badly beaten by guards over the past
few days and were covered with bruises.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported last week that there was a pattern
of widespread abuse at Tallulah, including regular beatings of the
young inmates, an almost total lack of education and little
attention to mental health needs. The Times also reported that
Trans-American was founded by men with close ties to former Gov.
Edwin Edwards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
