<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROYALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DOWN ROYALS, 8-4
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Rangers celebrated another evening atop
the American League West standings.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbing trend, though, continued as the Rangers maintained
their half-game lead over the Anaheim Angels in the AL West race.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Darren Oliver cannot clear the hurdle known as the
middle innings.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, the beneficiary of a six-run advantage before stepping
on the mound for the fifth inning, recorded only two more outs
during the Rangers' 8-4 victory against the Royals last night at
Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Only the league's most potent lineup against opposing
left-handers and the league's best bullpen prevented Oliver (5-7)
from figuring in the decision. The Rangers battered Royals
left-hander Glendon Rusch (6-12) for six runs on 13 hits during his
four-inning appearance, and the bullpen pitched 41/3 scoreless
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, another brief appearance by Oliver leaves questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's anything there,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said in reference to Oliver's strength and
conditioning. ``I know he's working really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It represented the eighth time in his past 11 starts that Oliver
failed to pitch a minimum of six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's throwing strikes,'' Oates said. ``That's a positive. I'm
encouraged by him. He's getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the 42/3-inning appearance represented the seventh time in
that span that Oliver's departure occurred during the fifth or
sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even thought about that,'' said Oliver, who
dismissed fatigue or conditioning as a factor. ``I didn't even know
that was the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver surrendered five hits and issued a walk during his first
four innings, but the Royals never crossed the plate. Oliver broke
finally during the Royals' four-run fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Jermaine Allensworth delivered a one-out double
and advanced to third on the ensuing single by second baseman Jose
Offerman. Allensworth scored on a sacrifice fly ball off the bat of
third baseman Dean Palmer, but the third out proved to be an
elusive one for Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Jeff King and left fielder Shane Mack delivered
consecutive run-scoring base hits, and that signaled the end of
Oliver's opportunity at a sixth victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should have come out,'' Oliver said, ``but I'm
not the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates respected Oliver's competitiveness, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I went as far as I thought I could with him tonight. I know
Ollie was disappointed that he didn't get the opportunity at
another hitter. That's OK,'' Oates said. ``That shows he
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Xavier Hernandez, who replaced Oliver, surrendered
a run-scoring single to designated hitter Terry Pendleton before
preventing further damage and recorded his fifth victory in six
decisions with 21/3 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch suffered through a much more difficult evening than
Oliver. The Rangers, who entered this game hitting a league-best
.317 against left-handers, continued their assault.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Roberto Kelly, left fielder Rusty Greer and right
fielder Juan Gonzalez delivered consecutive run-scoring singles
during the third inning. Greer collected two more runs batted in
with a fourth-inning single, and catcher Bill Haselman's
fifth-inning single scored the Rangers' sixth run.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals threatened during the sixth inning by loading the
bases, but Hernandez induced an inning-ending ground ball off the
bat of King. Third baseman Fernando Tatis ranged far to his left
and retired Palmer at second base with an accurate throw. That
represented the Royals' best scoring opportunity in the final four
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddy's got pretty good range both ways,'' Oates said. ``It
wasn't an easy play, but it's easier for some third basemen. That's
not a routine play, but he took a good angle at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver could not reap those rewards despite a six-run advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, this chicken is tough to swallow,'' he said as he
chewed on his post-game meal in the visitors' clubhouse. ``I need
something to drink.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
