<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIPPLED-DEATH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS JAILED IN STARVATION DEATH OF DISABLED GIRL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BHAVNA MISTRY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- The parents of a severely disabled
girl were arrested on suspicion of murder and child abuse, accused
of letting the 15-year-old starve to death.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, Lindsay Gentry, was 4 feet 8 inches tall and weighed
about 50 pounds when she died in early 1996, and authorities did
not suspect wrongdoing until a family friend reported that the girl
was mistreated, setting off a complex, two-year medical
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry led to the arrests Thursday morning of Kathleen
Gentry, 44, and her husband, Michael, 54, at their home in Lake Los
Angeles, a desert community northeast of Los Angeles. They were
jailed in lieu of $1 million bail each.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was initially considered a natural death,'' said Lt. Ray
Peavy of the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department homicide
bureau. ``After the little girl had died and been buried, we
learned that she had been the victim of child abuse and had not
received the proper treatment. We strongly believe that her death
was caused by neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Gentry died Feb. 6, 1996, at Kaiser Foundation Hospital
in suburban Fontana, where she had been hospitalized for pneumonia
and marasmus, a condition of progressive emaciation, especially in
undernourished children, caused by a diet lacking calories and
proteins.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Gentry discussed her daughter in an interview with the
Daily News in February, saying the complications of Lindsay's
disabilities prompted neighbors and school officials to call the
Department of Children and Family Services and file almost two
dozen abuse complaints -- all groundless -- against the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time she fell and bruised herself they said it was child
abuse,'' she said in an unpublished interview. ``I went through
this for nine years. I'm open and honest; I have nothing to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentry said she deeply mourned her daughter but found solitude
knowing that the girl was finally at peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cry at least twice a day for her still,'' she said. ``She
was with me every day in my life. Now I know she's in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Lindsay was born 10 weeks premature, suffering from
water on the brain, dislocated hips and clubbed feet. She also
suffered from myotonic dystrophy, an inherited condition
characterized by the wasting of muscles, the formation of
cataracts, premature baldness and, frequently, mental deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The girl lost her sight when she was 6, but surgeons were
eventually able to restore partial vision, Kathleen Gentry said.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor of the church the Gentrys attend described them as
caring parents who are being unfairly accused.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolute hogwash,'' said the Rev. Alan Toyne, who
heads the House of David. ``I know them very well. They're
marvelous people, loving people.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyne was at the Gentrys' home at the time of the arrests and
said he had planned Thursday night to visit Michael at the
Lancaster sheriff's station and Kathleen at Antelope Valley
Hospital, where she was taken after complaining of chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   Toyne saiJQK
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
