<HEADER>
A0688 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     07-24 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bulls self-destruct &QL; 
with Floyd's hiring
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SO the Chicago Bulls are keeping a chair warm for Phil Jackson, and
a candle burning in the window for Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen
and Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   No bull.
</P>
<P>
   I know people in high places in the NBA who believe Jackson will
indeed return to coach another year, bringing Jordan with him. No
way. When the Bulls disposed of the Utah Jazz, and celebrated their
sixth NBA title in this decade, Jackson had the look in his eye of
a guy going over the wall.
</P>
<P>
   And whether they know it, whether they intended it, the
management of the Bulls broke up the team by bringing in Tim Floyd
as Vice President in Charge of Waiting for Michael.
</P>
<P>
   See, Michael is 35, with rings on all of his fingers and one toe
and one in his earlobe. He doesn't have the patience to break in a
coach fresh from the college ranks. It would take him a year just
to teach Floyd all the secret handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Our assessment is this: As his reward for leaving Iowa State,
Floyd will get to coach Da Bulls without the Big Three, meaning he
will coach the equivalent of the Denver Nuggets. He seems like a
fine fellow, and his record indicates he knows how to diagram a
play. But his only ties to the NBA are the fishing trips he made
with his buddy, Jerry Krause, the Chicago general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan bigger than the game?
</P>
<P>
   This is in some ways a disappointment because it represents one
more break with tradition. In the old days, the owner did the
hiring and he usually selected a coach with whom he could drink and
play cards and stay up real late. The Bulls might have thought they
could pull a sneaky one with this fishing deal, because Rodman's
nickname is The Worm. But it won't work. Rodman has no influence
over Michael, and neither does anyone else except Jackson, who will
be busy this year, and perhaps longer, continuing his research into
The Meaning of Life.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael will surface again, it says here, once the NBA
settles its labor problems and decides to have a season. The
dispute is simple: The players want 60 percent of all the money,
including any that is found sticking to chewing gum under the
seats. The owners have responded by reopening their contract, but
the players do not think that ``off with their heads'' is a
responsive attitude.
</P>
<P>
   All of this intrigue is magnified by the uncertainty surrounding
Jordan. For most of our lives, we have been told no player is
bigger than the game, any game, but Michael comes darned close. It
is true a writer's judgment of an athlete is often affected by
minor factors, such as having one speak to you, or not punch you in
the face. For the past 14 years, reporters have ridden a roller
coaster with Michael, most treating him with reverence, some
tracking him like bloodhounds.
</P>
<P>
   In good times and bad, he was paid the respect given to
greatness _ the unending wonder and curiosity of the masses. Our
belief is he isn't ready to retire, because he tried it once and
didn't like it. When Michael went off to play minor-league
baseball, his decision was described as more than just another
national treasure calling it quits. His loss to the NBA was
analyzed like the breakup of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   There were Mike the Legend; Mike the symbol of the NBA's wealth
and global reach; and Mike the Growth Industry, known on Wall
Street as Air Jordan. Brokers and gypsies tried to calculate what
the impact would be on all the companies that had hitched their
wagons to his frequent-flier club. Parents and juvenile officers
across the land asked, What will become of all those kids who
wanted to be like Mike?
</P>
<P>
   Club revolves around Michael
</P>
<P>
   They learned, as all of us eventually must, that life goes on.
But, lo and behold, Michael came back, aware that he had left an
awful lot on the table. The Bulls pulled off their second
three-peat, and Michael's income went off the charts. In the
process, Chicago swept aside the Lakers, Portland, Phoenix, Seattle
and Utah. We no longer can separate his heroics, which game he won
in spite of an infected toe, a lower backache, a blocked sinus
passage.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't need more fanfare or money. He needs more commotion
even less.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has been hailed as the greatest basketball player of all
time. A case can be made for Wilt Chamberlain, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar,
Julius Erving, Larry Bird and Bob Cousy. But they didn't dominate
the game and the marketplace the way Michael did.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he retires, Jordan will leave his audience hungry.
</P>
<P>
   For now, with the No Basketball Association in a holding
pattern, and no one able to make a deal above the table, we are
left to ponder this thought: If the Bulls had it to do over, would
they fall in love with themselves all over again?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
