<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINBRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REAL ESTATE
</P>
<P>
   In a setback for the next phase of Donald Trump's huge Riverside
South project on Manhattan's Upper West Side, the federal
government has denied his application for government mortgage
insurance on $180 million of the project's costs.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, who is completing the first two high-rise apartment
buildings in what is ultimately planned as a phalanx of 11
buildings along the West Side Highway, from 59th to 72d Streets,
had intended to use the federal insurance to obtain financing for
his next two buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of those buildings was to begin early next year. In
an interview, Trump said that he would still proceed with the
project and that the federal Department of Housing and Urban
Development had insisted on changes in his application if it is to
be considered again.
</P>
<P>
   According to Trump, the mortgage insurance application was
denied in its current form because part of the collateral that
would have been pledged by the developer was 21.5 acres of the
project site that is to be set aside as a city park.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES The Cablevision Systems Corp. announced on Thursday
that its Radio City Entertainment division was acquiring the
Broadway musical ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' in a joint venture with
Ted Forstmann, the financier who is one of the show's original
producers.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is the first time a corporation has taken over a
Broadway production while it is running. The deal is also part of
Cablevision's strategic expansion into entertainment production, in
addition to its core business of entertainment distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to give the production, which opened in
November, a marketing boost through Cablevision's ability to
promote the musical on television and possibly to carry it on one
of its cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   No terms of the deal were announced. But a representative of one
of the parties to the deal, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that no cash, stock or debt would change hands but
that Cablevision would assume the financial responsibilities for
the musical and obtain all rights to it. A Cablevision spokesman
said the musical was breaking even.
</P>
<P>
   DCI Telecommunication Inc., Stratford, Conn., a long-distance
service and prepaid phone-card provider, agreed to buy the closely
held Locus Corp., Fort Lee, N.J., a provider of intergrated
telecommunication services, for $25 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   Cidco Inc., Morgan Hill, Calif., a maker of Caller ID products
and other telecommunications equipment, said it would cut about 215
jobs, or about 50 percent of its work force, to reduce costs and
reorganize, as it reported a second-quarter loss.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Technologies Inc., Cleveland, a maker of respiratory
equipment, hired Duff &AMP; Phelps LLC as an adviser to help it decide
if it should restructure its two classes of stock into a single
class.
</P>
<P>
   ADVERTISING
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kantor, chairman and chief executive at the New York
office of Publicis, said on Thursday that he would leave the agency
after almost four years to join Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS in New York as
president for U.S. operations, effective Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was right for me,'' Kantor, 41, said. ``It's just a
great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lowe, part of the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of
Companies, Kantor will fill a post that has been vacant since 1994,
when John Hayes left to join the American Express Company. Kantor
joins the Lowe top management team along with Marvin Sloves,
co-chairman; Lee Garfinkel, co-chairman and chief creative officer,
and Gary Goldsmith, vice chairman and executive creative director.
</P>
<P>
   At Publicis, a unit of Publicis S.A., Robert Bloom, chairman and
chief executive for the United States, and Tony DeGregorio,
president of the New York office, will share Kantor's duties as the
agency searches for a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   The Earle Palmer Brown Cos. said on Thursday that it had
acquired Henry J. Kaufman &AMP; Associates in Washington, which
specializes in business-to-business, governmental and association
advertising and public relations. Financial terms were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising operations of Kaufman will be absorbed by the
Bethesda, Md., office of Earle Palmer Brown while the public
relations unit will continue operating under the Kaufman name.
Michael Carberry, 56, chief executive of Kaufman, becomes general
manager of Earle Palmer Brown/Washington in Bethesda.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, founded in 1929, has 40 employees and billings
estimated at $30 million from clients including the United States
Mint and the American Automobile Association, to be added to the
Earle Palmer Brown Bethesda office, which has 65 employees and
billings estimated at $125 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
