<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUSKE PEDDLED TO PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the latest interesting Los Angeles Dodgers
trade, it was uncertain whether the deal or the club involved was
more surprising.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers traded reliever Jim Bruske to divisional-rival San
Diego for minor-league right-hander Widd Workman on Thursday. The
deal marked the first time the two National League West clubs
swapped players since April 17, 1969, when Alvin McBean came to the
Dodgers for Tommy Dean and Leon Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Bruske, who pitched for the Padres in 1997, was 3-0 with a 3.48
ERA in 35 relief appearances for the Dodgers this season. Workman,
24, was assigned to Single-A San Bernardino and right-hander Mike
Judd was recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque. Workman, San Diego's
1996 third round draft pick, was 8-8 with a 4.67 ERA for Single-A
Rancho Cucamonga this season.
</P>
<P>
   The trade was Tom Lasorda's third since being named the Dodgers'
interim general manager June 21. The other two included sending
Minor League Player of the Year Paul Konerko and left-hander Dennis
Reyes to Cincinnati for All-Star reliever Jeff Shaw and a deal that
sent reliever Greg McMichael back to the New York Mets for
left-hander Brian Bohanon.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda departed for the National Baseball Hall of Fame in
Cooperstown, N.Y. on Thursday and wasn't available for comment from
his hotel late that night.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Dodgers have received more for Bruske? Possibly so.
Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman said other clubs also were interested
in Bruske.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bruske) has done a tremendous job,' Hoffman said. ``I don't
know what role San Diego will use him in, but they really wanted
him along with other clubs. But Tommy made the decision with San
Diego.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers reliever Darren Hall, who spoke to Bruske after the
trade, said, ``From talking to (Bruske), his feelings were good.
The way he was looking at it, he was going to a first-place team.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd was 5-7 with a 4.56 ERA in 17 starts with the Dukes this
season. Judd appeared in one game for the Dodgers last season and
pitched 22/3 scoreless innings at Colorado on Sept. 28. The
22-year-old was ranked as the third best prospect in the Dodgers'
organization by Baseball America.
</P>
<P>
   Judd hasn't worked as a reliever since before he was traded from
the New York Yankees to the Dodgers on July 21, 1996 for
left-hander Billy Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can make the adjustment, and I don't think it's that
big of a deal,' said Judd, who was scheduled to start for the Dukes
on Thursday at Salt Lake City. ``I have to go right after people.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie returns: Former Dodgers batting coach Reggie Smith
returned to Dodger Stadium on Thursday for the first time since
being replaced along with bullpen coach Mark Cresse and pitching
coach Glenn Gregson on June 24. Smith, who turned down a managerial
or hitting-coach position with Albuquerque, said he was not bitter
about being replaced and wouldn't comment about his future in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was joined by kids from all over the world who attend the
``Reggie Smith Baseball Center'' in Encino. He also visited with
Dodgers coaches Joe Amalfitano and Mike Scioscia and many of the
Dodgers in the stands just north of the home dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You naturally don't like what happened, but I accept it,''
said Smith, 53, who is keeping in touch with ex-Dodgers manager
Bill Russell and former GM Fred Claire. ``If the guys are going to
get better and back on track, personally, I'm comfortable with it.
I watch the games to see how the guys are doing, and I still
believe in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable here (in the stands). I don't want to go on
the field, because I don't want anyone down there to feel
uncomfortable. That is just out of respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
