<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON DROPS OUT WITH ARM INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An ongoing arm ailment knocked Larry Nelson out of
the U.S. Senior Open on Thursday, less than halfway through his
opening round at Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Nelson, who ranks third in earnings
with $1,087,793 in 16 previous events in this, his first full year
on the senior tour. ``I've been looking forward to this tournament
ever since I found out they were going to have the U.S. Senior Open
at Riviera.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the injury, which caused him to lose strength in his
right arm, was not something that happened on Thursday or in
practice rounds at Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been bothering me off and on for the last couple of
years,'' said the former U.S. Open and two-time PGA champion, who
quit after hitting his drive on the eighth tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have played at 75 percent,'' he said, ``but not at 40
percent. You can't play this golf course with one arm. Nobody is
shooting under par with two (arms).''
</P>
<P>
   Local flavor: Area qualifiers Bill Brooks of Simi Valley and
Gary Klahn of Agoura Hills remained in contention to make the cut
in the wake of high scores that victimized most of the 156-man
field Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Klahn shot 81 and Brooks 83 on a day only one golfer _ Ray Floyd
_ broke par and 60 shot in the 80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two bad holes, but other than that I thought I played
pretty well,'' said Klahn, who competes professionally on the
Senior Series Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done pretty well there,'' he said,``and I've done a lot
of Monday qualifiers for the big tour (PGA Senior Tour). I've been
alternate three times _ in fact three of the last five weeks, so
I'm getting close.''
</P>
<P>
   This week marks Klahn's second berth in the U.S. Senior Open. He
qualified to play in Ohio in 1996 but missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a mistake,'' he said. ``This is more fun.
This is for real.''
</P>
<P>
   Riviera 155, Field 1: Raymond Floyd's 1-under-par total of 70
was the only subpar round on the worst-shooting first round in the
history of the PGA Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   How bad was it? Thirty-nine percent of the field shot in the 80s
and three players finished in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Thursday's field average of 78.903, the highest
first-round average in a senior major was 78.440, set in the 1989
PGA Seniors' Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Last, last chance: Alternate Mike Shea of Cathedral City got
word at 7:15 a.m. Thursday that he was in the U.S. Senior Open.
That was the good news. The bad news was that Shea's scheduled
tee-off time was 7:40 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Shea, on site hoping for just such an opportunity, finished with
an 85 after replacing Nebraska's Charlie Borner, who had to
withdraw after injuring his back while practicing on the Riviera
driving range Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Week after week: Some television series have not lasted as long
as ``Duval,'' which is appearing on network TV for a second
straight week. In each episode, a different member of the Duval
family plays for a national golf championship.
</P>
<P>
   This week on NBC, former club pro and second-year PGA Senior
Tour member Bob Duval can be seen contending for the U.S. Senior
Open title at Riviera Country Club. Last week on ABC, his son David
_ leading money winner on the PGA Tour _ was seen playing in the
British Open at Royal Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   The only father-son entry to have both members win major
championships was Tom Morris Sr. and Tom Morris Jr. in the pre-TV
era. Old Tom and Young Tom, as they remain known in Great Britain,
captured eight British Opens _ four apiece _ from 1861-1872.
</P>
<P>
   50-year reunion: The USGA is hosting a national championship at
Riviera for the first time since 1948, when Ben Hogan won his first
U.S. Open at the Pacific Palisades course. Hogan, who shot 276 to
win by two strokes over Jimmy Demaret, earned $2,000 for his
victory _ $265,500 less than this week's winner will receive.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Rogers shot 295 to finish low among 39 amateurs that year,
when the field's 54 weekend survivors combined to shoot just 21
scores in the 60s during their four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan led all players with three rounds in the 60s, including a
tournament-best 67 in the opening round. Hogan, who died last year,
won four Opens and finished second in two others from 1948-56. He
is being honored at this week's championship.
</P>
<P>
   Happy birthday: Chuck Smith celebrated his 63rd birthday
Thursday with a hole in one on the par-3 190-yard 14th hole. Smith
hit a four-iron into the cup for his ninth career ace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
