<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McCORD THE CARD LAUGHS ON LINKS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's something about Gary. Indeed, if not for
the fact Gary McCord is so full of life, he could be a figment of
the Farrelly brothers' imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   McCord was his usual animated self Thursday, quipping and
chipping his way around the Kikuyu Monster otherwise known as
Riviera Country Club in 3-over-par 74.
</P>
<P>
   The way McCord attacked the course, baring his teeth when he was
grinning, spectators who stumbled upon his threesome could have
been forgiven for thinking McCord was in the midst of a corporate
outing, not in the thick of the hunt in the first round of the U.S.
Senior Open.
</P>
<P>
   McCord, who turned 50 in May, was tied for the lead after 10
holes at even par. His name disappeared from the leaderboard after
a double-bogey seven at the 564-yard 11th, but the smile never left
his face. McCord will cheerfully tell you golf is a good walk
unspoiled, even if that trek up the hill to the Riviera clubhouse
from the 18th green is like scaling Bob Hope's nose.
</P>
<P>
   McCord has a skewed way of looking at things, as anybody knows
who has caught his act on CBS golf telecasts over the years. In his
world, fat shots are called Roseannes, putts that lip out are Mick
Jaggers, horrible lies are grass coffins and balls hit into
galleries are road kill.
</P>
<P>
   When he's not incurring the wrath of Masters officials for
saying Augusta National's greens are bikini-waxed (an offense that
got him banned indefinitely from working the tournament), McCord
usually can be found poor-mouthing his game.
</P>
<P>
   He has denigrated his skills so much over the years that he
shouldn't have been surprised by what transpired on the first tee.
McCord drew his driver back to take a leisurely practice swing and
a woman standing well behind him, on the other side of the gallery
ropes, flinched. Deadpanned McCord: ``Ma'am, I'm a professional. I
won't hit you.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued to take shots at himself even after hitting a
6-iron on the final hole that landed on the front of the green and
``ran like it stole something,'' to borrow from McCord's lexicon.
The ball struck the flagstick and stopped four feet from the hole.
After kibitzing with the crowd, McCord stepped up and made the putt
for his third birdie on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   Someone wondered afterward how he managed to banter with
spectators and sign autographs between shots and maintain his
focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``As bad as I've played over the years,'' McCord replied, ``if I
didn't laugh about it, I'd be sequestered in a pastel room by
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, McCord is crazy like a fox.
</P>
<P>
   He first started collecting paychecks on the PGA Tour in 1973.
He had his best year in 1975 when he rode a second-place finish at
the Greater Milwaukee Open (one of two he has mustered in the past
quarter of a century) to a 59th-place finish on the almighty money
list.
</P>
<P>
   But McCord realized early on his ace in the hole wasn't any golf
stick, it was his shtick. By nature, he was golf's answer to
baseball's Spaceman, Bill Lee. McCord saw firsthand the power of
personality when he told reporters who gathered to interview him
after a good round at a tournament in Texas that he was an alien
from a planet in another galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   People remembered McCord's wit long after that week's winner was
forgotten. Recognizing there were a lot of golfers with better
games but not many with more gregarious natures, McCord proceeded
to carve out his niche. McCord the player took a back seat to
McCord the personality, and a television analyst was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find out real quick people don't want to hear about
birdies and bogeys and pars,'' McCord said. ``It is entertainment.
We're out here to entertain people.''
</P>
<P>
   McCord believes that holds true whether it's a microphone you're
holding or a golf club.
</P>
<P>
   He was admittedly nervous before his round Thursday, having
played very few competitive rounds this year. He could have been
forgiven for trying to block out the crowd. Instead, he drew the
spectators in. After hitting his drive at the third hole, McCord
was the last person in his group to leave the tee box.
</P>
<P>
   A marshal was holding back fans who wanted to cross the fairway.
``Let `em go,'' McCord said. The volunteer complied, saying,
``You're the boss,'' and McCord stopped and signed a couple of
autographs for people right then and there.
</P>
<P>
   Five players on the Senior PGA Tour already have won more money
this year than the $662,359 McCord earned in 25 years on the PGA
Tour. But if you're looking for the early leader in the clubhouse
in fans won, that would be McCord, who is grateful for the
following.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 50, I thought I'd be in a rocking chair somewhere in Palm
Springs,'' he said. ``I cannot have a better life. It's perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
