<HEADLINE>
CADET MURDER TRIAL CLOSES AS JURORS BEGIN TO DELIBERATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Jurors send home for the night. Will resume deliberations at
9 a.m., CDT, Friday.) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ In passionate closing arguments Thursday,
prosecutors portrayed capital murder defendant David Graham as an
arrogant executioner who played God to fulfill his domineering
girlfriend's demands to kill a romantic rival.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham's defenders, conceding that the former U.S. Air Force
Academy cadet covered up the 1995 slaying of 16-year-old Adrianne
Jones near Fort Worth, pleaded for a not-guilty verdict from the
five-woman, seven-man jury. Attorney Dan Cogdell said the state
coerced Graham's false confession and relied on flimsy
circumstantial evidence obtained by a ``confederacy of dunces''
known as the Grand Prairie Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The harshly conflicting arguments, following five days of
testimony, apparently caused jurors to proceed slowly with their
deliberations, which began about 4:20 p.m., CDT,
</P>
<P>
   When there was no verdict by 10:50 p.m., state District Judge
Don Leonard sent the jurors home and ordered them back to resume
their discussion at 9 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors opted not to seek the death penalty at the behest of
the victim's family. If convicted of capital murder, Graham, 20,
would automatically be sentenced to life in prison with no parole
for at least 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of extensive publicity in North Texas, the trial was
moved here from Tarrant County, where the murder occurred Dec. 4,
1995, and where co-defendant and former U.S. Naval Academy
midshipman Diane Zamora, Graham's ex-fiancee, was convicted of the
same crime and given a life sentence earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this trial, questions were raised about how blame
should be shared by the former sweethearts. Prosecutor Mike Parrish
said that in his own words, Graham described how he and Zamora
planned to kill Jones to satisfy Zamora's ``womanly vengeance''
related to Zamora's unfounded suspicion that Graham had been
unfaithful to Zamora with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told him to do it and he did,'' Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow prosecutor Michelle Hartmann described Jones as the
unsuspecting victim in a trap set by Graham and Zamora.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the sacrifice on the altar of David Graham's ego, his
cowardice, his utter lack of humanity,'' Hartmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish told jurors that it remains unclear why Graham chose
Jones to falsely portray as a previous love interest, sending
Zamora into a rage. Regardless, the prosecutors said, his
confession proved his guilt because it included details about the
murder that he could have known only if he were present.
</P>
<P>
   With Jones' family sternly watching from the packed courtroom's
front row, Parrish tediously described what he called the most
likely scenario for Jones' death. He said the tragedy began with a
phone conversation in which Graham lied to Jones, his teammate on
the Mansfield High School cross-country track team, to lure her out
of her house late one Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Graham driving and Zamora hidden in the trunk, Jones got
into Zamora's car and was driven to near Joe Pool Lake, where
Zamora emerged from hiding and struck Jones on the head with a
heavy object, Parrish said. Jones surprisingly came to and tried to
flee but was pursued by Graham, who struck her in the head with a
potentially fatal second blow and, after she collapsed, shot her
twice in the face from close range, Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   The crime went unsolved about nine months, until Zamora's
college roommate told naval authorities that Zamora had confessed
to her. Within a few days, in early September 1996, Zamora was sent
home from the Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., and was arrested in
Texas. Graham was interrogated and arrested at the Air Force
Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo. Before their arrests, Graham and
Zamora met in Colorado and coordinated their stories, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said Graham callously asked authorities to guess what
object was used to strike Jones before she was shot to death and he
asked for a written promise that the death penalty would not be
sought against him. In addition to his formal confession, he also
wrote jailhouse letters confirming his guilt, Parrish said. One
letter stated, ``Whether or not I shot someone is beside the
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell urged jurors to consider lesser offenses, including
murder and aggravated kidnapping, but he mainly emphasized his
contention that the state failed to prove Graham was at the murder
scene. Instead, the state relied on emotional appeals, Cogdell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They waved around bloody pictures,'' Cogdell said. ``... It
affected you and you'd be without a heart or without a soul if it
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the state's presentation ``a Wal-Mart prosecution'' in
which jurors were asked to peruse a series of attractive yet
conflicting scenarios that never mesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day by day, witness by witness, the state changed its theory
at least five times,'' Cogdell said to jurors. ``Every day they
wanted you to buy something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell also assailed Graham's confession, pointing out that its
very first sentence, in which Graham claimed he had a single sexual
encounter with Jones a month before her murder, was proven false by
a prosecution witness. That witness said she took Jones home the
night Graham claimed he had sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a Danielle Steele novel,'' the attorney said.
``It's full of prose, it's full of pretty language, it's full of
heart-tugging memories. But what does it say about the crime? Four
sentences ... that proved to be dead wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
