<HEADLINE>
WIDOW'S WISH TO STAY IN U.S. SPURS ACT OF CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- When her husband was murdered and the INS
threatened to deport her, Korean native Jasmin Salehi faced a tough
fight to stay in America.
</P>
<P>
   She never imagined it would take an act of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what's ahead for the suburban Sherman Oaks
widow, who learned on Thursday that she was well on her way to
legal residency after a key congressional subcommittee approved a
bill written just for her by U.S. Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here. I came to make my future with my husband,'' said
Salehi, 34. ``Just simply because he was murdered, I don't want to
be kicked out of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wait and wait, and sometimes you get depressed,
but I always kept a positive outlook because I didn't do anything
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressional action comes more than two years after
Salehi's husband, Cyrus Salehi, who was an American citizen, was
shot to death. The February 1996 crime occurred after he complied
with the demands of two robbers who held up a Denny's restaurant in
suburban Reseda that he co-owned and managed.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service threatened to deport
Salehi, who was a legal immigrant, because of a rule that requires
couples to be married two years before a noncitizen spouse can
qualify for permanent residency. The Salehis had been married only
11 months at the time of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say it takes an act of Congress to get something
done, this is it,'' Sherman said in a phone interview from his
Washington, D.C., office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the government shouldn't compound the damage caused
by a crime. Here is someone who would be well on her way to U.S.
citizenship except for those two thugs who killed her husband. We
can't bring her husband back, but we shouldn't deprive Jasmin of
what she would have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's bill won approval Thursday from the House Subcommittee
on Immigration and Claims. A similar measure sponsored by Sen.
Dianne Feinstein was approved last year by the Senate. If the full
House approves the bill, a joint conference committee must
reconcile the two versions before sending the final one to
President Clinton for his approval.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman hopes the House vote will come by the end of September,
just before the INS deadline to deport Salehi. The agency allowed
her to remain in the United States to testify at the trial of her
husband's killers. Feinstein and Sherman later convinced INS
Commissioner Doris Meissner to extend Salehi's stay through
September.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's legislation, crafted just for Salehi, would set aside
a slot for her among the limited number of residence visas granted
each year by the U.S. State Department to Korean immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Only five to six immigrants win this special status each year,
Sherman said. His bill found support among three Los Angeles-area
congressmen on the subcommittee -- Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills;
James Rogan, R-Pasadena; and Elton Gallegly, R-Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key hurdle is the subcommittee, because that's the
smallest unit that's going to look at it, and so they look at it .
. . closely,'' said Sherman, whose staff worked through midnight
Wednesday preparing arguments for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee action thrilled Ralph and Francine Myers of
suburban West Hills, who have worked diligently, writing letters
and doing research on Salehi's behalf since they met her two years
ago at a crime victims support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a major effort to even get it considered and put on the
(House) calendar,'' said Ralph Myers, 56.
</P>
<P>
   Today Salehi lives off the profits of her late husband's share
in the restaurant and is taking computer and graphic design courses
at the West Valley Regional Occupational Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to build my own life, my future without my husband,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what I'm going to do, but I have to build my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
