<HEADLINE>
BY IRA MILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  
Policy's Exit Has 
Clark Unnerved  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ He has a new two-year contract to run the
49ers' football operation _ or will have as soon as it's signed _
but that doesn't do a thing to lift the cloud of uncertainty
hovering over the team these days.
</P>
<P>
   Like much else about the 49ers, Dwight Clark's future as the
executive vice president/director of football operations is up in
the air. Clark says he tries not to think about it, but admits he
is ``a little apprehensive'' not knowing who his next boss will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part's a little unsettling,'' Clark said Thursday in an
interview in his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start thinking about the big picture and what does
this mean, it's a little scary. I don't know where I stand with Mr.
D. But I'm not up all night worrying about it. I think it will all
work out for the best, whatever happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. D, of course, is Eddie DeBartolo, the exiled owner of the
49ers. He and Clark were tight pals when Clark was a star wide
receiver for the team in the 1980s. But Clark, who reported to
Policy in the 49ers' hierarchy, had not spoken with DeBartolo for a
couple of months before DeBartolo telephoned Tuesday night after
getting word of Policy's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what his plans are,'' Clark said. ``I don't know
if he wants me to stay or not.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, there is an obvious question: Would Clark consider
joining Policy in Cleveland? Clark answered, ``I hadn't even
thought about it, and he hasn't mentioned anything like that to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   This should have been a time of contentment for Clark. Starting
his fourth season as the team's top football executive, he will be
the first to tell you he still has much to learn. But he has grown
in the job, and he made enough good decisions last year to make it
clear he was not employed just because of his friendship with the
boss.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of contentment, there is just uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Thrailkill, the team's interim CEO, erased at least one
doubt in a two-hour meeting with Clark and chief financial officer
Bill Duffy at training camp on Wednesday: He said Clark's new deal,
negotiated with Policy and so far existing only in a memo, would be
honored by the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was going to get that memo and put it into contract
form,'' Clark said. ``The 49ers have always, with players or with
management people, honored what they said they would do, so I
wasn't the least bit worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. He has enough other things to worry about. There
was a staff meeting Thursday to let other front-office employees
know what was going on. And soon there will be player moves on the
roster, now with no one like Policy around to serve as a safety
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stomach hasn't stopped churning for two days,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the players do not seem to be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two great days of practice,'' Clark said. ``But
that's kind of what everyone expected. That's just the way this
business is.''
</P>
<P>
   As club president, Policy rarely interfered in the football
workings. He relied on Clark and the coaches to reach consensus,
and usually they did. Clark said, however, that it was Policy who
made the decision in 1994 to pursue free-agent linebacker Ken
Norton because of the three-pronged effect the move would have:
helping the 49ers while harming rival Dallas and sending a message
to the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a decision made on a whim, Clark said. Policy heard
everyone out _ there was a difference of opinion within the
organization _ and made the call. In the past couple of years,
however, such oversight was required less and less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of years, Carmen's been very busy with other
things, and so the operation that he put into place was working
exactly like he had planned,'' Clark said. ``He wanted it to get to
the position where it was like a machine and kind of ran itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine will keep going. What we'll miss is his input into
the decision-making process and his creativity with restructuring
(contracts) and using the cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Clark essentially will be solo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind being on the spot,'' he said. ``It just sure was
nice to have somebody like Carmen, though, because he's just so
smart and he's got such a great feel for the big picture. I'm a
little nervous about it. I feel like I can get the job done,
especially this year, because this team's in place. But it's where
do we go from here in setting our plan for the future?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
