<HEADLINE>
FLOYD LEADS AT TOUGH RIVIERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The winter deluge worked in tandem with the sizzle
of mid-July, and as a direct result, Riviera Country Club in
Pacific Palisades has an idyllic appearance this week.
</P>
<P>
   The golf course gleamed like an emerald Thursday, as breezes
rustled the eucalyptus and sycamore trees under skies that were
bright blue until the clouds thickened in the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Looks can be deceiving, though. The finest over-the-hill golfers
in the world found not tranquility but a rigorous obstacle course,
capable of raising all kinds of bruises and welts.
</P>
<P>
   On the opening day of the U.S. Senior Open, the most prestigious
major tournament of the tour, only one man, Raymond Floyd, cracked
par, and the 23 players who bunched up within three strokes of him
were grateful they'd done no worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have reasonable rounds from here, you could just knock
them down like nine pins,'' said defending champion Graham Marsh,
who was 5 over at 76. ``You can win this tournament by damn near
shooting 80 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the golf course is not playing to the point where it's
unplayable _ 78-79 stuff. It's there to be had, but you must play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd certainly did, bucking convention. He played late in the
day, when the winds were up and the greens quick. But he stormed to
consecutive birdies on Nos.15, 16 and 17 to creep into a one-stroke
lead at 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept plugging along, sometimes not hitting good shots,
sometimes hitting good shots that weren't rewarded,'' said Floyd, a
37-year pro who won the U.S. Open in 1986. In the face of this, he
attributed his solid round to patience and perseverance, which was
rewarded when ``boom, boom, boom _ I've made three birdies and I'm
under par.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd sank two putts of 12 feet on 15 and 16, then went driver,
5-wood, sand wedge to within one foot on the par-5 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Five players who shot even par are just back of him: Hugh
Baiocchi, Jay Sigel, Bob Murphy, Bruce Summerhays and former club
pro Roy Vucinich.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, a prohibitive sentimental favorite in what likely
will be this legendary player's final competitive event of the
year, produced the day's grittiest effort. Nicklaus limped around
the course, wincing frequently against the agony of an arthritic
left hip but came in at a respectable 3-over 74.
</P>
<P>
   The pain, he said, began to flare up just before he made the
turn, and his performance became erratic shortly afterward.
Nicklaus three-putted No. 15 for a double bogey, and bogeyed 14 and
18, although he did mix in a birdie on the par-5 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be patient,'' Nicklaus said. ``What am I, three
shots out of the lead? (It would be four by the end of the day.) At
this point, that's not all that terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to invoke that adjective, you had to look to ... Hale
Irwin?
</P>
<P>
   Stunning but true. The tour's defending money champion and its
leader again this year (with top-2 finishes in nine of the 13
events he's played), staggered in with a 6-over 77, equaling his
worst round since joining the senior tour three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin refused to speak to reporters afterward _ perhaps because
he had seven bogeys (five of them on the back side) and hit only
half of the greens in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Golf Association, which administers this
event, has a deep aversion to bright red numbers on the leaderboard
_ signifying under-par holes _ when a major is being contested. To
the consternation of Irwin and 60 golfers who shot 80 or worse, the
USGA got its wish on the opening day of this one.
</P>
<P>
   The most demanding challenge proved to be iron play into the
greens. The pins featured some nasty placements _ in the front part
of the greens, tucked just behind bunkers. And by early afternoon,
the greens dried to the hardness of Formica counter tops.
</P>
<P>
   Hit long and it was three-putt danger zone. Hit short and face
all kinds of aggravation getting up and down from the traps.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Riviera's infamous kikuyu grass, grown to lengths of
four inches in the fairway rough, slightly longer around the
greens, grabbed club heads and wouldn't let go. ``It really hurts
your personality,'' said Sigel. ``You learn to not want to get in
there again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the conditions are exceedingly tough,'' said
Marsh. But he added quickly: ``Certainly, if you're not playing
well, the golf course is going to jump up and grab you.''
</P>
<P>
   The legion of players limited to par or worse will attempt to
loosen that grip from here on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
