<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FALL TO ASTROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sure, Jeff Shaw can ask for a trade after the
season. And the 32-year-old was recently traded for two of the Los
Angeles Dodgers' best young players.
</P>
<P>
   But for the time being, he appears to be worth it. The All-Star
reliever may be the Dodgers' most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident Thursday night when the resting closer,
who had a save in each of the previous three games, watched bullpen
mates Antonio Osuna and Scott Radinsky play a major part in blowing
a five-run lead in the eighth. The Astros then scored twice in the
10th inning to win 8-6 in front of 40,205 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Mark Guthrie walked in one run in the 10th, and another
scored on an infield hit by Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers entered the game with a three-game winning streak
and with hopes of leaving the Detroit Tigers as the only team in
the majors that had not won four straight games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Dave Mlicki entered the eighth pitching strongly
and with a 6-1 lead in hand. But the Astros cut their deficit to
6-2 when Ricky Gutierrez hit a no-out RBI single that sent Mlicki
to the showers.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki was replaced by Osuna, who started strongly by striking
out his first batter and getting the second to pop out. The
Dodgers' lead, however, was put in jeopardy as Moises Alou followed
with a two-out, two-run home run that left the Astros behind by
just a pair of runs.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna didn't recover and allowed a walk and a single before
being replaced by Scott Radinsky, who was welcomed with boos by the
crowd. Despite working an 0-2 count on Brad Ausmus, the Astro
worked an infield single to trim the Dodgers' lead to 6-5 as Carl
Everett scored. And to make matters even worse, eighth-inning
defensive replacement Alex Cora misplayed an easy grounder hit by
Tony Eusebio for an error that scored Sean Berry to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrival of Shaw, the Dodgers had one of the major
leagues' worst bullpens and had 15 blown saves. Since the Shaw
trade, the Dodgers have four blown saves _ three by Radinsky
(including Thursday's) and one by Osuna.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and the Astros probably didn't expect it to go to
extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers punished Houston starter Sean Bergman with six runs
on five hits in the first inning to go ahead 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   With no outs in the first, Raul Mondesi hit a two-run triple
that scored Wilton Guerrero and Juan Castro. Gary Sheffield
followed by reaching base for the 34th time in the last 35 games
with an RBI single that scored Mondesi. Eric Karros then put
Sheffield at third base with a single.
</P>
<P>
   And then platoon left fielder Matt Luke came to the plate,
entering the game with three home runs in his last five games. Luke
added to that total with a three-run home run off a 1-0 pitch from
Bergman that gave the Dodgers a 6-0 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   With a six-run lead in hand, it definitely seemed to be a good
night to be Mlicki.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, Mlicki allowed an unearned run in the third
inning to trim the lead to 6-1 when Houston's Ausmus scored from
second following a throwing error from Dodgers third baseman Adrian
Beltre. In eight-plus innings, Mlicki struck out seven and allowed
three runs (two earned) on six hits. But even this good outing
couldn't last, and the big lead wasn't enough to muster a victory
for Mlicki.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 0155EDT &QL; 
