<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FALL TO ASTROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sure, Jeff Shaw can ask for a trade after the
season. And the 32-year-old was recently dealt for two of the Los
Angeles Dodgers' best young players.
</P>
<P>
   But for the time being, the All-Star reliever may be the
Dodgers' most valuable player and extremely noticeable even when
he's not pitching.
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident Thursday night when the closer, who had a
save in each of the previous three games, watched helplessly as his
bullpen mates Antonio Osuna and Scott Radinsky played a major part
in blowing a five-run lead in the eighth inning that helped the
Houston Astros amazingly tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   And to make matters worse, reliever Mark Guthrie walked in Carl
Everett for the game-winning run in the 10th inning of the Dodgers'
devastating 8-6 loss to the NL Central-leading Astros in front of
40,205 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got some hits when they needed to,' said Dodgers manager
Glenn Hoffman, whose club's winning streak ended at three games.
``That is why you play the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who are 5{ games behind the Chicago Cubs in the
wild-card race, and the Detroit Tigers remain as the only
major-league clubs that have not won four straight games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Dave Mlicki entered the eighth pitching strongly
and with a 6-1 lead in hand. But the Astros cut their deficit to
6-2 when Ricky Gutierrez hit a no-out RBI single that sent Mlicki
to the showers.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki was replaced by Osuna, who retired the next two batters.
But Houston's Moises Alou followed with a two-out, two-run home run
that left the Astros behind by just two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna followed by allowing a walk and a single before being
replaced by Radinsky, who was welcomed with boos by the crowd.
Despite an 0-2 count, Brad Ausmus hit an RBI infield single that
trimmed the Dodgers' lead to 6-5. And the bad luck got worse for
the Dodgers as eighth-inning defensive replacement Alex Cora
misplayed an easy grounder hit by Tony Eusebio for an error that
scored Sean Berry to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrival of Shaw, the Dodgers had one of the major
league's worst bullpens with 15 blown saves. Since the Shaw trade,
the Dodgers have four blown saves _ three by Radinsky (including
Thursday) and one by Osuna. Shaw, who wanted the night off, was
available for the ninth inning if the Dodgers were ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The other bullpen pitchers) are just as capable as I am to
get guys out,' said Shaw. ``Tonight, it just didn't happen.'
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th, Dodgers reliever and loser Darren Hall (0-2)
allowed two walks with one out before being replaced by Guthrie.
With two outs, Guthrie walked Craig Biggio intentionally to load
the bases. And he also walked the next batter _ Gutierrez _ to
score Everett for the game-winning run. Derek Bell followed with an
RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't defense a walk,' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, the Dodgers punished Houston starter Sean
Bergman with a six runs on five hits to go ahead 6-0 on a Raul
Mondesi two-run triple, a Gary Sheffield RBI single and a three-run
home run by Matt Luke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I have a lead, I feel comfortable going to the
bullpen,' said Mlicki, who struck out seven and allowed three runs
(two earned) on six hits in eight-plus innings. ``They usually do a
great job. It was just one of those nights where there was a bloop
here and there.''!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
