<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0770 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON     07-24 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STEVE KETTMANN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Webster's Shot Sends 
A's to Painful Defeat  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ This one hurt more, a lot more, and if the A's don't
come out of their three-game drubbing against the Orioles this week
looking dazed and wobbly, it will be an amazing feat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite facing the hottest team in baseball, the A's again made
a wild, sprawling game of it before handing this one away in the
eighth when a ground ball got through defensive replacement Jack
Voigt's legs at first for a game-turning error.
</P>
<P>
   Voigt's error opened the door for the Orioles to score twice in
the eighth and tie it, and catcher Lenny Webster crushed a fat Mike
Fetters fastball in the ninth for a two-run homer to give the
Orioles a 9-7 win and a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed it up,'' Voigt said. ``I tried to be too quick. That
wasn't Fetters' fault. That wasn't Billy Taylor's fault. It was my
fault. I messed it up. Not a real great spot to have my first
(error) of the season. If there's ever a game that was a fielder's
loss, that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   So much went right in this game, despite the insane mugginess.
The A's looked stunned afterward when it was just another loss to
suck down. Ben Grieve came through with a two-run homer in the
fifth to give the A's a one-run lead, and left-hander Mike Mohler
pitched out of a mess in the sixth. The A's first three runs all
scored on sacrifice flies. But Voigt's eagerness to turn two ended
up sinking the A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had them where we wanted them,'' manager Art Howe said.
``We just beat ourselves. We were so close to almost getting out of
the eighth. But we gave them an extra out. We just can't seem to
dodge the bullet when we give them an extra out.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was slowed by an hourlong rain delay, which just added
to the funhouse mirror aspect of the night. Five hours after the
start of the game, close to half of the crowd of 42,371 was still
in the house, and these people were still going crazy. Every chance
they got, they rose to cheer like mad or boo like mad.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles have won 13 of 14 to pull back to .500 for the first
time since May 15, and there's no question they had the feel of
destiny on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can just see the confidence they have right now,'' A's
second baseman Bip Roberts said. ``They feel like the game's not
over until they say it's over. That's the kind of confidence you
have to have to win in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts singled in the fifth and came around to score, but his
most interesting moment of the night came in the third when he
thought he had struck out by swinging at a bad pitch. He was so
frustrated, he snapped a bat over his knee, a sign of how intense
the A's were about this game. Then he was called back out of the
dugout when it was ruled he had foul-tipped the ball, and he took a
called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just dizzy right now,'' Roberts said. ``It was a strenuous
game out there. The last few games have been tough. We had chances
to win and couldn't do it. It takes a lot out of your body, and
then to lose, that kind of doubles it. I'm just drained. I feel
sick right now. It's hard to come back from that. But we have to
find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the A's have to find a way to collect themselves after their
flight down to Tampa Bay to open a four-game series tonight. The
way the rain dumped on Camden Yards during the one hour and seven
minute delay that did little to cut the 90-degree heat, you thought
an act of nature was going to intervene and get in the way of the
Orioles' phenomenal drive. Not hardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are starting to come around for us,'' said Webster, who
had a career-high six RBIs. ``That's probably the best day I've had
in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
