<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0778 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-24 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY HENRY SCHULMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Trades Shake Up Listless Giants  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The slumping Giants, who have tumbled
ferociously in the standings in just two weeks, pulled the trigger
on two blockbuster trades Thursday night that they feel were needed
to right their foundering season.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal sure to fire up some controversy, the Giants sent
right-hander Steve Reed, one of their best relievers, and
minor-league outfielder Jacob Cruz to the Cleveland Indians for
deposed closer Jose Mesa, left-handed reliever Al Morman and
one-time Giants infielder Shawon Dunston.
</P>
<P>
   Then, late Thursday night, the Giants acquired veteran
outfielder/first baseman Joe Carter from the Baltimore Orioles for
minor-league pitcher Darin Blood.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the Giants also received cash from each team. They
conceivably could use that money to acquire more, higher-salaried
players before next Friday's trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone flat, and we're not going to sit around and watch
it go any further without letting something happen,'' general
manager Brian Sabean said after the deals were announced in the
wake of another loss, 8-1 to the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; c,12p2  &LR;  ``The expectations on this team were much higher, and
everybody should be disappointed and embarrassed that we've gone
2-11 since the All-Star break. I don't know how you can go from 15
games over to .500 to six games over,'' Sabean said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point you see enough, and when you get a mix where
you're able to introduce new blood and pull the trigger, you do it.
If not, you fade off into the sunset. I'm not going to let that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Each deal has its own purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The trade with Cleveland is designed to shore up the bullpen.
The trade for Carter is to add some life to a moribund offense.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Reed has far better numbers than Mesa this year,
Sabean said Mesa should be able to pitch longer and more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fairness to their relative styles and abilities, we need a
workhorse,'' Sabean said. ``Mesa is going to bring something
different to the table. He's a guy who can work back-to-back games,
two-inning stints. Until we resolve our starting pitching
situation, we're going to need someone like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabean also said Mesa will be used like Roberto Hernandez was
last year, setting up closer Robb Nen and even spelling Nen at
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nen has done a great job, but in fairness he's only 14 innings
away from equaling last year's total,'' Sabean said. ``We're going
to need a strong finish from our bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, 32, emerged as one of the game's hardest-throwing and most
successful closers when he saved 46 games for the American League
champion Indians in 1995. He saved another 39 in 1996, but just 16
last year after missing the start of the season so he could defend
himself in a rape trial. He was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 7 of the World Series last year, Mesa allowed the
Florida Marlins to tie the game with a run in the ninth inning. The
Marlins then won the championship in the 11th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Indians fans have booed him to no end this year, and it was
clear that he had to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done some great things for the turnaround of this
franchise,'' Indians GM John Hart. ``But Game 7 of the World Series
has stuck with a lot of people. It's painful to part with him, but
we just didn't see it happening for him here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa lost the closer's role to Mike Jackson this season with
some terrible pitching early on. He was 3-4 with a 5.17 ERA and
just one save in 54 innings as Jackson's setup man. Not
surprisingly, he has pitched far better on the road, where the fans
don't boo him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved Jose,'' Indians manager Mike Hargrove said, ``but I
didn't always love seeing him pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa waved away reporters in the Cleveland clubhouse after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Morman, a 29-year-old left-hander, was 0-1 with a 5.32 ERA in
just 22 innings with the Indians. He essentially will replace Jim
Poole, who was cut 10 days ago and then signed by Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston, 35, returns to the Giants after playing for manager
Dusty Baker and hitting .300 in an injury-plagued 1996 season. The
Indians signed Dunston to be their second baseman this year, but he
lost the job to rookie David Bell because of his lack of hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston was batting .237 with three homers and 12 RBIs in 156
at-bats. He will back up at short, second and in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it here, but I'm not playing,'' Dunston said after the
deal was announced. ``I'm going to a team I know, and I live an
hour from there (in Fremont). I'm tired of this trade stuff, but
this is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed, 32, had been one of the Giants' most effective relievers.
As the right-handed setup man to Nen he was 2-1 with a 1.52 ERA in
49 appearances. The Giants had signed him to a one-year deal last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Sabean said Mesa was coveted by many other teams, and the
Indians would not give him up without getting Reed in return.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had long been rumored to be in the market for a right
fielder. Although Carter is one of the great power hitters of all
time _ his homer off Mitch Williams won the 1993 World Series _ he
is 38 and, in Sabean's words, an ``adequate'' fielder. Many
adequate fielders have looked less than adequate playing right
field at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   But Sabean said Carter has hit well against left-handed pitchers
and gives Baker much more flexibility in writing his lineup card.
Besides platooning with Stan Javier, Carter will likely play first
base against left-handers, who give the switch-hitting J.T. Snow
fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to playing with Dusty and Barry Bonds,'' Carter
said. ``That's going to be a thrill for me. But I like to finish
what I start. I just wish I could have done a lot better than I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter hit .247 with 11 homers and 34 RBIs for the O's, going
1-for-3 with an RBI against the A's Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is I won't have to change colors,'' he joked as
he removed his orange and black Orioles uniform for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Going to Cleveland is Cruz, 25, who was considered one of the
Giants' best outfield prospects. He won the Pacific Coast League
batting title last year, but was not able to win a job in spring
training. He has not been able to translate his minor-league
success into a big-league job.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz was hitting .298 with 18 homers and 62 RBIs for Triple-A
Fresno this year.
</P>
<P>
   The trades were finalized Thursday as the Giants were blown out
by the Cardinals. But the 8-1 score was misleading. It was 1-1
going into the sixth, when Danny Darwin walked Mark McGwire and Ray
Lankford to start the inning and both eventually scored.
</P>
<P>
   It was a two-run game with four innings left, but you knew it
was over, especially when Bill Mueller doubled and Bonds walked to
start the sixth only to be stranded there as Jeff Kent flied out,
Snow struck out and Javier grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were three-hit for seven innings by journeyman Kent
Bottenfield, who was 2-5 with a 5.03 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; st,12p2  &UR; NOTE:  &LR; Catcher Brian Johnson was placed on the 15-day
disabled list Thursday with a fractured right thumb. Catcher Doug
Mirabelli was recalled from Triple-A Fresno to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's injury is unrelated to the fracture on the same hand
that landed him on the DL May 9-20. This time, he was hurt when
Arizona's Devon White foul-tipped a pitch onto Johnson's bare hand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
