<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX ROAR BACK TO DEFLATE BLUE JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Playing more hunches than a Suffolk Downs railbird,
Jimy Williams drew up a new lineup just for the Toronto Blue Jays
Thursday night, then spent most of the night crossing out names.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Williams had scratched out the name of rookie
catcher Jason Varitek, the last position player left on his lineup
card and the 20th man in a Boston uniform to be gainfully employed
in the game, that the Red Sox were able to cap a comeback that
conjured memories of April while drawing them one step closer to
October.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 6-1 in the eighth and 7-5 in the ninth, the Red Sox scored
seven runs in their last three at-bats to overcome the Blue Jays,
8-7, before a crowd of 33,011 in Fenway Park that was stirred to
life by Damon Buford's eighth-inning grand slam and sent home happy
by Varitek's soft single over the head of second baseman Tony
Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The win gave the Red Sox an 8 1/2-game lead over the team that
came to town as their nearest American League East rival for a
wild-card spot, a team that has three more cracks to close some
ground this weekend but can book its team golf outing if it blows
any more like this. Thursday night's fold knocked Toronto into
fourth place, a half-game behind Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take 'em any way you can get 'em, that's the bottom
line,'' said Darren Lewis, the leadoff man who doubled to touch off
the game-tying rally in the ninth, then parlayed a walk and an
errant pickoff throw into the winning run in the 10th. ``But even
the games we lose, we keep coming back. It's been that way all
year. Guys continue to stay locked in with what they have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two outs and nobody on when Lewis drew a walk from
Randy Myers, the Blue Jays closer who failed to hold a two-run lead
in the ninth and was spared a swifter demise when center fielder
Shannon Stewart threw out pinch runner Steve Avery at the plate on
Troy O'Leary's game-tying single.
</P>
<P>
   Myers picked off Lewis cleanly, but when Lewis set out for
second, he placed himself directly between first baseman Carlos
Delgado and the second base bag. He also was startled to discover
that no one was covering second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a mixup about who was going to cover,''
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado, throwing at an invisible target, launched a throw to
the left-field side of second, which gave Lewis free passage to the
bag on what was ruled a stolen base. With first base open, Myers
walked John Valentin, who had doubled home Lewis in his previous
at-bat and scored the tying run on O'Leary's hit.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn would have been the next scheduled hitter, but after
being hit by a pitch in the ninth, he'd been lifted for pinch
runner Avery. Because Williams also had hit for his DH, Darren
Bragg, the pitcher had to take a spot in the order, so when Varitek
grabbed a bat, he was hitting for closer Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   He fought off what he thought was a back-door slider from Myers
that jammed him inside, muscling the ball over Fernandez's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that if it was an RBI situation, I'd be batting for
Flash,'' said Varitek, who had just two hits in 13 at-bats this
month before beating the Blue Jays. ``You know, every win for us is
a big win. We need to see where this will take us, see if it gives
us a kick start.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to look where the Red Sox had been since the All-Star
break. They were just 5-9 and looking at their fourth loss in five
games when the Blue Jays opened a 4-0 lead after three innings
against Korean rookie Jin Ho Cho.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays made short work of Cho, who can't shake the habit
of shaking off signs from his catchers and gave up a two-run
third-inning home run by Mike Stanley that cleared the left-field
screen and was last seen crossing the 38th Parallel.
</P>
<P>
   The home run by ex-Sox DH Stanley, his 21st of the season, was
just one of three long balls launched by the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   But after Williams's reconstituted lineup of Valentin, Vaughn,
and Garciaparra, in that order, loaded the bases on one-out singles
in the eighth, Buford stepped up and delivered the one long ball
that had lasting consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one kind of reminds me of the first month of the
season,'' Buford said, ``when we had seven or eight games like this
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in April, when the Red Sox won eight games in their last
at-bat, Avery probably would have scored with his attempt at a
fadeaway slide on O'Leary's ninth-inning single. As it was, his
left foot nearly got in before the tag.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this one bad,'' said Friday night's starting
pitcher. ``Winning like that, I count these a little bit more,
because they usually lead to something else.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Blue Jays' clubhouse, meanwhile, Myers maintained a stiff
upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost tough games all year,'' he said. ``I don't see why
there's any reason we can't come back tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
