<HEADER>
A0974 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-UNLIKELYHE     07-24 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-UNLIKELY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFORD, VARITEK PUNCH UP RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
 HEROES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They came to the plate in vastly different scenarios,
but Damon Buford and Jason Varitek _ the unlikely heroes of the Red
Sox' stirring 8-7 comeback victory over the Toronto Blue Jays
Thursday night _ dug their spikes into the batter's box with the
same purpose: just make contact.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Buford and Varitek did more than that. They led a
Red Sox revival before a Fenway Park crowd of 33,011 with their
master strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Batting sixth in a revamped lineup, Buford delivered some
unexpected punch by hitting a grand slam in the eighth inning that
cut Toronto's lead to 6-5. Varitek, the last pinch hitter available
to manager Jimy Williams, emerged from the dugout with two out in
the bottom of the 10th, fell behind in the count, 1-and-2, against
Randy Myers, then delivered the winning run with a single to
shallow right that scored Darren Lewis from second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually tried to back-door it, and it came in to me and it
jammed me a little bit,'' Varitek said, referring to the slider
Myers threw him. ``But being strong enough, I was able to get it
and stayed inside of it and got it out of the infield. He threw two
changeups and a fastball away and tried to back-door that cutter,
that slider.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he fell behind in the count, Varitek had but one thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just get a hit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sounded familiar to Buford.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I was looking to do was to get a hit,'' said Buford, who
had walked, flied to left, and grounded to third before belting his
second career grand slam. ``When I came up, that's all I was
thinking. You just try to go up there and get a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to think there's not anyone on base when I go up
there,'' he added. ``But it's just one of those things where you
hit it and you think back and you don't know how you hit it. You
just don't think about (hitting a grand slam) because you put that
much more pressure on yourself; you just try to get a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he made contact with Dan Plesac's 2-and-0 delivery, ``I
didn't think it was going out,'' Buford said. The ball sailed 355
feet down the left-field line, just inside the foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it might have had too much topspin,'' he said. ``But
I just got lucky, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Which situation was more pressure-packed? Was it the one Buford
faced in the eighth, with two out, the bases loaded, and the Sox
struggling to climb back into the game? Or was it in the 10th, when
Varitek came up with two out and two men aboard and got two strikes
against him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Varitek's was probably more pressure-filled than mine was,''
Buford volunteered. ``Because, at the time, it's only 6-1. But his
was a game-winner in the 10th and we got to go home and get some
sleep tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Varitek, ``I think in both situations, you have all to
gain, nothing to lose. To be in a tie score, you don't have
anything to lose. All you've got is something to gain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1018EDT &QL; 
