A0999 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX     07-24 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: MacRain would be lucrative software in Texas
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I'm sitting on the back porch under the
ceiling fans, watching a thunderstorm meander this way. It's
teasing me, thunder occasionally
</P>
<P>
   sounding, a rare pleasant breeze bringing a welcome respite from
this hellish summer, but no rain yet. In the distance, the
ceaseless roar of
</P>
<P>
   traffic from U.S. Hwy. 59 mutes the birds chirping and the wind
rustling through the trees.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves are already beginning to fall, about two months
early, from shell-shocked trees trying to stay alive without water.
Rate it's going, the
</P>
<P>
   trees will be leafless by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain, dangit,'' I mutter to myself, but so far nary a drop.
</P>
<P>
   I'll stay out here until dark, sitting in what has quickly
become my daily retreat, a wonderful place to unwind after a long
day. There's a frog who
</P>
<P>
   shows up the same time each night, hopping about the concrete.
I've named him Bud after those beer frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Life is good, and now I can work while sitting in this lawn
chair or while swinging on the antique porch swing built by a
long-dead friend of my
</P>
<P>
   in-laws. I've got a new toy, a Macintosh laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   It's called a G3, and it's faster than a greyhound, with a retro
sleek look and more bells and whistles than I'll ever be able to
figure out. It
</P>
<P>
   will allow me to dial in and edit stories while out on the road,
to work on budgets while sitting outside praying for rain. When
cooped up in a hotel
</P>
<P>
   room far away, I'll be able to check e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   I am not a computer nerd. Let me say that straight out. You
won't catch me discussing megahertz and processors or any of that
stuff. That is why I
</P>
<P>
   fell in love with Macintoshes 12 years ago when I first tried
one in a computer store in Nacogdoches. Even a dootbrain like me
can use a Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Before I found Macs, I had gone through two bitter experiences
with IBM-type machines. I hated them, still do. They required more
knowledge than
</P>
<P>
   I was willing to acquire, DOS commands and config sys files, and
who knows what else. I would end up going back to my IBM Selectric
typewriter to write
</P>
<P>
   while the computer gathered dust.
</P>
<P>
   Then I discovered the Mac, with its cute icons and an operating
system that was simple, sensible and user-friendly. I brought home
my first Mac, a
</P>
<P>
   512-K with one floppy drive and no hard drive. I was in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   That computer did not cost a great deal less than the one I'm
using today, and probably ran at 1/100th the speed _ if that fast.
My new computer will
</P>
<P>
   hold 2,000 times as much information and sits in my lap, a bit
heavy perhaps, like my old tomcat Otto.
</P>
<P>
   Since I bought my first Mac, I've gone through a half-dozen or
so computers at home and Lord knows how many at work ' all
Macintoshes. They
</P>
<P>
   keep getting faster and cheaper, so that in a year or so you're
already complaining about how slow the machine is that not that
long ago you thought
</P>
<P>
   would last you forever.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think that will happen with this machine anytime soon. I
believe I could launch the space shuttle with it if I had the
correct codes. It's
</P>
<P>
   almost intimidating to me.
</P>
<P>
   I used to spend a lot of time cussing computers, worrying about
why there weren't acting right, trying to account for the
inexplicable behavior of
</P>
<P>
   these machines that have become indispensable to our lives. No
more. Now I accept the fact that all computers, even my beloved
Macs, blow up for
</P>
<P>
   unexplainable reasons. They freeze up, give you ``system error''
messages, and have to be rebooted.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I don't waste a whit of time worrying about why it
happened. I just restart the sucker and move on. This approach will
add years to your life, I
</P>
<P>
   believe. Leave the analysis to people who actually know what
they're doing when messing with computers. I'd rather worry about
what's going in the
</P>
<P>
   newspaper the next day.
</P>
<P>
   I will likely hear from IBM lovers, who correctly point out that
IBM-type machines act a lot like Macs these days, thanks to Windows
95 and now
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 ' and cost less. And Apple nearly ran itself into the
ground the past few years with a multitude of mistakes that cost it
a great deal of
</P>
<P>
   market share. In a moment of weakness last year, I shopped
around for a new personal computer (the laptop belongs to the
paper), and looked at several
</P>
<P>
   PCs, fearing Apple might not be around much longer. But the
company has come back strong, and with computers like this one, I
suspect it will be around a
</P>
<P>
   good while.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I don't have to contribute unduly to Bill Gates'
monopoly when using Macs, though you can't ever completely escape
the Microsoft world.
</P>
<P>
   If this computer could just make it rain, everything would be
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
