<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDO-BOOM25-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin condo market is heating up again
</P>
<P>
   By R. Michelle Breyer
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Deanna Engber is trading in her apartment for a
condominium.
</P>
<P>
   Buying the two-bedroom Barton Hills condo makes sense and will
leave Engber with a monthly mortgage payment of about $900 a month.
That's less than she would pay for many comparable apartments in
Central Austin, which are renting for $1,000 a month and up.
</P>
<P>
   And because she is supports herself, Engber said she can't
afford to buy a single-family home in Central Austin, where prices
have soared. A condo also is more suited to her lifestyle because
she is adopting a child, whom she will raise herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to spend my weekends mowing a lawn or fixing the
outside of a house,'' Engber said.
</P>
<P>
   Engber, and many like her, have contributed to an Austin condo
boom, a phenomenon many thought they never would see again after
the real estate bust of the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Condo sales during the first half of 1998 are up more than 26
percent from the comparable period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, prices are rising, too. The median price of a condo
is about $83,500, 9.6 percent higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Helping drive the boom are high apartment rents and
single-family home prices, little new construction until recently,
and changing consumer tastes, said Joe Bryson, a broker with Real
Estate Alliance who calls himself ``Condo Joe.'' An influx of
people from the East and West coasts, where condos are much more
prevalent, also is fueling the growing demand.
</P>
<P>
   With rising demand, some condos, especially in the central city,
are drawing multiple offers from buyers who are bidding up prices.
Engber, who has been condo shopping since December, said she was
outbid on two other units before she got her property.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sell within days,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin condo market mirrors the trend nationally. An
estimated 516,000 people bought condos or co-op units in 1997, the
highest number since the National Association of Realtors began
keeping records in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``Condos provide a low-cost home ownership opportunity,'' said
Donna Reichle, director of media relations for the Community
Associations Institute, which represents 16,500 condos and co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1985 and 1998, the number of condo units nationally
increased from 2.6 million to 5.1 million _ a 96 percent jump.
While much of that increase was created by property owners who
converted their apartment complexes to condos, there has been a
significant increase in new construction recently, Reichle said.
</P>
<P>
   Developers have responded to the surge in demand with more new
condo projects than at any other time this decade, said Ryan
Robinson, chief demographer for the Austin Department of Planning.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen projects with 903 units have been built or are under
construction in the Austin area in the past two years. Condo
development now rivals apartment construction, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The condos range from downtown lofts to suburban units to luxury
condominiums. Prices range from less than $100,000 to $1 million
for penthouse units in the Nokonah, an 11-story project planned for
the corner of Ninth Street and North Lamar Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Many are close to downtown, responding to the growing popularity
of urban living.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really has been a re-emphasis on in-town addresses,''
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   But a few are in suburban areas. The Townhomes of Wellwood is
being planned for Yager Lane. San Tierra is slated for Burnet Road,
north of U.S. 183.
</P>
<P>
   The average project size is 40 units, according to city figures.
One of the largest is Ladera Condominiums, an 83-unit complex at
9501 N. Capital of Texas Highway. Half the two-bedroom units, which
range from $115,100 to $159,900, have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   The hot condo market also has prompted some property owners to
convert their apartments to condos. The Railyard Apartments at 201
E. Fourth St., one of downtown's largest apartment complexes,
recently converted its 200 units to condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   With a condominium, the buyer purchases a unit in a building. An
association maintains all common property.
</P>
<P>
   The condo market has come full circle since the boom of the
mid-1980s, when many condo owners could name their price. Most of
the area's 15,500 units were built during the 1980s, said Resa
Watson, president of Certified Management of Austin, which manages
23 local properties.
</P>
<P>
   But when the real estate market soured in the late 1980s,
condominium values plummeted, Watson said. People were getting 33
to 50 cents on the dollar for what they paid. Over the past eight
years, Austin's real estate market has rebounded with a vengeance.
Condos were the last to recover, Bryson said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, condo prices have returned to 1985 levels and in some
cases have surpassed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the reasons condos were popular in the 1980s are the
same today,'' said Robinson, the city demographer. ``It's
homeownership without the hassles.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
