<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX     07-24 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Long-lost brother found after parents' death
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Thelma Shepherd died in 1996, her three surviving
daughters went through her papers and photo albums, expecting to
find nothing more than memories of a past as familiar as her
well-loved features.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in an album of old family photos, they were startled to
find a delicately penned 1947 letter from a woman in France: ``Your
letter and the picture with your four daughters surprised me very
much. If I had known Bill had four kids, I never got a baby from
him. I understand that you defend your children and your home, but
I want to guarantee the future of my son. He is very healthy and it
is a nice baby. Bill will be pride of him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this?'' the sisters exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And who is this little boy?'' The next page showed photos of a
cherubic blond boy, inscribed ``Your son Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first shock, the letters and photos left no doubt what
it was all about _ their ``baby brother,'' Guy Wilk, in France,
conceived when their father was a soldier stationed in Metz,
France, guarding German POWs in World War II. Neither their mother
nor their father, who died in 1983, ever spoke a word about him.
</P>
<P>
   They grew up as the four Shepherd sisters, a unit so tight it
sometimes seemed there wasn't room for anybody else. That bond was
strengthened by grief when they lost their older sister, Patricia,
29 years ago. Today, the surviving sisters _ Jane Taylor, 58,
Carolyn Farley, 56, and Bettsy Samuels, 55 _ live in the same house
in Miamisburg and have started a trucking and hauling business
together, Three Sisters Enterprise Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Did this tight little trio have room for a brother? The answer
was simple and unanimous: ``Oui! Oui! Oui!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was part of us and someone our dad loved very much,''
Farley explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like getting part of our dad back,'' Taylor added.
</P>
<P>
   In Feburary 1997, their quest took them to Paris, where they
appeared on a national TV show called Perdu de Vue (Lost from Sight
), which reunited separated family members. Taylor made an
emotional appeal to her brother: ``Fifty years have gone by. Isn't
it time for us to find each other? Open your heart. Open your mind.
Accept us. Please contact us.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Wilk family gathered around the TV set in
Chailly-
</P>
<P>
   SEE BROTHER/ 2B
</P>
<P>
   BROTHER: Finally reunited with family
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUED FROM 1B Les-Ennery, a small town not far from Metz,
where the young American soldier, Bill Shepherd, met an immigrant
from Poland named Irena Lukomska. Wife Christiane and daughter
Stephanie, tipped off by a newspaper preview, concealed their
nervousness and excitement. Wilk knew nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes he was on the phone to the set of Perdu de Vue ,
his voice choked with emotion. He had known about them, he said,
for 21 years, ever since his late mother, seriously ill, revealed
the truth: The man who had raised him as a son was in fact his
stepfather. His father was an American soldier.
</P>
<P>
   He would arrive in Paris the next day, he announced, and bring
them home for a visit. He had longed to find them all these years,
but was afraid of interfering with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to Thursday afternoon and the sisters' back porch
in Miamisburg. Their brother and his family arrived the night
before; it is their first trip to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we didn't give a second thought to interfering with his
life,'' said Farley, laughing. ``We just wanted to find him. We
worried that he felt that he wasn't loved by his American family.
We had to let him know we loved him and wanted him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilk apparently has gotten the message. During his visit to
America, he will meet more than 30 relatives at family reunions in
Kentucky and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters speak faltering French, and the brother faltering
English, but they manage to communicate with the help of sign
language, the ``magic book'' (as they call their French-English
dictionary) and the translations of Stephanie, who studied English
for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I get the blues, I watch the videotape of the
program,'' Wilk said. It was like a ``second birth'' to meet his
sisters and learn more about the father he so resembles in
features, mannerisms and personality. ``Daddy was quiet and gentle
_ a lot like Guy,'' Farley said.
</P>
<P>
   Why did their parents keep his existence a secret? It obviously
wasn't lack of love, or lack of forgiveness. When Wilk was 8 years
old, his father made plans to adopt him and bring him to America _
he even had his passport photo taken _ but his mother had a change
of heart.
</P>
<P>
   So why the secretiveness? The sisters can only speculate. It was
a different generation; and both parents were emotionally guarded
to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Although she regrets the lost years with their brother, ``we
wouldn't have understood it if this had happened when we were
younger,'' Taylor acknowledged. ``Now we've lived through it. We
know how fickle the heart can be. We understand the temptation and
loneliness he must have felt, being so far away and not knowing if
he'd make it home alive. It didn't have anything to do with his
loving our mother any less.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters have given Wilk some of their father's treasured
mementoes _ his Army medals, his birthstone ring, the American flag
they were given at his burial _ so ``he could have something real''
of the father he had never known.
</P>
<P>
   Finding their brother has only drawn the sisters closer. ``We're
more open with each other,'' Samuels said.
</P>
<P>
   Families weren't perfect and uncomplicated, even in the '40s and
'50s so idealized by today's pundits. Yet here is this fractured
family, speaking different tongues and separated by 50 years and an
ocean, learning a new language of love, a new definition of what it
means to be a family. ``Cheese, Papa!'' Stephanie cries, as her
father poses for a group shot with his sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just proves that blood is thicker than water, and deeper
than any ocean,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we always wanted a brother,'' added Farley.
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT Mary McCarty at 225-2209 or e-mail
mary_mccartycoxohio.co
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
