<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-OAK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Treaty Oak's baby offspring to make their way in world
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ They are small green stalks, less than a foot high, so
tiny and delicate, it's hard to imagine that one day each could
grow into sturdy oak trees 100 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   These are the offspring of the centuries-old Treaty Oak, its
first saplings grown since the downtown landmark was poisoned in
1989. Their growers hope to begin selling them to the public soon.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the Treaty Oak died when the herbicide Velpar was
deliberately poured near its roots. Paul Stedman Cullen of Travis
County was convicted of felony criminal mischief and served three
years of his nine-year sentence before he was paroled in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of the Treaty Oak drew international attention.
Because of the poison, experts don't believe the oak, on Baylor
Street between Fifth and Sixth streets, will ever grow back to its
former proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the Treaty Oak produced its first batch of
acorns since the poisoning, tree specialists at the Native Texas
Nursery volunteered to harvest the acorns and grow the saplings.
</P>
<P>
   With twice-daily watering and special care, about 250 of the
1,000 acorns survived. The saplings may be available for purchase
as early as fall or as late as next year, said Mark Wieland,
coordinator of the Treaty Oak project and spokesman for the Austin
Parks and Recreation Forestry Program.
</P>
<P>
   The likely cost will be about $40, and proceeds will go to
support the Austin Parks and Recreation Planting for the Future
program, which pays for the care and planting of nearly 4,000 trees
every year in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long we have worried about the survival of the Treaty
Oak,'' Wieland said. ``This ensures that the Treaty Oak will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in the baby Treaty Oak project can call
416-0250.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-23-98 2328E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
