<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX     07-24 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem: stupid people at large
</P>
<P>
   By John Young
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Like most cities, Waco is trying to do something
about two problems with numbers: too many stray animals roaming the
streets and too many stray children doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   These are not concurrent conditions _ no reports of teen boys
group-sniffing fireplugs or of terrier mixes hogging ``Street
Fighter'' at the arcade. But both problems clearly merge at an
underlying numbers problem:
</P>
<P>
   Too many dumb adults.
</P>
<P>
   We have too many idiot pet owners. We have too many imbecile
parents.
</P>
<P>
   An expeditious, perfect-world solution of course would be
spaying and neutering of really stupid people, or of reasonably
cogent people who are just really irresponsible. Unfortunately,
though many adults do their best to forfeit any claim to standing
as higher life-forms, the 14th Amendment gives them due process
protection from such an initiative by virtue of said adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   So it's the animals to whom we administer the snip-snip. And
it's the 14-year-olds we lecture under a lamp post, though they're
only acting out the disinterest of parents who wouldn't care if
their progeny disappeared under a street sweeper's bristle.
</P>
<P>
   Waco implemented its form of a human leash law last year when it
launched a nighttime curfew. One difference between this and a
leash law, however: As with most curfews, the penalty falls on the
teen, which is like fining a runaway schnauzer for its owner's
laxitude.
</P>
<P>
   Young curfew violators commonly go to teen court and get
community service, with a $10 fee, rather than pay about $163 in
fine and court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Waiving the fine in favor of community service ``makes more
sense considering who you're punishing,'' said Municipal Judge John
Roberts. Agreed. But sometimes it's the parents who are at fault
for not acting like parents, for letting children scatter with the
night breezes. In those cases, we should aim at getting a message
to them.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's as yet not been exercised, Waco police have the
option of citing the parents of curfew offenders, which would mean
fines for them or precious TV time squandered doing community
service. That makes sense. That's a curfew with clout.
</P>
<P>
   Now to the other stray problem. Waco is debating pet licensing,
including a proposal to require a special permit for a home that
has more than four dogs and/or cats combined.
</P>
<P>
   A group of local veterinarians voiced valid concerns _ that
relying on responsible people to submit to and pay for licensing
would heap costs on these owners while the least responsible ones
would evade the rules, disavow accountability and responsibility,
and in some cases steer clear of a veterinarian entirely _ no
vaccinations _ so as not to be found owning an unlicensed pet. Good
point.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes back to the adults at home.The only way to curb
animals at large, as with children at large, shy possibly of
issuing parenting permits, is to keep an eye out for strays and
require those responsible to act responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   Spaying and neutering are the answer to pet overpopulation and
the holocaust of unneeded animals put to death every year at animal
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   And as said before, forcd population control in the stupid human
ranks would work, too, were there not a Constitution in the way.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
