<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART25-COX     07-24 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heart will go on without Ann, but guitarist Nancy sits out
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The irony is too much for Ann Wilson.
One of the first women to break into the testosterone-fueled world
of hard rock, the lead singer of Heart sought a place on this
year's Lilith Fair, that celebration of all things feminine and
musical. And she was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at first, festival organizers were encouraging. ``They
went `Wonderful, great, you're on,''' the 47-year-old Wilson
recalls, speaking from a tour date in South Carolina. But a few
months later, the singer found herself competing with everyone from
Queen Latifah to Bonnie Raitt for a spot on the roster. ``It's very
political, and you need to have a new album out,'' she concludes of
the selection process that snubbed her.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the irony is the fact that Wilson, the voice behind
such Heart hits as Straight On, Magic Man, Crazy on You and
Barracuda, has decided to mount her own tour this summer. And when
she begins her tour this summer, she'll be competing head-to-head
with Lilith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be interesting; maybe we'll have an audience of all
men,'' Wilson says with a chuckle. ``It will be like playing a USO
show.''
</P>
<P>
   The most significant aspect of the tour, however, might be that
Wilson is choosing to do it without her sister, guitarist and band
co-founder Nancy. There's no bad blood between the siblings: It's
just that Nancy wanted to spend time with her husband, film
director Cameron Crowe, in the hope of conceiving a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of shows we did, I would look over and she
wouldn't be there and that was unusual, but I talk to her on the
phone almost every day, so it's like she's there in spirit,'' says
Wilson. ``Among the audiences that are coming out, it seems to be a
non-issue. Everyone knows she'll be back when she can be.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which features Heart guitarist Howard Leese as well as
members of Wilson's other group, the acoustic-oriented Lovemongers,
promises to be something of a look backward and forward. Wilson
will feature many Heart hits from the band's '70s classic-rock
incarnation and its '80s ``glam-pop'' phase. But she'll also
include new songs she's writing for a solo album.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying for now is just a further evolution. It's a
little bit more sophisticated,'' says Wilson. ``We're not going for
the big image-first thing, like we did in the '80s. We're
definitely going for the music, for a good, live, vital sound.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether that sound will make it to record is another issue.
``I'm label-shopping, trying to network and get it going,'' Wilson
says. ``But on the record-company level they're all going, `We
can't figure out who Ann Wilson would be without Nancy?'''
</P>
<P>
   And Wilson even sees their point, especially in light of the
abundance of solo female artists around these days. ``I'm really up
against a lot of music here,'' she admits.
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone's accustomed to a good fight, it's Wilson, who had
to convince radio programmers and label executives in the '70s that
a female-fronted band deserved a shot. While she won't go so far as
to call herself a pioneer, she's clearly proud of her past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were among the first few to thumb our noses at the
conventions that existed among the brotherhood of men who ran the
industry,'' she says. ``It was not done in a bitchy way. It was
just, `Yes, we can.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-REVIEW25-COX     07-24 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-REVIEW25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appocalypse then: gritty movie celebrates American heroism
 &HT;    By Gary Schwann
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Artists understand the ugly truth that there can be beauty in
horror and horror in beauty. So do soldiers, who speak of the
resplendence that can accompany the grisliest battles.
</P>
<P>
   So does Steven Spielberg, a movie director with an instinct for
the pretty shot. Perhaps only he could direct a film about combat
that's both unflinchingly brutal and reflexively beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   It is called Saving Private Ryan, an engaging World War II epic
that dares to build on all the cliches of Hollywood war films.
Despite some struggles with the genre, Spielberg ends up
transcending stereotypes in his study of the stock character known
as GI Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg begins by making his war movie grittier than others.
He puts us on the beach at Normandy in the most realistic combat
footage this side of the Army Signal Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the movie's D-Day sequence is more powerful than Signal
Corps films. With his hand-held camera, Spielberg gets down and
bloody with the troops in ways that cameramen could not at the
shooting gallery known as Omaha Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan is nearly three hours long and contains more
than two hours of combat scenes. Be prepared to witness gutshots
and dismemberments. And be prepared to understand how dogfaces
endured it.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens peacefully enough, with a World War II veteran
and his family at a military cemetery in France. The man suddenly
falls to his knees before a grave site. Of course, an epilogue will
tell us who he is and whose grave he has stopped at. But first
there's a war to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The film segues to GIs aboard landing craft churning toward
Omaha Beach. We see a hand shaking. It belongs to Capt. Miller (Tom
Hanks). Around him, his men are vomiting, wincing, praying and
ducking. Then the ramp goes down, and we enter about 20 minutes of
chaotic combat as the infantrymen find a way to storm the German
bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   The adrenalin produced by this initial sequence is as intense as
the horror it depicts. How can the film follow its power?
Intermittently, is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting stops for a moment, Miller and his remaining
men are given an odd assignment. A paratrooper named Ryan has lost
three brothers in combat. The brass want this last surviving son
sent home. Miller's squadron is ordered to find him. He's out there
somewhere, amid the confusion of an ongoing invasion.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is up-and-down dramatically, and not just because
of the inevitable cliches, such as the ethnically mixed squad,
including a tough sergeant (Tom Sizemore), a Jewish private from
New York (Adam Goldberg) and a Bible-quoting sharpshooter from
Tennessee (Barry Pepper).
</P>
<P>
   Led by Hanks' captain, a mysterious Every-American, the men
wander the countryside on what comes to seem a kind of existential
_ if not suicidal _ mission. They bitch, battle and bond like GIs
everywhere, but what does it mean? Finding Pvt. Ryan (Matt Damon),
however, eventually becomes a metaphor for going home themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission leads to truly tense and dramatic moments _ the
fate of a German prisoner, for example, or a final battle that is
almost as explosive as the D-Day landing. But there's also time for
overcooked confrontations among the men, some drivel-ish, dogface
dialogue and fortunes of war that are simply too neat by half.
</P>
<P>
   But the film rises above the familiar. The acting is fine,
especially by Hanks, whose decency in a lousy situation never
becomes smarmy.
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan is a remarkable film about ordinary
soldiers. It's about heroism _ specifically, and unabashedly,
American heroism. Its last shot is of an American flag, and if you
don't have a twinge of pride, admiration or patriotism on seeing
it, maybe you are as dead as the GIs left behind at Omaha Beach.
</P>
<P>
   3 stars; running time 2 hours, 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
