<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1014 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-MODEL25-COX     07-24 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-MODEL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Modeling is kind of every little girl's dream''
 &HT;    Has sidebar: MODEL-SIDE
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're an attractive teen from Port St. Lucie. Do you: a.) get
chosen from 20,000 girls for a chance to be Seventeen magazine's
covergirl? b.) fly to New York c.) meet the guitarist for Garbage
d.) all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Willis has brown eyes, but she brought green ones
(contacts) just in case.
</P>
<P>
   She also brought her blanky and a reminder to not chew her
nails.
</P>
<P>
   Models shouldn't chew their nails. And Allison, 16, was about to
play one.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen magazine chose the Port St. Lucie, Florida, teen as
one of eight finalists for its New Model of the Year contest and
flew her to New York this month.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen, known for its highschool focus and its monthly
quizzes (August: ``Are you a gutsy girl?''), looked through about
20,000 entries. Some girls sent glamour pics. Some sent photos from
their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Allison sent a blurry snapshot taken by her friend, who leaned
in too close while they were watching an off-off-Broadway show last
year and caught Allison with toilet paper on her head.
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   ARE YOU A COVER GIRL?
</P>
<P>
   In your everyday life do you:
</P>
<P>
   a.) wear only lip gloss for makeup?
</P>
<P>
   b.) collect pig toys?
</P>
<P>
   c.) own knee-high, metallic-blue go-go boots?
</P>
<P>
   d.) all of the above?
</P>
<P>
   In June, Seventeen invited Allion to New York for a makeover,
photo shoots, tours and a coming-out event for media and modeling
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   They left the message on her answering machine. ``I was getting
ready to go to work, so there wasn't much time to celebrate,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Allison to describe herself and she'll say ``wild and
crazy.'' ``A teacher's pet.'' ``A beach bum.'' She just quit
playing violin. She loves sports, but on a rainy day she and her
friends will fool around with makeovers and take pictures of each
other. She collects the photos.
</P>
<P>
   Modeling, she said, ``is kind of every girl's little dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York invitation worked out just right, her mom, Maria
Mosley, said. It was the only week her daughter had nothing
planned. No volleyball camp, no softball camp.
</P>
<P>
   Allison came to New York with sock lines and a scraped leg.
</P>
<P>
   She barely told anyone she was going. Not her friends at Lin-
coln Park Academy, where she will be a junior this year. Not her
co-workers at Bubba's Fish Camp. Not her teammates. Even now she'd
rather wait until the maga- zine with the finalists' photos comes
out this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to be the kind of girl _ `I'm gonna be in
Seventeen, ha ha!''' said Allison, who is now called ``my little
super model'' by her best friend, Hagen Hastings. ``Then I don't
have to live up to any expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   So most people thought she went to New York to visit her aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she was sitting in a salon in midtown Manhattan, get-
ting a $290 hairdo for free while a crew from Entertainment Tonight
dipped a mike in her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be blond,'' she said. The cameraman called her
``Wild Spice.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl chosen for Seventeen's cover gets a five-day trip for
two to Paris and a $1,000 shopping spree.
</P>
<P>
   The ET reporter asked if any big names had come out of the
contest during its 14 years. Not really, Seventeen told her. The
reporter decided not to get that on tape.
</P>
<P>
   During your makeover and before-and-after shots, do you:
</P>
<P>
   a.) remove your bright-pink nail polish?
</P>
<P>
   b.) get compared to Linda Evangelista, Meg Ryan and Hayley
Mills?
</P>
<P>
   c.) stick out your tongue at the camera?
</P>
<P>
   d.) all of the above?
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta get your tongue pierced,'' Hannah Borum, 15, told
Allison. She plays volleyball, too, in Maryland. Her close-up photo
was taken in her house, standing with her lacrosse stick. The two
bonded fast.
</P>
<P>
   The eight girls spent their first night in New York hanging out
of the top of a limo, supplied by Seventeen, and checking out a
World Cup party. They couldn't get to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   This modeling thing is new for them. When Allison was 13, she
tried competing in a couple of pageants. With braces on her teeth,
she won Miss Port St. Lucie.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 14, she visited a modeling agency in New York. ``He
didn't see potential or any- thing. I figured I would wait a couple
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Other finalists already knew their way around. Samantha Harris,
18, took a year off from school in Texas to pursue modeling in
Paris. Ashleigh Borman, 15, just signed with a Dallas agency.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't competitive, they said. ``What do we have to
lose?'' They hung out in a corner of the salon, hair in funky get
ups, and chatted.
</P>
<P>
   They told the Entertainment Tonight reporter she was aging well.
</P>
<P>
   At your first major photo shoot, do you wear:
</P>
<P>
   a.) a slip-type dress with a leather jacket?
</P>
<P>
   b.) a blue shimmery top with a black skirt?
</P>
<P>
   c.) a bright-pink sleeveless dress?
</P>
<P>
   d.) all of the above?
</P>
<P>
   At first, the photographer didn't like the Polaroids.
</P>
<P>
   Then the art director didn't like the neckline.
</P>
<P>
   Then somebody didn't like something.
</P>
<P>
   Then the button-up shirt was missing a button.
</P>
<P>
   Allison finally got approval in a V-neck sheath over a
light-blue dress.
</P>
<P>
   The shoot was in a vast white studio not far from New York's
newest hot neighborhood, SoHo. They could see the World Trade
Center from the windows. Reggae blasted from a sound system on a
rolling cart.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were shot one at a time. The others waited, chose
outfits from racks donated by up- and-coming designers. They
compared their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be shy on me now, girl!'' the photographer shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too shy,'' Allison said, looking down and folding her
hands. Then she stuck out her tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who chooses the cover girl was sitting nearby,
watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has an interesting kind of boyish kind of look,'' said
Florence Sicard-Russo, Seventeen's art di- rector. ``It's very hard
for us to find models with short hair.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of August, the eight girls will know Sicard-Russo's
choice.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say what the Seventeen cover look is, she said.
They try to go for beauty that's unusual, then they get letters
asking ``How could you use a girl so ugly?''
</P>
<P>
   During your New York stay, do you get the chance to see:
</P>
<P>
   a.) the president of Chanel?
</P>
<P>
   b.) Sarah McLachlan?
</P>
<P>
   c.) the guitarist from Garbage?
</P>
<P>
   d.) all of the above?
</P>
<P>
   The press event took place in a replica of Coco Chanel's
original Paris salon. Someone lined up chairs to form a runway on
the carpet. Waiters wandered with finger foods and champagne.
</P>
<P>
   In back, the girls sang Christmas songs to get over being
nervous. ``Don't fall,'' Allison told herself. ``Don't trip.'' They
primped.
</P>
<P>
   They were announced one by one, in alphabetical order. Some
hurried down the runway and back, then joined the others, who were
holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't last long. People were free to mingle. Scouts from
modeling agencies moved forward, calling some girls by name.
``Ashleigh, hi!''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Hunter, Karin Models: ``I like the girl with the curly
hair. But they had a girl with curly hair last year. Allison's
bubbly. She has a lot of personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Planit, vice president, International Management Group: ``I
would say Sheena and Samantha are my favorites. Allison has a
really pretty face, but she doesn't strike me as a flashy model.''
</P>
<P>
   Some girls got business cards. Allison did not. ``I know
Ashleigh had an appointment with an agency on Thursday,'' she said,
after returning to Port St. Lucie.
</P>
<P>
   She was pooped. They got the entire model treatment, even
jumping up to walk the runway at the Fashion Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, she said, ``all I could do was smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Once home, do you:
</P>
<P>
   a.) sleep in?
</P>
<P>
   b.) get compliments from mom on your hair?
</P>
<P>
   c.) decide to start a modeling portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   d.) all of the above?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
