<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release the weekend of Saturday, July 25,
1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ The one truth in presidential
campaigns is ... that there is no one truth to be found there.
Rather, there are lots of forks in the political trail that lead to
either success or ruin. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED. EMBARGOED
UNTIL JULY 26.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Few in this country beyond our foreign-policy
cognoscenti noticed, but while the world was recently and
enthusiastically adopting a basic American ideal to try government
leaders or their agents for war crimes and for crimes against
humanity, Washington copped out. There were two reasons: ``Jesse''
and ``Helms.'' (Teepen, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Like most cities, Waco is trying to
do something about two problems with numbers: too many stray
animals roaming the streets and too many stray children doing the
same. These are not concurrent conditions _ no reports of teen boys
group-sniffing fireplugs or of terrier mixes hogging ``Street
Fighter'' at the arcade. But both problems clearly merge at an
underlying numbers problem: Too many dumb adults. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ I'm sitting on the back porch under the ceiling
fans, watching a thunderstorm meander this way. It's teasing me,
thunder occasionally sounding, a rare pleasant breeze bringing a
welcome respite from this hellish summer, but no rain yet. Life is
good, and now I can work while sitting in this lawn chair or
whileswinging on the antique porch swing built by a long-dead
friend of my in-laws. If this computer could just make it rain,
everything would be perfect. (Borders,
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Cox Newspapers columnist Howard Kleinberg is
on vacation. His column will resume for Wednesday, July 29.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ Cox Newspapers columnist Joe Murray is traveling
and reporting in Europe. His column will resume the week of July 27
with reports from abroad. (Murray, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ After Thelma Shepherd died in 1996, her three
surviving daughters went through her papers and photo albums,
expecting to find nothing more than memories of a past as familiar
as her well-loved features. Then, in an album of old family photos,
they were startled to find a reference to their ``baby brother,''
Guy Wilk, in France, conceived when their father was a soldier
stationed in Metz, France, guarding German POWs in World War II.
Neither their mother nor their father, who died in 1983, ever spoke
a word about him. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Ronald Reagan's decision to
dance with the Christian right now has the Republican Party dancing
to a gospel tune. Before Reagan's advisers decided to mix politics
and religion in exchange for votes, the GOP stood primarily for
fiscal conservatism, a strong defense and rugged individualism.
(Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CSIBLEY-COLUMN _ The old editorial writer on The Hartford
(Conn.) Courant who wrote that everybody talks about the weather
but nobody does anything about it should be living today. Nowadays
everybody is going crazy trying to conquer the weather. And I'm
here to say I'm very tired of it. (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/23. EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
