</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release on the weekend of Saturday,
July 25, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-MODEL _ You're an attractive teen from Port St. Lucie. Do
you: a.) get chosen from 20,000 girls for a chance to be Seventeen
magazine's covergirl? b.) fly to New York c.) meet the guitarist
for Garbage d.) all of the above. Allison Willis has brown eyes,
but she brought green ones (contacts) just in case. She also
brought her blanky and a reminder to not chew her nails. Models
shouldn't chew their nails. And Allison, 16, was about to play one.
Seventeen magazine chose the Port St. Lucie, Florida teen as one of
eight finalists for its New Model of the Year contest and flew her
to New York this month. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MODELS-SIDE _ Seventeen's beauty director, Liz Brous, looked
over photos of the eight finalists and explained what got them to
New York. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONDO-BOOM _ AUSTIN _ Deanna Engber is trading in her apartment
for a condominium. Buying the two-bedroom Barton Hills condo makes
sense and will leave Engber with a monthly mortgage payment of
about $900 a month. That's less than she would pay for many
comparable apartments in Central Austin, which are renting for
$1,000 a month and up. Engber, and many like her, have contributed
to an Austin condo boom, a phenomenon many thought they never would
see again after the real estate bust of the late 1980s. (Breyer,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-CHILDCARE PALM BEACH _ While some Internet companies
use videocameras to give parents the ability to watch their child
in day care, Safe Technologies International plans to take the
concept a step further and give parents the ability to have a
conversation ``face-to-face'' on a computer screen with their child
or child's teacher. (Bhatt, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   LAWNS-WATER _ Water crimes: Do you water your lawn in the
afternoon after work? Do you wet your shrubs with the sprinkler?
How about those pots? When was the last time you saw water seep out
the bottoms? If you've never thought about the proper way to water
you could be doing your lawns and garden more harm than good. Check
out this primer on the do's and donts for watering. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-LEEMAY _ Lee May's bi-weekly gardening column. (May,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TREATY-OAK _ AUSTIN _ They are small green stalks, less than a
foot high, so tiny and delicate, it's hard to imagine that one day
each could grow into sturdy oak trees 100 feet high. These are the
offspring of the centuries-old Treaty Oak, its first saplings grown
since the downtown landmark was poisoned in 1989. Their growers
hope to begin selling them to the public soon. The plight of the
Treaty Oak drew international attention. Because of the poison,
experts don't believe the oak, on Baylor Street between Fifth and
Sixth streets, will ever grow back to its former proportions.
(Tanamachi, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   CHILDRENOFGOD _ They were the Jesus Freaks, the Children of God
and now The Family. Among their techniques for evangelizing was
``flirty fishing'' - sending attractive young women out to seduce
and sleep with men to bring them into the fold. One long-time
practitioner of this was Miriam Williams, now a graduate student in
sociology at Georgia State University and author of a new book,
``Heaven's Harlot.'' (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-TEENS _ Imagine 30,000 teenagers descending on Atlanta
for five days. Could be a frightening experience. But these
youngsters, part of the National Lutheran Youth Conference that
begins today (July 25), will be spending most of their time
participating in community service projects and prayer. (Blake,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-GRAHAM _ Franklin Graham, founder of the international
relief organization Samaritan's Purse and recognized successor to
his father, evangelist Billy Graham, told the story of his own life
in his first book, ``Rebel With a Cause.'' Now, in ``Living Beyond
the Limits,'' Graham recounts the stories of other people who have
made an impression on him. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-MUSIC _ Most music fans know DC Talk through their
music. Their last album, ``Jesus Freak,'' went platinum and netted
the trio a Grammy Award for best rock gospel album. Yet less people
know about the group's public campaign to promote racial unity.
This interracial trio created the ERACE (Eliminating Racism and
Creating Equality) Foundation last year to promote what they call,
``living integration.'' A talk with DC Talk member Toby McKeehan
about their campaign. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)v
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   25TEXAS _ Next in monthly series on the history of theater in
Texas, with photos from Rebecca McEntee, this about the
experimental stuff that sometimes draws controversy. (Barnes,
Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RYAN-REVIEW _ Artists understand the ugly truth that there can
be beauty in horror and horror in beauty. So do soldiers, who speak
of the resplendence that can accompany the grisliest battles. So
does Steven Spielberg, a movie director with an instinct for the
pretty shot. Perhaps only he could direct a film about combat
that's both unflinchingly brutal and reflexively beautiful.
(Schwann, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HEART _ The irony is too much for Ann Wilson. One of the first
women to break into the testosterone-fueled world of hard rock, the
lead singer of Heart sought a place on this year's Lilith Fair,
that celebration of all things feminine and musical. And she was
rejected. Adding to the irony is the fact that Wilson, the voice
behind such Heart hits as Straight On, Magic Man, Crazy on You and
Barracuda, has decided to mount her own tour this summer. And when
she begins her tour this summer, she'll be competing head-to-head
with Lilith. (Passy, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
