A1087 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERICHO-CASINO-0725-C     07-24 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERICHO-CASINO-0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISLAMIC NEIGHBORS SEE SIN IN CASINO PROJECT IN ANCIENT JERICHO
 &HT;    With photo to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, West Bank _ This won't be the first time that there was
an infamous temptation near this ancient oasis.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the Mount of Temptation, where The Devil offered
Jesus all the kingdoms of the world, construction crews are working
overtime to finish the first modern casino in the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of this sleepy Muslim town say gambling offends their
religious values. But, with the approval of Palestinian leaders,
the slot machines and 35 gaming tables will open sometime this
fall. After that will come the entertainment lounge, 10-story
hotel, golf course and swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   All of it is directly across the street from the block houses
and dirt roads of a Palestinian refugee camp. Donkeys mill near the
entrance and goats graze nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, they could be replaced by the Las Vegas-styled white
tigers of Siegfried(CQ) and Roy, should they ever appear at ``The
Oasis Hotel and Casino.''
</P>
<P>
   The site is minutes from Jericho, population 15,000. The
Israelites conquered the 10,000-year-old city in 1250 B.C. by
making the ``walls come tumbling down.'' It was ruled by Herod
under the Romans and Jesus was baptized in the Jordan River nearby.
</P>
<P>
   At 825 feet below sea level, Jericho was a warm winter vacation
spot when ruled by Jordan. The Israelis captured it in the war of
1967. In the 1990s, it became the first West Bank city Israeli
troops withdrew from under the Oslo peace accords, ushering in the
rule of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The $150 million casino project is headed by an Austrian casino
company with Palestinian investors and the cooperation with the
Palestinian National Authority, headed by President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The resort is expected to attract Israelis, who have outlawed
casinos in their home country but have frequented Turkish casinos a
short airplane flight away. It will also be a draw for
international tourists and conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Just 40 minutes from Jerusalem, the project is on the outskirts
of Jericho. That could be a comfort to Israelis who are often
skittish about crossing into the West Bank and driving through
Palestinian towns.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman with the Israeli public relations firm
representing the project said it will be open to foreigners, not
Palestinians, just as Egyptian hotel casinos exclude local
Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
   That is just fine with many Jericho residents, who would rather
their quiet town remain known as ``The World's Oldest City'' rather
than home to the biggest casino resort in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good number of people in Jericho don't like the idea of
having a casino,'' said Jericho municipal spokesman Bassam
Abedrabbo, who stressed that the project was authorized by the
Palestinian national leadership, not the town.
</P>
<P>
   The 220-room hotel, he said, will be the biggest building in
Jericho and many feel it will not fit in.
</P>
<P>
   But, the biggest objections are on moral grounds that sound like
those raised against casino projects in the United States. Only
this time it is Muslims, rather than Christians, who are offended.
</P>
<P>
   Even at a local pool hall _ where the game is played without
wagering _ the casino project has no backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conservative. With a casino, there will be a lot of
girls they will import from abroad,'' said 20-year-old student Ziad
Saradih. ``No one will control what's going on in the casino and
that will result in destroying the values of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Tadmor, Tel Aviv-based spokeswoman for Casinos Austria,
said the project will provide 1,000 jobs. Hundreds of Palestinians
are already working on the construction.
</P>
<P>
   But Jericho residents question whether any of the big money will
stay in their community. The project might even keep some tourists
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will bypass Jericho,'' said David C. Hall, a Baptist
minister from Oklahoma who leads several tours a year to Jericho.
``I do not bring people who spend thousands of dollars to see the
land of our Lord to see a gambling casino.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
