<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULE OF THUMB ON DUPLICATE FILES: WHEN IN DOUBT, DON'T DELETE THEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm trying to clean my hard drive of duplicate files, but I'm
not sure which files to delete. Can you give me some insight as to
which files are needed? My problem is I don't know which directory
needs the files in question. How can I distinguish them and delete
the right file?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's a simple rule you can follow: If you don't know
whether to delete a file, then don't.
</P>
<P>
   One of the features found in lots of uninstall and
clean-up-your-hard-drive programs is a duplicate file finder.
Often, the files it finds in the vast reaches of a user's hard
drive duplicate those found in the Windowssystem folder.
</P>
<P>
   But hold on a second.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, those files aren't really duplicates. If you look
closely, they'll have different file sizes and dates on them. That
means they are different versions of the same files.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where users get into trouble. They believe they need only
one version, so they delete the older one. Or, they've heard that
all of these system files _ usually with extensions of DLL _ should
only be in the Windowssystem folder, and they remove the duplicate
found in an ordinary program folder.
</P>
<P>
   Bad move.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, they'll find their system starts crashing a
lot. Or a program doesn't run. Or they suffer mysterious lockups.
</P>
<P>
   What happens is that programs written at different times rely on
different versions of key system files. Let's say you've got a copy
of FindElvis 1.0, written back in the early days of Windows 95. You
install it on your new, Windows 98-based PC. You look in your
system folder and see a DLL file called BIGFILE.DLL, dated 5/6/98.
But in your FindElvis folder, there's another file called
BIGFILE-.DLL, and it's got a date of 8/24/95.
</P>
<P>
   When FindElvis 1.0 was written, the programmer who created it
may have relied on certain aspects of the older version of BIGFILE.
If you delete that older version from the FindElvis directory, you
may not be able to find Elvis at all _ the program may not have
what it needs.
</P>
<P>
   If you delete the version in Windowssystem, then other programs
that might also use it can't get to it, because they don't know
about the FindElvis folder. They expect to find BIGFILE in the
system folder.
</P>
<P>
   When you can delete duplicate files is when they are exactly the
same size, have exactly the same name and exactly the same date.
Even then, don't delete the duplicate at first. Change the file's
name instead. If your system runs fine for a few days, then delete
it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a recent question, a reader asked if it is better to
install a new motherboard first or Windows 98. You answered with
the motherboard. This is true, but before the user turns off the
computer to install it, he or she should go into the DeviceManager
and remove the old board's resources. This helps in that when the
PC is turned on with the new board, Windows isn't looking for the
old one and should not cause a lot of conflicts. This is helpful
when installing most new hardware and prevents a lot of headaches.
</P>
<P>
   A: You raise a good point. If the board you're installing is
fully Plug and Play compliant, there should be no problems. But
removing the drivers in Device Manager under System
Devices/Motherboard resources could prevent some lockups _ thanks
for the tip.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the most important components for decent Web-surfing
speed? Modem? Memory? Chip speed?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, of course, is your connection speed. Above a certain
processor speed _ say, 166 megahertz _ most browser software
performs about the same. So, what you really want is more memory so
the browser software runs smoothly and your operating system
doesn't write to the hard disk as often, which slows everything
down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
