<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-24 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER MUSCLE GETTING EASIER TO BUY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although computers priced below $1,000 get most of the attention
these days, the guts and glory in PCs are still in the high end. If
you want serious power, you'll have to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't have to pay much. For about the past 18 months,
the average price for a state-of-the-art Windows-based personal
computer has ranged between $2,000 and $2,600, down from $2,500 to
$3,000.
</P>
<P>
   If your needs are basic _ word processing, home finance,
Internet access, children's software _ you probably don't need a
muscle-bound machine. Spend your cash elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're into serious gaming, computer graphics and
multimedia, here are two systems to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Presario 5630, $2,600, Compaq Computer Corp.: Although
Compaq's Presario line is the most popular in home computing, it's
always suffered a bad rap from PC enthusiasts. They argue that the
Presario is so loaded down with bells and whistles that its
performance suffers.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Presarios once were loaded with proprietary
components _ sound and graphics systems built into the main system
board, modems mated with sound cards, and so on. As a result, those
who wanted speed and control over the configuration of their own
systems looked elsewhere, often at direct marketers such as Dell
and Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's answer is a new line of high-end Presarios that don't
suffer from performance anxiety. The 5630, Compaq's top-of-the-line
Presario, is fast, easy to upgrade and still has enough bells and
whistles to satisfy the greediest gadget freak.
</P>
<P>
   The 5630 comes with a 400-megahertz Pentium II chip; a generous
128 megabytes of memory; a 10-gigabyte hard drive; a DVD-ROM drive;
a built-in Zip drive; a 56K fax modem that uses the new v.90
standard; a four-megabyte ATI 3D Rage LT Pro AGP-based graphics
card; and a sound card that uses the impressive new Aureal 3D audio
standard.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes with a built-in Ethernet port, so you can plug it
directly into a home network. There are also two Universal Serial
Bus and one IEEE 1394 (also known as FireWire or iLink) connections
on the front of the machine, making it easy to plug in camcorders,
digital cameras and scanners that use these kinds of connections.
</P>
<P>
   Both the modem and the video card on this computer are on
removable cards, so if something better comes along, you can
replace them. There are also plenty of open slots for further
expandability.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq ships this system with a fancy keyboard that includes a
handy volume control, easy-access buttons for sound and playing
music CDs, and a set of four buttons aimed at making it easier to
get to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Those last four buttons are programmable, but figuring out how
to use them is tricky. Most of them point you to Web sites that pay
Compaq a little cash whenever you visit. This strikes me as just a
bit sleazy, particularly since changing the settings is not as easy
as it should be. Compaq has released a software patch that is
supposed to make it easier to change the buttons, but I have not
yet tried it.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq is selling this machine on its Web site, as well as
through kiosks it is installing in computer and electronic stores
around the country. You can order it with extra features, such as a
Diamond Multimedia Monster 3D II graphics card or a Syquest
1.5-gigabyte removable disk drive.
</P>
<P>
   I tried this system with a new, 14-inch, flat-panel monitor, the
FP500, that was a serious disappointment. Though it's an
active-matrix display, it's almost as dark and hard to see as a
passive-matrix system. At $999, it's too expensive for most home
users to consider. Stick with one of Compaq's traditional monitors
until the price on this comes down and the quality of the display
goes up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pavilion 8290, $2,600, Hewlett-Packard: Although this model is
relatively old _ it was replaced earlier this month by the 8380 _
it's still on store shelves and probably can be found for less than
the list price shown here. The 8380 has a list price of just more
than $2,000, so it's possible this older model might be found for
less than that.
</P>
<P>
   The 8290 comes with a 400-megahertz Pentium II chip; 64
megabytes of memory; a roomy 12-gigabyte hard drive; a
four-megabyte ATI 3D Rage Pro AGP-based video card; a DVD-ROM
drive; a 56K fax modem; and 3-D stereo sound.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's keyboard also comes with buttons and controls
for volume, playing music CDs and launching some programs. In fact,
Hewlett-Packard pioneered these keyboards, and they do it better
than anyone else. It's much easier to reconfigure these buttons
than those of the Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Although the HP is not quite as zippy as the Compaq, which could
be chalked up to having only half the amount of memory, it still
will not disappoint. And like the Compaq, it is highly expandable.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find this machine and opt for the 8380 instead,
note that it will have 96 megabytes of memory, but a smaller hard
drive at eight gigabytes. It also has USB ports on the front of the
machine. Otherwise, they're almost twins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
