<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S RICHEST NATION NEEDS TO RETHINK HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIT COSTELLO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Let's not buy the supposedly authoritative
pronouncement that comprehensive health care reform is dead.
</P>
<P>
   The health care industry scared the daylights out of the public
during debate four years ago over President Clinton's flawed
proposals, but that doesn't mean the concerns don't continue. For
the uninsured and the insured, health care insecurity has exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Few of us in real life resemble Harry and Louise, that famously
smug couple from the televised commercials. Yet this fictitious
couple successfully pandered to Americans' worst fears over
``government intrusion.'' They warned us that if ``the government''
is involved, we'll have higher costs, fewer choices,
unresponsiveness and burdensome bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later we have all of that and more, courtesy of the
health care corporations and their overpaid chief executives,
consultants and care-denying layers of bean counters. Daily we read
news stories about dissatisfaction with managed care, Medicare
fraud and overbilling. We read about doctors and nurses in open
revolt against cost-cutting pressures that have an impact on care.
</P>
<P>
   Studies by proponents and opponents of market-driven health care
call into question that presumed lack of public support for
systemic reform. Politicians should take heed at what the opinion
polls show.
</P>
<P>
   A group of reform advocates and organizations commissioned GLS
Research to conduct a random poll of 400 voters in Washington
state. The findings: Eighty-three percent of respondents (including
65 percent of voters identifying themselves as conservative) agreed
with the statement: ``Americans have a basic right to health
insurance regardless of their ability to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent agreed with this: ``By getting rid of red tape,
administration, advertising and huge executive salaries in the
insurance industry, we can expand health care coverage while
reducing its cost.''
</P>
<P>
   And: ``It's not right to let health insurance companies make
huge profits when so many people are uninsured because they can't
afford insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Results were about the same for a survey conducted by the
American Hospital Association, an industry trade group, which
surveyed public attitudes with 31 focus groups in 12 states,
utilizing data from 1,000 polled voters. It found people are
insecure about their health insurance and mistrustful of health
care insurers and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The public's ``image grid'' was summarized this way: ``America
has the best technology and training in the world but increasingly,
cost and other factors are barriers to access. These barriers are
caused largely by the greed of insurers and providers. Because of
this, providers and patients are losing control over important
health care decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Such findings indicate a phenomenal readiness to reopen the
debate on health care coverage and better public oversight of
hospitals, and a desire to see the health care dollar spent on
care.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was never made public by the hospital
association but was widely leaked, also identified major ``building
block images'' of health care and hospital care today. They
included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Americans of every age and economic status (excepting many
seniors on Medicare) expressed strong fear of the loss or erosion
of their health coverage and thus economic access to medical care.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many Americans see neither a planned system nor any
consumer-oriented organization, but quite the opposite. They see a
confusing, expensive, unreliable and often impersonal assembly of
medical professionals and institutions. If they see any ``system''
at all, it is one devoted to maximizing profits by blocking access,
reducing quality, and limiting spending _ all at the expense of the
patient.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average American believes that health insurance companies
have too much influence and exert too much control over personal
care _ more than their doctor, hospital, the government, or
themselves, sometimes more than all of them combined.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most believe profit has taken precedence at the expense of
quality.
</P>
<P>
   _ The key indicator cited as a measure of quality in hospital
care was the nurse. Respondents hold a strong belief that skilled
nurses are being systematically replaced by poorly trained and
poorly paid aides. The profit motive is seen as behind the
reduction in nursing care.
</P>
<P>
   _ A consistent concern was that advertising and other forms of
marketing were being done at the expense of quality.
</P>
<P>
   The public knows that health care in the United States is in a
meltdown phase. And they know it from personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tinkering around the edges with HMO incremental strategies will
not solve the fundamental problem. As long as health care is
treated like a market commodity, the abuses that have become
notorious will dominate public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   No other industrialized country treats health care like this. It
is considered a social responsibility subject to democratic public
policy solutions.
</P>
<P>
   If individuals, employers and corporations share responsibility
for funding through a fair formula, we could do what other
industrialized countries do _ offer health security to all. We
spend far more than any other country on health care _ 14.5 percent
of our gross domestic product _ yet have 42 million uninsured
(about 20 percent of us) and 31 million more underinsured.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to reintroduce the subject of universal health care in
the richest country in the world. Just ask the average person.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kit Costello, a registered nurse, is president of the
California Nurses Association.)
</P>
</TEXT>
