A1135 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-24 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME AND LACK OF PUNISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dave DeWard is well aware of the world's
imperfections. From his perspective, this country's refusal to put
Pat Buchanan in the White House is proof enough of that.
</P>
<P>
   But after his recent brush with the criminal justice system, he
now has a sharper appreciation of how grim things can really get.
</P>
<P>
   Dave DeWard is a burly, jovial, right-wing political activist
who operates a parking lot. One morning, at about 1:30, he was
lying in bed, listening to talk radio. That's when a knock came at
the door of his apartment in Troy, a gritty old industrial city
across the Hudson River from Albany.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of this month. A new neighbor was moving in
that morning. All that day, people had been banging on Dave
DeWard's door looking for the new neighbor. He figured that this
was just more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   So he got out of bed in his underwear, went to the front door
and removed the bolt and chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I go flying,'' he told me. ``The door comes flying
in. I hit furniture, with my lower back, especially ... The first
thing I see is this guy standing with his foot right on me. And he
has two women with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two women go scurrying through my apartment. This guy is
standing on my chest. He's not saying one word. And I'm not saying
one word to him, either. I'm just looking to get a good description
of him ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear drawers opening. I hear all kinds of noises. I just lie
there, 'cause who knows if you're going to get killed or not ... It
seemed like an hour, but it was probably more like 15 minutes. They
go through the whole place ...
</P>
<P>
   ``As they leave, I go out the door and I try to get the license
number. They drove off without lights in this big, brown Cadillac,
but I could see well enough to tell you who sat where in the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing, I try to see what's gone. And then I call the
police.''
</P>
<P>
   Who, Dave DeWard said, showed up in about 12 minutes. And, while
they were talking to him, a call came over the police radio. A man
and two women fitting the description Dave DeWard had given the
cops over the phone had just been nabbed with his ATM card at a
nearby bank branch.
</P>
<P>
   The cops took Dave DeWard to the bank branch. He identified the
man and the two women. Everybody went to the station. Dave DeWard
said he was treated royally. The cops even let him smoke. They told
him that the man and the two women immediately started squealing on
one another.
</P>
<P>
   So, Dave DeWard had a sore back, but he was still alive. He
hadn't lost any money. All three suspects were in custody. Under
the circumstances, a reasonably happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few days later and just before the Fourth of July
holiday, Dave DeWard got a message on his machine from a Rensselaer
County assistant district attorney. Call me, the D.A. said. Dave
called. He and the prosecutor played phone tag for that day and the
next.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday came and went. Then, the Tuesday after the holiday,
he got another message from the assistant D.A. You're an hour late
for court, the message said. Get down to city court right away.
</P>
<P>
   Dave DeWard ran to city court. He was told he'd ignored a
subpoena. He said he'd never received any subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out,'' he told me, ``that two of the three
individuals were released because I wasn't there. The one they kept
because there was another warrant for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, by the way, turned out to be precisely what happened. I
checked. One of the suspects, Laurie Johnson, 36, is currently in
residence in the Rensselaer County Jail. She has a lengthy criminal
record, mostly involving prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   But Troy City Court Judge Hank Bauer did release the other two
on no bail, since the prosecution hadn't had the victim present,
nor an arresting officer, nor had the cops taken an affidavit from
the victim on the night of the crime that could be submitted as
evidence. Since Antron Hilton, 29, had done state prison time for
drug dealing and Shannon Houser, 23, had done time for
prostitution, I called the judge to ask why he hadn't given the
prosecution the extension they'd asked for to produce any or all of
that, but he never got back to me.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Houser did, in fact, skip her scheduled court appearance
earlier this month. There's now a warrant out for her. That has
not, though, kept somebody who calls herself Shannon from calling
Dave DeWard, he told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting hang-up calls on my machine,'' he said. ``and she
left her name once.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did she say when she called?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `You son of a bitch. I want to talk to you. I know
you're there. Pick up the goddamn phone ... I finally got hold of
the assistant D.A. I was worried for my life. He told me, `Don't
worry ... I promise you that they wouldn't be stupid enough to come
near you again.''
</P>
<P>
   All three suspects were issued orders of protection requiring
them to stay away from Dave DeWard. The problem is that one order
of protection _ the one for Antron Hilton _ was mailed to Mr.
Hilton at Dave DeWard's address. A clerical error by city court, I
was told by the district attorney's office, and that was probably
only a copy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' I asked Dave DeWard, ``What do you think about all
this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he told me, ``I'm a little concerned for my safety.
But now when people ask me why I'm for Buchanan, I have a good
story to tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
