<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-STARS-$ADV26-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S `OUT THERE'? A BUNCH OF STELLAR CORPSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I dislike being an alarmist, but THE SUN IS DYING! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I know you are apathetic about this _ and may become even more
so when I tell you the sun won't turn into a burned out husk for
about 5 billion years (if scientists are to be believed). But if we
don't start planning and worrying now, one of these days our
great-great-etc.-grandchildren are going to freeze to death. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And as these lovely children suck in their final frozen breath,
they will exhale curses at us for not acting when we had a chance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may want that on your eternal conscience. But I don't. If I
have to spend eternity thinking about bad stuff, I'd rather be
reading the sports pages and learning that the Chicago Cubs now
have gone, say, 11,397 years since last winning the World Series in
1945. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, this summer is a good time to fret about the
impending death of our sun, not only because it's hot _ a situation
exacerbated by Al Gore running around preaching sermons about
global warming _ but also because some astronomers in Australia
have just announced exciting, if distressing, new developments in
the oft-neglected field of stellar corpse observation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the way, you may want to keep stellar corpse observation on
your list of employment possibilities when you talk to young people
in your family about careers because so few of them will think of
it if you fail to mention it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers at the Anglo-Australian Observatory (AAO) in Epping,
Australia, recently disclosed they have confirmed the discovery of
almost 100 previously unknown stellar corpses. I was deeply
saddened to learn about this, especially because the announcement
included no information on whether surviving suns(CQ) and daughters
have been notified. Nor did the announcement reveal what in the
world (literally _ in the world) one does with 100 star bodies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But these stellar corpses _ also known as ``planetary nebulae''
_ are just the beginning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At this rate,'' said Quentin Parker of the AAO, ``we can
expect about 1,000 new planetary nebulae to be confirmed in the
southern Milky Way galaxy over the next three years.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Let's take a quick vote. Raise your hand if you prefer
planetary nebulae. OK. How about stellar corpses? Good. Me too.
It's stellar corpses.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My fondest hope is that our own sun will not be among the
deceased to be found in the next three years. The best guess, as I
say, is that it should last another 5 billion years, but you have
to remember that scientists don't always get it right. Which
scientist, after all, predicted 5 billion years ago that by 1998
you could watch reruns of ``Starsky &AMP; Hutch'' on 76 cable channels
at once? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our sun, as you surely learned in school, is a star, not unlike
a hootybazillion other stars in the cosmos. Which means it's a
sphere of luminous gas (I can't tell you how hard I'm having to
work to avoid a Rush Limbaugh joke here). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sun generates energy by nuclear fusion, which means it's
really, really hot when you touch it, which I don't recommend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers estimate our sun _ which hangs out some 93 million
miles from Earth _ is one of about 100 billion stars in the Milky
Way, and they classify it as a yellow dwarf of the spectral class
G2. Which may mean something to them but which means zippo to me,
perhaps because I am not a yellow dwarf but, rather, kind of a tall
white guy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What should we do about our dying sun? I don't know, but maybe
we should take a hint from TV, and, if the sun really is
slip-sliding away, send it into reruns, where many dead stars enjoy
eternal life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
