<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1152 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NBC-HNS &LR;      07-24 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A RISKY BUSINESS, NBC EXCELS AT GIVING SHOWS A CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ NBC has been riding a remarkable wave of good
fortune this past decade. Yet the network is as much a story of
survivors as it is of success.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Conan O'Brien sat down for a string of
satellite interviews. During the course of the interviews, he was
told over and over how he and his show ``Late Night'' were bombing.
So he did the logical thing: He went back into his office and
curled up in a ball under his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fontana, the executive producer of ``Homicide: Life on the
Street,'' knew he was doing something different, something good.
The question was would the network and the audience get it?
Long-term planning wasn't an issue when his drama opened to
critical acclaim but virtually no viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had said to me the first season, `You're going to make
100 episodes,' I would have said to you, `I don't even know if
we're going to get past the first commercial,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, ``Conan'' enters his sixth season; ``Homicide,'' its
seventh. Both survived because both were able to take original
ideas and develop ways to connect with viewers and fend off
becoming road kill. The fact both are still on the air also says
something about NBC, and how the rich can get richer in this
business.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the basic contradiction in television: Good shows, more
often than not, need time to develop both an audience and a voice.
But networks, fearful of ratings and cash loss, are often quick to
yank a show off the air if it does not produce quickly. Sure, some
garbage remains on the schedule, and others are deservedly canned
early, but no one knows how many series could have developed into
quality programming if given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   This is where NBC's success has fed off itself. It had
``Seinfeld,'' ``ER,'' ``Frasier,'' ``Friends,'' ``Mad About You,''
and even, earlier in the decade, ``Cheers.'' They are or were
ratings monsters and when you have that stable, you can afford to
take a few shots in the dark elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Other networks struggling to move up the food chain don't have
that luxury. NBC will survive the loss of ``Seinfeld.'' Moving into
its time slot is ``Frasier,'' and new shows like ``Trinity,'' a
drama about an Irish family from Hell's Kitchen, and ``Will &AMP;
Grace,'' a sitcom that features a gay lead character, offer promise
of new hits.
</P>
<P>
   Survival is what NBC Entertainment President Warren Littlefield
is all about. He has been with the network 19 years, nine at the
top spot, in a profession where executives can be axed as quickly
as bad sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things you have to ask yourself is: `If we get rid
of it, could we do worse?''' Littlefield said. ``Enough things were
going right for us to say, `We can stick with this vision.'
Honestly, today, we are very happy we did,'' Littlefield said of
``Homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC players are quick to credit the media for keeping
``Homicide'' on the air, reminding us that these kinds of dramas
are almost always going to be as endangered as they are rare. But
NBC always knew the quality was there from the start, even if an
audience was not. Patience paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conan'' was another story. It was incredibly rough, heck, bad,
in the first two years. ``We had no idea what we were doing,''
Littlefield said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien sidekick Andy Richter agreed, saying that he thought the
show was always good, just in a rough form. ``It was always a
really well-written show ... with two nervous people who hadn't
been on TV five days a week ever before,'' he said. ``I felt from
the very beginning it was funny. We just continued working.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien went from being the butt of office and radio jokes to
the cover story on magazines. The man definitely remembers. He also
had the vision, and NBC the patience, to ride out the ridicule
until the show came into its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last laugh? I wouldn't be presumptuous enough, you know,
to come out here and say, `Well, it's done, and we won,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although, if you want to put that in your column, that's fine
with me. In fact, that's a great headline ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
