r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CBS-HNS &LR;      07-24 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK HORSE CBS IS CATCHING UP TO NBC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ If CBS ever does pass NBC to become the No. 1
ranked network, it will be one of the most improbable stories of a
cobbled-together, who-would-have-guessed, beat-the-odds network.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, it's business as usual in Hollywood. Because
nobody ever expected CBS to be No. 1 again for a long, long time.
Failure is almost a given with the network's built-in handicaps.
Suits _ and scribes _ never gave it a chance, saying things like
``CBS is the network of old people,'' or ``CBS is for rural middle
Americans, and Madison Avenue likes young, urban-dwelling people.''
</P>
<P>
   Or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Why would they think otherwise? Can a network ride a safe little
drama about angels to the top? Can it get there on the backs of the
geriatric journalists from ``60 Minutes''?
</P>
<P>
   This is a network whose only returning shows among those that
debuted last season were midseason replacements _ ``The Magnificent
Seven,'' which didn't exactly win the West, and ``Kids Say the
Darndest Things,'' a retread hosted by Bill Cosby, whose other main
show on CBS has sputtered badly. Everything else? Gone.
</P>
<P>
   And who would have thought there'd be a day that the once-proud
Tiffany Network would win only 36 Emmy nominations, just one more
than Fox?
</P>
<P>
   Bleak times, you say? Nonsense, says Leslie Moonves, president
and chief executive of CBS Television. This guy is motivated. He's
a believer. He knows he almost had it last year, but all the
disparate pieces weren't there. He smelled first place. Now he
couldn't be any hungrier.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Moonves is alone on an island with his beliefs,
his vision of transforming this baggage-laden network that he
inherited. But there are still plenty of tickets available to his
sermon, let's just say that.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the thing. It could happen. It's ludicrous and
unlikely, but the money here says don't count CBS out in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of total viewers,'' Moonves said, ``in the 1995-96
season, we trailed NBC by 3.5 million viewers; 1996-97, we trailed
by 1.4 million viewers. This past season, we trailed them by less
than 800,000 viewers. Without `Seinfeld,' without football, we
think we're going to do much better this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he took the hit on last season: ``It wasn't our best
development year. There were a lot of disappointments,'' he said.
``Some of them had to do with scheduling, some of them had to do
with demographic problems on our network, and some of them had to
do with the fact that the shows just weren't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does he win with that hand? He gains from NBC's weakness,
obviously. Football brings in male viewers _ exactly the people
missing from CBS. ``Thirty-five and younger men weren't watching
anything on CBS over the last four years. We lost that group almost
entirely. Our demographics were horrific in that group. So it hurt
Letterman, it hurt the news, it hurt all the places where there was
potential for those demographics to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS will use football to market other shows to male viewers. The
network is predicting, seriously, ``6 billion impressions'' over an
entire football season.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   That's marketing mumbo jumbo for ``we paid a lot of money for
football for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, the secret weapon. Moonves has led an almost solitary war
on the Madison Avenue standard of preaching to the youth market. He
doesn't have a youth market, so he's trying to change the system.
``And by the way, it's beginning to work,'' he says. ``It's not
happening fast enough for us, for our taste. But there is more and
more money being shifted to an older demographic _ 25 to 54s are
starting to take away from the 18 to 49s, and we hope that expands
even further. And that helps us immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   As for programs, there are very few standouts this season from
anybody, but CBS was the only network that passed on pilots from
major talent. If what they put on the air works, look out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's a package deal, and not a cogent, pretty package
at that. All those ugly elements have to come together. It's an
against-the-odds strategy. A miracle in the making.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain: Moonves believes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
