<HEADER>
A1183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-RYAN-2-HN     07-24 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-RYAN-2-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN': WAR AT ITS BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A man's leg flies off. A bullet tears another man's brains out.
A soldier lies in the sand, clutching his own entrails; ``Mama!''
he calls out. ``Mama! Mama!''
</P>
<P>
   A medic stanches the blood pouring from the bony stump of a
young troop's shoulder. An officer drags a comrade to safety, only
to look back and find that his friend's been blown to shreds. A
radio controller's face is gutted by gunfire. A one-armed soldier
searches the ground, then stoops to recover his missing hand. He
carries it away.
</P>
<P>
   So begins the assault on Omaha Beach, D-Day, June 6, 1944. And
so begins the assault on the audience: The 25-minute opening scene
(following a small preamble) of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Steven
Spielberg's stark, sickening, rivetingly ugly portrait of war and
the costs of heroism.
</P>
<P>
   It is a ghastly masterpiece. To watch is to feel both attracted
and repelled drawn in by the power of Spielberg's filmmaking,
repulsed by the face of death. The film dares us to see what
soldiers see in battle. It dares us to stick our hands into a gory
chest cavity, or place a blood-filled helmet on our head, or
casually murder surrendering Germans. It dares us, and we accept.
</P>
<P>
   War is a grotesque seductress.
</P>
<P>
   What a disturbing thing this film is: hideous yet beautiful,
elegant and compassionate and nauseating and black. Like
``Schindler's List'' and portions of ``Amistad'' before it,
``Saving Private Ryan'' is proof positive that the cinema's most
beguiling fantasist has changed, these last few years, into its
most brutal and gifted realist.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone always knew Spielberg could tell a story. But until
``Schindler,'' no one had an inkling what he might do with
history's cruelest lessons. The answer was: Show them to us. And
move us to horror.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of it all is the conflicted Capt. Miller, a role
filled with complexity and profound ease by Tom Hanks. Having
survived Omaha Beach, Miller is ordered to penetrate Nazi-occupied
France in a quest to find and return home Pvt. James Ryan (played,
once he materializes, by a pin-straight Matt Damon), whose three
brothers have just been killed in combat.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, ``Ryan'' is about everything war, humanity,
cruelty, death. In another, it's about nothing the plot whirls
around a mostly unseen goal (the titular Private Ryan), much the
way a Hitchcock thriller revolves around an invisible plot device.
The object isn't nearly as significant as the chase; and the chase,
during wartime, is a struggle with battalions of competitors but no
clear winner. It's vague but mortal mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Among the film's many virtues is its restraint in portraying
grief: Spielberg gives us just one glimpse of mother Ryan
collapsing to her knees in sorrow over her dead sons. That's all he
needs to show us. That's all we need to see before we, too,
collapse in tears. And ``Ryan'' is an excrutiatingly painful film.
</P>
<P>
   Once the rescue begins, the action is almost beyond description
_ it's all guns and bombs and bloodshed but what saves the film
from numbing sameness is its honestly sympathetic cast of
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and his men are people worth following: the steady Sgt.
Horvath (Tom Sizemore, of ``The Relic'' and ``Natural Born
Killers''), the bitter Pvt. Reiben (Edward Burns, convincingly
snide), the naive Cpl. Upham (Jeremy Davies, desperate and
brittle), the hotshot Pvt. Jackson (Barry Pepper), the decent Pvt.
Caparzo (Vin Diesel), the sensitive medic Wade (Giovanni Ribisi)
and the sardonic Pvt. Mellish (Adam Goldberg, ripping with anger).
</P>
<P>
   Mellish shows off his Star of David to German POWs. ``Juden,''
he says, pointing to himself, as they march sullenly past.
</P>
<P>
   To say that some of these characters die before saving Pvt. Ryan
gives nothing away. More remarkable than their deaths on the field
of battle is how deeply the audience cares about them. Dialogue
(from Robert Rodat's brilliant, fact-based screenplay) is minimal
and terse; the most profound moments are echoing caverns of
subtext. When Ribisi's medic wonders why, as a boy, he pretended to
sleep when his mother wanted to chat, his eyes say what the rest of
him doesn't: That he might die. That he might not ever talk to his
mother again.
</P>
<P>
   There's room for a lot of rich acting between the lines. Ribisi
is a marvel of conscience and quivering pain, while Sizemore, as
the group's weathered second-in-command, is one of the film's
sturdiest emotional ballasts. Everyone gets a nod for
understatement, even Burns, whose slick-urban-jerk routine (see
``The Brothers McMullen'') is effectively muted by shellfire.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Hanks who holds the film together; it's Hanks whose
tired eyes betray the moral and physical fatigue of war. Capt.
Miller is simply the truest, deepest, most dexterous
characterization of his career, previous Oscars included. He might
win another one.
</P>
<P>
   Janusz Kaminski's extraordinary cinematography is just as
evocative here as it was in ``Schindler's List.'' It's in muted
color this time, but it has the same bluntness of shading and view,
like a ``March of Time'' newsreel unspooled for modern audiences.
There is no more powerful way to portray atrocities than to shoot
them, foursquare, with the impartial eye of a camera. It makes them
all the more startling. In fact, whole stretches of the Omaha Beach
scene and later battle sequences were shot by hand-held cameras
equipped with old-style shutters, giving the film's goriest
episodes the jangly feel of an old documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The result is beyond realism: It's hyper-realism, realism buzzed
on panic. Red spatters the soldiers' uniforms. It spatters their
helmets, their eyes, their hands. And it spatters the camera,
dirtying our view and forcing us to face, up front, the angry blood
of war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
