<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-CLASSROOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCHOOL WITHOUT WALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ To see how much, and how quickly, the world
can change, one need look no further than a lecture hall close by
the Charles River.
</P>
<P>
   The students here comfortably chat among themselves, listen
intently to their teachers, take notes, and invariably laugh
easily. It seems like any classroom at just about any university,
except that the participants share a history of hate, distrust, and
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite remarkable, isn't it?'' said one of the 35
attendees, all of whom are senior officials of the major political
parties in Northern Ireland, the Republic of Ireland, and Great
Britain. Their weeklong series of seminars at Harvard's John F.
Kennedy School of Government, which ends today, was their first
opportunity to interact as a group since May's historic referendums
supporting the Irish peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The most important, telling aspect of their convergence clearly
was the lack of tension, and even the onset of camaraderie, among
the players who have long occupied opposite _ and hostile _ sides
of the Northern Ireland political ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, when the Kennedy School held its last
executive program for Irish and British leaders, the Democratic
Unionist Party flat-out didn't attend while members of the Ulster
Unionist Party wouldn't engage in conversation with their
counterparts from Sinn Fein, and a photo of all the attendees
proved impossible to arrange; the hardline DUP is represented this
year, and a group picture was taken Monday as a matter of course,
rather than as a result of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of collegiality and engagement and informality, from
my perspective...is significantly greater than it was two years
ago,'' said Marty Linsky, a Kennedy School lecturer who led the
Irish politicians Thursday in a morning-long discussion of
leadership. ``My sense...is that people are more willing to engage,
regardless of political affiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   None of which is to say that the anxieties and strains
surrounding one of the world's longest-running conflicts simply
evaporated in Cambridge this week. But, strikingly, those
sensitivities emanated far more clearly from Kennedy School
administrators than from any of the participants.
</P>
<P>
   For example, program officials established ground rules from the
start, to which the participants agreed, prohibiting them from
talking to the press.
</P>
<P>
   At The Globe's request, a reporter was permitted to sit in for
brief periods in a couple of classes this week. Though the rules
were that none of the participants could be quoted, their interplay
and discussion _ and even their positioning, with representatives
of historic adversaries sitting comfortably next to each other _
illustrated how far attitudes have progressed, notwithstanding the
continuing difficulties between Catholics and Protestants in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The stated reason for the high level of caution in Cambridge
itself revealed a concern about the fragility of the new, more
optimistic Irish reality: The intent was to keep the assembled
politicians from saying anything provocative that might start a
public tiff, thereby undercutting the positive atmosphere that the
Kennedy School was trying to foster.
</P>
<P>
   However, the participants and organizers are holding a press
conference at noon today, in the program's final hours.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants in this year's session, entitled ``The
New Political Architecture: A Workshop for Leaders from Northern
Ireland, the Republic of Ireland, and Great Britain,'' were 13
members of the new New Northern Ireland Assembly and three members
of the Republic of Ireland's Parliament. The project was sponsored
jointly by the New York-based Foundation for a Civil Society and by
the Kennedy School.
</P>
<P>
   Representing 16 political parties were such diverse and key
players as David Ervine of the Progressive Unionist Party; Gary
McMichael of the Ulster Democratic Party; Monica McWilliams of the
Northern Ireland Women's Coalition; Edwin Poots of the Democratic
Unionist Party; Dennis Rogan of the Ulster Unionist Party; Dara
O'Hagan of Sinn Fein; and Nigel Warner of the Labor Party, a top
adviser to Britain's Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, Mo
Mowlam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying they're all talking to each other, but they're
all behaving in a very civilized manner,'' said Paul Arthur, a
professor at Ulster University and an adviser to this week's
events. Added Pete Zimmerman, director of the executive program at
the Kennedy School and a project organizer, ``There is a new sense
of seriousness of purpose among the participants this year.
Whatever they think of the particulars, these are people who know
the train is now moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
