<HEADLINE>
FOR GAY RIGHTS, A TOUGH ROAD AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been more than a year since the House took a
vote on legislation aimed at homosexuals. Now, suddenly, a cluster
of proposals is moving to a vote, and the city most associated with
gay rights _ San Francisco _ may take a hit.
</P>
<P>
   First up is a measure that enjoys broad conservative support and
would cut federal housing funds to San Francisco as long as firms
doing business with the city are required to provide domestic
partnership benefits to employees.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the San Francisco measure could come as early as
today. Over the next two weeks the House will vote on other
measures designed to roll back certain rights and protections
extended to gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   One of the votes will be on legislation to overturn an executive
order signed by President Clinton in May that outlaws
discrimination in federal hiring on the basis of sexual
orientation. The House is also set to consider whether to forbid
the District of Columbia from providing domestic partnership
benefits to its employees,and to weigh a prohibition on adoptions
by same-sex couples next week.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals have drawn fire from gay rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These efforts point to one thing,'' said David M. Smith,
senior strategist for the Human Rights Campaign. ``There's a
desperate attempt to make discrimination against gay people safe
and legal.''
</P>
<P>
   But opinion is divided on why there is a flurry of expected
votes. Some speculate it is part of an orchestrated attempt to
energize religious activists in the Republican Party, while others
say the string of votes is simply coincidence. Either way, many
lawmakers are leery of the votes _ and of appearing intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry how this will affect the way Americans vote in
Novemeber,'' said Carl Schmidt, vice president of government
affairs for the Capitol-area Log Cabin, a gay Republican group.
``Obviously there is a core group that will like this, but they'll
get hurt with moderate and swing voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers say Republican lawmakers are skittish
about the votes, while others see the forced rollcalls as part of a
larger legislative scramble to appeal to the GOP's base of social
conservatives before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the Republican leadership's effort to solidify
their support with the religious right, which has made known its
displeasure with the Republican Congress's failure to deliver,''
said William Schneider, public policy analyst at the American
Enterprise Institute, a conservative Washington think tank. ``While
there is controversy, the fact is Americans don't get as upset
about gay rights as abortion rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The succession of votes comes one week after a coalition of
influential Christian groups launched a high-profile ad campign
attacking homosexuality. Earlier, Senate majority leader Trent Lott
likened gays to kleptomaniacs and alcoholics, and House majority
leader Richard Armey called homosexuals ``sinners.''
</P>
<P>
   These remarks were met by an outcry from moderate Republicans,
and some in the GOP have expressed concern over a possible backlash
if the party is perceived as antigay. The Republican leadership is
not actively promoting the measures, and even lawmakers openly
aligned with the religious right are balking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will support the effort, but on the merits of the issue,''
said Representative Joseph R. Pitts, a Pennsylvania Republican who
spearheads the Values Action Team set up in the wake of a series of
meetings this spring between the Republican leadership and a
coalition of religious groups demanding action on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Pitts said conservatives support an amendment
sponsored by Representative Joel Hefley, a Colorado Republican, to
overturn Clinton's executive order because ``homosexuals shouldn't
have special rights because of the lifestyle they've chosen.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans insisted the multiple votes are simply
coincidence, rather than an orchestrated campaign. With Congress
rushing to act on spending bills before the August recess,
lawmakers are trying to attach amendments to the must-pass
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for things to do,'' said Representative Barney
Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat. ``Their calculation is that gays
and lesbians are a small enough minority so there are fewer
negative political consequences in going after us ... but they
underestimated resistance to this kind of gay-bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank suggested that the spate of legislation may be an effort
to place conservative activists like James Dobson, who threatened
to bolt the Republican Party if it continued to stray from its
conservative roots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLS-MURDER-BOS &LR;      07-24 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLS-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH PENALTY OPPONENTS TAKE PERSONAL STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Mario Cuomo is ever murdered, he wants his killer
to be pursued and prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   But not to die.
</P>
<P>
   And, to make his feelings perfectly clear, the former three-term
governor _ who was discussed for many years as a likely Democratic
presidential candidate or a Supreme Court justice _ has attached a
notarized statement to his will.
</P>
<P>
   It reads: ``I hereby declare that should I die as a result of a
violent crime, I request that the person or persons found guilty
for my killing not be subject to or put in jeopardy of the death
penalty under any circumstances, no matter how heinous their crime
or how much I have suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 10,000 people across the country have signed a
statement just like this, according to a nun in Brooklyn, Sister
Camille D'Arienzo, who came up with the idea for it.
</P>
<P>
   D'Arienzo and a group of other local nuns, priests, and lay
Catholics started meeting during the 1994 governor's race, when it
seemed the death penalty _ which had not been administered in New
York State for nearly 30 years _ was headed for a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   She and her colleagues are planning to redouble their efforts
now, as New York's death-penalty law _ which was signed in 1995 by
Cuomo's successor, George E. Pataki, just months after he took over
as governor _ is starting to be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The revival began last month, when a jury in Brooklyn convicted
a man of killing three people and then sentenced him to die by
lethal injection. Thursday, a jury in Poughkeepsie declined to
execute a man it had found guilty of multiple murders. A half-dozen
more capital cases await trial sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her office at the Convent of Mercy, a 136-year-old
structure in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn, D'Arienzo
recalled the discussions four years ago, when her group was getting
involved in the issue. ``We were looking for something that was not
didactic but that expressed the depths of our concern,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The group came up with the idea of the document, which it
called, ``Declaration of Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of it is that it somewhat minimizes the sense of
powerlessness we have,'' said D'Arienzo, who runs the convent and
also serves as president-elect of the Leadership Conference of
Women Religionists, which represents over 90 percent of American
nuns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not changed the structure or the government,'' she
said. ``Some of us cannot claim to have changed a relative or close
friend. But this is what we believe. This is where we stand firm.
It's a very private statement, but it's also very public.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo was asked by D'Arienzo to sign the declaration in the
spring of 1994, shortly before his bid for reelection to a fourth
term _ which he ended up losing, in part, many pollsters say,
because of his outspoken opposition to the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed it immediately,'' he recalled. ``I had no hesitancy
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, now a practicing lawyer, acknowledged that the document
is not legally binding. However, he added, ``I am a believer in
victims' rights. It's appropriate to consult the victims or their
relatives in deciding a defendant's punishment. In capital cases, a
relative or a prosecutor sometimes says the death penalty would do
justice to the deceased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, in my case,'' he went on, a bit more emphatically,
``they're not going to be able to make that argument because I
don't consider it justice. If I get murdered and if victims' rights
have anything to do with the sentence, my posthumous poetry shall
be useful to the question.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Cuomo said, the district attorney prosecuting his
murder case, knowing such a document existed, would not seek the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Doyle, director of the Capital Defender Office in New
York, which offers legal counsel to defendants in death-penalty
cases, said, ``In New York, DAs would be likely to take that into
consideration, but it would be unlikely that they would publicly
state that as part of their rationale for not seeking death.'' At
the same time, in parts of other states, Doyle added, ``it might
not have any impact at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle and D'Arienzo said they know of no murder trial where the
declaration has been offered into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cuomo signed the declaration over four years ago, he
has taken no steps to publicize his action. He did suggest that
D'Arienzo ask Carolyn McCarthy _ whose husband was murdered in the
1993 Long Island Railroad massacre _ to sign it, which she did.
McCarthy, who became a gun-control advocate, has since been elected
to the US House of Representatives. Her life story was recently
made into a television movie.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have signed it include actors Martin Sheen and Mike
Farrell and Sister Helen Prejean, who wrote the book, ``Dead Man
Walking.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Arienzo said she has no idea how many people around the
country have signed it, though she has records of about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the US Supreme Court ruled in 1976 that capital
punishment was constitutional, 470 executions have taken place, 155
of them _ nearly one-third _ in Texas. An additional 3,300 sit on
death row, according to the Death Penalty Information Center in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The New York law gives district attorneys the discretion to seek
the death penalty in cases involving any of 12 types of
first-degree murder. If they do not ask for the death penalty, the
defendant, if found guilty, must go to prison for life with no
possibility of parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
