<HEADER>
A1197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOBSTER-DEPLETE-ART-B     07-24 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBSTER-DEPLETE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOLOGISTS SAY LOBSTER LEVEL IN A PINCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lobster, New England's most valuable seafood, has been a godsend
to depressed fishing communities, providing record catches at a
time when overfishing has decimated other fish populations. While
some fishermen have sold their boats and trained for new careers,
lobstermen from Stonington, Maine, to Marshfield, Mass. have been
putting out more traps.
</P>
<P>
   Now, biologists warn that the lobster trap ``arms race'' has
pushed the lobster population to the brink of a collapse that could
be worse than the one that closed much of Georges Bank in 1994.
Most female lobsters are caught before they can reproduce, the
researchers warn, meaning that lobster fanciers truly may be eating
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very disturbing trends ... which are similar to
trends we have seen in other fisheries before their catastrophic
decline,'' said Steven Murawski, biologist at the National Marine
Fisheries Service in Woods Hole, Mass. ``There's no way in God's
green earth that these catches could be sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal biologists calculate that lobstermen are catching at
least twice as many lobsters as is sustainable. As a result, most
of the big lobsters are gone and almost 90 percent of today's catch
is barely above the minimum legal size.
</P>
<P>
   But many lobstermen reject the gloomy predictions, arguing that
their abundant catches are a more reliable indicator than the soft
``Jello statistics'' of scientists. Last year, northeastern
lobstermen brought in a record 84 million pounds of lobster, though
the Massachusetts catch declined, and lobstermen say there is no
shortage of breeding females.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catches keep going up ... and some go down a little, but
they don't go crashing down. It's pretty stable. So fishermen say,
`OK, what's the problem?''' said William Adler of the Massachusetts
Lobstermen's Association, who questions the biologists' study
methods.
</P>
<P>
   Adler and other lobstermen agree that there are too many lobster
traps in the water, but they are sharply divided over what steps to
take. Only last week, four southern Maine lobstermen won an
injunction to block an 800-trap limit per fisherman put forward by
a state-backed panel of lobstermen.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of meaningful limits, lobstermen feel pressed to
add traps to match the competition. ``If you want to play the game,
you've got to keep up,'' said Rich Fuller, the 26-year-old owner of
the Kerri Lee in Scituate, Mass. ``I'm not going to fish 400
(traps) when everyone else is fishing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists fear that lobstermen and their regulators have
begun a painful replay of the paralyzing debate that preceded the
population crash of the cod, once so important to Massachusetts'
economy that a Sacred Cod hangs on the wall above the state House
of Representatives. Now, cod is worth less than a third of the $65
million Massachusetts lobsters bring in.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, officials at the National Marine Fisheries
Service say a lobster crash would be worse than the cod collapse
because lobsters reproduce so slowly. They said the better
comparison is the Alaska red king crab, whose population has not
recovered more than 15 years after the population drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fish can grow up very fast, but a lobster takes five to
seven years. It would be catastrophic if there was a (lobster)
crash,'' said National Marine Fisheries spokeswoman Teri Frady.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other seafood, American lobster is the symbol of
maritime New England, the creature behind those postcard villages
of shingled lobster shacks, colorful buoys and traps piled on the
pier. The rocky, cold waters of Maine account for more than half
the nation's lobster catch, and 87 percent of the lobsters are
caught in New England, providing 20,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But lobstering, once an ideal small business, has gone
increasingly large-scale as the catch doubled from 37.2 million
pounds in 1980 to 84 million pounds last year. Until Maine adopted
a limit of 1,200 traps, some fishermen were tending up to 2,000
traps, and overall trap totals soared to 2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, the second-leading lobster state, sets a more
restrictive limit of 800 traps, but lobstermen say there is so
little enforcement that lobstermen violate it with impunity, or
fish in federal waters where the state limit doesn't hold.
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly trap-covered waters have heightened conflicts
between fishermen in the territorial world of lobstering.
Lobstermen from two villages in Maine needed a state mediator to
resolve a fight over fishing rights off Monhegan Island last year,
while a Northport, N.Y., man suspected his boat was bombed for
invading another lobsterman's territory.
</P>
<P>
   But the local nature of the business makes it difficult to end
the trap escalation. Though the National Marine Fisheries Service
has legal power over fishing more than 3 miles offshore, 80 percent
of lobsters are caught in state waters. The New England Fishery
Management Council, in turn, could not win state support for its
plan, so the task fell to the Atlantic States Marine Fisheries
Commission in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, dominated by state officials from Maine to
Florida, has proposed a phased-in trap limit of 800, still more
than the 400 to 600 traps most lobstermen set and more than what
the National Marine Fisheries Service believes is needed. The
service suggests a limit of 480 traps, unless regulators take other
measures such as increasing the minimum legal size.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the minimum size would give young female lobsters more
time to produce eggs, but some lobstermen say the bigger minimum
creates more work than simply eliminating traps, making them toss
back more lobsters they've already caught.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all the proposed limits have drawn some objection,
including a lawsuit by large-scale southern Maine lobstermen who
argue that a local plan to go to the 800 trap limit immediately
would damage their livelihood. But the National Marine Fisheries
Service's 480 trap limit has been the real lightning rod.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make a living on 480 traps and I think there's a lot
of guys here who feel that way,'' said lobsterman David Merryman at
a hearing in Portland, Maine, in April. ``You're not just
regulating a fishery. You're regulating a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where the lobster catch has not grown like
Maine's, lobstermen are more receptive to low limits on traps or
other fishing limits, but they, too, differ on how far to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think fishing was ever meant to be a fulltime job,''
said lobsterman Joe Previte as he tied up his boat, The Puffin, in
Cohasset, Mass. Previte, who also works in construction, said he
would support a limit as low as 300 traps.
</P>
<P>
   But Scituate lobsterman Pat Patterson, who just bought his boat
last year, complained that part-timers undercut people who make a
living from lobsters. He said it would be more fair to have a lower
limit for part-timers and something higher than 480 for fulltimers
like himself.
</P>
<P>
   And Massachusetts state biologist Bruce Estrella warns that trap
limits are no cure-all, since lobstermen below the limit can keep
adding traps. He said measures such as an increase in the minimum
size of lobster may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   While the debate goes on, Boston Harbor lobstermen already feel
the pain that biologists fear could become widespread. Due to a
combination of overfishing and perhaps a change in water chemistry
caused by the harbor cleanup, Boston has fallen from first to fifth
in the state for lobster catch.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the once-full lobster pier in Hingham on Boston Harbor
has eight empty slips, and some lobstermen have had to find outside
work. ``The catch has been down ever since the cleanup started,''
said Shawn Cavanaugh of Weymouth, who has taken a night job at a
bank due to the lobster downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Though Boston Harbor is unique, Murawski warns that a crash
could come in two to three years if action isn't taken. The record
harvest of 1997, he said, was fueled by unusually favorable
conditions for lobster young that could disappear as swiftly as
they emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he said, lobstermen have banked their prosperity on
far too few lobster eggs. The National Marine Fisheries Service
estimates that egg production is less than 3 percent what it would
be in the absence of lobstering, and far below the bare minimum
legally required in federal waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fishery is right on the edge. It has no room for error,''
said Murawski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
