<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AGENTS-BOS &LR;      07-24 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AGENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AGENTS, CLINTONS, DUTIES AND PRIVATE LIVES MIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first signs of trouble came early: Hillary
Rodham Clinton, in her first months in the White House, reportedly
complained to friends that disloyal Secret Service agents had
falsely leaked word of a lamp-throwing fight between her and her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the style of Clinton's presidency took shape, there was
the risk of friction on many fronts between the president and the
elite corps of bodyguards assigned to protect him. Clinton insisted
on jogging through public streets in the busiest times of the
morning. He dined out often _ and spontaneously _ at night. Even
now, he rarely sees a crowd of people he doesn't want to meet.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last several years, agents and White House
officials said the Clintons have grown increasingly comfortable
with the sometimes suffocating presence of Secret Service agents in
almost every facet of their lives. Likewise, agents said the
bodyguards have grown more comfortable with the Clintons _ a fact
which underscores the irony of their present predicament, compelled
to testify before the Grand Jury investigating Clinton's private
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see firsthand how relationships and friendships form
between both sides,'' said Doug Sosnik, a Clinton adviser. ``I
would expect that in a transition to a new president. It takes a
while to get comfortable with each other. There's an adjustment
that everyone has to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Secret Service officials concede it is a tough adjustment
indeed _ not just for the Clintons, but for any new president
arriving in the White House. Agents stand watch in the residence
while the president sleeps. They shadow him wherever he goes,
inside the complex and out. And they occasionally search through
the sock drawers to make sure a listening device or chemical weapon
has not been planted inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a family dispute, they see and hear it all,'' said
Ron Noble, a former undersecretary for enforcement at the Treasury
Department, which oversees the Secret Service. ``They see your
underwear. There is really nothing that they don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is exactly why Independent Counsel Kenneth W.
Starr has coveted their cooperation. The same agents who are
required to throw themselves in the path of a bullet for the
president will now be required to share what, if anything, they
know of the secrets tucked away in the deepest recesses of
Clinton's life, particularly his relationship with former White
House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Larry Cockell, the lead Secret Service agent on the
presidential protection detail, became the first plainclothes agent
in the history of the department to testify before a grand jury
about the president he is charged to protect, answering questions
for just over an hour at the US District Court here.
</P>
<P>
   Starr won a prolonged court battle with the Clinton
administration last week over the testimony, and uniformed Secret
Service officers have already testified in the last few days.
Cockell and the officers, through their attorneys, have said they
will answer all questions put to them.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service officials and even former president George Bush
have warned that such forced testimony could have a catastrophic
impact on Clinton and his successors, spurring presidents to put
more distance between themselves and the Secret Service agents.
That distance, officials have warned, could cost bodyguards their
most effective weapon against a potential assassin: proximity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is already a day-to-day dilemma about how close the Secret
Service can get,'' said Philip Melanson, a political science
professor at the University of Massachusetts at Dartmouth and the
author of the book, ``The Politics of Protection: The US Secret
Service in the Terrorist Age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they get in the photo or outside the office or how
distant will they be? Any president now has to think, `What is the
Secret Service overhearing, and what in the realm of my personal
and policy-making life might be important?'''
</P>
<P>
   Agents still rue President Kennedy's refusal to drive through
Dallas in 1963 with a bulletproof glass top on his limousine, as
well as his order that agents could not ride on the rear bumper of
his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We begged him to put his bubble on top of the car, and he
refused because it was a political function, and we begged him to
put agents on the back bumpers,'' said Hamilton Brown, a retired
agent who worked on Kennedy's protective detail. ``He said people
were there to see him, not the agents.''
</P>
<P>
   To gain the desired degree of proximity, agents in the
presidential detail have donned an umpire's uniform at a baseball
game where the president is throwing the first pitch, dressed as a
graduating college student in cap and gown for a presidential
commencement address, even as a priest in clerical collar when the
pope last toured the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the White House, agents tend to be slightly more at ease
about covering the president, given the intense security they have
at the perimeter of the building and the searches of people coming
and going. It is when Clinton travels outside the gates that they
are especially attuned to trouble.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is meeting with just a small group, agents will stand
outside the door. If the gathering is larger, maybe a dozen people
or more, agents will stand inconspicuously inside, always silent.
</P>
<P>
   The plainclothes Secret Service agents assigned to the
presidential protection detail are the elite members of a law
enforcement group that prides itself on its work. They are required
to pass constant physical examinations, spend dizzying hours
performing brutally boring work, and, in the extremity, to
sacrifice their own lives to save the president's.
</P>
<P>
   The male agents always dress in impeccable dark suits, their
hair neatly trimmed, sunglasses ever shading their eyes. They speak
only when spoken to. Their allegiance, they say, is not to the
particular president, but to the job. As an example, Noble, the
former Treasury official notes, ``On Inauguration Day, the same
agents leave the White House with one president and come back with
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cockell, who was temporarily replaced last week as the
lead agent, and Clinton are often seen chatting amiably and joking.
When Clinton works a rope line, shaking hands and leaning into a
crowd, Cockell stands behind him and literally holds onto his belt,
prepared to pull him back should the president fall or be grabbed,
or to shove him to the ground to avoid an assassin.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton is chauffeured around town in his motorcade,
Cockell sits in the front of the presidential limousine, beside the
driver. And when Clinton jets around the country and the world on
Air Force One, Cockell and a second agent sit in a business class
seat just outside the presidential study.
</P>
<P>
   Agents typically work for a half dozen years or more in a field
office before being moved to the White House. Once there, they are
usually rotated out every four to five years. A president has no
say whatsoever in his protective detail. Even the detail directors
are always chosen from within the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Though they have arrived at the pinnacle of their careers by
joining the presidential detail, agents will sometimes be required
to stand for hours at a time watching nothing more than a hallway
in a hotel. Other times, they must frantically search a crowd for
potential trouble, the sounds of six agents' voices filling their
earpieces with word of something irregular.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go to work with the idea it's going to be a mundane
day,'' said Arnett Heintz, a Secret Service agent and spokesman.
``You have to be prepared. You are responsible for protecting the
president of the United States. If you screw that up, you have
quite a mess on your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who argue that such protection is unncessary, agents
quickly warn that four presidents _ about 10 percent of the men who
have ascended to the position _ have been assassinated. And more
recently, President Gerald Ford was shot at twice and President
Reagan once. In the Reagan assassination attempt in 1981, an agent
was struck by a bullet trying to protect the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1306EDT &QL; 
