<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1202 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-BOS &LR;      07-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI CAMPAIGN CONSIDERING SHIFT TO ATTACK MODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paul Cellucci's political advisers are debating an
abrupt change in campaign strategy as polls show the acting
governor is vulnerable to two of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and his advisers are considering dumping his
above-the-fray, Rose Garden campaign plan in favor of direct
attacks against Scott Harshbarger, according to close friends and
advisers to Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Although both Cellucci and Harshbarger face gubernatorial
primary opponents in September, Cellucci strategists say they
believe Harshbarger will win the Democratic nomination and that
Cellucci will easily defeat his primary opponent, Treasurer Joseph
D. Malone.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers also said that Harshbarger's constant criticism of
Cellucci has been taking a toll _ as reflected in recent polling
data _ and has gone unanswered for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting clearer by the day that this is a two-person race
and it's Governor Cellucci against Attorney General Harshbarger,''
said state Senator Brian P. Lees, the East Longmeadow Republican
who talks frequently to Cellucci. ``You have to begin to move into
full campaign mode after the Legislature is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   And state Senator Richard R. Tisei, a Wakefield Republican who
is also close to Cellucci, agreed: ``He really has to start
concentrating on November and on Scott Harshbarger.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci may begin calling attention to Harshbarger's record
once the Legislature adjourns for the year on July 31, but no
formal decision by the campaign has been made. Nevertheless,
Cellucci recently struck out at Harshbarger over the issue of
testing teachers for competency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes or No, Scott?'' one press release from the Cellucci
campaign reads. ``Harshbarger has trouble answering whether or not
he will support Paul Cellucci's plan to test teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another press release from the Cellucci campaign declares,
``Cellucci campaign blasts Harshbarger's opposition to testing
teachers.'' The release included a transcript of Harshbarger
answering reporters' questions in which he said he supports testing
new teachers and an ``assessment program'' to evaluate current
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the governor's race got underway, Cellucci has
concentrated on showing he could govern. He ignored the barbs and
jibes from the Democrats _ Harshbarger, Patricia McGovern, and
Brian Donnelly _ and he brushed off his Republican opponent,
Malone. On the issues, Cellucci has stuck to a steady diet of
noncontroversial rhetoric, calling for tax cuts and demanding
better child care and more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a month of heavy political advertising by Cellucci
in June, a recent University of Massachusetts poll indicated that
both Harshbarger and McGovern have pulled almost even with the
acting governor.
</P>
<P>
   In separate head-to-head match-ups, Cellucci received 39 percent
of the 401 registered voters surveyed, compared to 34 percent for
Harshbarger and 34 percent for McGovern. The poll had a margin of
error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   While Cellucci may begin responding to charges and launching
some of his own criticism at Harshbarger, no plans have been made
yet to attack Harshbarger on television. Although Cellucci became
lieutenant governor 6 1/2 years ago and acting governor one year
ago, he is still not known well enough around the state to do much
more than introduce himself and his agenda to voters through his
ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person being held up to scrutiny at this point is
Paul Cellucci because no one else is considered credible,'' said
Jim Rappaport, the former chairman of the state Republican party
and a major contributor to Cellucci's campaign. ``It makes sense
now to go after Harshbarger. It's the right thing to do and allows
you to differentiate yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger for Harshbarger is that Cellucci will begin blasting
him on television and he won't be able to respond in kind.
Harshbarger, unlike Cellucci, agreed to a spending cap in order to
receive state matching funds. The cap limits Harshbarger to
spending no more than $1.5 million up until the Sept. 15 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, on the other hand, has $3.3 million in the bank. He
can spend as much as he'd like this summer, continue raising money,
and spend as much as he's able in the days leading up to the Nov. 3
general election.
</P>
<P>
   As he begins to speak out, the two issues Cellucci is likely to
raise against Harshbarger are taxes and education. Though
Harshbarger called for tax cuts for working families in December
1997, Cellucci can say that he has provided taxpayers with cuts 26
times as lieutenant governor and as acting governor. And he
recently signed the largest tax cut in Massachusetts history,
despite the fact that it looked nothing like his own proposal.
</P>
<P>
   On education, Cellucci will fight Harshbarger with talk about
high standards, for both teachers and students, and about school
choice for parents. ``Mr. Harshbarger, to date, has been in the
pocket of teachers' unions,'' Rappaport alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tisei cautioned that Cellucci cannot write off Malone
completely. ``But it really seems that Harshbarger has solidified
his position within the Democratic Party and you really have to
start looking at post-September,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent (Cellucci) can connect the dots and frame the
debate, that's going to be the key to victory in November,'' said
Tisei.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
