<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-GRANNIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING FOR THE GOLD _ AND THE FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEDYARD, Conn. _ Cigarette smoke hangs over the slot machines at
the Foxwoods Casino in a blue, surreal haze, adding a macabre veil
to the scene: Hundreds of senior citizens, some in wheelchairs,
others carrying oxygen tanks, many steadying themselves with
walkers or canes.
</P>
<P>
   All are pumping quarters into machines that gulp their money and
belch deafening whistles, bells, whirs, and, for the lucky, a
clanging change windfall that keeps them playing, robotic in their
movements, hoping to hit the Big One.
</P>
<P>
   The tops of the slot machines are littered with empty and
twisted quarter rolls, lipstick-stained coffee cups, overflowing
ashtrays, and plastic pillboxes compartmentalized by days of the
week and meals: BREAKFAST, LUNCH, DINNER.
</P>
<P>
   In the bathrooms, secured to the walls near the towel
dispensers, are locked plastic boxes beckoning biohazardous waste.
They are used-needle repositories provided by the casino as a
``convenient customer service'' for diabetic bettors who, between
the craps tables and the bingo hall, can duck in and give
themselves an insulin shot.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon at Foxwoods, where the overwhelming majority of
gamblers seem to be grandmas and grandpas, has the ambience of a
revved-up VFW hall Las Vegas night. But gambling has always been a
favorite pastime for the elderly, and in the 26 states where it is
legal, the dominant casino color scheme is gray. A 1997 national
survey done by Harrah's found that 27 percent of Americans over the
age of 55 went to a casino at least once that year.
</P>
<P>
   Squint through the smoke and look more closely. There is delight
on the faces of the players, who anticipate their trips as a Big
Day Out. The women wear freshly sprayed hairdos, new Easy Spirits,
and colorful jogging suits. The men are in Sans-a-Belt slacks, knit
tops, and a light splash of Old Spice.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, they are happy to be here. After all, they are out
of the house, socializing with other seniors, enjoying a huge
buffet for about $5, maybe staying the night to catch the Paul Anka
show, and getting a little thrill when they leave a few dollars
richer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, at our age, what's left to do?'' said Joseph DiNicola,
66, of Norwood, Mass., who took a chartered bus to Foxwoods with
his wife, Amelia, 65, and about 50 other seniors from the suburbs
south of Boston recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not high rollers here, or spending our pensions. We're
smarter than that,'' noted DiNicola, who saves his big money for an
annual trip to Vegas and budgets for his trips to Foxwoods. ``It's
just the ladies with the bluish hair and the men with the gray.
There are the bingo junkies and slot-lovers and everyone is just
looking to kill the day with a little entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either that or sit home and watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are 175 deluxe motor coaches that pick up and deliver
patrons from all over New England to Foxwoods every 15 minutes or
so, every day. The Entertainment Tours bus company out of
Braintree, Mass. is one of 45 bus lines from Massachusetts that, in
the six years since Foxwoods has opened, have been bringing bettors
to the Connecticut woods. There are four buses a day that service
Boston's Chinatown alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although casino officials say the average age of a Foxwoods
bettor is 40, hundreds of gamblers waiting curbside for motor
coaches to take them home one afternoon recently were resoundingly
retirees.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, the average age of the bus crowd is about 60,
according to Donald Little, an Entertainment Tours driver, who,
after dropping off his passengers and servicing the bus, goes off
duty and engages in a few games of seven-card stud (limiting his
spending, he swears, to the $30 his wife allows).
</P>
<P>
   Little, 36, called his charges ``very well behaved,'' but
anxious, always, to get there and get winning. Indeed, when the
last passengers were picked up in Foxborough, Mass. during a recent
seven-town run that began in Quincy, Mass., a woman in the back
yelled, ``Go like hell now!'' when the doors closed behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are not expecting to win a lot of money. They're
just going for a good time,'' Little said. ``But they do go a lot.
I know almost everyone on this bus by name. Sometimes one of them
will get back on the bus at the end of the day with a new Buick or
$5,000 in their pockets. That's nice to see. They're good people
just out to have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   But good times, especially when gambling is involved, can lead
to trouble. The national organization Gamblers Anonymous says that
it does not categorize addiction populations, but given the small
amount of money it takes someone on a fixed income to fall into
debt, many elderly are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Although specialists say that 4 to 5 percent of all people who
bet are compulsive gamblers, problem gambling among the elderly is
on the rise. A number of states report increased calls to their
gambling hot lines from and about the elderly. In New Jersey, where
Atlantic City casinos in that state have long lured older gamblers,
the local chapter of the National Council on Problem Gamblers views
elderly gambling addiction enough of a problem to offer outreach
programs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roland Curry, 70, is in his element: Up $50 in a game of
seven-card stud, a free drink at his side, a fresh pack of Camels
in his pocket. He's sharing a few laughs around the Foxwoods Casino
gaming table with other gray-haired grandpas _ one chewing on a
toothpick, one missing the tip of his index finger, another, his
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, a retired grocery store security guard from Roslindale,
Mass., headed for the Poker Room after arriving on the Quincy bus.
He left the table only once in six hours, to attend a $1,000
drawing on the other side of the casino. Players must be present to
win. He was there, but lost. That's the way it goes. Poker's his
game anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Since his wife died, Curry goes to Foxwoods five or six times a
month, as much for the company as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this grandfather of 12, great-grandfather of 2, is a
gambler. Always has been. Sometimes he plays the slots or
blackjack, but only when the poker table takes more than it gives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't limit myself to any amount of money, I just make sure
I have enough to hold me out,'' said Curry. ``Five hundred has been
my biggest win. But I don't really come for the money. If I weren't
here, I'd have to get a part-time job or something, just to have
something to do, to be around people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Tufo of Walpole, Mass. fairly flew off the bus in search of
the exact ``Double Black Jack'' slot machine she won $960 on during
last week's trip. She walked by it that day, got a good-luck
feeling in her gut, and it paid off. This week, though, no matter
how much she fed it, ``Double Black Jack'' kept its money close to
the vest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think you could do a repeat, but it's just not happening
for me today,'' said Tufo, 67, who works part time as a bookkeeper
in her sons' company for extra cash to come to Foxwoods, while she
continued to slip quarters into the machine, hoping one would hit
the spot. Or, better, the bells or the cherries or the sevens.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't come to be social, usually. There's too much
concentrating to be done. On this day, though, she has baked some
cookies for a woman she's befriended on this bus route, but her
seat is empty today and Tufo is worried that she might be ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a sweet woman,'' said Tufo, a redhead with a big, easy
smile. ``We're both gamblers and we have that in common. Myself, I
have a bum leg. But gambling is good for people who are sick. You
can do it sitting down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tufo has won big at Foxwoods. A $10,000 jackpot on the slots
last year has her favoring Ledyard over Vegas, her former haunt.
There were a couple of big winners this time, resulting in a very
buoyant mood on the bus ride home.
</P>
<P>
   One woman scored $1,000 at a Wheel of Fortune game, and a man
won $900 at blackjack. Curry, the retired security guard, missed
the bus entirely. Everyone hoped it was because he had a hot hand,
and was ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Tufo admits to overspending her limits, getting into a little
financial trouble every now and then. But she says she punishes
herself by staying off the bus for a couple of weeks, building the
reserves back up, and promising she won't do it again.
</P>
<P>
   But she always comes back.
</P>
<P>
   How much has she won today? ``Not enough.'' How much has she
lost? ``Honey, I don't even tell God that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
