<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAKES ARE SKY-HIGH IN `PI' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
PI 
Written and directed by: Darren Aronofsky 
Starring: Sean Gullette, Mark Margolis, Ben Shenkman, Pamela Hart,
Stephen Pearlman, Sonia Shoaib, Ajay Naidu 
Running time: 85 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some disturbing images) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darren Aronofsky's ``Pi'' is the kind of feverish mind-bender I
wish the ``X-Files'' movie had been. Filmed in high-contrast
black-and-white, it's a hyperkinetic film about a hyperkinetic
protagonist, a numbers freak named Max Cohen who's convinced that
if he sits in his slummy walkup tickling his patched-together
homemade computers long enough and intensely enough, he'll discover
the numerical basis of the pattern of the universe. He's interested
in finding God, but it hasn't escaped the notice of others that he
may also have tapped into the key to, among other things, the stock
market and the Kabbalah.
</P>
<P>
   This brings him into contact with a pack of Wall Street traders
and a Hassidic sect. Although both camps are made up of renegades,
they have little in common except for being haunted by the feeling
that they can't take the chance that weird Max isn't on to
something. So they take turns pursuing him. Max, for respite, seeks
timeouts with his old prof, and rides the subways, favoring the
stops lit by fluorescent lights, the glare of which Aronofsky's
camera revels in. Aronofsky's film rides the grittiness of its very
downtown sensibility, including a techno soundtrack which lends
itself to Max's not quite deranged single-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   There's a nice tongue-in-cheek implied contrast between the
frenetic dartings of Max and his ever more tightly-wound pursuers
and the key-to-it-all secret pattern he feels he's on the verge of
uncovering. Beyond that, Sean Gullette's Max draws us into the
dance he does on the thin line between advanced enlightenment and
madness in his claustrophobic digs. Mind racing, too revved up to
sleep, Gullette's Max quickly persuades us he's not just any
crackpot. Certainly, Aronofsky's ``Pi'' is not just any sci-fi
movie. Unlike most would-be specimens of the genre, this one,
firmly ensconced on the ``Eraserhead''-``Rhythm Thief'' axis,
convinces us it's wired from the inside out and that the juice is
sizzling through its circuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
