<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A STRUGGLE TO REMAIN A CARD-CARRYING MEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ If it's going to rain for three hours, you've
got to do something other than what Richard Coughlan did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did nothing,'' he explained. ``I just sat and ate.''
</P>
<P>
   He played like it. After completing his 16th hole (No. 7 on the
Pleasant Valley CC course), a par 3, he finished bogey-bogey to
wind up the opening round of the CVS Charity Classic with a 3-over
74.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out flat,'' he lamented.
</P>
<P>
   There are guys who can afford to come out flat once in a while,
but 24-year-old Richard Coughlan is most assuredly not one of them.
The year is nearly half over and he is $168,010 short of the figure
he needs to maintain his precious PGA Tour card.
</P>
<P>
   And keeping the Tour card is merely the most important thing in
the young Irishman's life. If you do not keep your card, you are
thrown back into the shark-infested waters known as the PGA Tour
Qualifying School, the Q-School for short. We in the outside world
hear awful, horrible, stand-the-hairs-up-on-the-back-of-your-neck
things about the Q-School.
</P>
<P>
   So tell us, Richard Coughlan, is the Q-School as bad as we've
heard?
</P>
<P>
   ``Worse,'' he reported. ``If every round of golf felt like the
finishing holes of the Q-School, you wouldn't play. But I got
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. He finished 12th. He also picked up his European
Q-School card, although he hasn't had occasion to use it. As far as
he knows, he is the first person ever to come directly from college
(Clemson) and pick up both cards right out of the chute.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds nice and it looks good on the resume. But right now he
needs to put up some low scores and cash some checks. And an
opening-round 74 is not likely to make a cha-ching sound here.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlan arrived here direct from Madison, Miss., and a tie for
21st in the Deposit Guaranty Classic. He started that tournament
with a 74 also. But then he strung together rounds of 69, 67, and
68 for a 10-under 278, good for a career-high $12,000. He had fired
an 8-under 272 the week before that in the Quad City Classic. He
came here feeling good because those last two tournaments
represented his best golf in a long time, or since he shot a 286
(minus 2) in the Tucson Chrysler Classic back during the Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But he also arrived here tired. ``I should have taken a week
off, I guess,'' he said. ``But when you're playing well, you've got
to keep it rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   He is representative of life on the lower tier of the PGA Tour,
except that instead of arriving at Clemson from Florida or Georgia
or Virginia, he arrived there from Birr, a town of 5,000 in
little-known and nearly hidden County Offalay, smack in the center
of Ireland. ``It's next to Tipperary,'' he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   He had begun playing at age 12. No one pushed him into it.
Neither parent played golf, and he has no siblings. It was just
something he liked to do, and when the time came, he decided to
hone his game on an American campus. His choices sounded like those
of someone from the 5-Star Camp: North Carolina, Duke, Florida
State, Georgia Tech, and the school he wound up graduating from
with a psychology degree, Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   While at Clemson, he became a big Tiger football and basketball
fan, particularly football. The psychology degree? ``Just something
so I could get that piece of paper,'' he admitted. Hey, who among
us can't relate to that?
</P>
<P>
   He caddied for a 1991 US Walker Cup team that included Phil
Mickelson and David Duval, and at one point, he caddied for current
Tour fringe player Franklin Langham _ until Langham fired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was doing anything wrong,'' Coughlan shrugged.
``But I guess he didn't like my style, whatever it was. It was
nothing, really. He just wasn't playing well, and one day he just
fired me. Little did he know that five or six years later, he would
see me on the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that would come to pass, however, Coughlan would become a
Walker Cup player himself. ``I played eight matches last year,'' he
said. ``I halved four and I lost four tough ones. Overall, I played
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlan's blunt self-appraisal: ``I have a power game, really.
I need a better short game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's got to be a lonely existence. He has no real address, save
that of his college coach, Larry Penley. He is away from his
homeland and he is under the gun, because if he doesn't earn enough
money, the Q-School beckons yet again.
</P>
<P>
   He's got that European possibility, but it's obvious he wants
the Big Enchilada. He may not consider himself an American, but the
fact is he's just about lost his accent. When you spend four years
in a high-powered American college golf experience, your thoughts
do not turn easily back across the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Right now his life is all about numbers. He needs to make
$225,000 this year. He has made $56,990. He is ranked 176th. And
he'd sure like a 65 today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
