<HEADER>
A1206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MAFIA-BOS &LR;      07-24 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MAFIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAFIA PARODY HAS MORE MISSES THAN HITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
MAFIA! 
Directed by: Jim Abrahams 
Screenplay by: Abrahams, Greg Norberg, Michael McManus 
Starring: Jay Mohr, Lloyd Bridges, Olympia Dukakis, Christina
Applegate, Billy Burke, Pamela Gidley, Tony Lo Bianco, Joe
Viterelli 
Running time: 86 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (crude and sex-related humor, language, violence and
drug content) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to furlough the Mafia. If Jim Abrahams can't get
a screenful of ``Airplane'' and ``Naked Gun''-style sight gags out
of them, probably they need a rest. ``Mafia!,'' the new would-be
Abrahams gagfest, makes you an offer you can refuse. It begins
promisingly, parodying ``Casino,'' then quickly moves to an ``Il
Postino'' sendup as it switches to Sicily for the beginning of an
occasionally funny but mostly ponderous dynastic ``Godfather''
travesty that weighs it down until it sleeps with the fishes _ as,
indeed, you may if you go the distance with it.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to give away more than one or two of the sight
gags, since they alone relieve the tedious plot plodding and
unfunny crudeness, but it's a hoot to watch the godfather-to-be
flee to America on a ship called Il Pacino, or notice in a hospital
scene with Lloyd Bridges's klutzy Don Corleone figure that his
intravaneous unit is attached to a jar of spaghetti sauce. This was
the late Bridges's last film, and you can't help wishing he'd had a
better swan song. For the detail-minded, this movie originally was
called ``Jane Austen's Mafia,'' but Austen's name was dropped,
continuing her run of posthumous good luck in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   One problem encountered by Abrahams is that it's a little late
in the day for ``Godfather'' parodies, period. And most of the
film's Italian-American stereotyping is even more dated and
unfunny. Perhaps sensing the flatness and low level of
inventiveness of their material was what pushed Abrahams and his
collaborators into a desperate increase in gross-out jokes based on
bodily extrusions. Certainly Jay Mohr gives it a game try as the
Pacino surrogate, but it's a cement overcoat of a role, except when
a sight gag offers momentary relief, such as a check he writes for
$37,000 to The Bullet Store.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Applegate, as his WASP wife, is the best thing in the
film and its only consistently enjoyable presence. Applegate's
riffs on the Diane Keaton character in the Francis Ford Coppola
original are smartly timed and brightly executed. Sexy-looking
women can bring a special goofiness to comedy, and Applegate dishes
it out nonstop, from her whiny complaint that she's going to be
known as that Protestant chick who never killed anybody, all the
way to a zany touchdown dance. ``Mafia!'' doesn't score often, but
she does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DISTURBING-BOS &LR;      07-24 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DISTURBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DISTURBING BEHAVIOR' COULD STAND MORE OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DISTURBING BEHAVIOR 
Directed by: David Nutter 
Written by: Scott Rosenberg 
Starring: James Marsden, Katie Holmes, Nick Stahl, Steve Railsback,
Bruce Greenwood, William Sadler 
Running time: 83 minutes 
Rated: R (some violence, brief semi-nudity, a Wayne Newton song) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps Paul Lynde said it best in ``Bye Bye Birdie'' when he
posed the musical question, ``What's the matter with kids today?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question as old as time. Think Adam and Eve didn't spend
evenings fretting about Cain's unruly behavior and his inability to
make nice with his brother Abel? It's no different for today's
parents who wring their hands over children who smoke pot, listen
to rude songs, pierce themselves in all sorts of ungodly places,
and generally refuse to live up to their potential.
</P>
<P>
   Given such harsh realities, what parent wouldn't welcome the
chance to turn their terrible teen into an upstanding, well-groomed
straight-A student. So what if their personality is sapped, they
storm around like the Hitler Youth, and have a tendency to kill
when they become sexually aroused? At least they'll get into
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disturbing Behavior'' is a mildly amusing teen trifle, but one
which dares to have a bit of a brain. It is less a slice-and-dice
horror flick than a lightweight contemplation on the price of
conformity over individuality, as well as the desperation of
parents who want a productive child at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Clark (James Marsden) is the new kid in Cradle Bay, one of
those small towns with an endless supply of beautiful teen-agers
with cheekbones and dental work to die for. Steve's a little down
these days, still recovering from his older brother's suicide;
that's why his family left Chicago for this seaside town. At his
new high school, he encounters all the cliques and kooks --
techno-geeks, metalheads, skate punks, potheads like Gavin (Nick
Stahl) and his impossibly pale pal, U.V. (Chad E. Donella), and
multi-pierced leather chick, Rachel (Katie Holmes).
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Blue Ribbons, the ``freaks so chic,'' as
Gavin calls them. Clad in their blue and gold letter sweaters, they
are the cream of the school's crop. They don't drink, don't smoke,
don't take drugs, get good grades, and respect their elders. They
spend their days hanging out at the local yogurt shop, listening to
Wayne Newton's treacly ``Danke Schoen.'' (This may be the film's
scariest moment.)
</P>
<P>
   Gavin is convinced something wicked is happening in Cradle Bay,
but of course, no one else believes him. Even after Steve witnesses
a nighttime meeting with parents and his school's counselor, Mr.
Caldicott (Bruce Greenwood) voting to bring Gavin into the Blue
Ribbon fold, he just doesn't believe it. Then Gavin shows up at
school the next day having ditched his burnout friends for a letter
sweater, and his cynicism for a personality-altering implant in his
brain.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds familiar, it's because the film's premise mimics
``The Stepford Wives,'' the 1975 film based on Ira Levin's novel
about devious husbands, brainwashed women, and the nightmare of
waxy build-up on kitchen floors. That was a flawed, but clever film
which packed more punch than Scott Rosenberg's screenplay can ever
manage.
</P>
<P>
   That's the main problem. High school and adolescence are so
fertile for such a meditation on conformity, but it never happens
here. Rosenberg's screenplay never goes over the top _ which it
needs to do _ but then again, few of the actors here seem capable
of anything more than looking pretty for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disturbing Behavior,'' is a better movie than one would
expect, but given its juicy potential, it's never anywhere near as
good as it could have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PROFILE-SPIELBER     07-24 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-SPIELBERG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIELBERG ENTERS NEW PHASE WITH BRILLIANT WARTIME FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a guy who has more than proven himself.
</P>
<P>
   He has all the money anyone will ever need, has created some of
the biggest box-office hits ever made, has in recent years raked in
critical accolades _ the best director Oscar that long eluded him
(for 1993's ``Schindler's List'') and the American Film Institute's
Lifetime Achievement Award in 1995 _ and has a fulfilling family
life (he carpools and fixes breakfast for the kids he raises with
his second wife, actress Kate Capshaw).
</P>
<P>
   Yet no fewer than three times during a recent interview at the
Ritz-Carlton, the creator of ``Jaws,'' ``Close Encounters of the
Third Kind'' and his new World War II drama, ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' Steven Spielberg says he still worries about being
``pigeonholed.''
</P>
<P>
   To wit: ``I want to be able to do all different kinds of movies
that will not ultimately pigeonhole me as one kind of filmmaker or
another,'' said Spielberg, comfortably sinking into a plush chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as I had children and as I grew up I wanted to leave
something behind that I could really be proud of that wasn't just
dinosaurs stepping on stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' indeed is a long way from ``Jurassic
Park.'' The story of a unit, headed by Capt. Miller (Tom Hanks),
who survives the Normandy D-Day invasion only to be assigned the
task of locating a young private (Matt Damon) who is the only
surviving brother of four, the film begins with a stirring, brutal
take on the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg, 51, expanded that sequence from five pages in the
original script to 35, and it will surely go down as one of the
greatest, grimmest extended action sequences in movie history. But
it's not for the squeamish; the film narrowly avoided an NC-17
rating for its graphic, realistic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the audience to be participants in the physical
experience of battlefield combat as opposed to spectators as most
of us are when we're filmgoers,'' Spielberg said. ``I did a lot of
things in `Schindler's List' that were very graphically realistic
and true to the reportage of the survivors that talked to us before
we made that story. I felt I had that kind of duty to those
veterans of World War II, to finally acquit them of their
experience in a non-Hollywood way.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``Saving Private Ryan'' is, then, is an independent film
with a $65 million budget. Independent in the sense that its
artistic vision is unmitigated _ Spielberg's studio, DreamWorks,
made the movie and Spielberg and Hanks both waived their salaries
in exchange for back-end percentages, which shaved around $30
million off the budget.
</P>
<P>
   What they've come up with is the most realistic, unglamorized
war movie ever. Just ask noted historian Stephen E. Ambrose, who's
listed as a consultant in the film's credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the finest World War II movie ever made,'' said
Ambrose, whose ``Citizen Soldiers'' is a bestseller. ``He does
something in this film I never thought could be done. He shows
onscreen what I've been hearing the last 30 years from veterans who
were there: What it was like.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose, in fact, had the projectionist stop the film after the
D-Day battle sequence, he was so overcome with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So how did the maker of ``E.T.'' and ``Raiders of the Lost Ark''
come to this?
</P>
<P>
   The strange thing about Spielberg is that despite all the
accolades and success, he seems to crave something more, some kind
of validation he doesn't feel he has.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that people aren't stroking his ego. Damon said he
spent one of his off-days on the shoot following the director
around, so he could find out what it was like to ``be'' Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks, who acted for his close friend for the first time: ``His
attack in any movie-making process is such an energetic one and
hard to keep up with,'' Hanks said. ``He sees possibilities of
camera angles that you'd never ever begin to imagine. He does
things with shots _ close-ups, wide shots, anything, he puts the
camera places that you'd think, well, that's why the guy's a
genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Spielberg said that because of the subject matter
``Saving Private Ryan'' was one of his least enjoyable shoots in
his career, he threw himself into the project with customary zeal,
shooting the film as if he were a combat photographer: No
storyboards (``working off the page,'' Spielberg calls it) and
filming the entire movie in continuity. He and cinematographer
Janusz Kaminski diluted 60 percent of the color in the lab, giving
the movie that desaturated documentary feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave the movie a style,'' said Spielberg, who begins
shooting another un-Spielbergian project, an adaptation of Arthur
Golden's best-selling ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' which may represent
the filmmaker's final frontier: strong, complex female characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just grew up,'' Spielberg said. ``I had some very
creative and commercial, er, arrested development in my life which
I'm very happy for because I love stories of the imagination. ...
But I don't want to wind up making the same movie 80 times.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the real reason Spielberg has tackled this film, and
in the process made an American classic, is his dad. Arnold
Spielberg fought in World War II as a radio operator aboard a B-25
bomber in Burma. This week, Spielberg was to have shown ``Saving
Private Ryan'' to Arnold, now 81, in a secluded theater, just the
two of them.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of all those feel-good blockbusters is getting
personal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
