<HEADER>
A1210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-RYAN-BOS &LR;      07-24 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RYAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIELBERG'S `RYAN' GRITTY, BRUTAL _ VITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SAVING PRIVATE RYAN 
Directed by: Steven Spielberg 
Screenplay by: Robert Rodat 
Starring: Tom Hanks, Edward Burns, Tom Sizemore, Matt Damon, Jeremy
Davies, Vin Diesel, Adam Goldberg, Barry Pepper, Giovani Ribisi,
Dennis Farina, Ted Danson 
Running time: 168 minutes 
Rated: R (intense prolonged realistically graphic sequences of war
violence, and for language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the war movie to
end all war movies. It's the ultimate combat film, far
outdistancing what until now had been the genre's previous World
War II classics. Slamming us down on the beach with a bunch of
grunts under fire on D-Day, it never lets us forget that images can
be as powerful as bullets as the GIs stumble through the chaos and
terror, too intent on the moment-to-moment business of staying
alive to spare time for the thought that what they're doing defines
courage and heroism. After a prologue showing an aged veteran
returning to a military cemetery, the film's first section amounts
to the most astonishingly realistic depiction of war ever put on a
screen as US troops pour onto Omaha Beach in Normandy on June 6,
1944, to find that everything has gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Shells from the naval guns overshot the German pillboxes lining
the beach, landing too far inland, as did the air support _ bombs
and paratroopers. GIs swarming down the ramps of the landing boats
were sitting ducks for the German machine-gunners. Most in the
first two waves of attackers died on the beach. A Ranger detachment
led by Tom Hanks' Captain Miller tries to work its way up the
beach, sloshing through water red with the blood of fallen
comrades, some of whom we see trying to stuff their insides back
inside their torn bodies, many simply lying still, blood seeping
from bullet holes. Somehow Hanks and the other survivors scuttle up
the beach and take out the pillbox, tossing a grenade through the
slits in its concrete walls. And they haven't even heard of Private
Ryan yet.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner do they get the chance to relax with a cigarette after
the beach has been taken at heavy cost than they get an order
directly from General Marshall. They are to work their way inland,
find a Private James Ryan, and bring him out to be sent home. His
three brothers have been killed in combat and the War Department is
determined to return Mrs. Ryan's last son alive to her in Iowa. We
don't see Matt Damon's Ryan until the film is two-thirds over. When
we do, he fits into the ensemble with instant rightness, so much so
that we realize how gradually and how thoroughly Spielberg and his
terrific cast have unobtrusively transcended the usual
orchestration of GI stereotypes and got to us.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sizemore's sergeant brings compelling heart and conviction
to what could have been the cliches of a salt-of-the-earth type.
Edward Burns faces even greater odds as the cynic from Brooklyn,
but turns it into what will be his mainstream breakthrough role,
bringing an edge of sentience to his character's native wariness.
Barry Pepper, too, is more than just the Kentucky sharpshooter any
sane grunt would want alongside him in a foxhole; Pepper fills him
with individuality. Nor will you forget GregoryRibisi's
hollowed-out medic or Jeremy Davies's haunting terrified corporal,
imploding with cowardice, filled with clammy self-contempt as he
finds himself frozen in combat, unable to fire a shot.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the film is Tom Hanks' Captain Miller, a natural
leader who keeps a lid on his fear and conceals his occasionally
trembling hand as he pulls together strategy after strategy for
survival. Consolidating his standing as the new Jimmy Stewart,
Hanks', whose Miller turns out to be a high school English teacher
from Pennsylvania, is decency itself, doggedly doing what's right,
subject to combat fatigue, most complex in his responses to the
trauma that rains down upon them all. Without ever pushing it, they
draw us into the intimacy of their shared brotherhood, a thing that
makes it easy for us to understand Private Ryan's refusal to leave
his buddies when the rescue unit catches up with him. Damon's Ryan
convinces us he, too, has a stubborn conscience he must answer to,
and so they all stay on for one final battle as a stray German tank
patrol doubles back toward a bridge they must defend.
</P>
<P>
   Hellfire images erupt convulsively as the men never get the
chance to fully debate the morality of putting eight men at risk to
save one. One is interrupted in mid-sentence as a bullet tears into
him. One moment another is lining up a shot, the next he's staring
at a bloody stump where his leg used to be. Although smaller in
scale, the final battle is just as hellishly mesmerizing as the
D-Day landing, perhaps more so because by the time it comes we've
had time to develop feelings for the men we're seeing. But beyond
the capturing of detail, Spielberg's genius lies not just in
realistically recreating the carnage in all its visceral,
existential, horrific finality, but in slicing through two
generations of cliches attached to war movies.
</P>
<P>
   World War II movies were invariably saddled with a need to sell
the war, to be overtly patriotic. The Vietnam War movies were angry
reactions to an unwanted war. If World War II has been portrayed as
a just war, it also has fallen victim to its own pieties.
Mercifully, there's never a single overview or big-picture shot
here, never a scene with Ike or Montgomery standing at a map with a
pointer, spelling it all out for us. Nobody was spelling much out
for the grunts, and ``Saving Private Ryan'' maintains the integrity
of its grunt's-eye-view. It's not antiwar, as Vietnam War movies
were; it's as determined to pay tribute to the heroism of the
fighting troops as any movie ever made. But it does so more
honestly, more unflinchingly, and with more graphically unsparing
detail than ever before. And more subtle, telling detail _ an
exchange of glances between Damon and Burns, a snatch of Edith Piaf
over a radio in a seemingly deserted town _ reinfircing the film's
intimate epic quality.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons it works so magnificently is that it
recognizes that soldiers don't have much time or energy to spare
for reams of dialogue. Films are images, and Spielberg leaves no
doubt that he is film's premier image-maker of the last
quarter-century as he brings home the sickening shock and brutality
of war not as an antiwar placard, but as felt knowledge. It would
have been obscene to estheticize this subject, equally obscene to
gloss over the blood and terror and punishing nightmarishness of
what the GIs invading Europe went through. Spielberg mutes the
color _ except for the color of blood _ and brings up the sounds of
war. We hear every thwack and ping and thud as bullets enter bodies
and bodies fall.
</P>
<P>
   As death waits to explode from every pile of rubble, from every
rear-guard sniper, from every column of enemy tanks and trucks
swarming over the landscape with the desperation born of the gut
feeling that the war was turning against them, Spielberg sometimes
pulls back to eerie silence, making the slaughter seem surreal. But
never for long. His deliberately rough-looking newsreel style, with
its jagged pacing echoing the moment-to-moment uncertainty of each
step, insures only the briefest of respites from the tension. None
of this would count for much if there weren't depth and passion
beneath the shooting strategies of ``Saving Private Ryan.''
Thankfully, there are. Indelible as ``Schindler's List'' was,
``Amistad'' and now ``Saving Private Ryan'' exceed it. ``Saving
Private Ryan'' is a great film. It takes us as close as you can get
_ or would want to get _ to the consuming inferno that is war. It
is, finally, a movie designed to remind us that war is not a movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
