<HEADLINE>
ON NANTUCKET, FISH STORIES COME FREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ The weathered sign out front says ``Fishing
Tackle,'' and the place is full of rods and reels, hooks and line,
wool socks, fillet knives, and salt-water jig heads. But the most
coveted commodity here isn't for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Straight advice and steady service are the legal tender of Barry
Thurston's commerce. His Harbor Square shop, an island institution
for more than two decades, is a common-sense touchstone in a place
where worth is sometimes measured by the length of a yacht, or the
price of a palace on the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is homespun. It's not commercialized,'' said longtime
customer Andy Emory, as Thurston fusses at the counter with a rod
and reel Emory bought here 22 years ago when his son was a little
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what Nantucket is really all about. You come in here
and you get the fishing news. You get the local gossip. You find
out what's going on on the island. That's the fun of walking
through the doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurston's open doors, at the corner of Salem and Candle
streets, have been a lighthouse-steady fixture here since 1976,
when Thurston _ among 15 graduates of Nantucket High School's Class
of '59 _ traded in his suit-and-tie job with Aetna Insurance for a
chance to come home and turn his hobby into his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're raised on the island here you're always an
islander,'' Thurston said over a lunchtime hamburger. ``Even if
it's just to retire, everyone eventually comes back. This type of
life grows on people. If you're born to it, it's a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurston's recipe for business success on an island where the
turnover of commercial properties is constant is deceptively simple
_ something he probably didn't learn while getting his business
administration degree from Boston University in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Master your subject. Give away your knowledge. And the business
will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was born and raised here and he knows the island so well,''
said Mike Monte, Thurston's longtime assistant. ``The information
that we give people is fresh information. This is the first stop a
lot of people make when they get off the boat. They don't even go
to their homes. Think about that. And everybody gets everything.
There are no secrets and there are no secret places.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh, reliable information is precious data for fishermen, who
over the years have worn smooth the square-head nails in the
wide-pine floors of Thurston's Fishing Tackle. The over-the-counter
questions have changed little: Where are the fish? How big are
they? What lure should I use? What's been hot for the past couple
of days? Where should I go?
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows his fishing, and I don't know why because he never
has a chance to get out there,'' said John Moore, 65, of Fairhaven,
who was checking out fishing poles here recently. ``Fishing is a
great sport. It's a sport a family can do together. And Barry is
willing to answer anything. You talk to him like you'd talk to a
good tailor and say, `How do I look?' He's never too busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Jones, 55, of Greenwich, Conn., has been vacationing here for
28 years and has been a customer of Thurston's nearly that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's part of the long-term fishing lore of
Nantucket,'' Jones said. ``He really knows the island. He knows the
fishing and he's always very helpful. You come in and he can give
you advice not only on equipment, but where the fishing's good and
how to approach it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurston, whose father was a waterfront businessman here before
the boutiques and eateries supplanted the ice houses, coal yards,
and lumber mills of what used to be a genuine working harbor, has
the quiet bearing of a university scholar. His low-key intensity
helps make him the island's undisputed expert about fish _ and the
people who pursue them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these people come in and say, `What's happening?' They
don't just want to know if the fish are running. They want to know
where they're running, and what time they're running, and what
they're hitting on,'' Thurston said.
</P>
<P>
   On a walking tour of the nearby harbor, Thurston shakes his head
in wonder at the wood-trimmed boats and impossibly priced luxury
yachts that are a symbol of a roaring economy that has put even a
two-week rented vacation home here out of reach of most
middle-class wage-earners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think half of Wall Street must be on the island,'' Thurston
said. ``These guys are here to relax. They are demanding in the
sense they are willing to pay for what they get, and they want what
they want. They love doing something that they're never going to do
somewhere else. Simple things. Take the kids fishing. Take them
crabbing. These high-pressure guys from New York, they're never
going to do that anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurston sells $395 poles for expert and serious fishermen. But
he keeps a well-stocked supply of $18.50 rod and reels for the
newcomers to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does a really good job at not catering to just the serious,
serious angler, but also certainly the casual angler and kids,
too,'' said Dave Mills, 42, of Washington state, who was buying an
``indestructible'' rod for his 10-year-old son on a recent visit.
``I've seen kids walk in here, 12 years old, and he didn't blow
them off. Now, the fact that the kid's dad might be worth $10
million and just spent $1,000 the day before, hey seriously, he
doesn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurston sees the irony in being kept away from his passion by
his 13-hour daily shifts in his land-locked fishing shop. He said
he made peace with that a long time ago. And, besides, he noted,
there will be time enough to fish in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Buffett, Frank Sinatra, and much of the Kennedy clan have
been customers over the years, but Thurston seems more interested
in predicting the arrival of the Average Joe fishermen whose rods
are perennially kept in the rafters of his store when island
anglers return to their day jobs back on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you exactly whose they are,'' he said. ``Those are
the August people. Those are the July people. These are the June
people. And year after year they come back for their rods. Some
guys come back I haven't seen for 10 or 12 years. But eventually
they all come back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really concentrate on having a family-type business,''
Thurston said. ``That's the most important thing to me. I really
don't concentrate on getting the real hard-core professional
fishermen. I like to have them. Don't get me wrong. I hope they all
come to me. But do business with whole families, whole generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we deal with an awful lot of people who don't know much
about fishing. They want to learn; they certainly want to do it
while they're here because they may never do it again. My feeling
is that it's got to be a family-oriented, easy-come, easy-go type
place, because there's got to be a little piece of sanity in this
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
