<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BASTARD-BOS &LR;      07-24 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BASTARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCKY' CARRIES THE STAMP OF MCCARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
LUCKY BASTARD 
By Charles McCarry 
Random House, 385 pp., $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lucky Bastard'' is superior summer entertainment from Charles
McCarry, America's greatest master of the political novel and the
spy story.
</P>
<P>
   This tale about a foreign attempt to help a secret agent along
the path to the American presidency is a great yarn that hurtles
headlong through deeds of honor and horror, fidelity and
double-dealing, cunning and instinct. Unusually for McCarry,
there's a lot of steamy sex. There's no way to predict what is
going to happen next, and even the most fantastic inventions will
have the ring of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the first time, McCarry has found himself an advance man
for history. His presidential candidate, John Fitzgerald (Jack)
Adams, believes he is the bastard son of John F. Kennedy. Like
Kennedy, and some subsequent presidents, Jack has a zipper problem.
Because such problems are very much in the news, McCarry has had to
append an author's note saying his book is a work of prophecy, not
of imitation; he had plotted the book for years and wrote it months
before real events began to mirror and mimic his fictional ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucky Bastard'' isn't as dense, reverberant, and rewarding as
such McCarry masterpieces as ``The Last Supper,'' ``Second Sight,''
and ``Shelley's Heart.'' Those books are full of dodges; this one
unfalteringly moves in one straight line _ there are no subplots or
diversions. That's why ``Lucky Bastard'' would make a terrific
movie, if producers only had the nerve.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious Peter, who runs operations so secret that even
the KGB doesn't know about them, is the originator of the plot to
develop the youthful and priapic Jack Adams into malleable
presidential material. ``His rivals, the spies, wanted to steal
American history and lock it up in file cabinets. Peter, the
artist, wanted to steal history, too. But his idea was to feed this
stupid little bird sweets, tie a string to its leg, and then push
it out of the nest.'' The Marxist ideal had failed because it
entered the wrong nation's history at the wrong time; Peter wants
to give it another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Jack doesn't know anything about Peter, but he doesn't have to.
His handler is his own wife, Morgan, who in turn is handled by the
book's fascinating narrator, Dmitri, Peter's chief associate. Peter
is a pretty amoral moralist; these are shrewd commentators who
enjoy playing with the role of moralist. ``Issues don't make
presidents,'' Morgan observes. ``Publicity does.'' Dmitri thinks
like this too _ he calls the media ``the priesthood in charge of
ritual executions in the United States.'' Unlike the others,
however, Dmitri is ironically self-aware. ``Like many a handler
before me, including Judas Iscariot, I was beginning to love the
agent more than I loved the operation, a bad sign that I did not
recognize at the time, or until long afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   The other key figures in the story are Jack's lifelong friend
Danny Miller and Danny's lifelong girlfriend and wife-to-be, the
perfect cheerleader Cindy Rogers. The story covers decades, from
just before the Vietnam War to the end of the Evil Empire, and over
those years the personal relationships among the Adamses and the
Millers play through nearly every possible permutation of business
and sexual alliance and betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   More than that it would be unfair to say, but McCarry does know
whereof he speaks. The novelist, a product of the Berkshires,
served in the CIA for years and later ghost-wrote memoirs for Gen.
Alexander Haig and former Treasury secretary and chief of staff
Donald Regan, so he can toss off observations like, ``It was said
in the KGB canteen that Peter could make Andropov laugh and
Brezhnev think. This was enough to make anyone fear him.'' The
novelist's range of reference is wide, from Joseph Conrad to ``The
Godfather.'' A television spot makes an incompetent politician
``look like an especially stupid horse that had just awakened to
find itself in bed with the severed head of a Hollywood producer.''
There is a provocative analysis of the Alger Hiss case, and many
insider anecdotes that don't have to be true to sound convincing _
the story tells us that the Soviet way of dealing with the
wandering appetites of Hugarian prime minister Janos Kadar was to
castrate him.
</P>
<P>
   In a novel full of puppets and puppeteers, it is McCarry who
controls all the strings _ and he does it with practiced hands that
are also daring. McCarry is a more profound moralist than any of
his characters, and the most politically astute of all, if not
always the most politically correct. Humorless extremists of
several sorts and sects will find cold comfort here. McCarry says
he quarantined himself from the media during the months when he
wrote this book, which means he missed a lot of Monica Lewinsky
jokes, but in sticking to himself, he was keeping better company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      07-24 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORGAN MAKES CASE TO `ADORE PUMPKINS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Smashing Pumpkins are accustomed to abuse from critics, but
not from fans. Yet the Pumpkins' new album, ``Adore,'' has drawn
some fire from the band's core audience. The band admits to being
``puzzled'' by the reaction, says singer Billy Corgan, who asks
that fans give it a closer listen before writing it off.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, ``Adore'' is a low-key, down-tempo record compared
to the general head-snapping roar of past Pumpkins disks. But, says
Corgan, ``We just think it's an extension of an underplayed part of
our character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The album comes out and all of a sudden you have fans
completely overreacting,'' Corgan says from a tour stop in
Cincinnati. ``At the same time, you have a huge dichotomy in the
reviews, where it's either completely a masterpiece _ the `best
work of our career' and a `bold step forward' _ or it's a piece of
garbage. It's really kind of puzzled the band and made the band
realize that everything is so built on the thought of something and
not necessarily the substance of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole thing was to take the opportunity of our success to
really redefine what we're doing and why we're doing it,'' says
Corgan. ``So there was a real purity in that _ to go back to a
simpler way of writing and working and, in essence, just try to
start over. Which, of course, is a highly uncommercial thing to do.
Everybody likes all the dots to connect very easily, thank you very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Corgan is a convincing chap, but even he must realize that
``Adore'' is not an easily accessible work. The last Pumpkins
release, the double-CD ``Mellon Collie &AMP; the Infinite Sadness,''
sold 8 million copies, boosted by the hit song ``Bullet with
Butterfly Wings'' and its often quoted verse: ``Despite all my
rage/I'm still just a rat in a cage.'' The new album, though, is
more quietly philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   Some listeners think the new disk is Corgan's personal reaction
to the death of his mother and breakup of his four-year marriage.
``A lot has been made of that,'' he says, ``but I really think that
misses the gist of the whole album. It's more about someone just
surveying the landscape of the world that we're in right now. It's
almost more commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a world-view album _ and that doesn't necessarily
hit people until later,'' he adds. ``It looks way personal, but
there's a foundation under there of a bigger view. I honestly feel
this album is less personal than past work.''
</P>
<P>
   The music is meant to provide hope, says Corgan, in an age of
cynicism. ``I just think we're in a really negative era to the
point of ridiculousness, to the point of killing growth, certainly
artistically. Look at my generation. We have no heroes. None.
They've all been mangled and spit back out. Nobody walks out of
this unscathed. At least the '60s people got to be heroes for a
while, then later you found out they were (screwed) up. We're
(screwed) up now and are still trying to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album is ``really the backdrop for me to try to find the
soul amidst all the crap, for myself and for people who are
listening, to try to say what's really important _ that is, love
and the concept of family ... and to get at the core issues of
what's facing us in the light of this overwhelming negativity.''
</P>
<P>
   To rebuff the negativity, the Smashing Pumpkins, who include
guitarist James Iha and bassist D'Arcy Wretzky, are now doing a
tour in which all shows are benefits. They've been giving away
$100,000-$150,000 per show to charities. The Orpheum date will
benefit local children's AIDS programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the extension of the philosophy of the album to put
the thought into action,'' says Corgan. ``We're putting our money
where our mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have a John F. Kennedy to lead you, or at least
give you a kind of shining star, you have to create those,'' says
Corgan. ``I think what's poignant about a band like the Pumpkins is
that we're not squeaky clean. We're not Pat Boone or something.
There's a weight to the message because we've been there. I mean, I
can't identify with a baby that has AIDS, but I can identify with
problems in the home and we can identify with abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Corgan is still stung by critiques of the new disk,
he's encouraged by how its songs have been received in concert.
``The reactions to the shows have been so overwhelming that it's
given us the confidence to keep going,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason for the positive reaction, he says, is the addition
of new touring drummer Kenny Aronoff, who previously worked with
John Mellencamp, Melissa Etheridge, and Bob Seger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been fantastic,'' Corgan says of the Stockbridge-bred
Aronoff. ``His maturity and his experience have really helped bring
this album fo fruition live. He brings a kind of consistency every
night that we've never been used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Corgan remains a prolific songwriter and a highly in-demand
producer/guitarist for other musicians. Last year, he worked on the
solo album of Cars singer Ric Ocasek, ``Troublizing'' (``I got him
to be a little more edgy than he might have been,'' he says); and
this year on the forthcoming Hole album with Courtney Love. That
one has sparked a tabloid debate about who did what on it, but
Corgan says only, ``My influence is apparent and what shines
through from Hole's past work is apparent. ... People will hear
what I did and didn't do, and then all the dust will settle about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for future Pumpkins plans, Corgan says they'll start
recording a new album in September. What kind of music can we
expect this time? ``I'm keeping my mouth shut on that one,'' he
says with a good-natured laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
