<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURTLE IS CREEPING UP ON HARE IN GOVERNOR'S RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call him Governor Bullseye. Because everyone's out to get him.
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci was the lopsided front-runner late
last year when one of Boston's biggest bankers scoffed at the
notion that any Democrat could beat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course Cellucci will win,'' tut-tutted Mr. Bank. But as
they say when you go in to redo your mortgage, that was then, this
is now. And Cellucci's stumbling performance since the departure of
Senor Weld has brought him back to the pack. From the right comes
the sniper fire of Treasurer Joe Malone, whose Republican primary
campaign keeps Cellucci dipping into his treasure chest. From the
left comes the distant rumble of Democratic cannon, louder each
day.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci held two hole cards this summer: incumbency and cash.
His fund-raisers methodically amassed millions with the
implication: If you don't give, you don't get any consideration
from the present and probably future governor.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. Cellucci sits astride a shrinking ice floe in a
lopsidedly Democratic state, and the temperature's a-risin'. Labor
is turning up the heat. It's eight years since unions had a
friendly governor. And in Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, labor
has found its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   With calculations more professional than personal, after a
cold-hearted assessment of which Democrat has the best chance to
end eight years of hostile governing, union leaders swung their
heft and people power behind the AG.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Patricia McGovern has nipped steadily at his
heels. She has raised $700,000 this year, on top of a half-million
last year. But Harshbarger, who began running well before Joe
Kennedy dropped out, did a million last year, a million so far this
year, and will outgun her down the stretch. Brian Donnelly has been
lapped by the other two and looks to be out of it.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Cellucci strategy to counter labor's anticipated
onslaught and the seven-week postprimary Democratic surge, it is
not evident. Say Cellucci and Harshbarger win their primaries, the
Democrat tears into Cellucci from the get-go on primary night.
Wednesday, the armies engage, TV spots flashing. Thursday, the big
guns of the national Democratic establishment file into the Boston
Park Plaza. There'll be podium-thumping orations by President
Clinton, Vice President Gore, US Senate minority leader Tom
Daschle, House minority leader Dick Gephardt, Ted and Joe Kennedy,
John Kerry, and every Democrat running anywhere near the top of the
November ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The menu will feature Fricasseed Gingrich, Roasted Lott, Fried
Helms, and Overcooked Cellucci. This event is run by three local
Democrats who play on the national stage: national chairman Steve
Grossman, Alan Solomont, who is McGovern's fund-raiser, and Elaine
Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   And Harshbarger's campaign will that day have pocketed a check
from the Commonwealth, about $900,000, representing the whole pot
of state matching campaign funds that was set aside for
gubernatorial tickets that abided by the state's weirdly configured
campaign finance law.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci spurned the limits and therefore public funds, figuring
his muscle could euchre more dough the old-fashioned way, by
twisting arms till the shoulder buckled. So even though Harshbarger
had to expend a portion of his stash to repel McGovern, the
likeliest Democratic victor waltzes into his unity dinner with a
crisp check for $900,000 in his kick.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad way to start off the cocktail hour. Cellucci will have
more money. But he'll have been through a war with Malone. All
those lurking problems about Cellucci's personal finances will have
been raised, and not completely dispelled, during Malone's robust
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger cannot spend more than $1.5 million between the
primary and general elections. But his friends in labor, and
Democrats running other races, will have their own input. And there
are two political axioms in play: The crowd that has been out of
office for a long time is hungrier, and the gang that's been in for
a long time tends to get sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   And as the odds change on the tote board, the political
calculations mutate as well. Power brokers like Mayor Tom Menino,
whose hostility to Harshbarger's ambition is no secret, must
reassess. Does Menino give the wink to his minions and nudge them
to help Cellucci? Or does he go with labor, Clinton-Gore, and
voters who want to shake off eight years of Republican mastery?
</P>
<P>
   Should Harshbarger win without any sort of help from Menino, the
city administration can kiss goodbye to special treatment from the
corner office. Menino, who smarted for years at the perceived
slights of more powerful pols, knows better than most how sweet it
is to win after being written off. And not since the slow, steady,
under-the-radar campaigning of the young Dukakis or the young
Tsongas have we seen as methodical and sternly focused a statewide
campaign as Harshbarger's. His mascot is not the donkey but the
turtle.
</P>
<P>
   I know one banker and one big-city mayor who would gulp and
swallow hard if handed a turtle pin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
