<SLUG> BC-GUNNERS-MATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH PAST, PRESENT TENSE FOR GUNNER'S MATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joseph Harris is a gunner's mate, 3rd class, aboard the
guided missle cruiser USS Leyte Gulf, which has come to Boston to
participate in today's bicentennial salute to the USS Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Simpson is a gunner's mate, 3rd class, aboard the USS
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The two mates live by the same pay scale. But their jobs are
separated by two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Harris monitors a multimillion-dollar missile launch system and
sails the seven seas. Aboard Old Ironsides, Simpson fires a signal
cannon that is good only for ceremonies, sells sodas during special
events, and seldom leaves the dock. He also specializes in
capturing the visitor's imagination with descriptions of cannon
warfare during the War of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity about the job of gunner's mate, then and now, brought
the two men together for the first time Wednesday. And on one
point, they adamantly agreed: The gunner's mate aboard the
Constitution during the War of 1812 had far and away the lousier
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Harris summarized it best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank &UR;  &LR; you, but no thank &UR;  &LR; you,'' the missile launch expert
said as Simpson was midway through a description of the sand,
water, blood, and splintered wood that typically littered the
Constitution's gun deck during a battle.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 27, manages the forward 64 missile bays aboard the Leyte
Gulf, the 567-foot AEGIS-class cruiser that docked Wednesday
morning at the Commonwealth Pier in South Boston. Harris works
behind a door deep in the ship inscribed with several warnings
referring to the explosive nature of his work.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Tennessee taking things apart, including the tail
lights on the family station wagon, a hair dryer, and several home
appliances, none of which could ever be put together again. It was
a long leap to missile launch systems, but fortunately, the Navy
has also taught him during the past several years how to put the
systems back together, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is one of a half-dozen sailors aboard the Leyte Gulf who,
in times of crisis, are issued keys that appear designed to unlock
bicycles, but when used in concert, actually unlock missiles. To
date, Harris says, he has had to fire missiles only during
peacetime exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is odd, I must admit, to think that my targets can be 700
miles away and that I will never see them,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   A gunner's mate aboard the Constitution, on the other hand,
would put a 32-pound cannon ball through the 20-inch thick wooden
hull of a ship 1,200 yards away, then see and smell the damage. But
unlike Harris, who single-handedly can oversee his next shot with
the push of a button, the crew to reload a cannon was 14-men
strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the fury of what was going on, it's remarkable
they could get the next shot off in 40 seconds,'' said Simpson, 21,
a native of Kentucky who chose to become a gunner's mate in the
wake of his father, who served on the USS Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   While the Constitution was undefeated in more than 30
encounters, the ship became legendary for three close-quarter
victories against the British during the War of 1812 when, as the
ship historian and author Tyrone Martin has said, battles were
fought ``fiercely, in slow motion aboard a ship that sailed about
four knots during engagements.''
</P>
<P>
   As a battle neared, a crew of 500 would take up battle stations
with the captain's command: ``Beat to quarters,'' Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen sailors pumped water from the bilge onto the gun
deck to minimize the risk of an inadvertent explosion. Then they
sprinkled sand on the deck so barefooted gunners would not slip
should the deck become bloody.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that a cannon, recoiling from a shot,
accelerated to 80 miles an hour backward until ropes stopped it.
Then the 3 1/2-ton gun bucked several feet in the air, its ascent
checked by ceiling structures. Insignia on the cannon barrels have
been found pressed into the wood above.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the ears of a gunner's mate were bleeding from the
racket 45 minutes into a battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why sailors to this day wear handkerchiefs. They would
wax the ends, then stick them in their ears for protection,''
Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Harris never sees the weapons that launch from the
tubes he maintains. He turns a key, says, ``Manned and Ready,'' and
prays that the missiles clear the launchpad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
