<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS BANK &AMP; TRUST THRIVES AMID GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who says size matters?
</P>
<P>
   Giant institutions like State Street Corp., caring for trillions
of dollars of their clients' financial assets, dominate the
lucrative business of securities custody. Conventional wisdom calls
their vast scale a must to compete in a line of work driven by
sophisticated technology and known for its intensely competitive
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Investors Bank &AMP; Trust, a little-known Boston
competitor that is thriving despite its relatively tiny piece of
turf in the custody world.
</P>
<P>
   IBT and its parent firm, Investors Financial Services Corp.,
processed $164 billion of assets for customers as of the end of
June. It struck an important deal this week with BankBoston that
will add another $70 billion of assets to the total.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with State Street's $4.5 trillion in assets under
custody. Another big name in the business, Bank of New York, is
custodian to $4.4 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business about scale at one end, but at the other end
it's about niches and finding profitable customers,'' said Charles
Ruffel, editor of Global Custodian, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Investors Bank &AMP; Trust had been growing steadily by 30 percent a
year before the BankBoston deal. One key: flying under the radar of
gigantic competitors and clients to find smaller investment
managers and assure them their business won't be neglected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly the strategy we prey upon,'' said Investors
Financial chief executive Kevin Sheehan. ``You don't have to have
$70 billion to get us to stand up and take attention.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt to have some high-profile names on the client
roster, like John Hancock, Goldman Sachs Asset Management, and
Deutsche Bank. But that list includes many more smaller to midsize
money managers, like Standish, Ayer &AMP; Wood, Northeast Investors,
and David L. Babson &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Custodians and processors perform much of the investment grunt
work that is never seen by mutual fund shareholders or other
customers. They are hired by money managers to keep track of
individual stocks and bonds, collect dividends, settle trades made
by their customers, and other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing very sexy about the business,'' Sheehan
concedes.
</P>
<P>
   Investors was formed in 1969 by Boston money manager Eaton Vance
Corp., then called Eaton &AMP; Howard, to provide in-house trustee
services for the company's own funds. The custodial business, once
a division of Bank of New England, was bought from the struggling
bank in 1990. In November 1995, Eaton Vance spun the entire
operation off into a public company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors Financial Services launched its initial public
offering at 16 1/2 per share. The stock reached a record 60 1/2
earlier this week and closed Thursday at 59.
</P>
<P>
   A few other companies have grown smaller custody businesses at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Brothers Harriman, a custodian for about $550 billion, is
perhaps the most prominent of the group. It makes a pitch that the
giant competitors are becoming less suitable for many customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether some of these (big competitors) have
become so large that they've become less efficient, not more,''
said Susan Livingston, a Brown Brothers partner in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Nearly all of Investors Financial's client list was grown
from scratch, mostly smaller customers pitched and eventually won
over. But the BankBoston deal, by far the largest single addition
of business, was a rare and dramatic departure.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will buy BankBoston's business, providing custody to
600 customers with $45 billion, for $44 million in cash up front
and a kicker of up to $6 million more based on future performance.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston also agreed to outsource some backshop functions to
Investors Financial for its own $25 billion asset management
business.
</P>
<P>
   Investors agreed to extend its subcontracting arrangement with
the bank for custodial work in Latin America, a small but growing
piece of business. It also agreed to offer Boston jobs to
BankBoston's 106 custody employees working in Canton.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston officials said they entertained at least three bids
for the custodial business, but chose Investors because it could
accommodate them on more details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew being a significant customer, we would mean more to
them than anyone else,'' said Peter Manning, BankBoston's mergers
and acquisitions chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a deal starts out by showing us the best price, it
quickly moves into shaping the best deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
