<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUSTEE NEEDS TO PRIORITIZE MOTHER'S NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I need some direction in helping my mother with her future
investment plans. I am now trustee of her trust because she is
totally disabled and cannot take care of herself or her finances. I
recently selected and placed my mothers in a skilled nursing
facility and am in the process of selling her home. When this is
completed, it should bring her about $300,000. How should I
conservatively invest this so as to provide for her continuing care
for the rest of her life (share is 83) and still disperse some
gifts she has designated, in her will, for her grandchildren? She
now has about $200,000 in tax-free municipal bonds, and has
pensions bringing in about $1,500 per month. Her expenses, after
the sale, will be around $6,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   J.R., El Cajon, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The first thing I'd do is prioritize your duties as trustee
-- focusing first on your mother's needs and comfort and forgetting
about her wishes for bequests to grandchildren for the foreseeable
future. Why do I say this? Because while it's likely your mother
will have sufficient funds to see her through, it's far from
certain. Let's suppose you were able to invest her $500,000
remaining assets (after the real estate sale) so as to achieve a
6,.5 percent portfolio average return. With monthly withdrawals of
$4,500, the result would be that her funds would last early 14
years, and then be exhausted. It's true that not many people live
to reach age 97, but as a trustee you must consider the possibility
and act accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The second thing to do is determine whether the tax-free
municipal bonds are still appropriate for her. I am far from an
expert on this matter, but I understand that a portion of the
charges at a nursing facility are considered health care expenses,
while another percentage is designated living costs. Since the
former quality for a tax deduction, her move to the nursing
facility may change her overall tax situation sufficiently that
all, or some, of the tax-free bonds might be profitably swapped for
higher-yielding taxable issues.
</P>
<P>
   I would begin with the administrators at the nursing facility,
who can explain what percentage of the monthly bills represent
deductible health care charges, and then take the problem to her
(or your) tax advisor.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, once you've done that, weeding out whatever
percentage of the municipals that seem to be indicated, I'd build a
portfolio dominated by a good GNMA fund, such as Fidelity GNMA or
Vanguard GNMA, which you can expect to yield about 6.5 percent. You
might put 55 percent of the portfolio here; I would divide the
balance among the municipals, a two-year CD, and a good high-yield
corporate bond fund such as Fidelity Capital and Income or Vanguard
Corporate High-Yield Bond. Yes, it's true that those last two
qualify for the tag ``junk bond funds,'' but since the positions
would represent only about 15 percent of the portfolio -- or less,
if it remains advisable to hold significant tax- exempt position --
you should be willing to accept the fairly moderate risk in favor
iof a higher yield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 24 and work for McDonald's, where I recently qualified
to enroll in the 401(k) program. I have decided to contribute 13
percent of my salary, which will be matched 50 percent by the
company. There are five different options for investment. I am
young and retirement is a long way off, and from what I've heard I
should be making my investments grow. How would you divide
contributions among these five options, in 10 percent increments: a
money market fund, a stable value fund, a blended stock and bond
fund, and a diversified stock fund?
</P>
<P>
   K.E., Portland, Maine
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You didn't mention it, but I'm guessing the fifth option on
the 401(k) menu is McDonald's Corp. common stock.
</P>
<P>
   You're correct that what you want is long-term growth, since you
can probably expect the account to be building for 35 to 40 years.
For that reason, I suggest you summarily reject the first two
options -- the money market fund and the stable value fund, which
is probably only slightly more aggressive than the money market
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Only if your consider yourself a very cautious person, or one
who might lose sleep over the prospect of short-term reversals in
the market, would I consider the balanced offering very seriously.
A typical balanced fund holds about 60 percent of its assets in a
portfolio of stocks and the remainder in bonds. I consider it's
reasonable over a long period for a stock fund to average 10
percent annual growth, while 7 percent might be a satisfactory
target for a bond portfolio. That would give you a portfolio
average return of 8.8 percent. Let's suppose that your
contributions plus those of your employer will work out to $3,000 a
year. If you kept that pace up for 30 years, the calculator shows
the pool would grow to $406,824.
</P>
<P>
   But if you went entirely with stocks and achieved that target 10
percent average return over the same period of time, the total
would be $516,048, which strikes me as quite a difference.
</P>
<P>
   So if it were my money, I'd put 90 percent of the contributions
into the diversified stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   As for that final 10 percent, if I'm correct in assuming that
shares of McDonald's represent the final option, I'd put the last
of the money there. I think the booming growth days of McDonald are
probably behind it, bit it's obviously a very valuable franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, I like the idea of employees owning a bit of the
action -- it changes your point of view, even when it comes to
things both large and small. I remember that my first journalism
job was at a closely held newspaper, and one older employee
perpetually seemed to be rescuing 3'' pencils from the wastebasket
and using them.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked a colleague to explain this, he said simply, ``He's
a stockholder.'' Finally, if you think the plan I suggest is a bit
too bold, but you also want to be a bit less conservative than
going entirely with the balanced fund, you might consider a
compromise -- 60 percent diversified stocks, 30 percent balanced,
and 10 percent company stock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
