<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNERS, MUSCLE, AND ECONOMY IN ONE COSTLY PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, July 26, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime in the afternoon, the flashy yellow BMW convertible had
been spirited away and replaced by a Mercedes-Benz sedan finished
in some exotically labeled hue that looks like gray to me. It
turned out to be Calypso Green in the Benz paint scheme, although
several people told me it was turquoise. I really wouldn't know.
</P>
<P>
   This weekly _ sometimes more often _ motor metamorphosis keeps
neighbors occupied in speculation. For some, curiosity got to be
too consuming; one came knocking at the door asking what I did that
caused the procession of new vehicles. One, being a Globe reader,
actually put two and two together and came up with auto writer.
But, while adults mostly speculate in silence, children are more
direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you a dealer?'' The question came loudly, from a group of
youngsters in the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answered, and proceeded to tell them what I did. ``How
would one dealer have so many different makes?'' I asked my
interrogator. But he hadn't been asking was I a car dealer; he was
figuring drug dealer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The green Mercedes proved a very pleasant car, as do most Benz
cars. For the kind of money Benz requests to part with one of its
chariots, one has a right to expect a pleasant experience. This
four-door, five-passenger E-Class is elegantly appointed, quiet,
offers good performance _ although the tested model seemed to have
a bit of hesitation on initial acceleration _ something to pursue
as I roll up miles on it.
</P>
<P>
   I had rolled up a couple of hundred miles plus, approaching the
refuel moment, but the gauge indicated a half tank. Either fuel
economy is extraordinary or the tank is enormous. Or maybe the
gauge is malfunctioning? At 300 miles, the gauge was still
indicating plenty of fuel; it was time to sort this out. The
answer, had I looked, was clearly written on the back of the car,
but I found it in the paperwork in the glove box: This E-Class is
the E300 Turbodiesel. It has a modest-sized fuel tank, under 22
gallons, and an EPA economy rating of 26 miles per gallon city, 34
highway. The mystery of the extended range also answered the
question of why the hesitation; diesels are slow to wind up.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure to recognize the car as a diesel immediately by
the usual diesel clues testify to the quantum leap in diesel
technology since the short-lived diesel craze of 20 years ago. The
diesel is instantly recognizable by the noise _ it usually sounds
like crushed stone in a clothes dryer _ and the aroma; diesels
stink. The E300 is quiet, odorless. And diesel fuel in these parts
is still cheaper than gasoline, a lot cheaper than mid and premium
grades of gas.
</P>
<P>
   I began listening for the telltale sound of a diesel;
occasionally you could hear what might be taken for engine knock in
a gas car _ but only occasionally and only when you slam the pedal
to the metal. The odor, however, was another matter. Nose close to
the tailpipe, I thought I smelled a trace of that familiar stink.
And maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The E300 Turbodiesel is an expensive car, $41,800 plus $595
delivery. That Calypso Green finish is an extra, the leather
upholstery added almost $1,700 to the bill, and the sunroof tacks
on $1,110. Total as-tested price: $45,895. That's an enormous
amount of money for a working stiff to contemplate shelling out for
basic transportation, but there's nothing basic about this car.
When you look at the technology aboard invested in safety, the
price doesn't seem quite so steep _ not to mention the technology
devoted to the sybaritic devices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the front air bags, there are side air bags in
the doors. The passenger-side front bag is equipped with the Benz
``Baby Smart'' technology that senses when a child seat is there
and deactivates the bag while the seat is there. The front seat
belts are rigged with pre-tensioners and force limiters; the
tensioners make certain there's no slack on impact, and the force
limiters allow the belt to give some, to avoid injury from the belt
in high-speed impacts.
</P>
<P>
   The brakes are four-wheel antilocks with a new twist _ what Benz
calls the Emergency Brake Assist System. This has nothing to do
with the emergency brake but everything to do with braking
emergencies. For the short person who cannot extend to depress the
brake pedal fully, or for the frail who cannot exert a lot of brake
pressure, the car's microprocessor deduces emergency from the speed
of the braking stroke and the forces on the car, and automatically
signals for mamximum force. And there is the automatic slip control
that senses yaw, steering angles, driver steering input, and
instantly computes impending skid and corrects same _ usually
before the driver is aware he/she was actually in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   And the E300 has a tilt/telescoping steering wheel for maximum
comfort, a Benz engineeering concession to Americans. It is not too
long ago that inquiries about the possibility of tilt wheels in
Benz cars brought a reprimand: ``The engineers have determined the
optimum position for the steering wheel and there is no need to
change it.''
</P>
<P>
   The E300 is equipped to the max, but not everything works the
way one might expect all the time. The dual climate control, for
instance, didn't do what I really wanted done _ cool on one side,
warm on the other. It took a lot of finagling to keep the cool off
the arm side, and the result was that the cool area wasn't all that
cool after all. This is an effort to accommodate what seems to be a
basic difference between men and women; men usually are more
comfortable in a cold car, while women seem to need warmth.
</P>
<P>
   The radio controls are obviously the result of a plan by a
thinking individual _ the buttons are large enough for most fingers
_ but the whole thing needs more thought. It's time to think
``knobs'' here for the basic functions. The driver's window switch
has an ``express up and down'' feature that worked flawlessly on
the up but was a bit random on the down _ I almost never got it to
do an ``express down.''
</P>
<P>
   The 174-horepower (243 ft/lb torque) was mated with a
five-speed, automatic transmission that offers alternative
clutchless manual operation, a decided benefit in mountainous
regions, even after you concede the downhill holding power of a
high-compression (22:1) diesel engine.
</P>
<P>
   The handling is superior _ crisp and precise. The ride is quiet
and forgiving _ but not soft. The car felt good on the dirt byways
and the concrete highways. Fuel mileage was extraordinary for a
five-passenger luxury car with such performance; for 1,300 miles
measured, the Benz delivered about 30.5 miles per gallon _ three
tanks isn't enough to get a precise handle on the mileage of foamy
diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, this is an exuberant thumbs up for an automobile
of grace, manners, and muscle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
