<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AGE-COMPANIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOZEN TOP COMPANIES FOR THE NEW ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SPENCER REISS AND JOHN BROWNING  
 From WIRED  
 c.1998 Conde Nast Publications Inc.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; World rights excluding Japan &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Today a new economy is emerging, just as dramatically as
smokestacks sprang from the wheat fields of the agrarian age.
</P>
<P>
   Industrialism is about things, and the efficient production of
them. The revolution today is rooted in networked information _ how
to create it, move it and manage it.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 of the companies that are building the new economy _
not just the usual high-tech suspects, but a variety of enterprises
that are using technology, networks and information to reshape the
world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN INTERNATIONAL GROUP, INC.
</P>
<P>
   New York
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $27.9 billion
</P>
<P>
   The insurance business is classically information-driven _ just
think about an actuarial table. But it is also intensely local: To
accurately assess risks _ much less sell policies _ you need to be
there. All of which explains why globe-girdling AIG is a high flier
in a notoriously low-altitude sector.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Shanghai in 1919, AIG focuses on the simple idea that
in much of the world, insurance _ for people and businesses alike _
is primitive or nonexistent. With offices in 130 countries, more
than half its pretax income comes from non-U.S. sources, including
China, Russia, eastern Europe, Africa and the Middle East. Last
year it even reached an agreement with the Chinese government to
reoccupy its old Shanghai headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA ONLINE, INC.
</P>
<P>
   Dulles, Va.
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $1.7 billion
</P>
<P>
   With 11 million subscribers _ plus another 2.5 million on
recently acquired CompuServe _ AOL is the Net's 800-pound gorilla,
and the world's largest (by far) ISP, or information services
provider.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's paying customers cough up $21.95 every month and, earlier
this year, took a 10 percent price-hike in stride. Marketing
companies are lining up to write checks as large as $100 million
for the privilege of offering the AOL masses everything from
videogames to discount phone service.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES SCHWAB CORP.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $2.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission sparked a democratic
revolution on Wall Street when it eliminated fixed commissions for
brokers two decades ago. Now the Internet promises to finish the
job. Schwab _ and millions of happily liberated investors _ have
been cheering all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab leaped enthusiastically into discount trading while most
brokers tried to protect their inflated profit margins. It
diversified into mutual funds and introduced 24-hour telephone
touch-tone trading.
</P>
<P>
   And it invested heavily in automated trading _ paving the way to
the Internet, where Schwab now owns 47 percent of the electronic
brokerage business. It has also moved into lucrative overseas
markets _ notably stock-mad Asia _ where discount brokering is
still a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   DELL COMPUTER
</P>
<P>
   Round Rock, Texas
</P>
<P>
   '98 revenue: $12.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   If any executive understands the Zen of the information
revolution, it is Michael Dell. His company, the world's No. 3 PC
maker, does few things that are not a direct response to customer
demands. That gives it a big advantage in tracking the marriage
between fast-moving technology and fast-evolving customer tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Dell builds no computer until someone has ordered it. The
company stocks only a two-week inventory. Customers are encouraged
to order directly through Dell's Web site, which chalks up $4
million per day in sales. Suppliers deliver on hourly schedules.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST DATA CORP.
</P>
<P>
   Hackensack, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $5 billion
</P>
<P>
   Electronic money isn't the future _ it's here. Credit and debit
cards alone have already taken over an estimated 13 percent of the
U.S. economy. That, in turn, has created a booming, mostly
invisible market for handling noncash transactions _ an opportunity
First Data has quickly climbed into.
</P>
<P>
   First Data controls more than a third of the U.S. credit-card
processing business, including application processing and billing
for MasterCard and Visa. It does Wal-Mart's credit- and debit-card
processing, and works with retail banks on everything from check
verification to in-store ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a stealth power on the Internet, handling transactions
for some of the biggest online retailers, including Amazon.com and
Dell Computer. It's also expanding overseas, into Germany, Hong
Kong and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIOTT INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $9 billion
</P>
<P>
   E-mail, fax and videoconferencing keep people in touch, but
there are some messages you can deliver only by being there. Enter
Marriott International, a dematerialized company geared to the
rising demand for physical presence in an ever-more-networked
world.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott International operates hotels that span the cost
spectrum, from cheap and cheerful (Fairfield Inns and Suites) to
posh (Ritz-Carlton). But the key to its success is classic new
economics: It doesn't actually own most of the hotels it operates.
Investors with a taste for bricks and mortar do that; Marriott
concentrates on the lower-capital, higher-markup business of making
people comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   And in some markets it goes further, franchising everything but
a hotel's essence: operating procedures, quality control and a
familiar name.
</P>
<P>
   The result is steady income flows, insulation from real estate's
booms and busts and a string of powerful brands _ not to mention
the irony that a company that depends on people needing to be
somewhere can disembody itself.
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO CO.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $7.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Monsanto became a new-economy Cinderella: It spun out
its venerable chemicals business and plunged all-out into
biotechnology. ``Life sciences'' is the company buzzphrase. But the
customer is still farmers around the world _ especially big-time
agribusiness _ clamoring for everything from sharp-shooting
pesticides to designer seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto has already racked up one of smart farming's first hits
with Roundup Ready cotton and soybeans _ crops genetically altered
to resist the effects of Monsanto's widely used biodegradable
herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   The big leap now includes a bid _ which could top $2 billion _
for Illinois-based DeKalb Genetics, a high-flying seed company that
develops transgenic crops custom-designed to resist insects and
improve yields. Some of the biggest potential markets are in the
pest-ridden, fertilizer-poor developing world. As such, Monsanto
has major plans for both China and India.
</P>
<P>
   NOKIA CORP.
</P>
<P>
   Espoo, Finland
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $9.7 billion
</P>
<P>
   Wireless communications is both a boom and a boon. Digital
technology takes it a step further. Nokia sells more digital
mobile-communications devices than anybody in the world. More
intriguing, it also leads the way with mobile
phone/fax/e-mail/browsers, new hybrids that put information at your
fingertips, no matter where you are or what you're doing _ a new
economy niche if there ever was one.
</P>
<P>
   Nokia is one of those rare organizations that has never been
afraid to reinvent itself. The companies that merged to create it
in 1922 made galoshes, tissues and cables. Today, one in four
employees works in research and development.
</P>
<P>
   But in choosing opportunities, Nokia has consistently been
driven by its customers. Scandinavia has the highest mobile-phone
usage in the world _ something about long distances and longer
nights. Meanwhile, Finland vies with the United States for the
title of most-connected nation.
</P>
<P>
   SCHLUMBERGER
</P>
<P>
   New York
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $10.6 billion
</P>
<P>
   The essential problem of the oil business isn't drilling holes _
it's knowing where to drill. When big oil companies need to decide
where to set up their rigs, they pay Schlumberger to tell them.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in France 80 years ago, Schlumberger gets its talent by
scouring universities for serious geeks with a taste for adventure
travel. Airlifted into remote sites with a few high-powered
workstations and a satellite link to the supercomputers back at
headquarters, Schlumberger's frontline teams pull information from
deep underground, then run the data through software models to
predict where the oil is and how it will flow into the well.
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger's smarts are a crucial reason why proven oil
reserves are now 60 percent bigger than they were than in 1980,
when the world was convinced it was running out of oil.
</P>
<P>
   SMITHKLINE BEECHAM
</P>
<P>
   Brentford, England
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $12.8 billion
</P>
<P>
   Like all the big drug companies, SmithKline Beecham makes most
of its money from prescription drugs _ the popular antidepressant
Paxil, for one _ plus a menagerie of branded over-the-counter
remedies such as Tums, Contac and Aquafresh. Unlike the rest of the
industry in the early 1990s, it was quick to see _ and pounce on _
the implications of a heady new field of bioresearch: genomics.
That single move put SmithKline miles ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Today, its genomics-driven research-and-development program is
the envy of the industry. Since 1989, it has signed more than 150
biotech alliances, the most important a five-year-old partnership
with Rockville, Md.-based Human Genome Sciences, a pioneer in
genome research. Marketable products are still years away, but
SmithKline's $125 million investment in HGS has already produced
hundreds of patents on disease-related genes.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline is also clever about brand extension. Its labs do
more than 100 million diagnostic tests per year, including a
lamentable growth area: workplace drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART INC.
</P>
<P>
   Bentonville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   '98 revenue: $118 billion
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the downmarket image fool you: Wal-Mart has reinvented
retail logistics. Wal-Mart rose to prominence through a combination
of Sam Walton's dedication to quality, his eye for location and a
system of hub-and-spoke logistics _ stores linked to a central
warehouse _ that meshes local service with economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wal-Mart is taking the logic several steps further. For an
increasing number of products, its stores hold little or no
backroom inventory _ suppliers keep them stocked with just-in-time
deliveries. Wal-Mart's keen computers provide the information about
who's buying what, and why.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's Retail Link network not only records what goods are
purchased and when, but it also lets companies predict sales based
on past buying patterns, special offers and a host of other
factors. Result: Wal-Mart cut inventory by more than $1 billion
last year, even as it expanded sales 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the future, Wal-Mart is looking overseas: It opened 289
stores outside the United States in 1997, only some of which carry
fishing lures and gallon jars of mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   THE WALT DISNEY CO.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   '97 revenue: $22.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   Once the definition of tired Americana, Disney, under chair and
CEO Michael Eisner, has been reborn as a global powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Its twin pillars are reassuringly safe, ``family'' values _ the
sort that play well from Prague to Peoria _ and up-to-the-minute
technological innovation. Part media giant, part marketing monster,
the Mouse continues to write the book on intellectual property _
how to create it, how to manage it and how to leverage it to the
hilt.
</P>
<P>
   Though its acquisition of a TV network, ABC, has yet to be fully
digested, Disney is one of the few companies working successfully
across different media. ``The Lion King'', for instance, has earned
more than $4.5 billion in worldwide movie, merchandise, video and
music sales.
</P>
<P>
   Disney keeps up technologically, partnering with bleeding-edge
animator Pixar (``Toy Story''), automating its global string of
theme parks and, through its DisneyQuest division, pioneering
virtual reality and so-called location-based entertainment (read:
high-end video arcades for grown-ups).
</P>
<P>
   Eisner has commissioned work by virtually every notable U.S.
architect and has some of biggest thinkers in technology tethered
to Imagineering, the corporate skunkworks. Now if only it could get
Disneyland Paris _ as EuroDisney has been redubbed _ into the
black.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Spencer Reiss is a senior editor and John Browning is a
Europe-based contributing editor to Wired. This is adapted from
their index of 40 companies, ``The New Blue Chips.'') &LR;
</P>
