<HEADER>
A1242 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     07-24 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAL A BRICK HOUSE? NOT NECESSARILY SO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. A man suggested spraying my 65-year-old brick house with a
sealant, to make the bricks waterproof. The house was built by my
father, who was an Italian bricklayer. Is spraying it with a
sealant a good idea?
</P>
<P>
   MARION RAGANTINO, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's not necessarily so. If the house is not leaking nor the
mortar deteriorating, there is no need to seal the bricks. They may
be absorbing a little water, but it will evaporate in dry weather.
If the mortar is crumbling or deteriorating in any way, it can be
chipped out and new mortar inserted. It is called repointing, and
will make the walls as good as new for another 50 years or so.
Besides, if any sealing is not done right, the sealer can trap
moisture in the bricks, making things worse. The right way to seal
is to use Chimney Saver water repellent, which seals the bricks
against outside water and weather but allows water vapor to escape
through it; in other words, if water does get in the bricks, it
will evaporate through the chimney saver. The water repellent is
not sold retail; it must be applied by a chimney sweep or other
professional.
</P>
<P>
   It is the handyman's feeling that since your house was built by
an Italian bricklayer, it will be good for many more years. The
handyman's father-in-law was a Sicilian brickie, and his house in
Connecticut is in excellent shape 42 years after he built it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for a source for old-fashioned milk paint. Can
you help?
</P>
<P>
   LOIS, from Sharon, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I can try. I looked up milk paint in my trusty electronic
file that proved untrusty _ I found nothing. But I did find this in
another file; in fact, there is a whole folder full of information
from a previous story so old that I forgot about it.
</P>
<P>
   Two places that sell milk paint are the Old-Fashioned Milk Paint
Co. of Groton, Mass., telephone 448-6336, and the Trend-Lines
Catalog in Chelsea, Mass., phone 617-884-8882.
</P>
<P>
   And, in this treasure-trove of information that I found are
several recipes for making your own milk paint. This one is the
easiest, from John A. Johnson of Johnson Paint Co. in Boston: Mix
equal parts of powdered milk (sold in supermarkets) and dry
pigment, such as red oxide, sienna, umber, and other agents (sold
in paint stores); add twice as much water by volume. Add more water
if necessary. Other formulas are more complicated and involve more
ingredients, some of them hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A contractor told me not to install vinyl siding in July and
August but did not give a reason. Another contractor said it was
OK. Who's right?
</P>
<P>
   FRANCIS CURLEY, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's the first time the handyman has heard any taboos on
installing vinyl in the heat of the summer, and as far as I know,
the fellow who says it is OK is right; it really does not matter.
After all, July and August are the heart of the vinyl installation
season, and it's a sure bet that those people would not shut down
in that prime time. Besides, vinyl siding is hung on the wall, not
nailed tightly, to allow for movement during expansion and
contraction, so it should not matter when it is installed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am relocating my washer and dryer from the basement to the
first floor. The dryer is going in a closet (exhausting to the
outdoors), but the washer has to go into a bathroom with little
room to spare. Could I take out a vanity to make room for the
washer?
</P>
<P>
   SARAH MONTGOMERY, Wayland, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You could, because I don't think there is a law that requires
a bathroom to have a sink. But it would be better, in my opinion,
to install a mini-sink in addition to the washer. It's a matter of
convenience. A plumber can find you a super-small sink.
</P>
<P>
   Another solution, depending on plumbing connections, your
budget, and the age of your present appliances, is to invest in a
piggy-back combo, with dryer over, washer under.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am doing everything to redo my rooms, but I am wondering
what to do first, second, third, and last. Is there a rule about
painting ceiling, woodwork, and walls, and sanding and refinishing
floors?
</P>
<P>
   SELMA SHERMAN, Swampscott, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You answered your own question as to the order of projects in
redoing a room. Paint the ceiling first, then the woodwork, then
the walls. Sand and finish floors last. This doesn't sound logical,
because sanding is such a dirty job. But thinking about it, doing
the floors last makes sense, because the sanding dust is clean, and
is easily vacuumed and wiped off floors and wall and ceilings, all
of which are equally clean. Besides, if you did the floors first,
you would be tramping around and spilling paint on a new floor,
unless you use tarps.
</P>
<P>
   There is always some question as to the order of painting walls
and woodwork, but the reason the handyman suggests woodwork first
is that it is easier to paint the narrow edges of the woodwork
before doing the walls. Try it; you'll see what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
