<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERPLANT-SITES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCERS RACING TO BUILD GENERATING FACILITIES IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Denis &UR;  &LR; Fraine worries that Bellingham, Mass. and some towns
near it could become the ``kilowatt capital'' of New England.
</P>
<P>
   Bellingham already has a large power plant and five more are
proposed for the immediate area. Fraine, a town administrator, is
eager for all the tax money new electric plants would bring to
Bellingham, but he's also leery about the environmental and
aesthetic headaches that come with big power facilities.
</P>
<P>
   For good or bad, prospectors are rushing into New England with
proposals to construct a new generation of electric facilities, all
natural gas-fired. The lure: newly opened power markets.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, and Maine have
recently enacted electric deregulation laws that eliminate
utilities' monopoly over power generation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, independent power producers _ mostly from outside
New England _ have proposed building nearly 50 electric generating
plants producing upwards of 30,000 megawatts of power in the four
states. That's more than all the power currently available in all
of New England.
</P>
<P>
   The new natural gas facilities would be more efficient than
existing oil or gas plants and thus produce cheaper power. Also,
they would significantly reduce air pollution and require less
water to cool their turbines.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, where deregulation is furthest along, has been
the biggest magnet. Eighteen plants have been proposed here,
including a 1,500-megawatt plant in Everett that would replace most
of the existing Mystic River plant, a major air polluter formerly
owned and operated by Boston Edison Co.
</P>
<P>
   Under deregulation, which required utilities to divest
themselves of their generating facilities, Boston Edison sold
Mystic River to Sithe Energies Inc. of New York, which proposed the
new Everett facility.
</P>
<P>
   In Agawam, Charlton, and Dighton, three plants that would
produce over 800 megawatts are under construction. Two more
facilities are proposed for Bellingham and Blackstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before deregulation, when we first proposed building an
electric generating plant whose power we sell to anyone at
prevailing rates, people in Boston thought we were crazy,'' said
Kenneth Roberts, chief operating officer of Power Development
Corp., a Boston company that began construction in January on a
272-megawatt plant in Agawam. ``Now those same people call us
visionaries. It's a very fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   The power plant rush also is being fueled by two natural gas
pipelines that will come into Massachusetts from Canada next year.
Compared with other regions, New England has long been more
dependent on oil and less on natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a big opportunity in the region,'' said Thomas
O'Connor, of North Carolina-based Duke Energy Corp., which is
involved in building one of the pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   But it's far from certain all the plant proposals will get off
the drawing boards. Tempering the optimism are a series of
environmental and state requirements for site permits plus
community reviews of the impact on local water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Money also will be a big question mark. Only a small number of
the new power developers will be able to raise the $100 million to
$700 million needed to build an electric plant. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Financiers who put up the money for the new plants will
remember the lessons of the 1980s here, particularly in the
overbuilding of real estate and other assets,'' said James Gordon,
president of Energy Management Inc. of Dartmouth, which is building
a 175-megawatt electric plant in Dighton.
</P>
<P>
   For communities that open their arms to the new power players,
rewards can be huge.
</P>
<P>
   In Bellingham and Blackstone, American National Power Co. of
Houston hopes to break ground by year-end on a pair of 550-megawatt
facilities. Both towns will gain $45.5 million in real estate tax
revenue over the next 20 years from American National Power. For
Bellingham, the company also agreed to spend $2.4 million to
improve the sewer system, $500,000 for a new Council of Aging
building, and $650,000 for a water conservation fund. It also
pledged to turn over 92 acres for town conservation use.
</P>
<P>
   In Blackstone, American National Power agreed to sell
electricity at a discount for five years, and to provide $600,000
for water conservation and $3.5 million for the sewers.
</P>
<P>
   But the new electric plant proposals also have drawn flak.
Bellingham's selectmen recently rejected a proposal for a
1,035-megawatt plant as too big. But the plant's developer has
offered to pick up the town's $8 million cost for a new high school
and pay approximately $4.5 million in taxes a year. ``If they
downsize their project ... we would reconsider it, said Fraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
