<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-TOURISM-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN TOURISM LANGUISHING IN SHADOW OF MIDEAST STALEMATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, July 26) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ The picture on the wall shows Tareh
Saliba, a gray-haired Palestinian businessman, cutting a cake in
celebration of the opening of his new hotel, The Nativity. At his
side, flanked by burly security men, is Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, in town to mark the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Taken in April 1996, the snapshot hangs near a large wooden
cross in an empty hotel conference room used by Christian pilgrims
as a prayer hall, a reminder of the high hopes Palestinians pinned
on increased tourism in the wake of peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the picture seems out of place with the air of solitude
outside the conference hall. It's not one of the peak tourist
seasons _ those are in March, for Easter, and November, for the
Feast of Tabernacles. Still, occupancy rates are far below
expectations &UR; .  &LR; Only 20 of Saliba's 90 rooms are filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Israel and the Palestinians signed the peace treaty, we
thought things would be OK in the future,'' said Saliba. He
converted his original plan to build a business center to the hotel
project in anticipation of an influx of tourism after the 1993 deal
was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that things would be good because peace was
coming,'' he said. ``But it hasn't happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional birthplace of Jesus and a 20-minute drive from
religious sites in Jerusalem and the Jordan Valley, Bethlehem
should be overflowing with Christian pilgrims and curious tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not, indicating that perception of the region as
dangerous will be more difficult to overcome than entrepreneurs
like Saliba had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, suicide bombings carried out by Palestinian militants
killed 59 Israelis. The tourism industry, riding the crest of a
two-year wave precipitated by peace, never fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   But with better facilities and a steady influx of Jewish
visitors, particularly from the United States and Europe, Israeli
tourism can limp along where nascent Palestinian tourism cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestinian infrastructure for tourism is in a bad state,''
said Mohammed Shtayyeh, who heads the Palestinian Economic Council
for Development and Reconstruction, an extragovernmental body set
up in the wake of the peace agreement to oversee foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bethlehem is the Mecca of the Christian world, and yet there
are no five-star hotels there,'' said Shtayyeh, an economist.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians blame the state of their towns on Israeli neglect
during 30 years of military rule. Main streets in Bethlehem are
under construction or repair.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinians also suffer from television images of rioting
and the vague perception among tourists that areas under their rule
are not safe.
</P>
<P>
   That perception is reinforced by Israeli car-rental companies
that refuse to insure cars driven in Palestinian areas. Until
recently, Israel posted signs at the entrances to Palestinian-ruled
towns warning tourists not to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are frightening the people away,'' said Saliba. ``They
tell tourists at the airport that there isn't security here. That's
not good, and it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 17 months of political stalemate have not improved those
perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when the Israeli-Palestinian peace process was moving
forward, 2.5 million tourists visited Israel, the highest number in
years. Many of them came to the traditionally Christian towns of
Bethlehem and Jericho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they say, `not this year, we can come to see Bethlehem and
Jerusalem when the situation improves,''' said Nabil Bandak, an
operator with Near East Tours, one of the Palestinians' largest
tourist companies, based in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening politically is not comfortable to the ears of
the American or the European tourists,'' Bandak said. ``They hear
the Israelis threaten and the Palestinians threaten. It's not
comfortable for the pilgrims. And it's not good for tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   The state of affairs mirrors an economic downturn, both in
Israel and in the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Palestinian Authority was set up in 1994, 8,500 new
Palestinian companies have been set up, a phenomenal number in an
economy with less than 3 million people.
</P>
<P>
   But many of them are ``only on paper,`` said Shtayyeh. ``The
potential for investment is great,'' said Shtayyeh. ``But the real
investment is not yet there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reason, he said, was due to Israel's prolonged
policy _ in place since 1993 _ requiring Palestinians to get
permits to travel in between the West Bank and Gaza. Similarly, the
total value of goods and services produced within the region
declined 24 percent between 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, likewise, has suffered an economic downturn since 1996
that some economists partially attribute to the downturn in the
peace process. Unemployment in Israel hovers around 11 percent and
the economy is in recession.
</P>
<P>
   Saliba, like most Palestinians in tourism, says he hopes
celebrations planned for the year 2000 will pull the industry out
of the dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Israel expects 4 million tourists to come that year, more than
double the usual annual number. Italy, Turkey and Jordan are also
heavily promoting their religious sites to attract tourists in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   High expectations for 2000, said Saliba, are enticing investors
to sink money into an industry that has limped along with a 20
percent occupancy rate for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people thinking to start building hotels,'' he
said. ``Some have already started. They are living on hope.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
