<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-RYAN-1-HN     07-24 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-RYAN-1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, SOMETHING GOOD FROM STEVEN SPIELBERG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I must begin this review by reiterating my stand on the work of
director Steven Spielberg. I think its cheap thrills and thudding
sentimentality have contributed to the general infantilization of
American movies. That stated, it is my pleasure to announce that
not only is ``Saving Private Ryan'' the best movie he ever made,
but it is a terrific movie by any standards. Spielberg is growing
up.
</P>
<P>
   The director says he has recently been traveling the country
giving interviews about the movie, not to promote it, but to warn
people of the graphic nature of its violence. I doubt the
ingenuousness of this notion, but he would have nothing to be
ashamed of if he admitted to simply wanting as many people as
possible to come see his wonderful new movie.
</P>
<P>
   The story is foolproof. Proving himself to be the great everyman
actor of his era yet again, Tom Hanks plays Capt. Miller, an
ordinary man thrown into the extraordinary circumstances of World
War II European battle. After surviving the carnage of the Omaha
Beach D-Day landing, he and a small group of soldiers are ordered
to embark on what seems a wild goose chase.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has discovered that a Mrs. Ryan of Iowa, mother of four
boys, has lost three of them to the war. On the assumption that one
is still alive, Miller and his troops are sent on foot through
battle-torn areas to find Pvt. James Ryan and send him home to his
grieving mother before he gets killed.
</P>
<P>
   As the soldiers in the unit note, the mission is both
humanitarian and galling at the same time. Poor Mrs. Ryan, they all
concede; yet why is saving Ryan worth risking the lives of a bunch
of other perfectly nice guys who also have mothers?
</P>
<P>
   World War II was one of the last times in recent history when
Americans felt proud of being one of the most militarily powerful
nations on Earth. It was a time when we could believe that our
firepower would actually be used to do good in the world. The
soldiers who fought knew they were eradicating evil. They could
persuade themselves that the brutality of war might actually be
justifiable.
</P>
<P>
   And the people back home were rooting for them to accomplish the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg does a wonderful job of capturing this idea of
nobility. Even though his soldiers are scared of being killed, you
understand that they have a profound sense that they are all
working toward something greater than themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons this movie is so much better than
``Schindler's List'' is that Spielberg is no longer in pedagogic
mode here. He is not teaching tolerance, at least not overtly, nor
proving that a horrendous episode of history took place in the face
of doubters. All he is doing is telling _ with skill and heart _ a
story about several human beings interacting under the duress of
life-threatening times.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason ``Private Ryan'' succeeds is that unlike the
Schindler story, the ``Private Ryan'' conflicts are amazingly
simple. We know that Spielberg _ who did well making ``Duel,''
about a man being chased by an evil truck, and ``Jaws,'' about
several men being chased by an evil shark _ is good at Simple.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's talent has always been to tell a story well, but he
often did so by resorting to the overkill of technical
contrivances. He came up with amazingly real-looking dinosaurs, but
the movie's premise was so far-fetched, who could care?
</P>
<P>
   This time, the fantasy is abandoned, and Spielberg applies the
technical wizardry to a painfully harsh reality. The first 24
minutes of ``Saving Private Ryan'' are a brutal evocation of the
landing of American troops on Omaha Beach during the Normandy
invasion of 1944. ``Private Ryan'' makes ``The Longest Day'' look
like ``Beach Blanket Bingo.''
</P>
<P>
   For just one example of the cruelty of war (and of the great
cinematography by Janusz Kaminski), there is much drama and sorrow
in watching soldiers weighed down by their equipment sinking in the
surf as they fall out of the invading vessels. We see them struggle
to shed their weights and swim to the surface for air, but in many
cases German bullets streak through the water and kill them before
they can rise.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg clearly had in mind to emulate some of the best war
movies ever made _ ``All Quiet on the Western Front,'' ``Stalag
17,'' ``The Great Escape,'' ``Grand Illusion'' _ as he skillfully
assembled ``Private Ryan.'' Nothing beats a ragtag band of soldiers
thrown together. And to re-create those great collections of
humanity, he assembled an emotionally satisfying cast of young
actors.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks brings a quiet brilliance to his sensitive portrayal of
Miller. Edward Burns (director of ``The Brothers McMullen'') is
fine as Reiben, a Brooklyn-bred soldier fed up with the war and
with authority, a character John Garfield might have played. And
Tom Sizemore is the William Bendix stand-in as Sarge, Miller's
right-hand man. There's Jackson, the religious sharpshooter played
by Barry Pepper, and Adam Goldberg as Mellish, the Jew only too
happy to see German prisoners-of-war marching to prison.
</P>
<P>
   To help us newcomers in the audience acclimate to the rigors of
war, Spielberg gives us a naive guide, Cpl. Upham (Jeremy Davies),
a translator who has never been under fire. He asks all the dopey
questions we un-uniformed people in the audience want to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Damon, best-screenplay-Oscar-winner for ``Good Will
Hunting,'' plays the title character. He doesn't have much to do,
but he does it well. Throughout the quest for Ryan, Miller and
company continually voice the weary and angry hope that Ryan will
turn out to be a fellow worth saving. It is Damon's tough job to
make us believe that this is so.
</P>
<P>
   Damon is saddled with giving one of the movie's more sentimental
speeches, but he is good enough to pull it off. He does writer
Robert Rodat proud. Less good, but forgivable, is Spielberg's
insistence on tacking onto this movie a completely unnecessary coda
reminiscent of the ``Schindler's List'' ending. Many viewers may
disagree with this view at least partly because Spielberg's ending
provides the crowd with one big, cleansing cry. Sometimes an
audience enjoys the catharsis of the great boohoo. I enjoyed my
cry, too, but that doesn't make it good.
</P>
<P>
   The movie would undoubtedly have been a better work of art had
it ended before Spielberg glued on all the curlicues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the many pleasures of this movie is Spielberg's giving up
on storyboard (drawings that look like cartoon panels and to some
degree dictate a cartoonishness to his films) to get down in the
trenches (literally) and shoot battle scenes with hand-held cameras
as if the cameramen were in battle with the soldiers. The effect is
riveting and frightening. You feel you are under siege with the
combatants.
</P>
<P>
   We bring the close-up horror of those opening minutes with us
though the rest of the film. The D-Day landing on Omaha Beach was a
slaughter, and from the first moments you have a profound
understanding of how capricious the fates were. That the character
Hanks plays survives the landing is a minor miracle. Every day
forward from that moment in the movie seems a bonus. And you may
feel that way about your own life, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
