   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND _ BELFAST, Ireland _ It took the tragic deaths of three
boys to ease the worst tensions in this war-torn nation in years.
Tensions that were expected to wither following a decisive vote for
one Ireland this spring. President Clinton has added a stop-over
here on his return trip from Russia in September to add his voice
to those pleading for unity and calm. But some significant
questions need to be answered, not the least of which is: Has the
peace process, having weathered this latest crisis, regained
momentum? (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   JERICHO-CASINO _ JERICHO, West Bank _ This is the oldest and
lowest city in the world. But, is it lucky? In the dusty expanse of
desert across the street from one of the oldest Palestinian refugee
camps, hundreds of workers are building a casino hotel aimed
largely at tempting Israelis to come gamble _ something they cannot
do next door in Israel. It's a business venture that is sure to
cause political waves among both Palestinians and Israelis even as
it could turn a big profit. The casino project is headed by an
Austrian firm with the consent of Yasser Arafat's Palestinian
Authority. But, it is widely disliked by the Palestinians who live
in the refugee camp and famous biblical town nearby. The problem is
not that Palestinians will not be allowed to gamble there. Rather,
they see gambling and the western culture it represents as a threat
to their Islamic values. Some even object to the high profile the
10-story hotel will cut amid the peaceful town of 15,000. Many of
their arguments would be recognizable to Americans who have heard
the religious opposition to casino gambling in their own country.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 11 a.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COSSACKS _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The feared Cossacks
ride again? Russia's tradition-steeped warrior caste is undergoing
a revival of sorts, after being submerged for decades by the Soviet
Union. St. Petersburg officials plan to use the Cossacks to patrol
city parks and assist regular police in fighting crime -- sort of
the Guardian Angels, Russo-style. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Thursday, July 24.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH _ WASHINGTON _ Despite a veto threat from the White
House, Republicans are rushing to the House floor with legislation
they brought forward only a week ago to respond to Americans'
complaints about health plans. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FARM-AID _ WASHINGTON _ Just two years after the nation's
farmers were put on the path to independence from subsidies and
price supports, the concept of the ``Freedom to Farm'' act is
coming under a severe test in the drought of 1998 as lawmakers and
the president rush to provide aid. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT _ WASHINGTON _ Setup for vote likely Monday in the Senate
on credit union reform. (Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EUROPA _ WASHINGTON _ Much of scientists' concerns about the
possibility of extraterrestrial microbes infecting Earth in samples
collected by space missions involve two moons of Jupiter, Europa
and Ganymede, where conditions are believed best to support life.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
