<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV26-B     07-24 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEWSPAPER FOR THE CARTOON FAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dean Wallace had his dream, it had cartoons running through
it.
</P>
<P>
   It still does. Last week the Somerville, Mass. entrepreneur
pumped out the 200th issue of ``Editorial Humor,'' a scrappy,
mostly-cartoons-with-a-few-columns biweekly tabloid which, if it
doesn't give you a laugh on every page, will give Wallace gas
pains.
</P>
<P>
   To call him a cartoon nut is to understate the situation. His
fascination with drawings-in-a-box began 1951, Wallace says with
the specificity of a truly maniacal cartoon fan. At age eight, he
came across a Herblock cartoon in the newspaper, showing Gen.
Douglas MacArthur riding through cheering crowds.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur had just been sacked by President Truman for
insubordination over the conduct of the Korean war. Herblock
labelled one MacArthur ``World War II Hero,'' the other
``Politician,'' and the caption ran: ``Hurrah for the one on this
side,'' signifying the cartoonist's cheer for the hero, not the
politician.
</P>
<P>
   The kid was hooked, but he could never draw even a stick figure.
Through Trinity College in Hartford, and a masters at Northwestern
in history, to a University of Connecticut PhD, Wallace's cartoon
fetish remained in check.
</P>
<P>
   A stint as a chanteyman and performer at Mystic Seaport in
Connecticut moulted into a 12-year career as president of a
wholesale dealer in non-mainstream music. He hit the ``burnout''
wall in 1985, sold the business, and ``tried to write the Great
American Novel.'' So, Dean, how was that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Harder than it looks,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, he and a newspaper editor friend schemed to
start up their own little newspaper, which can be as daunting a
task as starting up your own little automobile factory. Soup to
nuts, it's a lot of work to make it go.
</P>
<P>
   At the 11th hour, his first partner got a promotion and dropped
out, and Wallace turned to an artist friend, Phil Uzanas. ``Without
Phil's help I never could have gotten the paper off the ground,''
he says. They opened under the business title ``HOP Publications.''
``Hop'' is either his mother (Hopkins) nickname, or stands for
``handshake over pizza;'' Wallace tells both versions.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to start a paper that saw the world through the
skewed or screwy or seer-like eyes of the most talented cartoonists
the pair could muster. He quickly scrapped plans to call his paper
``Strip Tease'' because of the invidious implications; there's
nothing blue or salacious in his selections. Teachers at a number
of high schools use the paper to get across sophisticated notions
of satire and political manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   The initial name was ``Out.rage.us,'' but that gave way to
calling it the Boston Comic News, till an associate, Stavros
Cosmopulos, persuaded him to rename it ``Editorial Humor,'' so
``advertisers would not think we are aimed at the 10-year olds who
read comic books.''
</P>
<P>
   Since one person's cartoon meat is another's cartoon poison,
Wallace has fielded hundreds of opinionated letters through the
years, such as one in '94:
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you're a paper for `intelligent adults' or you're not.
You take away Feiffer and add Dilbert? Give me a break!'' Every
editor who's ever had to yank one cartoon strip to add another
opens that kind of mail with a sinking heart. Taste in cartoons is
like taste in food or fashion, only more so.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace gets to propound his own whimsical or wacky take on
current events in his own regular column. He invites readers to
submit their cartoons (no original copies, please), runs a cartoon
contest judged by local luminaries Szep, Wasserman, Danziger and
Holbert, as well as further-away 'toonists cqsuch as Tom Toles of
Buffalo, Jim Borgman of Cincinnati and Kevin Kalligan (KAL) of
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   When the National Sports Daily folded, Wallace bought 200 of
their newspaper vending machines, and his boxes are ubiquitous
around Greater Boston. He's heavy on Harvard and Davis Squares,
along the Cambridge-Somerville hipness axis.
</P>
<P>
   His advertisers range from local restaurants, pubs, clubs to
boutiques, the Allston Amvets Thrift Store, youth and young-adult
marketers, and a recent issue's back page pictured a full color
pint of creamy Guinness stout.
</P>
<P>
   Cover price is 50 cents, but some are distributed free. The fare
is mostly national and international. If the young are supposed to
be getting their news largely from television, then a good portion
of the more educated slice of the population gets their chuckles
from sophisticated cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace says reader surveys show 45 percent of his audience is
between 25 and 34, a third of them have graduate degrees, and 61
percent attended college. Out of every ten readers, he says, six
are professionals, one self-employed, another's a techie, and
(almost) two are students. ``Teachers use us in all sorts of
settings, for current events and arts to English as a second
language or helping GED students overcome their fears of writing.''
</P>
<P>
   What may seem like a zany cartoonist's fevered imagination can
turn out to be the next day's news with fearsome rapidity. Wallace
points to the many global developments since he started in 1989
where many established patterns in geopolitics ``were turned upside
down'' in ways that may have surprised cartoonists less than
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Cold War, the Soviet breakup, Mandela going from
prison to the presidency of South Africa, the Pope in Cuba, these
developments were wilder than any cartoonist would have predicted.
But the cartoonists often cut a lot closer to the bone of reality
than, say, the columnists or editorial writers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
