   VLASIC (Cherry Hill, N.J.) _ Vlasic, which was spun off from
Campbell Soup a year ago, is trying to revitalize a group of food
businesses that its old parent company decided it did not need.
Some analysts think the effort could produce healthy profits. By
Constance Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments in the General Motors
strike. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ENRON-WESSEX (Dallas) _ Enron buys Wessex Water, a water and
sewerage company in the west of England, for 1.36 billion pounds,
or $2.2 billion, in cash. The price per share is 27.8 percent above
the closing share price, of 4.93 pounds, on Thursday. The planned
purchase is the electricity and gas company's first venture into
the water industry. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Mexico City) _ As if low oil prices were not doing
enough economic damage, Mexico also has to contend with the impact
of the Asian crisis. In the latest example of Asian fallout,
Mexico's largest steel producer, Altos Hornos de Mexico, is cutting
3,000 of its 20,000 jobs. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ECON (London) _ The pound's strength is causing pain for
many British exporters. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up 52 points at 1:55 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments: The long bond
was uo 5/32 at midday. By Robert Hurtado.
