<HEADLINE>
FOR BANKER, JAMMIN SCIENCE FEST IS A SOUND INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There's a technical question for executives: What do
astronomy and space exploration have to do with banking and
business?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty, says Seafirst Bank Chairman John Rindlaub. Rindlaub is
one of the driving forces behind the ``Jammin Science Fest'' held
this week in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A science enthusiast from way back, he has an ulterior motive
for getting kids excited about science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching kids about science helps them in ways that also benefit
employers, he said. ``It encourages kids to develop
critical-thinking skills and the ability to use new information in
problem-solving _ which are important skills they can bring to the
workplace as future employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they're not working in high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at jobs today, more and more jobs _ and the
better-paying ones _ will touch on science literacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even customer service jobs in non-technical industries assume a
certain level of technical proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real challenge we all have is in hiring, training and
retaining good people,'' he said. ``In an area with one of the
lowest unemployment rates in the country, that's increasingly a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   That awareness led to the development of the science festival.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old science program for kids is designed to give
students a hands-on chance to learn about science in an
entertaining fashion. Since 1995, it has reached more than 14,000
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Each year has a different theme. This year, kids delved into
space exploration through exhibits on constellations, the solar
system, star colors and a real meteorite.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching kids science by having them participate is what builds
their excitement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to instill some curiosity at an early age, and do
it not through show-and-tell but in an interactive way.''
</P>
<P>
   His hope is that it will lead to more and better science
learning as they go through school.
</P>
<P>
   American students have been lagging in science scores in recent
years. Earlier this year, for example, U.S. high school seniors had
among the lowest scores of 21 nations in the Third International
Mathematics and Science Study.
</P>
<P>
   And a 1996 study reported by the National Assessment Governing
Board showed that four out of 10 seniors were deficient in science
knowledge and skills. Lower-grade students fared somewhat better,
but only 3 percent of kids in all the grades were capable of
advanced work.
</P>
<P>
   Why does that matter, unless you're planning to be a scientist?
</P>
<P>
   The value of a grounding in the sciences goes deeper than
technical knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skill set needed in business gets back to scientific
literacy,'' Rindlaub said. Doing good science depends on the
``three C's _ curiosity, creativity and critical thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   And that leads to a fourth C critical to business _ the ability
to compete. All businesses rely on employees who can solve problems
and think beyond the obvious, which is what science is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking is even more critical with advances in information
sciences and the explosion of Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a data-rich and information-poor society,'' he said.
``There's lots of data out there. It's how we translate that into
information that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, real competitive advances in business will come
from an interdisciplinary approach similar to the one taking place
in various scientific fields. The combination of computer sciences
and genetics, for example, is leading to a revolution in
understanding how genes work in the body, and has generated a new
model for treating disease.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rindlaub envisions similar innovations will come from
``horizontal'' thinking across divisions from customer service to
product development.
</P>
<P>
   Rindlaub has loved science since he was a kid getting up in the
middle of the night to look at the planets through his telescope.
He admits his office today ``looks like a recording studio and
print shop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seafirst's program has already expanded to Oregon and Idaho.
Other business leaders have expressed an interest in mounting
similar programs, or launching other initiatives to try to build
scientific literacy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to turn as many kids as possible into students who
will carry a desire to learn new things into their careers, he
said. ``As fast as the world is changing, lifelong training is here
to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Smith is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. Her e-mail
address is carolsmith(at)seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
