<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DUO-HAPA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPA'S HYBRID BLENDS ISLAND FOLKLORE WITH MAINLAND POP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hapa means ``half-half'' or ``ethnically mixed'' in Hawaiian
slang.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an affectionate local term,'' guitarist Barry Flanagan of
the music duo Hapa said by phone from Waikiki. ``There's a great
mixture of ethnicity here. It means `half-half,' and that can mean
half Hawaiian and half Caucasian or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan, who co-founded the duo with Keli'i Kaneali'i in 1984,
grew up in a mostly Italian neighborhood in New Jersey. Kaneali'i
grew up in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   They met at a Christmas party on Maui in 1983. An impromptu
performance convinced them to form a duo combining their diverse
but complementary styles, creating a blend of Hawaiian music with
American and European pop and folk.
</P>
<P>
   The two musicians share lead vocals and play a variety of
stringed instruments, mostly guitars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who heard us at the party thought we were this
rehearsed group,'' Flanagan said. ``But it was actually the first
time we had played together. It was very serendipitous.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan had been playing in a country-rock band in Colorado
when he decided to travel to Hawaii in 1980 to study the Hawaiian
slack-key guitar style, which involves retuning the guitar by
slackening the strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up moving back here with my girlfriend about three
years later,'' Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hapa is one of Hawaii's most popular groups. The duo's
debut album, ``Hapa,'' was released about five years ago and has
sold almost 500,000 copies. The current album, ``In the Name of
Love,'' so far has sold about 75,000. The group also has released
an album of electric surf-guitar music called ``Surf Madness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hawaiian music scene is really an anomaly,'' Flanagan
said. ``It's a pretty huge scene, one of the largest regional
markets in the world. Local artists can sell 100,000 albums here
(in Hawaii) in a year, and records just continue to sell. They
don't have a six-month lifespan.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Flanagan has composed many of the duo's more
Hawaiian-styled songs, among them ``E Hele Ana E,'' ``Nani Wale o
Ka'inlani'' and ``Lelehuna.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Flanagan's more striking compositions is ``The Waikiki
Beachboy Song,'' a wistful, almost eerie ballad about Waikiki's
vanishing beach boys.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan was inspired to write the song after reading ``The
Waikiki Beach Boy,'' a book by Grady Timmons about the history of
Hawaiian beach boys, who serenaded tourists and taught them how to
surf.
</P>
<P>
   Performing guest vocals on the song is Hawaii's most famous
singer, Don Ho, a man Kaneali'i calls ``the Frank Sinatra of
Hawaiian music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a verse for Don and he loved it,'' Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Ho agreed to record the song with Hapa, Flanagan and
Kaneali'i began sitting in on Sunday nights at Ho's regular
performances at the Waikiki Beachcomber. ``I really wanted to know
why this man was the No. 1 name in Hawaiian music since the late
'50s or early '60s,'' Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan and Kaneali'i were floored by Ho's professionalism.
``He still does five nights a week. He's the consummate
entertainer. It's no mistake or fluke that he's been the No. 1 name
in entertainment here for almost four decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan recalled one of the first shows Hapa did with Ho.
``When the show was over, he was running by me to be the first
person out in front to greet everyone. And as he's running by me,
he goes, `Hey, Barry, get out there and be with the people. Don't
be like Elvis. Look what happened to him,''' Flanagan said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The current album also includes versions of the guitar classic
``Sleepwalk,'' played on a Hawaiian steel guitar; and U2's ``Pride
(In the Name of Love).''
</P>
<P>
   Hapa first played the U2 song on Martin Luther King Jr. Day five
years ago in front of a crowd of 30,000 at Hawaii's Hula Bowl. The
day also marked the 100th anniversary of the overthrow of the
Hawaiian monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest crowd we had ever played, and it was a very
emotional day for many Hawaiians,'' Flanagan said. ``We liked the
song so much we started closing all our shows with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hapa spends most of the year performing in the Hawaiian Islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything from baby luaus to large-scale theater
shows,'' Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three months of the year, Hapa travels to the mainland to
perform a series of concerts. The duo currently is on a West Coast
tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
