<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITLER-PLOTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITLER'S ASSASSINATION MIGHT HAVE LED TO ANOTHER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The newly disclosed fact that secret British
intelligence plans to assassinate Adolf Hitler during World War II
never came off is probably good news for the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   If, as revealed this week, British agents had succeeded in
bumping off the 20th century's master monster, it might have
assured that the Hitlerian myth would have survived to help revive
the Nazi cause a generation later and to bring on World War III.
</P>
<P>
   His assassination would have resulted in another
``stab-in-the-back'' theory like the one that fueled Germany's
nationalism after its defeat in 1918, leading to the eventual rise
to power of the dreadful corporal with his promise of revenge. When
the Germans lost World War I, many claimed that enemies within had
overthrown the regime of Kaiser Wilhelm and that, had that
treachery not occurred, Germany would have pursued the war and
ultimately prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Hitler's ignominious 1945 suicide in his Berlin
bunker to escape capture by the Russians effectively destroyed the
myth of the great leader except for a handful of Nazi diehards.
</P>
<P>
   With the war's end, the vast majority of Germans were ready to
abandon the memory of their past conquests and military glory and
to begin looking toward a different kind of future. For almost the
first time in their history, they started building a nation based
on democratic foundations. But a martyred Hitler might well have
been a serious obstacle to that process.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the failure of a July 1944 plot by German officers
to kill him and stage a coup was also a good thing although it led
to the executions of hundreds of brave men. Anything that allowed
the Germans to claim they hadn't lost the war because they were
beaten by stronger enemies _ which was the case _ would have meant
trouble for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the newly revealed secret archives show that
British agents seriously embarked on a scheme to kill Hitler _
either at Berchtesgaden, his Bavarian retreat, or on board his
special train _ only in 1944 when it was already apparent that
Germany was losing the war. British Prime Minister Winston
Churchill, among others, favored assassination and was ready to
approve a feasible plan. Luckily, no such plan was ever developed.
</P>
<P>
   The most persistent objection to the plot made by allied
officials was that Hitler was committing so many strategic errors
that his removal would prolong the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been true in the immediate sense, but a deeper
objection to killing him was that it would have assured the
continuation of the Hitler legend. Thank heaven it didn't happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
