<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAIL-THEFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIL CAN BE EASY BOOTY FOR THIEVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With MAIL-THEFT-TIPS)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Several months ago, Claudia Dean stopped at her
bank to make a deposit and instead made a disturbing discovery: Her
account was $300 short.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing her balance statement, Dean found three checks she
didn't remember writing. Someone had stolen Dean's new checks. They
had been left sitting on a shelf in the unlocked, communal foyer of
her apartment building, delivered by the mailman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even think about my mail, never gave it a second
thought,'' said Dean, 37. ``But I do now. I'm not having my checks
delivered anymore. I'll pick them up at the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Mail theft, and subsequent mail fraud, bleeds Americans of
millions of dollars every year _ between $20 million and $30
million in stolen credit cards alone, according to U.S. Postal
Inspection Service statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``These scams are relatively easy to do,'' said Ray Smith, a
Postal Service inspector in Albany. ``A person can steal thousands
of dollars in a matter of hours using just a few pieces of mail _
credit cards, blank checks, bank statements. Even a signed check
you send out to pay a bill has your account number and your
signature, that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, about 4,300 people were arrested for mail theft
nationwide and some 4,100 were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Other types of fraud, however, are on the rise. Technological
advances have armed thieves with a new arsenal of tools including
color printers and scanners used to make counterfeit documents.
Personal information of potential victims _ like Social Security
and credit card numbers _ are accessible on the Internet at the
click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Mail theft often occurs because many people unwittingly
advertise their mail to potential thieves by raising the red flag
on their mailbox, Smith said. A flag alerts thieves that there
might be signed checks inside, which is why trolling for full
mailboxes is sometimes referred to as ``flagging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a better idea to mail bills in a secure box on the
corner, or at the post office,'' Smith said. ``And know when your
financial statements come in.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is immune to mail theft, Smith said. It occurs in tony
suburban neighborhoods and inner-city apartment complexes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
