<SLUG> BC-MAIL-THEFT-TIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYS TO PROTECT MAIL FROM THIEVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are ways to protect your mail from thieves, according to
the U.S. Postal Inspection Service:
</P>
<P>
   _ When paying bills, do not place signed checks in your home
mailbox and raise the red flag as a signal to the letter carrier
that there's something inside; thieves look for that flag too.
Instead, drop bills in a secure corner mailbox or at the post
office.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to collect your mail soon after it is delivered. Don't
provide opportunities for someone to commit mail theft.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pick up renewal checks at the bank, don't have them sent to
your home. The boxes are too easily recognized by thieves.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're going out of town for more than three days, make a
``stop delivery'' request at your local post office, or have a
neighbor collect your mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bank statements, pre-approved credit card applications, Social
Security checks and replacement checks or credit cards are prime
targets for a mail thief. Try to be aware of when this kind of mail
is due to be delivered to your house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not simply discard potentially sensitive documents _
anything with your Social Security, bank or credit card account
number on it _ destroy them to avert ``Dumpster divers,'' who sift
through the trash in search of these items.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you believe you are a victim of mail theft or mail fraud,
call the U.S. Postal Inspectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
