<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-BUDGET `PI' IS A BIG-SCREEN SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``PI'' will not be for everyone, but for those who are fed up
with the mainstream idiocy that gets dumped into theaters each
summer, this movie will be like a great big palate-clearing taste
of sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Darren Aronofsky has made a dark, comic drama
about Max, a madman mathematician played by Sean Gullette, an actor
who seems to have deep reserves of personal pain to draw from if
the simulated migraines Max suffers are any indication.
</P>
<P>
   With black-and-white cinematography by Matthew Libatique, an
eerie soundtrack by Clint Mansell and a tortured-looking leading
man, the movie is quirkily modern at the same time as being a dear
love note to all those sci-fi thrillers of the '50s when the threat
of nuclear annihilation loomed around every corner.
</P>
<P>
   Aronofsky had the clever idea to combine the ethereal passion of
a mathematician looking for a numerical explanation of the physical
world, with the spiritual interests of a group of Hasidic Jews
seeking the sacred number derived through Kabalistic means that
expresses the most holy name of God, and the financial lust of a
group of Wall Street types who want to use Max's genius to
manipulate stock investments.
</P>
<P>
   So in this movie there is passion (for knowledge), love (of
God), greed and plenty of conflict. I had a ball.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is minimal. Max's inner torment, not to mention his
excruciating headaches, provide most of the film's action, although
when the suits come after him looking for Dow Jones predictions
things get pretty cloak-and-dagger.
</P>
<P>
   Long sequences concentrate on Max's face as he tries to prove
that the universe is an orderly place. He believes that therefore,
even though no one has as yet discerned the pattern in the stock
market, he is certain there is one. Once decoded, it will apply to
many other long, seemingly arbitrary strings of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   That anyone is out there sweating to make movies (and this one's
budget was only $60,000!) about mathematical theories, philosophy
and other exertions of the mind would be great news all by itself.
That the movie is also good is even better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
