<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MAFIA!-2-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW GOOD LAUGHS IN `GODFATHER' SPOOF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wish I could report that ``Mafia!'' is half as funny as
``Airplane!,'' ``The Naked Gun'' or ``Hot Shots!,'' other items on
director-writer Jim Abrahams' resume.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Abrahams has, as always, created a number of hilarious
moments in this spoof of ``The Godfather'' (no exclamation point),
but not enough to keep a more or less one-gag movie going.
</P>
<P>
   To save you the trouble of hiring the baby sitter, parking,
buying tickets and drinking watered-down Coke, here is a partial
list of the best moments. (For those who absolutely must go, I omit
a few jokes.)
</P>
<P>
   The casino games include Chutes and Ladders, Go Fish and
Candyland. In some cases the casino prefers gamblers to just mail
them the money. It eliminates the unnecessary plane fare.
</P>
<P>
   Godfather Vincenzo Cortino (the elder version is played by Lloyd
Bridges) hails from that famed Sicilian town Salmonella. In his
boyhood he ate the taste treat spaghetti-on-a-stick. Times were so
bad that even nothing cost five cents.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vincenzo is head of the powerful Cortino family, he is
no mental giant. When members of another crime family ask Don
Cortino to become their partners in distributing a new product,
they carefully unwrap a cache of white powder. The Don thinks that
non-dairy creamer sounds like a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Don is gunned down by enemies, his son Anthony (the
rather insipid Jay Mohr) assures him, ``You lost a lot of blood,
but we found most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yup, those are the jokes. But this movie did have a saving grace
and that was the presence of Olympia Dukakis as the Don's aged
mother. Dukakis, who is a handsome and vibrant woman, plays Mama
Cortino as an aged, bent-over and angry matriarch. Watching her
actorly transformation was the highlight of the movie for me.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I feel I can in good conscience reveal what was the
movie's funniest line to me, as I was the only one in the theater
who laughed: A little boy says to Anthony's wife (Christina
Applegate), ``You smell good,'' and she replies, ``I had cantaloupe
for lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there something wrong with me?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
