A1481 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV26-     07-24 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV26-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE TIME TO STUDY THE FLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 26)  
(lh) 
 By TOVAH MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. _ People once went to Garden in the Woods
seeking nothing more than a stroll through the forest. In
springtime in the mid-1980s, the parking lot was filled by families
who descended into clouds of azaleas bedded with carpets of phlox,
walking with Virginia bluebells and poppy celandine lapping at
their ankles.
</P>
<P>
   They ventured into the garden, a 45-acre preserve here that is
the headquarters of the New England Wildflower Society, to commune
with painted turtles sunning themselves by the pond bank and to be
serenaded by a chorus of bird song. If they paid attention to the
signs, it was probably to point and say, ``Nice Anemonella
thalictroides,'' before the name slipped out of sight, out of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, a stroller is likely to encounter people at every bend
in the path with pens poised and note pads in hand, feverishly
jotting ideas for color combinations and easy-to-grow wildflowers
they want to incorporate into their own backyards. And Garden in
the Woods _ like many other public gardens _ has changed from a
place to take the children for a walk to an educational site. It
delights the eye while providing sharply focused information on
incorporating wildflowers into an ordinary yard. It has sunny
wildflower gardens and shady counterparts; it has wetland
wildflower gardens and arid versions, which demonstrate that the
moisture-demanding rose mallow (Hibiscus moscheutos) doesn't mix
happily with the moisture-averse butterfly weed (Asclepias
tuberosa).
</P>
<P>
   Those who yearn for a meadow will find a multiseason one with
purple coneflowers, blazing stars, black-eyed Susans and asters. If
you have hankered for a pond, the Garden in the Woods has one to
copy, native plantings and all. The garden has 1,700 species of
wildflowers, mostly native, displayed to best advantage. And it has
just created a garden devoted to plants on the government's
endangered species list. Although walking its paths is still a
pleasure, to be sure, the garden strives to get visitors involved.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy seems to be working. Parking spaces are at a
premium. (The garden reported 40,000 visitors in 1997, as against
8,000 in 1985.) And visitors have to drive slowly to avoid little
red wagons brimming with newly purchased native plants. People take
their strolls in the woods seriously these days.
</P>
<P>
   Although earlier visitors may not have noticed, Garden in the
Woods has always had an educational slant, going back to the time
when it was privately owned. It dates to 1932, when Will Curtis, a
landscape designer with a bent for natural plantings, saw an
undeveloped country parcel on Hemenway Road. It had everything: a
pond, a wooded bog, sunken ditches with steep slopes on either
side, a flowing brook and good soil.
</P>
<P>
   He bought the land, built a modest cottage in the forest and,
with his partner, Richard Stiles, spent the next 30 years creating
a garden that blended native and cultivated plants, ostensibly as a
selling tool for his design business. It was nature perfected; it
was the woods without poison ivy at a time when very few people
were working with native plants. In 1965, with suburban Boston
developments encroaching on all sides, Curtis gave Garden in the
Woods to the New England Wildflower Society, founded in 1900, which
needed a headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The name Garden in the Woods is a little misleading, because the
woodland is only one of the many habitats featured on the 45 acres.
Much of the 13 acres of cultivated wild gardens (that sounds like
an oxymoron, but managing wilderness is what Garden in the Woods is
all about) remains as Curtis and Stiles designed them, including
that grove of oaks and azaleas.
</P>
<P>
   But other areas have become more sharply focused for educational
and conservation purposes. There are a lily pond, a shady New
England bog, a sunny bog, pine barrens, an alpine rock garden, a
rock garden and a Western garden complete with hardy cacti and a
meadow.
</P>
<P>
   All the plants in those gardens are meticulously labeled, and
many can be purchased in the nursery. The staff members who
maintain decorum among the wildlings _ not a low-maintenance chore
_ are eager to share their secrets with visitors. For example, to
keep the entryway woodland garden abutting the original Curtis
cottage door in pristine condition, the beds are fertilized, a
percentage of the wildflower seeds are harvested before they
scatter, invasive weeds are yanked, trees are trimmed to provide
proper shade and leaves are raked in autumn. The leaves are stored
under a tarp, shredded (Garden in the Woods uses a chopper, but
home gardeners could enlist their lawn mowers) and reapplied as
mulch after a hard freeze.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But if wildflowers aren't self-sustaining, if they don't promise
more hours in the hammock, why are they so popular now? After all,
the society reports that its membership has increased 34 percent in
five years, 14 percent since October 1997 alone.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Brumback, the garden's director of conservation, said he
thinks that in addition to being charmed by wildflowers' innate
beauty, people are trying to make a difference, preserving what is
slipping away: A third of North America's flora is endangered, and
they are eager to help. Adopting a nursery-propagated lady-slipper
won't prevent the species, which is endangered, from disappearing,
but it can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the society is concerned that
well-intentioned people might simply go into the woods and dig
plants to take home. Although Brumback conceded that commercial
collecting was a far bigger threat to wildflower populations than
individual digging, he was quick to point out, ``There's no
difference between one person digging 1,000 lady-slippers and 1,000
people each digging only one lady-slipper.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why Garden in the Woods recently began
propagating and selling wildflowers. It now lists 343 plants.
Judging from the phlox-laden red wagons being pulled through the
parking lot, many people are now taking their weekend woods
experience home.
</P>
<P>
   BEAT THE SEEDS: Pick beans, cucumbers and squash before they get
tough as seeds ripen. Herbs are most flavorful harvested just as
flowers begin to develop. For the sake of next year's crop, treat
asparagus as you would tulips: Don't cut ferny foliage until stems
have turned brown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
