   &UR; NEWS AND FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RELIGION-NYT (Washington) _ Legislation to require the
U.S. government to punish foreign countries that permit or endorse
religious persecution was put off indefinitely Thursday by a Senate
committee because Republicans were deeply divided over the issue.
The measure, which pits social conservatives like the Christian
Coalition against business interests like the Chamber of Commerce
and the major farm organizations, is strongly opposed by the
administration. By David E. Rosenbaum. Moved 7-23.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-BISHOPS-NYT (Rome) _ Seeking to curb the independence of
bishops, Pope John Paul II issued an apostolic letter Thursday that
tightens the Vatican's control over 108 bishops' conferences around
the world. Under the new rules, it would be almost impossible for
the National Conference of Catholic Bishops in the United States to
issue major, binding statements on topics like nuclear weapons,
homosexuality or the status of women, that diverged from the
Vatican view. By Alessandra Stanley. Moved 7-23.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CULTUREWAR-NYT (Jerusalem) _ A look at the dispute
between religious and secular Jews, which has steadily intensified
in fury and emotion. It is common now to hear references to
Kulturkampf, a culture war in which the secular ``Tel Aviv'' and
the religious ``Jerusalem'' are battling for the very soul of
Israel. By Serge Schmemann. Moved 7-20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTS-UNITARIANS-BOS (Undated) _ The Boy Scouts of America has
ordered the Unitarian Universalist Association, a liberal
denomination with long roots in New England, to stop giving out
religious awards to scouts who are Unitarians because the church
promotes gay rights. By Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 7-20.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-BOOKS-COX (Dallas) _ Baby boomers looking for the
meaning of life, Generation Xers wanting to avoid the mistakes of
their parents, business professionals seeking new leadership and a
general population wondering about the millennium have one thing in
common. They are buying millions of Christian books. Book sales are
estimated by industry analysts to account for $1.2 billion _ and
rapidly rising _ of the Christian retail market. By Kim Sue Lia
Perkes. Moved 7-21.
</P>
<P>
   NH-BISHOP-BOS (Manchester, N.H.) _ Bishop John B. McCormack, a
clergyman with deep Boston roots, has been appointed by Pope John
Paul II to be the ninth bishop of the diocese of Manchester. By
Lois R. Shea . Moved 7-21.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-RELIGIONS-TEX (Undated) _ Article on series on world
religions focuses on the Church of Scientology: its beliefs,
history, controversies, etc. Moved 7-22.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Caring in Vietnam inspires a
journey to priesthood: profile of the Rev. Tinh Van Nguyen, a
Catholic priest in Boston's Vietnamese community. By Diego
Ribadeneira. Moved 7-22.
</P>
