202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- HMO. Connecticut lawmakers on HMO reform votes
today. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- FEC. Polk County's two congressmen are going in
opposite directions in campaign fund-raising. Williams
</P>
<P>
   -- COLUMN. Weekly column with U.S. Reps. Dan Miller,
R-Bradenton, and Porter Goss, R-Sanibel. Williams
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- ARMYSEC. Conventional wisdom has it that secretaries
of the major military service branches should have first-hand
knowledge either of the military or of politics. In Louis Caldera,
sworn in as the 17th secretary of the Army earlier this month,
President Clinton has both. (for Sunday/Monday) Williams
</P>
<P>
   -- PARCA. The House is expected to pass a Republican
managed-care reform bill this afternoon similar to provisions first
proposed by U.S. Rep. Charlie Norwood. (Working) Williams
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN. VANDERJAGT -- Five years after a shocking primary loss
to Rep. Peter Hoekstra, Guy Vander Jagt still sits on his leather
congressional chair, and uses the same wooden congressional desk he
sat behind for more than 27 years representing Holland in the
nation's capitol. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- DEWINE-DRUGS. A bill introduced by Sen. Mike DeWine
would provide an additional $2.6 billion in interdiction funds to
stop drugs from entering the U.S., and today part of it passed. The
DeWine amendment to the transportation bill provides about $37.5
million for new and restored boats, planes and technology to use in
drug interdiction. Barton
</P>
<P>
   -- EUCLID. The Senate Transportation Appropriations bill passed
today. It includes $4 million for the Euclid corridor improvement
project in the Cleveland area. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- CAMPAIGN-NEY. Rep. Bob Ney, R-St. Clairsville, is maintaining
his lead over challenger Robert Burch for the 18th District seat in
the 1998 election campaign. Egbert
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA -- FRITZ. U.S. Sen. Ernest ``Fritz'' Hollings,
D-S.C., lashed out today against House Republican-backed tax-cut
proposals, which he said would jeopardize the future of Social
Security. Preston
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- GREEN. V.I. Delegate to Congress Donna
Christian-Green argued in vain Friday for House passage of the
Democratic version of managed-care reform legislation (for insert
into wire copy) Williams
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- PETRI PROFILE. Rep. Thomas Petri won his first
election to Congress against the state's future governor, Tommy
Thompson. Although he's been criticized for spending too little
time in the district and not doing enough for the state party, his
district has returned him to office with 70+ percent of the vote.
(working). Marlin.
</P>
