<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SHOOTING (Washington) _ A gunman opens fire at the U.S.
Capitol, at least two police officers and at least one civilian. By
BENNETT ROTH and JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ President Clinton's private
attorneys and special prosecutor Kenneth Starr are trying to reach
agreement on securing Clinton's testimony in the Monica Lewinsky
matter, White House spokesman Michael McCurry says. By JOHN C.
HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-HOUSE (Washington) _ The House approves, 216-210, a
Republican plan to protect patient rights under managed care.
Earlier, the representatives defeated a rival Democratic plan by
five votes. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CONVENTION (New York) _ The head of the GOP committee
searching for a 2000 convention site tells the Republican National
Committee meeting that there is no clear front-runner. Eight cities
are competing for the coveted convention _ Charlotte, Chicago,
Indianapolis, Minneapolis, New Orleans, New York, Philadelphia and
San Antonio. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   CADET-TRIAL (New Braunfels, Texas) _ Jurors convict former Air
Force cadet David Graham of capital murder trial in the slaying of
a 16-year-old girl. His former fiancee received a life sentence in
a separate trial. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT (Austin, Texas) _ Texas officials say federal
Judge David Fulson will sign the $15.3 billion settlement between
the tobacco industry and Texas, clearing the way for the state to
recoup money it has spend on smoking-related illnesses. By LAURA
TOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-HEAT (Houston) _ So you think it's hot in Houston? Quit
your whining. Believe it or not, we live in a veritable tropical
paradise, compared to the hellish summer climes in other hot spots
in Texas and elsewhere. By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HITLER-PLOTS (Paris) _ The newly disclosed fact that secret
British intelligence plans to assassinate Adolf Hitler during World
War II never came off is probably good news for the rest of the
world. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-CART (Brooklyn, Mich.) _ Italian Alex Zanardi is going for
his record-setting fifth consecutive victory on the CART circuit in
this weekend's U.S. 500 auto race. At the rate he is going, Zanardi
may have wrapped up the CART points championship before the circuit
gets to Houston in October. He also has his sights set on Formula
One starting next year. By TERRY BLOUNT.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (San Diego) _ After overcoming a six-run deficit to
win in extra innings Thursday night in Los Angeles, the Houston
Astros move down the coast and open a three-game series against the
NL West-leading San Diego Padres. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-PREVIEW (San Diego) _ This weekend's series between the
Houston Astros and San Diego Padres could well serve as a preview
of the playoffs this fall, as these two division leaders are on
course to meet in the first round if things stay as they are now.
By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
