<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CLINTON-HAMPTONS-$     07-24 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-HAMPTONS-$ADV26-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCK! HERE COMES THE CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 26)  
(lh) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clintons are coming! The Clintons are coming! For weeks that
has been the cry raised on the South Fork of New York's Long
Island, and now that plans for the visit next weekend by the
president and the first lady have come into focus, the anticipation
has boiled over, with many residents and vacationers clamoring for
invitations _ and just as many planning to grab the kids, close the
blinds and batten down the hatches.
</P>
<P>
   It's been three decades since a U.S. president paid a visit to
the Hamptons. In 1968, president-elect Richard Nixon slipped in
along Route 27 and checked quietly into Gurney's Inn in Montauk for
a weekend. When he left, stopping at an ice cream parlor on Route
27 and ordering a pineapple sundae, Nixon and his sundae made the
front page of The East Hampton Star.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that when Bill Clinton hits town five days
from Sunday for a three-day visit, Friday to Sunday, the sundaes
will be at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the hedge clippers, the martini shakers and the
blow-dryers. ``The entire community is thoroughly engaged in
anticipating the president's visit,'' said Judith Hope, the
chairwoman of the New York state Democratic Committee and a
part-time resident of East Hampton. ``It's not just myself having
my hair done, but the waitresses at the catering companies having
their hair done, making reservations weeks in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday evening, actors Alec Baldwin and Kim Basinger are
playing host to a political fund-raiser at their Amagansett estate
for 1,000 guests, who will donate up to $5,000 each. On Friday
night, there's an intimate dinner for 60 _ the price of admission
is $25,000 a couple _ at the investment banker Bruce Wasserstein's
house in East Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumors of a golfing trip to the Atlantic Golf Club on
Saturday (gardeners are pruning, seeding and trimming). And from 4
to 6 p.m. on Saturday afternoon, Dr. Christopher Barley, an
internist, and Jonathan Sheffer, the artistic director of the Eos
Orchestra, will be the hosts of a small gathering at their home in
East Hampton to benefit the Democratic National Committee's Finance
Council. Barley expects the president to attend, and he confirmed
that the Secret Service would be shutting down neighborhood roads.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about area-wide gridlock are what have caused most of
the advance fretting. Sam Schwartz, the former deputy commissioner
of the New York City Transportation Department, who now writes the
Gridlock Sam column for The New York Daily News, predicts that the
drive out on Friday night could last as long as 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president's going out to the Hamptons, well, that's
about as peak as you get,'' Schwartz said. ``But it is also the
change-over weekend for the month _ new renters going in for the
month, old renters going out. And it's a Friday night. So you
basically have a triple whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Glen Stonemetz of East Hampton Village thinks the
10-hour figure must be wrong. ``From what I understand, in terms of
the protocols the Secret Service uses to move the president
around,'' Stonemetz said, ``I'd make that 12 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of impending doom for many Hamptonites has led to
plans to hunker down in houses and not leave the premises. Dini von
Mueffling, a writer who summers in a house on Town Line Road, which
straddles the towns of East Hampton and Southampton, said she would
stock up on essentials, then check the tires on her bike and settle
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing to do is go to King Cullen on Wednesday, hit
the farm stands on Thursday and then not move for the rest of the
weekend,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Canfield, a Manhattan art dealer who spends most summer
weekends in East Hampton, said he planned to stay in New York City.
``On the other hand, how can you add any more to what it is
already?'' he said of the Hamptons traffic. ``It's already a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The small coterie of vacationers who commute from Washington to
the Hamptons each weekend don't quite understand the fuss. ``We're
used to getting stuck in the motorcade, so it's kind of old hat for
us,'' said Mark Ein, a venture capitalist, who lives in Washington
and shares a house with friends in Bridgehampton.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All the elements involved in planning a presidential getaway _
from the sublime to the ridiculous _ are full steam ahead. On
Monday and Tuesday, the Secret Service will meet with the East
Hampton Village police (22 officers) and the town police (60
officers) to get acquainted with the neighborhood and plan their
bomb sweeps. The hairdressers at the Echo Salon in East Hampton are
solidly booked for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At Dreesen's Excelsior Market on Newtown Lane in East Hampton,
Rudy DeSanti will be awake at 6 a.m. on Saturday to prepare the
dough for the 800 Dreesen's Famous Donuts he is donating to the
fund-raiser at the Baldwin-Basinger estate. And all across the
island, waiters and waitresses are trying to finagle a presidential
catering spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there's been some fighting,'' said Ariele Fierman, a
server at the Bridgehampton Cafe, who had to submit her Social
Security number, date of birth, sex and race, along with a
statement that she has no criminal record, to the Secret Service
about two weeks ago. ``It caused a lot of tension in the kitchen,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Much to her delight, Ms. Fierman will be working the
Baldwin-Basinger party, where the levels of access among the
several hundred guests will vary widely. For $5,000, invitees get
to venture inside the house. For $1,000, partygoers get to stand
under a tent next to the house, and the president will work a rope
line, shaking hands. And for $250, the remaining attendees get to
stand a few hundred yards from the house and snarf as many
cocktails and Dreesen's doughnuts as they can manage. (The entire
weekend is expected to net the Democrats $1 million.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hundred and fifty bucks to stand 500 yards from a
motorcade?'' said Glenn Horowitz, a rare book dealer, who has a
shop on Newtown Lane and is bravely giving a party for the novelist
Dani Shapiro that same evening. ``It's potentially one of the great
social shakedowns of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   For those in charge of ensuring that all runs smoothly, there is
the tricky problem of the Hamptons temperament. Anyone who has ever
spent time waiting for a Sunday newspaper at the General Store in
Sagaponack, or watched a famous divorce lawyer rant at a helpless
clerk under a ``Sold Out'' sign at the United Artists East Hampton
Cinema, has seen it. The people who have weekend homes in the
Hamptons _ the land of the $5 million summer cottage and the $10
million ego _ are not exactly used to being bossed around. Even the
United States Secret Service has taken notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you have to be able to tell someone no in a polite
way,'' said Chip Smith, the Secret Service special agent in charge
of the president's visit. ``Maybe in a way that they don't even
know you're saying no. In a polite way.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the possible conflicts _ gridlock traffic, doughnut
overdoses, Secret Service squabbles, oversize egos _ Ms. Hope, the
state Democratic Committee chairwoman, is naturally, delighted that
East Hampton is playing host for the President.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fierman, the waitress who will be serving at the
Baldwin-Basinger party, is also eagerly awaiting the weekend and
Saturday night's party. But for a different reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm keeping my eyes out for a Baldwin brother,'' she said, her
voice brimming with hope. ``But I guess I'll take a Secret Service
man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
