<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T SWEAT IT: THINGS COULD BE WORSE IN HOUSTON _ AND IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ So you think it's hot?
</P>
<P>
   Quit your whining. Believe it or not, we live in a veritable
tropical paradise compared to the hellish summer climes found in
other hot spots around the state and globe.
</P>
<P>
   You only have to go as far as Dallas _ which has endured nearly
three straight weeks of triple-digit heat _ to find folks sizzling
under higher temperatures. Yes, this is an off-the-charts heat wave
in Texas, the steamiest since 1980. But Dallas always gets hotter
than Houston on average in July. The normal high for Dallas during
this month is 96.5 _ almost four degrees above Houston's
goose-pimply 92.7.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a punishing summer. Nationwide, deaths from the heat
stand at 133, including 87 in Texas (four in Houston.) Now it's
even getting hot up North, where once-chic New Yorkers now sweat
copiously. Meanwhile, we currently bask in the brisk high 90s.
</P>
<P>
   We have geography to thank for our comparatively lower
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're near the Gulf (of Mexico), and so that keeps us a bit
cooler,'' said Jill Hasling, director of the Weather Research
Center in Houston. ``We get that nice sea breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   When we recently neared our July record of 104, weary citizens
of Abilene simmered at 107 and unfortunate souls in Arlington
toasted at 108. They were downing plenty of mineral water in
Mineral Wells (107), Long View (105), Midland (109), Fort Stockton
(108) and San Angelo (107). We were even cooler than the ultra-cool
denizens of Austin (106) and the stiff-lipped Aggies at College
Station (105.) Pueblo and Grand Junction, Colo., both recently
reported record highs of 104.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling chilly yet?
</P>
<P>
   In general, it gets hotter in north Texas than in the balmy
regions of Southeast Texas because of our close proximity to the
coast, said Paul Lewis, a meteorologist with the National Weather
Service in League City. This also makes us wetter, which increases
an unfortunate thing called the heat index.
</P>
<P>
   ``A high heat index makes it feel hotter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What happens is the humid coastal breeze, while cooling things
down, makes it harder for the moisture-laden air to absorb sweat as
effectively as dryer climes. So while we may boast cooler temps, we
feel more miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, consider this: In recent days, Houston has been
considerably cooler than a slate of forecasts for Phoenix, Palm
Springs, Calif., and Carlsbad, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   And on the same day we hovered just three measly degrees above
100:
</P>
<P>
   _ The thermometer hit 107 in Roswell, N.M., too hot for even the
most intrepid space aliens to land on the scorched desert Earth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Folks were feeling prickly in Organ Pipe Cactus, N.M., where
it zoomed to 112.
</P>
<P>
   _ It was Hades incarnate in Needles, Calif., which became the
absolutely hottest place in the nation when it hit 114.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the thermometer reached 122 degrees in Lake Havasu, a
tourist town smack-dab in the middle of the Arizona desert, making
it the hottest place in the nation so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only hell is hotter,'' said Candi Isaacs of the Lake Havasu
Chamber of Commerce. Even so, Lake Havasu hasn't broken its own
record, reached in June 1996, when the mercury hit 128 degrees. But
it's plenty warm for Isaacs, who said that the town's population of
mainly senior citizens and tourists combat the heat by staying
indoors, like people do in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go from air-conditioned car to air-conditioned home to
air-conditioned business. If we're not there, we're in the lake.
Literally,'' she said, referring to the 45-mile-wide Lake Havasu,
spanned by the original London Bridge. The historic bridge was
dismantled and reassembled there in 1970 by a chain-saw-company
entrepreneur. You can catch a breeze standing on it, said Isaacs.
</P>
<P>
   But Lake Havasu's temperatures are positively Arctic compared to
steam boilers like the appropriately named Death Valley, Calif.,
where the highest degree ever was reached (so far) on June 10,
1913, when the mercury reached 134. Recent forecasts have Death
Valley nearing 127.
</P>
<P>
   And you said you were hot?
</P>
<P>
   When temperatures get this high, said Hasling, you can hardly do
anything. It hurts to move. It hurts to think. You can't even fly
planes to escape the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to watch things like gasoline tanks,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other places around the world are doing their own tango with
high temps. Try toughing it out in a barbecue pit like Fort
Flatters, Algeria, located just 28 degrees above the equator, where
the average high in July is a blistering 110 degrees. The record is
124.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, temperatures have climbed to 120 degrees in San Luis,
Mexico. And don't even consider tripping over to Adrar, Algeria,
where the average in July is a steamy 115. Ditto places like Libya,
Mali and Argentina, all of which get way hotter than Houston (and
in Argentina, it gets hot in January.) It's the same story for
Baghdad (121 is the July record) and Iran (127.)
</P>
<P>
   Desert areas, explained Hasling, tend to get extremely hot
because of the lack of cooling rains and heat-deflecting clouds.
They also get lots of high-pressure areas _ that's
meteorology-speak for clear weather. The opposite of storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just the bearing down of the heat and the sun,'' she
said. ``It just radiates.''
</P>
<P>
   We should thank our stars, too, for Houston's comparative
flatness. Sure, we don't enjoy picturesque vistas like those found
in New Mexico and other deserty places, but we avoid the dreaded
``sinking air'' syndrome, another cause of high heat, said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air cools as it goes up, but then it rises over the mountains,
loses its moisture and warms up,'' he said. ``Voila! Instant
desert. Just add water.''
</P>
<P>
   So while Houston is hot, it isn't the hottest, not by a long
shot. And don't go cooking up any scary scenarios like global
warming to explain why we're sweltering so. Sometimes it's just,
well, hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most meteorologists you meet don't tie global warming into
(the current heat),'' said Hasling. ``Right now, we're not as hot
as we were in the 1980s. Actually, global warming could produce
more clouds, which could actually make us cooler.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Texas is in the midst of an awesome heat wave
breaking records set more than a century ago. Last month alone, 70
daily temperature records were bested in 17 Texas cities, according
to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   If things get too bad, just close your eyes and imagine slipping
into a parka in Truckee, Calif., or Mountain Home, Idaho, where
residents recently shivered their way to 33 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   And just wait until winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
