r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-24 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SENATOR, THE ATHLETE, THE ASTRONAUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   FRED THOMPSON: The lawyer-turned-movie actor-turned-U.S. senator
says he might run for president in 2000, which raises a question:
Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is the Tennessee Republican whose Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee conducted those coma-inducing hearings last year
in search of campaign finance violations by President Clinton and
his money-raisers. The hearings failed to produce any significant
evidence of Clintonian lawbreaking and also failed to launch the
Thompson-for-President bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson hopes to generate interest in his candidacy by talking
up issues such as nuclear proliferation. Fat chance. He'd have
better luck talking up his roles in movies such as ``In the Line of
Fire'' and ``Die Hard 2.''
</P>
<P>
   JANET RENO: The U.S. attorney general hasn't made any movies
lately _ although a Reno look-alike was featured on television's
``Ally McBeal.'' What Reno has in common with Thompson is the
albatross known as campaign finance. The attorney general has
bravely resisted demands that she seek an independent counsel to
investigate Clinton's money-raising tactics _ does this country
really need one more independent counsel? _ but a newly leaked
``confidential'' report from a Justice Department underling has put
the special-prosecutor gun to Reno's head once again.
</P>
<P>
   Reno-watchers say she has no plans to back down. I say good for
her. If Thompson couldn't crack Clinton's campaign-finance
stonewalling, and if Ken Starr is having all this trouble proving
that the president dallied with an intern, why spend a fortune on
another futile investigation?
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL JORDAN: His Airness is still threatening to retire from
basketball, and that would be a tragedy for fans who hang on
Michael's every move. To untold numbers of kids and grownups,
Jordan IS basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I think he ought to hang up his sneakers. Don't
misunderstand. I'm no less thrilled than any other fan by Jordan's
matchless spirit of competitiveness and mind-boggling feats of
athleticism. He's in a class by himself, a transcending presence
who long ago rendered moot any debate about the identify of
basketball's best-ever player. There is Michael Jordan, and then
there are all the others.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan has ruled the game long enough. It's time to let the
other guys take their shots at fame and fortune. Besides, Jordan is
still at the top of his game _ or near it _ but he won't be much
longer. Athletes almost never have enough sense _ pride? _ to bow
out before erosion of their skills begins to tarnish their legacy.
Jordan ought to be the one who does.
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT YOUNG: That's an impressive list of movies that Young
racked up over the decades, but it was television that made him an
American icon. Most TV actors are lucky to star in one show that is
remembered by viewers as an all-time favorite; Young starred in
two. He was TV's greatest dad on ``Father Knows Best'' and TV's
greatest doctor on ``Marcus Welby, M.D.''
</P>
<P>
   Young died the other day at 91, leaving his legions of fans with
fond memories of the great guys he played on television in the
'50s, '60s and '70s: a father who never lost patience with his
children and always commanded the respect of his family, and a
doctor whose main concern was the health and well-being of his
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Were those the good old days or what?
</P>
<P>
   ALAN SHEPARD: Kids growing up in 1950s America had fictional
space heroes to admire: ``Tom Corbett, Space Cadet,'' ``Captain
Video and His Video Rangers,'' Buzz Corey of ``Space Patrol.'' But
the real deal seemed a distant dream _ until Alan Shepard burst
onto the scene.
</P>
<P>
   When Shepard became the first American to fly in space in 1961,
he delivered the futuristic fantasies that0TZ5
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
