</P>
<P>
   Were those the good old days or what?
</P>
<P>
   ALAN SHEPARD: Kids growing up in 1950s America had fictional
space heroes to admire: ``Tom Corbett, Space Cadet,'' ``Captain
Video and His Video Rangers,'' Buzz Corey of ``Space Patrol.'' But
the real deal seemed a distant dream _ until Alan Shepard burst
onto the scene.
</P>
<P>
   When Shepard became the first American to fly in space in 1961,
he delivered the futuristic fantasies that Tom Corbett and the rest
had promised. And he was exactly what a hero was supposed to be:
forthright, resolute, courageous. He was 74 when he died, but in
our mind's eye he will always be 37, making dreams come true in a
Mercury space capsule.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
