<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, July 25. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ Keizo Obuchi, Japan's congenial but
colorless foreign minister, was elected as president of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and thereby in line to become prime
minister, dashing the hopes of those who saw a glimmer of political
reform in the selection process. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-ASSESS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Hunger has been a weapon of war
since Homer's time, but perhaps nowhere have starvation and food
supplies been so entwined with military tactics as in Sudan's
interminable civil war. By James C. McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP (Washington) _ At least one gunman entered
the Capitol Building and fired shots that were heard in the
hallway. Three people, one civilian and two cops, hurt and en route
to the hospital. The gunman may have been apprehended in Tom
DeLay's office. (With sidebars)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ House votes on managed
care/consumer protection bill, both the Democratic alternative and
Republican proposal. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-COLLAPSE-RDP (New York) _ New details on the scaffolding
collapse, including that an investigator who has been at the site
describes how unstable the structure is _ that the scaffolding is
being held up by the elevator tower, instead of the other way
around. Details from 4:15 p.m. ET news conference. (Sidebars as
needed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TOUR-DE-FRANCE (Le Cap D'Agde, France) _ The Tour de France, the
world's greatest bicycle race, nearly unraveled Friday in the wake
of a widening drug scandal that produced a two-hour strike by
riders, confessions of illegal drug use by as many as five members
of the suspended Festina team and the discovery of drug
paraphernalia in the hotel of the Dutch TVM team. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
