<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE STORY ON ELEVATORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My friend Andrew has an enormous fear of elevators. Is there
an official term for that? Also, how many elevator deaths occur
yearly?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.H., Corpus Christi, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: There doesn't appear to be a phobia named specifically for
elevator fear, though claustrophobia (enclosed spaces), acrophobia
(heights) and mechanophobia (machines) all come close.
</P>
<P>
   A recent ``20/20'' report indicated that 6,500 people were
hospitalized for elevator-related injuries last year, usually from
being struck by doors or falling when exiting an unlevel elevator.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 100 fatalities since 1991, according to
``20/20.'' Most occur when someone tries to exit a stalled elevator
or walks into an open elevator shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a Postal Savings System $1 certificate purchased on
July 12, 1932. How much is it worth?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.W., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Those certificates, which were sold from 1910 until 1967 for
amounts from $1 to $2,500, paid 2 percent annual interest. A $1
certificate purchased in 1932 would be worth $3.69 today.
</P>
<P>
   However, a 1984 law prevented any Postal Savings claims from
being filed after July 13, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1971, $60 million in savings deposits certificates was
unclaimed, according to Valerie Welsch of the U.S. Post Office Fort
Worth district.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money was divided among the states, with a small
amount withheld for any remaining claims.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Richard Bach, the author of ``Jonathan
Livingston Seagull?''
</P>
<P>
   _ L.R., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Bach in care of William Morrow &AMP; Company, Royalties
Dept., 1350 Avenue of the Americas, New York, N.Y. 10019.
</P>
<P>
   Bach, who turned 62 on June 23, lives in Seattle with wife
Leslie Parrish-Bach. ``Seagull'' has sold more than 30 million
copies since being published in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
