<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSAT HAS FEATURES OF PRICIER COUSIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an automaker owns both a mass-market brand and an upscale
name plate _ such as Toyota and Lexus, Nissan and Infiniti,
Volkswagen and Audi _ people who buy the less-expensive brand often
get many of the advantages of the more-expensive one without paying
the extra bucks.
</P>
<P>
   What the buyer lacks, of course, is the snob appeal of the
more-expensive brand. But if value for money is what you're looking
for, it makes more sense to choose a fully loaded 1998 Volkswagen
Passat GLX, for instance, than the comparable but pricier Audi A4.
</P>
<P>
   The Passat, VW's biggest sedan, is all new for '98, and is based
on the platform of the A4 that was introduced a couple of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The two cars aren't identical; the Passat is actually a bit
larger and roomier inside, qualifying it as a midsize, while the A4
remains a compact. But this newest version of the Passat truly
feels like a premium car. It goes way against the perceptions that
most people have of Volkswagen as a company that builds small,
economical, practical cars.
</P>
<P>
   With a base price of $26,250 that includes leather seats and the
same 190-horsepower, 2.8-liter V-6 engine of the A4, the Passat GLX
is a real bargain compared with some of the competition _
especially the A4, whose comparably equipped price is about $5,000
more.
</P>
<P>
   This Passat is one really fun car to drive, too. Although the
suspension is a bit cushier than the A4's, the new four-link front
suspension arrangement is a great improvement over that of the
previous Passat. The cushiness makes for a smoother ride but cuts
some of the sporty firmness out of the road-handling
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Passat feels expensive and a lot sportier than one
would expect from even the most expensive VW. The vehicle holds
tightly to the road in curves, and the acceleration is surprisingly
good. Power is comparable to that of V-6 Toyota Camry and its twin,
the Lexus ES 300, but handling is definitely more crisp on the
Volkwagen.
</P>
<P>
   The GLX comes with a four-speed automatic transmission and
front-wheel drive, but an all-wheel-drive version is available.
</P>
<P>
   To get a Passat with a five-speed manual transmission, you would
have to back up a bit and choose the less-expensive GLS model (base
price $20,750), which comes with VW's impressive 1.8-liter
turbocharged four-cylinder engine, rated at 150 horsepower. To
this, add the leather ($950) and other standard amenities of the
GLX, such as the power glass moon roof ($1,000) and get a vehicle
comparable to the GLX but with a manual gearbox.
</P>
<P>
   You can add the nifty five-speed Tiptronic automatic
transmission to the GLX for $1,075, an option that showed up on our
test car. This transmission allows you to shift manually, although
without the bother of a clutch. It's similar to the Tiptronic
offered in the Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic traction control and the excellent Bosch four-wheel
antilock braking system are standard. The brakes are discs all
around _ vented in front and solid in the rear. Steering is
power-assisted rack-and-pinion.
</P>
<P>
   The new Passat is one of the roomiest and most comfortable
midsize sedans on the market. Three adults can fit easily into the
back seat, and the two front bucket seats are living-room-lounger
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Trunk space is unusually generous at 15 cubic feet, thanks to
the squaring of the rear end. The split-folding rear seat allows
cargo to be extended into the back seat, great for skis or other
long or bulky items.
</P>
<P>
   All Passats come with alarm system, AM/FM/cassette stereo,
central door locking with remote control, center console, cruise
control, dual heated power mirrors, dual illuminated visor vanity
mirrors, fog lights, plenty of interior lights (including one in
the trunk), manual air-conditioning, power windows with one-touch
up and down for both front windows, rear defroster, tilt and
telescopic steering wheel, trip computer, variable intermittent
wipers and wheel covers.
</P>
<P>
   GLS models with the V-6 engine (a $2,440 upgrade) get cloth and
wood door-trim panels.
</P>
<P>
   Our top-of-the-line GLX got even more goodies: leather and wood
door trim, the all-weather package (heated front seats and
windshield-washer nozzles), automatic climate control, eight-way
power driver's seat with memory, leather-wrapped steering wheel,
and the power moon roof.
</P>
<P>
   Total price for our test car was $27,825, including $500
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Although EPA fuel-economy ratings were not provided, expect the
GLX's V-6 to get mileage comparable to the A4's 17 miles per gallon
in the city and 27 on the highway. The fuel tank holds 18.5
gallons, enough for a long ride between fill-ups.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1998 Volkswagen Passat GLX sedan
</P>
<P>
   The Package: Midsize, four-door, five-passenger, V-6 powered,
front-drive sedan, an all-new model for 1998 based on the Audi A4.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Excellent styling, performance, road handling and
construction; a great value that looks and feels a lot more
expensive than it is; roomy and comfortable for five adults; large
trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: No manual transmission available for sportier
performance from the V-6 engine.
</P>
<P>
   Major competitors: Toyota Camry XLE V-6, Honda Accord EX V-6,
Nissan Maxima GLE, Mazda 626 ES V-6, Oldsmobile Intrigue GL,
Mercedes-Benz C-class, Volvo S70, BMW 323, Saab 900, Buick Regal
GS, Infiniti I30, Cadillac Catera.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel economy: 17 miles per gallon city, 27 highway.
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $26,250 plus $500 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $37,825, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   On The Road rating: A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
