<HEADER>
A1651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHOLOGIES-980(2TAKE     07-24 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHOLOGIES-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MULTI IN CULTURAL STILL LEAVES ALSO-RANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Ideas) 
(lb) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What inevitably prompts the most discussion about an anthology
isn't what's put in but what's left out.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews of ``The Dictionary of Global Culture'' (Alfred A.
Knopf, 1997), for example, noted the included and the excluded.
Schubert in, Schumann out; Homer in, Horace out; Franklin Roosevelt
in, Ronald Reagan out; Joe Louis in, Arthur Ashe out.
</P>
<P>
   It's an engaging parlor game, but there are weighty questions
embedded in list-making: How thorough is the research? What are the
intellectual or artistic criteria and are they sound? Who is even
entitled to make such decisions?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer the case that you automatically have the
authority to pronounce these things because you're two Harvard
professors,'' said Kwame Anthony Appiah, who, together with his
Harvard colleague Henry Louis Gates Jr., edited the dictionary.
``We've had the general democratization of culture in which there
is a wider range of people who rightly feel entitled to declare
their views.''
</P>
<P>
   As the editors note in their preface, the twin problems of being
exhaustive and being representative have existed since Diderot
wrote the first modern encyclopedia in the 18th century. The global
dictionary doesn't pretend to be either, Appiah and Gates say, but
instead offers ``an invitation for readers to begin the process of
understanding those cultures that most of us educated in the West
barely know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried in our introduction to be clear that our idea wasn't
to identify the basic minimum knowledge needed to be the global
citizen of something,'' Appiah explained, adding that they still
got complaints like ``Why is Jackie Robinson not in here?''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, on the cover, right under the title, the book
pronounces itself ``the global citizen's guide to culture,
emphasizing the achievement of the non-Western world _ what every
American needs to know as we enter the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without that subtitle, however, Appiah and Gates are
essentially doing what all anthologists do: deciding what does and
what does not belong in a given canon. And increasingly, such an
undertaking involves contentious debates about race, gender,
ethnicity and sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true object of this dictionary is to question deep-rooted
assumptions of European pre-eminence,'' the critic Frank Kermode
said about the global dictionary in The New York Review of Books,
``and let white culture ... take its proper place, diminished but
accorded the measure of respect now thought decent, in a global
account that includes all the others.'' The editors' goal, he adds
``is to establish a new and aggressive point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Weinberger said his anthology of ``American Poetry Since
1950'' (Marsilio, 1993) became enmeshed in vituperative arguments
about who deserves to be included and why they should be.
</P>
<P>
   A critique in the American Poetry Review accused him of holding
degrading views of African-Americans, he said, because he had
selected the work of Amiri Baraka and Langston Hughes, who the
reviewer felt were not representative of African-American writing.
To Weinberger, that such a selection could be labeled racist was
like entering a world of ``Alice in Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly never do another anthology,'' Weinberger
added. ``It's a thankless task.''
</P>
<P>
   David Curzon had a different experience with identity politics,
however. He said he was initially irked by pressures of political
correctness in assembling his two anthologies of poetry based on
biblical texts such as the gospels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it a little irritating to be asked to think about
nonliterary criteria such as the proportion of people of one gender
or ethnic origin,'' he said. ``But it turned out not to be a
problem. I was pushed by some of these requirements to look further
afield than I probably would have, and I think I came up with some
interesting poems which I'm glad are in the anthology.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, identity politics aren't the only politics that can
cause problems. In assembling his ``Columbia Anthology of British
Poetry'' with Carl Woodring a few years ago, James Shapiro said,
``There were Irish distributors who had the rights who did not want
to part with those poems unless we changed the name of the
anthology _ they didn't like the idea of British.'' He said that
``every anthology is a political statement or a series of political
statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because their anthology of world poetry covered so many
ethnic groups, Katharine Washburn and John S. Major did not worry
so much about multicultural considerations. ``We didn't see this as
the United Nations,'' Ms. Washburn said. ``Nevertheless, it turned
out to have an extraordinary range of diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The two editors updated Mark Van Doren's ``Anthology of World
Poetry,'' published in 1928. Their volume, ``World Poetry: An
Anthology of Verse From Antiquity to Our Time,'' published by W.W.
Norton in April, includes more than 1,600 poems spanning a period
of 4,000 years from the era of ancient Sumer to the late 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   The book consists of eight chronological parts, from the Bronze
Age forward, with each section subdivided by language. (Most of the
poems were translated into English for the anthology by other
poets.)
</P>
<P>
   Helen Vendler, probably the most powerful poetry critic in the
United States, attacked this organizing approach in a review in The
New Republic, arguing that Van Doren's method of dividing poems by
language in chronological order was more intelligible.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Washburn defended their attempt to create linkages across
geography and time. ``You have a poem from seventh century B.C.
from Greek, and not far away in the same section you have a Chinese
poem from the Han dynasty,'' Ms. Washburn said, ``This has
unexpected resonances, so that readers could see connective tissue
and could see parallels and echoes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The book weighs in at a hefty 1,338 pages, including the index.
Nevertheless, Ms. Vendler still noted what was left out. ``Would
you represent Tennyson without mentioning `In Memoriam'?'' she
asked in her review. ``If you could print four poems by Keats,
would you leave out all the odes?''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Lopate, the essayist, is preparing an anthology for
perhaps the toughest crowd of all: New Yorkers. He is editing a
collection of writings about New York that is scheduled for
publication by the Library of America in September. ``They're a
more educated audience,'' he said. ``And every New Yorker is an
expert on New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Having decided to start with Washington Irving, Lopate said, he
pushed himself to go up to the present, which he described as the
hardest period to address. ``They're our contemporaries _ sometimes
they're our friends, sometimes they're our enemies _ and we don't
have perspective, we don't know how to judge them,'' he said. ``It
would have been easier to stop at the '60s, but it seemed to me
that would have been cowardly.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet what many people may not realize is that often a particular
selection may have absolutely nothing to do with taste, scholarship
or politics but simply be a matter of space. The more pages there
are, the more entries can be included.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get enough pages, you can circumvent this whole
issue of the canon,'' Lopate said. ``You can have as many
multicultural authors and you can have as many dead white males as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At other times, copyright might be the problem. In many cases,
editors say, the cost of the permissions is prohibitive, so
material is ultimately left out because it was too expensive to
acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of the new range of questions, professors say
they try now to present anthologies as just one of many sources,
rather than offering them as an authoritative selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthologies today are taught self-consciously on the part of a
teacher who wants to call attention to the fact that the book
represents a particular version of literary history and has its
organizing principles and assumptions and is not the only version
of things that might be available,'' said Langdon Hammer, an
associate professor of English at Yale University who is also the
director of undergraduate studies in English.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, anthologists say they have to expect debate.
``I finally had to be governed by my own love and my own passion
for this or that,'' Lopate said. ``I think being an anthologist is
an invitation to guilt and defensiveness. In a way you're convicted
in advance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
