<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIL FINN: BROODING ABOUT AN UNCERTAIN WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Misery loves melody. Or so it seemed when the
songwriters Neil Finn, from New Zealand, and Ebba Forsberg, from
Sweden, shared a double bill on Wednesday night at Irving Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Finn's big hits, notably ``Don't Dream It's Over'' by Crowded
House, have been declarations of enduring love, filled with
promises that romance can transcend the mundane. But he also has a
less reassuring side, as he broods over private anxieties and past
sins.
</P>
<P>
   In a set that stretched more than two hours, there was a
distinct gap between Finn's older songs and the dozen new ones he
played from his current album, ``Try Whistling This'' (Work
Group/Sony). The older songs were steeped in 1960s rock like the
Beatles and the Byrds, wrapping poetic imagery around his vows,
while the newer ones are more experimental and oblique.
</P>
<P>
   Finn is one of those songwriters who, following an example set
by the Beatles, like to see how much unlikely material they can
slip into what sounds like a pop tune.
</P>
<P>
   His new songs generally have at least three different sections,
and they might use a lugubrious lounge-piano undertow, sampled and
looped percussion, distorted voices or oddly shaped chromatic
melodies (including the one that makes the song ``Try Whistling
This'' a challenge) alongside folk-rock fingerpicking and pop
nonsense syllables.
</P>
<P>
   The new songs touch on love, but only as one shifting element in
an uncertain world. In ``Sinner,'' Finn contemplates a child he
left behind, as ``conscience plays upon me now''; in ``Loose
Tongue,'' set to a pushy blues guitar riff, he berates himself for
talking too much.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Truth,'' he confesses, ``They say that I am worthy of their
love and attention, but they still don't know the truth,'' while in
``Addicted,'' he wakes up after nodding out, telling someone, ``You
say I was addicted to the drug, but I know when I've had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The songs drift into their troubled reflections, then rise above
them with expansive melodies. At Irving Plaza, an adoring crowd
sang along whenever Finn offered them a chance, letting the tunes
cushion his misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Forsberg suggests Carole King and Sarah McLachlan midway
through therapy, singing midtempo songs centered on steady piano
chords with touches of country in her voice. She was best when she
wallowed in depression _ ``Nobody falls like I do,'' one song
morosely boasted _ and only halfway convincing when she insisted,
``I must forgive myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
