<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNT YA LATER, ALLIGATOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Counting books are a fun way to get your kindergartner ready for
the first day of school.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't care if your child can count to 100 and back by 10s,
she'll still get a big laugh out of Judy Sierra's ``Counting
Crocodiles,'' which starts ``On an island in the middle of the
Sillabobble Sea lived a clever little monkey in a sour lemon tree
...''
</P>
<P>
   Seems our little friend has prepared those lip-curling fruits
every which way he can and, frankly, he's tired of them. When he
spies a banana tree on an island across the sea, it's up to the
monkey and his friends, the fox and snail, to deal with a flotilla
of mathematically challenged crocodiles.
</P>
<P>
   If the story sounds familiar, the author allows that the story
is based on a Pan-Asian folk tale in which a tricky animal
persuades members of a duller species to form a bridge over water
under the guise of counting them.
</P>
<P>
   The rhyming text is a joy, but the real giggles come from Will
Hillenbrand's illustrations. Anybody who hasn't seen a picture of
six crocs with pink mohawks just isn't living right.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Sandy Guerra-Cline
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Counting Crocodiles''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Judy Sierra
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Harcourt Brace &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $15
</P>
<P>
   Ages: 3 to 6
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
