<HEADER>
A1667 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANTS-SOFT-OPEN     07-24 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANTS-SOFT-OPENINGS-ART-$ADV26-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREAD THE WORD: WE'RE NOT OPEN YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 26)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A discreet net curtain shields the Mercer Hotel and
Kitchen from the eyes of curious passers-by. But once the lights
come on, that curtain acts as a scrim, and behind it, a roisterous
performance was in progress last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening Kate Spade and Marie-Anne Oudejans, fashion
designers, were among those swarming the upstairs dining room and
bar. Downstairs in the hangarlike hub of the restaurant, Holly
Solomon, the art dealer, and Brian McNally, the restaurateur, were
among the crowd squeezed shoulder-to-shoulder behind pared-down
refectory tables, sampling bite-size portions of onion tart, black
sea bass with eggplant caviar and chilled berry soup. The next
night, the diners included James Truman of Conde Nast, Gabe Doppelt
of VH1 and Famke Janssen, an actress.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes from the latest hot restaurant to open in SoHo? Not
quite. The Mercer Kitchen is still a work in progress. It is not
scheduled to open its reservation book to the public before
mid-August. But that has not stopped a heat-seeking crowd from
zeroing in on its door at Prince and Mercer Streets, eager to be
among the first to experience a highly anticipated new destination.
They have been invited to preview the food _ or in some cases,
simply to check out the space during a cocktail party for a book or
a movie _ weeks and even months before the official opening.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the process known as a soft opening, a gradual
tease in which taste makers _ clothing designers, Hollywood stars,
foodies, fashion magazine editors _ are invited to new restaurants
that are being promoted like nightclubs. It's a two-way street: the
restaurant owners court the attention of the chattering classes,
and the beau monde are eager to arrive early at a hip new
destination.
</P>
<P>
   A string of soft openings preceded the official inauguration of
such hot spots in lower Manhattan as the Bowery Bar, Bond Street
and Cafeteria, generating enough advance press and hyperbolic word
of mouth to ensure that when the curtain really did go up,
reservations were as hard to come by as courtside seats at a
Knicks-Bulls game.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mercer Kitchen, which is a collaboration between hotel
impresario Andre Balazs and celebrated chef Jean-Georges
Vongerichten, the preopening drumroll began in April.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Anna Wintour, Vogue's editor in chief, used the
restaurant for a book party, held jointly with The New Yorker, for
Michael Roberts, a fashion illustrator and commentator. The kitchen
was barely operational, and Vongerichten, whose other restaurants
include Jean Georges and Vong, had not settled on a menu, but a
glittering crowd descended nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before there was even a morsel of food, there already was a
great buzz about the place,'' said Drew Nieporent, a partner in
Montrachet and the TriBeCa Grill and a professed nonbeliever in
soft openings.
</P>
<P>
   Elle magazine used the Mercer Kitchen for a preopening party for
its new fashion and style editor, Sally Singer, who had returned to
New York after several years in London and who found the
soft-opening concept an amusing new twist to Manhattan night life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could only work in the double-cell-phone, double-decaf
world of New York, where people are so driven by the excitement of
consumption that they have to be at a new place in the first five
minutes,'' Ms. Singer said. ``The only safe way to go to a place
while it still has any hip credibility is to be there before it
exists.''
</P>
<P>
   As Balazs tells it, the object of staging preopening tasting
dinners is not really to generate buzz, but to train the staff and
refine the menu before a restaurant's official debut. Last week,
the fare was still being altered daily, the staff members had
clearly improvised uniforms from anything black that came to hand,
and the air-conditioning system had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to make mistakes, it's better that they happen
in Philadelphia, so that when, finally, you do step into the
limelight, you're putting your best foot forward,'' Balazs said.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt. But the sort of crowds invited to his tastings, like
bees to wild clover, hardly qualify as an out-of-town audience. On
the contrary, they're the ones most likely to spread the word if a
restaurant is found lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Or if it's a going to be a hit. ``It's stupid, but people love
to get to know a place before the general public does, so they can
brag to their friends: `I've been there. The food is fantastic,'''
said Nadine Johnson, Balazs' formidably well-connected publicist,
who helped compile the invitations for the tasting dinners. She is
married to Richard Johnson, the Page Six columnist for The New York
Post, one of the places restaurateurs most love to be mentioned.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Mercer Kitchen would likely draw an enthusiastic crowd even
without the advance buildup, because of the reputation of its chef,
Vongerichten. It is a hybrid among restaurants: partly the city's
next hot scene, partly a food-lovers' destination.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity chefs and restaurateurs can usually count on their own
panache to draw a stylish crowd, without courting high-profile
drop-ins before the opening. People like Daniel Boulud, who plans
to reopen his Restaurant Daniel in January in the former Mayfair
Hotel, and Keith McNally, the owner of Balthazar, ``bring with them
an aura of prior success as they branch out,'' Paul Wilmot, a New
York fashion publicist, said, adding, ``That's part of their
positive luggage, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   But for many others, whose reputations do not speak so loudly,
the soft opening, often engineered with the help of a publicist's
mailing list, is the way to go. It helped establish Bond Street, a
Japanese-inspired restaurant filled, on the first floor, with
aspiring Masters of the Universe and their dates and, on the second
floor, with fashion insiders like Patrick Robinson and Lainey
Keogh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always catered to the fashion world,'' said Jonathan
Morr, a partner. Morr, who also owns Indochine, the long-running
downtown mecca for the hip, knows a thing or two about courting a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But when Ms. Johnson, the publicist, helped to orchestrate a
Donatella Versace post-fashion-show party at the restaurant last
April, before it opened, the name Bond Street became a household
word, at least in the lofts of trend-setting New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party, the telephoning before the event, the post-party
buzz, all recorded in the gossip columns, are part of the drumbeat
that raises a restaurant's glamour quotient,'' Ms. Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago when Tony Fortuna and Charles Palmer opened the
Lenox Room, on Third Avenue near 73rd Street, they agreed to let
Tommy Hilfiger and the Estee Lauder Companies give a party there
the night before its opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``John F. Kennedy Jr. came, and everyone picked up on that,''
said Fortuna, who had previously managed the Monkey Bar. ``My
mother saw the Lenox Room on TV that night, and that made the
business.'' Today his regular crowd, he said, includes Katie
Couric; Mary Boone, the art dealer, and Michael Fuchs of HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Attaining _ and sustaining _ that kind of sizzle requires the
endorsement of not only the gossip columnists and the occasional
television report, but also other taste makers, including fashion
designers, whose influence these days extends well beyond skirt
lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designers tell you how to smell, what linens to sleep on and
which plates to eat off of,'' said Wilmot, who as Vogue's former
public-relations chief helped organize more than his share of
restaurant parties. ``Their presence is almost a ratification of a
restaurant's good taste.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miller girls always make a room,'' Wilmot added, referring
to the three Miller sisters, duty-free heiresses Alexandra Von
Furstenberg, Pia Getty and Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want Oscar and Annette,'' he continued, referring to the
de la Rentas. ``You want Calvin Klein and John Bartlett. And if
you've got them in a room with David Bowie and Iman, and Blaine and
Robert Trump, you win the game, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   But that game is reinvented weekly by a handful of new players,
including a crop of young publicists specializing in night life.
Lizzie Grubman, who by her own account handles publicity for one
new restaurant a month, was the force behind the preopening parties
in June at Cafeteria on Seventh Avenue at 17th Street, a restaurant
owned in part by Victor Alfaro, the fashion designer.
</P>
<P>
   Circling and swanning in Alfaro's packed-to-capacity room were
Veronica Webb and Bridget Hall, Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, Ted Fields of
Interscope Records and a cast of more anonymous, but sleekly turned
out twentysomethings. ``I call them the CIAs _ clubbies in
action,'' Ms. Grubman said. ``They are the 100 opinion makers who
talk up each new place and get the word out in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   But to talk up the action may sometimes be to sow the seeds of
future disappointment. Almost by definition, what is hot this
moment will be cool six months from now. ``I don't believe in the
pressure of a high-profile opening,'' said Steven Hanson, who owns
a string of long-running popular restaurants including Park Avalon
on Park Avenue South, and the Atlantic Grill and Isabella on the
Upper West Side. Hanson has refused to hire publicists to organize
his previews, for fear they might whip up a frenzy that can be
sustained only for a few months at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might get a star-studded evening or two, but where do you
go from there?'' he said. ``It's almost like you're setting
yourself up in the following weeks for a letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson contends that the showy crowds attracted by soft
openings are anathema to certain restaurant critics, who begin
trickling in after the initial fanfare has subsided. ``You don't
want to buzz a place to such an extent that it draws attention from
the fare or turns off the food writer,'' said Ms. Johnson, who
remembers being cautioned by one food critic, ``You can be
ambitious as you like, but if you have too many beautiful people or
your waitresses show too much cleavage, you can forget about
earning that third star.''
</P>
<P>
   Balazs brushes off such reservations like specks of soot from
his natty cream suit. In fact, he used the soft-opening strategy _
heretofore largely the province of restaurateurs _ to generate
interest in the Mercer Hotel, too.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of on-again, off-again construction, the last
of the Mercer's 75 rooms was completed in June. But beginning as
early as last December, it discreetly welcomed such
attention-getting guests as Leonardo DiCaprio, Claire Danes,
Heather Graham and fashion designer Alexander McQueen, their visits
duly reported in the tabloids and the fashion press.
</P>
<P>
   Balazs, who is married to Katie Ford, the chief executive of
Ford Models, also owns the stylish, hacienda-style Chateau Marmont
in Los Angeles. He simply spread the word about his hotel's soft
opening by telephoning friends in the fashion and entertainment
industries. By the time the hotel was fully operational, Vogue was
declaring it ``the place to be right now in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was natural for Balazs to extend the strategy to his
restaurant. A keen student of group psychology, it is his
conviction that you can never attract too many beautiful people _
they are part of what keeps a business percolating.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a restaurant, people's sense of who they are is affected by
who is sitting next to them,'' Balazs said. ``And that is the full
explanation of why a restaurant is perceived as hot or not hot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
