<HEADLINE>
LIFEDANCE/GLORIA MCLEAN: PROMISING, YET DISJOINTED, ELEGANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ingredients were promising for ``Her Father,''
presented by Lifedance/Gloria McLean and Dancers on Thursday night
at the Tenri Gallery in SoHo. Ms. McLean is an intelligent,
imaginative choreographer with long experience in dance. Kazuko
Miyamoto's black-and-white photographs of her elderly nude father
were the inspiration for the dance, providing documentation with a
stark elegance. And Ms. Miyamoto's design of the space and props
and her text, spoken as part of the performance, had a spare
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   But those ingredients never quite came together to form a
greater whole. The small stage space looked cluttered, filled with
seven performers, slide projections and the set elements, which
included a hanging chair and rope sculpture, a gauzy kimono with a
soft-toned black-and-white photograph printed in its back and wall
hangings of stones and twigs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLean's involvement in the subject matter was puzzling. She
seemed to be addressing her own father in her opening comments and
in her interaction with Robert Yahner, a father figure of sorts,
throughout the piece. The connections between the two fathers and
between the diffuse movement and apparent theme were never made
clear.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Her Father,'' set to music by Ushio Torikai,
Karlheinz Stockhausen and Erik Satie, also included Joy McEwen,
Rachel Margolis, Rod Rufo, Beth Simons and Ms. Miyamoto. Rufo stood
out for his quietly intense presence. The lighting was by Haen
Naruo, with sound editing by Tim Hatfield.
</P>
</TEXT>
