<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GORE-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE VOICES CONFIDENCE IN RUSSIAN PREMIER'S ECONOMIC POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Vice President Al Gore ended two days of talks here
Friday by declaring his confidence that Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko will be able to carry out the fiscal reforms needed to
make the Russian government solvent again.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's statements came after two days of get-acquainted meetings
with Kiriyenko, who has replaced former Prime Minister Victor
Chernomyrdin as the senior official on a panel that coordinates the
two governments' work on major U.S.-Russian issues.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with Kiriyenko, Gore said the prime
minister had ``full command'' of the economic issues confronting
Russia ``and a very impressive understanding of economic reform and
what must be done in order to advance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial experts and some Russian officials have said the
government has but three to five months to make major improvements
in its tax system and budget or face another fiscal crisis like the
one that nearly bankrupted the government early this month.
</P>
<P>
   Using political pressure and executive declarations, President
Boris Yeltsin and Kiriyenko managed earlier this month to put in
place most of the laws needed to make financial reforms that have
been demanded by Russia's creditors as the price for continued
investment there. But persuading Russia's stubborn bureaucracy to
carry out the laws is another matter, as is forcing powerful
private interests to obey them.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko, who turns 36 on Sunday, seemed crisp and confident at
Friday's meeting with reporters. He dismissed speculation that
Russia's Communist-led Parliament would block reforms, saying the
Parliament's opposition to some of the more onerous tax laws is
normal, considering that many members face re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not pay too much attention to the inevitable
political emotions,'' he said, ``we'll find common approaches and
agreed solutions together.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And he handily put down a reporter from the frequently critical
Independent newspaper of Moscow, who asked Gore if the United
States had plans to step in should the Yeltsin government ``prove
unable to cope'' with economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Vice President, this is a favorite subject with the
Independent newspaper,'' Kiriyenko said. ``For the past four months
they have been tensely waiting for collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gore said the United States and Russia had arrived
at ``an epochal moment in human history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we make the right choices now, there could be great
trouble in the future,'' he said. ``By contrast, if we do make the
right choices now, the future can be very bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit produced three agreements that had been prepared in
advance for release during the trip. The most important commits the
United States to spend $3.1 million to help Russian scientists in
so-called closed cities _ towns devoted to nuclear weapons research
and production _ start work on nonmilitary projects.
</P>
<P>
   Workers in one of those cities staged a strike this week,
protesting the government's failure to pay them. One goal of the
U.S.-backed programs is to prevent hostile nations from luring
those scientists to work on clandestine nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
   Another agreement would open a new effort to convert plutonium
from dismantled nuclear weapons into fuel for nuclear reactors,
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Gore visited Ukraine, a former Soviet republic
in even more dire financial straits than Russia, to encourage its
leaders to adopt capitalist-style economic reforms. The
International Monetary Fund has demanded such reforms before it
will extend a loan that could help prevent the country from sliding
into bankruptcy next month.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also visited the concrete-encased Chernobyl nuclear power
reactor, which exploded 12 years ago in what remains the worst
civilian nuclear accident on record. He was promoting efforts to
raise $760 million to build a new concrete tomb for the reactor,
something scientists say is needed to prevent further radioactive
contamination of the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
