<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: COCKTAIL DENIMS; ARTSY RESTAURANT, POWER SNACKS, CANNED
MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 26)  
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STYLISH DENIM
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that the cowboy hat is back, what could be more
natural than the return of the jean jacket? Spotted around town
lately: stylish women in black cocktail dresses or long, silky
skirts, who have accessorized with a denim jacket. Designer denim
is particularly hot. Karl Lagerfeld has included a denim jacket for
the first time in many seasons in his line that will be available
in November. Gucci, Helmut Lang Jeans and the DKNY jeans line are
featuring denim jackets.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Calvin Klein brought back his original jean jacket
from the 1970s for the CK jeans line. And the Gap has knocked off
the Gucci jacket so closely that it is hard to tell the difference.
But Andrea Linnett, a fashion writer at Harpers Bazaar, prefers her
simple old Wrangler jacket, which she wears with a slip dress or
trousers and heels. ``It instantly creates a fresh, sporty look,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ KIMBERLY STEVENS
</P>
<P>
   PALETTE TO PALATE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The art dealers who pulled up stakes in SoHo for new
galleries in deserted west Chelsea don't miss the throngs of
tourists, but they are nostalgic for one thing: good food. Rather
than wait for an enterprising restaurateur to discover their
up-and-coming art district, a group of dealers took matters into
their own hands. They invested $10,000 each in Bottino, a low-key
but stylish trattoria in a former hardware store at 246 10th Ave.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant, which serves simple Tuscan fare on an open
backyard terrace, as well as indoors, has already become a
destination for a sleek-looking crowd. It has played host to
post-art-opening parties for Ellsworth Kelly and Mike Kelley. It
was opened six weeks ago by Daniel Emerman and Sandro Prosperi, who
also own Barocco in TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer-investors include Barbara Gladstone, Matthew Marks
and the owners of Metro Pictures. In return for their stakes, each
gallery gets a food tab worth $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting hungry!'' Ms. Gladsone said. ``We wanted a place
to socialize that was intelligently set up but without
pretension.''
</P>
<P>
   The new restaurant is across the street from the Getty _ a gas
station, that is, not the museum.
</P>
<P>
   _ JULIA CHAPLIN
</P>
<P>
   4 O'CLOCK PRETZEL BREAK
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are trends in hemlines and trends in footwear
and, just as surely, there are trends in snack foods. The latest
must-have accessory for many in the fashion flock is Rold Gold's
new Honey Mustard pretzels _ 99 cents for a fat-free, four-ounce
bag. ``They are on every desk at 4 o'clock,'' Pixie Yates, a
downtown designer, said.
</P>
<P>
   At Frou by Paige Novick, another fashion design house, they
can't get enough of the pretzels. ``All the women in the office eat
the pretzels all day,'' Ms. Novick said. Philosophizing about their
appeal, she added, ``The feminine shape and delicate line represent
the ultimate snack.''
</P>
<P>
   Another popular snack is Parrillo Bars, a power bar sold in
health clubs. ``If you go to events, all the girls about town have
them in their bags, right there next to the cell phone,'' Kimberly
Ryan, special projects editor at Vogue, said. ``Nobody eats meals
anymore, they just snack.'' And for those low-energy lulls between
snacks? Caffeinated water like Water Joe is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   _ DANY LEVY
</P>
<P>
   CANNED MESSAGES
</P>
<P>
   Since last month, Miller Lite has been sold in seven different
cans that invite the guzzler to establish a meaningful relationship
with his beer. One can has a Cal-O-Meter on it, a scale to show the
calories consumed, from zero ounces (zero calories) to 12 ounces
(128 calories). Another can has a space where a drinker can write
his name, address and phone number _ in case the can gets lost.
Some cans note, ``Not every can of Miller Lite contains the same
number of bubbles.''
</P>
<P>
   The arch labeling is pitched to the postcollegiate crowd,
beer-drinkers weaned on Lettermanesque humor. It is Miller Brewing
Co.'s response to a flatness in sales, said Gina Shaffer, marketing
communications manager for Miller Lite in Milwaukee. She said the
labeling is ``focused on 21- to 28-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller Lite, introduced in 1975, had its peak year in 1990, said
Eric Shepard, executive editor of Beer Marketers Insight, an
industry newsletter. A six-pack of 12-ounce cans is $4.50.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELAINE LOUIE
</P>
</TEXT>
