<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1762 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DURHAM-DANCE-REVIEW-3     07-24 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DURHAM-DANCE-REVIEW-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C., N.Y.)  
 CELEBRATING ISRAEL'S 50th ANNIVERSARY: A LIVELY MULTICULTURAL(js) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ The three modern-dance choreographers who
presented premieres as part of the annual International
Choreographers Commissioning Program at the American Dance Festival
here on Thursday all grew up in countries built by immigrants.
Brenda Angiel was born in Argentina, Inbal Pinto in Israel and
Barak Marshall in the United States. For all their differences,
history and circumstances brought them together at the festival to
present highly distinct experimental works on an evening that was
billed as a salute to Israel's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall moved from his native Los Angeles to Israel in 1994,
after graduating from Harvard. His father is American and his
mother is Margalit Oved, who was a leading dancer in the famed
Israeli Yemenite troupe, Inbal Dance Theater, and was later a
distinguished choreographer and teacher at UCLA Those who have seen
Miss Oved in her own dance pieces over the years in New York and
elsewhere would not be surprised that the dramatic presence she
brought to Marshall's premiere as a performer is as fierce as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Pinto, Marshall directs his own dance troupe in Israel.
Miss Angiel, known as Brenda Angielczyk when she studied and
presented choreography in New York in 1990-1991, directs her
company in Argentina. All three choreographers are Jewish, but this
program, called ``Celebrating Israel's 50th Anniversary,'' could be
seen chiefly as a timely tribute of convenience. If anything, it
suggested that heritage was to be treated or ignored according to
esthetic sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Angiel's piece offered a super-polished image of dancers
suspended in the air. Ms. Pinto created a clever surreal fable, and
Marshall presented a collage of exciting athletic movement and
charismatic solos.
</P>
<P>
   Each work was choreographed during the festival's six-week
summer school on the Duke University campus. Since 1987 the
International Choreographers Commissioning Program has provided
rehearsal space and dancers for choreographers from abroad. The
dancers are drawn from the students and other foreign
choreographers attending the festival school.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In ``South, Wall and After,'' Ms. Angiel made striking use of
what is now a tired device: dancers harnessed to ropes and
suspended in the air. The original twist was to suggest a
bird's-eye view of performers, creating the illusion that the
viewer was seeing pedestrians on a pavement below. The backdrop by
Anna Wirth and Frank Sheets suggested gray bricks or paving stones,
depending on how Ms. Angiel experimented with perspective. At
times, the dancers looked as if they were perpendicular to a
bricked wall. The structure of the choreography became formal, with
dancers in unison or in staggered repetitive permutations that sent
them flying into the air or combining steps on the wall within a
pendulum swing. There was a stunning moment when a trio engaged in
the aerial equivalent of synchronized swimming expanded into a
group of five.
</P>
<P>
   Yet suddenly, the choreography might focus on the dancers (Oren
Bar-Noy, Michelle Knudson, Maria Emilia Cominguez, Megan Mazarick,
Domenico Giustino and Edgardo Mercado) in pairs. The viewer became
a voyeur, looking at embraces from an imaginary window above.
</P>
<P>
   A riveting duet for a man and woman, often head-down in their
twisting and tumbling entanglements, opened the work. The beauty of
the piece is its ability to operate on two levels: one sees the
reality of the movement and believes in the illusion it creates.
The eclectic musical score, created by Ms. Angiel and Christian
Cherry, was rhythmically apt, ranging from Astor Piazzolla to jazz.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Frieda and Rosa,'' Ms. Pinto used a Cuban recording by
Esteban Salas and the theme from Charlie Chaplin's film
``Limelight.'' The action on stage was a charming surprise: Five
women in Ms. Pinto's Victorian pleated skirts moved as doll-like
figures on a music box. Four moved on platforms under their skirts
and towered over the fifth. All twitched or undulated and puffed up
their cheeks in a charming image. But these may have also been the
ghosts of elderly aunts of a thoroughly modern pair of young women
sitting on a red bench, perhaps the Frieda and Rosa of the title.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Hardy and Ariane Malia Reinhart (Elizabeth Swallow and
Summer Belnap in an alternating cast) took up the second half of
the piece. They moved at top speed in a sitting dance that
consisted of leg and arm movements so swift that one could barely
follow the sequence. As these permutations became more complex, the
relationship of the two women evolved into sisterly and playful
swipes.
</P>
<P>
   There were absurdist but not illogical touches. The last had one
of the Victorians entering to take a photo of the two women in the
dark. The excellent cast also included Ms. Belnap, Ms. Swallow,
Adrienne Longenecker, Stephanie Nugent and Liliana Tasso.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Wives' Tale,'' set to Romanian and klezmer music,
Marshall suggests that experimental and ethnic dance are not
mutually exclusive. Ms. Oved enters with lighted candles on her
head and after she passes, this image from a Yemenite wedding is
succeeded by a dance for six women with lighted candles on their
heads; it is lyrical and flowing, contrasting with units that fuse
from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oved is the charismatic storyteller, resonant in her voice
and gestures. She holds the audience in her palm when she speaks of
two grandmothers whose book of wisdom cannot be found in the
library because ``I swallowed it.'' As a choreographer, Marshall
knows how to move 17 dancers around as a group. His highly
energetic natural movement is grounded in deep plies, followed by
leaps and high swings of the leg. English, Arabic, Yiddish and
Hebrew were the tongues heard on stage. ``The Wives' Tale'' is a
fine quilt, not quite a woven tapestry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
