<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1771 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-HOUSES-MERGER     07-24 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HOUSES-MERGERS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MERGER NIGHTMARE ON FASHION STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 26)  
(lh) 
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corporate mergers are all the rage, what with Daimler-Benz
buying Chrysler, Bertelsmann swallowing Random House, and other
high-stakes marriages in banking, pharmaceuticals and
telecommunications. In the fashion industry, unions of famous
labels have long seemed highly unlikely, given that designers
consider themselves brilliant originals, whose artistic visions
could not possibly be merged into one entity.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent acquisition by Prada of a 9.5 percent stake of
the publicly traded stock in Gucci, its archrival in the Italian
high-fashion business, has changed old assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be the start of merger mania on the catwalks? Who
would be a likely partner for whom? Most important, what would
their new perfumes be named? Below, some spurious speculations on
the new landscape of a post-merger style world.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH MOET HENNESSY-LOUIS VUITTON BUYS EVERYONE
</P>
<P>
   SCENARIO: To fill out its alphabet soup of houses, the French
luxury-goods conglomerate, which already owns Celine, Dior, Loewe
and Givenchy, acquires Victor Alfaro, Byblos, Escada, Andrew Fezza,
Istante, Wolfgang Joop, Michael Kors, Martin Margiela, Lucien
Pellat-Fine, Todd Oldham, Cynthia Rowley, Paul Smith, Isabel
Toledo, Emanuel Ungaro, Vivienne Westwood, X-Girl, Yeohlee and
Ermenegildo Zegna. And QVC.
</P>
<P>
   NEW COMPANY NAME: ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ.
</P>
<P>
   ADVERTISING SLOGAN: We've got it all!
</P>
<P>
   CHIEF EXECUTIVE, CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER, CHIEF BOTTLE WASHER:
Bernard Arnault.
</P>
<P>
   MOTTO: If you're doing business with us, you're not doing
business!
</P>
<P>
   PRADA'S HOSTILE TAKEOVER OF GUCCI
</P>
