<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flash flood and severe thunderstorm warnings were issued Friday
for parts of Arizona as moisture continued to stream into the
Southwest from the tropics. On Saturday, a high-pressure system
building over the southern California Coast at high altitudes will
curtail the flow of moisture into the Southwest, limiting the scope
and intensity of storms. Nonetheless, isolated storms fueled by
residual moisture will develop, particularly over the southern
Rockies, where the uneven heating of mountains and valleys promotes
currents of rising air.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will erupt over parts of eastern
Colorado, eastern Wyoming, Nebraska and Kansas as moist winds
blowing from the east just behind a stationary front are forced to
ascend the sloping terrain. A disturbance at high altitudes will
also provide lift for showers and storms. Farther east,
thunderstorms may become heavy from southeast Kansas to southern
Missouri and northern Arkansas as surging humid air from the Gulf
of Mexico meets the stationary front.
</P>
<P>
   A risk of thunderstorms will extend east near the stationary
front to the Carolinas as hot, humid air converges along the front.
Storms, however, will tend to form in isolated clusters, dousing
one area but missing others.
</P>
<P>
   A dry air mass will soothe the northeast quadrant of the nation
Saturday. Isolated showers and thundershowers are possible, mainly
over the mountains of northern New England and parts of the central
Appalachians, as a weak trough of low pressure at jet stream levels
pivots east from the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden Floods
</P>
<P>
   The risk of flash floods was heightened Friday in parts of the
West as slow-moving thunderstorms, fueled by tropical moisture
streaming northward, blossomed in the heat of the afternoon. The
places at greatest risk were determined mainly by topography.
Canyons and mountain passes in the Rockies are notorious for sudden
summer floods. With steep slopes to channel runoff from heavy rain
into gorges below, small creeks and low-lying beds called dry
washes (because they are usually dry) can fill with surging water
in a very short time, sometimes catching unsuspecting travelers
off-guard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
