<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, July 25,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: Adds: CAPITOL-SHOOTING, SHOOTING-SCENE, SHOOTING-TOURISTS,
SHOOTING-SECURITY, SHOOTING-HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, July
25, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING AT THE CAPITOL
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING _ WASHINGTON _ Four people were shot, and one
possibly killed, when a lone gunman somehow managed to get by
security in the U.S. Capitol building Friday and shot an
unidentified woman, according to U.S. Capitol police. The gunman
was also shot and injured, apparently in a shoot-out with police
near the House Majority Whip's office in the Capitol. The incident
caught hundreds of tourists and Capitol workers looking forward to
a normal winding down of a Friday in the nation's capital by
surprise. The metal detector at the entrance near the Majority
Whip's office sounded when the gunman went through, followed by a
hail of bullets. Developing. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With SHOOTING-SCENE _ WASHINGTON _ According to eyewitnesses in
House Majority Whip Thomas DeLay of Texas' office in the Capitol
Building, the gunman chased an unidentified woman into the offices
and began shooting. What followed was complete chaos. (Harlan, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With SHOOTING-TOURISTS _ WASHINGTON _ This time of year, the
U.S. Capitol Building is teaming with thousands of tourists each
day. The last thing they expect to experience or witness is a
shooting. We talk to some of them. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With SHOOTING-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ Getting into the Capitol
with a gun is extremely difficult. The public is only allowed into
the Capitol through a few entrances and everyone _ except members
of the House and Senate _ must pass through metal detectors similar
to those found at airports. Large bags must be placed on an X-ray
machine that shows a video of their contents. Staff members and
journalists are allowed in some entrances barred to the public, but
they still must pass through a metal detector and have their bags
searched by hand. That wasn't enough Friday afternoon. (Lipman, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With SHOOTING-HISTORY _ WASHINGTON _ A primary reason that
Friday afternoon's shooting was so surprising to many people is
that the U.S. Capitol Building is viewed as one of the most secure
public building complexes in the world. But Friday's incident was
not unprecedented. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND _ BELFAST, Ireland _ It took the tragic deaths of three
boys to ease the worst tensions in this war-torn nation in years.
Tensions that were expected to wither following a decisive vote for
one Ireland this spring. President Clinton has added a stop-over
here on his return trip from Russia in September to add his voice
to those pleading for unity and calm. But some significant
questions need to be answered, not the least of which is: Has the
peace process, having weathered this latest crisis, regained
momentum? (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   JERICHO-CASINO _ JERICHO, West Bank _ This is the oldest and
lowest city in the world. But, is it lucky? In the dusty expanse of
desert across the street from one of the oldest Palestinian refugee
camps, hundreds of workers are building a casino hotel aimed
largely at tempting Israelis to come gamble _ something they cannot
do next door in Israel. It's a business venture that is sure to
cause political waves among both Palestinians and Israelis even as
it could turn a big profit. The casino project is headed by an
Austrian firm with the consent of Yasser Arafat's Palestinian
Authority. But, it is widely disliked by the Palestinians who live
in the refugee camp and famous biblical town nearby. The problem is
not that Palestinians will not be allowed to gamble there. Rather,
they see gambling and the western culture it represents as a threat
to their Islamic values. Some even object to the high profile the
10-story hotel will cut amid the peaceful town of 15,000. Many of
their arguments would be recognizable to Americans who have heard
the religious opposition to casino gambling in their own country.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 11 a.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COSSACKS _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The feared Cossacks
ride again? Russia's tradition-steeped warrior caste is undergoing
a revival of sorts, after being submerged for decades by the Soviet
Union. St. Petersburg officials plan to use the Cossacks to patrol
city parks and assist regular police in fighting crime -- sort of
the Guardian Angels, Russo-style. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Thursday, July 24.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH _ WASHINGTON _ Despite a veto threat from the White
House, Republicans are rushing to the House floor with legislation
they brought forward only a week ago to respond to Americans'
complaints about health plans. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FARM-AID _ WASHINGTON _ Just two years after the nation's
farmers were put on the path to independence from subsidies and
price supports, the concept of the ``Freedom to Farm'' act is
coming under a severe test in the drought of 1998 as lawmakers and
the president rush to provide aid. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT _ WASHINGTON _ Setup for vote likely Monday in the Senate
on credit union reform. (Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EUROPA _ WASHINGTON _ Much of scientists' concerns about the
possibility of extraterrestrial microbes infecting Earth in samples
collected by space missions involve two moons of Jupiter, Europa
and Ganymede, where conditions are believed best to support life.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWSUIT _ Attorney General Dan Morales announces final
agreement in Texas' landmark tobacco lawsuit. We seek specifics on
what's next. How much money will the state get, when and where will
the money be spent? (Hight, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SIXMONTHS _ On the eve of his official installation as president
of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, Martin Luther King
III talks about the six months that have passed since he was named
to head the organization his father founded. An immediate challenge
is dealing with the fallout from the SCLC board's decision to sever
ties to SCLC Women, which happened in April but just recently
became public knowledge. (Byrd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DAMS -- Substandard dams pose a growing threat to people
and property in Texas, and the state's inspection program to keep
track of the problem is woefully inadequate, according to a report
by a special task force. (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
