<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTRUMENT-MAKER-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ARTIST CONDUCTS HIS STRING SOLOS IN WOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHUSHAN, N.Y. _ Most people are eager to share family photos.
Geoffrey Ovington is a host with three-dimensional treasures. He
wants you to see different planks of wood.
</P>
<P>
   He's in his studio, a splendidly renovated space on the second
floor of a rustic red barn, the rolling Taconic Mountains in
southern Vermont framing the landscape to the east. Moving about
like a youngster showing off birthday presents, Ovington goes from
one piece of wood to the next.
</P>
<P>
   For the artisan with an international reputation for handmade
string instruments, the planks of maple, pear and spruce represent
the staffs of life. He removes a pillow-case-size piece of wood
from a shelf, caressing the surface with his muscular hand, an
appreciative smile creasing his round face.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pear wood, it's wonderful for cellos,'' he explains.
``Cellos are the only instruments for which I'll use pear wood.
It's much more common for me to work with maple. Some of the maple
I have here was imported at the turn of the century by Italian
violin makers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this curly maple,'' Ovington adds, removing another
plank that, to the untrained eye, looks not unlike the pear plank.
``Doesn't it have just a magnificent grain? This is a beautiful
piece of wood, just beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The plank, which will be cut and scraped and cut again before it
is etched and varnished, will become even more beautiful in
Ovington's capable hands. The 53-year-old has been creating
instruments for a quarter of a century, and during that time has
become a much sought-after maker of violins, violas and cellos.
</P>
<P>
   From the Philadelphia Orchestra to the Vienna Philharmonic to
the Deutsche Kammerphilharmonie, there are few world-class
symphonies or philharmonics without at least one musician playing
an Ovington. And in Victoria, British Columbia, a quartet has paid
him a high and rare honor, calling itself the Ovington String
Quartet because two of the four play his instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he toils in almost total anonymity in Shushan, a hamlet
northeast of Albany, known better in concert halls in Milan, Munich
and Vienna than in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month he completed his 200th instrument, a viola
for Cecily Friedman in Callicoon, N.Y., one of Ovington's few
amateur clients. It was a milestone that warranted a toast with
glasses filled, for he has reached a point where even he will agree
he has a substantial body of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought that before you sum up a maker's work,
they better have made a couple hundred instruments,'' he says.
``It's really not fair to judge a maker by basing your judgment on
one or two instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a watchful parent he has carefully kept track of the 200
Ovingtons in circulation, noting for the record that four have
succumbed to unfortunate fates. One was stolen, one was destroyed
in a ship accident, one was stepped on in an orchestra pit, and one
was pushed under a car in its case by a toddler just as her mother
was backing out of the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   A work of art, an acclaimed hand-made instrument worth $10,000
to $15,000 and increasing in value all the time, crushed into
splinters in the blink of an eye. Notes Ovington, ``Those are the
only four I know of that have been taken out of existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 196 are in musicians' hands, bringing pleasure to
the makers and lover of classical sounds on at least three
continents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ovington take a chestnut-handled knife to the deep-set
rim of a new viola, it is easy to imagine this same setting two
centuries earlier. There are no high-tech tools in his studio; the
maker uses hand-sized knives and planes just as the European
craftsmen once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``With one notable exception,'' Ovington interjects, pointing to
the hi-fi system in the corner of his studio. ``If this was the
18th century, I wouldn't be able to listen to NPR (National Public
Radio) every minute of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   The central Massachusetts native first realized he wanted to be
an instrument maker while he was studying English at Clark
University in Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when I saw a real instrument for the first time,'' he
explains. ``It belonged to my girlfriend at the time. It was a
beautiful violin, with mouthwatering varnish that made me want to
touch it and stroke it. I thought, `I want to make those.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always liked classical music, along with rock and other
kinds of music. I guess I was ripe, because my reaction to her
violin was immediate. I thought this is the thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It took almost six years for Ovington to act on his revelation.
After college he taught English and remedial reading in the New
York City public school system, a job he took to avoid being
drafted for the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But he knew it wasn't what he wanted to do. ``I kept feeling
that I was being sucked in. I had other reasons pushing me into
teaching. My heart wasn't in it.''
</P>
<P>
   So he listened to his inner voice. He bought a how-to manual for
making a violin, and paid a visit to the Metropolitan Music Co. in
New York City to buy the wood he needed. He struggled, he
remembers, yet in 1973 he finished his first violin, an instrument
he dismisses today as ``a total amateur effort.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter, though. At last he was doing what he wanted to
do, what he believes he was meant to do.
</P>
<P>
   Ovington also started taking violin lessons, for practical as
well as artistic reasons. ``I decided if I wanted to build them I
had to learn to play them. I ended up making a lot of friends in
the violin field, and it's turned out to be a real blessing for me
as an instrument maker.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovington is devoted to classical music, and he and partner
Bonnie Hoag, regularly host string quartets in their barn,
nurturing music appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   It both saddens and angers him to report that the percentage of
people who can read music in the United States is roughly 4
percent, compared with 76 percent in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've abandoned teaching music. We'd rather have a $50,000
scoreboard than fund a music program,'' says Ovington, the words
rushing out as he speaks with passion. ``We don't spend a dime on
string programs in most of our schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody bothers to tell kids how to like classical music. You
can't just expose them, they have to be led to it. We're failing.
Music is a big thing and we're throwing it out the window. The
general public is ignorant of the value of music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
