<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-YIELDS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD YIELD IS GETTING MUCH HARDER TO FIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic showing long bond vs. S&AMP;P dividend yield will be
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26)  
 (af)  
 By PEGGY EDERSHEIM KALB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many stock fund portfolios seem sorely lacking in dividends
these days. With the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index paying an
aggregate yield of just 1.24 percent, even funds that bill
themselves as growth-and-income offerings seem far more weighted
toward growth than income.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as the bull market keeps roaring, many shareholders
are perfectly happy with the situation, much preferring a capital
gain to a dividend that is taxable as ordinary income.
</P>
<P>
   But other shareholders, noting that shares are trading at
historically high valuations, want yield as a safety factor.
Dividends are paid regardless of movements in price and permit
investors to get some money off the table with each payout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things that is hard to remember in this
kind of a stock market is that you need to distinguish between what
is knowable and what is not knowable,'' said Janet McKinley,
president of the Income Fund of America, a $22 billion stock fund
whose goal is to produce income for shareholders. ``The only thing
you can know with some degree of certainty when you look at stocks
is the stream of dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   But that stream has slowed to a trickle, and the funds that
traditionally pay the most in dividends, like utilities and real
estate investment trusts, may be sacrificing capital appreciation
in today's market. The stock prices of REITs are down about 10
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The average utility fund yields just 2.33 percent; indeed,
Merrill Lynch has the only utility fund yielding more than 5
percent, according to Lipper Analytical Services in Summit, N.J. A.
Michael Lipper, the firm's president and chief executive, warned
that many individual investors might think twice before giving up
the diversification of a more general fund for the
not-so-impressive yield of utility funds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there are growth-and-income funds, in which
managers are supposed to be seeking a balance between yield and
capital appreciation. The group includes warhorses like the Mutual
Series funds, which yield only 3 percent, and Vanguard Windsor II,
at 1.9 percent, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Yield is also elusive in the bond markets. Thirty-year Treasury
bonds are yielding just 5.68 percent, near their historical low,
and even high-risk junk bonds are paying relatively skimpy interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Among equity-income funds, which invest a minimum of 65 percent
of their assets in dividend-paying securities, Heartland Value
Plus, a small-cap value-oriented fund managed by William Nasgovitz
and Patrick Retzer, has consistently strong yields. The 12-month
yield, at 3.62 percent, is small by historical standards but is
more than twice that of the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   And the fund has also managed to perform in the top 10 percent
in its category over the last three years, with an average
annualized total return of 20.85 percent through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nasgovitz, who called Heartland Value Plus a more conservative
version of the well-known Heartland Value fund, said the emphasis
on yield was intended to make the fund more defensive than its
sibling in a down market.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, 61.4 percent of the assets were in common
stocks, 10.8 percent in REITs, 24.9 percent in corporate and
convertible bonds, 2 percent in preferred stocks and less than 1
percent in cash.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fund's favorite high-yielding stocks, with a dividend
of 6.5 percent, is the Interstate Energy Co., based in Madison,
Wis., which just merged with two Iowa utilities. Retzer expects the
stock, which closed at $30.625 on Friday, to reach the mid- to high
$30s in 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to get yield into a portfolio is to buy shares of
balanced funds, which tend to have a fixed allocation of stocks and
bonds. Mark Mullin, chief investment officer for Diversified
Investment Advisors, called this ``a common sense approach'' that
provided exposure to the primary asset classes, but he added that
``if you truly wanted to maximize income, balanced funds would not
be the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   His firm's Diversified Investment Balanced fund is a standout
among such funds, with a yield of 5.55 percent over 12 months and
average annual return of 17.1 percent over the last three years,
putting it in the top 25 percent of its group. The subadviser of
the fund, which has $451 million in assets, is the Institutional
Capital Corp. of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has 59 percent of its assets in equities, 40 percent in
fixed-income instruments _ typically triple-A rated government and
agency bonds _ and 1 percent in cash. A current stock favorite is
General Motors, considered a reorganization play, for which the
fund has a price target of $84. It closed on Friday at $71.06, with
a yield of 2.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A variation on the theme is asset-allocation funds, which give
portfolio managers more latitude to switch their amounts of stocks
and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   One such fund is Income Fund of America, which had a 4.1 percent
yield for the 12 months ended Thursday, and has been in the top 25
percent of its peer group in total return over the last five years.
Since its inception at the end of 1973, the fund, which is marketed
by American Funds, has returned 14.3 percent a year, just a
fraction of a point below the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a get-rich-slow kind of person,'' said Ms. McKinley, the
fund's president, adding that the fund's strategy meant that ``you
get to sleep at night.'' As of June 30, the fund was about 60
percent in equities (including convertibles) and 14 percent in
cash, with the balance in corporate and government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McKinley declined to identify stock picks under
consideration but said the fund's managers looked for companies
that generate a lot of cash flow, pay dividends and in some cases
buy back shares. ``Many of the banks and telecoms around the world
fit that bill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any hope that yields will rise? Kenneth Heebner,
manager of CGM Realty, a perennially popular REIT fund with a
12-month yield of 4.51 percent, contends that REIT dividend growth
will remain strong, though share prices are now depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Heebner has more than half of his fund in office and industrial
REITs because that sector, with its long-term leases, is more
defensive than higher-yielding hotel REITs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
