<HEADLINE>
WILL ALLIANCES DARKEN THE FREQUENT-FLIER SKY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 26)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic on three airlines' frequent flier miles is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines recently notified the 30 million members of
its frequent-flier program that award redemption levels for certain
tickets would rise next Feb. 1. An upgrade from coach to first
class on a domestic flight will require 30,000 miles, up from
20,000, for example, and a business-class ticket to Europe or Latin
America will require 90,000, up from 80,000.
</P>
<P>
   To clarify these and other adjustments, American has printed a
handy chart _ detailing 196 separate redemption requirements in 11
different categories.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to believe for those who think frequent-flier
plans are already too complex, but these are the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, the country's six largest airlines, which
collectively carry 70 percent of all air traffic, are to combine
their frequent-flier plans into three separate alliances. Plans
that seem difficult to follow now will seem simplistic once members
of one program can redeem tickets in another.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines call the new links a boon for consumers, who will
be able to accumulate and redeem mileage on more than one carrier.
But analysts and consumer advocates, who already say frequent-flier
miles are not that great a deal, worry that they will shortly
become a worse deal.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much worse is hard to say, because the airlines have
been reluctant to describe exactly how the new arrangements will
work.
</P>
<P>
   American, the country's second-largest airline and a unit of AMR
Corp., and U S Airways, the sixth largest, are set to begin their
alliance on Saturday. United Airlines, the country's No. 1 carrier
and a unit of UAL Corp., and Delta Air Lines, No. 3, are to start
offering reciprocal rights in each other's frequent-flier programs
Sept. 1. The details for each of these alliances remain sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines, the country's fourth-largest carrier, and
Continental Airlines, No. 5, were first to announce their alliance,
in January. Six months later, they have not even said when their
joint program will start.
</P>
<P>
   After a bumpy start in the early 1980s, frequent-flier programs
have become a huge success for the airlines. About 75 million
people around the world now belong to at least one program.
Consumers annually divert billions of dollars _ to credit cards
affiliated with the programs, or to goods and services tied to such
plans _ to obtain more miles.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an estimated three trillion miles are waiting to be
redeemed, the equivalent of about 110 million tickets at the
average redemption level _ or more than half what the domestic
industry sells in a year.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines earn $1.5 billion a year simply selling miles _ at
2 cents apiece _ to marketing partners like hotels and rental car
companies, according to Randy Petersen, the editor and publisher of
Inside Flyer, a magazine that monitors frequent-flier programs.
</P>
<P>
   For that, they give away seats that, according to the industry's
calculations, probably would have flown empty.
</P>
<P>
   Each new alliance appears to be slightly different. American and
U S Airways say members of their plans will be able to redeem miles
for tickets on each other. Eventually, fliers with memberships in
both plans will be able to pool their miles for tickets from either
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   United and Delta members will be able to designate which program
they want to credit with miles they earn on individual flights. The
airlines say they will soon announce when United fliers can cash in
miles for tickets on Delta and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   The reciprocity will be limited, however, to the airlines'
domestic flights. And there will be no pooling of miles between the
two programs.
</P>
<P>
   As for Northwest and Continental? ``Until we make a formal
announcement of when the program begins, we will not be forthcoming
with details with how the program will operate,'' said Sara
Anthony, a spokeswoman for Continental.
</P>
<P>
   When will that announcement be? Ms. Anthony would not say.
</P>
<P>
   One of the airlines plan to address the biggest consumer
complaint about frequent-flier programs: that free seats are not
available when people want to fly.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines say the number of new destinations added by the
alliances will relieve the pressure on the seat supply. But many
critics say the alliances will aggravate the problem because more
people will be competing for the same choice destinations at the
same peak periods.
</P>
<P>
   American said its decision to raise mileage requirements for
certain tickets had nothing to do with its alliance with U S
Airways. But some rivals disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Jilek, Delta's director of relationship marketing,
said American was forced to act because by pooling its program's
miles with those of U S Airways, more people would suddenly be
eligible for free tickets on American.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, Ms. Jilek said, was not planning to raise its award
redemption levels, a view echoed by United, Continental and U S
Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue: United, American and Northwest require their
miles to be used within certain lengths of time, or they will
expire. But their respective partners _ Delta, U S Airways and
Continental _ all offer miles that do not expire (though Delta
requires members to use the airline once every three years) and say
they have no plans to change.
</P>
<P>
   That will create some interesting choices. A frequent traveler
on United, for example, might be tempted to credit all his miles to
Delta, to keep them from expiring. But if he does so, he will lose
his elite mileage status when he flies on United.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be so complicated out there,'' said Petersen,
the frequent-flier expert, ``that it is going to be hard to figure
out how to get the best benefit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
