</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-YIELDS-DFA-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG YIELD, BUT NO STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic showing DFA Enhanced funds compared to other
funds will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26)  
 (af)  
 By PEGGY EDERSHEIM KALB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In contrast to all those funds that find the quest for yield a
veritable snipe hunt, the DFA Enhanced U.S. Large Co. fund boasts a
stratospheric 12-month yield of 10.88 percent. But the fund's
manager, David Plecha, warns that his esoteric fund is not for many
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Plecha described the fund as ``an equity portfolio that
typically doesn't hold stocks.'' Instead, he largely buys futures
contracts of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, generally about
three months out, giving the fund an equity component while
allowing him to keep cash in interest-bearing instruments, thus
raising the income component of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   His management team is particularly partial to high-quality
bonds in foreign currencies, which often have higher interest rates
than those in the United States, and the fund hedges the currency
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fund gives you full stock exposure with income more
reflective of a bond portfolio,'' Plecha said. Among recent
purchases were bonds issued by Denmark, maturing in October 1999
with a coupon of 6.5 percent, and by GE Capital Canada, maturing in
July 1999 with a 7 percent coupon.
</P>
<P>
   From its inception in July 1996 through Thursday, the fund's
annualized return has been 33.7 percent, far ahead of the 25.5
percent for the average growth-and-income fund. Still Plecha says
his fund, available to institutions and through investment
advisers, is not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It generates a lot of taxes because of the amount of activity
in the futures markets,'' he said. Both dividends and short-term
capital gains are taxable at ordinary income-tax rates. Thus, it is
a more appropriate investment for tax-exempt or tax-deferred
accounts. Then, of course, there is the inherent volatility of the
futures market to consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1853 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      07-24 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD ACHIEVES CROWNING GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - My neighbor Louie's a big guy, a Phoenix motorcycle
cop and a longtime driver of Chrysler products. Sometimes he'd
settle for a Chevy, but never, ever would he buy a Ford. Not his
style.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with some amusement that I recently discovered a new,
white Crown Victoria sitting in his driveway. ``What's the deal?''
I asked.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the modern run of front-drive, wedge-shaped,
V-6-powered sedans are not up to snuff, in Louie's view. What he
wanted, and without spending a small fortune to get it, was a
full-sized American sedan in the classic sense.
</P>
<P>
   There are only three of these left on the planet, all built by
Ford Motor Co. That's the Crown Victoria and its upscale corporate
twin, the Mercury Grand Marquis, and the top-drawer Lincoln Town
Car.
</P>
<P>
   Louie wanted the space, the comfort, the compliant ride and the
sense of security of a big American, so that's how he ended up with
a Crown Vic in his driveway. He grudgingly admitted that he likes
it, too, even if it is a Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Louis is not alone in finding the Crown Vic's traditional values
appealing. For one thing, Ford has a lock on the nation's fleet of
police cars, cabs and other public vehicles where size and strength
matter. It used to face stiff competition from the Chevrolet
Caprice, which Chevy axed two model years ago to turn over its
factory space to sport-utility vehicles and pickups, the nation's
hottest sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The Caprice was mourned by many, especially older drivers and
those, like Louis, who favor the big rear-drive sedans. And many of
those people have turned to Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The Crown Victoria is something of a throwback. Its name hints
at its old-fashioned appeal, the Victoria label first being applied
to a Ford in 1932 for the cars that replaced the Model A.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the wheel, with the long hood jutting forward and the
soft seats underneath, a middle-ager can recall learning to drive
in Dad's Galaxy 500. Older drivers can be lulled into recalling
their own cars of the '50s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford's trying to expand the appeal of the Crown Vic beyond
the traditional-car market. Improvements in suspension, steering,
brakes and styling give the Crown Vic more of a modern edge.
</P>
<P>
   The V-8 engine under that big hood is a thoroughly modern
overhead-cam design with fuel injection and coil-on-plug ignition
that eliminates spark-plug wires, delivering a solid 200
horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   It's linked to an electronic four-speed automatic that's been
improved for '98 with smoother shifting. The front and rear
suspension have been redesigned for better handling and quicker
response, and the brakes are bigger and more effective.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an optional handling package available that adds
beefier suspension, better tires and 15 more horses of engine
power. I'd go for that.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Crown Vic rides comfortably and competently. On
a quick trip to Tucson, its quiet ride and high-speed highway
manners were well appreciated. So was the excellent stereo system,
cushy seats and broad roominess. This kind of distance cruising is
where a Crown Vic shines.
</P>
<P>
   Around town, the big sedan was surprisingly nimble, cornering
ably while it soaked up bumps and irregularities. The power
steering is quick and not too light or overboosted, like so many
big American cars.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a big car and sometimes feels as if it can't get out
of its own way. The float and vague handling of past years is
mostly gone, but it can feel heavy and ponderous.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is sedate and the appointments conservative. Driving
excitement has been pretty much dialed out of the equation,
replaced by the secure, placid ride of a luxury barge.
</P>
<P>
   I drove the LX model, fully equipped with all the goodies. One
thing you can say for the Crown Vic, you get a lot of car for the
money, both in sheet metal and ameni ties. This loaded LX had just
about everything you could want, except maybe that handling
package, and still came in just over $26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not cheap, but the kind of value that has kept Crown Vic in the
game all these years and, according to Ford, for many more to come.
</P>
<P>
   With the standard engine, acceleration is quiet and smooth, the
V-8 moving the heavy cruiser quickly. Gas mileage suffers badly
with this kind of activity, though, so spirited driving will cost
you at the pump. Once up to speed, cruise-control keeps things on
track, the torquey engine pulling evenly up and down grades, while
you relax behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The optional leather seating is nice, in the manner of a
living-room easy chair. The spacious interior provides true
six-passenger space, once common but rare these days. Headroom and
legroom are great, front and rear. Styling and trim are very
traditional, befitting its mainstream appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Not so traditional is the digital dashboard, which I found
distracting and annoying, especially the speedometer. Most
automakers flirted with these things but eventu ally did away with
them, spurred by consumer complaints, in favor of regular analog
gauges. Some companies, particularly Chrysler, are fitting gauges
that look vintage.
</P>
<P>
   I also think it's time that Ford changed the trunk
configuration, which is too deep and narrow, lacking space for
anything other than bulky, square objects. A broad, flat floor
works so much better.
</P>
<P>
   While the sedan's styling has been upgraded with smoother lines
and some new shapes front and rear, there's no mistaking the Crown
Victoria. It's a survivor among automobiles, carrying a torch for
drivers who remember fondly when American cars were big, wide and
driven by their back wheels. &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at 444-8106, or at bob.golfen(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ford Crown Victoria LX
</P>
<P>
   Vehicle type: Six-passenger, four-door sedan, rear-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $23,135.
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $26,810.
</P>
<P>
   Engine: 4.6-liter V-8, 200 horsepower at 4,250 rpm, 265
pounds-feet of torque at 3,000 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Transmission: Four-speed automatic.
</P>
<P>
   Curb weight: 3,776 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Length: 212 inches. &QL; 
EPA fuel economy: 17 city, 25 highway.
</P>
<P>
   Highs: Comfort. Value pricing. Highway cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Lows: Digital dash. Geriatric image. Weird trunk shape. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
