<HEADER>
A1857 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-CAT-AZR &LR;      07-24 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-CAT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A BARK-MEOW WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It has been said that there are two kinds of people in
the world: those who divide the world into two kinds of people and
those who do not. But I've never met any of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody and his brother-in-law splits the world into two
categories: male and female; conservative and liberal; Gene Autry
fan and Roy Rogers fan; those who get it, and those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying every other distinction, however, is the basic,
fundamental one: between dog and cat. Every animate being on the
planet is one or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've come to this understanding, you can see it in the
faces of everyone around you.
</P>
<P>
   They are opposed personality types. They function in the world
differently and see the world differently.
</P>
<P>
   For the dog, the world is essentially simple. Truth is truth, up
is up and down is down. The dog has a direct relationship with the
things of the world: They are what they are.
</P>
<P>
   A cat, on the other hand, sees the world metaphorically. Things
are never only what they seem. They can mean one thing Monday and
something entirely different on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When dogs read poetry, they like to read, ``what oft was
thought, but ne'er so well expressed.'' Their word is their honor
and they have 30-year mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   There are many kinds of dogs in the world. Some are bureaucrats
and some, the more stylish, wear whatever is touted in ``Esquire.''
Some are noble and become doctors or missionaries; others bring my
slippers at day's end.
</P>
<P>
   It is plain, especially to dogs, that the world functions only
because of them.
</P>
<P>
   But cats have eyes that change as the moon changes. They live by
their own rules and amend them as their mood shifts. They are
filled with prevarication and treachery. Their minds shuffle like a
gambler's deck of cards, and we never know what face will show, or
what suit. ``Spades and Diamonds, Courage and Power; Clubs and
Hearts, Knowledge and Pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to poetry, cats often prefer to write their own.
</P>
<P>
   There can be little meaningful dialogue between the dog and the
cat, because they mean different things when they use the same
word.
</P>
<P>
   This frustrates the dog no end; he cannot pin the cat down,
while the cat delights in the ambiguity, and will even do what he
can to amplify it.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are trustworthy. A dog will be on time; a cat will be late,
cancel or forget.
</P>
<P>
   A dog joins the Rotarians; a cat never does, unless he can use
his membership toward the end of world domination, or something
else he thinks might be fun.
</P>
<P>
   Among women, cats can wear too much eye makeup; dogs put too
much lacquer in their hair. The difference is total and complete.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a dog can certainly be selfish, but it takes a cat
to be egocentric. A telling difference.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs have faith in the basic goodness of the world, and although
they make a place for evil, they nevertheless believe it is
something that can be overcome. A cat may or may not believe in
evil, but whatever else, he believes in the relativity of goodness
and truth.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just people: All animals are also dogs or cats. Think
of a sea otter. Cat or dog? There can be no question. Anything that
can sleep floating on the ocean surface so curled up that its head
rests comfortably on its own belly is a cat. Sturgeon are dogs. So
are bears, horses, elephants and cows _ ungulates as a class are
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to see this play out in nature. Don't be
confused by taxonomy. It is not names that define dogness and
catness. Foxes, for instance, are classified as canines by the
doggy scientists, but they are nevertheless cats. And cheetahs _
you only have to look at those stiff, tensioned legs to recognize
their essential dogginess.
</P>
<P>
   The main physical difference is in their bendability. Pick up a
dog by his middle and what do you feel? The beast is stiff as a
two-by-four. He is uncomfortable off the ground. He whimpers. Put
him back down and his tail wags.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up a cat, and it drapes over you, form-fitting and at ease.
I know a man who used to wear his big orange cat as a kind of
living Davy Crockett hat. The cat sagged over his skull and down
his neck and never wavered. The cat just purred.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell the relative caninicity or felinicity of a person
when you dance some old-fashioned thing like a waltz. If your
partner's spine is rigid, he or she is a dog. A cat-partner will
swing and sway with the rhythm like a willow in a gust.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone remember seeing archival TV film of Richard Nixon
attempting the Twist? The very definition of a dog.
</P>
<P>
   That is because a dog is all of a piece; he is one thing, head
to tail. A cat is a loose concatenation of impulses, a pile of
multiple personalities. When a dog dances, every part of him has to
move in the same direction at the same time. A cat is syncopated.
</P>
<P>
   This pervades their world views. A dog is regimented and feels
most comfortable when most conventional. A cat is individual and
often takes little notice of what is expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the American Revolution. The redcoats, marching in
rank, were dogs; the Americans, taking potshots at them from the
woods, were cats.
</P>
<P>
   Groucho Marx, taking his potshots, is the quintessential cat. If
a canine becomes too officious, a cat is always there to flick his
cigar ash and wiggle his eyebrows. Although dogs do not understand
cats, cats understand dogs all too well.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, although almost all politicians are dogs, the
most effective religious evangelists are cats. They don't actually
believe what they say, but they get a great deal of pleasure from
persuading listeners to line up behind them, cheering (and sending
money).
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, the cat believes what he is saying as he says it. It
is just that tomorrow, he can say something else. I'm thinking of
Marjoe Gortner, for instance, or Lyndon Larouche. A foolish
consistency, they rejoinder.
</P>
<P>
   A true cat will really enjoy making one argument now, then
switching hats or podiums, proving himself wrong in the next
breath. The pleasure is in the arguing, not the results. Strife is
the natural order of things.
</P>
<P>
   This makes dogs very, very uncomfortable. For the dog, arguments
are proof that the world is out of balance. Equilibrium must be
restored: The two sides in a dispute must work it out, so the truth
will prevail and peace _ the dog's natural order of things _ will
re-emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The dichotomy is at the bottom of some of the most familiar
cultural pairings we know. Benjamin Franklin, with his ``early to
bed, early to rise,'' was a dog; Thomas Jefferson, with his house
filled with maps and stuffed elk, inventive contraptions and lack
of heat, was a cat.
</P>
<P>
   Tolstoy was a dog; Dostoevski was a cat. Hemingway went woof
woof; Faulkner, meow.
</P>
<P>
   The very earliest organized philosophies broke down along these
lines. Plato was a cat. Even now, you can never know for sure when
he actually believes some of the piffle he comes up with.
Aristotle, on the other hand, was the very model of a dog. ``Let's
make lecture notes.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to marriage, a dog can be happy married to a dog.
But a cat can be happy married to either a cat or a dog. There is
fun either way. But you see, there is a built-in paradox. How many
marriages do you know where one party is happy and the other isn't?
The reason, I tell you, is always the same: One dog, one cat.
</P>
<P>
   Two cats mated can be happy briefly. But such marriages don't
tend to last. Think of a Hollywood marriage and you pretty much get
the picture. Variety is not just an ideal for a cat but a way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the arts are heavy with cats, just as the field of
accounting is not. You don't last long at H&AMP;R Block if you believe
arithmetic is a matter of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   At bottom, we need both animals in the world. You need the dogs
to make life possible; you need cats to make it worth living. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1859 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPORTINGONRELIGION-T     07-24 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORTINGONRELIGION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INFORMATION AGE MEETS THE AGE OF FAITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Star-Telegram religion reporter Jim Jones
recently joined with writers, publishers and editors of news
organizations in a Religion and Media 2000+ conference in Rome.)
</P>
<P>
   ROME _ The new millennium, less than two years away, will usher
in one of the most religious centuries. And religious and media
leaders, who are often at odds over news coverage of religion, must
forge closer ties in interpreting the new wave of spirituality
sweeping a troubled world.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message coming from an unusual ``Religion and
Media: 2000+'' conference held recently in the shadow of the
Vatican. It brought together cardinals, archbishops and other
religious leaders to mingle with publishers, writers and TV
producers.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of a surge in religious interest, speakers quoted
Gallup polls and increased sales of books on faith and
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``When 120 million Americans say that God is very important to
them, that should be all editors and publishers need to hear'' to
persuade them to give higher priority to religion coverage, said
Sandra Mims Rowe, editor of The Oregonian in Portland, Ore., and
immediate past president of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors.
</P>
<P>
   But she added: ``Covering this expansion of religion in the new
millennium will not be easy. If religion and spirituality will be
one of the defining issues in the next five years, we must be
prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Vatican, physical preparations for the coming millennium
are evident. St. Peter's Basilica and other major buildings are
covered with scaffolding as workers renovate them for a massive
influx of pilgrims in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are preparing for the 2,000th birthday of Jesus Christ _ a
pretty major event,'' said Archbishop John Patrick Foley, president
of the Vatican's Pontifical Council on Social Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium provided more questions than answers about
improving religion coverage and strengthening ties between religion
and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a beginning of dialogue, the beginning of
understanding each other better,'' said Tim McGuire, editor of the
Star-Tribune in Minneapolis, which has started a religion section
in its newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists who write about religion have a hard job, said
Cecile Holmes of Houston, president of the Religion Newswriters
Association, a national organization of religion reporters in the
secular media.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the millennium we find that religion is
both a powerful force of peace and justice, and also a relentless
weapon for war, rape, torture and genocide,'' said Holmes, religion
editor of the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of newspapers, ABC, NBC, CBS and CNN television
and National Public Radio, along with Christian and Jewish leaders,
heard good news and bad news about religion coverage in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Although many newspapers have increased religion coverage, and
one major network _ ABC _ has hired a religion specialist, the
American media still have much room for improvement, speakers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, most of us, do a profoundly inadequate job of covering
matters of faith,'' said keynote speaker David Lawrence Jr.,
chairman and publisher of the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   The religion beat, in most newsrooms, doesn't get the attention
shown to politics, education, business and the environment,
Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people in my business simply cannot see, before their
very eyes, just how big this story of faith is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Neary, religion correspondent for National Public Radio,
said that four years ago, much attention was given to the fact that
she was hired to cover religion and Peggy Wehmeyer was employed by
Peter Jennings as a religion specialist by ABC television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years later, we're still it,'' Neary said. ``We still are
the only ones covering religion on a national basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Register of Atlanta, vice president for special projects
for CNN, said his network is having a lively internal debate about
whether to hire a religion correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We covered the pope in Cuba extensively, but it was not
covered specifically as religion,'' he said. ``Some say we need a
religious correspondent to cover the issues well.''
</P>
<P>
   Register said the global scope of CNN makes it hard to hire a
religion specialist who would be qualified to cover world religions
such as Islam, Hinduism and Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We covered an important pilgrimage in India as well as the
pope's visit,'' said Register. And the network, for the first time,
covered the annual Muslim pilgrimage to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   Some conferees argued that without a religion specialist, news
organizations often miss the religious dimensions of major stories.
And it even happens, in some cases, when a news organization has a
religion reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, the Miami publisher, noted that when Pope John Paul II
visited Cuba, his newspaper covered the event extensively _ as a
political story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one of the best religion writers in the country in
April Witt,'' he said. ``But in our planning and brainstorming
about how to cover that story, her advice simply was not sought.
The editors managing the Cuban coverage thought this was a
political story, not a religion story. We think, obviously, it was
both.''
</P>
<P>
   John Dart, Los Angeles Times religion writer and co-author with
the Rev. Jimmy Allen of a much-quoted study, ``Bridging the Gap,''
said a way must be found to gather evidence to show news media
executives that excellent religion reporting can be to their
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Such information would include the popularity of new religion
sections at several major newspapers, and the fact that Time,
Newsweek and U.S. News and World Report say their cover stories on
religious topics are among the bestselling issues, Dart said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
