<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AKERS NOW SEEMS AT TOP OF HER GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite knee injuries and chronic fatigue syndrome in recent
years, Michelle Akers is still the leading scorer in history and a
protagonist for the U.S. women's national soccer team. The
32-year-old Akers, the only player who has been with the program
since it started 13 years ago, has been a leader in gaining
acceptance for women's sports.
</P>
<P>
   With Akers always in a key role, female soccer players in the
United States broke many barriers. Winning the first World Cup for
women and capturing the gold medal in the first women's Olympic
tournament in 1996 brought credibility to American soccer and
financial rewards to the players and to the U.S. Soccer Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people know how many sacrifices some of us are still
making to be part of this team,'' Akers said after practice the
other day while preparing for Saturday night's game against Denmark
in the Goodwill Games. ``But it's been a rewarding experience for
all of us, and it's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   There were those who thought that because of injuries and
chronic fatigue, Akers would retire after helping the Americans
capture the gold at the Atlanta Olympics. But Akers has been so
rejuvenated by a strict diet to combat her chronic fatigue syndrome
that she plans to play through the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not where I was a little younger,'' Akers said, ``but I'm
very close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers has scored 96 goals in 120 games with the national team.
Of her two well-known teammates who follow her on the scoring list,
Mia Hamm has 92 goals in 150 games and Kristine Lilly has 59 goals
in 156 games.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Akers twist and turn with the ball at her feet and
accelerate through the midfield and into the attack during practice
this week, one is convinced that she is at the top of her game, as
she was in 1991 when she led the Americans to the world
championship in the first Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   That World Cup was staged in China, and Akers led all goal
scorers in the tournament with 10. In 1995, she sustained a
concussion and a knee injury in the game against China and missed
part of that year's World Cup, which was staged in Sweden, where
the Americans finished third after losing to Norway in the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, which has been the Americans' main rival, will play
China in Saturday's other Goodwill Games match, and the winners
will meet for the gold medal Monday night. All games will be played
at Mitchel Field near the Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Norway is the only team to have defeated the United States this
year, a 4-1 victory in a tournament in Portugal. The Americans'
record this year going into Saturday night's game against Denmark
is 14-1-2. The loss was to Norway, and the ties were with China and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the American women in the World Cup and the
Olympics prompted FIFA, soccer's world governing body, to award the
1999 World Cup to the United States. U.S. organizers have already
sold 130,000 tickets for next year's tournament, more already than
the tournament attracted in Sweden in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this place will be full for the opening game,'' Akers
said about Giants Stadium, which will stage the opening ceremony
and a double-header that will include the American team. ``If you
told me in 1985 we would be playing before thousands of people, it
would have been beyond my wildest dreams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
