<HEADLINE>
BRIDE, GROOM WANT DONATIONS OF BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HOLLINGSWORTH  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kansas City area bride and groom are asking
their wedding guests for an unusual gift: a pint of blood.
</P>
<P>
   They've registered for the typical household items at an area
store. But when people ask about it, they say they also hope their
guests will open a vein at the Shawnee Mission American Red Cross
in honor of their Aug. 12 wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need stuff to live on, but the most important thing is
knowing we've made a difference,'' Loretta Stewart said Wednesday
afternoon before donating blood with her future father-in-law,
George Hoover, and brother-in-law Zac Hoover. ``We can always get
stuff, but that feeling, you can't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart added that she and her fiance, Jason Hoover, both enjoy
giving back to the community.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old couple got engaged in the spring. They've been
separated a lot since. Jason Hoover, who is in the Navy, has been
in Florida assisting the Red Cross with disaster relief. Stewart
kept busy with her studies in biology at Rockhurst College, where
they began dating, and with her volunteer work for the Multiple
Sclerosis Society.
</P>
<P>
   To help Jason Hoover feel a part of the blood donation outing,
his mother, Jonette Hoover, took pictures of the three.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, this is for Jason,'' Jonette Hoover told Stewart, ``so
look happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Grayson, an American Red Cross volunteer since 1961, said
they've never had anyone donate blood in honor of a wedding _ or
any other event like it, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They expect a lot out of the best man, but not normally a pint
of blood,'' Grayson teased 17-year-old Zac, who will be his
brother's best man. ``That's going all out to be in a wedding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
