<SLUG> BC-FORD-CLAYCOMO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD UNVEILS PLAN FOR NEW SPOT_UTILITY VEHICLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Ford Motor Co. already has started expanding
its Claycomo, Mo., plant to accommodate the launch of a new,
compact sport-utility vehicle in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With cranes hovering over the plant, several hundred Ford
workers and business and public officials gathered Wednesday to
hear the automaker officially unveil plans to enter the
fast-growing, compact sport-utility vehicle market.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and union officials even held a ceremonial pouring of
concrete on the plant floor, which will be expanded by 122,000
square feet in order to produce the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Jac Nasser, president of Ford's automotive operations, divulged
only a few details about the new vehicle, saying it will seat five
passengers, come in front- and four-wheel drive, offer side air
bags and run at more than 20 miles to the gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size of this vehicle will be smaller than any other
sport-utility vehicle we make,'' Nasser said. ``At the same time,
it will still have the same tough, Ford-brand essence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Claycomo plant, which also produces the top-selling F-series
pickup, beat out three other Ford facilities worldwide for the new
vehicle, according to Nasser. Ford is receiving a variety of tax
breaks in return for picking Claycomo.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's entry into the compact sport-utility niche will be a
first by a domestic automaker, said George Magliano, analyst with
the WEFA Group in New York. Toyota created the market with its
vehicles, including the RAV4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing a little bit of catch-up, but it's also a good
move,'' Magliano said. ``The SUV market has room for more growth.
The competition is heavy, but Ford's got an excellent track record
when it comes to light trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford has not named its new vehicle, dubbed the U204, nor issued
any price information. However, rival vehicles such as the Toyota
RAV4 had a 1998 base-price range of $15,858 to $18,128. The Honda
CR-V, another competitor, has a base-price range of $18,745 to
$20,645.
</P>
<P>
   Ford hopes the retooling and expansion of the 3.7
million-square-foot plant will be completed by early 2000. While
the new product may not lead to many new jobs, Nasser said some
work now performed at other locations might be transferred to
Claycomo.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Minor, Claycomo's plant manager, said it was too early to
tell how many additional jobs would be created. The plant now
employs about 5,200 workers, including about 4,800 hourly
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said Ford's decision to build the new sport-utility
vehicle at the Claycomo plant would create job security. He noted
the plant's recent strong showings in quality and productivity
studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of what we're really doing here is to ensure the
long-term viability and strength of this plant...well into the 21st
century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser would not comment on the size of Ford's investment to
build the new vehicle. However, area executives familiar with
Ford's plans said it was about $750 million. Earlier estimates had
pegged the investment at $100 million to $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Claycomo plant could be shut down for a short time in early
2000 before the new product's launch, Nasser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be longer than the two-week traditional summer
shutdown, but it will be as short as we can make it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new sport-utility vehicle will hit dealer showrooms in the
2001 model year and will replace the Ford Contour and Mercury
Mystique passenger cars. Those cars will continue to be built at
Ford's Cuautitlan plant near Mexico City. The passenger cars have
never lived up to the hype Ford created when it launched them four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said the Contour and Mystique sold nearly 200,000 units
last year in the United States, although sales never met Ford's
initial expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clearly in between two very, very popular products, the
Taurus and the Escort,'' Nasser said. ``The second thing is in the
U.S. market, there has been a marked shift to more versatile
vehicles, (like) sport-utility vehicles, trucks and pickups.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said Ford's $6 billion investment in developing the
Contour and Mystique continues to be the standard for building
other products, such as Claycomo's sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to reuse many of the parts and systems
developed for the Contour-Mystique in this new vehicle,'' he said.
``That's another reason we chose Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Top officials from the United Auto Workers union commended Ford
for working with the union in making product decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UAW wants to be a part of Ford's growth,'' said Ron
Gettelfinger, a UAW International vice president in charge of
Ford's national department.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Kline, president of UAW Local 249, said Ford's decision
was a testament to the work ethic of the Claycomo plant.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan said the state cooperated with Ford
by expanding an existing enterprise zone at the plant and offering
assistance with job training programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (enterprise zone) expansion will allow Ford tax relief on
its substantial new investment,'' Carnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   The state incentives included an income tax refund of $2 million
a year over five years if Ford proceeded with the Claycomo
expansion and renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said Missouri's tax relief packages were a factor in
putting the new vehicle in Claycomo, ``but we had similar offers
being made at many other locations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
