A1893 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-24 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 To get your way, use the power play  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Your position in an organization may give you
authority, but it is your ability to influence people that gives
you power, regardless of your position.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Charles E. Dwyer, a faculty member of the University
of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business, told managers from
Kansas City area companies at a recent Institute for Management
Studies seminar.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to write off overt or covert influence peddling as
nasty office politics. Do so at your peril, Dwyer advises.
</P>
<P>
   You will get what you want in the workplace, he says, if you _
day in and day out _ are the most persistent at getting others to
do what you want. And the genius is that you will get what you want
while convincing others that it's the best behavior or outcome for
them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make you squirm?
</P>
<P>
   It does me. It sounds so Machiavellian, so manipulative. And,
Dwyer admits, it is. There are costs associated with trying to get
others to behave in ways that suit your ends.
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, the costs will be worthwhile, provided you ``never
expect anyone to engage in a behavior that serves your values
unless you give that person adequate reason to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean in real life?
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you've been assigned to lead a team of co-workers on a
certain project. You're not their boss. You don't write their
performance evaluations. You don't dole out their raises. They have
no reason to do what you say unless you can convince them they
should.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one way:
</P>
<P>
   You say, ``John, I know that researching why the last rollout
failed is a thankless task, but if you will do this for me _ for
the group _ I will owe you big time. If you do this, I will make
sure the big guy knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, you follow through. When John does his part,
you write him a terrific thank-you note. He'll put it in his file
and his memory bank. You also write ``the big guy,'' John's boss,
and tell him what a great job John did. And you make sure John
knows you did it. You give him a copy of your letter to the boss.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the organization's needs, John came through. In
terms of your needs _ succeeding as the project leader _ John came
through. But Dwyer suspects that what John will remember most from
the project team experience is that you came through for him.
</P>
<P>
   That's power. He owes you, and you both know it.
</P>
<P>
   Still squirming? No doubt. But Dwyer says there's also no doubt
that it works. To make sure it works, he offers suggestions for
hammering home your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if John is obviously unenthused about his
assignment the first time you speak with him, you take the
responsibility and follow up immediately: ``I don't think I said
that very well. This is very important to me. Let me try it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   You must, of course, be perceived as sincere. The sincerity part
is what trips up some excellent manipulators. Co-workers get a clue
if they're used too often for personal gain.
</P>
<P>
   But the more you're good for your word, the more you return a
favor or provide a benefit for John _ and for as many others in the
organization as you need in your sphere of influence _ the more
they trust you. The more they trust you, the more influence they
grant you.
</P>
<P>
   Voila, Dwyer says. You have power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
