<SLUG> BC-FARM-AID-0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISASTERS TEST PROGRAM TO END FARM SUBSIDIES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Parched fields in Texas, drought-withered crops in
Florida, and tumbling grain prices have combined to severely test
one of the major accomplishments of the Republican congressional
revolution, the program to wean farmers off federal subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   For two relatively fat years since passage of the Freedom to
Farm Act in 1996, the new program plowed smoothly through the
agricultural belt, as wheat and other grain prices soared, and many
of the nation's farmers pulled down some of their best profits
ever. And to top that, they shared in more than $5 billion in
annual ``transition'' payments, the first in a seven-year phase-out
of farm price supports.
</P>
<P>
   Now in lean times that happen to come in a congressional
election year, officials in Washington are rushing to propose
emergency assistance and raising doubts about the new program. ``It
gave farmers more freedom to make their own planning decisions ...
But it did not have an adequate safety net,'' President Clinton
said on Thursday as he called on Congress to approve $500 million
in disaster aid already passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., has pledged quick action to
speed up the $5.5 billion for the next annual Freedom to Farm
payments so that they would be in the farmers' hands by early fall,
a plan also pushed by Senate Republicans, including Texas
Republican senators Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Democratic critics have failed to repeal the Freedom to
Farm Act and return to the old system, which paid farmers when
prices dropped and controlled how much acreage they planted.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom to Farm program is still ``overwhelmingly popular''
with American farmers, said Andy Fisher, spokesman for Senate
Agriculture Committee Chairman Richard Lugar, R-Ind. ``These are
regionally isolated problems,'' said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some of the latest disasters have rekindled old doubts
about the new program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it would be under attack as soon as prices dropped,''
said Bob Amstrup, farm director for the radio station KNOX in Grand
Forks, N. D., who farmed until a flood three years ago put him out
of business.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, many farmers received higher payments under
Freedom to Farm than under the old program, Amstrup said. ``Now
this year the old system would pay more,'' he said, because it
would have compensated farmers for the low prices after the Asian
economic crisis drastically reduced exports.
</P>
<P>
   The hard times raise questions about whether the politicians
will stick by their plans to cut off the subsidies altogether in
the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time the whole Freedom to Farm Act is being
tested, and members of Congress are falling all over themselves to
increase farm supports,'' said Steve Moore, vice president of the
Cato Institute, a Libertarian research group that has cheered the
effort to remove government from the farm economy. Now Moore has
concluded that ``it's unlikely we'll ever see these farm programs
entirely eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Avery, director of global food issues for the
conservative Hudson Institute, said that the disaster aid may be
only a temporary setback for taking government out of farming.
``But we've not yet taken the second step, eliminating trade
barriers'' to open up foreign markets, said Avery, who predicted a
huge market for American goods in the coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   However, he conceded, ``The American farmer isn't really
convinced about the free market.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Webster, a senior agriculture official in the Carter
administration and now editor of a farm newsletter, predicted that
the pressure on the new farm program has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have a lot more debate over this very
question,'' he said. ``The Freedom to Farm Act will come under
severe challenge'' as the presidential campaign begins in earnest,
with the first major test coming in the farm state of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
