<HEADER>
A1906 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TINDALL-INDICTMENT-KA     07-24 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINDALL-INDICTMENT-KAN </SLUG>
  
 KC politician indicted  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM JACKMAN, GROMER JEFFERS JR. and MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A federal grand jury Wednesday indicted
former Jackson County, Mo., Legislature Chairman James D. Tindall
on charges of bribery, embezzlement and tax evasion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The action wasn't unexpected. Last fall a federal jury convicted
public relations consultant Elbert L. Anderson of paying $10,000 in
bribes to Tindall. On Wednesday Anderson testified before a grand
jury about his dealings with Tindall.
</P>
<P>
   Tindall has sworn under oath that he neither asked for nor took
bribes. During Anderson's trial, he testified that ``I've never
done anything like that. Would never think or dream of doing
anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the charges Wednesday involved allegations that Tindall, a
bishop in the Metropolitan Spiritual Churches of Christ, stole more
than $14,700 from a church-affiliated social services agency he
helped create in 1977. The indictment alleges Tindall took checks
intended as rent payments and deposited them into accounts he
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tindall is accused of filing false tax returns that
underreport his income for the years 1992 to 1995. The indictment
states Tindall's true income each year was ``substantially in
excess of the amount stated'' on each tax return, although the
amount wasn't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Tindall, 56, is expected to make his first court appearance
Monday. If convicted, he faces a maximum 10-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr. said,
``When you have this type of public corruption, it damages the
integrity of government in general and weakens the confidence
people have in government.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Tindall was one of the most formidable political
presences in Kansas City. He had been a member of the Jackson
County Legislature for 14 years and its chairman from 1991 to 1996,
when he suddenly retired from politics.
</P>
<P>
   Tindall also was president of Freedom Inc., an influential
inner-city political club.
</P>
<P>
   But in September 1996, as FBI subpoenas began circulating
through the Jackson County courthouse, Tindall unexpectedly
resigned from the Legislature. A pastor of his own church in Kansas
City, Tindall said his archbishop was ordering him to step down to
spend more time on his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   As the federal corruption probe snared then-Kansas City
Councilwoman D. Jeanne Robinson, a friend of Tindall's, and
evidence arose that Robinson had sent money to a Tindall company,
Tindall maintained his innocence. Robinson pleaded guilty to
defrauding her employer, Marion Merrell Dow, in September 1996, and
agreed to cooperate with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson revealed to prosecutors and FBI agents that she had
taken bribes from Anderson and that she'd helped Anderson pay
bribes to Tindall.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, a grand jury indicted Anderson on charges of
bribing both Robinson and Tindall. Tindall wasn't charged, though
he was repeatedly named throughout the indictment as ``the chairman
of the Jackson County Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson took his case to trial, but three key government
witnesses _ Robinson, Robinson's assistant Jane Lacy, and
Anderson's top assistant Michelle Lathan _ all told of Anderson's
cash payments to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   In Tindall's case, Jackson County had agreed in 1995 to provide
$40,000 to Black Expo USA, a trade show staged by Anderson. The
county paid $30,000 before the show and agreed to pay $10,000 more
after Black Expo filed an accounting report.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson testified, and the indictment alleges, that in late
November or early December 1995, Tindall knew that the $10,000
payment still hadn't been made. The indictment contends Tindall
called Robinson twice, ``urging her to contact Elbert Anderson
immediately,'' because ``Tindall wanted this money for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Robinson testified, Tindall offered to increase
Black Expo's funding in 1996 to $50,000. The indictment offers new
information that Robinson and Anderson both met and spoke on the
phone about Anderson's willingness to pay Tindall.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Madden, the Jackson County auditor, testified that
in December 1995, Tindall asked him specifically to speed up the
payment of Black Expo's remaining $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson testified, the indictment alleges, that Anderson then
gave her $5,000 cash on two occasions to be passed to Tindall.
Robinson said she and Tindall used the first $5,000 for a gambling
spree in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   On the witness stand last fall, Anderson said he never paid a
bribe to Tindall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard he wanted a bribe,'' Anderson said. ``Nobody has
ever asked me for anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tindall followed, saying he never requested any money to support
Black Expo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done it,'' Tindall said.
</P>
<P>
   Tindall also denied making a special request to the county
auditor for Black Expo's check. ``I wouldn't, as a legislator, know
how they would get checks,'' Tindall testified. ``I wouldn't have
any idea whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors later said they found Tindall's testimony hard to
believe, based on his lengthy political experience.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1977, according to its articles of incorporation, Tindall
was one of the founders of Metropolitan Sociological Resources
Corp. Located next to Tindall's church, the nonprofit company
distributed money for utility and food assistance projects and held
computer education programs.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 registration report filed with Missouri lists Tindall's
brother, Wallace Tindall, as the president and another brother,
Monta Tindall, as a director. Tindall is not listed as an officer
or director. The corporation's purpose is stated as: ``To serve
those that need.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 through 1996, the company received roughly $200,000
from Kansas City. Although nearly $21,000 came from the city's
general fund, most of the money was from federal Community
Development Block Grants administered by the city.
</P>
<P>
   The company operated in a building owned by Tindall's
congregation, and prosecutor Hill said Metropolitan Sociological
paid rent to Tindall's church next door.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges that in 1994, Tindall deposited 13 checks
from Metropolitan Sociological that had been written as rent
payments to the church. The checks totaled $8,675.
</P>
<P>
   Tindall is accused of embezzling 10 checks totaling $6,107 that
were intended for rent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said ``there was a relationship'' between the agency and
Tindall's church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reverend Tindall used that working relationship to access
those accounts,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Sociological later presented copies of the checks
to the city to be reimbursed for its rent payments, which are
typically recoverable under federal grant guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the checks appeared to be legitimate rent
payments and did not raise red flags.
</P>
<P>
   The state dissolved Metropolitan Sociological in December 1997
when it failed to file its annual corporate report.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities subpoenaed city records on the corporation
in September 1996, after Robinson's guilty plea. Tindall resigned
from politics the next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
