<HEADER>
A1909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAL-SAVINGS-$ADV2     07-24 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-SAVINGS-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL SAVINGS ACCOUNTS ENTER DEBATE OVER MANAGED CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Republican-led House passed a bill last
week to regulate managed care plans, it performed reconstructive
surgery on a little understood but highly controversial program
called medical savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Initially approved by Congress in 1996 as a pilot project,
medical savings accounts (MSAs) offer tax deductions as incentives
to help individuals save for out-of-pocket expenses incurred when
they purchase high-deductible medical insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Between January 1997, when the accounts first became available,
and June of that year, 22,051 MSAs were opened, according to
Internal Revenue Service figures, the latest available. By
unofficial estimates, as many as 100,000 such accounts are now
operating.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers purchase them as companions to health insurance
policies with deductibles that are no lower than $1,500 for
individuals and $3,000 for families. For the most part, these
insurance policies are designed to guard against catastrophic
illness or injury.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to MSAs are fully tax deductible. Withdrawals are
used to meet medical expenses under the deductible. Once expenses
rise above the deductible, the insurance policy picks up most or
all health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican measure would expand MSAs by dropping limitations
built into the 1996 pilot program. The Senate could take up its
version of the managed care measure, which includes MSAs, as early
as this week.
</P>
<P>
   MSA advocates say the accounts would ease increasing concern
that managed care prevents patients from obtaining the care they
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical savings accounts are an antidote for people tired of
medical gatekeepers and hospitals that throw people out early,''
said Jack Strayer, head of the Washington office of the National
Center for Policy Analysis, a conservative Dallas-based think tank
that formulated the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a medical savings account, you can stay in the
hospital as long as you need to, and decisions are made by your
doctor and you, not someone at a switchboard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have rejected the MSA concept. They and their
supporters _ particularly organized labor _ consider it a sop to
the healthy and wealthy at the expense of the poor and the
unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see them as savings accounts that would afford the rich an
opportunity to squirrel money away tax free,'' said Gerald McEntee,
president of the 1.3-million American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees (AFSCME). ``There's not too many run
of-the-mill middle-class people who can afford that kind of a
deductible. It's a boondoggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the House measure passed Friday, the White House
condemned the MSA expansion in it as one of several ``poison
pills'' that would derail any chance of legislative compromise. An
exodus of healthier and wealthier people into medical savings
accounts would drive up the cost of conventional, low-deductible
insurance and managed care for those poorer and sicker, the White
House said.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress created the MSA pilot project two years ago, it
said money in the accounts could be invested and dollars not spent
on medical care could be carried over to the following year.
</P>
<P>
   But it said withdrawals for non-medical purposes would subject
account holders to a 15 percent penalty. Eligibility during the
pilot period was limited to the self-employed and those in
companies with 50 or fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   Employees could buy them on their own or employers could fund
them. But no matched employee-employer contribution was permitted.
Also, yearly contributions were limited to 65 percent of the
deductible for individuals and 75 percent for families.
</P>
<P>
   Both House and Senate GOP bills would end all these
restrictions. Nonmedical withdrawals would be subject to normal
taxation, but not the 15 percent penalty. And the deductible floors
would be lowered to $1,000 for individuals and $2,000 for families.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and their supporters say MSAs are an ingenious way
to get around limits on doctor choice and specialist care, which
are targets of numerous complaints about managed care. And,
supporters say, MSAs do it without federal mandates and lawsuits
against health plans, which the Democrats favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical savings account is a vehicle that permits the
aggregate cost of medical care to be controlled just as effectively
as managed care, but without the undesirable matter of bureaucrats
saying no,'' said J. Patrick Rooney, chairman emeritus of Golden
Rule Insurance Co. in Indianapolis, a leading advocate of the
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney himself has become a lightening rod in the debate because
of Golden Rule's financial support of Republicans. Rooney and
Golden Rule executives gave $757,875 to the Republican Party
between 1991 and 1997, according to a review of Federal Election
Commission documents by Common Cause, the campaign finance
watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Rooney acknowledged contributing $49,000 to a failed
ballot initiative in California that would have required unions to
get written consent from members before spending dues money on
political candidates and issues.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1996 congressional compromise, Golden Rule has sold
31,522 medical savings accounts, according to company spokeswoman
Amanda Newlin.
</P>
<P>
   Medical savings accounts are ``geared to make Pat Rooney more
rich than he is today,'' said AFSCME's McEntee.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney denied a monetary motivation. ``If I were driven by
money, our best interest would have been to go the managed care
route'' instead of emphasizing medical savings accounts, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
