<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TALKS MAY BE STALLED UNTIL AUTUMN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Despite visits by three senior Israeli officials to
Yasser Arafat and an unusual flurry of political activity in the
last week, the Sabbath siren sounded this evening with no tangible
movement on the Israeli-Palestinian front and growing fears that it
could stay that way till fall.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, the Palestinian leader, received Public Security
Minister Avigdor Kahalani in Ramallah on Friday with smiles and
promises of more such meetings. But Palestinians and Kahalani
himself emphasized that the Israeli was not a negotiator and had
not gone there bearing a message from Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The only official meetings, between Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai and the senior Palestinian negotiator, Mahmoud Abbas,
began on Sunday and ended on Wednesday with no breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai then appealed to the Americans to return and help
break the logjam. But after eight months of fruitless efforts to
extract a decision from Netanyahu, Washington showed no eagerness
to rush back to assist the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   By general consent, that leaves only one week to find a way to
resume negotiations before the Israeli Parliament's summer recess,
followed by a series of Jewish holidays and municipal elections,
imposes new restraints on talks for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in this exercise for the past eight months, this
game in which Netanyahu takes us for a ride,'' said Saeb Erekat,
one of the Palestinian negotiators. ``First the Knesset recess,
then municipal elections, then the Americans are busy with
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key point now is that this government of Netanyahu
either cannot take the decision or does not want to take the
decision. Either way they want a pretext for a lack of decision by
this process of meetings, envoys, talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week Netanyahu gave the impression of a man
seriously intent on achieving an agreement. He refrained from
blaming the Palestinian Authority for a botched terror attack in
Jerusalem on Sunday, he avoided his usual litanies of accusations
against the Palestinians and he told reporters that he was ready to
meet Arafat round the clock to strike a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Kahalani's visit to Arafat was apparently linked to the threat
by his small, centrist party, the Third Way, to quit Netanyahu's
coalition unless it agreed to make the withdrawal in the West Bank
that the United States has sought as a condition for resuming
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   After 90 minutes of talks, Kahalani and Arafat emerged smiling
and promising to meet again. That appeared to be enough for
Kahalani to call off his threat of pulling out of the government.
``This week it sounds to me we are going to close the gap, and I
don't think there is a reason to make this kind of decision,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinian officials said nothing substantive had changed
through this meeting, nor in one on Thursday between Arafat and
Netanyahu's coalition chairman, Meir Sheetrit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Arafat treated Sheetrit to lunch and a promise that he would
seriously consider the Israeli's suggestion that the Palestinian
leader meet directly with Netanyahu. Sheetrit attributed what he
perceived as his success to ``Sheetrit charm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes one's image makes all the difference,'' he told
reporters. ``That's one of the prime minister's problems _ his
image in the Palestinians' eyes, which I think is wrong _ regarding
his desire for peace. The ball is now in Arafat's court.''
</P>
<P>
   However charmed he might have been by Sheetrit or Kahalani,
Arafat did not cancel his plan to travel early next week to
Austria, which is assuming the rotating leadership of the European
Union. The trip only served to further cool expectations of a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   In public at least, Arafat's consistent position before and
after all the meetings has been that he is awaiting Netanyahu's
reply to the U.S. proposal, which calls on Israel to withdraw from
a further 13 percent of the West Bank. It also calls on the
Palestinians to undertake a concrete set of measures against
terrorism and to complete the revision of the Palestinian charter,
which originally called for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has said he accepts the U.S. proposals. He has also
declared that he will proclaim a Palestinian state on May 4, 1999,
the date by which the Oslo agreements were to have produced a final
settlement, unless an agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   On the Israeli side, intensive efforts by the United States,
including threats by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, have
failed to secure a concrete decision from Netanyahu. The issue of a
further withdrawal has generated constant threats from within his
coalition, with the right wing fiercely opposing a full 13 percent
and centrists like the Third Way and Mordechai insisting that
Netanyahu agree.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai's meeting on Sunday with Abbas, who is better known as
Abu Mazen, came about after the United States reportedly declared
it had exhausted its efforts, and believed that the two sides had
to overcome the final hurdles themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai reportedly came to the Palestinians with a ``10 plus
3'' proposal under which Israel would cede control over another 10
percent of the West Bank, while another 3 percent, in areas near
Jewish settlements, would be turned into a ``nature preserve,''
where the Palestinians could not build and Israel would have
security control. Mordechai also reportedly softened Israeli
demands that the Palestinians should convene the full 500-member
Palestinian National Council, the parliament of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, to adopt a new charter.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians listened to the ideas, but reiterated that they
were awaiting Israel's reply to the full U.S. proposal. They said
the ``nature preserve'' proposal effectively kept the land in full
Israeli control, as it is now, under what is termed ``Area C'' in
the Oslo agreements. Area A is fully under Palestinian control, and
Area B is under joint control.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to me without specific percentages, without maps,
saying that they intended to maintain overall security, including
public order, and a veto on planning and zoning,'' Erekat said. ``I
said I will answer like in the American television show,
`Jeopardy': `What is Area C?' What they really offered is Area C.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's aides told reporters that Arafat was playing his
usual 11th-hour stalling game to extract more concessions, and that
a breakthrough really was imminent and possible.
</P>
<P>
   But after so many months of delays, it was not only Erekat who
was not convinced. ``We've been through this too many times
before,'' Joseph Alpher, director of the Israel office of the
American Jewish Committee, was quoted as saying. ``It's too early
to conclude that this is a truly serious attempt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
