<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-SECURITY-072     07-24 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-SECURITY-0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SECURITY IN CAPITOL TIGHT, WELL-MANNED
 &HT;    With CAPITOL-SHOOTING.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Getting into the Capitol with a gun is extremely
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The public is only allowed into the Capitol through a few
entrances and everyone _ except members of the House and Senate _
must pass through metal detectors similar to those found at
airports. Large bags must be placed on an X-ray machine that shows
a video of their contents.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members and journalists are allowed in some entrances
barred to the public, but they still must pass through a metal
detector and have their bags searched by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Most tourists enter the Capitol through the double-doors on the
east side in the center of the building which lead into the massive
rotunda. There are two banks of metal detectors and X-ray machines
which must be navigated. This is apparently where the suspect
entered the Capitol, setting off the detectors.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Hill is a large sprawling complex which consists not
only of the dome-capped Capitol but also three enormous office
buildings on the House side and another three on the Senate side.
The office buildings are connected to the Capitol through
underground tunnels. There are metal detectors and X-ray machines
at the entrances to the tunnels which are manned by uniform police.
</P>
<P>
   Public entrances to the House and Senate office buildings also
are limited and have metal detectors. Usually there are one or two
uniformed Capitol police officers at each entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza on the east front of the Capitol has been sealed to
traffic since a bomb went off on the Senate side in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Capitol, security is tight.
</P>
<P>
   Uniformed police officers are to be found almost everywhere,
particularly on the second and third floors where the House and
Senate chambers are located. Plain-clothed officers roam the
corridors and are stationed near the offices of congressional
leaders, including Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists are free to roam through the Rotunda on the second
floor and the crypt _ the circular room below the rotunda _ on the
first floor, where there are numerous displays of Capitol history.
</P>
<P>
   On the first floor, where the shooting occurred, tourists can
walk down a central corridor lined with statues toward the south,
or House side, of the building. DeLay's office is on that corridor.
They also can walk down a similar corridor toward the north, or
Senate side, and eat in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
