<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NBC-LITTLEFIELD-96     07-24 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-LITTLEFIELD-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
 
NBC PLAYS IT SAFE WHILE THE WILY fOX TAKES ALL THE RISKS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Warren Littlefield, master kidder and actor
wannabe, was introduced the other day as the network president most
likely to find positives in the most dire of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a roomful of critics ready to pounce on NBC's
proliferation of newsmagazines and its breezy dismissal of cable
competitors, Littlefield cued up a video to comically drill holes
into the premise that after ``Seinfeld's'' departure, he was this
close to stepping in front of a moving train.
</P>
<P>
   On the video, a collapsed Littlefield is wheeled into, yep,
``ER,'' where the drama's core players revive him by playing the
show's theme music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't go anywhere!'' he tells each cast member, getting
promises from everyone except the departing George Clooney, who
nervously quips, ``Uh, hmm, gotta make a phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   The video ends with Littlefield strutting through the ER to the
tune of the Bee Gees' ``Staying Alive.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK _ you had to be there. But Littlefield wants to make the
point that America's most-watched entertainment network, the one
that still commands enormous respect on Thursday nights, is doing
fine.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer holes to fill than its competitors and ``Frasier''
taking over ``Seinfeld's'' real estate, Littlefield again gets to
watch the network ships sink from the safe, snug confines of a
lifeboat.
</P>
<P>
   And safe is the operative word here. What's distressing about
the new series NBC showcased for critics at this semiannual
gathering is how bland and shielded they are _ in premise or
execution or both. It's as if this is a championship team playing
``not'' to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the return of ``Married ... With
Children's'' Christina Appelgate, but there's nothing distinctive
about her sitcom, ``Jesse,'' in which she plays a harried waitress
who wants to be a nurse taking care of a bunch of clueless guys _ a
father, brother and son. Older and looking more sophisticated,
Appelgate acknowledged that she has no idea whether the audience
will accept her ``with clothes on.''
</P>
<P>
   On that note, Bo Derek resurfaced, too, arriving on the NBC
press stage along with a crew of incredibly good-looking young men
to discuss ``Wind on Water,'' a poorly acted drama about ``a large
youthful cast seeking love and adventure in the world of extreme
sports competition.'' The pilot episode was just as vague.
</P>
<P>
   The series is produced by Zalman King, he of ``Wild Orchid'' and
``Red Shoe Diaries,'' projects in which cinematic style and nudity
work as one. Since the series, called a family drama, is scheduled
to air at 7 p.m. on Saturdays, the best King could do was some
terrific slow-mo water scenes (the young bods are always surfing)
and Derek in a bathing suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's still got it,'' King observes, at least for her age,
which was exposed when one of her young co-stars, Brian Gross, said
he had no idea who Derek was, ``but my dad and my grandpa sure
did.'' With that compliment, Derek popped the poor guy upside the
back of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Even NBC's most controversial series is controversial for what
it ``won't do.'' ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is an energetic, well-crafted
sitcom about a woman who'd have the perfect man if only she could
sleep with him. He's gay, a fact revealed in the pilot's first
scene when the two are seen simultaneously salivating over George
Clooney.
</P>
<P>
   Friends since college, the two _ played by Debra Messing and
Eric McCormack _ are so close it's almost annoying. Funny, smart
and devoid of the usual gay stereotypes (wisely, Will is the
understated gay guy and his friend is the overstated,
Broadway-show-tunes-loving gay guy), ``Will &AMP; Grace'' will
inevitably face the issue of dating and, dare we say, kissing. And
you thought a lesbian's libido was difficult terrain in ``Ellen.''
</P>
<P>
   James Burrows, the show's executive producer, best known for
``Cheers,'' dug himself a hole early by insisting that they weren't
interested in ``politicizing'' the show by giving Will a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Questioners, led mostly by angry, offended gay and lesbian
critics, ripped into his statements mercilessly, asking, ``What's
inherently political about two gay men having a sex life?''
</P>
<P>
   Burrows stumbled nervously through the answer, finally saying,
``I think to go to that area takes away from the essence of the
show.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormack, a product of Canadian theater, isn't gay, so brace
for the inevitable charges that this is proof of television's
discomfort in casting gays in gay roles. Muddling the proceedings
was the presence of Max Mutchnick. One of the few openly gay
writer/producers in Hollywood, Mutchnick sounded much like the
straight producers.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
