<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1943 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NBC-LITTLEFIELD-2n     07-24 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-LITTLEFIELD-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: straight producers. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The honest truth,'' he said, ``we're not hiding from anything.
I feel like you guys want us to talk about something that hasn't
come up yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, NBC is also taking hits over Kyle Secor's character on
``Homicide: Life on the Streets,'' whose story arc last season
suggested bisexuality. While picking up ``Homicide's'' Television
Critics Award for best drama series, Tom Fontana spoke glowingly
about Littlefield, saying he was the reason the ratings-challenged
drama has stayed on the air.
</P>
<P>
   But the next day, while introducing new ``Homicide'' cast
members Michael Michele and Giancarlo Esposito, Fontana criticized
NBC for its skittishness on that story line.
</P>
<P>
   When Littlefield showed up for his semiannual State of NBC
address just a couple hours later, he told reporters, ``I wasn't
aware that I was uncomfortable with Kyle Secor's sexual ambiguity.
The question that we did ask was, how long are you going to keep
this ambiguous? Is there going to be a declaration one way or the
other?''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Littlefield listed the TV remote as NBC's most feared
enemy, and suggested that the network needs to stay ahead by not
taking silly risks. This steamed Fox's Entertainment Group
President Peter Roth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think holding the line _ it's about as anathema to the Fox
philosophy as you can possibly imagine,'' Roth said. ``I have no
intention, ever, of being satisfied with holding the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Fox have such a luxury. Roth backed up his tough words
with the introduction of some, well, intriguing fare. In
``Brimstone,'' Peter Horton is Ezekiel Stone, a dead former cop
dispatched by the devil to find 113 of his disciples who escaped.
``Costello'' features standup comic Sue Costelloas a bartender
constantly at odds with her traditional Irish Catholic family and
friends. Her favorite word in the pilot can't be printed here,
which illustrates its approach.
</P>
<P>
   Diane English's ``Living in Captivity,'' a comedy about life in
the suburbs, features an Archie Bunker-type bigot (Lenny Venito),
although English would prefer the description, ``ignorant. He has
never even known a African-American, let alone an Asian or
Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't appear till midseason, but the best of the Fox lot
might again be an animated series. ``The PJ's'' is clay animation
and takes a satirical look at life in a big-city housing project.
The pedigree is impressive: Eddie Murphy created the series; Ron
Howard and Brian Grazer are producers. Judging from a four-minute
clip, it has the potential to be downright hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Groening, creator of ``The Simpsons,'' dropped by to
discuss his developing half-hour series, ``Futurama,'' which is set
1,000 years from now and will bring his unique and satirical humor
to ``this unconventional family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't do this anywhere but on Fox,'' Groening said.
``The other networks could never look outside their box and do this
sort of thing. And you'd think that would have changed with ``The
Simpsons.'' They're innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly are. The other night, Fox rented the hotel's
large, indoor garage and turned it into a '70s disco hall, filled
with lava lamps, smile buttons, 8-tracks and beanbag chairs. Roth
showed up at the party dressed in bell-bottom bluejeans and
platform shoes, as did the cast of ``That '70s Show,'' a fall
sitcom set in the 1970s and featuring young, promising unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing to '70s hits until late in the evening, a good time was
had by all, except perhaps The Monkees' Mickey Dolenz, who was
brought in to give nostalgic resonance to the proceedings. In a
graying ponytail and black suit, he strolled around kind of
aimlessly, mostly alone, with people pointing to him and saying,
``That's what's-his-name ...''
</P>
<P>
   Roth had better hope his series isn't treated like Dolenz, a
'70s relic no one remembers _ or cares about.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
