<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISAS-WORKERS-BOS &LR;      07-24 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISAS-WORKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK BRIGHTENS FOR INCREASE IN FOREIGN WORKER QUOTAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Prospects for a plan to boost the number of
skilled foreign workers admitted to the United States improved
sharply Friday, after lawmakers reached an agreement on measures
aimed at protecting American workers from layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by Congress, the annual quota of foreigners admitted
on so-called H-1B visas would rise to 115,000 by the year 2001, up
from 65,000 today. The agreement would also add 20,000 to this
year's quota, which had been filled in May, leaving employers with
no available visas until the next federal fiscal year begins in
October.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech firms say a higher quota of foreign workers is needed
because the booming economy has left thousands of US computer jobs
vacant. H-1B visas are good for six years and are used to fill a
variety of skilled jobs, from computer programmer to nurse to
fashion model.
</P>
<P>
   But employee groups and labor unions quickly criticized the
congressional compromise, saying it would allow employers to use
low-cost foreign labor instead of raising wages to attract American
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is a sell-out of American college graduates,''
said Jack Golodner, president of the AFL-CIO Department of
Professional Employees, which represents 4 million professional,
technical and administrative workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary question is still whether there really is a
shortage of skilled workers, and many measures say there is not,''
said Steven Camarota of the Center for Immigration Studies in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, a higher quota for visas was supported by EMC
Corp., Cognex Inc. and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal reached Friday, certain employers who want to use
H-1B labor would have to certify that they have not laid off an
American worker before hiring a foreigner, and that they tried to
recruit Americans before hiring foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   A House committee had voted that all employers should have to
sign those certifications, but the compromise says the rule applies
only to ``heavy users'' of the visas. Heavy users are likely to be
defined as employers who hire H-1B labor as 15 percent or more of
their work forces, but that could change as final language is
drafted, said an aide to Representative Lamar Smith (R-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   The 15 percent rule appears aimed at so-called ``job-shoppers,''
or businesses that bring in foreign labor only to hire the workers
out to other employers. ``That's where the problems have been,''
said Allen Kay, the Smith aide. ``The Intels and Microsofts -- you
rarely see any signficant complaint against them, and there is no
evidence of serious problems with their use of H-1B visas. So the
safeguard is focused where the problem is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This both protects American workers while raising the cap for
visas,'' said Sandy Boyd of the National Association of
Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But Golodner of the AFL-CIO complained that big companies, with
thousands of employees, would never fall under the certification
requirement because they could hire hundreds of H-1B workers
without reaching the 15 percent mark. ``Big employers are off the
hook,'' he said. The protections for US workers ``are cosmetic, but
nothing more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise also says that complaints about a company laying
off Americans to hire H-1B workers would be investigated by a
three-member arbitration panel selected by the parties involved.
</P>
<P>
   Labor groups criticized this provision as ineffective, while
employer groups applauded it. Traditionally, enforcement of the
H-1B program has been handled by the Department of Labor, but
employer groups feared more federal intervention in their hiring
practices.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the arbitration panels would have money or
authority to actively investigate complaints. Kay, of Smith's
office, said details of the arbitration rules had not yet been
drafted.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise would have to be approved by the House and
Senate. The Senate has already voted to boost the number of visas,
but its bill included no certification requirements for employers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton had threatened to veto any increase in H-1B
visas unless it included protections for American workers and a
worker-training component. Kay said a worker-training plan would be
part of the final bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
