<HEADER>
A1959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPTER&AMP;VERSE-TEX     07-24 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Challenge of Fundamentalism''
</P>
<P>
   By Bassam Tibi
</P>
<P>
   University of California Press, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bully Pulpit''
</P>
<P>
   By James Guth, John Green, Corwin Smidt, Lyman Kellstedt and
Margaret Poloma
</P>
<P>
   University Press of Kansas, $19.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Religion and politics shouldn't mix, some would say, but a
sizable chunk of humanity has never bought into that. And as long
as that remains true, scholars will have something to write about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious fundamentalisms couple a premodern sensibility with
an instrumental exploitation of modernity (for example, the
employment of modern arms and technologies),'' writes professor
Bassam Tibi of the University of Gottingen, ``and it is for this
reason that I consider the politicization of religion as the
greatest challenge to cultural modernity and the gravest threat to
world stability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Challenge of Fundamentalism'' is an academic critique of
politicized Islam. Tibi asserts that those who seek an ``Islamic
order'' to replace secular, Western-style nation-states have
presented no concrete outline of their ideal government; that the
Islamic world is too culturally fragmented to sustain it anyway;
and that such radicals can nevertheless cause the world
considerable trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Tibi is a self-described ``liberal Muslim,'' but he does not
focus on theology. He does, however, distinguish between Islam as a
faith and the religio-political ideology he criticizes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, dismiss any suspicions of disparaging wordplay in the
title of ``The Bully Pulpit.'' This study by James Guth, John
Green, Corwin Smidt, Lyman Kellstedt and Margaret Poloma is a
scrupulously neutral assessment of the politics of Protestant
clergy.
</P>
<P>
   The five collegiate scholars present a detailed analysis of the
views and actions of leaders in four evangelical denominations (the
Assemblies of God, the Southern Baptist Convention, the Evangelical
Covenant Church and the Christian Reformed Church) and four
mainline groups (the Reformed Church in America, the United
Methodist Church, the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) and the
Disciples of Christ). The book considers what issues clergy see as
important, how they vote, how they view political activism, how
they are likely to be active, and how various theological and
political factors intertwine.
</P>
<P>
   The authors find a distinct split between ``orthodox'' clergy,
who tend toward political conservatism and the Republican Party,
and ``modernist'' religious leaders, who tend toward liberalism and
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bully Pulpit'' outlines its statistical findings in some
detail, but it still remains accessible to the lay reader.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
