</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAD-SOAPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GH' STAR FINDS PARADISE IN THE VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Brad Maule's a happy guy.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing well-broken-in jeans and a t-shirt, perched on the
stucco ledge around the rear balcony of his Sherman Oaks home
overlooking a rain-forest-like back yard, he's strumming his guitar
and singing one of the tunes he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby, I would stay here all night long
</P>
<P>
   Just to see the moonlight on your face.
</P>
<P>
   Something tells me it's time to walk away
</P>
<P>
   And common sense tells me there's a price to pay.
</P>
<P>
   But my heart only knows what it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my secret place,'' explains the star of ABC's
``General Hospital.'' ``I come here to work on my music. I can be
quiet and sit. And'' _ he grinned _ ``if I lock the door, nobody
can find me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Maule's a hermit. In his neighborhood, he's just the
guy next door. And to his wife and kids, he's Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   But to the nearly 4.5 million ``GH'' viewers, he's crazed,
baby-kidnapping neurosurgeon Dr. Tony Jones, a character light
years away from the good ol' Texas fella who finds happiness in a
song, a splash in the pool and a cuddle with the kids and the
family's small herd of cats and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Maule, wife Laverne and their kids live in a renovated 1920s
home filled with the actor's own paintings, eclectic Mexican and
religious pieces, and a back yard with a pool and a fish pond.
</P>
<P>
   His real life is far different from life on the ``GH'' set,
where Tony Jones has morphed over the past year from the loyal
husband and dedicated doctor he's been since 1983 to a dangerous
man just this side of insanity, the result of his daughter's death
and his wife's infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   It's a turnaround the laid-back Maule relishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a ball on the show,'' he said with a grin. ``I had
to play that good guy so long, it's great to play something else.
I'm not the old, dull Tony anymore. That Tony's gone _ probably
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   His character may live life on the edge, but Maule's rock-solid,
retreating each day after work to a home that looks like any other
on a tree-lined street off Ventura Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Step inside, and it's like being inside an adobe art gallery,
with heavy Mission-style furniture, pierced-tin picture frames,
clay religious figures and primitive art. Weather-beaten leather
chaps Maule's father once wore when herding cattle hang on the
wall, a piece of 3-D western art.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee table _ a piece of heavy glass balanced on two giant
concrete fish sculptures _ is covered with family photos. An
old-fashioned ladies' ``fainting couch'' has been reupholstered in
a western-themed print. The dining-room table was once a heavy
wooden door, with legs added. What looks like a church pew along
one wall is a stripped-down reject from the ABC lot, where it had
been covered with ugly '60s naugahyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never pay retail,'' Maule advised with a grin, running a hand
over the grain in the pew's wood. ``Go to a garage sale. You get
the best stuff, and you don't have to spend an arm and a leg.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maule house is filled with children's laughter, the ringing
of phones, skittering cats and dirty-footed dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children were babies when we moved in here, so they've got
a whole street full of `grandparents','' Maule said. ``We love it
here. We've got great restaurants two blocks away, a great hiking
trail two blocks away. It's a great neighborhood. If you're leaving
town, you tell your neighbors, and they'll put your garbage out and
pick up your mail.''
</P>
<P>
   His kids _ daughter Lily, 10; son Hunter, 11; and Laverne's son
Michael, 19, who just finished his freshman year at the University
of North Carolina _ are unimpressed with what Dad does for a
living. They only know they like to hit him up for cash regularly
and splash with him in the backyard pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think acting is a silly job,'' he said. ``They want to be
jocks. They were born with me doing what I'm doing, so for them,
it's not that weird.''
</P>
<P>
   When the musical muse calls, Maule migrates to the tiny backyard
balcony, where he works on his second career: singing and
songwriting. He's produced a video and two albums of
country-western songs and is working on a third CD; he's also a
featured performer on a ``GH'' album released earlier this year,
singing ``My Heart Only Knows What It Feels'' and an upbeat
country-western tune, ``There Ain't Nothin' Wrong With Me That You
Can't Fix.'' He's sung both songs on ``GH.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the comma-shaped pool, the Maule back yard holds a tiny
guesthouse that doubles as a playhouse for the kids, and the garden
is filled with trees that yield bananas, olives and plums _ plus a
rare coral tree _ that are legacies of silent-film actor Gino
Carrato, who built the home. The trees, plus a stand of bamboo that
keeps spreading in spite of efforts to curb it, provide a curtain
of privacy from neighboring homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have such a good time here, so much fun,'' Maule said. ``We
just like to be together.''
</P>
<P>
   Family has always been important to Maule, whose parents _
married for 56 years _ still live on the family farm near a wide
spot in the road called Hobbs, Texas (pop. 36).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great sense of belonging. My roots are like an old
mesquite tree; they go down and down and down,'' he said. ``Every
song I write goes back to there.''
</P>
<P>
   He _ and a four-years-older brother who died at 17 of a heart
defect _ were raised doing chores and playing in the fields. The
budding actor left home to live with his grandmother when he was a
teen-ager so he could enroll in theater classes at a junior high in
Snyder, 20 miles down the road.
</P>
<P>
   After earning degrees in English and theater from Stephen F.
Austin University, Maule began to pick up acting jobs wherever he
could, including performing in a regional spectacle celebrating
Texas history ``for about 20 cents an hour. What I was really doing
was riding a horse on stage and shooting a gun and yelling,
`Yahoo'!''
</P>
<P>
   With hopes high, he headed for Hollywood and the big time. Five
weeks later, his bankroll had dwindled to $11, and he was living on
half a meatloaf sandwich a day. To keep from going home a failure,
he joined a singing group on a yearlong tour that ended in Hawaii,
where he donned a flowered shirt and became a backup singer for
tourist heartthrob Don Ho.
</P>
<P>
   Moving back to Los Angeles after a couple of years, he worked as
a backup singer for Bobby Gentry and acted in one play after
another, winning a Drama Logue Award in 1983 for his performance in
Stephen Sondheim's musical, ``Marry Me a Little.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in genuine show business. And the rest is just an
incredible success story of one tragic, silly job after another,''
Maule said, laughing. ``But I still wanted to be in television. I
wanted to act.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been accepted into the chorus of the first national
company of ``Evita'' when he landed a guest spot on ``Charlie's
Angels,'' the hottest show on TV in the late '70s. But the
``Evita'' director refused to give him time off to do the show, so
he quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opted out of culture and theater for `Charlie's Angels.' I
never looked back, and I never regretted it.''
</P>
<P>
   His big break came a few weeks later. When singing star Andy
Gibb failed to show up to sing ``Arthur's Theme'' for the American
Movie Awards, Maule was stuffed into an usher's tuxedo and sang the
song for a nationwide television audience. Somehow, a tape of the
show found its way onto the desk of the ``GH'' casting director,
who saw the fresh-faced singer from Texas as Dr. Tony Jones, the
new neurosurgeon in the fictional town of Port Charles, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't life bizarre?'' said Maule with a grin. ``All of a
sudden, I was on TV. And I'm still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Maule continues to perform in musical theater and concerts
around the country as his schedule permits. And he makes time every
year to emcee a telethon for the West Texas Rehabilitation Center,
where his brother was treated free of charge before he died because
the Maule family had no money.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the Maules have an easygoing marriage that'll be 14
years old in December. He's the family's public figure, and she's
the support staff; she recently gave up a longtime stressful career
as a certified public accountant to work at being a free-lance
fiction writer.
</P>
<P>
   Laverne Maule says her husband is a protector, a lover, a
companion, a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to take care of people, and he does it well,'' she
said. ``He can cook _ whip up whatever: pasta, salads _ and he's a
better cleaner than I am. And when things get crazy, he'll take
just me out to dinner, or we'll take a drive, have private `date
time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy is out of the question when the two appear in public. As
a longtime ``GH'' cast member, Maule is often mobbed by autograph
seekers _ especially since his character's attitude turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this story started, people stop me all the time and say,
`We hate you, we really hate you _ but we understand','' Maule
said. ``Then there's a small percentage of people who think you are
the character. They think you can't act that crazy on TV and not be
warped in real life. That's when it gets real spooky.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently on a plane to Las Vegas, a male passenger struck up a
seemingly innocent conversation. Then he suddenly became convinced
that Maule was crazy Tony Jones and began yelling and screaming at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers around me were defending me. They were like, `Leave
him alone; he's just an actor.' He was still screaming at me as we
landed, accusing me of ruining the morals of the whole United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   But on another occasion, a woman thanked Maule for playing out
the emotional story line of the death of Tony's daughter, B.J., and
the donation of her heart to another child (he won an Emmy
nomination for that story line), saying it helped her get over her
own daughter's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of thing I really appreciate,'' he said. ``It
makes it all worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Maule's CDs are available only by mail order. For information,
call Texas World Records at (800) 964-2723.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
