<HEADER>
A1980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV26-B     07-24 2017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER ``YELLOW RAIN?'' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 26, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Defense Department report last week put a final spike through
the CNN/Time report that US forces had used nerve gas on a secret
raid in Laos in 1970s. American stocks of sarin &UR;  &LR; gas were no nearer
than Okinawa, the Pentagon said. Only a few cranks will continue to
subscribe to the idea that American commandos spewed deadly nerve
gas in their choppers' wakes during Operation Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   Why such passion over the details of a battle fought more than a
quarter century ago? It is worth thinking about the matter a
little, for it offers some revealing clues to the climate of
opinion in the present day, both political and economic.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that questions about nerve gas kindled so quickly
into sensational reporting is that troops may have gone into battle
that day with the atropine syrettes that are supposed to serve as
the antidote to nerve gas _ three apiece, according to a medical
corpsman who accompanied the Tailwind force. To &UR;  &LR; possess even one
of these syrettes was unusual in those days, but it happened that
they were handed out sometimes in remote locations. Nerve gas was
something that the American army feared that its enemies might
employ in mortar attacks.
</P>
<P>
   These fears were fanned into flames starting in late 1970s, when
reports began to filter out that Hmong tribesmen in Laos, loyal to
the Americans, were being subjected to attacks by Laotian
communists using a strange new weapon that took the form of clouds
of droplets, usually yellow. These ``yellow rain'' attacks were
said by tribesmen to be associated with jets and propeller-driven
planes, artillery and mortar shells, hand grenades, and landmines.
They were said to cause vomitting, hemorrhagic bleeding, and
sometimes death.
</P>
<P>
   This was a time of extraordinary brutality in Asia. The Vietnam
War had just ended. The episodes of the Killing Fields, the Boat
People, the Russian invasion of Afghanistan had begun. ``Laos was a
black hole during the war,'' as Peter Arnett said recently,
explaining much. ``A lot went on there that we didn't know about.''
To knowledgable observers, the yellow rain reports were plausible
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In due course the issue was taken over by the editorial page of
The Wall Street Journal, which promptly connected the attacks
against the Hmong to the Soviet Union. In those days the Journal's
ed page was just beginning to accumulate an audience that for a
time would become one of the largest and most sophisticated
readerships in the world. Its editors recognized just how potent a
symbol of evil might be biological warfare waged against a
primitive tribe _ all the more so since it would be a ruthless
violation of a 1972 treaty banning chemical and biological weapons
that had been held up as one of the fruits of detente.
</P>
<P>
   Belief in yellow rain quickly became a central tenet of the
foreign policy of the Reagan Revolution, part of the rationale for
its ``Star Wars''-led military build-up. The Soviets denied the
charge, but Secretary of State Alexander Haig Jr. announced in a
celebrated speech in West Berlin in September 1981 that the United
States finally had obtained ``physical evidence'' of biological
warfare in Laos: telltale yellow spots a few millimeters in
diameter deposited on samples of leaves and twigs.
</P>
<P>
   First Haig, then his State Department successor George Shultz,
asserted in full-dress reports to Congress that yellow rain as a
biological weapon was a proven fact. It was a vital part of the
case against the ``Evil Empire.''
</P>
<P>
   Then just as quickly as it had arisen, the government's case
collapsed _ at least the most prominent part of it, the physical
evidence, the dozens of samples of yellow rain turned in by Hmong
refugees. US tests had concentrated on isolating the active
poisonous ingredient, a substance known chemically as
trichothecenes, but when a British scientist looked at a sample of
yellow rain under an ordinary light microscope, it turned out to
consist entirely of pollen. Caught by surprise, the government
countered that the Soviets apparently were deliberately mixing in
pollen with their chemical agents, in order to enhance their
poisonous effect.
</P>
<P>
   But in May 1983, a Yale University expert on bees suggested that
yellow rain was nothing more complicated than the feces of honey
bees deposited during cleansing flights after winter hibernation _
and that the tricothecenes that had been identified (in tests never
replicated outside of a couple of government labs) were either
naturally occurring or inadvertant contaminants. When laboratories
around the world studied the American samples, it turned out that
every last specimen of yellow rain consisted of the empty husks of
pollen grains, such as those digested by bees.
</P>
<P>
   A period of intense scrutiny among scientists and policy-makers
followed; fairly quickly the matter was resolved. Scientific
American, Nature, and Chemical and Engineering News weighed in
against the government's case, C&AMP;E News in the course of a 27-page
special section calling it ``tenuous at best.'' Three broad
failures to persuade were noted: no corpses were produced, nor
blood or urine samples containing tricothecenes; no credible
eyewitnesses were found; no pieces of a delivery system were
produced.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in Foreign Policy in 1987, Harvard University
biochemistry professor Matthew Meselson drove home the point: in
order to assure maximum impact for its 1981 charge, the government
had bypassed the president's science adviser, the Defense Science
Board, and the National Academy of Sciences. With virtually no
support in established channels from scientific experts in chemical
and biological warefare, the governent's case had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal didn't retract its claims, however;
instead it escalated them. After C&AMP;E News found against it, the
Journal editorialized ``Among men of affairs the `yellow rain'
debate is closed.'' When the editors of Science, Scientific
American, and Nature piled on, the Journal asked, ``For whom do
these science magazines speak? What is science, anyway? Can it
really be so dense?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; There was no response in a neutral scientific venue; a florid
series, ``Beyond Yellow Rain,'' appeared in the Journal in 1984.
From then on, the Journal's editorial writers mainly lapsed into
silence, puctuated by occasional re-assertions, until a pair of
dispatches from Claudia Rosett appeared in 1990, hypothesizing that
the Laotian government was at it again, ``drawing on old dumps
bequeathed by Soviet advisers in the days before Glasnost.'' The
Hmong were ``sick and tired of bringing samples,'' she reported. By
the early 1990s, Journal editorialists were snidely using
``science'' and ``scientific community'' in quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Like television producer April Oliver, who held a news
conference last week to defend her CNN report &UR;  &LR; on Operation
Tailwind, the Journal editors still contend that they successfully
made their case. A few more newsies come to grief? Their
embarrassment would be of no greater significance than hers except
for two things.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that the Soviet Union really was violating the 1972
treaty all those years, pursuing an extensive R&AMP;D program in the
forbidden weapons with a view to outdistancing the United States,
which it suspected of doing the same. A suspicious anthrax outbreak
in Sverdlovsk in 1979 (to which the Journal repeatedly called
attention) was only the visible tip of this program. Defectors
since have described a vast Soviet buildup in convincing terms
(though nothing has been said about yellow rain). In this, as in
much else, the editorial page of The Wall Street Journal was
esposusing a large part of an important truth. Russian know-how
apparently is for sale now in various black arms markets, and in
recent years, Saddam Hussein has demonstrated beyond a shadow of a
doubt that the world has much to fear from biological and chemical
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a treaty is in the works to criminalize the possession
and use of these agents under international law _ just as
hijacking, slavery, and genocide are. Its passage would enable
governments to pursue scientists who do the work, the bureaucrats
who supervise them, the industrialists who supply the manufacturing
apparatus _ not just the leader who authorizes its release. Among
its architects? Matthew Meselson. Of this the Journal wants no
part. Outlawing chemical and biological weapons is ``a quick fix
that will do more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   The second reason to remember yellow rain is that the episode
was the beginning of the Journal's long slow descent into a radical
skepticism and rhetorical nihilism that today is polluting the
atmosphere of American politics. The paper's editorial page is
commonly thought to be conservative; in fact, it is the fount of
one radical idea after another. Supply-side economics, the gold
standard, the long rearguard action against a balanced budget,
Steve Forbes's insurgency against Bob Dole, the current campaign to
scuttle the International Monetary Fund, and above all, the drive
to impeach Bill Clinton: all of these views are distinctly on the
fringe of American politics today. And the hallmarks of the
Journal's opinions in these debates are those that emerged with
yellow rain: a contempt for expert opinion, an inability to narrow
differences, or to identify common ground. The result is to
routinely discredit a wide variety of positions on which many
readers are anxious to agree.
</P>
<P>
   If anything like the energy that was spent on CNN were spent on
the Journal, the persons who pursued the yellow rain matter would
have been discredited. Instead, the episode was permitted to fade
away. Dow Jones &AMP; Co. made no independent investigation of the
Journal's finding, as did CNN; even the highly respected newsside
of the paper shied away. The government has shown no interest in
retracing its steps. Editor Robert Bartley, who led the campaign,
is still running the page; William P. Kucewicz, who wrote most of
it, is editor of Markets magazine, a Dow Jones publication.
Recently it was Kucewicz who was chosen to recommend Milton and
Rose D. Friedman's memoirs to Wall Street Journal readers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Do not misunderstand: the sorry history of the yellow rain
debate does not demonstrate that chemical or biological weapons
were never used in Laos, only that the case was never proved, nor
even broached in a very convincing way _ and that the main attempt
to make it backfired in a highly embarrassing fashion. It would
take an investigative saint to deliver a convincing opinion now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (For an extraordinary example of what a serious investigation
would look like, see ``The Spirit Catches You and You Fall Down,''
by Anne Fadiman, editor of a quarterly journal, The American
Scholar. It is an account of the collision between Hmong refugees
and &UR;  &LR; various members of a California health care community over the
etiology and treatment in a three-year-old Hmong girl of the
ailment commonly known in the West as epilepsy. Ms. Fadiman is
strikingly agnostic on yellow rain.)
</P>
<P>
   By not presenting honestly the evidence that was brought to bear
against its positions, by not backing away from its more
insupportable allegations, The Wall Street Journal in fact behaved
much worse than did CNN in the nerve gas escapade. There was no
attempt at closure; only reiteration and exaggeration: its
editorial writers thereby demostrated a willingness to pollute the
conversation. The same intransigence that has characterized yellow
rain now can be found in almost any issue in which they take an
interest, from Arkansas's Mena airport to the goings-on in Janet
Reno's Justice Department. They are like people who, on a hunch,
cry fire in a crowded room in order to demonize their foes. Not
once but over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
