<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORALES EXPECTS FINAL APPROVAL OF $17.3 BILLION TOBACCO DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorney General Dan Morales said Friday that he
expected a federal judge to give final approval to a revised, $17.3
billion settlement of Texas' lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Morales also reported that he agreed to reduce state
government's potential share of the record deal from $15.3 billion
to $15 billion to help convince cigarette makers to add almost $2.3
billion to the settlement for counties and hospital districts.
</P>
<P>
   The way was cleared for U.S. District Judge David Folsom of
Texarkana to make the settlement final after the local governments
were guaranteed the tobacco funds and Morales negotiated a separate
truce with Gov. George W. Bush and seven legislators over lawyers'
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Morales signed the final documents Friday and had them flown to
Folsom late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The money to the counties and hospital districts is designed to
reimburse them for their smoking-related health care costs. Morales
also is urging the Legislature to spend the state's settlement
proceeds on health care and anti-smoking programs, especially for
children.
</P>
<P>
   State government is to receive more than $1.2 billion from
cigarette companies this year, with the remainder to be paid out
over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the at the end of what has been a very long and
grueling but very gratifying and fulfilling process,'' Morales
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement represents a tremendous victory for the state
and an unprecedented opportunity to promote the public health in
our state, particularly the health of our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of counties and hospital districts challenged the
original $15.3 billion settlement announced in January because of a
provision that prohibited them from filing their own health care
claims against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Morales succeeded in winning an additional $2.3 billion in
tobacco money for the local governments under a settlement clause
that enabled Texas to match, proportionately, a better monetary
deal that Minnesota had negotiated with cigarette companies.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said the tobacco industry, in turn,
insisted that Texas give up $330 million from the state's share of
the settlement. That represented extra funds that Texas had
negotiated for being one of the first states to sue tobacco
companies. Morales said Texas would have received the money only if
Congress had approved national tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Minnesota settlement, which Texas was attempting to
match, did not include a similar provision.
</P>
<P>
   Texas counties and hospital districts will share $450 million in
tobacco money over the next three years. An additional $1.8 billion
will be placed in a trust fund. Income from that fund also will be
distributed among the counties and hospital districts beginning in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over how much to pay a group of private lawyers who
helped Morales sue the tobacco industry will be separated from the
body of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who initially opposed treating the fees as a separate
issue, agreed to a compromise with the governor and seven
legislators to allow the settlement to become final. Bush and the
lawmakers contended that $2.3 billion awarded to the lawyers by
Folsom under a 15 percent contingency agreement with Morales was
excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Although the months-long political fight was nasty, Morales said
Friday that it was all ``strictly business, nothing personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Their ceasefire is supposed to hold until a three-member
arbitration panel sets the lawyers' fees in November. The tobacco
industry has agreed to pay the amount set by the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and legislators reserved the right to resume their
fight if the lawyers aren't satisfied with the amount the arbiters
set and ask Folsom to honor their full contract.
</P>
<P>
   Morales predicted the panel's award will be ``so high there will
be no need for these outside lawyers to try to enforce their
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
