<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VENGEFUL MJ WILL DUNK ON JERRYS
 &HT;    By GREG STODA
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He won't quit.
</P>
<P>
   It is now a dead-lock cinch that Michael Jordan will play in the
NBA next season. Believe it regardless of who says what in upcoming
lockout days, weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   What is not a dead-lock cinch _ and this is the
truth-is-stranger-than-fiction part _ is that Jordan will play for
the Chicago Bulls next season.
</P>
<P>
   That's what this bluffing game has come down to in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jerrys (Bulls owner Reinsdorf and general manager
Krause) are about to learn a lesson they should have learned long
ago. They should have learned it, because they've heard about it
happening to Jordan's own teammates in sessions at the team's Berto
Center practice facility in suburban Deerfield, Ill., and they've
seen it happen to Jordan's opponents around the league.
</P>
<P>
   They are about to feel the full fury of Jordan's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   They are about to get a taste of what it's like to be on the
receiving end of Jordan's insatiable taste for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, when he feels wronged, is passionate in defining and
exacting his own brand of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Jordan, who feels monstrouslsy wronged in this
process, may well decide to devour the Jerrys.
</P>
<P>
   In briefest briefest review of the situation:
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who has led the Bulls to six NBA titles in the past
eight years, said he wouldn't play for any coach other than Phil
Jackson, who recently quit after the team won that sixth
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerrys hired Tim Floyd, ex-head coach in the college game at
Iowa State, as the director of basketball operations. Floyd, long
speculated to be Jackson's bench successor, also has long been the
butt of Jordan's jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerrys, however, now have pulled a joke of their own.
Indeed, they hired Floyd. But they gave him a fancy title, and said
Jackson could have the coaching job back if he wanted it. (Jackson
declined faster than a Jordan dunk, which put Floyd back in
successor's posture.)
</P>
<P>
   But the Jerrys can say they've done everything possible to
accomodate Jordan ... and Jackson. The Jerrys can say Jordan's
quibble should be with Jackson for leaving him, not with them.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, though, will argue that the Jerrys drove Jackson away.
</P>
<P>
   And the one thing Jordan will not allow is for the Jerrys to
drive him out of the game, too. The desire to quit on his own terms
has always been Jordan's mantra _ it was his theme when he
``retired'' after the 1993 title season _ and if he walks away now,
it won't be on his own terms no matter how loudly he insists
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   So, what recourse does Jordan have?
</P>
<P>
   He can take his Superman act elsewhere, that's what.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerrys are gambling with a gambler. They have called and
raised Jordan in a high-stakes game of poker, and it's Jordan's
turn to call the topped-out pot.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerrys' problem? Jordan holds the hole ace.
</P>
<P>
   He can leave Chicago without leaving the game.
</P>
<P>
   He can leave the rebuilding process to Toni Kukoc and Jerry R.
and Jerry K. and the man he disdainfully calls ``Pink'' Floyd. He
can bolt for an on-the-cusp-of-a-championship team with lots of
millions to spare (Phoenix?), take the small-end chunk in a package
deal with teammate/fellow free-agent Scottie Pippen and win another
trophy. Or, in ultimate snub, he could work for minimum NBA wage _
secure with endorsement portfolio _ and try to win a crown while
playing for one of the Bulls' nastiest Eastern Conference rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Patrick Ewing together in New York?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Reggie Miller together in Indiana?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Pat Riley together in Miami?
</P>
<P>
   Dream, Heat fans, dream.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
