<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWBOYS-STRICKLAND25-     07-24 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-STRICKLAND25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strickland, for now, still man in the middle
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The greatest motivator for a football
player near the end of his career is the prospect of being
unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Strickland, one month shy of his 32nd birthday, was getting
dangerously close to that point. Some suggested he was over the
hill. Washed up. Damaged goods. Overweight. Lazy.
</P>
<P>
   The player who signed a two-year, $1.2-million contract to play
for the Dallas Cowboys admitted some of the criticism was
justified.
</P>
<P>
   The middle linebacker knew his career was in jeopardy after last
year's 6- 10 disaster. Almost every player was highly scrutinized.
To blame Strickland for the losing season, though, is like blaming
Sylvester Stallone for all bad movies.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland was only part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Don't explain that to his boss, defensive coordinator Dave
Campo. He challenged Strickland to return this year in good
physical condition, something the veteran player lacked last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The age factor caught up with him,'' Campo said bluntly. ``He
never changed his routines.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Strickland is too old to be unproductive. The
Cowboys have a young and talented player who eventually will play
the middle but, for now, Randall Godfrey, a third-year player from
Georgia, will remain at outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   After one week of training camp, Strickland has proven that his
attitude and work habits have improved. The player who led the team
in tackles just two years ago has been so impressive that talk
about his eventual departure has practically ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland looks like the player who dominated the defense in
'96, not the one who was a major disappointment in '97. After a
recent workout, a drop of blood trickled down from the bridge of
his nose, a badge of honor for someone at his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a little frustrated and a little upset by all the talk
(of losing a job), but I won't get upset because that's just part
of the business,'' Strickland said. ``You go with it and compete.
This will make people see who is going to be the better guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Strickland's improvement is no accident. He hired a personal
trainer for the first time in his career, meets regularly with a
dietitian and spent the entire off-season in Dallas instead of his
home in Upper Saddle River, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland blames his poor '97 season on two factors: Leon Lett
missed 13 games at defensive tackle, and a strained knee limited
his own agility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensive line wasn't all there,'' Strickland said. ``Leon
wasn't there. That was a big loss for most of the season. Still, I
thought I played well enough to come back and be a starter this
year. But that's their decision, and they've made that clear to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lett's absence hurt the entire defense. He was suspended from
the NFL for violating the league's drug policy, and the Cowboys
compensated with young, inexperienced players. That forced
Strickland to take up the slack, a difficult task for someone
hobbled with a bad knee.
</P>
<P>
   Lett has returned, and Strickland is healthy again. The Cowboys
can only hope they don't get pushed around like they did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas might not have a middle linebacker controversy now, but
the Strickland-Godfrey battle is worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   If the season started today, the linebackers would be Godfrey
and Dexter Coakley outside and Strickland in the middle. That group
had a combined 417 tackles last year.
</P>
<P>
   When veteran Broderick Thomas went down with a season-ending
knee injury Sunday, that ended speculation that Godfrey would be
shifted to the middle. Thomas was expected to lend depth at outside
linebacker, and some considered him a threat to crack the starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys cannot afford to lose another outside linebacker,
especially one who had 148 tackles last year.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said Strickland, meanwhile, has earned the right to stay
at middle linebacker. For now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred's kicked up his routine in the off-season,'' Campo said.
``He came back knowing he was going to be in a battle with Randall
Godfrey. That brings out the best in everybody. That's what
competition is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
