<HEADER>
A1995 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CZECH-FIRM25-COX     07-24 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-FIRM25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palm beach firm to be a major Czech player
 &HT;    By Michael Utley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH _ In a deal that would create the largest
American-owned industrial operation in the Czech Republic, SDC
International Inc. has agreed to buy Tatra Inc., a 100-year-old
truck manufacturer once owned by the Czechoslovakian government.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, which is expected be complete by Sept. 30,
Palm Beach-based SDC International will buy a controlling stake in
the company and assume Tatra's bank debt. In all, the price exceeds
$43 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the handcuffs caused by former state ownership and
capital restrictions, Tatra, after serious losses in prior years,
seems to have turned the corner,'' said Ronald A. Adams, chairman
of SDC International (OTC BB: SDCN, $2.25), a small holding company
with branch offices in Fort Lauderdale and Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disintegration of the company's markets caused by the fall
of communism choked Tatra's earnings for many years,'' said Adams.
``We want to lift the yoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatra made a profit of $2 million (U.S. dollars) in 1997, said
Adams, citing the company's most recent audit report, which was
certified by the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young. The company
generated 1997 revenues of $290 million. It has about 7,500
employees at its headquarters in Koprivnice, in the eastern end of
the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fall of communism in Eastern Europe, Tatra was
controlled by the Czechoslovakian government. The company was
privatized in 1990, a year after Czechoslovakia broke from the
Soviet Union and began establishing a democratic form of
government. In 1993, Czechoslovakia split into two nations _ the
Czech Republic and Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   SDC International, which calls Palm Beach home solely because
its chairman lives here, was formed in 1994 to find high-quality
products in Eastern Europe and market them to developing nations in
Central and South America. SDC has since grown into a holding
company and Adams said future acquisitions are being explored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to move products out of the old communist world
and into developing nations,'' said Adams.
</P>
<P>
   SDC's stock now trades on the NASD's Bulletin Board, but Adams
said the Tatra deal should qualify the company to move onto one of
the larger U.S. exchanges. If SDC converts Tatra's $30 million bank
debt into equity _ which it has the right to do _ Adams said Tatra
would have a book value of about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ENDIT_
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-23-98 2329E
</P>
