<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-535(2TAK     07-24 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-535(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JAPANESE PREMIER IS CHOSEN OVER STRONG OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: JAPAN-OBUCHI-PROFILE)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 C.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi was elected
president of the governing party Friday and will become prime
minister, despite an extraordinary open revolt against his
candidacy within his own party and overwhelming public sentiment
against him.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Liberal Democratic Party, which has reigned
over postwar Japan virtually unchallenged except for a brief fall
from power in 1993, Obuchi will be Japan's 23rd prime minister
since World War II. He could assume the post as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   He will take the job as Japan faces its worst financial crisis
in decades, with banks staggering under bad loans, a pension system
on the verge of bankruptcy, and rising unemployment. Japan's allies
will be pressing Obuchi to take quick, decisive measures to revive
Japan's economy, or risk dragging the rest of the world into a
prolonged recession.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi will also have to restore the confidence of Japanese
voters, many of whom are wracked with concerns about their future
as unemployment rises and the public pension fund is running dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to eliminate people's anxiety,'' Obuchi said at a
press conference following his election.
</P>
<P>
   But Obuchi has no record of bold leadership, and his economic
pledges have already been criticized for failing to go far enough.
Obuchi has promised to cut taxes and spend additional money to
stimulate the economy, but many economists believe he must make
fundamental changes in Japan's banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, believe that Obuchi can capitalize on
the very consensus-building strengths that enabled him to win the
election despite opposition. ``His election reflects the sense of
the LDP, although it is not the sense of the people,'' said Yukio
Okamoto, a political consultant. ``Mr. Obuchi has an advantage in
that expectations are so low at the beginning that whatever he
does, he can turn it to an advantage if he steps forward in a
decisive manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi became party president after a spectacle all but unheard
of in Japanese politics: an open effort to defeat a candidate
anointed by most of the ruling party elders, and a public race to
compete for the post of party leader. In the past, a party
president emerged from a smoke-filled room after hours of wheeling
and dealing among faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, supporters of Obuchi's rivals, Seiroku Kajiyama
and Junichiro Koizumi, actively lobbied party elders, even passing
out copies of newspapers containing public opinion polls showing
Obuchi's lack of popularity. Obuchi's challengers spoke their minds
in endless rounds of television shows and actually tried to
campaign on policy, although they were hampered somewhat by the
fact that they shared many of the same ideas.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear whether these stirrings of rebellion
foreshadow changes within the Liberal Democratic Party. Many of the
rebels ended up voting for Obuchi, and most pledged their support
for him Friday. But voter disenchantment has been growing as
Japan's economy falters, and public opinion polls suggest that the
party might lose control of the powerful lower house of the
Legislature if elections are held soon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders are already calling for a dissolution of the
lower house. They hope to capitalize on public anger and win a
majority there. Japanese voters sent a warning message of their
displeasure in upper house elections July 12, when the LDP
unexpectedly lost control of the chamber. The party's defeat led
the current prime minister, Ryutaro Hashimoto, to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be the LDP president who was greeted with the biggest
amount of disappointment ever,'' said Kazuo Shii, chief secretary
of the Japan Communist Party, which has been gaining popularity
among voters.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi recognizes his lack of voter appeal. ``I am inferior to
the other candidates in general popularity,'' he said. ``I know
well that popularity among the people and popularity in the party
should match each other.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he would try to travel around the country and the
world to expose people to his way of thinking and his personality.
``It is now difficult to achieve anything with only support in
Nagatocho and Kasumigaseki,'' Obuchi said, referring to the areas
in Tokyo where the party and the government, respectively, are
located.
</P>
<P>
   The markets, which favored Kajiyama because he promised to
restructure the banking system, reacted with barely a quiver.
Obuchi has been regarded as the front runner for some time, and the
yen actually gained against the dollar after news of his election
broke. The stock market closed before the vote was completed.
</P>
<P>
   But the despair among those who supported Kajiyama and Koizumi
was palpable. Kajiyama received 102 of the 411 votes cast, while
Koizumi captured only 84, indicating that members of his own
faction voted for his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was betrayed,'' said Makiko Tanaka, a non-aligned party
member who voted for Koizumi, currently the health and welfare
minister, in spite of a recent, widely quoted comment in which she
characterized him as eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   She said she voted for him because her constituents favored him.
``Among the public, opinion of Koizumi-san is very high,'' she
said. ``And I think it is the job of a Diet member not only to act
on one's own thoughts but also to listen to constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   That's rare thinking in the party, although there are
undoubtedly more than a few junior members who voted for Obuchi who
are worrying about how their constituents will react. Many voted
for the foreign minister under pressure from factional leaders,
although people back in their districts had encouraged them to
select one of the other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Obuchi's victory strongly suggest traditional ways of
handling party business are alive and well. While many were
predicting that he would fail to secure a majority on the first
vote, 225 members wrote his name on their ballot sheets, giving him
a comfortable margin of support.
</P>
<P>
   That vote underscored Obuchi's one proven strength: his ability
to coax a fractious party membership to coalesce. He used his
advantage as the leader of the largest faction to attract other
faction leaders, who then pressured their members to toe the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of votes was just what we expected,'' said Yoshimi
Watanabe, an Obuchi supporter. ``From now on, LDP will not be
split. We will unite under the new party chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Unity, if achieved, will help Obuchi push through the tough
measures that will be needed to fix the banking system, revise the
tax system and bolster the social safety net.
</P>
<P>
   He has promised a 6 trillion yen tax cut and a 10 trillion yen
supplementary budget, although at his press conference Friday he
said they were not ``completely a concrete figure.''
</P>
<P>
   He reaffirmed his commitment to overhauling the tax system,
saying he would like to lower both the highest individual income
tax bracket and the corporate tax rate, both of which are high by
international standards. ``Otherwise, we should worry about a large
amount of capital flight in this globalized economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there is talk of defections from the party or withholding
votes when the lower house officially votes to elect Obuchi as
prime minister, even his biggest critics say they will cast their
vote for him. ``At least he should be given a chance,'' said Taro
Kono, a young legislator who worked tirelessly on behalf of
Kajiyama's campaign. ``He is now our president. I will vote for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kono and others are keenly awaiting Obuchi's cabinet picks.
If his choices are regarded as ``the appropriate people for the
appropriate posts,'' a phrase now of the lips of everyone in the
party, he will gain the confidence of the skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   Should he fill his cabinet and the party's ranks based on
factional seniority, however, their worst fears will be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, factional considerations governed this vote, in spite
of junior members' demands that factions be disregarded in the
election.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, given the open campaign for party president,
they were. And, in the end, a few party members did brave their
leaderships' wrath and crossed faction lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, the power of the party's hierarchy
prevailed. Up-and-comers in the senior ranks like Koichi Kato, the
party's secretary-general, and Taku Yamasaki, chairman of its
Policy Research Council, feared that their own chances of becoming
prime minister in a few years would dim if the factional system
were thrown to the wind, and they worked hard to keep it in place.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it is clear that generational politics will
continue to threaten that system. The challenge will come from
younger members who are educated abroad and have less ability to
distribute pork to their constituents than more established
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger generation went about this in a really
straightforward manner,'' said Kono. ``The others, they all thought
about their futures. I don't think they thought about the people or
the party or the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
