<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-HISTORY-0725     07-24 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-HISTORY-0725-1STLD-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: In 2nd graf, corrects year to read '1983' sted of '1993'
 &HT;    GUN VIOLENCE IN CAPITOL NOT UNPRECEDENTED
 &HT;    With CAPITOL-SHOOTING-0725.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The shots fired on Friday were the fourth such
incident in the U.S. Capitol, a structure that has been the scene
of several acts of violence, including three bombings, in its
nearly 200-year history. Among the other incidents:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  November 7, 1983 -- A bomb that exploded in a window seat in
the corridor of the empty Senate chamber in November of 1983
stunned the capital and led to a security crack down. Soon
afterwards, Capitol police set up metal detectors at entrances and
began requiring identification tags for staff and journalists.
Three people later pleaded guilty in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 1, 1971 -- A bomb demolished a restroom in the old
Senate wing, doing extensive damage to a hearing room and the
Senate barber shop, but not injuring anyone.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 2, 1915 -- A homemade bomb damaged a Senate reception
room. It had been placed there by Erich Muenter, a former
instructor of German at Harvard University who was upset by private
sales of U.S. weapons to the Allies in World War I.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 1, 1954 -- Five members of the House were wounded on the
floor of the House of Representatives by three gun-wielding Puerto
Rican extremist nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 12, 1947 -- Sen. John W. Bricker, R-Ohio, was shot at
twice in the subway tunnel under the Capitol. His attacker was a
disgruntled former Capitol policeman. The senator was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  February 28, 1890 -- Charles E. Kincaid, a correspondent for
the Louisville Times, shot former Rep. William P. Taulbee, D-Ky.,
in a stairway in an argument over a scandal report in the
newspaper. Taulbee later died from his wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Congressional Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-PROFILE-     07-24 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-PROFILE-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JAPAN'S NEW PRIME MINISTER, A QUIET RISE TO THE TOP  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: With JAPAN-OBUCHI) 
(js) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For someone who has been plying the treacherous waters
of Japanese politics since 1963, Keizo Obuchi has made scarcely a
ripple. He is not identified with any major government policies,
has no memorable personality traits, and has not been tarred by any
scandals.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only time he ever commanded the attention of his
countrymen was on a winter morning in 1989, when Obuchi announced
the name of Japan's new Imperial era, following the death of
Emperor Hirohito. And that bit of history fell to him only because
he was the government's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet political experts here say it is precisely Obuchi's
unobtrusive style that brought him to the top of Japan's ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and has made him the designated successor
to Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto. At 61, Obuchi has mastered the
art of staying out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret of his success is to fly low,'' said Takashi
Inoguchi, a political science professor at Tokyo University.
``Nobody feels threatened by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Obuchi has assiduously cultivated his low profile, it may
have grown naturally out of his early political career. His home
district produced two of Japan's most powerful postwar politicians,
Takeo Fukuda and Yasuhiro Nakasone, who eclipsed the young Obuchi.
He once likened his No. 3 status to being ``a noodle shop that
stands between two high-rise buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a prosperous silk manufacturer, Obuchi was born on
June 25, 1937, in Nakanojo, a bucolic town in the mountains 60
miles northwest of Tokyo. Obuchi's father had his own political
ambitions, and won a seat in Japan's parliament, though his career
was marked by more defeats than victories.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Obuchi had little taste for politics, setting
out to study literature. His academic record, however, was
mediocre, and he failed the entrance examination for the
prestigious Tokyo University three times. Obuchi eventually
enrolled in Waseda University in Tokyo to study English literature.
Like many English majors in Japan, he does not speak English.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Obuchi's father during his freshman year persuaded
him to switch his interests to politics. He joined a debating group
to hone his speaking skills and even began lifting weights on the
then reasonable assumption that if he were elected to parliament,
he might come to blows with his fellow lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to join parliament came at the age of 26, when
Obuchi won a seat from his home district of Gumma. In a gesture
that some political observers have described as evidence of his
small-town roots, he brought his mother to witness his swearing-in
ceremony. Japanese news programs on Friday showed pictures of a
boyish Obuchi, mugging for the cameras from his seat in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   From then on Obuchi stayed in the background, rising quietly
through the ranks of the Liberal Democratic Party. He became an
acolyte of Noburo Takeshita, helping to engineer Takeshita's rise
to prime minister in 1985. Takeshita, who is now 74 and is one of
the power brokers of the party, returned the favor by championing
Obuchi's candidacy this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has Takeshita behind him, and that's all he needs,'' said
John Neuffer, a political analyst at the Matsui Marine Research
Institute. ``He is going to be prime minister because Japan's
`shadow shogun' put him there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was Takeshita who gave Obuchi his moment in history, by
appointing him chief cabinet secretary, a post that carried with it
the once-in-an-era requirement to announce the name of the new
Imperial reign. So on Jan. 7, 1989, Obuchi somberly held up a
plaque with the Chinese ideograph for Heisei, the name the
government had chosen for the reign of Emperor Akihito.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Obuchi was the perfect messenger. Heisei
translates roughly as achieving peace, and by then Obuchi had
already made his name in the Liberal Democratic Party as a deft
consensus-builder _ even in a party where consensus-building is
considered almost a prerequisite for membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``His talent is in aggregating support,'' Inoguchi said. ``In
one sense, it's unfair to say he's had no impact. He's actually had
a lot of impact simply by amassing so much support behind his own
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi was elected to the parliament in the same year as
Hashimoto. Although the two men are not particularly close, Obuchi
had become so powerful within the Liberal Democratic Party by the
mid-1990s that Hashimoto appointed him to the politically sensitive
post of foreign minister in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last May, Obuchi characterized his relationship with
Hashimoto as a straightforward series of favors given and received.
``When I became leader of the faction, Hashimoto supported me,'' he
said. ``It's my turn to support him now. Then next time, he might
support me.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's skills as a back-room politician were dramatized in
Friday's party election. He beat back a threat that members of his
faction might abandon him for two party officials who are more
charismatic, Seiroku Kajiyama and Junichiro Koizumi. In the end,
Obuchi won 225 of the 411 votes cast, a better-than-expected margin
that vindicated his years of internal party politicking.
</P>
<P>
   People who know him say Obuchi has a warm demeanor and seems
incapable of offending people. Despite years of living in Tokyo, he
has not lost the accent of his country home, a trait that Inoguchi
said puts him in the tradition of ``folkish, paddy-style Japanese
politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Obuchi also knows how to take criticism. Last
week, Neuffer described him in an interview with The New York Times
as having ``all the pizazz of a cold pizza.'' The comment was
picked up by the Japanese news media, and Foreign Ministry
officials took umbrage.
</P>
<P>
   But Obuchi was unfazed. Last Sunday, when reporters were camped
out in front of his home in Tokyo, Obuchi ordered several pizzas
and had one of his aides distribute them to the crowd. They were
warm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
