<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELIEF-PARANORMAL-COX     07-24 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELIEF-PARANORMAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Think tank in N.C. has become a hotbed of scientific studies
into ESP phenomenon
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. -- A shadowy figure in a small, dark room plops
pingpong balls over your eyes, gently wiggles a pair of goggles
over your face, hands you a set of earphones and softly urges you
to kick back in an overstuffed chair.
</P>
<P>
   The door creaks shut, and suddenly you're bathed in a weird,
reddish glow. Undulating sounds of a gentle sea wash over you like
warm ocean waves _ background noise that, combined with the red
light, is supposed to tune out distractions and turn on your
ability to enter an ``internally focused state.''
</P>
<P>
   Your mind's supposed to start picking up thoughts beamed your
way by someone in another room, a ``sender'' who tries to transmit
a mental picture of a scene chosen randomly out of 156 images.
</P>
<P>
   For about 20 minutes, you describe all images that pop into your
head, all recorded by a scientist in another room. If the
experiment works, you see what the sender does.
</P>
<P>
   Is there really something to ESP _ extrasensory perception?
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans think so. The latest Southern Focus Poll by The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution found that 58 percent of people in the
South, about the same as in the nation, believe in ESP.
</P>
<P>
   As you sit there, babbling random thoughts, you wonder. Soon,
the lights go down and the music stops. The sender and the
scientist stroll in and turn on a TV. You're shown four images,
including the one the sender tried to implant. If you pick the
right one, you've scored a hit. The scientist who's been jotting
down your thoughts checks your choice against your
stream-of-consciousness descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Chance says you should score a hit 25 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   No telepathic ``hit'' was scored this day. But in thousands of
such experiments here, at the Rhine Research Center, and at other
parapsychological institutions around the world, the average hit
rate has been about 30 percent, significantly above chance, says
Cheryl Alexander, one of four full-time Rhine researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did one series here with 51 subjects and had a 37.3 percent
hit rate,'' she says. ``We did studies with sibling pairs,
parent-child pairs and spouse pairs. The parent-child pairs had a
hit rate of 53.5 percent, the sibling pairs 71.4 percent and only
19 percent for the spouse pairs. They were all fairly small
samples. But taken altogether, the end result is proof.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rhine Center, originally the Duke University(N.C.)
Parapsychology Laboratory, was founded in 1927 by psychologist J.B.
Rhine. He took the institution private in the 1960s, moving into a
huge, spooky old white frame house, full of tiny rooms and secret
doors and a musty-smelling basement jammed with file cabinets
packed with moldy records.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its historical connection to Duke, with its worldwide
reputation as a major medical research center, the Rhine Center is
seen by many scientists as a mecca of mysticism. Phillip Costanzo,
chairman of psychology at Duke, says ``those who research this are
on the fringe.'' Evidence for ESP, he says, isn't compelling.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK with Richard Broughton, 51, the psychologist who runs
the Rhine Center, He says with a hint of crankiness that
parapsychology is grossly misunderstood, especially in America.
ESP, the study of which began in England in 1882, has been proven
scientifically valid, yet, like Rodney Dangerfield, still gets
little respect, he maintains.
</P>
<P>
   He spends a lot of time talking to media types and finds those
from overseas less skeptical, while their American counterparts
seem more inclined to lump ESP with UFOs, trolls and leprechauns,
just another topic for wild-eyed kooks like the weirdo scientist in
the ``Back to the Future'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   But if parapsychology isn't a real science, he wonders, why did
the CIA admit in 1995 that it had spent $20 million over two
decades studying clairvoyance and training people to see and locate
Iraqi bunkers used by Saddam Hussein during the Persian Gulf War?
</P>
<P>
   Why do police departments hire psychics? Why are businesses
pumping money into the center to support precognition research? And
why are ESP experiments being done not only in America but at
universities in the Netherlands, Britain, Japan, Brazil and
Scotland?
</P>
<P>
   Duke historian Seymour Mauskopf, author of the 1980 book ``The
Elusive Science,'' says parapsychology, which he has studied for
years, ``flies in the face of any kind of physical science. It
seems associated with spiritualism, like seances. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, there are good scientists doing this. It's
not a simple `Yes, it's true' or `No, it's false.'''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Rhine Center:
</P>
<P>
   -- At the Princeton University Engineering Anomalies Research
Center in New Jersey, humans have successfully influenced the
behavior of a variety of mechanical, electronic, optical,
acoustical and fluid devices, solely by mental volition. Machines
that are supposed to produce random numbers have been affected by
human thoughts, even thoughts projected from thousands of miles
away, Princeton researchers says.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jessica Utts, a professor of statistics at the University of
California-Davis, was commissioned by the CIA to review its study
on remote viewing. She concluded the technique works.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cornell psychologist Daryl Bem, who also was a government
consultant, said that during the Gulf War, the Pentagon ``wanted to
locate Saddam's underground bunkers. They'd give the remote viewer
the latitude and longitude and ask what he saw there. He'd say, `I
see something underground at this level, large walls. I see what
looks like a possible rocket launcher.''' Bem says he has done
successful ESP experiments himself. ``There is evidence for
telepathy, clairvoyance, precognition and for having intuition
about the future. I have come to believe that there are powers of
the mind that we don't know yet. We're going to have to have a
different worldview about how the world works.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Rhine Center, researcher Robert Bourgeois conducts
experiments in remote viewing, quite different from tests for
telepathy. One recent morning, he ushered a visitor into a large
closet as a computer in a nearby room selected one of 100 images at
random.
</P>
<P>
   The task for the guinea pig: Think about the image you've been
told is on the TV screen down the hall, which no one is seeing, and
say or sketch whatever comes to mind. You feel you're on the top of
a building, looking at trees. You see a long strip, with a dot that
might be a car, and draw it. Then your mind's eye sees what appears
to be sloped roofs of houses. You write and draw feverishly as he
tells you periodically to stop and start again.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, you both go to the room with the TV. You're
shown four images, including the one that was on the TV screen
while you concentrated. You don't see a match, but Bourgeois does.
The sloping mountains are similar to the slanted roof lines you
drew, and there's a highway with a single car, and in front of the
mountain range is a modern city, full of tall buildings. He gives
you a score of two, on a scale of zero to four.
</P>
<P>
   Not great, but better than average. And that's more than enough
to keep the Rhine Center researchers busy trying to prove to the
world's skeptics that ESP isn't just BS.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
