<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' $17.3 BILLION TOBACCO DEAL SIGNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A federal judge Friday signed off on a nearly
$17.3 billion settlement between Texas and the tobacco industry,
putting an end to a six-month battle over details of the historic
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But a potentially bigger fight could erupt next year when state
lawmakers decide how to spend the multibillion-dollar windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that overall, the agreement represents a tremendous
victory for the state and an unprecedented opportunity to promote
the public health in our state,'' said Texas Attorney General Dan
Morales, who filed suit against the tobacco industry and helped
broker the final settlement, the largest in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there is no more worthy objective than to direct
these funds towards the well-being of our children and the
well-being of those who are in need of assistance,'' Morales said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will get $15 billion over the next 25 years, while
counties and hospital districts will divide nearly $2.3 billion,
the bulk of which will be placed in a trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   A dispute over how much to pay the private lawyers Morales hired
to fight the tobacco industry will be handled by a special
arbitration panel later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The documents were signed by the parties involved and flown to
U.S. District Judge David Folsom in Texarkana, where he signed them
Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Morales sued the tobacco industry two years ago in an effort to
recover the costs Texas had incurred in treating smoking-related
illnesses. The night before the trial was to begin in January, the
state and the tobacco companies reached a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But disputes over legal fees and compensation to counties and
hospital districts delayed finalization of the agreement for some
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush led the challenge against a provision in the
settlement that would have paid $2.3 billion to the attorneys hired
by Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said the tobacco industry would pay all the legal fees,
but Bush said he was concerned Texas taxpayers might somehow end up
paying some of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, an arbitration panel that convenes in November will decide
how much to pay. The lawyers can challenge the panel's decision,
but Morales and Bush have said they would fight any attempt to use
any of the settlement to pay the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleased to represent the state of Texas. We're pleased
all this is behind us,'' said Tom Banning, a spokesman for the
private lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The second dispute involved a group of counties and hospital
districts that had complained they were unjustly left out of the
settlement. Under an agreement reached last week, counties and
hospital districts across Texas will share $2.275 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money was made possible under a clause in the
agreement that no other state would get a better deal than Texas.
Minnesota recently negotiated a better settlement that allowed more
money to flow to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies have reached agreements with four states
that total $39.1 billion. The other two states are Florida and
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In 30 days, nearly $400 million will be put in the state
treasury. Texas will get almost $1.3 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   The counties and hospital districts will get their first payment
of $300 million on Jan. 4. An additional $450 million will be
distributed to them over the next three years, and about $1.8
billion will be placed in a trust fund over five years. The income
from that fund will be directed to counties and hospital districts
starting in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said $264 million will be designated for a pilot program
intended to reduce the use of tobacco products by minors. A ban on
using billboards for tobacco advertising also took effect Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature cannot change the terms of the money
allocated to the counties and the hospital districts, Morales said.
But lawmakers, who meet again in January, will decide how to spend
the rest of the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see this money preserved and protected
specifically for public health care investment,'' Morales said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would make his own recommendations on how to
spend the money if he is re-elected this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
