</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CSIBLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Critics' windy pronouncements ignore gems
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    BY Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't behoove those of us who write for a living to take
out after literary critics, but I'm telling you that Modern Library
group who picked the alleged ``top 100 English-language novels of
the 20th century'' can't read!
</P>
<P>
   If they can read, they missed the most stirring, unforgettable,
totally readable book of our time. ``Gone With the Wind'' was
completely ignored. They also overlooked ``To Kill a Mockingbird,''
easily one of the all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   There might have been something about flawless writing, although
looking over the winners, I can't believe that was a standard. I
don't think anybody ever noticed the quality of Margaret Mitchell's
prose. We were too engrossed in the story.
</P>
<P>
   She herself said she wasn't a good writer. In fact, she said she
couldn't be paid enough to reread some of her book. She said her
aim was to tell a story _ and what a story! Millions of people all
over the world read it and feel as close to Scarlett and Melanie
and Rhett as they do to their own blood kin.
</P>
<P>
   Babies were named for them, Tara subdivisions went up all over
the place, newspapermen from faraway Japan come to town regularly
and want to know from those of us who knew her if Mitchell was ``a
nice lady.''
</P>
<P>
   One family in South Georgia takes tourists to their bathroom to
see the toilet they were told came out of Mitchell's now
nonexistent home on Peachtree Street when it was torn down to make
way for an office complex.
</P>
<P>
   All this from an inferior, unnoticeable book? Well, it won a
Pulitzer Prize. It was made into an Academy Award-winning movie
that continues to play today. I saw ``Gone With the Wind'' playing
in France and in Germany almost half a century after it was made.
Can they say the same for any other book on the top 100 list?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the books on that list are favorites of mine. I have
read ``The Grapes of Wrath'' two or three times and commend it to
all the young people in my family who never knew the Great
Depression. I thought Robert Penn Warren's ``All the King's Men''
one of the most absorbing political stories I ever read. (Edwin
O'Connor's ``The Last Hurrah'' was pretty good, too.)
</P>
<P>
   For many years I thought Somerset Maugham's ``Of Human Bondage''
was my favorite book. But then I surrendered ``Of Human Bondage''
in favor of a lot of excellent ones I kept meeting. I don't think
the judges on this dumb list were as flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't they mention Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings' ``The
Yearling''? It would have given Southern writers their 10th nominee
out of a hundred. They tossed us a crumb, but if they could make a
list without Eudora Welty being mentioned, what do they know
anyhow?
</P>
<P>
   And Toni Morrison is not a Southern writer (Ohio, I think), but
her subject matter is familiar to Southerners, and I think as a
Nobel winner she is worthy of the attention she didn't get.
</P>
<P>
   As for Margaret Mitchell and Harper Lee and, of course, Miss
Welty, could it be they are for us readers and too good for
literary list makers?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
