<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-STUDENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tale of two rankings: Students' choices more diverse
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Random House Modern Library panel that selected the 100
greatest English-language novels since 1900 included one woman _
British author A.S. Byatt _ and nine men: Modern Library editor
Christopher Cerf, author Gore Vidal, former Library of Congress
librarian Daniel J. Boorstin, author Shelby Foote, Carnegie Corp.
director Vartan Gregorian, historian Edmund Morris, art scholar
John Richardson, historian Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. and author
William Styron.
</P>
<P>
   The project was launched more than a year ago, said Random House
spokesman Tom Perry, when several of the board members gathered for
lunch and started scribbling down titles. ``They came up with a
long list and then they would phone or fax in other selections,''
Perry said. ``We ended up with a list of 400 books, and that was
sent to all of the board members for their votes. The books that
received the most votes were ranked highest.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, about a month ago, Cerf asked some 100 students enrolled
in the renowned Radcliffe Publishing Course to compile their
choices as a comparison to the Modern Library board's. That list
turned out to be more diverse _ and more contemporary _ with nearly
a third of the novels written by women and African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the Modern Library panelists were satisfied with
their final selections. Calling the list ``typically American,''
Byatt regretted that the Australian Nobel Prize-winning novelist
Patrick White had not been chosen and said there was ``definitely
room for more women.''
</P>
<P>
   Like American author Styron, she regretted the absence of
British writer Doris Lessing and American novelist Mary McCarthy.
Styron said he was surprised, too, by the omission of White and
wished the list had included American writer Eudora Welty.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregorian said he and several other judges had thought they
should choose only books that had been in print a long time, thus
showing that they ``have really stood the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
