<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Grazing in grass always a gas in Motor City
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Wait a minute, wait a minute. Here I am at the Motown
Historical Museum, recalling that sweet, smooth music that got
millions of us onto dance floors _ even those of us who couldn't
dance _ followed us into cars, where radios kept us moving,
grooving; yes, here I am at Hitsville, U.S.A., and I'm looking at
the plants around the buildings, and I'm thinking: I could be in
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Hostas, lots of hostas, grow neatly around the blue and white
two-story brick house that sits on West Grand Boulevard, next door
to the James H. Cole Home for Funerals. And cotoneaster, a wealth
of these shrubs, along with a few others and some small trees.
</P>
<P>
   I like hostas as well as anyone, and cotoneaster has fine form.
It's a berry producer, which always makes it a hit.
</P>
<P>
   But as neat and nice as these are, they are not what I want to
find on this hot day. Not at this shrine to the Motown sound, where
echoes of the Supremes hum in my ears: Baby love, my baby love ...;
where the Four Tops swing through my mind: Sugar pie, honey
bunch....
</P>
<P>
   No, I am here hoping for something else, something somehow
evocative of that long-ago innocence in music, when the Temptations
were singing ``My Girl,'' when Michael Jackson wasn't whoever he is
but was one of the Jackson Five, bouncing around bubble gum hits
such as ``ABC'' and ``I Want You Back.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's obvious I've come in search of a slice of my youth,
hoping to find it in plants that could remind me of Motown when it
was kicking out the jams _ when that music accompanied my heated
pleasure in making my own hits. Just what those plants might be
(graceful willows, lovely swaying ornamental grasses to recall
Diana Ross? A great oak signifying the Four Tops' longevity?) I
can't say. But I know hostas and cotoneaster are not the ones.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking help in this search, I chat with Thomas Lykes, Motown
groundskeeper. What plants make you think of Motown hit makers, I
want to know. What plants might they have liked?
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about it for a moment, answering: ``They used to like
sitting on the grass a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Grass, of course. What could be more right for Motown's days and
nights? Grass. It's sweet and simple; its uncomplicated nature
meshes perfectly with a recording era uncluttered by today's
supremely high technology that leaves you wondering if what you've
heard is real or synthetic.
</P>
<P>
   I come now in praise of grass, even though I do not grow it.
But, like many plants I don't cultivate, grass appeals to me in
someone else's space.
</P>
<P>
   Even on this scarlet day in Detroit, the lawn looks green, cool,
inviting; it could be a carpet to lie on, a floor to dance on, a
chair to sit in sipping something cool, talking about what the next
hit will be, who next will sing her way to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   For a few minutes, Lykes and I stand gazing at the grass. I see
a dream of the past; he sees reality of the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to keep it green,'' he says, noting that the grass
sits ``right out in the sun. We rely on the rain, and we haven't
got much of that this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, do I ever know what he means. I feel my plants in Atlanta
and McCaysville suffering so much, I think of taking a midday train
to Georgia. But I can't. Motown memories really got a hold on me.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
