</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWNS-WATER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't let your lawn or garden be a victim
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead. Grab it with both hands. Steady that aim.
</P>
<P>
   But before you begin blasting away, think about what you're
doing. With one shot of that hose, you could be about to level your
lawn or garden.
</P>
<P>
   That's because there's a real science to watering. Think of
water as a chemical; if you use it incorrectly, you could do more
harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   Water for too long and you invite fungus to invade plants and
lawns. Water too little and roots become shallow. Water in the
evening and insects come out to feast. Water from too high and
nearly half the moisture evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can do is to go out after work and
sprinkle the lawn for 10 minutes,'' said Wayne McLaurin, a
University of Georgia horticulture professor.
</P>
<P>
   Drowning in confusion? Join the crowd. Water crimes are being
committed all day and all night.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say homeowners need to become more aware of their habits
regarding such a precious resource.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 3 percent of the world's water is available for use,
McLaurin said. ``But when you see a sprinkler going round and
round, you're using about 300 gallons of water per hour.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's windy, about 40 percent of that water is tossed into the
air, where it evaporates. That's why McLaurin recommends soaker
hoses and drip irrigation over sprinklers, so water will be
delivered directly to roots.
</P>
<P>
   What's the most heinous hose crime when it comes to lawns?
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to water enough at one time,'' said Walter Reeves,
horticulture educator with the DeKalb County(Ga.) Extension
Service.
</P>
<P>
   In summer heat, lawns growing in Georgia's heavy clay soil
typically require an inch of water per week, which takes a
sprinkler about 90 minutes to deliver to one area, Reeves said. Yet
a common sight is the well-meaning homeowner, armed with the latest
in hose attachments, waving a quick spray across his centipede
before retreating minutes later to the cool comfort of the den.
</P>
<P>
   And, typically, that takes place in late afternoon or early
evening. Unfortunately, watering at that time of day allows lawns
and plants little time to dry before darkness falls. And drying is
important because wet foliage attracts disease and insects. In
addition, water evaporates most quickly in the heat of afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The net result of light waterings is shallow root systems, which
promote heavy top growth and, eventually, a matted layer of thatch.
</P>
<P>
   Trees and shrubs, especially recently planted ones, require
direct watering. ``You want to give them a real good soaking at
least every week to 10 days,'' McLaurin said. ``Take care of them,
because you've probably got a lot of money in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they are such big consumers of water, trees can suck
needed moisture from nearby plants. ``People need to establish
priorities in their landscapes,'' Reeves advised. ``It may be
easier to take down a tree they don't care about rather than
struggle with flat after flat of impatiens.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to plants in containers, most require daily
watering, because roots and soil are confined. Don't allow the soil
in pots to dry out, Reeves warned, because then the soil will
shrink, forming a well around the root ball instead of allowing
water to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   If all that watering sounds like a lot of work, help is
available. A layer of mulch, such as composted leaves, pine straw
or pine chips, placed around the base of plants will help soil
retain its moisture.
</P>
<P>
   And mulching cuts down on water consumption. ``When you do
water, make it count,'' McLaurin said. ``Just don't waste it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
