<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disney cruises offer much more than Mickey
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 26: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anchors aweigh at last for the twice-postponed maiden voyage of
the Disney Magic, the first ship in the Disney Cruise Line fleet.
On Thursday, the Magic sets sail from Port Canaveral, Fla., for a
four-day cruise to Nassau and Castaway Cay, Disney's private
Bahamian island.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic _ 83,000 tons of steel capable of speeds exceeding 24
knots _ will be joined at sea next spring by the Wonder. Originally
scheduled to begin March 12, the Magic's maiden voyage was pushed
to April 30 and then July 30 after delays at the Italian shipyard
where it was built.
</P>
<P>
   Each Disney ship boasts 875 staterooms that are 25 percent
larger than the industry average. In another departure from the
norm, guests dine in a different themed restaurant
</P>
</TEXT>
