<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-GRAHAM-COX     07-24 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-GRAHAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Franklin Graham finds common thread of faith
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Franklin Graham, 46, founder of the international relief
organization Samaritan's Purse and recognized successor to his
father, evangelist Billy Graham, told the story of his own life in
his first book, ``Rebel With a Cause.'' Now, in ``Living Beyond the
Limits,'' he recounts the stories of other people who have made an
impression on him. He lives with his wife and children in Boone,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Where did you find, and how did you choose, the people you
write about?
</P>
<P>
   A:These are people I've met along life's road that have made
impressions on me, lessons I've learned from them, values I've
adopted. There's a common thread that runs through each of them.
Each person is a person of faith, a person of prayer, and a person
who's 100 percent sold-out to almighty God.
</P>
<P>
   I believe there are a lot of people ... who are living a life
that's unfulfilled. They may go to church and Sunday school, but
something's not clicking. I believe God has a plan and a purpose
for every child of his. I want that person to know God's plan and
to experience it. To do that, we've got to be in sync with God.
We've got to surrender ourselves to him. We've got to be able to
trust him. That's hard to do. We like to be in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What are some of the lessons you learned from the people in
the book?
</P>
<P>
   A:The first chapter is on facing our fears. I had a fear a
number of years ago about going to Angola during the war, but I
really felt there was something calling me and drawing me to
Angola. I went. It's the only place I've ever been where I was
afraid, and I had a feeling in my soul I wouldn't come back. As I
look back, I think God was using that to teach me to face my fears.
I'm sure the Apostle Paul, when he had to go to Rome, was afraid.
He was shipwrecked. He had a chance to run, but he didn't. As a
result, he's changed history.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Describe someone whose story you tell in the book.
</P>
<P>
   A:There was a woman from West Virginia named Mary Damron. We
call her Mama Gump in the book. She was helping with a project
collecting shoeboxes filled with Christmas gifts for children in
Bosnia. She showed up with 1,200 shoeboxes. I was impressed with
this woman of humble background who collected 1,200 shoeboxes on
her own, without any help from me and without even being asked. The
next year, she collected 5,000. Somebody in the White House heard
about it and invited her to Washington to meet President Clinton.
She said she didn't want to go. She said she didn't know anybody up
there. She said she'd go if I would go. I told her I wasn't
invited. I called the White House and tried to explain. ... We get
up there, and the president is honoring people in volunteer work
who had been working in Bosnia. He was getting ready to sign the
Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he asks me to meet with him privately in his office.
He said, ``How're your mom and dad?'' We chatted, and he asked me
how I met this woman from West Virginia. I told him I hadn't found
her, she had found me. He said, ``She's the most powerful woman I
ever met.'' ... He invited Mary to come back in. She asked me, ``Do
you think it'd be OK if I prayed for that-there president?'' We go
back in, and Mary said, ``Mr. President, can I pray for you?'' He
looked a little surprised and said, ``Yes, Mary, please.'' She
prayed a very simple prayer. It went something like, ``We pray for
the president and all the responsibilities he carries that affect
all our lives. We pray he will make the right decisions. In Jesus'
name, amen.'' There were tears running down the president's cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   I've been back to the White House several times. Each time he'll
ask me, ``How's that woman from West Virginia? How's Mary Damron?''
</P>
<P>
   She made an impact on the president because she was bold. She
realized that what the president needed was not advice, not another
policy _ it was a prayer invoking the power and wisdom of almighty
God.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Does your mother or father collect stories of people?
</P>
<P>
   A:My mother has been kind of a pack rat all of her life,
collecting stories and illustrations, recording things. She's
working on a book now _ ``How to Be Married to a Preacher and
Remain a Christian.'' I think she's got Dad a little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What about your father? After all these years, do you think he
still learns from the people he meets?
</P>
<P>
   A:I think we all do, to some degree. We can learn good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Would you expand on that idea?
</P>
<P>
   A:I've always in life tried to look for those people that can
strengthen my life, and what principles they have used, and try to
copy or follow the same example. If we want, we can do the same for
bad. We can look for the evil, for the wicked, and copy those too.
... What we need to do is follow the example that Christ set,
follow him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
