<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-TEENS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More than 30,000 Lutheran teenagers in Atlanta for one of the
largest gatherings of young Christians ever held.
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Brace yourself, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of young people will descend on downtown Atlanta
today. They will fill hotels. They will jam subway stations. They
will dance into the night.
</P>
<P>
   But this is no party. The visitors are Lutheran youths who are
coming to Atlanta to serve, not to party.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30,000 teenagers are expected for the National Lutheran
Church-Missouri Synod Youth Gathering, held at the Georgia World
Congress Center and the Georgia Dome today through Wednesday. It's
one of the largest gatherings of young Christians ever held.
</P>
<P>
   Participants will be hard to miss.
</P>
<P>
   Look for kids wearing red backpacks emblazoned with the
gathering's theme, ``Called to Be,'' a biblical phrase taken from
the Book of Romans: ``And you also are among those who are to
belong to Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   The teens will fulfill that call in the streets of Atlanta. They
will distribute canned food, work in soup kitchens and clean parks.
One group will even build a Habitat for Humanity house _ inside the
Georgia World Congress Center. The home will subsequently be moved
to a prepared site in East Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not go unnoticed,'' said Eric Cannedy, 15, of
Marietta, who will participate in the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   The national youth gathering, founded in 1980 and held every
three years, draws young people 15 to 18 years old from all over
the United States and from as far away as Germany and Japan. Among
Christian youth gatherings, it is surpassed in size only by the
Catholic Church's World Youth Day.
</P>
<P>
   The event virtually has become a rite of passage in the Lutheran
church. Many of the participants' older siblings attended previous
gatherings. Now they say it is their turn. The goal: building
friendships and faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited to meet people from around the country and
around the world,'' said Eric, whose parents attended a previous
youth gathering. ``We get a chance to welcome them in our city and
in our homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Johnston, 38, one of the conference's organizers, said the
gathering is designed to reach out to young people in a way the
traditional church often does not. Many of the events are geared to
keep teens' attention. Every night, participants will meet for
Christian music and games. Tuesday night will feature a rock opera.
Teens also can take classes on contemporary issues such as living
in a blended family, chastity and racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want these kids to come away feeling that each of
them as an individual counts, that God loves them and that they
will take that message to someone else,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Jones, 19, of Marietta, who is helping to organize the
event, said Atlantans shouldn't worry that the teens will trash the
city.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this group prefers to clean up trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to change the community for the better when we leave
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
