<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA AND UNION TO RESUME TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid the backdrop of two legal actions taken by the
players association, the league and the union will resume
bargaining Aug. 6 in an effort to move closer to resolving the
disputes that have left the National Basketball Association in a
lockout for more than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled session, which was announced Friday, will be the
first time the two sides have bargained since an unproductive
30-minute meeting June 22. Since then, the union has fired off two
legal shots at the league: a grievance on behalf of players to be
paid during the lockout, and a charge filed with the National Labor
Relations Board challenging the owner-imposed lockout as unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our legal actions have been in response to what the league has
done,'' said union executive director Billy Hunter. ``At the same
time, we are pursuing collective bargaining, and the legal actions
have not delayed that process in any way. We have scheduled a
bargaining session Aug. 6 and intend to follow through with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the players association borrowed a page from its major
league baseball counterparts when it filed a charge with the NLRB
alleging that the league had imposed the lockout without having
come to an impasse, as required by law. With the NLRB's help, the
1995 baseball strike was brought to an end. After deciding that the
owners had not bargained in good faith up until the point that the
baseball players went on strike, the labor board asked U.S.
District Court Judge Sonia Sotomayor to restore the original work
rules. Judge Sotomayor granted an injunction and ended the strike
on March 31, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA owners have made multiple proposals, while the players
have refused to budge from their first offer,'' Jeffrey Mishkin,
the league's chief legal officer, said in response to the union's
charge. ``The only refusal to bargain here is by the players.
Arbitration, charges of unfair labor practices and threats of
decertification will not end this lockout. That will occur only if
there is good-faith negotiations leading to a new collective
bargaining agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The players association's latest charge follows a grievance
filed by the union with arbitrator John Feerick on behalf of
players whose contracts call for them to be paid during the
lockout. In response, the NBA sued the union, contending that the
league should not have to pay players during the lockout and that
it should not have to go to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The league also asked that Feerick, who reduced Golden State
guard Latrell Sprewell's suspension by the league for choking his
coach, be removed as arbitrator on the grounds that his term had
expired. Feerick will hear arguments next Thursday concerning
whether he has jurisdiction in this matter.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the dispute is the owners' desire to put a
ceiling on how much players can earn in a system they reluctantly
approved three years ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
