<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF BOMBING SUSPECT MAY BREAK SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ala., Ga.)  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ In a development that federal authorities say
could help lure out of hiding an accused abortion-clinic bomber,
someone representing one of his relatives has asked to make a
public statement here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe that the representative, whom they did
not identify, may be a lawyer working for the mother of the
fugitive, Eric Robert Rudolph, who has eluded law-enforcement
agencies for nearly six months.
</P>
<P>
   He has been charged with setting off a bomb at a Birmingham,
Ala., abortion clinic that killed an off-duty police officer and
injured a nurse. He is also wanted for questioning in three
bombings in Atlanta, including one that killed one person and
injured 111 at the 1996 summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be an encouraging sign,'' said Earl Woodham, a
special agent with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and
a spokesman for the federal, state and local law-enforcement
agencies that have been searching for Rudolph in the mountains of
western North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not participating in this,'' he added. ``But the family
wants to make a statement through their representative, and they
want the publicity. That could be a positive sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodham said that someone who claimed to represent the Rudolph
family contacted the FBI and expressed a desire to speak in
Andrews, where reporters wait for periodic updates from the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   He said the conversation with the representative was ``not
adversarial,'' but he declined to speculate on why the family is
choosing to comment now, after months of intensive search efforts
by as many as 200 agents. He conceded that one possibility is that
they might ask Rudolph to give himself up and face charges, rather
than risk a dangerous confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hears it,'' Woodham said of the representative's
message, ``it may hit him. The handwriting is on the wall.
Everybody wants the man to give himself up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, a 31-year-old carpenter, has touched off what Woodham
described as one of the United States' largest fugitive searches in
recent years in terms of the number of agents involved, the amount
of time they have been searching and the sophisticated equipment
they are using to comb acres of rugged terrain. The mountains
around Andrews are generally virgin forest, with thick underbrush
and heavy foliage. The area is home to wild boar, bears and snakes.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators, who have been tracking the region, say they
have a general idea where Rudolph has been spending his time. In
addition to finding a pickup truck he recently took from an
acquaintance, George Nordmann, authorities say they have found
fingerprint samples at campsites he might have used while in
hiding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Woodham also said other evidence suggests that over his six
months in hiding, Rudolph has lost ``a significant amount'' of
weight, has grown a beard and may be wearing his hair in a
ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   Woodham said authorities may have additional evidence of his
whereabouts, but it would not necessarily be in their interest to
divulge it. ``If we said what we have and he has a radio, we're
telling him what we know,'' Woodham said.
</P>
</TEXT>
