<HEADER>
A2038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-CHRISTIAN-COX     07-24 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-CHRISTIAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' FB is Christian in name and spirit
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Falcons fullback Bob Christian has come a long way
since breaking into pro football, so maybe it's fitting that he
traveled all the way to South Africa and Zimbabwe in the offseason
to spread the message that faith makes anything possible.
</P>
<P>
   Christian, 29, was concerned that he would not be able to
communicate, when he traveled to Cape Town in February with
Athletes In Action. As it turned out, his story communicated for
him.
</P>
<P>
   American football is foreign in that part of the world, but when
the 5-foot-11, 230-pound Christian explained how he never gave up
during a tough career, he felt like his message was heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wondering if I was going to be able to get the message
across,'' said Christian, who last season was one of the leaders of
the Falcons' Bible study group. ``I ended up telling how I
struggled, getting cut three times, and perservered to end up doing
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in some ghettos like you couldn't believe, and you
could see how maybe some people, if they failed at something, might
give into despair. But I could see in their eyes, some of them,
that they were receiving the message: Don't give in, don't give
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian's group, which also included former Falcon defensive
back Darnell Walker and team chaplain Charles Collier, went from
South Africa to Zimbabwe. They went to a small village, and
Christian discovered a very different world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things probably haven't changed there in 1,000 years. They
were all barefoot and carrying things in baskets on their heads,''
he said. ``They didn't have any electricity or running water.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an eye-opener for Christian that put his career in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   After setting several school rushing records at Northwestern,
Christian was cut by the Falcons in 1991. Then he was cut by the
London Monarchs of the WFL in 1992, and again the same year by San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But he made the practice squad for the Bears the same year,
played in the last two games, and then two more years in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 with Carolina, he caught the first pass in franchise
history _ against the Falcons. He missed the 1996 season after
tearing a pectoral muscle in the preseason, and the Falcons signed
him as a free agent last year.
</P>
<P>
   He carried the ball seven times for 8 yards, but he caught 22
passes, one for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, he threw a lot of lead blocks for Jamal
Anderson and Byron Hanspard and helped pick up blitzing
linebackers. He's a critical special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any chance I get to tote the rock, I love it, but I don't
expect to be the main runner,'' said Christian, who is still
looking for his first career rushing TD after carrying 63 times for
214 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a lot of satisfaction out of laying a good block to
spring Jamal for a good run, even if nobody notices. I kind of like
being about to go out and not have anybody recognize me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
