<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NEWS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1997 second-rounder Davis quits Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- What was considered the Atlanta Falcons' big reach of
the 1997 NFL draft turned into a massive flop on Friday, when
second-year defensive tackle Nathan Davis quit on the second day of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a second-round draft choice, walked away from a drill
eight minutes into the morning practice and told coach Dan Reeves
his heart wasn't in it. Reeves didn't try to change Davis' mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to him so many times it doesn't make any
difference,'' Reeves said. ``When he said he just didn't have it,
and he didn't feel like he wanted to play, I didn't want the door
to hit him in the back on his way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was a non-factor as a rookie, reporting to Suwanee last
summer injured, out of shape and overweight despite a three-year,
$1.74 million contract. He achieved ``active'' status for only two
games during the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   He had not been highly regarded by many NFL personnel people
after his senior season at Indiana, but the Falcons had hoped he
would fill needs on a thin defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of training camp Thursday, he played poorly at
backup right tackle. A medical report revealed he was playing with
a ``stomach illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he lost 13 pounds by taking diuretics on Wednesday
night in an effort to get down to 295 pounds, a preassigned
reporting weight. He weighed in at 313 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Davis played at 285 pounds as a college senior,
when he was slowed by a pelvic injury that lingered into last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't feeling it, and at this level you can't play that
way,'' Davis said after quitting. ``The past two days I went 180
degrees from where I was the night before camp started. I was
feeling good, in better shape, feeling strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I (lost) 13 pounds that night ... taking Vivarin (a
non-prescription stimulant), a lot of them. That didn't work too
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was put on the ``reserve/did not report'' list, and the
Falcons got a requested roster exemption from the NFL to fill his
spot. The team brought in William Gaines, a 6-foot-5, 318-pounder
for a tryout on Friday afternoon. Gaines played with the Redskins
last season. The Falcons are expected to fill the opening today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts when you have a second-round draft choice you're
hoping is going to be a player,'' Reeves said. ``But you make a
mistake, you admit it and move on. We tried everything we could to
make him a player, but it's got to come from inside. You can't
change a man's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
