<HEADLINE>
FEUDS TAKE TOLL ON DIVISIVE ZAPATISTA MOVEMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, July 26) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASOJA SHUCJA, Mexico _ Gnawing through its fifth year, the
stubborn Maya Indian rebellion of southernmost Mexico continues to
devour lives and tear psychic wounds within communities that may
take decades to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Rent by clashing visions of their people's place in the world,
Maya parents have disowned their children, cousins have killed one
another, villagers have forced neighbors they've known since birth
to flee for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict grinds on with scant hope for easy settlement,
the Zapatista rebel movement that once seemingly promised renewal
for Mexico's impoverished Maya has become mired in personal
rivalries, village backbiting and religious schisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left our brothers, our mothers, our fathers,'' says Mario
Torres, a 24-year-old Roman Catholic lay leader and rebel supporter
who led his family and five others into exile in this farm hamlet
in northern Chiapas state three years ago. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``We don't know when we can return,'' Torres says, as scores of
pro-rebel refugees nod in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Maya all, the rebels and their enemies sprout from the same thin
soil. They work the same land, eat the same foods, worship the same
Christian God and traditional Maya deities. But, encouraged by
insurgent and government leaders, they have thrown up barriers
between themselves, often resorting to bloodshed to settle their
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Maya villages here were solidly Roman Catholic
and controlled by traditional leaders, or ``caciques,'' who kept
them solidly in the camp of Mexico's long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Now, communities are splintered between the PRI and opposition
parties, between Catholicism and a host of Protestant faiths,
between reactionaries and radicals, between those who oppose the
Zapatista rebels and those who support them.
</P>
<P>
   Feuding across eastern and northern Chiapas has killed hundreds
of people since the mostly Maya Zapatista National Liberation Army
staged a brief armed uprising in January 1994. The Zapatistas are
demanding greater indigenous rights as well as economic, social and
political reforms in Chiapas and throughout Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of refugees from one side or the other have been
forced to flee their homes, first as the Zapatistas seemed to gain
the upper hand and then as government forces regained military
control over much of rebel territory.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, and those who love them, claim the government has
stoked the violence by pouring guns and money in, favoring certain
groups over others, playing on old hatreds and new ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates claim that at least a dozen
``paramilitary'' organizations, which they say have been financed,
armed and trained by the Mexican government and the PRI, operate in
the Maya areas of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Zapatista Maya complain that the rebels have been
heavy-handed in trying to force everyone to join their rebellion
and reject the public works bonanza that the government has
showered on Chiapas since the uprising began.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides blame the conflict on a shortage of good
land and on economic deprivation, as common here as corn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without bread, work or social justice, there is no peace,''
says Roberto Albores Guillen, 55, the fifth PRI governor of Chiapas
in six years. He took office in January after allegations of
government involvement in a massacre of pro-rebel Indians forced
his predecessor to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catalyst for the violence is poverty,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Employing a time-honored formula for buying peace in Mexico, the
government has poured hundreds of millions of dollars worth of
roads, schools and health clinics into the state's Maya areas.
Government officials are promising the creation of some 300,000
jobs over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, from the beginning, the Chiapas conflict has been as much
about religion as about politics or poverty. The Protestant
transformation that has swept the Maya communities since the 1970s
has driven yet another wedge among people here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the (Catholic) Church took a radical,
ultraradical, attitude in this area,'' says Samuel Sanchez, a
Chol-speaking Maya schoolteacher and PRI state congressman who
helped found a pro-government group known as Paz y Justicia, or
Peace and Justice, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates claim the group is among the most deadly
of the anti-rebel organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have rejected the diocese for promoting conflict in the
region and conflicts between indigenous brothers,'' Sanchez says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CONFLICTING LAND CLAIMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatista movement came late to Masoja Shucja and dozens of
other Chol Maya villages in the spooky, misty mountains near the
ruins of Palenque, the majestic city that many believe ranks among
the purest expressions of ancient Maya culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas launched their rebellion in Tzeltal-, Tzotzil-
and Tojolabal-speaking Maya settlements of the Lacandon rain
forest, a swath of canyons and river valleys along the Guatemala
border. The rebels quickly gained a following in some Tzotzil Maya
villages near San Cristobal de las Casas, the largest city in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   But not long after the Zapatista uprising rebellion began, Chol
farmers invaded thousands of acres of ranch and plantation land
that they claimed had been stolen from their ancestors. A peasant
movement sympathetic to the Zapatistas and linked to the opposition
Democratic Revolution Party quickly gained popularity. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Generations of rage and resentment made the Chol, like other
Maya groups, ripe for rebellion. After losing much of their land in
the Spanish conquest, many Chol villagers worked as virtual slaves
on coffee plantations and cattle ranches owned by German and U.S.
companies as late as the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Zapatista idea arrived in the Chol communities, it
swept through the area like a religious revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Zapatistas were talking about the poverty of the people,''
says Torres, the Catholic lay leader, or catechist, in exile in
Masoja Shucja. ``When they rose up, we had to find a way to express
ourselves, to join them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro-rebel villagers, who opponents say were encouraged and led
by Catholic priests and catechists, pressured their neighbors to
join.
</P>
<P>
   No fence-sitting was allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started having problems because they didn't want to
join them. We felt very threatened,'' says Marcos Albino Torres, a
32-year-old farm union activist in Tila who, human rights group
say, is a military leader of Paz y Justicia. ``In those days, there
was no justice for us. No army, no police, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the squabbling has been about land, as it has been for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   To the casual eye, the land seems abundant and productive
enough. In the summer rainy season, gray and white clouds drape
hump-shouldered mountains. Small villages dot hillsides and sit in
valleys among a mosaic of fields planted in corn, beans, fruits and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   But families of eight or more children are common in these
villages. Farmland granted by the Mexican government in the 1930s
has been divided among sons and grandsons. The average Chol farm
has shrunk from about 50 acres to less than 10 acres. A growing
number of families has found it all but impossible to make a living
from the soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caciques'' and non-Indian ranchers hold a disproportionate
amount of the land. Conflicting claims have spurred bloody disputes
among families and villages. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
