<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV27-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING OUT AND GETTING THINGS DONE
</HEADLINE>
  
 Advance for Monday, July 27  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Let's not let a single second go to waste,'' observes
 &UR; Miriam Goodman &LR; , who reports that exercisers pedaling away the
pounds on two stationary bikes at the YMCA in San Francisco are
thereby creating enough energy to activate the attached computers.
</P>
<P>
   This gives the fitness enthusiast a chance to work out while
surfing the Net, shopping electronically, watching TV, &LR;  or checking
out e-mail. In addition, says the center's health and fitness
coordinator  &UR; E.J. &LR; , an incentive program earns gift certificates
for CDs; last month, exercisers earned frequent-flyer miles for
every mile pedaled.
</P>
<P>
   (Goodman's observation came the same day the New York Times
described an overachieving businessman who tries to find a bank of
pay phones when he needs to make calls. He uses one phone to check
his voice mail while he returns calls on another.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO WAS THAT MASKED WOMAN? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At the Rite-Aid pharmacy in San Francisco last weekend,
 &UR; Jennifer &LR;  and  &UR; Chris Stevens &LR;  were waiting in a line held up at the
front by some kids arguing with the cashier over whether they'd won
a free Coke in a contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This went on for a few minutes,'' writes Chris, ``until a tall
blond woman waiting in line said, `Look, we're in a hurry here. Why
don't each of you kids grab a Coke from the cooler. It's my treat.
Just hurry!' ''
</P>
<P>
   After the kids got their drinks and the woman and her husband
left, the cashier agreed with the customers: ``That was  &UR; Sharon &LR; 
 &UR; Stone &LR; !''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A full-page picture headlined ``On the Town, the Spirit of
City Living'' in the latest issue of Town &AMP; Country (a magazine
that specializes in beautiful people, their brides and their
horses) features  &UR; Wilkes Bashford &LR;  in his ``stately (but never
stuffy) shop,'' San Francisco Mayor  &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  (in Brioni,
Borrelli and Testoni, a threesome that sounds suitable for a
high-wire act) and developer  &UR; Richard Dewey &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; President Clinton &LR; , long quiet on the musical front, picked
up his saxophone Thursday at a 90th birthday party for  &UR; Lionel &LR; 
 &UR; Hampton &LR;  at the White House. The president played ``My Funny
Valentine,'' a rendition the Washington Post called ``very pretty
and accomplished,'' with ``impressive fingering flourishes.'' It
should be noted that this was a Washington Post gossip columnist,
not a music critic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVE ON THE ROAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In the East Bay,  &UR; Martin Schaaf &LR;  overheard a couple in one of
those new VW Beetles having a terrible argument and swears that he
never saw such behavior in a ``love bug.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tom Walton &LR; , on the other hand, was stuck in a traffic jam
Thursday afternoon, just south of San Francisco on Highway 101
north, when he saw the driver of a small white car pull over to the
shoulder, stop and put on his flashers.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking the car was in trouble, Walton kept watching as his own
car inched by. The driver and his passenger _ obviously responsible
types _ passionately kissed; then he restarted the engine and moved
back into traffic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO MAKE MUSIC FOR THE MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood music supervisor  &UR; David Was &LR;  tells Musician magazine
that moviemakers never want music directly related to the subject
of the films they're creating. If a composer were commissioned to
write for ``Mighty Ducks,'' for example, he shouldn't write a song
about ducks playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better to picture some bony Canadian foghorn belting out one
of them eternal love anthems,'' writes Was, ``that work with
anything from ship sinkings to killer asteroids. Vagueness and
dime-store sentiments should always prevail when writing for the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then arrange for a bigger mailbox and watch the royalties flow
like the mighty Blue Danube.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``A series of propositions, some more personal than others,
others more creative than most, yet all propositions that may
coexist without the overriding stricture that has become known as
`fashion.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Designer Martin Margiela in response to Vogue magazine, which
asked him what fashion is. Merla Zellerbach thought it was deciding
which blouse to wear with what skirt.
</P>
