<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2044 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-2NDTAK     07-24 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-2NDTAKES-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
MASOJA SHUCJA, Mexico: families and villages. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We have been left with nothing,'' shrugs Cristobal Gomez, 42,
who frets about dividing his 10 acres among four sons. ``We have no
corn, and we have no money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez and Savelino Torres, his friend and fellow Presbyterian in
the village of Tzaquil, were among those who balked at revolution.
(Savelino Torres, Marcos Albino Torres and Mario Torres are not
related. After centuries of intermarriage among the 200,000-odd
Chol Maya, Torres and a few other last names predominate in the
region.)
</P>
<P>
   Because Savelino Torres had lived for a time outside of Chiapas
and was thus considered worldly, his father and other pro-Zapatista
elders in Tzaquil wanted him to lead their movement, he says. But
Savelino Torres, who had renounced the Catholicism of his family to
become a Protestant, was not interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said we peasants were going to take away everything the
merchants had,'' Savelino Torres says. ``I didn't like that. I
didn't want to be with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In anger, his father, an uncle and several cousins beat him
unconscious on the village basketball court in November 1994,
Savelino Torres says. On the same day, pro-rebel villagers killed a
teen-age boy, who also had declined to join the Zapatista movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own father was going to kill me,'' Savelino Torres says,
shaking his head at the thought. ``They said they were going to
harm anyone else like me who refused. We felt very threatened. The
majority of us were going to flee.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Savelino Torres and other Zapatista opponents in 83
villages across the Chol highlands formed Paz y Justicia. Human
rights advocates say the group acquired guns from the government or
from local ranchers and merchants, then began pushing back at the
Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing bloodshed, at least 69 members of Paz y Justicia
and 23 Zapatista supporters were killed. Zapatistas were expelled
from pro-government villages. Government supporters were run off
from rebel strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   The violence in the Chol region mirrored that sweeping Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-government forces _ encouraged and, many believe, armed by
local PRI leaders _ massacred 45 unarmed Zapatista supporters in
the mountain hamlet of Acteal in December. Last month, army and
police forces killed eight Zapatista supporters in the town of El
Bosque after stepping into a squabble between pro- and
anti-government villagers.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1995, 19 pro-rebel families, including cousins of
Savelino Torres, fled down the mountainside from Tzaquil to the
Zapatista village of Masoja Shucja, where Mario Torres had taken
refuge with people from his own town. Many of the families from
Tzaquil have since negotiated with their anti-rebel neighbors and
returned home.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Torres, who remains in Masoja Shucja, admits that he
served as Zapatista leader in his hometown of Miguel Aleman. He
says he had to leave after a pro-government faction gained the
upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-government Maya block all the roads leading into Masoja
Shucja and other Zapatista villages. No one can enter or leave
without their permission. And permission is rarely granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who left are our cousins,'' Savelino Torres says of the
rebel supporters who fled from Tzaquil to Masoja Shucja. ``We think
about it a lot. We feel bad about it. But those who have stayed out
there still think they will win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CULTURAL INTOLERANCE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, among others, argue that the Maya are
feuding today largely because that's what they've always done.
</P>
<P>
   Ruins of ancient cities dot the mountains and forests where the
Zapatista uprising simmers. Some scholars believe that interminable
warfare among these city states eventually destroyed classic Maya
culture _ famous for its architecture, written language,
mathematics and astronomy _ a thousand years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The dozens of languages and dialects spoken by the scarcely 6
million Maya in Mexico and Central America today are a legacy of
that fragmented ancient society.
</P>
<P>
   The ``quarrelsome culture'' explanation infuriates Zapatista
supporters, who say there would be no conflict if the government
did not encourage it. But even some scholars sympathetic to the
Zapatista demands say that cultural intolerance plays a role in the
current troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a mechanism for pluralistic expression,'' says
Gary Gossen, an anthropologist at the State University of New York
in Albany who has made the Tzotzil Maya of the Chiapas highlands
his life's work. ``You're either in or you're out.''
</P>
<P>
   Zapatista supporters tend to portray the rebels as the only true
indigenous activists in Chiapas. But the Zapatistas represent just
one of many pro-Indian social movements that have sprung up in the
state's Maya areas over the past three decades. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Supporters of the rebels tend to be loyalists of Samuel Ruiz,
the Catholic bishop in the diocese of San Cristobal de las Casas
and a proponent of ``liberation theology,'' which holds that it is
a Christian's duty to actively promote change benefiting the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-rebel Maya largely come from conservative Catholic families
or from the many mainstream Protestant or evangelical churches that
have gained followings in Chiapas in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Paz y Justicia leader Sanchez and other Zapatista opponents
claim that Ruiz has used Catholic lay leaders to push the Zapatista
rebellion among poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Samuel (Ruiz) has always talked of the injustices, and
that's why they said he caused this,'' says Mario Torres, the
Catholic catechist finishing his third year as a refugee in Masoja
Shucja. ``But Samuel didn't invent our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Some human rights activists blame Paz y Justicia for last
November's ambush of a convoy in which Ruiz was traveling that left
several catechists wounded. The pro-government group continues to
prevent priests and pro-rebel catechists from entering the villages
that it controls.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Catholic-linked human rights group complained that
Paz y Justicia members were intimidating a priest in Tumbala, a
Chol village near the market town of Tila.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONEY ROLLS IN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An avalanche of government money has fallen on the Chol
communities in the years since the Zapatista rebellion came here.
But, as in other indigenous areas of Chiapas, almost all of the
money has gone to areas controlled by pro-government Maya.
</P>
<P>
   Zapatista supporters ``see us as a counter-revolutionary force,
a defender of the ruling party and of the government,'' Sanchez
says after a Paz y Justicia meeting in Tila in which slates of PRI
candidates for October's local elections were proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the PRI has been using us for 70 years,'' Sanchez says.
``Now we can use the party for our own interests.''
</P>
<P>
   New hospitals, water treatment plants and schoolrooms have been
built in Tila and the farm villages that surround it. The roads
connecting Tila to nearby towns have been widened and paved. Shiny
new aluminum roofing covers houses that relied on thatch before.
</P>
<P>
   Army units control the highways, and state police patrol
pro-government areas. Crime has dropped, villagers say, and people
feel safe again.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo helicoptered into Tila earlier this
month to make a showy donation to Paz y Justicia. Human rights
groups say the money likely will go for weapons. Sanchez and the
group's other leaders say the money will be used for agricultural
development projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing, so the only way to advance is to work with
the government,'' Marcos Albino Torres, the Paz y Justicia leader,
says as he meets with followers in the concrete-floored front room
of his small house in Tila. ``We go with whatever party is
ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunkered in their villages, Zapatista supporters sneer at what
they consider the sellout attitude of Paz y Justicia. The more
money the government dangles before them, the Zapatistas say, the
more resolved they are to hold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have sold themselves for just a little money,'' Mario
Torres says of anti-Zapatista Maya.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
