<HEADLINE>
GM DEALERS FEEL PINCH OF STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - As the General Motors strike drags into its seventh
week, Arizona car dealers are beginning to feel the pinch in repair
parts and are running out of the more-popular GM vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area is better supplied with GM cars and trucks than
some other areas of the nation, according to local dealers, though
they fear that a prolonged strike will cost them sales and the
goodwill of regular customers.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part, they say, is that the strike has kept customers
from shopping in GM showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not seeing the showroom traffic we usually see in
July,'' said Tony Komandina, president and general manager of the
Biddulph automotive group in Glendale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are seeing that dealers are low on
cars and they think we're raising prices,'' he added. ``That's
really not true. We still need to move our inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   GM cars are still fairly plentiful, dealers say, but trucks are
in short supply across the state, especially the popular full-size
sport-utility vehicles _ Chevrolet Suburban and Tahoe, and the GMC
Suburban and Yukon _ with smaller dealerships running out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all out of Yukons and Suburbans,'' said LaVelle McCoy,
owner of McCoy Motors in Flagstaff, Ariz., which deals in Pontiacs,
Buicks and GMC trucks. ``I delivered my last Yukon over the
weekend. They're the hotter merchandise, and they're gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm missing business, particularly in that segment.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Mullan, a fleet manager for Bill Luke Chrysler who also
supplies GM vehicles for lease customers, said that in the Phoenix
area, ``most of the trucks are gone, and it's getting worse and
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have cars to sell, but they don't have trucks to sell,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the strike hit June 5, GM unveiled a retooled line
of full-size pickups and sport-utility vehicles that the
dealerships were anticipating with enthusiasm for the fall. But
very few of them were built, and their arrival will most likely be
pushed back several months.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger dealerships, such as Biddulph, are holding up mainly
because of the volume of their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley (Phoenix area) dealers really do have good
inventory,'' Komandina said. ``There are some areas of the country
where they are out of cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his supply of Yukons and Suburbans, usually about 100
``on the ground,'' is now about half that, he said, raising
concerns that he could run out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where this is affecting us is in (GM) parts,'' he said.
``There are shortages in sheet metal (body parts) and high-volume
parts, like alternators, air-conditioners and transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, GM's not out of parts, but locally, we can't
replenish.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy said his dealership has a customer's Suburban waiting for
repair after a fender-bender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any idea when we'll get the parts to fix it,''
he said. ``We're trying to locate parts, but it's probably not
going to be fixed until the strike's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming on the horizon, people are going to have trouble
getting parts for their existing GMs.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy agreed with Komandina's assessment that the strike is
costing dealers business not so much because of shortages but
because of public perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that the strike is definitely dampening the public's
desire to shop for a GM vehicle,'' he said. ``We have inventory,
but business is lousy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, who's been in the car business for 30 years, said he's
seen several major GM strikes but believes this one could be the
most serious ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me like this is going to be the mother of all GM
strikes,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
