<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHOOTING-DC (Washington) - Arizona Rep. Bob Stump was nearby when
the shooting started, and Rep. J.D. Hayworth was on his way to the
airport. Color sidebar to the shooting at the Capitol. By ADRIANNE
FLYNN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALARMS (Phoenix) - If you believe the numbers, Phoenix-area
homeowners have more to fear from Christmas decorations, billowing
drapes, and feisty ferrets than from robbers. That's because 65
percent of the alarms called into Phoenix police are false, wasting
millions of dollars and thousands of hours annually. False reports
are now fined, and the worst offenders go to False Alarm School. By
HANNAH MILLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMMIGRANT-BOMBS (Undated) - In deadly summer heat, illegal
immigrants crossing the southern Arizona desert are increasingly at
risk of being blown up by bombs. Rising numbers of trespassers are
traveling through the Chocolate Mountain Aerial Gunnery Range
northwest of Yuma, a site controlled by the Marine Corps but used
by all military branches, even NATO, to train bombing pilots. The
danger is advertised on warning signs in Spanish in English, but
that hasn't deterred crossers. In just two weeks between June 19
and July, Border Patrol picked up nearly 350 people on or near the
range. All were safely rescued, but military and Border Patrol fear
the increased traffic will cost lives. By GRACIELA SEVILLA. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RYAN-SNAFU (Phoenix) - Steven Spielberg ran into a first-class
snafu Friday morning, when copies of the new World War II film
``Saving Private Ryan'' failed to show up in some of the nation's
theaters. In Phoenix, about 20 prints were late arriving at area
Harkins, AMC and United Artist theaters, leaving matinee filmgoers
to find some other film to save them from the summer heat. By
RICHARD NILSEN. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAR DEALERS (Undated) - Arizona dealers in General Motors cars and
trucks find supplies on vehicles and mostly parts getting tight,
though it's not as bad in AZ as it is in some other parts of the
country. The hot-selling Suburbans and Yukons are gone, in some
cases, and customers' cars are stacking up waiting for parts. Worse
is the public perception that dealers are out of cars entirely or
trying to gouge customers for scarce vehicles, resulting in empty
showrooms and and lax sales for July. By BOB GOLFEN. Story movedin
the ``F`` category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
ASTEROID - A mile-wide asteroid that could one day collide with our
Earth, and destroy life on our planet, was discovered recently by
Arizona scientists using a new device specifically designed to
search for potential killer space rocks. Dubbed ``1998 MQ,'' the
asteroid is the first near-Earth space debris discovered by Lowell
Observatory's Near-Earth Object Search, or LONEOS, which began
scanning the night skies from Flagstaff in March. LONEOS is part of
a larger project funded by NASA, which has the goal of discovering
at least 90 percent of all near-Earth objects within the next
decade, thereby providing an early warning system for any objects
in space that could pose a threat to human survival. By STEVE
YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``A`` category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
DOG-CAT - (undated, NYT) - Everybody splits the world into two
categories: male and female; conservative and liberal, etc. But
underlying every other distinction, is the basic, fundamental one:
between dog and cat. Every animate being on the planet is one or
the other. With DOG-CAT LIST. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DOG-CAT LIST (Undated) - Comparing familiar dogs and cats. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Undated) - My neighbor Louie's a longtime driver of
Chrysler products. So it was with some amusement that I recently
discovered a new, white Crown Victoria sitting in his driveway.
What Louie wanted, and without spending a small fortune to get it,
was a full-sized American sedan in the classic sense. There are
only three of these left on the planet, all built by Ford Motor Co.
By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RIGBY-PROFILE (Phoenix) - When Cathy Rigby soars above audiences in
``Peter Pan,'' youngsters see only a wondrous creature, a ``boy''
who can really fly. Their imaginations are engaged. Their elders
can't help seeing a different Rigby, a shyly smiling 15-year-old
with blond pigtails and amazing moves who roused spectators at the
1968 Mexico City Olympics. The more thoughtful recall the
vulnerable young woman who struggled with bulimia and self-image
problems. Never a tragic figure perhaps, Rigby had her share of
dark corners waiting for the light. Unlike Peter Pan, she grew up.
By KYLE LAWSON. Story moved in the ``E`` category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
