<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-TOURISTS-0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAPITOL TOURISTS 'SHOCKED,' 'SCARED' BY SHOOTING INCIDENT
 &HT;    With CAPITOL-SHOOTING-0725.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the whirlwind of police cars, television cameras
and hurried reporters swirled around the Capitol grounds following
Friday's fatal shoot-out, vacationing onlookers stared at the scene
with shock and dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really shocking and scary that he could get passed
security,'' said Carolyn Brunson, a 20-year-old visiting from
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   `` It's sad that this happened in such a public place -- in the
focal point of Washington, D.C.,'' added Chris Brown, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Once the scene was roped-off and reporters were moved far from
the Capitol building, tourists became curious spectators of the
chaotic scene outside. Vacationers joined groups of reporters
bunched up around witnesses relating their harrowing tales over and
over.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Nichols, 15, who had been on a different floor of the
Capitol at the time of the shooting, stood with her parents and
little sister, Jenna, near a podium covered by dozens of black
microphones.
</P>
<P>
   They, too, were waiting for the official update.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty scared. There was so much yelling. I want to know
what happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Three sisters from Hawley, Minn., who had been at the Capitol
building earlier Friday morning, stood on the grass, staring at the
marble structure.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the shooting, they were at the Library of
Congress across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just saw a bunch of lights,'' said Carlene, 23. ``I thought
somebody fainted in the heat and needed an ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the last thing on my mind,'' she added, declining to
give her last name. ``I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister, Connie, 17, said the news was frightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary because the female tourist (victim) was just
20-years-old,'' she said about one of the shooting victims. ``It
could have been me.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
