A2056 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIGBY-PROFILE-AZR &LR;      07-24 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIGBY-PROFILE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYMNASTICS GREAT CATHY RIGBY SOARS AS STAR OF `PETER PAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KYLE LAWSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Stars always travel with baggage. Not Louis Vuitton,
though there's plenty of that. Expectations. Who they have been,
who the public thinks they are. There's no escaping the past when
the future is a hostage to memory. It's the black hole of fame.
</P>
<P>
   When Cathy Rigby soars above audiences in ``Peter Pan,''
youngsters see only a wondrous creature, a ``boy'' who can really
fly. Their imaginations are engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Their elders can't help seeing a different Rigby, a shyly
smiling 15-year-old with blond pigtails and amazing moves who
roused spectators at the 1968 Mexico City Olympics to a sustained
roar of ``ole!'' as she dominated the U.S. gymnastics effort. Or
maybe they remember the Rigby of four years later, when, still a
teenager but also a budding beauty, she inspired similar cheers in
Munich.
</P>
<P>
   The more thoughtful recall the vulnerable young woman who
struggled with bulimia and self-image problems and who, after her
second Olympics, moved into the equally competitive arena of show
business, fighting to secure a place in a world where she no longer
was supple enough to work the balance beam.
</P>
<P>
   Never a tragic figure perhaps, Rigby had her share of dark
corners waiting for the light. She doesn't pretend otherwise or
chide her fans for bringing up the past. Unlike Peter Pan, she grew
up. One can forgive her for thinking she made rather a nice job of
it.
</P>
<P>
   At 45, she is a respected actress, with her own theater and a
Tony Award nomination to her credit. She is a crusader in the fight
against eating disorders, speaking openly about her personal
battles. More importantly to her, her marriage is a byword in a
business where relationships are ephemeral, and her four children
are proof that living in the spotlight doesn't necessarily lead to
a blackout.
</P>
<P>
   That engages the imagination, too. In a way that
rigging-assisted flight never could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have been one to put my mind on what lies ahead of
me,'' Rigby says. ``I don't look back. It isn't easy. I wouldn't
tell you that it is. But if you want to be happy, you must take
control of things.''
</P>
<P>
   She does look back, of course. She can't help it. There was no
escaping the clips of her Olympics achievements when ABC's ``Wide
World of Sports'' named her one of America's Most Influential Women
in Sports. And hardly a month goes by that ESPN doesn't mention her
name in some context or another. (``Honestly, I don't own stock,''
she says, laughing.)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she raises the memories herself. She has become a
national spokeswoman in the fight against eating disorders. Her
video on the subject is a bestseller, and she spends as much time
at the podium giving motivational speeches as she does on the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's purely business. And fun.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Rigby came through Phoenix in another
production of ``Peter Pan,'' earning rave reviews and big box
office. The success was duplicated on Broadway, where she had the
added joy of earning a Tony nomination (as did the show). Fans
loved the musical and kept asking her to revive it. Finally she
did.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the press kit says. She seems to be under
the impression she's appearing in ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather is really terrible here in Kansas,'' she says
during a phone interview. ``We had tornado warnings last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse us, Dorothy, but we placed our call to Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my gosh, I'm not doing that show, am I?'' she giggles. ``I
can't believe I said Kansas. I did it on the radio once. Got the
place completely wrong. What can I say. Touring drains the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   An interview with Rigby is like putting on a pair of those bunny
slippers: warm and fuzzy and who cares how dumb they look when they
feel so good? Or, in this case, how dumb the questions must sound
to a woman who's heard them all before. She never lets on that
she's bored. No wonder she was America's Mother of the Year in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I adore playing Peter Pan. Who wouldn't? You never
have to grow up and you have all those wonderful songs. And you get
to fly. Really, really fly. I love that part. A new company is
handling my rigging on this tour. They're mostly young, and we get
each other into trouble. On the first tour, when I would say I
wanted to go higher and further out over the audience, the people
in charge would say, `Now, Cathy . . .' These guys _ they just get
this excited look and say, `Cool!' My husband gets very nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because Tom McCoy is co-producing the show with
Rigby. She falls, he loses a star. To be honest, chances of that
happening are slim because (A) McCoy supervises that rigging like a
husband in love and (B) Rigby says, ``I've actually had fewer
problems than I did on the first tour. I joke about it, but we're
really very careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, McCoy and Rigby accepted an offer from La
Mirada, Calif., to take over operation of the city's performing
arts center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came at a really good time,'' she says. ``We were thinking
of moving to the East Coast because we thought it might be easier
to pursue our careers there, but our families are in California.
That's no small matter. I'm one of five and Tom is one of 11. To
take the children away from that would have been difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple stage up to six musicals a year at the theater along
with numerous special events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have the best of it,'' she says. ``Tom does the dirty
work, like putting together the budgets. I handle the artistic
side. I sit out front and say, `This is what I think.' Tom lets me
get away with it because he knows that, if I weren't stuck behind
that desk, we'd be in Connecticut!''
</P>
<P>
   This second tour of ``Peter Pan'' is a result of a successful
revival at La Mirada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew people liked the first version, but even so we were
surprised at the response to the revival,'' she says. ``I guess we
shouldn't have been. A new generation of children has come along
that hasn't seen the show. I don't know what there is about the
Peter Pan story, but it absolutely engages kids. And their parents,
too. I think all of us secretly wish we had never grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time she toured through Phoenix, her children
accompanied her. This time, Ryan, 18, and Theresa, 16, have other
plans for their summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep them in Never Land, no matter how hard you
try,'' Rigby sighs.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaitlin, 13, is traveling with her mom and Buck, 22, is in
the show, playing the roles of the Crocodile who stalks Captain
Hook, and Nana, the dog who looks after the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, I'm a mother, so sue me, but Buck is wonderful,''
Rigby says. ``It couldn't have been easy auditioning for his
parents, but he got the job because he was right for the parts. The
response has been incredible, especially for Nana. I tell you _ he
just gets into that dog.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 1938EDT &QL; 
