<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES HEALTH-CARE BILL BUT LEGISLATION'S FUTURE REMAINS
UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., S.D.)  (js) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Turning to a popular election year issue, the House
on Friday passed a contentious Republican bill that would expand
the rights of millions of patients who are dissatisfied with their
medical care.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill, which faces a possible presidential veto,
would guarantee coverage of emergency medical care in certain
cases, allow consumers to appeal disputed decisions to an
independent board, assure open communication between doctors and
patients, and permit women to go directly to obstetricians and
gynecologists.
</P>
<P>
   It also aims to decrease the number of uninsured by expanding
the use of medical savings accounts and allowing businesses to band
together to buy insurance, two provisions the White House and
Democrats vigorously oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up its own proposals in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats have traded a flurry of barbs and
advertisements over patient protections in the past few months, and
lobbyists have spent millions of dollars trying to frame the
debate. The issue is one of the few to spark voters' interest in a
humdrum election year, in large part because consumers feel
frustrated that they are not getting the care they deserve from
cost-conscious managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the partisan wrangling over the issue, the House
legislation squeaked to victory by a 216-210 vote, with 10
Republicans opposing the bill and three Democrats supporting it.
Still, the bill's passage gives Republicans something to offer
voters on the campaign trail and it helps mute Democratic attacks
on a Republican ``do-nothing'' Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic measure, supported by the American Medical
Association, that would have included more sweeping, but costlier
protections, failed Friday by a 212-217 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a patient today or think you might be one in the
future, you ought to thank your lucky stars that this bill passed
today,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., who has championed
patient protections for the past two years and who pushed his
leadership to take up the issue. ``In general I can go home and
tell my folks they are on second base.''
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation's prospects are far from certain as the
issue wends it way to the Senate, back into negotiations with the
House and then on to President Clinton's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats attacked the legislation on Friday as a ``sham'' and a
``fig leaf,'' and the White House said that Clinton would likely
veto it, dampening prospects that the bill will become law. Adding
to the uncertainty, Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., said Friday that
he was ``very pessimistic'' a bill would be signed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There are also considerable differences between Senate and House
Republican bills, which could prove difficult to iron out. The
Senate is expected to act on its legislation in the coming weeks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The House decided to move forward with the legislation after
late-night negotiations on Thursday with Republican moderates and
conservatives, who were unhappy with the bill for different
reasons. In fact, most members did not see the final legislation
until shortly before debate began on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charged that Republicans were trying to ram the bill
through, without committee hearings, to keep them from scrutinizing
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Boiling the congressional battle over managed care down to its
ideological essence, Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said Friday that
Democrats sought only to enrich one of their truest constituents
and contributors with their bill _ trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   One major difference between Democrats and Republicans on the
issue centers on granting patients the chance to sue their managed
care plans and recover substantial damages for denial of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give you better treatment, faster with medical specialists
at lower costs,'' Gingrich said. ``But we do one thing that our
good friends can't stand. We don't make the trial lawyers
richer.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
