<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-SEMINAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH LEADERSHIP SEMINAR ENDS IN DISSENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE _ A weeklong effort to bridge the gap among Northern
Ireland's politicians ended by showing just how far the two sides
have to travel, as members of two Protestant parties refused to
attend a final press conference because it included ``terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   A confusing, contentious scene unfolded as a result, much to the
chagrin of the event's organizers. The dissenters tried
unsuccessfully to stage their own briefing in the same room after
the first one ended. They were told that they had to talk to
reporters in the adjoining hallway instead.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of this week's executive program at Harvard's John F.
Kennedy School of Government was to teach leadership skills to
members of the various Irish factions and to improve the atmosphere
as they talked with one another. And, by all accounts, a good deal
of that goal was accomplished. Moreover, all the participants
agreed there was far more diversity of opinion, openness, and even
camaraderie this week than at a similar program in 1996,
demonstrating the progress made in Northern Ireland during the last
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have forged friendships with people here ... and I think
that's a very, very important step on the road to reconciliation,''
said Dara O'Hagan, a member of Sinn Fein who was recently elected
to the Northern Ireland Assembly. She was among the six officials
of Catholic and Protestant parties who spoke at Friday's official
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   All the politicians praised the program they had just completed
and the people who presented it. But historic animosity dies hard,
and Friday's dramatic detour from the path that Kennedy School
officials had drawn demonstrated just how rough a road lies ahead
for them back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never sit at a podium with terrorists of the IRA-Sinn
Fein,'' said Jim Wells, a member of the Northern Ireland Assembly
from a Protestant faction, the Democratic Unionist Party. In
addition to rejecting Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, Wells
said his party also objected to the presence of parties linked to
Protestant paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   After the official press conference, leaders of the two parties
that staged a boycott, the Democratic Unionists and the Ulster
Unionist Party, entered the briefing room and removed the name tags
of the half-dozen participants who had just left.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that seemed to confuse nearly everyone who watched,
the two parties' politicians then sat at the table and prepared to
address the reporters present. Within seconds, organizers asked
them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   While there is basic agreement between the two Protestant
factions about the Irish Republican Army, there are differences
that demonstrate the complexities of politics in Northern Ireland.
Democratic Unionists say they will never interact with anyone in
the IRA or its branches under any circumstances. The Ulster
Unionists, the largest Protestant party in the North, say they will
do so once the IRA meets conditions including giving up its weapons
and renouncing violence.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both Protestant parties said progress was made at
this week's program and praised its organizers. But Democratic
Unionists took pains to state that neither they nor Ulster
Unionists had interacted with members of Sinn Fein during the
classes, parties, and other events held for the group.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Democratic Unionists criticized Kennedy School
officials for not sufficiently understanding the sensitivities they
were dealing with when they suggested a single press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The event's sponsors, the Kennedy School and the New York-based
Foundation for a Civil Society, did not want to discuss the
controversy. When pressed, they said the 35 Irish attendees,
representing 16 parties, had agreed beforehand that only a single
briefing would be held.
</P>
<P>
   But Stuart Deignan, a Democratic Unionist spokesman, said his
party and the Ulster Unionists had voiced their disapproval of the
arrangements Thursday and were told only Friday morning that they
could not hold their own press conference. ``I think it reflects
badly on the university and on the organizers,'' he said. ``It does
leave a bit of a bad taste that this happened ... at the very
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Arthur, an Ulster University professor who helped put
together this week's events in Cambridge, said that the core
concept of promoting unity and group decision-making would have
been undermined by giving any party or parties a separate forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
