<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP TRIES TO END SPECULATION ON 2000 CONVENTION CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Furious competition among eight cities seeking the
Republican presidential nominating convention in 2000 has created
so much speculation that the head of the party's site-selection
committee moved Friday to quash it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no front-runner,'' Jan Larimer members of the
Republican National Committee who are attending a three-day summer
meeting at the Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech to the committee Friday, New York Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani managed to slip in ``just one plug'' for his
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great place to have convention,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   The fierce competition among the eight cities and intense
lobbying have spurred horse-race handicapping, speculation and
rumors, Larimer said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to New York, the cities bidding for the convention
are Charlotte, N.C.; Chicago; Indianapolis; Minneapolis; New
Orleans; Philadelphia; and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the cities have jockeyed for attention. Former
Rep. Tom Loeffler, co-chairman of San Antonio's Convention 2000
Host Committee, said earlier this week: ``Our frequent appearance
at these meetings has helped catapult San Antonio to a front-runner
position in the convention contest.''
</P>
<P>
   And North Carolina House Speaker Harold Brubaker said Charlotte
appeared to be a top choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear Chicago is out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The party conventions, largely beauty contests for candidates,
are highly coveted. In addition to bringing attention to the host
city, they pump millions of dollars into hotels, restaurants and
tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Laird Stabler, a site-selection team member from Delaware, said
the race remained ``wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I would be hard pressed to pick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The site selection committee has toured several of the cities,
and heads to Indianapolis on Sunday and Minneapolis afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The committee plans to narrow the field to three cities by Labor
Day, Larimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the final three are chosen, the site-selection panel will
return to each for further review. A decision is expected later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Republican Party picked San Diego over San Antonio
in part because the Texas city lacked hotel rooms needed for 25,000
delegates, family members, news media and sponsors. Thousands of
hotel rooms have since been added, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Host committees in each of the cities have bid on the
convention. New York has pledged $40 million; Philadelphia $35
million; Charlotte $26.5 million; and Chicago and Indianapolis $25
million each; San Antonio $21.5 million; and New Orleans $20
million in cash and incentives. Minneapolis has yet to announce its
bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
