u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      07-24 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURNELL BLOCKED IN QUEST TO BECOME TIGHT END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ When Lovett Purnell emerged on the scene
three years ago, he was considered the heir apparent to Ben Coates
as the Patriots' tight end. It hasn't quite worked out that way.
</P>
<P>
   Purnell has receiving ability but lacks blocking skills. That
prompted the Patriots to seek a big tight end who could block like
Coates, use him on third-down running situations, and eventually
develop him as a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   This year's heir apparent is second-round draft pick Rod
Rutledge, a 6-foot-5-inch, 260-pounder from Alabama, where in a
primarily wishbone offense, he got more chances to mow down
linebackers and defensive ends than he did to catch a football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to replace Ben Coates, I'm here to complement
him,'' said Rutledge. ``I'm here maybe to do some things he can't
do _ though he can do everything. I'm here to help out more on a
blocking standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge knows Coates is on a Hall of Fame career track. Just
28, the 6-5, 245-pound Coates isn't exactly ready for a rocking
chair. But eight years removed from tiny Livingstone College in
Salisbury, N.C., where the football field often didn't have lines,
Coates has endured extreme punishment from the double coverage he's
received ever since he supplanted Marv Cook in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Such grace and toughness may not be seen again. And the undying
faith quarterback Drew Bledsoe has in Coates makes for a special
combination which has produced a prolific tandem.
</P>
<P>
   For Purnell and now for Rutledge, the trick to advancing will be
to study Coates up close, take in everything he has to offer, and
attempt to duplicate what he does on the field.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Coates catches hundreds of balls a day, not only from the
quarterbacks but from the throwing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Purnell has always been impressed by Coates's dedication and
hard work during the season. And this past offseason, Coates, who
like Bruce Armstrong had skipped the regular conditioning program,
took part in the majority of the workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben's a great guy,'' said Rutledge. ``He watches me go out and
play and improves what I'm doing wrong and helps me do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's hard to learn from the best, because that
person's talent level is so far superior to the next guy's. It's
impossible to teach how Coates can get downfield with linebackers
and safeties hacking at him and still manage to catch a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Either you have that ability or you don't.
</P>
<P>
   In Rutledge, the Patriots drafted a big body who they know can
block smaller, quicker defensive ends and perhaps surprise one and
all with his receiving. Most of his blocking has come against
Willie McGinest and Chris Slade during practice, and word is he's
holding his own and then some against arguably tougher competition
than he'll face in games.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts who covered Rutledge regularly saw a kid who ran very
well as a sophomore and a junior but then sprained his knee during
spring drills before his senior year and seemed to lose speed. He
wound up starting every game and caught 15 passes. Some of them
were of the spectacular variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those kids who is going to get better and
better,'' said one scout who watched Rutledge a lot. ``No, he's not
the finished product yet, which is good, because he's going to be
able to catch the ball. He's going to be a pretty good player.''
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious last season that the Patriots lacked a second big
tight end, especially on short-yardage third-down situations to
block for the running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past two years, the tight end is a big emphasis in this
offense,'' said Rutledge. ``When Ben's gone, they have to replace
him with someone who's as good. That's why I'm trying to learn as
much as possible. Technique is very important. Shannon Sharpe isn't
the biggest guy, but see what good technique means to him. Everyone
at this level is gonna be a great athlete, so technique comes in
very handy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge feels he's a different type of tight end from Coates or
Purnell. He believes he'll provide something the Patriots need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovett is sort of like Ben; he's a smaller guy (6-3, 245),
more of a receiver than a tight end,'' said Rutledge. ``He can't
block as well. My first priority is to block, and that's what I
come here as. They'd like for me to do both, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Patriots have tried to test Rutledge's receiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can throw me the ball and see if I get open,'' he said.
``They're giving me opportunities, and hopefully, I can open some
eyes. I know I can catch the ball. I have soft hands, but I never
had much of a chance to be a receiver because of the offense we had
at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've opened some eyes with my work ethic,'' he added.
``The new environment and the pressure is tough on a rookie. I'm
trying to keep things in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   He's done everything the coaching staff has asked. He came to
the minicamps in June weighing about 272 pounds. Pete Carroll told
him he needed to lose 10 pounds. Rutledge lost 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made sure I did that,'' he said. ``They felt I was too
heavy. Being lighter always helps with the speed. It could take
away from the blocking some, but not a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's apparently true. Slade and McGinest go up against
All-Pro-caliber tight ends and often make them look silly. It's
happened a time or two against Rutledge, but the big man with the
deep voice has won respect, including from Coates, who has
applauded the rookie's work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Many draft gurus thought Rutledge was taken too high for what he
brings to the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was the type of guy we needed,'' said Carroll. ``Our
need was a blocking tight end, and we feel we have a good one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
