<SLUG> BC-SMITHBARNEY-SETTLE-455&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISED PACT IS APPROVED IN SMITH BARNEY BIAS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER TRUELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge approved a revised settlement Friday
of the sex discrimination case at Smith Barney Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Constance Baker Motley, who rejected an earlier version of
the settlement plan last month, gave final approval to the
settlement of the class-action suit in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan after several amendments were made in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant new amendment grants more court
jurisdiction if a new mediation system for resolving employment
disputes runs into difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   The new system for settling employment disputes at Smith Barney
would replace mandatory arbitration, allowing employees to take
their claims to an independent arbitration panel instead. That
three-member panel would always include at least one woman and at
least one person with experience in employment law.
</P>
<P>
   The suit against Smith Barney painted a tawdry picture of sexual
harassment and discrimination, detailing a ``boom-boom room'' at
the firm's office in Garden City, N.Y., where carousing male bosses
would grope and harass their female subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   The case has already had broad repercussions, chipping away at
the securities industry's established system of settling employment
disputes through mandatory industry arbitration _ a system that
critics said favored securities firms and put employees at a
disadvantag.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith Barney case has also influenced a similar class-action
lawsuit filed by women brokers at Merrill Lynch that is scheduled
for a final federal court hearing in Chicago in September. It also
played a part, lawyers say, in the recent decision of the National
Association of Securities Dealers to shelve its requirement that it
adjudicate discrimination claims.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement approved Friday covers some 22,000 women who
worked at Smith Barney between May 1993 and November 1997. Smith
Barney, a subsidiary of Travelers Group Inc., acquired Salomon Inc.
in 1997 to become Salomon Smith Barney. Under the pending merger of
Travelers and Citicorp, that firm would become the
investment-banking group of what would be the United States'
largest financial-services company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased and frankly surprised at how soon after the
hearing the judge approved it,'' said Mary Stowell, the Chicago
lawyer who along with her partner, Linda Friedman, has represented
the plaintiffs in both the Smith Barney and the Merrill Lynch
suits. Ms. Stowell said Friday that she hoped national legislation
would ``outlaw mandatory arbitration in all professions.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her law firm are now receiving claims related to the
suit. ``We have had well over 1,000 phone calls and queries about
the Smith Barney settlement,'' Ms. Stowell said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a memorandum sent to employees Friday, James Dimon and Deryck
Maughan, the co-chief executives of Salomon Smith Barney, expressed
satisfaction at the settlement, saying that it ``focuses on
effecting real change and progress rather than simply delivering
monetary rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, the two executives said, will ``give additional
impetus to diversity initiatives already under way at the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   But the settlement drew criticism from those who argue that it
is not much of a step forward since mandatory arbitration is so
inimical to civil rights in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a sad statement that Smith Barney gets lauded for
merely allowing people to bring claims in a neutral forum as though
that's some great achievement,'' said Cliff Palefsky, a
civil-rights employment lawyer and an avowed opponent of mandatory
industry arbitration. ``But the reality is the system they have set
up is far better than the securities arbitration system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
