<SLUG> BC-NC-BAPTISTS-WOMEN-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALEIGH CHURCH MAY BREAK WITH SOUTHERN BAPTISTS OVER WOMEN'S
SUBMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Mabel Claire Maddrey, who was born 13 years
before the 19th Amendment gave women the right to vote, stared at
her television set in bewilderment last June as women delegates at
the Southern Baptist Convention raised their hands in support of a
declaration that asks them to graciously submit to their husbands'
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   A Baptist herself, this delicate 91-year-old woman with the soft
and gentle voice does not consider herself a feminist. Yet, for
much of this century, she has followed her own mind, and rarely
submitted to any man's opinions just because she was the one in
sensible heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do remember one time in a small town in eastern North
Carolina, when I was speaking before a congregation in a Baptist
church on behalf of my college,'' said Mrs. Maddrey, thinking back
to 1928. ``I walked right up to the pulpit, and I don't think the
preacher was comfortable with women up there. He said maybe I would
like to speak below the pulpit. So, I took one step down, but I was
elevated, still. That was the only time.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others here in the prestigious, influential First Baptist
Church of Raleigh, she cannot understand why, in 1998, any woman
would vote to sacrifice the independence of other women.
</P>
<P>
   The 186-year-old church, a mainstream Baptist congregation but
one that has historically included women in leadership roles, is
expected to vote sometime in the next few months to break from the
Southern Baptist Convention, the nation's largest Protestant
denomination.
</P>
<P>
   If the 1,300-member church votes, as expected, to leave the
Convention, it will be the first large, long-established church to
do so over the submission declaration, which asks husbands to lead
their families and wives to serve as gracious, uncomplaining
helpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an 18-year-old daughter, and how could I look at her
and tell her that her opinion does not mean as much as some
man's?'' said Carolyn Dickens, 46, who heads the Deacon Board at
First Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Southern Baptist Convention, 16 million
members strong, said they are not concerned with the church's
impending exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, it is a statement of their integrity to finally
say, `We don't like the Southern Baptists, we don't believe in what
they're doing, and we're not going to keep holding on to the
fiction that we are a Southern Baptist church,'' said William
Merrell, vice president for convention relations.
</P>
<P>
   Merrell said the declaration is intended to organize Christian
families, ``in a way that reduces the amount of tension and
conflict that American families in many cases are characterized by.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude of the male should be one of sacrificial love, so
that, as in the case of Jesus, a husband should be prepared even to
die for his wife. The attitude of the child should be one of
obedience to the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude of a Christian wife,'' he said, ``should be an
attitude of submissiveness, as opposed to argumentativeness, or
demand, or attempt at conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   At First Baptist, Raleigh's oldest and largest church, the
declaration was the last straw for a congregation that has grown
weary with an organization that it sees as increasingly rigid and
right wing, church members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the wives want to submit, that's their business,
though I don't quite understand it,'' said Mrs. Maddrey, a widow
who was married to the same man for 50 years, and does not recall
submitting very much. ``The problem is with me, when I am a member
of a denomination that seeks to impose someone else's standards and
wishes upon the entire denomination. I'm a Democrat, but I don't
bring that to church with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's decision is important, symbolically and otherwise,
historians say, because the exit of a leading ``first church'' is
proof of the disenchantment some congregations feel with the
Convention's conservative direction. Traditionally, ``first''
Baptist churches are cornerstones of Protestant communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is a great deal of dissatisfaction with the
resolution, a huge amount, even in churches that are not as large
or sophisticated as First Baptist,'' said Dr. Furman Hewitt,
director of the Baptist studies program at Duke University. ``I
know of rural churches where there is a great deal of
dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   The stand by First Baptist will embolden other, more moderate
churches in the Convention, he said. ``There will be some who will
follow that lead,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives took over the leadership of the Convention in
1979, and this is just the latest conflict with its more moderate
congregations. But in the stately old First Baptist, rich in
stained glass and history, congregants say it is a question of
basic freedom to interpret one's faith, and Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the congregation say over and over that they do not
enjoy the attention they are receiving over the expected split, but
they are amused at the notion that some in the Convention consider
them radicals.
</P>
<P>
   In a dinner and business meeting Wednesday night in the church's
auditorium, an elderly woman walked up to the pastor's table and
insisted that someone go fix the American flag. It was being
displayed slightly out of its traditional place near the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people ate barbecue sandwiches and brownies at long
tables before beginning a routine discussion of church business.
When it was a time for a prayer, most of the heads that bowed were
crowned with silver hair. Mrs. Maddrey was a tad late for supper,
but she has been a little flustered since the test she recently
took to renew her driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, in the darkened sanctuary, the late afternoon sunlight
stabbed through the stained glass and caused the air above the
wooden pews to glow in lavender, green, gold, pink and red. The
massive Bible near the pulpit was opened to the story of the Good
Samaritan. The pews were padded with velvet cushions, for those
days that the sermons light run a little long.
</P>
<P>
   This is anything but a radical, liberal church, said its
members. A roll call of its membership would would show the pews
filled with religious, political, business and education leaders,
people long bound by Baptist tradition and heritage. They vote both
sides of the ticket, though one woman said many members would
consider themselves conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rich deposit of people who use their brains to interpret
their Bibles,'' said the Rev. Daniel Day, the pastor at First
Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Such people feel uneasy toward a Baptist organization that,
people here say, is rejecting long-held traditions of autonomy and
individual conscience, freedoms that their faith was founded on.
</P>
<P>
   But if a confrontation with a large, historic mainstream church
was going to come, it was not unexpected that it came with First
Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Women hold positions of power here. For more than 100 years, the
church has elected women as deacons and half the seats on the
deacon board are held by women. Voices of women in the
congregation, especially those of older ones, are valued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a family of strong, independent women,'' explained
Mrs. Maddrey, whose mother served on the Ahoskie, N.C., town
council in 1917, a time when women in politics were rare. ``Not
abrasive, I hope, but independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of her life she has served on civic committees and
charities, usually headed by men. ``But that didn't bother me,
because women are smart enough to get work around the men and get
done the things they want,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dickens, who directs a literacy program when she is not
helping with church business, said there is nothing radical about
having women head the deacon board, though some churches have been
slower to allow women into such positions of authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very presumptuous to preclude another person's gifts of
leadership,'' said Mrs. Dickens. ``That goes against being a
Baptist.''
</P>
<P>
   Although spokesmen for the Southern Baptist Convention say they
do not know how many, if any, churches may be planning to exit, it
is unlikely that the issue will usher anything close to a mass
exodus. An increasing orthodoxy, like its conservative leadership,
seems to sit well with many members, said Baptists on both sides of
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rumblings that the Convention is mixing religion and
politics, its membership has gradually grown, from 36,979 churches
in 1985 to 40,887 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Merrell of the Convention said: ``It might be healthier for a
church that is not in sympathy'' to leave the Convention. ``If they
think they have to change us, it is very difficult to do with a
convention of our size.''
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the Southern Baptist Convention can be loosely de-
fined, as churches decide individually to send money, or use the
conven- tion's literature in church, and also may participate in
other Conven- tions, like the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship, an
organization of more moderate churches that was formed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   First Baptist does not use Southern Baptist Convention
literature, for instance, in Sunday school. It no longer sends
money to the Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But it is rare, historians say, for a large, influential Baptist
church to formally vote to abandon the Convention.
</P>
<P>
   For such a church to come to that point is a process that often
takes years, even decades, said Hewitt, as ``people think about
whether they can separate themselves from the religious community
that birthed them.''
</P>
<P>
   First Baptist of Raleigh predates the Convention. It was founded
in 1812, 33 years before the Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to officially declare itself disassociated with the
Southern Baptists is still ``in committee,'' church members said,
and will require a vote of the congregation. But the church's
pastor said there seems little opposition to it. ``The die is
cast,'' said Day.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Maddrey has made up her mind. She is asked if her late
husband would have expected her to submit, automatically, to his
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noooooo,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
