<HEADLINE>
TEXAS OFFICIALS WORK ON SAFETY AFTER INMATES DIE OF APPARENT HEAT
STROKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State prison officials said Friday they have
begun safety measures to reduce the risk of heat-related health
problems to inmates and employees following the deaths of two
prisoners from the Houston area earlier this summer from apparent
heat strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But the executive director of a prisoner rights organization
said the prison system's efforts are too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Archie White, 48, died June 29 at the Hendricks Medical Center
in Abilene after riding for about two hours on a prison bus without
air conditioning. He was being taken from the Montford prison in
Lubbock to the Robertson prison in Abilene, said Bob Koenig,
director of risk management for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice. White had been sentenced to 28 years for burglary and drug
possession in Brazoria County.
</P>
<P>
   The other inmate, 27-year-old Alfred Wilder, died May 29 at the
Crosbyton Clinic Hospital after he collapsed on an outdoor
recreation yard where he had been playing basketball, Koenig said.
Prison records show that Waller had been sentenced to 15 years in
Waller County on burglary and several drug-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
   White was en route to the Robertson Unit on a medical transfer
to a psychiatric facility in Rusk, Koenig said. He arrived at the
unit at 4:15 p.m. and showed signs of heat exhaustion when he got
off the bus. He was pronounced dead about three hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig said temperatures can reach 105 degrees inside prison
buses while they are parked, but while they are moving the air
flowing in the windows drops temperatures to a much lower level.
</P>
<P>
   TDCJ spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said the buses _ about the size
of a full-size public school bus _ can be unloaded in a matter of a
few minutes, although felons are chained in pairs while being
transported.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig said records indicate that Wilder had been playing
basketball in the recreation yard at the Dickens County
Correctional Unit, when he went up for a lay up and collapsed. He
was taken to the Crosbyton hospital, where he was died. Koenig said
he does not know how long Wilder had been playing ball in the sun;
he was being housed in a privately operated county facility from
whom TDCJ leases bed space.
</P>
<P>
   The day after White's death, another prison inmate who had been
bused from the John Sealy Hospital in Galveston to the Estelle Unit
north of Huntsville was hospitalized with signs of heat stroke, but
he recovered, Koenig said.
</P>
<P>
   White's death and the other inmate illness on a prison bus
prompted Koenig to order about 100 fans for the buses plus some
large fans at the prison gates to force air through the buses while
prisoners are waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've also altered the bus schedules ... so we're not
transporting any prisoners between noon and about 5 or 6 in the
afternoon,'' the hottest part of the day, Koenig said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials have taken a variety of other steps, including
placing water misters in ventilation systems at some units,
altering work schedules _ particularly for those who work outdoors
in the farm fields _ and providing additional rest and water
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   But Linda Marin, executive director of the Texas chapter of
Citizens United for the Rehabilitation of Errants, said TDCJ's
efforts are not beginning to meet prisoner needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really concerned because you've got 140,000 people with
major problems, whether they're physical or emotional, and the heat
just makes conditions worse,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ventilation (at some facilities) is not good, so people are
really roasting,'' Marin added. ``It's absolutely miserable. People
with continuing medical problems are suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that although TDCJ may be taking preventive measures at
some units, the efforts are not consistent statewide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
