<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CHEAP-FARES-$ADV26-ART-855(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAME THAT FARE, AND OTHER ONLINE CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mo., Pa., N.J., Hawaii, Pa., Texas)  (For release Sunday, July 26) 
(ART ADV: Graphic showing Web sites for airline tickets is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just because August is around the corner and you still haven't
planned your summer vacation, don't despair. The Internet can help
book a quick _ even bargain-priced _ getaway.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com has generated a big buzz since its start-up in
April, when it kicked off a multimillion-dollar advertising
campaign, promoting a ``name your own price'' service for buying
discounted plane tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline's online auction, though, is only one of the most
recent additions to the Internet's fare deals. Depending on how
nimble a traveler you are _ and how much inconvenience you can
endure _ various travel opportunities are only a click away. Each
week, the World Wide Web sites of individual airlines post deeply
discounted fares for travel that weekend. Other sites gather and
update information on inexpensive fares from several sources.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Priceline has made a sizable impression in a relatively
short time. Jay Walker, chairman of the company, based in Stamford,
Conn., said it had already sold 40,000 tickets, generating revenues
of more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though Priceline has satisfied some customers, its lengthy list
of requirements has frustrated others. And most major domestic
airlines do not participate in the service, as they promote their
own specials online to fill their empty seats; this limits
Priceline's offerings.
</P>
<P>
   To use the service, customers complete a ticket request on its
Web site, saying where and when they want to travel and how much
they are willing to pay. (Travelers without Internet access can bid
by phone.)
</P>
<P>
   If a bid is much lower than published fares, it will be
rejected. To determine a reasonable price, customers should
research the standard range of fares on the route.
</P>
<P>
   Once a bid is submitted, Priceline sorts through the airline
seats at its disposal. It says it can notify customers within an
hour whether a bid for a domestic flight has been accepted or
rejected _ 24 hours for international flights.
</P>
<P>
   In submitting bids, customers also provide their credit-card
information. If a bid is accepted, a ticket is automatically issued
and the credit card is billed; if the bid is rejected, travelers
can submit other bids using different airports or different dates,
but cannot rebid with higher amounts using the same itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   There are other restrictions: Tickets are not refundable or
exchangeable and are not eligible for frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline's services are free for travelers using electronic
tickets, which are generally available only on domestic flights; if
travelers require a paper ticket, they pay a $12.50 overnight
delivery fee.
</P>
<P>
   And those are just the rules for getting tickets. The flights
themselves may challenge an individual's notion of ease and
comfort. Travelers must be willing to leave any time between 6 a.m.
and 10 p.m. on their selected date if flying domestically, or any
time if flying overseas. Flights may also require a stop or a
connection en route.
</P>
<P>
   A potentially bigger obstacle is that the auction site seems to
have the cooperation of only a few domestic airlines. Eight of the
10 major U.S. airlines _ Alaska, American, Continental, Delta,
Northwest, Southwest, United and US Airways _ say they have chosen
not to work with Priceline. The other two _ America West and Trans
World Airlines _ declined to comment, though industry executives
say they do work with the service.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say you can't get tickets on the major carriers
through Priceline's auctions. As a licensed travel agency, the
company offers discounted seats on major airlines through the
Worldspan computerized reservations system and its inventory;
Priceline also sometimes resells the wholesale seats offered by
consolidators.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, though, said that less than 5 percent of the tickets
Priceline sells are through Worldspan or consolidators.
</P>
<P>
   Walker declined to identify which major U.S. carriers worked
with his company, saying only that a total of 15 U.S. and
international carriers are giving Priceline seats to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The limits on inventory can stymie bidders, as Michael Spohn, a
21-year-old student at the University of Missouri, has discovered.
Since late May, Spohn, an intern in the retail advertising
department of The Des Moines Register, has placed bids with
Priceline nine times to fly from Omaha, Neb., or Des Moines, Iowa,
or Cedar Rapids, Iowa, to his hometown, St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, he said, he has bid three or four days before he
wanted to travel and set a price $10 to $15 above the lowest
available published advanced-purchase fare; in his research, he
also found that seats were still available on these routes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet each bid was rejected. He said he suspects that Priceline
simply had no seats to sell on those routes. ``I don't understand
why they can't do it,'' he said, ``especially if you offer bids
above the airlines' lowest fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said Priceline could not offer seats in all markets,
acknowledging that it had ``no lift in small cities that have no
lift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be willing to drive to a bigger city,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Priceline has its fans, including George Miller, 54, the
artistic director of the Theater Outlet in Allentown, Pa. Several
weeks ago, Miller bought two round-trip tickets, at $550 each, to
fly on Aer Lingus from Newark, N.J., to Dublin, Ireland, for his
honeymoon, which begins Sunday. The lowest published fare offered
by the airline for the same date was $598.
</P>
<P>
   Ashita Patel, 34, a pharmacist from Edison, N.J., is also happy:
Earlier this month, she bought four round-trip tickets, at $300
each, for her family to fly on United from Newark to London for a
September wedding. United's lowest published fare on that route for
that time was $788. (Prices do not include tax.)
</P>
<P>
   Other Web sites also offer deeply discounted tickets; in some
cases, they can arrange for cheap hotel rooms and car rentals, too.
</P>
<P>
   Most major U.S. airlines offer special weekly Internet fares,
usually for travel that weekend; prices are much lower than their
cheapest advance-purchase fares. The drawback, of course, is that
destinations are limited: You have to go where they want to take
you.
</P>
<P>
   Online travel agencies including Previewtravel.com,
Expedia.msn.com and Travelocity.com have special features that help
track low fares. Preview offers low fares and announcements of
airlines' latest specials. Expedia, owned by Microsoft, and
Travelocity, controlled by AMR, the parent of American Airlines,
send regular e-mail to travelers listing the lowest published fares
on the routes of their choice. Travelocity also posts a list of
each day's lowest fares.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaptickets.com, a consolidator based in Honolulu, sells
published and unpublished discount fares for flights on domestic
and foreign airlines; Michael Hartley, its president, said it
obtains the unpublished discounts from carriers far in advance.
Travelers must provide credit-card information before they can
conduct a fare search; requests result in a choice of 25 fares,
which the customer can accept or decline.
</P>
<P>
   Another site, Bestfares.com, based in Dallas, has sections with
general access to rate information and others only for subscribers,
who pay $60 a year to get more detailed travel data and more deals.
</P>
<P>
   A site operated by 1travel.com, a Zionsville, Pa., travel
agency, provides another path to discounts. It publishes all
airlines' weekly Web specials and will send e-mail lists of them,
customized to the traveler's requirements. It also provides data on
deeply discounted international tickets sold by several large
ticket consolidators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
