u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-IRAQ-KURD-320&AMP;AD     07-24 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-IRAQ-KURD-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRIES NEW TACTIC TO UNITE IRAQ'S OPPOSITION AGAINST SADDAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sign of the pragmatism that now rules U.S.
policy toward Iraq, the Clinton administration has invited to
Washington the Kurdish leader who betrayed the CIA's covert action
program against Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Massoud Barzani was seen by the CIA as the
Quisling of Iraq. But State Department officials said Friday that
Barzani will come to the United States for high-level talks later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also planning to attend that meeting is Jalal Talibani, the
leader of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan and Barzani's bitter
rival for leadership of the Iraqi Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's decision to invite the two men to the
United States is part of a new campaign to unify the Iraqi
opposition, and to demonstrate to Saddam that he still cannot
exercise control over northern Iraq, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important signal to Bagdad,'' said a U.S. official.
``Saddam is a gangster, and we want to show that he doesn't control
all the corners in his neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, U.S. officials are now willing to forgive and forget,
convinced that Barzani's betrayal of the CIA in August 1996 was
simply a temporary ``tactical move'' prompted by internal Kurdish
politics. U.S. officials say Barzani never formed a permanent
alliance with Saddam. As a result, U.S. officials believe it is
important to strengthen relations with Barzani in order to make
sure he continues to stay out of Saddam's orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game is to keep the Kurds at a distance from Bagdad,'' a
U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   But the move to embrace Barzani also underscores how few options
Washington has in its long-term strategy to counter Iraq. Any
effort to work against the Iraqi leader from within his country
must rely in part on the support of Iraqi minority groups, either
the Kurds in northern Iraq or the Shia Muslims in the south.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the wake of the Persian Gulf War, the United States began a
covert-action program that sought to unite Barzani's Kurdistan
Democratic Party and Talibani's Patriotic Union of Kurdistan under
the umbrella of a CIA-backed anti-Saddam organization known as the
Iraqi National Congress. Both Barzani and Talibani were placed on
the CIA payroll.
</P>
<P>
   But in August 1996 Barzani was in the midst of one of his
periodic battles with Talibani, who was then backed by the Iranian
military. Kurdistan Democratic Party officials say Barzani invited
the Iraqi army to move north into his territory to counter the
Iranian support for Talibani. The Iraqi army took advantage of the
opening in order to attack the Iraqi National Congress, and shatter
what was left of the CIA's presence in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi army quickly pulled back, and Barzani's reward was to
gain control of Irbil, the major city in the Kurdish region.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his betrayal, the Clinton administration soon decided it
could not afford to give up on Barzani, since his deal with Saddam
had turned him into the dominant Kurdish leader.
</P>
<P>
   Washington officials reopened talks with him soon after Saddam's
move to crush the Iraqi National Congress, and this month David
Welch, principal deputy assistant secretary of state for Near
Eastern affairs, met with both Kurdish leaders to try to mediate
peace talks between them. A fragile cease-fire has been in effect
between the two groups since October.
</P>
<P>
   Now, U.S. officials believe that the fact that Baghdad has
expressed anger over Welch's visit and Barzani's decision to
re-engage with the United States is the best evidence that the
administration's policy is the right one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at a signal it will send to have Barzani standing
here,'' said a U.S. official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
