<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS &LR;      07-24 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-STARR NEGOTIATIONS INDICATE STRATEGY SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorneys for President Clinton are negotiating
with the independent counsel over how Clinton can provide testimony
to the federal grand jury investigating the Monica Lewinsky
allegations without appearing in person, White House officials
acknowledged Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, carried out between Clinton's personal
attorney, David Kendall, and Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, signal a possibly dramatic strategic shift by the president
in his response to the probe, and are yet another in a string of
indications that the investigation, begun in late-January, may now
be hurtling towards a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that Mr. Kendall will try to work out something
with Mr. Starr's office so that the grand jury or Mr. Starr gets
the information they need,'' White House spokesman Michael McCurry
said Friday. ``I can't tell you what the status of discussions are
that the lawyers are having.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing secrecy rules, McCurry refused to say whether Clinton had
received a subpoena from independent counsel Kenneth Starr to
appear before the grand jury, though there was no indication that a
subpoena had been issued. Legal analysts said such a subpoena would
be unprecedented and would likely be fought by Clinton all the way
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand jury proceedings are held in secret, and deliberations
related to grand jury proceedings are secret because we don't rush
to the assumption that people are guilty merely because grand
juries are meeting,'' McCurry said. ``Remember?''
</P>
<P>
   Within the administration, officials said privately that Kendall
is attempting to reach an arrangement with Starr that would allow
the president to voluntarily provide videotaped testimony recorded
from the White House, rather than visit the grand jury room in
person. Under this arrangement, Clinton could avoid what aides
believe would be a demeaning drive to the US District Court and the
walk up the courthouse steps that would play countless times on the
network news.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials increasingly regard a subpoena from Starr
as an inevitability, and launched this latest round of discussions
in an attempt to cut the best deal they could, according to aides
and analysts. ``It's an effort to look purer than the other guy,
Starr,'' said Paul Rothstein, a professor at Georgetown Law Center.
``They are trying to look like they are being open and making
offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials within the White House also said that Clinton's
lawyers have been engaged in discussions with Starr's office, on
and off, for several months, though those discussions have taken on
a new, more hopeful tone within the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   The acknowledgement of legal negotiations by the White House
came hours after reports that a uniformed Secret Service officer
testified before the grand jury this week that he and former White
House aide Harold Ickes saw Clinton alone with Monica Lewinsky in a
small study off the Oval Office on a Saturday morning in early
1996. Ickes, now a consultant and informal adviser to Clinton, has
emphatically denied the assertion, and the report carried no
indication that the two men witnessed anything sexual between the
president and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Associated Press report, a White House operator
contacted a Secret Service officer standing guard outside the Oval
Office door saying there was a telephone call for Clinton. The
guard, in turn, saw Ickes walking by and asked him to alert Clinton
to the call. When Ickes and the guard went inside the Oval Office,
they did not see Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The two men walked down a short hallway to a private study just
off the Oval Office and saw Clinton and Lewinsky inside the room,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person on the record in that story is Mr. Ickes, and
he is saying it didn't happen,'' said James Kennedy, a spokesman
for the White House legal counsel. ``Beyond that, I have no
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in a January depositition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit that he had no recollection of ever being alone
with Lewinsky. That assertion was called into question by retired
Secret Service officer Lewis Fox, who told the grand jury that he
recalled Clinton and Lewinsky were in the Oval Office for 40
minutes, alone as far he could tell, one Saturday while he stood
guard outside. Lewis later said through his attorney that he could
not be certain, from his vantage point, that the two were alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president did not speak truthfully in the Jones case,
he would be in a very precarious position now,'' said Jonathan
Turley, a criminal defense lawyer and professor at George
Washington University law school. ``If he lied under oath, he would
have to admit an earlier act of perjury or recommit an act of
perjury. If the president commits perjury, few Democrats in
Congress could treat the matter lightly in an impeachment vote.''
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's daily briefing, McCurry attempted to stave off rapid
fire questions on whether Clinton had received a subpoena and why
he was negotiating over his possible testimony. For months, Clinton
aides have privately speculated on the president's possible
testimony, with many advisers believing that his refusal to testify
might prove catastrophic to the Democratic party, especially the
congressional candidates in the autumn elections.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several weeks, the level of intensity in Starr's
investigation has surged. First, Starr brought Pentagon aide Linda
Tripp, who made the secret tape recordings of Lewinsky, before the
grand jury, in a signal that he was reaching the end of his witness
list.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he won a crucial US Appeals Court ruling that
required Secret Service agents to honor subpoenas and testify
before the grand jury, marking the first time a president's
bodyguards were forced to provide information about the man they
are supposed to protect. The Supreme Court upheld that ruling the
following day, and Starr immediately brought several uniformed
officers before a grand jury to begin taking evidence.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he shuttled Ickes and Clinton's personal secretary,
Betty Currie, back before the grand jurors, and called in Secret
Service agent Larry Cockell, the head of Clinton's elite security
detail. Starr summoned the federal grand jury to the courthouse on
Wednesday, which is normally a day off for the jurors, and on
Thursday he actually used two separate grand juries to hear
testimony in an apparent effort to hasten the pace of the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has appeared so busy that he actually postponed the
completion of Tripp's testimony at least until next week.
</P>
<P>
   All the activity has been followed closely by Clinton, his aides
and his lawyers, who have seen their legal appeals and various
manuevers dissolving in the face of various legal rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy who has been working at a somewhat leisurely pace,
to now move to two grand juries at the same time shows he is moving
faster,'' said Ann Lewis, Clinton's communications director. ``We
see what everyone else can see that he is in a state of activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three known potential witnesses remain, Clinton being one
of them. The other two are Clinton's deputy legal counsel and close
confidante, Bruce Lindsey, and Lewinsky herself.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey has been subpoenaed to testify, but Clinton's lawyers
are trying to block that testimony on the grounds that it violates
attorney/client privilege. Starr is asserting that Lindsey is a
government attorney, and thus would not be covered. The case is
pending in federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors appear unsure about whether they will indict
Lewinsky for perjury, grant her immunity or summon her before the
grand jury and provide her limited immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need Monica Lewinsky desperately, Starr does, or he has a
circumstantial case,'' said Paul Rothstein, a Georgetown Law Center
professor. ``He would like to have Bruce Lindsey because Lindsey
was close to everything going on. And he would like to get the
president on record and catch him in a lie in a more serious
proceeding than the dismissed Paula Jones case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
