<HEADER>
A2105 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ICOS-$ADV26-AR     07-24 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ICOS-$ADV26-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UPSTART WITH FRIENDS IN THE HIGHEST OF PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic showing list of board members for ICOS; List of
drugs in he pipeline of ICOS will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
(af) 
 By ANNE TERGESEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Icos is anything but a typical development-stage biotechnology
company.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, like others in the field, it has yet to market a product or
to make a profit from operations. (It announced on Thursday that it
had lost $9.4 million in the second quarter, or 24 cents a share, a
bit more than analysts had forecast.)
</P>
<P>
   And a familiar kind of industry hype has begun to swirl around
one of its projects _ a compound that bullish analysts predict will
supplant Pfizer's runaway hit impotence drug, Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   But look who's behind the Icos Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In a field populated by shoestring operations run by starry-eyed
scientists and littered with failures, Icos, based in Bothell,
Wash., has managed to attract some of the bluest of blue-chip names
in corporate America to its board. Its roster of directors, which
would make any Fortune 500 company proud, never mind a 275-employee
fledgling, includes heavyweights like Walter B. Wriston, former
chairman of Citicorp; Frank T. Cary, former president of IBM; James
L. Ferguson, former chairman of General Foods, and William H.
Gates, chairman of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up the A-list board to the credibility of Icos' chairman
and chief executive, George B. Rathmann, whose previous effort in
the field yielded the Amgen Corp., the world's largest
biotechnology company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, his enormous success at Amgen gave anyone who was
contemplating this thing a lot of confidence,'' said Wriston, who
holds a stake in Icos valued at about $3 million and _ like the
majority of the board _ has been with the company since its
inception in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these luminaries have invested more than their time and
reputations. Gates and Rathmann are Icos' two largest shareholders
and have injected capital into the company several times. ``If
there was an equity offering, we would always be available,''
Rathmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates became involved in 1990, when Paine Webber was setting up
Icos' first round of financing. ``We had dinner, and the next day
he put in $5 million and joined our board,'' Rathmann said of
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, having the country's richest man on the team is no
guarantee of success. But it adds substance to the buzz surrounding
Icos' potential Viagra replacement, a compound called IC351.
</P>
<P>
   Too new to have a brand name, IC351 works in a way that is
similar to Viagra and will be available in pill form, as Viagra is.
But IC351 appears to be more selective than Viagra in blocking an
enzyme that can prevent erections; the advantage may eliminate
side-effects associated with Viagra, including a temporary
blue-green tinge in vision.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Murray, senior biotechnology analyst at Lehman Brothers,
said, ``IC351 could be as large or larger than Viagra,'' which
Lehman expects to generate $900 million in sales this year and $1.5
billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And analysts say Icos' drugs run a below-average risk of
flopping in clinical trials because Icos does more careful
laboratory groundwork than many biotechnology hothouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Icos is very well known for the high quality of the research
they do,'' said Mary Ann Gray, senior vice president at Raymond
James &AMP; Associates. ``They take their time and do things correctly
and have a solid background.''
</P>
<P>
   But Icos isn't depending on IC351 alone. In its research
pipeline are a number of promising drugs aimed at large markets _ a
fact that cheers David Simpson, manager of the WM Northwest Fund
and the WM Emerging Growth fund. The two funds bought Icos in 1995
and now have a $13.4 million stake.
</P>
<P>
   Icos is conducting preliminary trials of four drugs to treat
nine diseases and conditions, including stroke, multiple sclerosis
and asthma. Its goal is to have at least two of those compounds,
possibly including IC351, in the pivotal third and final stage of
clinical trials by the end of the year, said Lacy J. Fitzpatrick,
the company's associate director for investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   The great challenge faced by most biotechnology companies _ how
to keep the bills paid until products are ready to market _ doesn't
look like it will faze Icos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to capital for that company is not going to be
difficult, especially with a strong stock price and the board they
have,'' said Jay Silverman, senior biotechnology analyst at
Robertson Stephens. Most biotechnology companies find themselves
having to trade away rights to their discoveries to raise
development cash from richer partners, but Icos can afford to hold
tight to its rights and the profits they promise, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Icos turned to creating limited partnerships, a way of
raising development capital that fell out of favor in the
biotechnology field in the early 1990s after several product
failures. The company has raised about $150 million so far by
transferring rights to three of its compounds (but not IC351) to a
partnership and selling interests in it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sharing in royalty income from the drugs, the
limited partners get warrants to buy company stock; Icos retains
the right to buy back the partnership interests. Gates and Rathmann
have each bought partnership stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The degree to which we control our destiny is more important
than anything else,'' Rathmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, the fund manager, is impressed with Icos' ability to
retain its independence. ``If they chose to partner with one of the
big pharmaceutial companies, they don't have to give away all the
value in order to get money for research,'' he observed. Icos has
forged alliances with Abbott Laboratories and Japan's Suntory,
under which Icos shares but does not surrender rights. Analysts
expect something similar for IC351.
</P>
<P>
   Given Icos' advantages, is the company's $20 stock price a good
value? A growing number of short-sellers apparently believe the
stock is headed for a fall: As of June 15, the uncovered short
interest in Icos stock had swollen to 2.28 million shares, triple
the level of a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But Simpson disagreed with the short-sellers. ``I don't think
it's overvalued,'' he said. ``It's tough to find biotechnology
companies with nine drugs in phase 2 trials. If they all flop, you
are overpaying, but if just one of them works, you're well
rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say investors in the volatile biotechnology field must
take the long view. ``I would never recommend someone buy the stock
unless they were long-term holders, by which I mean at least three
years,'' said Andrew Heyward, director of research at Ragen
MacKenzie of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Icos expects to have at least one product on the
market _ all it should need to turn a profit, Rathmann said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2013EDT &QL; 
