<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-SLEEP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN IN HOSPITAL TEST OF SLEEP DRUG DOSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Donning a special night cap that picks up his brain
waves and a motion-sensing wrist device that tells researchers when
he's asleep, Sen. John Glenn spent Friday night in a laboratory at
Brigham and Women's Hospital while researchers monitored his
biorhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's laboratory sleepover began a unique experiment that will
culminate three months from now, when the once and future astronaut
will rocket into space for the second time in his long life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, Glenn became the first American to orbit the Earth.
This fall the Ohio senator, who turned 77 a week ago, will become
the oldest human to escape the planet's bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now pioneering a different kind of frontier,'' said Dr.
Charles A. Czeisler, who is running the experiment _ and who
recalled Friday evening at a hospital press conference how thrilled
he was, as a boy of 10, when Glenn orbited the Earth in his tiny
Friendship 7 space capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really know how to make a guy feel old,'' quipped the
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's new frontier might be called space gerontology _ the
study of the physiologic changes induced by space travel, which in
many respects are curiously similar to the slower ravages of age.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that he wanted to be a doctor before World War II came
along and turned him into a celebrated fighter pilot and member of
the first elite group of astronauts, Glenn listed the parallels
between aging and space travel effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are sleep changes, immune system changes, cardiovascular
changes. Bones become thinner and muscles break down even though
you exercise,'' he said. ``If we can determine what turns these
systems on and off, we will not only benefit astronauts but will
have made a great step forward in benefiting the old and frail here
on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Half of all elders have trouble sleeping, Glenn said. (He said
he isn't one of them.) Disordered sleep patterns impair the health
of one-third of all elders, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Difficulty sleeping well and staying alert when they must has
plagued astronauts since the dawn of space travel 36 years ago.
During orbital flight, day and night alternate every 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Czeisler, a specialist in circadian rhythms, began working with
NASA in the early 1990s, when an astronaut read a newspaper article
about his success in using precisely timed doses of bright light to
reset the circadian clocks of shift workers.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting the Harvard Medical School researcher, the astronauts
quickly became convinced of the effectiveness of the light
treatment _ they took to calling Czeisler ``Dr. Light'' _ and
insisted on retrofitting their crew quarters with bright-light
devices to put them in synch with their flight schedules before
boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Now Czeisler and his colleagues are studying Glenn and his
fellow astronaut Dr. Chiaki Mukai, a Japanese cardiovascular
surgeon who will be on the same Space Shuttle flight, to see if
their internal clocks can be reset less cumbersomely, by well-timed
capsules of melatonin.
</P>
<P>
   Melatonin is a natural hormone the brain manufactures every
night to tell the body it's time to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The pills that Glenn and Mukai will take in space are the same
stuff many travelers swallow in the hope it will alleviate jet lag,
except the astronauts' pills contain pharmaceutical-grade melatonin
at a dose that mimics the brain's nightly output.
</P>
<P>
   The melatonin pills many people purchase at their local pharmacy
or health food store elevate blood levels of the hormone 50 to 100
times more than normal, which mean daytime levels are higher than
they should be. Furthermore, the over-the-counter hormone is often
adulterated with other chemicals that may render it useless.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies, such as one the Harvard researchers conducted
on astronauts aboard a space shuttle flight last April, suggest
that a tiny dose of pure melatonin, a mere 0.3 milligrams, may work
best.
</P>
<P>
   The April experiment and the upcoming one involving Glenn and
Mukai, Czeisler pointed out, are the first rigorously conducted
trials of any pharmaceutical ever done in space.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn responded to skeptics who note that science can learn
little from such tiny experiments _ and imply that the real reason
for Glenn's flight is to fulfill a US senator's personal wish to
return to space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, where do you start except with a data point of one?''
Glenn said. ``This is more than a one-shot deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
