<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TACKLE SEEKS EDGE FROM TRAINING IN MARTIAL ARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ He is one of the more celebrated former
residents of this military town, having cut his teeth for 13 months
here in pilot training at Sheppard Air Force Base from 1988-89.
There are now thousands of Wichita Falls residents claiming they
hung out with Chad Hennings before his professional football days.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the focus on Hennings wanes when it comes to talk about the
Cowboys' defensive line. Fans go crazy if Leon Lett does anything
extraordinary on the practice field; they scream his nickname,
``Big Cat,'' in approval. Assistant coaches have gone crazy
preparing tenderfoot ends Greg Ellis and Kavika Pittman for NFL
action.
</P>
<P>
   Hennings, entering his fourth season as a starting defensive
tackle, has been an afterthought. That is not to say Hennings is
not expected to make a big difference this year. In fact, after
eight days of camp, defensive line coach Jim Bates has already
declared that Hennings ``is on the way to having his best year.''
</P>
<P>
   If you know Bates, then you know he is pretty enthusiastic and
positive about everything. But when you consider that Hennings is
finally healthy after two years of nagging groin and elbow injuries
and his work with a tae kwan do expert to take some of the
``stiffness'' out of his pass-rushing technique, then you can see
why Bates is ebullient.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, Hennings will have something new to throw at
opposing offensive linemen in 1998. Perhaps that alone will equate
to a few more big plays for a unit that was 18th in sacks and 24th
against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year Leon was out and I was injured, which caused a lot
of problems for us,'' Hennings said. ``Then the frustration with
things not going well set in and that caused some penalties and a
lack of turnovers created by our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennings refused to put the entire blame on injuries. He knew he
needed to improve. His coaches knew as well. Look at him. He looks
like he could play the part of a superhero with his 6-foot-6,
295-pound chiseled frame, and his bench press of well over 500
pounds. But his impact the past few years has not quite measured
up.
</P>
<P>
   He has 9.5 sacks the past two years, fewer than most Pro Bowl
tackles get in a season. He has only seven tackles for losses,
three pass knockdowns, and two forced fumbles in the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad has always been steady, but making more plays _ like
pressuring the quarterback, knocking balls down, sacking the
quarterback, getting hits at the line of scrimmage in the running
game, that's where he can pick it up,'' Bates said. ``And we expect
him to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that, the Cowboys hired former tae kwan do champ Joe
Kim to work with the defensive line. A medalist for the United
States at the 1989 Pan Am Games, Kim was the perfect candidate to
show Cowboys linemen how to use their hands to escape the grips of
offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Hennings was Kim's first client.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Day One in working with Chad, I found him to be a little
robotic, kind of mechanical,'' said Kim, who first used his
martial-arts skills with Cleveland Browns linemen from 1991-95.
``Now, watching him, he's very fluent. His hands never stop.
Instead of thinking about what to do, he just does it. It's like
somebody learning to dance. After the first few moves, you are in
the flow of things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stiff? A little bit,'' Bates said, ``things weren't happening
fluidly. Now, though, everything is working together. He is quicker
with his hands in getting the offensive lineman's hands off of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope, now, is that Hennings can combine this new-found
technique with brute strength to make offenses key on him with the
same kind of energy that they use on Lett.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that happens will not be known for at least another
month, Hennings said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see a difference,'' Hennings said, ``but until we play a
real game, you just won't know for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
