<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YARAFAT ANNOUNCES MORE MEETINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Rumors of the collapse of Israeli-Palestinian talks
on the peace process seem to have been greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian President Yasser Arafat said Friday the two sides
would have more meetings next week to try and bring an end to the
16-month deadlock on the handover by Israel of more West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's announcement came at the end of a week in which the
Palestinians said that three days of direct talks had collapsed,
and the Israeli government appealed to the United States to step in
to mediate.
</P>
<P>
   Peace moves have been deadlocked mainly over Jewish settlement
building, Palestinian suicide bombings and the scope of an Israeli
troop pullback from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   With the process long stalled, the United States has continued
to back away from its active mediating role and told the two sides
that they must resolve how to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton told reporters Thursday at the White House
that he still believes the talks can get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't thrown in the towel because I think it is a lot
better to get an agreement, to get them in final status talks, than
it is to give up and let this thing drift dangerously toward
conflict,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is easy to be confused by US policy on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the US State Department publicly talked
tough about the ``endgame'' and warning that the ``ball was in
Israel's court'' to act on the US proposal which lies at the center
of the current debate.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has proposed a 13.1 percent further withdrawal
from the West Bank at this stage without clearly defining whether
there would be a third withdrawal before the so-called final status
talks as outlined in the historic 1993 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians accepted the US proposal, although it is far
short of their expectations of a 30 percent withdrawal at this
stage. The Israelis have rejected it, saying that they can accept
no more than a 10 percent withdrawal while still ensuring security
and protecting water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the current hurdle is cleared, most analysts say the far
more complex and potentially irreconcilable differences between the
two sides will emerge in the final status talks on Jerusalem.
Israel captured East Jerusalem in 1967 and sees it as part of its
eternal and indivisible capital. The Palestinians see East
Jerusalem as the site of a future state.
</P>
<P>
   The final deadline of the peace agreement is May 4, 1999. Arafat
has vowed to unilaterally declare a Palestinian state at that
point. That declaration, combined with deep frustrations and failed
promises on both sides, could embroil the Middle East in what many
experts -- Israeli and Palestinian alike -- believe could be a
military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk has termed it an
``explosive situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high stakes and the tough talk earlier this month by
State Department officials, now the United States is calling for
patience as the clock ticks on.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli analysts believe domestic politics play a large
part in the delay. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu may be
trying to buy time until the end of this month when the Israeli
Knesset recesses for the summer. That, experts believe, would help
Netanyahu avoid the no-confidence vote that the far right and even
hawks in his own cabinet, such as Minister Ariel Sharon, have
threatened to use to topple the fractious coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Politics aside, a Gallup poll released Friday confirmed that 59
percent of Israelis support the US-proposed transfer of 13 percent
of the West Bank to Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Rubin, an expert on the peace process for Bar Illan
University's BESA Center for Strategic Studies, says the fact that
each side is entrenched in its own position and threatening to walk
out shows the process is close to moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   It is, he says, the essence of Middle East bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers around the world are interpreting that as the edge
of a breakdown. It is not correct. As long as it makes progress, as
long as both sides want to keep the talks alive, it will work,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace process is not a tightrope that we can fall off
of,'' he adds. ``It is a roller-coaster that will go up and down
but stay on the tracks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
