<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COIN-TOSS-ELECTION-AR     07-24 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COIN-TOSS-ELECTION-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE A FLIP OF A COIN DECIDES THE ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mo., N.D., N.J., Ohio, Pa., S.D., Va., Wis.)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(js) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL, N.D. _ Back in Jersey, they would never believe it.
</P>
<P>
   First, Vinnie Amato Jr., a Buick salesman from Newark, gets
himself elected mayor of Crystal, N.D., population 222 in a good
year.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Hizzoner gets the proverbial boot _ and some jail time _
after an unfortunate and still somewhat shadowy incident involving
rabbit hunting, arm wrestling, some stunning fettuccine Alfredo and
a drive-by shoot-'em-up in the neighboring town of Hoople. (More on
that later).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Amato wins his old job back. How? On the night of June
23, someone flipped a coin and Amato called it in the air. Heads.
Now he is mayor again.
</P>
<P>
   The coin-flipping was perfectly kosher. In fact, because Amato
was neck and neck with another candidate, the coin flip was
explicitly required by North Dakota law.
</P>
<P>
   Other states do the same. Coin flips have decided tie votes in
Missouri, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin, for example. When
candidates tie in Virginia, the winner's name is plucked out of a
hat.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago in South Dakota, the man who had been the Stanley
County prosecutor for 22 years was unseated when he lost a game of
poker _ five card stud _ to a pair of red tens. In Arizona, a card
game determined the winner of a 1988 City Council seat in Show Low
(named, coincidentally, for a game played there in 1876 to see
which of two rival businessmen would have to leave town).
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure beats the heck out of dueling pistols,'' said Doug Lewis,
executive director of the Election Center, a nonprofit group for
election officials.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a new election would be ``very, very expensive,'' said
Richard Smolka, editor of Election Administration. ``The number of
votes cast is very, very small. The voters tried. They couldn't
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   In North Dakota this summer, 12 elections were decided by
tossing a coin or drawing lots, said Cory Fong, the state elections
director. Of course, Fong and others who butter their bread with
democracy would love things to be different. But with small towns
getting smaller, it is hard enough to find someone who wants to run
for office, let alone want to run again to break a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Fong tells the story of one longtime town official who decided
not to seek re-election this year and was excoriated by his
constituents. ``They said: `You've been serving our town for so
many years. We still have potholes. We're overtaxed. And now you
have the nerve to not even run again.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is,'' Fong added. ``Something has to happen
that inspires people to serve.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Vinnie Amato, one of the truly inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Love brought Amato, 41, to this remote, flyspeck of a city in
the northeastern corner of North Dakota. After selling Buicks,
Dodges and Toyotas for 18 years in New Jersey, Amato went to Miami,
where he fell in love with a woman named Nancy Salwei from Crystal.
In 1993, he followed her home.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal was the polar opposite of everything Amato had known, a
blink in a blanket of farmers' fields, silos instead of
smokestacks, endless echoing miles of wheat, potatoes and sugar
beets, an astronomical plant-per-person ratio. Most folks, politely
laconic farmers of Scandinavian descent, had never met someone with
his Popeye physique, ponytailed hair, chunky gold rings and gold
Italian horn dangling from his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was,'' Amato said, ``an adjustment period.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, Amato had become a sensation by opening Vinnie's Pizza
and Pasta in the back of a bar in Hoople. ``An Italian is making a
ripple here in the heart of Norwegian potato country,'' said The
Grand Forks Herald, the regional newspaper, quoting patrons who
called his fettuccine ``to die for'' and liked his concession to
cattle country, the Philly cheese steak.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Amato ran for mayor of Crystal. He got 21 votes. There
was no other candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Things were going fine. The municipal dam was fixed and city
officials got raises (the next mayor's annual salary would increase
to $600 from $400).
</P>
<P>
   Then a friend told the police that Amato had committed a
drive-by shooting in Hoople. Amato admits that he was in a Ford
Bronco, coming back from rabbit hunting, angry at three young men
who had bloodied his friends after arm-wrestling matches in the bar
where he cooked his pasta. He also admits that someone in the
Bronco fired a semiautomatic rifle at the apartment building where
the young men lived, injuring no one but driving the young men out
of town.
</P>
<P>
   Amato says he was railroaded into pleading guilty to a felony
charge of reckless endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he attended City Council meetings while on work
release from the county jail, where he was serving 110 days. But
then someone in Crystal realized that it is illegal in North Dakota
to be mayor while incarcerated. A new mayor took office, but quit
after only one year.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, when Amato, still on probation and now the
proprietor of the Corner Bar in Crystal _ its slogan: You Don't
Have to be Bad to Sit in the Corner _ sought the mayor's job again,
things looked good. The only other candidate moved out of town and
had to drop out. Then somebody started a write-in campaign for Gary
Barclay, a city councilman.
</P>
<P>
   Each man received 29 votes, a tie that might have been avoided
if Barclay's wife had gone to the polls or if a friend of Amato had
remembered to vote. And so it was up to a quarter, tossed by the
outgoing mayor and landing on the floor, George Washington-side up.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, who plans to frame the quarter and display it in his bar,
is excited about the future of Crystal. In a community where the
biggest issue is ``dogs at large,'' the new mayor is systematically
surveying residents about their concerns. ``I'm going to make it
the hub'' of Pembina County, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to bring a little Jersey here,'' Amato
said. ``I'm pretty much direct. I say, `This needs to be done and
that needs to be done _ let's go do it.' It's not an ego trip. I
firmly believe that small towns can survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he added, ``If I went to Jersey tomorrow, they'd say,
`Who'd you pay for a double-headed coin?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
