<SLUG> BC-MA-SEX-REGISTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE SEX-OFFENDER LAW UPHELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL LANGNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Supreme Judicial Court upheld Friday the state's
sex offender registry law which requires all sex offenders to
notify police of their presence in the community in which they
reside.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-1 decision, the court rejected two Superior Court rulings
which held that the law improperly gives the power to classify
offenders to the Sex Offender Registry, an appointed board, instead
of a court.
</P>
<P>
   The two judges who made that ruling did so after two unnamed sex
offenders argued that the current law has no procedure to let them
challenge the board's conclusion that they should be classified as
Level 3, or most likely to offend again.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men was convicted of raping his 12-year-old
step-daughter and the other of raping his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The offenders also had argued the board used the so-called
``preponderance of the evidence,'' standard to make its
classification, instead of the stricter standard of ``clear and
convincing evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Superior Court judges declared the entire sex
offender registry law unconstitutional and the other ruled that
part of it was. Both judges, aware of the controversial nature or
their rulings, reported their decisions to the Appeals Court, but
the SJC independently took the case for direct review.
</P>
<P>
   In a 21-page opinion written by Justice Roderick Ireland, the
court threw out both Superior Court rulings, but it also orders the
state sex offenders review board to hold hearings again on the two
cases.
</P>
<P>
   If the board finds that both men should be classified as Level
3, the court ruled, it must back its judgment with specific
reasons, and it must so find by a preponderance of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC declined to declare the law unconstitutional. The court
said that when a law makes no provisions for appeal hearings, they
had in the past required such hearings and had helped devise
appropriate procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in dissent, Justice Margaret Marshall agreed with the
majority opinion _ that the state sex offender registry board, a
comparitively new body, should be allowed to make its own rulings
on an offender's dangerousness, and that the board should have time
to establish its own procedures before the SJC is asked to decide
if they are constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``due process requires that proof be by clear and
convincing evidence,'' Marshall wrote,
</P>
<P>
   The law was patterned after New Jersey's, which was drawn up
after 7-year-old Megan Kanka was raped and murdered in 1994 by a a
paroled repeat sex offender who had moved into her neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts law was passed in October 1996. The registry
board consists of five unpaid members who work without a staff, and
offenders are required to register under the honor system.
</P>
<P>
   Since it went into effect, the sex offender registry law has
been repeatedly challenged in court, and critics have pointed out
numerous loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gilberto Sanchez, a convicted sex offender, was
arrested after he allegedly entered the room of a sleeping
12-year-old girl in Framingham and fondled her. Sanchez had been
registered as a sex offender in Boston, but moved from Boston to
Framingham without telling police.
</P>
<P>
   A new sex offender registry bill, in the House Ways and Means
Committee, would plug some of the holes. Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci
has been pushing for the bill to emerge for a vote before the
legislative session ends July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSUICIDE-COX     07-24 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSUICIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta man leads cyberspace rescue
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- His computer screen said there was a message pending,
but Michael Cline went to lunch. When he returned, his heart sank:
Melissa from Colorado was going to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time you read this I will be gone. Gone as in dead. I
have tried before and now know what will work,'' wrote Melissa, 24,
on Tuesday. She said she was an alcoholic and pregnant. ``And I
hate the person I have become.''
</P>
<P>
   She wrote personal goodbyes to the sign-on names of a dozen
faceless on-line friends as far away as Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Cline lives in the Druid Hills area and is a Hare Krishna
believer. Melissa was searching for something and often questioned
him about his faith.
</P>
<P>
   Panicked, Cline immediately created an on-line chat room to get
his cyberfriends working on finding her. And he frantically called
the Internet service provider America Online, trying to get it to
find her through their records.
</P>
<P>
   A passerby found the woman later that day, unconscious, on a
park bike path in Westminster, a Denver suburb. Her stomach was
pumped and she survived.
</P>
<P>
   Cline and another chat buddy, Don Viner, of Omaha, Neb., said
Friday they had bombarded AOL with calls but were frustrated by the
service's seeming indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they handled it was terrible,'' said Viner, who was
trasferred within AOL and dumped into voicemail boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Viner, who installs computers for a living, took over the
``command-central'' Cline had set up. Viner used three phone lines:
one for e-mail, one for incoming calls and another for outgoing
calls. He and his cyberbuddies called metro Denver police
departments looking for a needle in a haystack _ a girl they only
knew as Melissa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought she might be lying there dying,'' said Cline. ``I
talked to AOL and later got a form letter. It said it might take
the company 72 hours to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL officials declined to comment Friday, but said employees are
trained for such emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our protocol is to treat (possible emergency calls)
seriously,'' said John Ryan, AOL assistant counsel for AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Westminister police said they could find no evidence AOL called
the department during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled everything I could find and we don't show AOL
calling, '' police spokesman Jim Buckner told the Denver Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
