A2131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-COX     07-24 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House passes wide-ranging health care legislation
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Prodded by a growing public frustration with health
insurance companies, the House passed legislation Friday that calls
for dramatically changing the way health care is administered
across the country by giving patients a way to appeal when they are
denied treatment and imposing steep penalties for failing to
address the needs of patients.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted by a narrow 216 to 210 margin to pass the
wide-ranging bill, despite a veto threat hovering over the measure
and despite an attempt by Michigan Democrat John Dingell and Iowa
Republican Greg Ganske to offer a bill that would have gone even
farther than the Republican bill.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a day for Georgia Republican Charlie Norwood, a
dentist, who has made overhauling managed care the central thrust
of his two terms in Congress. Norwood did so against the wishes of
the Republican leadership and the business community that helped
him get to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have wanted this to happen for a long time,'' said a smiling
Norwood, following the vote. ``For the first time since 1974,
health care is going to go back to two people: the patient and the
doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill will impact 161 million consumers with private
insurance. Managed care plans now insure more than 75 percent of
Americans and hold down costs by limited access to doctors and
tests.
</P>
<P>
   This bill attempts to open up that access by allowing women for
example to go directly to their gynecologist and children to go
directly to their pediatrician. The bill would also make it easier
for patients to seek emergency care and lift rules that prevent
doctors from having full discussion with their doctors about health
care choices. Most importantly, it gives patients access to an
external review process if they are unhappy about decisions made by
their health management company.
</P>
<P>
   That appeals process would be enforced with fines of up to $500
per day up to $250,000 for decisions that are made by insurers ``in
bad faith.'' Health plans that ignore the advice of the doctor
would also face fines, which Republicans say gives a judge the
opportunity to make a punitive damage assessment against
out-of-line health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill does not remove the liability protections that
Norwood and a bill proposed by Dingell and Ganske had sought. Those
liability protections were at the heart of the rancorous dispute
over how best to regulate managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a 1974 law known as the Employee Retirement Income
Security Act. The law, which was set up to address concerns that
corrupt pension managers were illegally taking money from federal
pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   The law has come under fire today because it precludes
individuals from suing their insurance companies for punitive
damages. Under current law, a patient can not collect more than the
cost of the denied treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight now goes to the Senate chamber where a managed
care bill could come up for a vote as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will protect consumers from abuses in the
managed care industry while increasing access to affordable
alternatives,'' said Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, during debate on
the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   The vote for the Dingell-Ganske bill was close enough that it
showed the splinter in the GOP, with some Republicans balking at
the idea of supporting a measure that would grant liability
protection to the managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier vote on the Dingell-Ganske measure, the House
voted 217 to 212 to reject the measure, which had the strong
backing of Georgia Democrat John Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many patients are paying more and getting less,'' Lewis
said. ``The differences are clear. Democrats are concerned about
protecting patients. Republicans are concerned about big business
and insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the health care system is clearly broke when a
``doctor had to fight his insurance company to get coverage to
treat his cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe in the free market, if you believe in the power
of individual choice, if you believe our private health care system
is really the best in the world, then listen up,'' said Rep. Jim
McCrery, R-La.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bill has a long way to go before it becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Office of Management and Budget said in a
statement the GOP bill ``provides too few patient protections, and
it contains unnecessary and irrelevant provisions that undermine
the chances for bipartisan agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's senior advisers would recommend that he veto
this bill if it were presented to him by the Congress,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
