<SLUG> BC-SIXMONTHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King faces many challenges as SCLC President
 &HT;    By Kimberly H. Byrd
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When Martin Luther King III is sworn in today as the
fourth president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
he will face several challenges, including how to bring the
old-line civil rights organization into the future. He also will be
searching for a diplomatic way to heal wounds inflicted in April
when the SCLC board vote 10-9 to sever ties with SCLC/W.O.M.E.N.
</P>
<P>
   King had hoped to have that challenge behind him before he
headed to Washington for the organization's 41st annual convention,
which begins today and ends Wednesday. But when he met last week
with Evelyn Lowery, founder and president of SCLC/W.O.M.E.N., they
were at an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgement, we made a mistake on voting on terminology
that created this particular rift,'' King said. ``The intent was to
bring SCLC/W.O.M.E.N. back under the umbrella of the organization
and restructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery - whose husband, the Rev. Joseph Lowery, is immediate
past president of SCLC - was quoted in the Washington Post as
saying the reason given was ``that we were competing with them ...
for money, I guess.'' She did not return numerous phone calls last
week, and when a reporter visited her office, a worker said through
the intercom that Lowery was unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   But Clayola Brown, a member of both boards, characterized the
discussions as ``relatively productive, although not conclusive.''
She did not attend the meeting, but she remains hopeful resolution
is near.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of SCLC, including women, have played a role in making
sure human rights have been protected,'' Brown said in a phone
interview from her New York office. ``I'm hopeful the women's
element within SCLC can take on more aggressive leadership roles
within the organization and help format where SCLC is going.''
</P>
<P>
   SCLC/W.O.M.E.N. has sponsored a Civil Rights Heritage Tour,
awarded scholarships, held an annual Strengthening the Black Family
Conference and participated in prison ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Given that history, William Boone, an associate professor of
political science at Clark Atlanta University, wondered why the
SCLC board would tinker with the women's group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon the news reports, that was definitely a boo-boo,''
Boone said. ``You do not begin an organization's new thrust by
alienating the base.''
</P>
<P>
   But King said SCLC will rise up from this impasse a unified
organization. And he said he has already begun to formulate goals
that he'll present during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a blue suit, striped white shirt and a multi-colored
tie, King spoke candidly from his modest Auburn Avenue office about
how he intends to breathe new life into the organization his
father, the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., founded in 1957 with the
Rev. Ralph David Abernathy Jr., Lowery and other ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three to five years, King said the organization's
focus will be on mentoring youth, preserving affirmative action,
caring for the elderly, improving education, forming corporate
partnerships, recruiting new members and erasing environmental
injustices in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for bringing those goals to fruition, he said, will be
hammered out in August when he convenes a meeting with SCLC
staffers and board members.
</P>
<P>
   Some are wondering whether the 40-year-old King has what it
takes to lift the organization to the level of notoriety it enjoyed
in the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Martin King is untried,'' Boone said. ``He served on
the Fulton County Board of Commissioners, but I'm not quite certain
that's the kind of experience one needs.''
</P>
<P>
   What King does need, according to Boone and others, is
organization skills and the ability to raise money. He also needs
to immediately organize a coherent, unified national staff and to
develop a mission plan for chapters.
</P>
<P>
   ``SCLC will require a lot of rebuilding,'' said the Rev. Timothy
McDonald, who left SCLC in 1989 after eight years as director of
Operation Breadbasket and special projects. ``It has kind of lost
its bite.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald suggests reinvigorating the organization by mobilizing
communities around ``prevalent issues for African Americans,'' like
affirmative action, AIDS and crime.
</P>
<P>
   Another key will be attracting young African-Americans, many of
whom are oblivious to the struggles of the '50s and '60s that
necessitated the creation of organizations like SCLC, said the Rev.
Gerald Durley, an SCLC member.
</P>
<P>
   Boone agreed, describing the younger generation as ``a different
kind of black people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're younger, more affluent and can't relate to the
oppression of the past,'' Boone said. ``So SCLC will have to figure
out a way to reach them.''
</P>
<P>
   King offered assurances last week that he's up to the task
</P>
<P>
   ``I now have the beginning stages of the apparatus to not just
talk about and raise issues, but to execute results,'' he said.
``Little by little as people evaluate us, they're going to be
pleased with the direction we take as an organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
