<SLUG> BC-WNBA-LANDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA's Landers in talks
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ University of Georgia women's basketball coach Andy
Landers interviewedFriday for the head coach/general manager
position of the to-be-named Minnesota franchise of the WNBA, a
school official said.
</P>
<P>
   Landers, a three-time national coach of the year, attended the
Nike All-America girls basketball camp in Indianapolis on Wednesday
and Thursday. Landers, whose wife, Pam, said he was expected to
return to Athens late Friday night, was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had candidates in this week, but they haven't
announced anything,'' said Kent Wipf, director of media relations
for the Minnesota Timberwolves, the NBA team that will operate the
WNBA franchise. ``I don't expect them to do anything until
September because they still haven't met their ticket depository
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota and Orlando were awarded WNBA franchises April 22,
with final approval dependent upon each city selling 5,000 season
tickets by September 1. The Timberwolves announced July 17 that
deposits for only 2,337 tickets had been received. The team would
begin competition in the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Timberwolves chief financial officer Roger Griffith, who will
serve as president of the WNBA franchise, didn't return telephone
messages Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Landers, 45, is the only full-time women's coach in Georgia
history, with a career record of 459-141 in 19 seasons, the
third-best mark among active Division I coaches with as much
tenure. He is just one of four coaches to make four trips to the
Final Four, with runner-up finishes in 1985 and 1996, and has won
six Southeastern Conference titles.
</P>
<P>
   Landers is the second-highest paid coach at Georgia, earning a
base salary of $117,600 in 1996 and a total package of $202,600,
which includes a $50,000 consulting fee from Nike. Landers and
gymnastics coach Suzanne Yoculan threatened the school with Title
IX sex discrimation suits in 1994, but Bulldogs athletics director
Vince Dooley averted the issue by awarding significant pay raises
to both.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
