<HEADLINE>
`SAVING PRIVATE RYAN' PRINTS DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg ran into a first-class snafu Friday morning
when copies of the new World War II film ``Saving Private Ryan''
failed to show up in some of the nation's theaters.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, about 20 prints were late arriving at area Harkins,
AMC and United Artist theaters, leaving matinee filmgoers to find
some other film to save them from the summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll settle for ``Lethal Weapon 4'' right now and catch
``Private Ryan'' later,'' said Blaine McCollum of Phoenix, voicing
the sentiment of many of the approximately 60 people in line who
were turned away from AMC's Arizona Center 24 theater Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m. Friday, AMC theaters had received all their prints.
</P>
<P>
   Prints for movies opening on Friday typically arrive at local
theaters Thursday night, where they are built up in the projection
booth for Friday's opening matinees.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the prints never
arrived. Eventually, the theater managers received notice from the
movie studio that there was a problem with distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally out of our control,'' said Allison Frost of
AMC.
</P>
<P>
   She said that most people who came for the early shows simply
came back later to see the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Harkins Theaters was partially lucky. Three of its theaters
received prints early Friday morning, in time to prepare them for
the matinees.
</P>
<P>
   Harkins hoped to have prints at all theaters for Friday night's
prime-time shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never tell us what the real problem is until it's not
important anymore,'' said Kelly Maloney of Harkins Theaters. ``They
always say the same thing: It's a problem at the depot.''
</P>
<P>
   Prints are sent from the studio to a central depot, where
they're shipped to cities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Studios typically don't cut prints until the movie is about to
be released to prevent piracy.
</P>
<P>
   The missing prints of the film, which was produced by
Spielberg's studio, DreamWorks, were supposed to be delivered by
Technicolor Labs of North Hollywood, where the actual prints were
struck.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks spokesman Mike Vollman said, ``We, as a movie studio,
use a vendor, Technicolor Labs, to dupe and distribute the prints
and ship them to theaters. And they had a problem with the
distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was not universal, he said, but did occur
sporadically across the nation. He did not say which cities were
most affected, except that Phoenix was one of the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' Vollman said. ``They screwed
something up. I don't know where the ball fell apart, but when we
got the word we got right on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Technicolor did not return calls. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Republic writers Bob Fenster and Kathy Cano-Murillo contributed to
this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
