<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANA JUDGE DISMISSES STATE SUIT AGAINST TOBACCO COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARRY MEIER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a victory for tobacco producers, a judge for the first time
has thrown out a state lawsuit seeking to recover billions of
dollars in smoking-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit by Indiana Attorney General Jeffrey Modisett was
part of a wave of actions filed since 1994 by 40 states and Puerto
Rico. But, while some of those cases have been weakened by rulings
in some states, Friday's decision by Marion County Superior Court
Judge Gerald Zore in Indianapolis marked the first time that a
state anti-smoking case was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Zore held that to recover damages, the state would have to
effectively prove claims for each affected resident on a
case-by-case basis, and then demonstrate the excess Medicaid
expenses associated with their treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's order did not elaborate on his reasoning. Cigarette
producers, however, have long argued that states should have to
prove their cases in such a fashion, and they said they were
pleased by Friday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general said he would appeal the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indiana now has the dubious distinction of being the only
state in the country where all of a state's claims against the
tobacco industry have been dismissed,'' Modisett said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McKim, assistant general counsel for R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co., a division of RJR Nabisco Holdings, said in a
statement: ``Judge Zore's sweeping ruling is clear and concise and
strikes at the heart of similar suits around the nation. It
confirms our position that the suits brought by attorneys general
to recoup their states' Medicaid costs are simply without legal or
factual merit and should never have been filed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Little, the associate general counsel for Philip Morris
Cos., sounded a similar theme. ``We are delighted to see that
courts across the country are following the law and ignoring the
politics of tobacco litigation,'' Little said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds, other defendants in the
Indiana case included Brown &AMP; Williamson, which is owned by BAT
Industries; Lorillard, a subsidiary of Loews Corp., and U.S.
Tobacco Co., a subsidiary of UST Inc.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As a group, the state claims have moved forward because other
judges have allowed state officials to bring claims representing
residents in a single action and then use statistical models to
prove alleged damages.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Zore also threw out all other elements of the
Indiana case, including claims that tobacco companies had conspired
together, deceived the public about the dangers of smoking and
unjustly enriched themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana lawsuit did not state a specific amount of damages.
But Modisett said he estimated that Indiana's share of last year's
proposed $368.5 billion tobacco settlement would have ranged from
$3.5 billion to $4 billion over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Zore's ruling Friday came on the eve of another round of talks
between state attorneys general and industry negotiators aimed at
reaching a new tobacco settlement agreement; the talks are
scheduled to begin Monday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, tobacco producers have paid out about $36 billion to
settle with four states _ Florida, Minnesota, Mississippi and
Texas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
