<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-DeLAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING TURNS VICTORY PARTY TO TRAGEDY IN MAJORITY WHIP'S OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House and Senate had quit for the week and most
lawmakers were on their way home on Friday when Rep. Tom Delay's
staff broke out some cake to celebrate a big legislative win and
the promise of a beautiful weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The party ended in chaos when a gunman shot his way into the
Capitol just outside the House Majority Whip's suite of offices, a
floor below the building's stunning Rotunda. The violent incident
turned a good-times Friday afternoon into a nightmare of confusion,
fear and death.
</P>
<P>
   Terrified, screaming tourists dove for cover as Capitol police
officers returned fire. The gunman burst through a door leading to
DeLay's extensive office complex, where he was shot by Officer John
Gibson, a member of DeLay's security detail.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and another officer, Jacob Chestnut, were fatally wounded
in the shootout. The gunman and a tourist were hospitalized with
gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Police and witnesses said the gunman did not target DeLay, a
conservative from Sugar Land, but the incident left the Republican
lawmaker and his staff shaken and glad to be alive. The staff had
been celebrating House passage of a Republican health care bill
when the shooting started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of scary around here,'' said John Feehery, DeLay's
communications director. ``There was all kinds of commotion.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who called the shooting a ``horrible incident,'' issued a
statement praising the slain officers. He said he considered Gibson
a member of his congressional family.
</P>
<P>
   ``John gave his life to protect me and the members of my
staff,'' DeLay said. ``There is no doubt that if John had not acted
quickly and with great bravery, as he did, others would have been
killed. I cannot express the depth of my sorrow for this loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The chaos at the shooting site contrasted with the
business-as-usual mood in the rest of the Capitol complex. Two
floors above the carnage, aides to another Texas Republican, House
Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving, were oblivious to the danger.
The hard-to-find suite became a sanctuary for scores of frightened
tourists who were directed out of the line of fire by police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't hear anything,'' said Michele Davis, Armey's press
aide. Horace Cooper, another Armey aide, said one tourist was
separated from her child in the confusion, but they were later
reunited.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol offices are reserved for top House leaders in both
parties, so most rank-and-file lawmakers were nowhere near the
shooting. Republican Reps. Kay Granger of Fort Worth and Joe Barton
of Ennis were on their home to Texas. Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas,
learned about the shooting after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   But for lawmakers and tourists alike, the incident was another
reminder that senseless violence can strike anywhere, anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the times that we're in,'' said David Arroyo, a visitor
from Pasadena. ``It's an unfortunate thing. Nowadays no one is
surprised when something like this happens. It's sad to say, but we
have gotten used to violence in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Capitol shooting seemed to strike a nerve among
tourists who had come to marvel at the seat of representative
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad because this is the people's house, our house,'' said
Jerry Price of Boulder, Colo. ``No one has the right to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hutcheson, (202) 383-6101
</P>
<P>
   rhutcheson &LR; krwashington.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
