u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-RIGHTS-450&AMP;ADD-     07-24 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-RIGHTS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONGO MASSACRES: THE U.N. STEPS ASIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An investigation into massacres in Congo, an
issue that rights groups consider critical to the credibility of
U.N. human rights operations, has been virtually shelved.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council has chosen to take no action in response to
a report presenting evidence that troops now under the control of
Congo and Rwanda were implicated in the deaths of thousands of Hutu
refugees driven out of camps in what was then eastern Zaire in late
1996 and early 1997. Reports of violations of human rights, often
based on ethnicity, still flow out of both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the Security Council asked both governments to look into
the allegations themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International called the inaction shameful. ``It is
extraordinary for the Security Council to have abdicated its
responsibility and for it to expect the very authorities which have
been identified as being responsible for such horrendous atrocities
to bring the perpetrators to justice,'' Amnesty International said.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat disagreed, saying the Security Council had
put both governments on notice that the issue would be revisited in
the fall, when progress would be assessed and action considered.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the Rwandan government, the United Nations has
also closed a human rights office in Rwanda, the most important of
a few centers set up in countries with large-scale violations.
There are similar offices in Burundi, Cambodia, Colombia and Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The Tutsi-led Rwandan government snubbed Secretary General Kofi
Annan when he visited this year. Rwandan leaders have been furious
with the United Nations since 1994, when Washington blocked the
Security Council from sending peacekeeping forces to prevent
massacres of hundreds of thousands of Tutsi by Hutu.
</P>
<P>
   In Congo, the government of President Laurent Kabila obstructed
the human rights team sent by Annan until its work became
impossible and it had to be withdrawn. That team wrote the report
on which the Security Council had been asked to act.
</P>
<P>
   Rights groups were quick to link the fate of the Congo inquiry
to the position that the United States, a friend of Rwanda, took at
a recent conference in Rome setting up an International Criminal
Court: Washington argued for Security Council control over which
issues were to be turned over to a court judging those accused of
genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Rights groups say that the aborted Congo investigation is
exactly the kind of case the Security Council might face, and that
its actions did not inspire confidence. Kenneth Roth, executive
director of Human Rights Watch, noted that the Security Council
also refused to act when Iraq gassed Kurds in 1988.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the Rome conference ended, the Security Council was left
with the power to stall proceedings but not prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Brody, advocacy director of Human Rights Watch, said that
in Congo, ``we see a real regional retreat'' by the West. He said
the United States and others had chosen stability and good
relations with regional governments over accountability for
killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concern about security in the region is trumping human rights
when in fact the protection of people is a key to stability,''
Brody said. ``Look at the Congo, where you have a United Nations
team saying crimes against humanity have been committed. Yet the
Security Council can't muster the political will to act. Clearly
many members of the Council have ties to the governments that are
implicated and don't want to see human rights concerns weaken those
governments.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
