<HEADER>
A2141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSCOW-TRAFFIC-ART-NY     07-24 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSCOW-TRAFFIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW TRAFFIC: WHIMSICAL RULES AND A ZEST FOR CREATIVE DRIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(hlw) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Enmeshed last May in a two-and-a-half-hour traffic jam
on his way to a Moscow airport, the driver of a city bus decided to
save his passengers some time by taking a short cut through the
park.
</P>
<P>
   Not on a road. Through the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an accredited city bus, driving through a park from one
side of the block to the other, but via the grass,'' said Dona
Johnson, a Canadian living here who was stuck in the same jam.
``Finally it just came over the sidewalk on the other side, cut off
a trolley bus and proceeded down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Most world capitals have traffic problems. Then there is Moscow,
where traffic is not just awful, but boisterously, exuberantly so.
Free for eight years to buy anything they can afford, Muscovites
have bought cars with an absolute vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   They drive them that way, too. Never have so many cars driven by
so many novices descended so quickly on such an unprepared
metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, when the Communists ran things, Moscow traffic
was as orderly as the line at Lenin's tomb. Now it is better
compared to the obligatory scene in a grade-B western where riders
gallop their horses through the town saloon.
</P>
<P>
   People also get killed. There are about 20 serious accidents on
Moscow streets each day, many involving pedestrians, and roughly
7,500 injuries and 800 deaths a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one learns to drive in Moscow, there isn't any other city
in the world in which to be scared,'' said Andrei Schavelev, who
heads the propaganda department of the State Automobile
Inspectorate, known everywhere by its Russian acronym GAI
(pronounced guy-EE). ``In Switzerland, I could drive with one
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Russians have always had a reputation as zestful
drivers. But for decades hardly anyone noticed because there were
so few cars. The Soviet Union limited the production of cars, and
those that were made usually went to Communists and the
well-connected.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, a city of 8 million, counted only about 320,000 autos in
1981. When the Berlin wall fell in 1989 there were still but
877,500 _ barely one car for every 10 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nine years later the ratio is closing in on a car for
every three people _ more than 2.2 million cars on the city
registry, plus an estimated 300,000 more registered elsewhere. Five
years ago, when the total was half that, the appetite for cars was
so voracious that drivers snapped up more than 150,000 Japanese
models that had been rushed across the continent _ with right-hand
drives.
</P>
<P>
   Such force-feeding would give any city indigestion. Moscow is
positively bloated, for even in the best of times this was not a
place for a leisurely Sunday drive. As in any 850-year-old city,
the downtown street grid is a crazy quilt. Even the more modern
roads frequently change names from block to block, making
map-reading an exercise in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic signals are relatively infrequent _ the city has fewer
than Washington, a city of 550,000 people _ and they tend to change
according to their own unwritten rules. Many stoplights are not yet
synchronized to speed the flow of cars. Increasingly, the thump of
traffic has proven too much for Moscow's old streets, which have
begun to cave in with alarming frequency, occasionally parboiling
unfortunate victims in a spray of broken steam pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking of all are the city's traffic rules, which to
Westerners can seem inscrutable, if not wrongheaded. ``No Parking''
can often be translated as ``Park on the sidewalk, not the
street.'' Left turns are largely banned, except when they are not;
signs do not always distinguish the two.
</P>
<P>
   U-turns are encouraged, but only on busy streets, and only in
certain spots. The preferred method of making a left turn is to
continue driving past one's destination, sometimes for several
minutes, until the car reaches an overpass or a U-turn zone. With
that, it is possible to turn around, backtrack to the destination
and make a legal right turn.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the only way to make a left turn is to turn right,
then navigate a maze of U-turns and side streets to reach a traffic
signal that will allow you to cross the street you were on to begin
with. In that case, a left turn from, say, the Novy Arbat onto the
Garden Ring entails a right turn, two U-turns, three more turns and
a trip around the Russian White House and the American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   None of this mattered much when there weren't many cars in
Moscow. Today it creates a 24-hour probka _ Russian for ``cork,''
and slang for traffic jam _that brings out the cowboy in many
motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, Russian drivers are less disciplined than
elsewhere,'' said Andrei Karlov, a senior expert at the All-Russia
Society of Motorists, a rough equivalent of the American Automobile
Association. ``The rules are good. But there are no conditions
under which to observe them.''
</P>
<P>
   The official city speed limit of 60 kilometers per hour, or
about 37 miles per hour, exists largely on the books. On the
busiest roads _ the broad prospekts that stretch like spokes from
the city center, or the 10-lane ring road that circles downtown _
the white lane dividers are, in effect, pleasant decorations.
Drivers establish their own lanes by muscling at high speed to
within a few inches of less courageous cars, and waiting for them
to back off.
</P>
<P>
   The most intrepid of these men _ women drivers were virtually
unheard of until a few years ago _ will do almost anything to avoid
a backup. It is not uncommon for a car to take to the sidewalks for
short distances when traffic stops on the street.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long ago that cars were spotted on one major Moscow
street nonchalantly climbing and descending a ramp for the
handicapped in order to get around a city bus. The bus had hit a
large pothole, which then turned into a sinkhole, swallowing it.
</P>
<P>
   None of this behavior was learned from Emily Post. Much of it
undoubtedly stems from the fact that many Muscovites are relative
newcomers to the road. Some of it is surely due to the city's
understandable problem in channeling this flood of new cars onto
proper routes.
</P>
<P>
   Schavelev, of the GAI, blames a growing culture among new
motorists _ especially rich ones with foreign cars _ to flout
traffic laws as evidence of their wealth and power. Moscow is rife
with Mercedes, and while European cars like Volkswagens and Volvos
are the most popular imports, costly American sport-utility
vehicles have lately become cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``They drive in any lane and think they can pay any fine,'' he
said. ``Sometimes they throw packs of money to inspectors, as if
they are dogs, so we won't detain them.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlov, the traffic expert, lays some blame at the feet of the
Communists, who he says drove as if they were the only people on
the road, which, of course, they often were.
</P>
<P>
   Money would help. Moscow needs another 175 miles of streets just
to accommodate today's traffic. The GAI, which operates a
traffic-control center in downtown Moscow and employs 7,000 traffic
policemen and inspectors, wants to hire 5,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's big-spending mayor, Yuri Luzhkov, has made traffic a
priority. The city has nearly completed construction of a second
major beltway around Moscow's outer regions, and is building new
pedestrian tunnels downtown. And it has nearly completed the
freeway-quality reconstruction of the so-called ``Death Road'' _
the MKAD, the outermost of the three ring roads that encircle the
city.
</P>
<P>
   There remains a problem: a spate of collisions along stretches
of the road that permit a new, higher speed limit of just over 62
mph. But there is a ready explanation: ``Drivers are not used to a
road of such quality,'' the head of the GAI, Nikolai Arkhipkin,
said this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
