<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-DC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURISTS STUNNED IN AF TERMATH OF SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of tourists stood outside the Capitol in
near silence, stunned as they watched ambulances and helicopters
take away the wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, tourists fled in panic as they realized the sounds they
heard were gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``People . . . started pouring out of the old Supreme Court
chamber as well as the various corridors screaming at the top of
their lungs and running,'' said Allison Applegate-Slatter, a staff
assistant for Rep. John Hostettler, R-Ind., who was conducting a
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were, luckily, right by a hallway, and an officer poked his
head around the hallway and said, `Please go out this way. Run.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't have to tell me twice. I ran.''
</P>
<P>
   The glory of a sun-washed summer day at one of the nation's
symbols of freedom was broken Friday afternoon by a gunman who
forced his way past security at a ground floor door, shot two
Capitol Police officers and a 24-year-old woman before he was shot
inside the office suite of Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   House business had broken up nearly an hour before and most
members had started home _ by car, train, or plane _ but as the
news came over congressional office televisions, perpetually tuned
to all-news stations, chiefs of staff took head-counts and ordered
interns to call home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to send everyone home a few minutes early,''
said Fran McNaught, chief of staff for Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz. ``I
had all our interns call (home). In fact, I had all our people call
and let people know they were all right.''
</P>
<P>
   McNaught said one of her interns was shocked when he realized as
he crossed the Capitol grounds that the hundreds of tourists who
were milling there had fallen almost entirely silent.
</P>
<P>
   Among Capitol Hill staff there was a certain resignation to the
inevitability of something like the shooting happening in the
nation's seat of power.
</P>
<P>
   No one ran around terrified, said Mike Paranzino, chief of staff
for Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., though he acknowledged that would be
one way to handle the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other view is, `Let's stay put until they have the suspect
in custody.' We're all staying put.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident is going to mean even more heightened security,
despite fortifications installed after the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all just speculating on what will be shut down next,''
said Elisabeth Hickey, press secretary for the House subcommittee
on the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sobering,'' she said. ``If you're not safe in the Capitol
where there are police all around, where are you safe?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., who was interviewed from his plane
as he headed back to Arizona, said he would hate for increased
security to mean more limited contact between members of Congress
and their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the worst things we could do is try to cloister members
of Congress away from the people they serve,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
