<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FINDS FORMER AIR FORCE CADET GUILTY OF CAPITAL MURDER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ In a jury decision hailed as
``courageous'' by the victim's tearful family, former cadet David
Graham was convicted of capital murder Friday for the 1995 slaying
of a 16-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   Like his former fiancee, Diane Zamora, Graham was automatically
sentenced to life imprisonment and will serve a minimum of 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   The former U.S. Air Force Academy cadet took the verdict
stoically, ``like a soldier,'' said attorney Dan Cogdell. But he
wept during a private meeting with his parents afterward.
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared shaken when, moments after the verdict was
read, state District Judge Don Leonard allowed the parents and two
teen-age brothers of the slain girl, Adrianne Jones, to address the
silent defendant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that everyone remembers our daughter with the integrity
that she has, because she is still among us, watching us,'' said
mother Linda Jones. Fixing her gaze on Graham, she added, ``I
remember her eyes with joy. You will, with fear. I am sorry for you
and your family.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim's brother Justin Jones said, ``I have no hate for you
because I can't hate an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Another brother, Scott Jones, his voice cracking with emotion,
thanked jurors, saying, ``What you did was very, very courageous.''
He chastised Graham for making ``bad choices'' that ``ruined so
many lives, so many families.
</P>
<P>
   ``And unlike my brother, I can hate an animal. And I hate David
Graham.''
</P>
<P>
   With their verdict after eight hours of deliberation, jurors
accepted the prosecution theory that Graham fatally shot Jones to
please Zamora, who was consumed by jealousy after Graham falsely
told of a sexual relationship with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors said they did not buy the defense argument that
prosecutors had not proven Graham, now 20, was at the crime scene.
He did admit helping Zamora cover it up for nine months before
their arrests, which made national headlines and ended promising
two careers _ he with the Air Force in Colorado Springs, Colo., and
she as a midshipman at the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The murder was committed in Tarrant County on Dec. 4, 1995, when
Graham and Zamora were high school senior sweethearts; they have
been in custody since September 1996. Their romance fizzled soon
thereafter when they were pitted against each other in court.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence showed that Graham, then a Mansfield High School
senior, called the sophomore track star a few hours before her
death and convinced her to leave her house for a late-night
rendezvous, ostensibly to discuss Zamora's irrational jealousy.
Graham, who appeared to be alone in the car when he arrived at
Jones' home, convinced Jones to go for a ride, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The drive ended near Joe Pool Lake, where Zamora sprang from
hiding in the car's trunk and struck Zamora, prosecutors said.
Injured and stunned, Jones fled a few yards before collapsing,
where Graham finished her off with two gunshots to the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``David ... you betrayed her trust, when she was just there to
help you with a problem,'' Jones' mother told him in the hushed
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Mike Parrish said Graham was convicted largely
because of his confession, which provided explicit details about
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confession was obviously impossible to overcome,'' Parrish
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strangest thing about this case is not that David and
Diane did it, but that they did it for a fabricated reason,''
Parrish said. ``David Graham never had sex with Adrianne Jones.
David Graham did tell Diane Zamora he had sex with Adrianne, but it
was a lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of telling his girlfriend he had made this up, once
she demanded it _ she did lead and she did call the shots _ he went
along with it. That's the amazing part of this story.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors took one vote to reach their conclusion, said foreman
William Everett Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a confession, it would have been a whole different
deliberation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell's decision not to present defense witnesses was
surprising, Wright said, but ``the jury considered it a legitimate
tactic.`` The Jones family's comments to Graham were ``tough to
take'' for jurors, Wright said, as was the decision to ``put a
young kid away for the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said the verdict was expected and Graham was prepared
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's spending 40 calendar years in a cage somewhere. He's not
a real happy camper. Neither am I,'' he blustered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told David going in that the odds of us winning this case
were about the odds of me flying an F-16 upside down under and
overpass with a martini in my lap and not spilling the olive,'' the
Houston lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he would appeal the verdict ``as soon as I can get
to a word processor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got at least three families that have been devastated by
what did or didn't happen,'' he said. ``And there ain't no winners
in a deal like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's parents and other family members departed hastily after
the trial without speaking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones family said they will spearhead efforts to create a
``serenity park'' in their hometown in Adrianne Jones' memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a strong family,'' Linda Jones said, ``and we are going
to process our grieving and go on like normal people do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
