<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-24 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR DE FRANCE BIKERS PROTEST AS NEW DRUG ALLEGATIONS EMERGE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LE CAP D'AGDE, France _ The 85th Tour de France nearly unraveled
Friday as at least five expelled riders admitted they had used
illegal drugs, a second team was warned about possible ouster and
the remaining riders went on strike for two hours to protest
harassment in the doping scandal that has engulfed the world's
greatest bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   In a climate of innuendo, rumor and anger, widespread doping
practices that have long been suspected in bicycle racing are now
surfacing in the sport's showcase. The tour, which began in 1903
and has been held every year since except during the world wars, is
not only the richest and most prestigious bicycle race but it is
also an integral part of French culture, watched by hundreds of
thousands of fans at the side of the road every day and by millions
more on television.
</P>
<P>
   Angry riders among the 150 competitors that remain in the
three-week race refused to start Friday to protest what they called
hounding and criticism by the news media. Race director Jean-Marie
Leblanc said the riders cited a French television segment Thursday
night that examined the garbage of the Asics team from Italy and
displayed medical paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, three members of the expelled Festina team from
France, including the world road race champion, Laurent Brochard,
admitted to the police that they had used performance-enhancing
drugs. Two other members of the nine-man team were also reported to
have admitted using the drugs by late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a great sense of relief at having confessed,'' said one
rider, Armin Meier, who is Swiss. ``But I feel victimized. It's
like everybody is driving 100 kilometers an hour on a highway with
a 90-kilometer limit, and they pull only us over.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case, police continued to hold two officials of the
TVM team from the Netherlands and a magistrate said that a search
of the team's hotel had revealed ''a large quantity'' of ``doping
products'' and masking agents, substances used to flush drugs from
the system to avoid detection.
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc warned the Dutch team that he and the International
Cycling Union, which governs the sport, were paying close attention
to the police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is revealed that this team has not respected the rules
and the ethics of the Tour de France and International Cycling
Union,'' Leblanc said, ``the team will be immediately expelled.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the riders would protest again Saturday
morning. Leblanc said he used the popularity of the race to
persuade them to start Friday's stage. ``We negotiated with the
riders, we explained our position,'' Leblanc said. ``We cited the
multitude of fans who were awaiting them to encourage the riders
and show their appreciation. In the end, they understood.''
</P>
<P>
   He added regarding the Friday segment, ``If the stage had been
canceled, it might have been the end of the 1998 tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc said he would meet before Saturday's stage with an
official of the French Cycling Federation and a rider from each of
the 21 teams in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The three Spanish teams _ Banesto, ONCE and Vitalicio _ and the
Mercatone Uno team from Italy were reported to have led the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some pretty harsh stuff in the Spanish media and
a lot of the riders were hurt by it,'' Stuart O'Grady, an
Australian with Gan who wore the overall leader's yellow jersey for
three days, said Friday. ``It cut deep. A lot of teams didn't want
to take part in the race today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the central French city of Lyon, the nine members of the
Festina team plus three of its officials who had been in custody
were released. Apart from the five riders who were said to have
confessed, three others _ including Richard Virenque, the team's
leader and the second-place finisher in the last Tour _ reportedly
continued to deny that they had been involved in a systematic
program of doping.
</P>
<P>
   Citing media attention to the case and the Festina riders'
objections that they had been treated harshly by the police, the
riders who gathered Friday morning in the town of Tarascon sur
Ariege in the Pyrenees decided they had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   They slowly rolled about two miles from the ceremonial start to
the real one and then stopped, dismounting their bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Jalabert, the Frenchman who is ranked No. 1 in the
world, approached Leblanc in his lead car and spoke with him.
``Since the start of this Tour we have talked only about scandal
and not sport,'' Jalabert said. ''The riders are disgusted. We have
been treated like cattle and we will act like cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is interested in the sport side of the race. We won't
ride. It's finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing and sprawled on the road, the riders conferred among
themselves and with their coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so sick and tired of everybody being blamed for what
Festina did,'' said Frankie Andreu, an American with U.S. Postal
Service. He favored not racing.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, the riders were persuaded to start but they
rolled so slowly that they covered only 16 kilometers in the next
hour. Then the racing started in earnest with bursts of
accelerations. Jalabert went on a long attack with two other riders
and was later said to have done so because he was so angry that the
pack had agreed to start that he wanted racers to suffer at high
speed in the sultry heat.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first strike by riders. In 1978, they refused
to cross a finish line to protest long transfers between daily
stages and in 1991 they refused to start a stage to protest the
mandatory wearing of helmets. In both instances, the tour softened
its rules.
</P>
<P>
   In another legal development, Judge Patrick Kiel, who has been
leading the Festina investigation in the northern city of Lille,
released ``under strict conditions'' Willy Vogt, the team masseur
whose arrest unleashed the drug scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Vogt, a Belgian, was seized July 8 at the French-Belgian border
with an official Tour de France car reported to be holding a huge
quantity of such drugs as amphetamines, steroids, masking agents
and EPO, a potentially lethal drug that thickens the blood by
multiplying the red blood corpuscles that carry oxygen to the
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, just before the tour began on July 11 in Dublin,
Ireland, news of his arrest was made public. Festina coach Bruno
Roussel at first denied that Vogt was part of his tour entourage.
On July 14, Vogt changed his story that the drugs were for his
personal use and said through his lawyer that he was acting on team
orders.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, a day after the race reached France, Roussel and the
team doctor, Eric Ryckaert, were taken into custody. The next day
Roussel was suspended by the International Cycling Union and the
day after that, he said that he had supplied the illicit drugs to
his riders, which they denied. Under French law, drug users are not
liable to imprisonment but suppliers are.
</P>
<P>
   That night, July 17, the Festina team, which ranks first in the
world, was expelled from the race in the first such action in the
tour's history.
</P>
<P>
   On July 21, the team doctor said that the riders had contributed
up to $70,000 of their prizes to a fund to buy
performance-enhancing drugs. The riders were summoned to court in
Lyons on Thursday, the same day that police raided the TVM team's
hotel in Pamiers and took four officials into custody. The team's
coach, Cees Priem, and its doctor, Andrei Mihailov, remain in
custody.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial the newspaper Le Monde said, ``The 1998 Tour is
finished. It is a race without faith or law. If it dies it will
bury our childhood dreams with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour is seriously ill,'' responded Marie-George Buffet,
the French minister for sport, responded, ``but there's no reason
to kill it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
