</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CAPITOL: AN OPEN SPACE PRONE TO VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-SCENE, CAPITOL-VICTIMS,
CAPITOL-GUNMEN, CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO) 
(hlw) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Capitol has been the scene of bombings,
shootings and other forms of mayhem since the early days of the
Republic. In 1835, a gunman tried to kill President Andrew Jackson
in the Rotunda; his pistols misfired. In 1890, a Louisville
newspaper reporter shot a former Kentucky congressman to death on a
staircase after a long feud. But the two events with the most
lasting effect occurred in 1971 and 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-dawn hours of March 1, 1971, a bomb exploded in a
men's restroom in the Senate wing, causing about $300,000 damage to
surrounding rooms. The radical Weather Underground organization
claimed responsibility for the bombing _ retaliation for U.S.
military activity in Cambodia, it said.
</P>
<P>
   That bombing, which was never solved, prompted elaborate new
measures: guards at the entrances began inspecting briefcases,
purses and packages. Surveillance devices were installed at
strategic points. X-ray machines were put at 10 entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those steps, a bomb was detonated shortly before 11 p.m.
on Nov. 7, 1983, in a second-floor alcove only 30 feet from the
Senate chamber. There were no injuries or structural damage, but
the bombing left lawmakers and Capitol security officials deeply
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   That very day, top lawmakers had agreed on new security measures
inspired by an incident only three weeks before, when an Israeli
tourist with a homemade bomb under his shirt was arrested in the
House gallery after threatening to blow up the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is the symbolic capital of the world,'' a Washington
police officer said after one incident. ``If you want to strike a
blow against the United States of America, you don't go to Des
Moines and blow up a cow.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1983 bombing (to which three self-described Communists
pleaded guilty seven years later) accelerated the rush to tighter
Capitol security, ushering in measures that have become familiar _
and others that remain little-known, even secret.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors no longer had their pick of 10 doors; they could use
half that many. Metal detectors were installed at all entrances.
Concrete barriers (sometimes topped incongruously with flowers)
were erected at driveways. Parking and car traffic were restricted.
The Capitol Police force, 622 in 1971, grew to 1,265 by 1990.
People with regular business in the Capitol were assigned badges.
</P>
<P>
   And bulletproof steel plates were installed in the chairs on the
floor of the House of Representatives to guard against terrorist
attacks. The Senate's sergeant-at-arms decided against bulletproof
chairs, but assured the public that new secret new precautions had
been put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with the tighter security of recent years, and for all
its importance as a center of government and national symbol, the
Capitol remains a relatively open place.
</P>
<P>
   Hordes of tourists are shepherded through on a typical day, and
they have access to many rooms and corridors. The Capitol Police
are generally friendly, treating tourists as guests _ which, of
course, they are.
</P>
<P>
   Given the history of violence there, it may be surprising that
the building is as open as it is. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
