<HEADER>
A2153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-NYT &LR;      07-24 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT VIOLENCE IN THE CAPITOL AND SECURITY MEASURES INSTITUTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-SCENE, CAPITOL-VICTIMS,
CAPITOL-GUNMEN, CAPITOL-SECURITY) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   July 2, 1915 _ The Senate reception room was damaged by the
explosion of a homemade bomb placed there by a young Cornell
University professor who was protesting arms sales by the United
States to countries that later became its allies in World War I.
After the explosion, additional officers were added to the small
Capitol Police Force.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 13, 1932 _ A young man entered the House gallery, drew a
loaded revolver and began waving it wildly, demanding time to
address the House. A member of the House approached the gunman and
talked him into dropping the gun. Police arrested the gunman
without a shot being fired.
</P>
<P>
   July 12, 1947 _ Sen. John Bricker, R-Ohio, was shot at twice as
he entered the Senate subway. Both shots missed. The gunman was a
former Capitol policeman who had lost money when an Ohio building
and loan firm was liquidated fifteen years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   March 1, 1954 _ A band of Puerto Rican nationalists opened fire
from the House visitors' gallery wounding five representatives. The
three assailants, and a fourth member of the group who was captured
later, received prison sentences. After the shooting, more police
were hired and, for a time, thought was given to enclosing the
galleries in bullet-resistant glass.
</P>
<P>
   March 1, 1971 _ In the pre-dawn hours, a bomb ripped through
part of the Senate wing of the Capitol, demolishing a restroom and
causing extensive damage to six other rooms. The radical Weather
Underground organization said it set off the bomb as an act of
retaliation for U.S. military activity in Cambodia. The actual
perpetrator was never found. In the aftermath, tighter security
measures were installed, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Guards at the entrances to the Capitol and Senate and House
office buildings would inspect briefcases, purses and packages of
all persons, including members of Congress. At 10 entrances, the
guards would be aided by X-ray machines.
</P>
<P>
   _ An electronic surveillance system was installed at strategic
points throughout the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Capitol Police Force was increased to 1,265 by 1990 from
622 in 1971. Police would patrol the buildings throughout the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 7, 1983 _ Shortly before 11 p.m., a powerful device
exploded in a second-floor alcove about 30 feet from the Senate
chamber. There were no injuries or structural damage. In May 1988,
seven people describing themselves as a ``communist
politico-military organization'' were indicted for the bombing.
Three of the accused pleaded guilty on Sept. 7, 1990, clearing the
way for prosecutors to drop charges against the remaining
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol building security was again tightened.
</P>
<P>
   _ Visitor access was limited to four or six doors. Metal
detectors were installed at all entrances.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lobbyists and tourists no longer were permitted in the
hallways immediately outside the House and Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vehicle traffic and parking on the East Front lot were
restricted; delivery trucks were searched.
</P>
<P>
   _ Concrete barriers were erected at driveways and large trucks
were parked at entrances to the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Congressional Quarterly; The New York Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
