<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2157 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONs-NOTES25-COX     07-24 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONs-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves concerned about conditioning
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It didn't take long to see the effects of multiple
practices as the Atlanta Falcons were somewhat ragged in the second
day of training camp Friday _ the first time the squad practiced
twice. In a two-hour, full-pads workout in the morning, the team
started out working in groups, including placekicking specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Stryzinski was the chief holder for kickers Morten Andersen
and David Akers. Coach Dan Reeves paid special attention to this
group.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, the team went for two hours in helmets,
shoulder pads and shorts, and at the beginning, instead of
placekicking, Reeves was watching Stryzinski and Akers punt.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of practice, Reeves put players through ``grass
drills,'' a condititioning exercise where they jog in place and hit
the ground, shuffle left, right, forward, and sometimes crawl
depending on the orders Reeves gives while standing atop a tractor
so he can be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is concerned about conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things we try to emphasize because a lot of
times in the fourth quarter you're tired and you start feeling
sorry for yourself and you start making mistakes,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense has really looked good, and what made us a good
defense last year (second in the NFL in sacks, sixth in
interceptions, eighth against the run, 20th overall) has carried
over ... 11 guys hustling to the football.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons today will practice at 9 a.m. and 3 p.m., both times
in full pads. Both sessions are open to the public at team
headquarters in Suwanee, off exit 44 on I-85 north. The team will
be off Sunday except for evening meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Turning down the heat
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two months of torturous heat in Atlanta, the
Falcons have been spared. At the start of the morning session, it
was 77 degrees and overcast with 87 percent humidity. There also
was a breeze. In the afternoon, it was a modest 88 degrees with 60
percent humidity under partly cloudy skies and again, there was a
breeze. Thursday, it was 93, but humidity was less than 50 percent,
and it was breezy.
</P>
<P>
   QB watch
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the quarterback situation: Chris Chandler _ Got
most, if not all, reps with the No. 1 unit in all drills, including
some 9-on-9 and 11-on-11 work. In the afternoon, he fumbled one
snap from center Robbie Tobeck, but threw several exceptional
passes. Tony Graziani _ Worked at No. 2 all day, throwing high a
couple of times and getting intercepted a couple of times, once in
a goal-line drill by cornerback Lenny McGill in the end zone as he
threw a fade to rookie receiver Tim Dwight. Steve DeBerg _ Worked
at No. 3, and also as backup holder on placekicking drills. At one
time, while Chandler and Graziani were working passing drills,
DeBerg was working on the next field handing off as most of the
offense worked on the running game. Brian Brennan _ Pretty much the
same kind of day as DeBerg minus holding duties.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad and ugly
</P>
<P>
   Good: On a screen pass to running back Byron Hanspard, reserve
guard Scott Adams (6-feet-6, 315 pounds) flattened linebacker Eddie
Sutter (6-3, 239) in the open field. ... Bad: Receiver Kevin
Thornal ran a nice flag route on the right sideline to beat McGill
in a passing drill, but when Chandler threw a nearly perfect
45-yard pass, it bounced off Thornal near the goal line. ... Ugly:
While the QBs were warming up in the afternoon, Graziani turned
away and got beaned in the head on a 20-yard toss _ ``Thwack!'' _
from Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   What he said
</P>
<P>
   ''What happened to the love, fellas?'' _ Safety William White,
in the morning, when some defensive backs were jawing with
receivers during one of the earliest drills.
</P>
<P>
   Aches and pains
</P>
<P>
   Friday was more problematic than Thursday with cramping
especially being a problem. Several players had to be helped from
dinner, in fact, when their legs tightened up. Cornerbacks Randy
Fuller and Juran Bolden limped from the field after afternoon
practice with undisclosed injuries. Others: RB Harold Green
(sprained thumb), LB Cornelius Bennett (Achilles'), LB David
Brandon (foot) and DT Shane Dronett (foot). It was unclear if any
players would be held out today.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   At every lunch and dinner, the team has pasta, poultry and fish
options. At dinner, there also is a red-meat option, and a few
times a week that option is steak. On those days, the kitchen cooks
250 prime cut 14-16 oz. New York strips and filets.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding ``Big Nate''
</P>
<P>
   While the sudden departure Friday of second-year defensive
tackle Nathan Davis surprised nobody, starting left defensive end
Lester Archambeau was disappointed. ``I was hoping for him that his
(disastrous) first year would prove to be a learning experience,
and he would realize he was getting another chance,'' he said. ``I
think it's a shame anytime a man has a chance to play pro football
and he gives it up.'' By putting Davis on the ``reserve/left
squad'' list, the Falcons will not have to pay his $335,000 base
salary, but under the complicated rules of the salary cap the team
will gain a little more than $100,000 in cap money, leaving the
team nearly $2 million under it. The Falcons will be charged
$220,700 against the cap for the prorated portion of Davis' signing
bonus, and also for the $25,000 he picked up for an offseason
workout bonus. Backup left guard Adams said, ``As a guy who's been
making the NFL minimum most of his career, I sure would like some
of his money.'' Adams re-signed with the Falcons in the offseason
for $375,000 (a $100,000 raise), $50,000 more than the minimum. He
also got a $25,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Musical chairs
</P>
<P>
   After Davis walked off, defensive end Barry Mitchell moved from
defensive end to tackle for several rotations in the morning
practice, but that won't last. The 6-3, 273-pounder, who made last
year's practice squad as an undrafted rookie out of Idaho, is too
light to play inside. ... Bob Christian (5-11, 230) and rookie free
agent Darren Fisk (6-1, 230) are the only fullbacks on the roster,
but reserve running back Gary Downs (6-1, 216) and reserve tight
end Brian Kozlowski (6-3, 255) have been getting work there.
</P>
<P>
   Dog of the week
</P>
<P>
   Got to be ``Dino,'' the 4-year-old, 4-pound white miniature
Maltese that belongs to 6-4, 298-pound deep snapper Adam Schreiber.
Dino is staying with the 15-year veteran for a couple weeks. He can
be seen between practices bouncing around outside the Falcon Inn
motel, scouting for outhouses, if you catch the drift.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
