<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gym Dogs visit with President
 &HT;    By Samar Abulhassan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To Kim Arnold, finishing her last season as a
member of the undefeated national champion University of Georgia
gymnastics team was sweet enough. But Arnold, the NCAA national
gymnast of the year, says the grand finale came with
congratulations from President Bill Clinton on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing made us feel very special,'' said the 21-year
old All-American senior, speaking on the White House north lawn
shortly after the Georgia team met with the president in the Oval
Office. ``This was the best way I could have ended my career as a
gymnast.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 14-member top-ranked squad took the NCAA championship
last April, they were invited to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Gym Dogs won the NCAA title by the largest margin in more
than 10 years. It is the first Georgia team to meet the president
since the 1990 national championship baseball team met
then-President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Suzanne Yoculan, who accompanied the team along with
assistant coach Doug McAvinn, said the invitation signified a
stepping stone for womens' sports. Jenni Beathard, national
champion on bars, said the president chatted with the team about
gymnastics, applauded their 35-0 season, and accepted a polo shirt
which he promised to wear during his next golf game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person we've met has been excited to see us,'' said the
21-year-old senior. ``We are the ones who are honored. We'll
remember this for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
