A2162 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX     07-24 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER DROVE `ICE MON' TO SHOW WARMTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big Bertha suffers a broken neck today. Or, at the very least,
she's banished to a dark spot in the back of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing the titanium driver in my golf bag with its persimmon
predecessor in my garage seems an appropriate way, on this somber
occasion, to honor a local sports legend. Heck, THE local sports
legend.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it has been exactly one year since Ben Hogan left the
earth, leaving a legacy of greatness that placed Fort Worth on the
global golf map.
</P>
<P>
   When fans stop today to reflect on Hogan's wondrous career, most
will conjure images from his 63 PGA Tour titles and nine major
championships. But I'll recall a broken driver in the bag room at
Shady Oaks Country Club that eventually led a couple of teen-agers
from west Fort Worth to develop a deep respect for a very private
man.
</P>
<P>
   It is a journey that began 20 years ago, with a lethal mix of
bad judgment, attempted humor and teen-age bravado. It began with a
single set of clubs waiting to be washed by a pair of golf shop
employees. One was me. The other was longtime friend Brann Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs, alas, belonged to Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   After washing them, Jeter did what came naturally to a Shady
Oaks bag boy intent on impressing a fellow 18-year-old with his
derring-do. He removed Hogan's driver, placed it across his knee
and pretended to apply pressure.
</P>
<P>
   I rolled my eyes, having used the same trick on countless
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never break it,'' I said, issuing a tongue-in-cheek
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he responded. ``But what if I just bent it a little?
He'd never notice.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, wiser heads would have laughed and walked away.
But we were cool. We were daring. We were seniors.
</P>
<P>
   We foolishly pressed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much did you have in mind?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe two or three degrees,'' he responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not enough,'' I said, sneering. ``You'd have to get to
five degrees before anyone would notice.''
</P>
<P>
   We went back and forth, laughing the entire time, before
agreeing that a five-degree bend would be worth $10. Once again,
Jeter placed the driver across his knee and feigned pushing on the
respective ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There,'' he said, holding it aloft. ``That's five degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver remained pin straight. Both of us knew it. Having
done club repairs, we realized that any golfer _ especially Hogan _
would recognize the slightest bend of the shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Our ongoing joke was nearing an uneventful conclusion. But I
couldn't resist getting in another dig. It proved to be a tragic
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't do anything. You've got to apply some pressure to
bend a golf club,'' I said, never dreaming that Jeter would try to
one-up me a final time.
</P>
<P>
   But he pressed the driver against his knee a third time. He
applied minimal pressure. And the stiff shaft snapped like a twig
in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God!'' he said, eyes wide and body trembling. ``What
are we going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' I replied, staring at the incriminating
evidence in his hands. ``We didn't just break Ben Hogan's driver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're part of this,'' he insisted. ``You're an accomplice.
You're as guilty as I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, I knew he had me. So we did what most teen-agers
would do in a similar predicament. We cooked up a story and stuck
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, we related to head golf pro Art Hall, my buddy had
tripped while carrying Hogan's bag. The clubs tipped forward,
almost spilling. In an effort to regain his balance, Jeter grabbed
the head of the driver and snapped the shaft against the rim of the
bag. It was a freak accident but one that could be corroborated by
an eyewitness.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a pleasant man prone to high blood pressure, turned
absolutely crimson as he heard the tale. A chain smoker, he must
have polished off a carton of cigarettes while waiting for Hogan to
arrive at the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years I've been at Shady Oaks, and we've broken one
golf club. And it's Ben Hogan's $%&AMP; &LR; ! driver,'' he said, shaking
his head.
</P>
<P>
   But he bought the story. And he passed it along to Hogan, who
listened and nodded toward Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ever let that red-headed boy touch another one of my
golf clubs,'' Hogan said, fuming.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, a delivery truck from the Hogan factory arrived at
Shady Oaks. Its payload: one reshafted driver, which met with the
Hawk's approval.
</P>
<P>
   For the next month, Jeter arranged to be in the cart barn, on
the practice range or otherwise occupied when the golf legend
arrived for his daily visit to the club. Others shagged balls for
Hogan and cleaned his clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Then, something very unusual happened. Hogan strolled through
the golf shop one day and noticed Jeter. He invited him to shag
balls. The two talked and cleared the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Hogan's way of saying, `This is behind us now,' ''
Jeter said. ``He was much cooler about it than I expected him to
be. After that, he was as cordial to me as if nothing had ever
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wee Ice Mon, it turns out, knew how to forgive and forget.
Even in the case of a couple of irresponsible teen-agers who have
grown to regret their transgression. But without the initial
mistake, there would have been no opportunity to glimpse a kinder,
gentler side of a local legend that few golf fans saw. A quiet,
decent man worthy of admiration and respect.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad I got to see that. I'm sorry that more people never
realized that Ben Hogan, reclusive champion golfer, had a heart as
pure as his golf swing.
</P>
<P>
   So, while the rest of the world reflects today on favorite
memories of a champion golfer, I'll focus on repaying a
longstanding debt.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bertha is headed to the sideline, with or without a broken
neck. I'm unsure of her ultimate punishment. In her place, however,
will be a persimmon model, just like the one I used to clean at
Shady Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   One that is solid but forgiving, just like its namesake. A Hogan
driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
