<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-ASSESS-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN SUDAN, ONLY THE STARVING FAVOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Hunger has been a weapon of war since Homer's
time, but perhaps nowhere in modern history have starvation and
food supplies been so entwined with military tactics as in Sudan's
interminable civil war.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in a decade, a famine is growing in the
southern part of the country, and the catastrophe is as much
man-made as natural. Almost everyone who has studied Sudan says
famines will continue until there is peace, but peace has proved
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: It is in no one's interest except the wretched and
politically impotent farmers who must watch their children die.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest indication of the scope of the famine, a
nutritional survey released Friday by Doctors Without Borders said
at least 120 people were dying every day within a three-mile radius
of Ajiep in the southwestern state of Bahr el Ghazal, one of the
hardest-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
   The survey said the mortality rate had skyrocketed in the last
10 days, to about seven deaths per 1,000 people each day from about
1.7 per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the government nor the main rebel organization puts a
high priority on concerns like feeding the masses. Both are more
concerned with winning the 15-year-old war. Again and again they
have manipulated the U.N. relief operation to their own tactical
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Islamic government in Khartoum, the Sudanese
capital, will not allow the United Nations to deliver food to the
rebel-held areas in the central Nuba Mountains but does allow
relief supplies to go to the towns and ``peace camps'' in that
region.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of this policy is to draw hungry Nuba people away from
the rebel-held territories into the towns and camps, where they can
be easily controlled and pressed to convert to Islam.
</P>
<P>
   In Bahr el Ghazal, where the current famine began, both sides
ignored the precarious situation of farmers earlier this year when
fighting suddenly resumed, sending more than 100,000 people
fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   As 1998 opened, the people in Bahr el Ghazal had lived through
two bad droughts and poor harvests. Constant raids by Kerubino
Kuanyin Bol, a former rebel leader who was siding with the
government, kept many communities from planting at all.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Kerubino chose this year to switch sides again,
rejoin the rebellion and attack the government-held town of Wau.
</P>
<P>
   Kerubino's decision set off a wave of fighting that displaced
tens of thousands of people at a time when they should have been
preparing to plant before the March rains.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the government immediately imposed a
flight ban on all but four airstrips in the region for most of
February and March.
</P>
<P>
   Again the reason appeared to be tactical. Khartoum did not want
the United Nations shipping massive amounts of food into rebel-held
territories at a time when government troops were trying to hold on
to Wau and defeat Kerubino's forces.
</P>
<P>
   Under heavy international pressure, the government relented in
April and opened the region to air traffic, but government-backed
militias continued to raid farms in northern Bahr el Ghazal,
disrupting aid operations.
</P>
<P>
   On the rebel side, the massive airlift is a godsend. Like
everyone else, soldiers have to eat. The rebel's civilian arm
levies a ``tax'' on people within its territories, taking a portion
of the grain that the United Nations hands out after relief workers
leave, aid officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is unclear how much grain ends up in the hands of the
Sudan People's Liberation Army, some aid organizations, like
Doctors Without Borders, have estimated the amount to be as much as
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The taxation has continued despite the growing famine. That is
why well-fed rebel troops can be seen in the same villages where
displaced people are at death's door. In Nairobi, U.N. officials
from Operation Lifeline Sudan, as the airlift is known, have
objected strenuously to rebel leaders about the practice, but it
continues in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is the taxation,'' Michelle Quintaglie, a
spokeswoman for the World Food Program, acknowledged Friday.
``These people give a portion of their relief food to the
community. The amount they have been giving recently is far greater
than they had been giving before.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the rebel food tax, the massive infusion of aid
helps the insurgents' military position, because their leaders do
not have to pay the political price for causing the people they
declare they are liberating to starve to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the U.N. is willing to ship 10,000 tons of food to the
front line, don't tell me that doesn't have an impact,'' said one
diplomat in Khartoum, who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 years of stalemate, it is beginning to look as if the
war is unwinnable. Neither side appears to have the logistical
capability and resources to support a sustained offensive that
could prove decisive, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have proved unable to take and hold major towns like
Juba and Wau. The government has proved unable to rout the rebels
in the bush.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks have limped along in Nairobi, under the flawed aegis
of a regional association, several of which, like Uganda and
Ethiopia, actively support the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   A new round of talks is scheduled for next month, but the two
sides are far apart. The rebels continue to demand a secular
government and a united Sudan, something the Islamic government in
Khartoum cannot agree to without going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Khartoum's Islamic leaders have proved masterful at dividing the
rebellion. They have reached separate accords with several small
rebel factions and have successfully played rogue rebel commanders
off one another, creating insecurity and chaos in several crucial
regions.
</P>
<P>
   But neither side has found a knock-out blow.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As the war drags on, the United States and its allies in western
Europe have done relatively little to pressure the two sides to go
to the negotiating table, diplomats say. Indeed the secretary of
state, Madeleine Albright, met with rebel leaders in December and
openly expressed moral support for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this is that peace does not necessarily suit U.S.
interests, aid officials said. U.S. foreign policy in the region
hinges on protecting the secular government in Egypt, the largest
recipient of U.S. aid, and containing Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   But the Moslem hard-liners in the National Islamic Front, who
control Khartoum's government, are seen as a direct menace to
Egypt's moderate government because they are sympathetic to the
fundamentalist terrorists there, notably the Islamic Brotherhood.
In short, the ongoing civil war in Sudan serves to weaken Khartoum
and strengthen Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A de-stable Sudan amounts to a stable Egypt,'' said a U.N.
official, insisting on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the rebels are hopelessly fractured along
tribal lines and have been unable to unite long enough to push the
government troops out.
</P>
<P>
   Their movement has also been made less effective by several
commanders who are little more than warlords and profiteers. These
men profess to be rebels but have switched sides several times and
appear to be more interested in reaping a profit from the war than
in winning it. They have little to gain from peace.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the rebellion's weakness that the SPLA began
in the 1980s as a communist revolt, when it was supported by the
then-Marxist government of Ethiopia, but it now professes to be
fighting for the principles of Jeffersonian democracy.
</P>
<P>
   This comes as no surprise to most Africans since the rebels'
current backers _ Uganda, Ethiopia and Eritrea _ are all firm
allies of the United States, who receive U.S. military aid and, in
turn, give similar aid to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not a grass-roots movement,'' said one aid official.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus is growing among aid officials that until the major
industrialized powers apply heavy pressure on both the rebels and
the government to come to terms, the tragedy of Sudan is doomed to
repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the problem lies is that Western democratic governments
are using Operation Lifeline Sudan and humanitarian assistance as a
substitute for any real policy on Sudan,'' complained one U.N.
official in Nairobi, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``They should be seriously engaged at the highest political levels
to end the conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
