<HEADER>
A2167 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-HULBERT-NEWSLE     07-24 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-HULBERT-NEWSLETTERS-$ADV26-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `BUYS' HAVE IT: BEWARE THE POLLYANA MESSAGE FROM BROKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 26) 
(af) 
Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. 
 By MARK HULBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brokers are to stocks what Will Rogers was to people. Hardly
ever do brokers meet a stock they don't like.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what the First Call Corp. discovered from its data base
of buy, hold and sell advice from brokerage firms. Using a
five-point scale in which 1 is a strong buy and 5 a strong sell,
the average recommendation for all stocks is a bullish 2.2. Fewer
than 1 percent of the recommendations that brokerages issue are
sells; only about one-third are holds. That means that roughly
two-thirds of all brokerage recommendations are buys.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is clear: Brokers won't tell you what or when to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   What to do instead? The best answer may be to decide now on a
strategy for selling stocks _ and then have the discipline to stick
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Discipline is the key. The investor without it gets caught up in
bullish enthusiasm at each market top and second-guesses every sell
signal, like the guy on the beach who threatens to beat up anyone
who steps over the line he has drawn in the sand _ but, when
challenged, simply draws a new line.
</P>
<P>
   Such investors are always reacting to what already has happened,
selling stocks after they have disappointed and switching into
other stocks after they have rallied. Because these investors are
constantly buying high and selling low, they are likely to be among
the biggest casualties when the market decides to head south.
</P>
<P>
   The Hulbert Financial Digest has monitored the performance of
investment newsletters for 18 years, and their track records
highlight the importance of discipline. The clear lesson is that
almost any decent strategy will work, as long as it is followed
strictly over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, even the most theoretically flawless strategy
won't work if it is not followed with discipline. For almost any
strategy, there is at least one investment letter in the Hulbert
Financial Digest data base that has done well with it and another
that has done poorly.
</P>
<P>
   One example can be found in the newsletters that pursue the
so-called Dogs of the Dow strategy. The variant of this approach
that is most popular among newsletter editors calls for buying the
lowest-priced, highest-yielding stocks among the 30 companies in
the Dow Jones Industrial average each Jan. 1 and then holding these
stocks for 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Following the strategy requires discipline, because it favors
stocks that already are down in the dumps _ stocks that often keep
languishing for a few months before turning around.
</P>
<P>
   Newsletters that followed the strategy last year with discipline
realized a creditable 23 percent return on their portfolios. One
that didn't _ BI Research, edited by Tom Bishop _ returned just 8
percent. Four months into the year, AT&AMP;T, one of the Dow dogs of
1997, was off 15 percent. Bishop acknowledged in his newsletter
that a purist would continue to hold AT&AMP;T, but nevertheless wrote
that he was kicking it out of his portfolio and replacing it with
Exxon.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's Law immediately kicked in: Exxon far underperformed
AT&AMP;T through the end of the year, gaining about 8 percent, compared
with 83 percent for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Newsletter editors aren't alone in their lapsed discipline.
Terrence Odean, a professor of finance at the University of
California at Davis, recently documented that Bishop's experience
was the norm among individual investors, too.
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing trading records for 10,000 accounts at a large
discount brokerage firm, he found that the stocks sold by investors
did 3.2 percent better, on average, over the next year than the
stocks they chose as replacements.
</P>
<P>
   On average, investors would make 3.2 percent more per year _ not
to mention saving the cost of trading commissions _ if they held on
to the stocks they wanted to dump and refrained from buying the
ones they were so sure were better bets.
</P>
<P>
   Why is investment discipline so rare a virtue? Because losses
exact an intense psychological toll.
</P>
<P>
   An experience of the Value Line Investment Survey makes the
point. Value Line's ranking system has such an impressive long-term
record that even skeptical academics have conceded that it beats
the market. One would think that this record would earn Value Line
a little slack in the face of short-term underperformance, but not
so.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of 1992, its system stopped working:
its least-favored stocks were outperforming its most-favored ones.
Value Line received a lot of bad press and came under great
pressure to tinker with its stock-picking model.
</P>
<P>
   As Samuel Eisenstadt, its research director, recounts the
episode, the company chose to resist that pressure _ and was amply
rewarded. By the end of 1992, its top-ranked stocks had roared
back, more than erasing losses incurred during the first half of
the year. Caving in to the pressure at midyear might have made life
easier for Value Line, but it would have been costly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to discipline, investors may also need advisers who
don't have an aversion to the ``S'' word. A top-performing
investment letter might fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Editors of newsletters have less of an aversion to offering
``sell'' advice than most other players in the investment advisory
arena. Most of the newsletters monitored by the Hulbert Financial
Digest recommend selling stocks as often as buying them.
</P>
<P>
   But remember: Even the best advice is little help without the
discipline to follow it over the long haul. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
