u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-BASKETBALL25     07-24 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-BASKETBALL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. basketball team grows up quickly
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Goodwill Games journey that began with so little
promise for the fledging U.S. team has instead emptied into Friday
night's gold-medal basketball game. They grow up so quickly in the
big city.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's semifinal was a stressless 89-76 victory over
Lithuania for the U.S. collegians, who met Australia for Goodwill
gold. Earlier Thursday, the Aussies disposed of Puerto Rico 86-74.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what to do to bury this team (Lithuania). That's how
far we've come. Sunday (in losing to Puerto Rico), we didn't know
how to bury a team,'' said Mississippi guard Keith Carter, whose 12
points, all in the second half, threw several shovels of dirt on
the Lithuanians.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. built a 16-point lead at the half behind the
inside-outside combination of Georgia's Jumaine Jones (nine points)
and Miami of Ohio's Wally Szczerbiak (13 points, 3-of-5 from beyond
the arc).
</P>
<P>
   It grew to as much as 25 points in the second half before the
Lithuanians did some cosmetic work on the scoreboard late in the
game. Szczerbiak, who grew up in nearby Long Island, led the
Americans with 20 points, followed by 15 from Duke's Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   That opening loss to Puerto Rico, in which the U.S. gave up a
19-point second-half lead, seems another lifetime. Since, they have
shown steady improvement, with a 15-point victory over China, a
31-point victory over Brazil and the never-any-doubt job against
the Lithuanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud and very excited to be playing for the gold,''
said U.S. coach Clem Haskins. ``After Sunday, we were a little
down. But these guys have bounced back and are playing some
outstanding basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   For the gold, they had to cope with another experienced,
physical opponent. But, warned Donn Nelson, an assistant coach for
the Lithuanians, ``Now that they're (the U.S.) coming together at
the right time, they're going to be tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
