<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DAMS-COX     07-24 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dams pose a problem for Texas
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Substandard dams pose a growing threat to people
and property in Texas, and the state's inspection program to keep
track of the problem is woefully inadequate, according to a task
force appointed by the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without public pressure to improve conditions, it is only a
matter of time before dam failures will begin to take their toll on
life and property on a more frequent basis,'' a report issed this
month by the task force concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-member task force, whose members included city officials,
dam owners, engineers and others, called for sweeping changes in
state policy. Among the recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   -- Beef up the state's dam-safety team, which now numbers six
people, compared with 45 about 20 years ago. The team currently
inspects only about 2 percent of the roughly 7,200 dams in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   -- Grant soil and water districts authority to impose taxes,
impact fees and capital development fees to finance improvement of
dams for which the districts are responsible.
</P>
<P>
   -- Require dam owners to prepare emergency-response plans for
all dams in populated areas. Such plans identify areas that would
be in danger if a dam collapsed, as well as evacuation routes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Modify state regulations to give owners of substandard dams
options short of fortifying dams to withstand worst-case flooding.
For example, owners could adopt a combination of risk-reduction
measures, such as lowering the level of the reservoir or lake
formed by the dam, installing an early-warning system and stepping
up inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Few dams in Texas are in imminent danger of collapsing. And most
large dams are in good shape or scheduled for improvements. But
more than 300 dams, primarily small and medium-sized structures,
could collapse in unusually severe floods, unleashing deadly waves
onto downstream houses, shopping strips, schools and highways.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous substandard dams are located in Central Texas,
including more than a dozen on Brushy Creek and its tributaries in
Williamson County.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Austin American-Statesman identified the
substandard dams and the shortcomings of the state's inspection
program. The conservation commission subsequently formed the task
force, and House Speaker Pete Laney ordered a separate review by a
special subcommittee of the House Natural Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The task force report has been given to the subcommittee. The
conservation commission is also reviewing the report and plans to
issue its own recommendations, said Jeffrey Saitas, executive
director. The subcommittee is expected to issue recommendations
later this year for lawmakers to consider during the next
legislative session, which opens in January.
</P>
<P>
   The task force, which spent a year preparing its report,
concluded that the dam-safety team is so short-handed that it
cannot perform basic duties. For example, dams in populated areas
are inspected once every 15 to 30 years. The federal government and
most independent experts recommend once every five years.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also found regulatory gaps. Smaller dams that
form detention ponds for stormwater runoff must meet state safety
standards, but construction plans for such dams do not have to be
filed with the conservation commission.
</P>
<P>
   Public and private owners of dams, including individuals,
property associations, hunting clubs, water districts and counties,
frequently lack the money to upgrade. Improvements can cost
hundreds of thousands of dollars, even millions, for each dam.
</P>
<P>
   Besides recommending that soil and water districts be granted
taxing and fee authority, the task force made no finding on how
money for other dams should be raised. It said lawmakers might want
to grant the conservation commission the power to charge fees to
help finance a larger inspection staff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
