<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LAWSUIT-COX     07-24 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Morales delivers agreement, ending tobacco lawsuit negotiations
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas tobacco war officially ended Friday
when U.S. District Judge David Folsom of Texarkana signed off on
final compromises involving the state, the tobacco industry,
counties and the state's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales, who filed the suit in March 1996
amid general indifference from other state officials, held a press
conference Friday to underline its end. He called the settlement
``a tremendous victory for the state and an unprecedented
opportunity to promote public health in our state, particularly the
health of our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit sought compensation for smoking-related health care
costs incurred by poor Texans and covered by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said that although Gov. George W. Bush and the
Legislature had not expressed much interest in the anti-tobacco
suit when he filed it, ``I do think that they're willing to accept
the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement will trigger a flow of $17.3 billion to the
state, counties and hospital districts over the next 25 years. The
issue of how much the industry must pay the state's private lawyers
who were hired to handle the suit was turned over to an arbitration
panel that will meet in November.
</P>
<P>
   The first payment of almost $400 million should be paid to the
state within a month, Morales said, with a total of $1.3 billion to
be paid this year.
</P>
<P>
   The final settlement of $17.3 billion includes $15 billion,
which the Legislature will decide how to spend. Originally, the
state was to get $15.3 billion, but the state gave up about $300
million of that to secure an additional settlement of $2.3 billion
for counties and hospital districts, Morales said.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.3 billion will go directly to counties and health
districts for indigent health care, with the first payments in
January. That first payment will include $10 million to Travis
County, $2.5 million to Williamson County, $1.1 million to Hays
County and $675,000 to Bastrop County, state figures showed.
</P>
<P>
   Morales announced the settlement in January, but it quickly
bogged down in legal skirmishing. Some critics, especially Bush,
argued that the lawyers should not get the $2.3 billion they said
they were owed under their contract with the state. And the
original settlement did not satisfy the claims of the counties and
health districts, although the tobacco industry maintained it
covered them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, however, got a break: After Texas reached agreement
with the tobacco industry, Minnesota settled its lawsuit on even
more favorable terms, triggering the ``most favored nation'' clause
in the Texas settlement. That clause said that the industry would
pay Texas more if other states later got better terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota settlement generated an additional $2.3 billion
for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   By committing that money to the counties and health districts,
their claims were resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry said Friday that the revised settlement
terminates the most favored nation clause.
</P>
<P>
   As for the private lawyers, a spokesman, Tom Banning, said
Friday only that they ``look forward to presenting our case to the
arbitration panel in November.''
</P>
<P>
   If the lawyers don't get as much money from the tobacco industry
as they think they should, they can go back to court to enforce
their contract with the state, under which they would be paid $2.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But even a group that was highly critical of the lawyers'
claims, Texans for Reasonable Legal Fees, said it was ``unlikely''
that the state would have to pay.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the governor, Linda Edwards, said he was
pleased that Texas will soon start getting its money and that the
issue of attorney fees had been separated from the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
