<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-EXPAND-NYT     07-24 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EXPAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL JOINT VENTURE AT HAND FOR AT&AMP;T 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bidding to significantly expand its presence outside the United
States, the AT&AMP;T Corp. is close to an agreement with British
Telecommunications PLC to form a joint venture serving
multinational business customers, executives close to the
negotiations said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The venture could be announced as early as Sunday, executives
said.
</P>
<P>
   A partnership between AT&AMP;T, the nation's No. 1 long-distance
carrier, and British Telecom, Britain's biggest communications
company, would perhaps be the foremost international
telecommunications venture. Demand for advanced communications
services is growing even faster overseas than it is in the United
States, according to many analysts, and big businesses are the most
lucrative segment of the international market.
</P>
<P>
   For AT&AMP;T, an agreement with British Telecom would represent
another piece of the puzzle that C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's
chairman, is putting together as he tries to reinvent AT&AMP;T as a
powerful yet nimble player in the highly competitive industry.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the agreement were unclear Friday, but the executives
close to the talks said that the two companies could be expected to
devote significant resources to a new business that could generate
hundreds of millions of dollars in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent a new strategy for AT&AMP;T, which has seen its
efforts to expand internationally largely founder in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the problem has been that the company has generally
shied away from investing significant sums to ensure lasting
relationships with its foreign affiliates. Rather, AT&AMP;T has formed
loose agreements to cooperate with more than a dozen foreign
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The dangers of that path became clear in April 1997 when
Telefonica de Espana SA, the largest communications provider in
Latin America, defected from an AT&AMP;T alliance to join a group that
was then led by British Telecom and the MCI Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecom and MCI had agreed to merge and form a new
multinational communications giant called Concert, though that deal
later fell apart and MCI agreed to be acquired by Worldcom Inc.
instead.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Fernando Panizo, chief operating officer of one of
Telefonica's main subsidiaries, said, ``The commitment of AT&AMP;T to
new investment has not been as strong as BT-MCI.''
</P>
<P>
   After MCI agreed to be acquired by Worldcom, Telefonica chose to
work with those two companies instead of with British Telecom.
Sprint Corp., the No. 3 long-distance carrier in the United States,
is partly owned by Deutsche Telekom, Germany's dominant
communications company, and France Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   That left British Telecom with dozens of international partners
but no fast friends in the United States at the same time that AT&AMP;T
was looking to revamp its overseas agenda.
</P>
<P>
   And Armstrong, who took over as AT&AMP;T's chairman last fall after
running Hughes Electronics, has demonstrated that he is not afraid
to move swiftly when he perceives opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he took the job, Armstrong agreed with outside
analysts that two of the main areas he needed to focus on were
expansion in the local communications market and expansion
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has committed the company to spending more than $40
billion to shore up those areas.
</P>
<P>
   In January, AT&AMP;T announced that it had agreed to acquire
Teleport Communications Group Inc., a new local phone company, for
$11.3 billion. That deal was AT&AMP;T's main bid to get into the local
communications market for business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the company announced an agreement to acquire
Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's No. 2 cable television
company, for $31.8 billion in an attempt to buy local line access
to millions of homes.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and British Telecom declined to comment, but in an
interview two days after the TCI deal was announced, Armstrong said
he was turning his attention to the international arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of buying a PTT or two,'' he said, using
telecommunications jargon for big foreign communications carriers.
``If that's the qualification for boldness, I'll disappoint you. On
the other hand, I think that we will announce something that indeed
satisfies that we have really a strong international global
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the telecommunications industry, a strong global strategy
generally requires a strong business serving multinational
corporations. International consumer calling continues to rise, but
big corporate customers are largely driving the consolidation of
the telecommunications industry with demands for advanced data
services that offer higher profit margins than everyday phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   In today's business world, a top-notch communications system can
provide companies a strategic advantage over their less-advanced
competitors; big multinational companies demand seamless global
communications. And seamless communications can be provided only by
telecommunications carriers with presence in major markets around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   So for British Telecom, an alliance with AT&AMP;T could represent a
recovery from its aborted merger with MCI, AT&AMP;T's archrival.
Forging a deal with AT&AMP;T, with its vast financial and technical
resources, would give British Telecom unparalleled access to U.S.
market, the world's richest.
</P>
<P>
   And British Telecom would still have the means to make another
big move. When Worldcom completes its acquisition of MCI, British
Telecom will receive more than $7 billion in cash for its 20
percent stake in MCI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
