<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-24 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE THREE STOOGES, ALL OVER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a great trifecta for Toronto. Talk about the Three Stooges
making a comeback. Mo Money, the Texas Con Man, and Wrong Way Jose
all under one roof in SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Con Man went north two years ago because he wanted to
play for ``a winner.'' Wrong Way Jose left a little while later,
wanting to be with a winner, in Oakland. Mo Money said a year ago
that he wanted the Red Sox to spend more money on better players so
he could be with ``a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   How quickly they forget about winning. Amazing, isn't it, how
these players forget about the talk and take a walk right to the
money?
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens left Boston, had a phenomenal year in Toronto in
'97, and said the reason was better fielding behind him. Of course,
it had nothing to do with the extra 30 pounds he was lugging around
in Boston that he shed in Toronto. And the message also was that
the guys he left behind in Red Sox uniforms, his former teammates,
couldn't field a lick.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mo Vaughn talks about being comfortable in Toronto with his
former mates and another manager after he becomes a free agent at
the end of the 1998 season. This leads us to believe he is not
comfortable with his present teammates and manager.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Canseco? He pulled a Mo Money when the Florida Marlins came
to Toronto earlier this year. Jose lives in Florida and sent the
message back home that he would love to finish his career with the
Marlins. So much for winning.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the owners of the Blue Jays can't wait to open their
wallets for Mo Money. The Blue Jays lost $34 million a year ago
when they added the Texas Con Man to help boost their sagging
attendance. He won the Cy Young Award, and no one cared. When he
pitched, they averaged about 500 more fans a game, clawing and
scratching their way to the empty seats in SkyDome to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what. This year's class of Red Sox defectors has Toronto
fans staying away in record numbers from SkyDome, where the Jays
are on course to draw 100,000 fewer fans than they did a year ago.
Do you think the Toronto owners want to shell out another $10
million (American) to have Mo Money join Clemens and Canseco in
baseball's version of welfare?
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Con Man was right when he told Mo that heading north
could add four or five years to his baseball life. In Toronto, you
can lose all you want, get paid big money, and no one cares.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what someone perhaps should have explained to Mo. In
Canada, the dollar is worth only about 75 percent of the US dollar.
So before the season starts, the Jays have to take in about $15
million extra just to break even, because almost all their payroll
is in American money.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know the Blue Jays' history will tell you that the
great fans up there were turned off by the baseball strike of 1994
and decided not to come back in record numbers. Falling attendance,
the conversion rate on the dollar, and bad teams have the
organization taking an annual bath financially, with no apparent
way out. But perhaps, because Mo is such a great leader of men,
they would like him to join the rest of the conscientious objectors
and add another $10 million in losses.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the phone was ringing off the hook at Fenway Park,
with fans delivering a strong message to get Mo Money out of town
immediately, the Red Sox will not. Unless.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan is still to try to win the American League
pennant. As long as Mo keeps playing well and doesn't become a
major distraction to the team, they will not trade him. This was
decided before the season and it will not change, unless the team
starts to fall out of playoff contention and some other team is
willing to part with something for Mo.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the season, the Sox will not be snookered the way
they were by the Texas Con Man, who claimed all along that he
wanted to come back to Boston. Remember when Clemens said on the
record that if he left Boston, he could never go to another
American League team because he would not want to play in Fenway
Park against the Red Sox? Of course, that was before Toronto showed
him the money. The Red Sox made the mistake of waiting for him to
make a decision in 1996; meanwhile, other free agents were being
signed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This year Mo will be given a take-it-or-leave-it offer as soon
as the season is over and have a short period of time to decide. As
soon as he makes it official _ as if he hasn't already with his
comments _ that he wants to leave, the Red Sox will take the $10
million they offered him and spend it elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   To this humble scribe, the most interesting part of Mo's
comments to Toronto writer Mike Zeisberger was not that the Blue
Jays are his first choice but this: ``It's a situation where you
would take a good deal and try not to break the bank. It's not
something where you try to set a new (salary) standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the Red Sox offered Mo Money $30 million over three
years. Not enough. In spring training, they offered him $22 million
for two years, or $11 million a year. Not enough. At the All-Star
break, they offered him $37 million over four years. Not enough.
Evidently, he doesn't feel any of those offers are what he would
consider a ``good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter, just two years old, will be getting a facelift
in the near future. ``I still haven't figured out for sure how we
are going to do it, but it will be part of the new development,''
says Bruins owner Jerry Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   When the demolition of Boston Garden is completed, Jacobs says
the next phase of the project will be to open the side of the
building facing Causeway Street to enlarge the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we have to do this,'' says Jacobs, ``and the
project would be moving along faster if I would sit down and decide
what I want done there. That is up to me, and it is something I
should start to get to work on. We defenitely need more space. We
have to create more room for our lobbies and corridors. We were
confined when we built the building, but now with the old Boston
Garden down, we have a chance to add more space to the new
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs says the project will be complicated because he also has
to factor in what space will be left for the rest of the
development, which is supposed to include a hotel plus office and
retail space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do something that is upbeat and that will blend
with the future of the area,'' he says. ``Boston's economy is
vibrant. What they are doing in town with the Big Dig and the rest
of it will be fantastic. We have to look at our business a little
differently. We have to take a look at what they are doing in other
parts of the country with theme restaurants and what we think will
serve our customer best. The building has been successful _ in
fact, in several ways, more successful than we thought it would be
at this point in time. What we have learned in the last couple of
years is that you have to keep on producing teams that people want
to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Omari Walker, now an assistant football coach at Framinhgam
(Mass.) High, gave these quotes to sports editor Len Megliola in a
terrific column in the Middlesex News.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were guys that bet againt us,'' said Walker, referring
to the gambling scandal at Boston College in 1996, his next-to-last
season, ``and guys who just bet on things like the World Series.
There was so much backbiting. We didn't know who to believe. The
team was so factioned out. You didn't even trust guys who block for
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were racial things. The team basically was divided.
There was a lot of stealing going on in the locker room. I had
never locked my locker because I didn't even know the combination.
It was a miserable time. You didn't want to talk with anyone. There
were all these things going on, and (Tom) O'Brien (who replaced Dan
Henning as coach last year) comes into this tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he had a fun year as a senior with O'Brien. ``It
wasn't draining and depressing like the year before,'' he said.
``We didn't win (4-7) but we were surrounded by good people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is how the NFL intends to turn the new Cleveland Browns
into the most expensive team in sports history. Goldman Sachs of
New York, which once tried to sell the Patriots, has been employed
by the league to handle the bidding. Goldman Sachs will go to the
list of bidders _ at least a half-dozen on record and maybe more _
and ask for an initial offer. Then it will take the highest bid and
revisit the rest of the field, one by one, seeing who wants to top
it and dropping those who don't. It will go back and forth with
``managed bids'' until there is just one left _ the new owner.
</P>
<P>
   Some think former Cleveland resident George Steinbrenner, owner
of the Yankees, could sell his baseball team once he sees what the
Browns are worth. Reportedly, one estimate is that the Yankees
could pull in $725 million if Steinbrenner decides to sell in the
current market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
