</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS RISE AS GM MOVES TO REOPEN A KENTUCKY PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico, Ind., Ky., Mich., Ohio, Tenn.)  (js) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ General Motors and the United Automobile Workers
union moved on Friday toward a confrontation in Kentucky even as
lawyers for both sides continued to argue before an arbitrator over
the legality of strikes at two GM parts factories here.
</P>
<P>
   GM announced earlier this week that it would use replacement
parts from factories elsewhere to reopen its Chevrolet Corvette
factory in Bowling Green, Ky., and a sport utility vehicle factory
in Silao, Mexico. Both assembly plants have been closed for more
than a month, along with virtually all other GM assembly plants in
North America, for lack of parts from the struck factories here.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to settle the strikes here have been complicated by
disputes popping up at a growing number of GM factories. Workers
are also threatening strikes at car assembly plants here and in
Tennessee and at parts factories in Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, the union's vice president for GM issues,
said in an interview on Friday that when workers show up at the
Corvette factory on Monday, they will probably object to the use of
replacement parts. When GM tried two weeks ago to reopen an engine
factory in Romulus, Mich., workers threw replacement spark plugs
from Japan on the floor and refused to use them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they call workers back to the Bowling Green plant, they'll
have the same problems finding them cooperative that they've had
elsewhere,'' Shoemaker said, adding that GM had ended up asking the
Romulus workers to assemble other engines that did not require
replacement parts.
</P>
<P>
   But Shoemaker said that though the local union leadership at the
Corvette factory had asked the national UAW leadership for
permission to call a strike, that permission had not been given.
The national leadership wants to watch the arbitration process here
and GM's other actions over the coming days before making a
decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful we can find a way to resolve all this without
resorting to that,'' Shoemaker added. If the national leadership
decides in favor of another strike, it will be required to give
five days' notice to GM.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Holmes, a GM spokesman, said earlier on Friday that GM
still planned to reopen the Corvette factory on Monday. GM
officials did not return calls for further comment on Friday night
after Shoemaker spoke.
</P>
<P>
   The Corvette factory is the only GM assembly plant in the United
States where the UAW has not reached a local labor agreement with
the auto maker since the last national agreement was concluded in
1996. That lack of an agreement would make it easier for the UAW to
call a walkout there.
</P>
<P>
   But the union's national leadership is often wary of granting
permission for local strikes, because once a strike begins, its
duration is partly determined by the local union leaders, who share
negotiating responsibilities with the national leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Corvette factory accounts for less than 1 percent of GM's
North American production, while the Mexican factory is somewhat
larger. The Kentucky factory produced just 2,768 Corvettes in May,
while a full-size GM assembly plant produces about 20,000 vehicles
a month. Of the company's 29 assembly plants, the only one still in
full production is the giant Saturn factory in Spring Hill, Tenn.,
which is already using replacement parts, notably spark plugs from
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturn factory has a highly independent local union and a
strong tradition of working with management to preserve sales and
market share. The local union there has objected to the outside
parts, and workers authorized their leaders to call a strike if
negotiations failed on such other issues as Saturn's growing use of
parts made in other GM factories and by outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   In Flint, both sides have been somewhat hopeful that they can
reach a settlement at the bargaining table after the arbitrator,
Thomas Roberts, reaches his decision. Lawyers for the company and
the union made opening statements before Roberts on Wednesday. GM
then presented its case on Thursday and Friday morning that the
strikes here violate the union's national agreement with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The union began presenting its case Friday afternoon and is
expected to continue doing so on Saturday. Roberts is allowed up to
30 days to deliver his decision, but he is expected to issue a
ruling quickly, perhaps next week, because of the strike's huge
cost to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   GM's national labor agreement with the UAW allows only
factory-level strikes over issues of health and safety,
productivity standards and subcontracting. The company contends
that the union made up such grievances at the factories here as an
excuse for strikes, and then began using the local strikes to
demand that the company invest more money here, which is not a
legitimate strike issue. The union contends that GM has bargained
over investments during many previous local strikes, so that the
national contract should be interpreted as allowing factory strikes
in which investments are among the issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
