<HEADLINE>
SANDERS MAKES DEBUT AT COWBOYS PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
And KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders
practiced at training camp yesterday for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who has been sidelined since having arthroscopic
surgery on his left ankle May 29, worked out in the afternoon
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' presence was attention-grabbing. The most notable
sighting was a hit he put on running back Emmitt Smith although the
practice was without pads. After Smith broke outside on a running
play, the normally tackle-shy Sanders met him chest-to-chest,
knocking Smith back and startling the crowd, which cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders declined to comment on his return.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates and coaches, however, said they are glad to see
him back, including Smith, who offered a word of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see him out there,'' Smith said. ``But if he
keeps doing that, he'll be out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, who hopes to deploy Sanders as a
receiver, said it will be three weeks before Sanders starts working
with the offense. &QL; 
IRVIN IN THE BACKFIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the Cowboys continue to install the offense, new wrinkles are
being revealed daily. Yesterday, it was receiver Michael Irvin
catching a screen pass out of the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   The wrinkle partly shows how Gailey plans to free Irvin from the
numerous double-teams he faced last season.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin said he is used to catching the ball downfield but doesn't
mind the tricks, if they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like any new wrinkle that doesn't put the pressure on a team
to find a big-time receiver,'' Irvin said. ``The pressure is on
Chan. He's the man. It puts the pressure on him to move me around
and create mismatches not only with me but with other receivers,
and that's a great situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin said he was ``loving it'' until ``I saw big Leon Lett out
there. If it had been a real game I might have been in trouble.'' &QL; 
HARPER TO BE EVALUATED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys receiver Alvin Harper, cut yesterday by Saints
coach Mike Ditka, could get a look from the Cowboys, team vice
president Stephen Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The team will evaluate the eight-year pro as they do all free
agents and decide whether he can help the team, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Making the prospect more intriguing is that Harper stated more
than one once the past few years that he wants to return to the
Cowboys, who have sought a No. 2 receiver to complement Irvin since
Harper left after the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints were Harper's third team in the past two years. He
was with the Buccaneers in 1995-96. He played with the Saints and
Redskins last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka, upset that Harper missed minicamps and didn't show up for
off-season work, cut him before the team had its first practice of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alvin is a good guy,'' Ditka said. ``I don't have time to hold
his hand.'' &QL; 
EMMITT RETURNS TO PRACTICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith was back in his familiar role taking
snaps with the first-team offense after missing practice Thursday
because of fluid on his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said an errant kick to the leg last week probably caused
the swelling. He said there was some swelling yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got the (magnetic resonance imaging exam), there was no
concern,'' Smith said. ``I wanted to know why it was swelling. It's
probably because last week I got kicked in the upper shin area. It
was swelling, and it probably moved up to my knee.'' &QL; 
MURPHY MARTIN RETIRES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murphy Martin, the Cowboys' longtime public-address announcer at
Texas Stadium, has decided to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Martin will be replaced by George Dunham, co-host of the Dunham
and Miller morning show on KTCK/1310 AM.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will honor Martin before the regular-season opener
against Arizona on Sept. 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
