<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SEEK N.H. RAPE SUSPECT IN THE NETHERLANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police in Manchester, N.H., sought warrants Friday for the
arrest of convicted rapist and New Hampshire fugitive Steven B.
Gordon after he admitted to a police detective Thursday that he
raped a Nashua, N.H. realty agent and two Irish women.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did confess,'' Manchester detective Dan Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who police believe is still hiding in Amsterdam, made a
pre-arranged phone call to Brennan at the suburban Boston home of
his mother, who has been in regular contact with her son since he
fled New England last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, Amsterdam investigators, and at least four New England
police departments are trying to find Gordon, who is also suspected
in a series of Massachusetts robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified Gordon as a suspect in the rapes of the Irish
women in Portsmouth, N.H. July 18 through paperwork he filled out
to rent a car.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30-minute phone conversation with Brennan, Gordon sounded
confused and discussed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But detectives hope to find him soon. ``It's a matter of time,''
Brennan said. ``He is running out of money, he doesn't have a place
to stay, he hasn't slept, he hasn't eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, posing as a home buyer, allegedly raped a realty agent
he asked to show him a house for sale on July 7. After the alleged
rape, he forced the realty agent to drive him to Nashua; Brennan
said he will face kidnapping charges in addition to the rape
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan said Gordon provided details that police believe only
the man who raped the realty agent would know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good evidence, but you still need to put together a
case,'' Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   A police source said that a black pellet handgun Gordon's mother
allowed the Globe to photograph on Thursday does not appear to be
the weapon used in the rape of the realty agent.
</P>
<P>
   However, police believe Gordon did use a pellet gun in that
rape, and the source said the gun that was in his mother's
possession closely resembles the weapon the victim described to
police.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's reported confession to police Thursday came one day
after a man who said he was Gordon confessed to a Globe reporter
that he committed all three rapes. Gordon said he felt out of
control, regreted his actions, and neglected to take medication he
said was prescribed for mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also said he committed several armed robberies after he
raped the realty agent on July 7, including a Marriott Hotel in
Burlington, Mass., a Holiday Inn in Lexington, Mass., and a
D'Angelo's sandwich shop. There were robberies at those businesses
that night, and now police are investigating whether Gordon
committed them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other details of what appears to be a 2 1/2-week
crime spree by Gordon are beginning to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed in Superior Court in New Hampshire by Gordon's
probation officer show that Gordon violated his probation to travel
to Las Vegas, Nev. from July 1 to July 5. Police are now
investigating whether Gordon may have committed crimes there.
</P>
<P>
   Records also show that Gordon flew from Logan International
Airport last July 19 to New York, where he is believed to have
boarded a plane to Amsterdam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
