<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNFIRE SEEMED TO COME OUT OF NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-VICTIMS, CAPITOL-GUNMEN,
CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He wore khaki pants and a green fedora hat with a
feather, witnesses said, as any tourist might. But he was armed
with a six-shot Smith &AMP; Wesson .38-caliber revolver, and almost as
soon as he traded the July heat for the cool of the Capitol, he
opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses and authorities described a sudden and shocking burst
of shots after officer Jacob Chestnut asked Russell Eugene Weston
Jr. to pass through a metal detector, like every other visitor.
</P>
<P>
   As tourists screamed and stampeded, Weston left Chestnut
mortally wounded on the floor. His path into the Capitol was
blocked by other officers, so he turned left toward a door marked
private that opens onto the ``rabbit warren,'' as insiders call the
maze of offices belonging to Tom DeLay, the House majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the door Special Agent John Gibson was shouting at staff
to hit the floor. Witnesses and authorities offered conflicting
versions of what came next. What is clear is that Gibson and Weston
traded shots that cut each other down, but not before Weston
reached the first office of DeLay's extensive suite.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later some 10 officers surrounded Weston, their guns
trained at his head, said two of DeLay's aides. The office carpet
was soaked in blood.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in the echoing marble hallways of the Capitol's first
floor, the visitors' blend of boredom, curiosity and awe had turned
to bedlam as shell casings scattered across the stone floor, and
officers shouted at them to get out. In the fusillade, one
bystander, Angela Dickerson, was seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors took refuge behind pillars; others simply crouched
where they stood. As his wife dove to the floor, one man covered
her with his own body, while a young woman lost a sandal in her
scramble for a revolving door _ which turned out to be jammed by a
boy's backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Beamish, a 69-year-old tourist from England, said that he
bent over a wounded police officer _ it must have been Chestnut _
feeling for his pulse as the officer muttered words he could not
make out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled, get a stretcher,'' said Beamish, whose khaki pants
were stained with blood. ``There was blood coming from his head,
and one eye looked as if it was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone had had the presence of mind to summon Sen. Bill Frist
of Tennessee off the floor of the Senate. The senator, a heart
surgeon, checked the pulse of one of the wounded, then helped
resuscitate Weston and rode with him to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980724.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2200 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP-     07-24 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 DEAD IN CAPITOL SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: We call your attention to a New York Times photo of a
wounded victim minutes after the shooting at the Capitol on Friday.
Paul Hosfros of the New York Times staff was the first photographer
on the scene and his image of the bleeding tourist, Angela
Dickerson, will appear on the front page of Saturday's New York
Times. The photo is available to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(hlw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A gunman with a history of Secret Service
investigation burst into the Capitol building on Friday afternoon
and killed two policemen in a corridor shootout that left a tourist
and the gunman lying wounded as terrified bystanders darted for
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Without uttering a word, the intruder stormed past a weapons
detector at an East Front entrance and immediately opened fire,
mortally wounding a policeman on guard duty and setting off a gun
battle by the office suite of Rep. Tom DeLay, the Republican
majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   As the first officer, Jacob Chestnut, lay dying, DeLay's
plainclothes guard, Special Agent John Gibson, drew his weapon and
intercepted the intruder a short distance into the building. As
screams and gunfire reverberated through the halls of power, Gibson
suffered mortal wounds before the gunman was brought down in a
burst of a score or more bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect someone to come in with guns blazing,'' John
P. Feehery, DeLay's communications director, declared after the
gunman was felled in a bloody exchange near the legislator's office
and a gift shop busy with summer tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman was identified as Russell Eugene Weston, Jr.,
described by authorities as a man with a criminal record and a
history of mental disturbance who has been previously listed on the
Secret Service's watch list of hundreds of possibly troublesome
individuals, following reports that he had made threatening remarks
about President Clinton. Among the many reports the Secret Service
investigates, Weston was not considered as a major danger,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's driver's license described him as blonde-haired and
blue-eyed, with an address in Valmeyer, Ill., according to police
authorities who said he also had recent roots in Helena, Mont.
Authorities said he had used a 6-shot .38-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson
revolver in his attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The carpet in our office is covered in blood,'' Tim Berry, a
30-year-old policy advisor to DeLay declared in describing the
scene as the gunman, in khaki pants and a green fedora with a
feather, was finally shot down. ``Ten police officers surrounded
the suspect with guns trained at his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry was drinking champagne amid a group of DeLay staffers in
the whip's suite of offices, celebrating the passage of health care
legislation when the gunman burst into the building, about 30 yards
from DeLay's inner office. Some of them dove under desks, others
darted for the back of the office suite.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman's siege erupted at 3:40 p.m. shortly after both the
Senate and House had ended their debating business for the week.
Alerted in minutes about the casualties, Sen. Bill Frist, a cardiac
surgeon, rushed from the Senate offices in the northern end of the
Capitol, administering to one of the dying police as well as to the
gunman, who was later reported in non-critical condition with two
gunshot wounds to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was focused on keeping their heart and lungs going,'' the
senator said later after riding with emergency workers to the
hospital. ``This is a very serious catastrophe,'' he added,
speaking shortly before the extent of the tragedy was confirmed by
the lowering of the Capitol flag to half-staff in honor of the two
police slain as they denied the gunman deeper entrance to the
building.
</P>
<P>
   The tourist wounded in the crossfire, identified as 24-year-old
Angela Dickerson, was listed in serious condition with wounds in
the face and the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   There was potential for far greater mayhem, for the gunman had
set off the weapons detector at one of the Capitol's main public
entrances, the Document Door passage at the top of the Capitol
steps that opens past the gift shop, with the historic Crypt area
beyond, below the Great Rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of tourists at nearby turnings were suddenly propelled
into panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone was making a purchase and I heard shots to my right,''
said Tyvon Crawford, a 20-year-old student and employee at the
gift-shop kiosk. ``I looked, and jumped down into the booth and
then a tourist jumped in with us. I was able to see downed bodies.
The gunman came in and fired one shot and security guards fired
back at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Beamish, a 69-year-old tourist from Gloucester, England,
stood and recalled the scene later, his pants stained with blood.
``We heard the shots go off,'' he said. ``Everybody scattered. I
saw an officer hit the floor. I went over to him and felt his
pulse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to say something to me,'' Beamish continued. ``I
yelled, `Get a stretcher!' There was blood coming from his head,
and one eye looked as if it were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Just beyond, at the museum display cases on the Crypt floor,
Judson Threlkeld and his wife, Rachel, were studying a bit of
Capitol history when gunfire and screams startled them. ``We heard
a bang,'' he said later. ``She dropped to the floor and I got on
top of her. There was a pause and we were afraid he was going to
come into the open space and start firing.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple ducked behind a pillar as Capitol police came
through. ``They yelled, `Get out! Get out!' and about 20 of us ran
out of the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was about to depart for a weekend at his Camp David
retreat in Maryland when the Capitol attack occurred about a mile
to the East. He was kept apprised of the attack, keeping to his
schedule, just as legislative officials emphasized that the Capitol
would be open on Saturday, with no curtailing of its routine. ``We
will not shut down the Capitol,'' insisted, Rep. Bill Thomas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
