<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST BREACH RAISES NEW QUESTIONS ABOUT CAPITOL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Security at the US Capitol has been violated in
some high-publicity incidents over the years, including Friday's
shooting rampage, despite a 15-year effort that has markedly
tightened access to the building.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, US Capitol Police have imposed a variety of measures
to improve security, including the installation of metal detectors
and closing the road directly in front of the Capitol. Overall,
officials stressed, the symbol of the nation's democratic system
must be secure but open to all.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Capitol is more open than most federal buildings.
There are numerous entrances, including tunnels that connect to the
nearby House and Senate office buildings. At any moment during the
day, the maze of hallways and ornate public rooms are filled with
senators, representatives, lobbyists, journalists, and thousands of
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The 181-acre grounds of the Capitol and the surrounding
buildings are patrolled by 1,000 uniformed members of the US
Capitol Police. The roads around the Capitol are lined with 758
concrete barriers and have 33 barriers that rise from the road.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anyone can walk up to the Capitol building before going
through security, which is different from the White House, where a
gated security system rings the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's shooting, there were conflicting reports about
whether the gunman went through the metal detector and set it off
or whether he avoided it. Representative William Thomas, a
California Republican, said gunman ``went around the
Magnetometer,'' referring to the metal detector.
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by an exchange of gunfire and the death of two
officers.
</P>
<P>
   If Thomas's description of the assailant's entry is correct and
the gunman went around the metal detector, it raises serious
questions about whether the visitors' entrances are secure.
</P>
<P>
   The incident comes at a time when the federal government
continues to evaluate the effectiveness of metal detectors and
other security devices. A 1996 government study of metal detectors
at airports found a 40 percent failure rate in detecting bombs,
grenades, guns and knives.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, a federal study found a broad range of deficiencies
in the government's ability to track terrorists who might attack
federal buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Arenberg, spokesman for the National Association of
Police Chiefs, said if a person is determined to get a gun past a
metal detector, he or she could probably do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who really wanted to get a device through could do so
in pieces and then put it back together again,'' Arenberg said. He
said the effectiveness of metal detectors depends entirely on the
person operating them. Such devices can be set to varying degrees
of sensitivity and must be watched closely to determine whether a
gun is present.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Capitol Police often search bags by hand, a
method that is not foolproof.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Holmes Norton, the congressional representative from
Washington, said on CNN after the shooting that she is satisfied
with the security at the Capitol and urged that there not be an
overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a breach of security. This was a maniac barging
in,'' she said. ``You can't design security around a maniac. I
don't think there is a lot more they can do. We must not overact so
the people's house is no longer that.''
</P>
<P>
   A series of incidents in recent years have underscored that
security at federal buildings can be violated. Even the White House
has not been immune, with an airplane crash-landing on the South
Lawn and a shooting occurring at the gate. Then came the bombing of
the federal building in Oklahoma City, prompting a new wave of
security concerns at federal facilities.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the stretch of Pennsylvania Avenue in front of the
White House has been closed to vehicular traffic since May 1995.
Most recently, a series of shooting at schools and elsewhere by
children have led to a debate over the easy availability of guns
and other weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol has been the scene of sporadic violence, but
Friday's incident was one of the worst ever. Most famously during
this century, Puerto Rican extremists in March 1954 went to the
House visitor's gallery and shot and wounded five congressmen on
the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   A new round of security measures began after a 1983 incident in
which a group opposed to US involvement in Lebanon and Grenada
planted a bomb outside the Senate chamber. That prompted the
Capitol Police to install metal detectors and X-ray machines.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1985, after a suicide bomber killed 241 Marines in
Beirut, Capitol Police closed off public access to the street
directly in front of the Capitol building.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been incidents since then demonstrating that
security is vulnerable. In 1989, columnist Jack Anderson sneaked a
plastic handgun into the Capitol and displayed it during an
interview with then-Senator Bob Dole. At the time, Capitol security
officials criticized Anderson for staging a publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a man brought a .357 Magnum into a Senate committee
hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those who work on Capitol Hill said security is notably
tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have known a guard here five or six years, and she makes me
show the ID every day,'' said Jim Jones, press secretary for
Senator John F. Kerry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
