<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-OFFICERS-NYT &LR;      07-24 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-OFFICERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST CAPITOL POLICE OFFICERS EVER KILLED IN LINE OF DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-SCENE, CAPITOL-TOURIST,
CAPITOL-GUNMEN, CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO) 
(lh) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After 18-years in the Capitol police force, Jacob
Chestnut was looking forward to his retirement. But the 58-year-old
officer remained so ebullient and outgoing with tourists that one
senator said he seemed like the Capitol's official greeter.
</P>
<P>
   John Gibson, an eight year veteran of the force worked in the
plainclothes division, assigned to guard Rep. Tom DeLay, the third
ranking member of the House Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Friday both men gave their lives stopping a gunman who barged
into the Capitol and opened fire. According to the Senate historian
it was the first time on record that Capitol police officers had
been shot and killed in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers who were killed _ and those who apprehended the
gunman _ are true heroes of democracy and every American owes them
a deep debt of gratitude,'' said House Speaker Newt Gingrich
</P>
<P>
   Police said both men were married and each had three children.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were members of the Capitol's own police force,
formed shortly after an 1828 incident in which a journalist slapped
President John Quincy Adam's son, who was on official business for
his father at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Now the force counts about 1,200 officers who guard the doors
and entry ways on Capitol Hill, investigate threats against members
of Congress and provide them with personal protection.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he knew the two men, Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., said,
``We passed them multiple times during a day. And you exchange _
you know, `How are you?' You don't expect an answer. And they're
there every day. And no one expects this to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, according to members of Congress was shot in the chest
when he stopped the gunmen and told him to go through the metal
detector stationed at the entrance that he guarded. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
