<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-BABANGIDA-935     07-24 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-BABANGIDA-935&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGERIAN REVISITS HIS PLACE IN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNA, Nigeria _ Consider the general in his labyrinth,
ensconced beside the Oriental vases and the chocolate-filled glass
bowls, switching television channels with the same nonchalance he
has shown in defying Nigerian political gravity for more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   At ease, one might say of this legendary African survivor,
Ibrahim Badamosi Babangida, IBB for short, military ruler of
Nigeria from 1985 to 1993, and still for many the real power behind
the country's enduring military government. But something, it
seems, is ruffling Babangida.
</P>
<P>
   That something is the fact that _ having talked for years about
Nigeria's need for democracy, having engineered many ``transition
programs'' _ Babangida annulled the presidential election of 1993,
ushering Africa's most populous nation into a five-year nightmare
under his former second-in-command, the late Gen. Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard for me,'' a barefoot Babangida said of the
annulment. ``In fact the agony I went through is really better not
imagined. But it was the price I had to pay. I was the chief
executive in 1993. You delegate authority but you do not delegate
responsibility. The buck stopped at my table. What we did was wrong
but we tried to rationalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the subject of Moshood K.O. Abiola, the opposition
leader who died in custody this month and whose apparent victory in
1993 he denied, the twinkly-eyed Babangida continued: ``Abiola was
my friend for 25 years, a very genuine friend. From the day we met,
there was a rapport. I had my friend there waiting to take over. It
would have been a great destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Destiny, however, led elsewhere: to the cruelty and crassness of
the Abacha regime. The general shook his head. Having survived two
coup attempts, he learned long ago to leave certain things unsaid.
Nigeria is a great, seething amalgam of tribes and religions, as
exhilarating as it is dangerous. But the general's son, Muhammed
Babangida, offered the following clarification of the riddle of the
fateful 1993 decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were other generals, including Abacha, who said that if
power was ceded to a southerner like Abiola, the north would have
nothing left,'' the younger Babangida said. ``They put my father in
a corner. They threatened him.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know what degree of armed duress led
Babangida to deny Abiola. But what is clear, as Nigeria embarks on
yet another promised transition to democracy, is that the central
conundrum of this country remains unchanged: how to balance a
devoutly Muslim north, accustomed to power, with a mainly Christian
or pagan south that is increasingly restive.
</P>
<P>
   The oil reserves are in the south, and are of the highest
quality and good for several more decades. The big businesses are
in the south, in Lagos. The north without the south would be
barren, landlocked, dismal.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal military academy is in the north, in Kaduna. The
sons of northern notables, or emirs, have prospered in the armed
forces. And on the unspoken principle that economic and political
power cannot reside in the same place, no ruler of Nigeria since
1979, civilian or military, has come from the south.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, who took power when
Abacha died suddenly last month, is a longtime neighbor of
Babangida. They grew up together in this north-central town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head of state and I went to school together,'' Babangida,
who is 56, said. ``His home was next to mine. Our parents knew each
other. We are not really related, but we are very close, having
been together in a typical northern Nigerian society for about 48
years.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Babangida, as some newspapers here have suggested, behind
Abubakar's appointment and a speech he made on Monday? In that
speech he rejected opposition calls for the installation by Oct. 1
of a civilian government of national unity, but promised to hand
over power to an elected president on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, Babangida said, could be further from the truth. He was
not even consulted on the speech, he said. His role now, he added,
is to provide advice, but only when requested, and ``do what I can
to bring about the painful coexistence of nationalities and
religions in a united Nigeria.'' However, he added, it was a good
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The general feels his life has been dedicated to the
preservation of Nigeria _ in the civil war after the southeastern
Ibo tribe seceded and declared the state of Biafra in the 1960s; in
his attempts to curb the more extreme forms of Islamic zealotry in
the north; in his victory in 1990 against an attempted coup whose
southern instigators wanted to expel five northern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am from the crisis generation,'' he said. ``Turbulence,
turbulence, turbulence has been my lot. A supreme price was paid
for the unity of this country: the sacrifice of more than 1 million
people in the civil war. No matter what, 95 percent of Nigerians
now see themselves together. The question of Nigeria as one entity
is a settled one.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that widespread intermarriage, the presence
of different tribes in all parts of the country, the absence of
recrimination or revenge killings after the Biafran war, and a
palpable sense of being the big power in Africa have imbued the
Nigerian idea with an unlikely vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in a 38-year-old state that has never achieved
stable democracy, the issue of unity appears anything but resolved.
Indeed, Babangida's decision in 1993 to deny victory to Abiola, a
man with support in all parts of the country, clearly delivered
Nigerian nationhood a body blow.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Criticism of Abubakar's program has centered on the absence
before elections of any democratic forum in which Nigeria's
structure could be discussed. Despite this criticism, and the anger
in the south over Abiola's death, Babangida said he was confident
that Abubakar would now steer the country to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a Third World political nation,'' he said. ``We
have a vibrant, well-trained population that wants to participate.
The military's esprit de corps has suffered from too much time in
government, and it is time to go back to the barracks. The world
has moved on, and as I have said many times since 1989, military
rule is now an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave a smile that somehow bridged the colossal gap between
his words and his actions. A man for all seasons, it seems. Written
off, plotted against, denounced, but as yet in the saddle. Perhaps
then, in retirement, a future democratic leader?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no interest in politics, therefore no interest in
forming a party, and therefore no interest in elective office,''
Babangida said. ``I think I am out. People are scared I will rear
my ugly head again. But no, not really. They will have to find
somebody else as a target for their darts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
