</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHOOTING-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SAY CAPITOL MUST REMAIN OPEN DESPITE SHOOTING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
and TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of Congress pledged Friday to retain the
openness that allows citizens to roam the Capitol's many corridors
despite the shootout that left two officers dead and a tourist
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the people's house, and I deplore the actions of the
person who brought violence within these sacred halls,'' said
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The gleaming white building that houses the House chamber on its
south side and the Senate chamber on its north side has withstood a
number of attacks from terrorists over the decades. But only in
recent years has access become more restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, recalled a time when staff could
drive cars past the east front of the building, a practice that
ended with a 1983 bombing outside the office of Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., and the Beirut blast that killed more than 200 U.S.
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will need to investigate the situation, but we need to do
everything possible to not restrict the people's access to the
capital. This is the shrine of democracy throughout the world. If
we were to become overly restrictive it would be like coddling the
terrorists, and I don't think we want to do that,'' Bentsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Turner, D-Texas, recalled one of his biggest thrills as
a high school student was a tour of the Capitol building. ``This
building belongs to the people of the United States. I think there
will probably be an examination of the security, but I would
certainly hope we would not restrict the public's access,'' Turner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol building is one of the most popular tourist
destinations in the city, and there has always been a delicate
balancing act between protecting the leaders and staffs who work
there and allowing public access.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, several incidents _ both directed at the Capitol
itself and against U.S. targets elsewhere _ have prompted
authorities to take measures to increase security at the building.
</P>
<P>
   It has been bombed three times, and was once set on fire _ by
the British in 1814. There have been shootings and attempted
assassinations, and countless brawls and fights. However, on one
has ever died in an incident.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more memorable and significant of those acts were the
attack in 1954 in the House of Representatives by Puerto Rican
nationalists, in which five lawmakers were injured by gunfire; a
bomb blast in a toilet in 1971 that caused extensive damage but no
injuries; and a bomb blast in the Senate wing in 1983 in which two
leftist radicals caused about $260,000 worth of damage.
</P>
<P>
   Other incidents directed at U.S. facilities over the years,
including the bombing of the Federal Building in Oklahoma City in
1995, prompted even tougher security measures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Capitol remains open in comparison to the White
House. The president's residence is ringed by an iron fence.
Tourists must have tickets, pass through metal detectors and are
allowed inside for guided tours only. People with official business
must have their names and Social Security numbers given to the
Secret Service before being cleared onto White House grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, tourists, lobbyists and journalists are granted
access to the Capitol building after passing though security
screens at each door. Tourists have unfettered and unescorted
access throughout the Capitol except for some hallways clearly
marked off limits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, prompted by constant protests by anti-Vietnam War
activists, the U.S. Capitol Police department was formed.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30 metal detectors manned by armed guards screen
visitors to the Capitol and nearby offices. The entire complex is
surrounded by concrete barriers disguised as flower pots, virtually
every nook and cranny inside is scanned by television cameras, and
plainclothes officers supplement the uniformed force.
</P>
<P>
   At any given hour, at least 27 armed patrolmen, some with dogs,
walk the grounds. There are more than 1,200 officers now.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, lawmakers proposed streamlining visitors' entry into
the building by constructing an $83 million visitors center
underground on the east side of the Capitol where all visitors
would pass through security before entering the building. The
Capitol Police also proposed erecting a fence around the entire
building. Both of those proposals are on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure Americans are ready to be told they can't come to
their Capitol,'' said Michael Sullivan, a spokesman for Rep. Ron
Paul, R-Texas. ``You can't stop the lone lunatic. It's a sad
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Texas, said there may be some changes, but
``I don't anticipate a lessening of the openness.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the congressman expressed sorrow at the deaths of the
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their dedication that keeps the freedom available,''
Lampson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
