<HEADER>
A2220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-MOURNERS-NYT &LR;      07-24 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-MOURNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOSNIAN TOWN WHERE THOUSANDS DIED, ETHNIC HATE OVERWHELMS
KINDNESSES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SREBRENICA, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ As dozens of American soldiers
stood guard and a military helicopter hovered, Hasan Nuhanovic
nervously carried out one of the most basic of human rituals _
mourning the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after ambushes and mass executions by Bosnian Serb
soldiers here left 7,300 Bosnian Muslims presumed dead, he and 65
other men and women recently became the first group of Bosnian
Muslim civilians to peacefully re-enter this mining town in eastern
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   No violent confrontations erupted during the hour-and-a-half
visit, on June 11, to the site of the worst atrocity of the Bosnian
war. There were even brief conversations between once-bitter
enemies. One Serbian woman helped Muslim women cut back weeds at an
overgrown Muslim graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Nuhanovic, 30, a U.N. translator whose parents and brother
disappeared during the killings, found a Serbian policeman who
fondly recalled once working for his father. ``This big smile
spread across his face when he heard my father's name,'' Nuhanovic
recalled. ``But when I told him my father was missing, his face
went blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half years after American troops arrived in Bosnia,
there is scant evidence that the peace accords are being carried
out in Srebrenica.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials hailed the mourners' visit as an example
of how aggressive Western policies over the past year are producing
results _ even in a town with the bitterest ethnic hatreds.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, though, say the military force required to allow the
Bosnian Muslims to visit reflects the painstakingly slow progress
of the American mission. One Western diplomat predicted that the
tensions would require a foreign military presence for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, there was a minor grave-site visit,'' the diplomat said.
``But it's going to take decades for there to be reconciliation in
that area. There's been too much bloodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   The war wrecked the town. Srebrenica's two mosques were
dynamited. Muslim graveyards are the only trace of the ethnic group
that had made up 70 percent of the residents.
</P>
<P>
   Its water system, when it works, spews water too dirty to drink.
Its shrapnel-pocked schools lack classroom supplies and heating
oil. The mines south of the town lie idle, the factories to the
north are gutted.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in an empty cafe on Srebrenica's deserted main street
one day last month, Radomir, a 39-year-old Bosnian Serb, bitterly
criticized the Bosnian Serbs' wartime leader, Radovan Karadzic, and
other nationalists. Radomir spoke on condition that only his first
name be used because he fears retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I fought for four years?'' he asked. ``To be a
beggar?''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Serbs, Radomir moved to Srebrenica after he lost
his home elsewhere in Bosnia. He said he has no future in
Srebrenica and hopes to return to the suburb of Sarajevo where he
lived before the war.
</P>
<P>
   His anger reflects the success of American and European efforts
to use economic pressure to influence Bosnian Serb public opinion.
Areas controlled by Bosnian Serb moderates are receiving economic
aid, while the economy in areas controlled by Serb hard-liners,
including Srebrenica, is withering.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Mark Littel, the commander of U.S. forces around
Srebrenica, said he had seen a shift in Serbian attitudes that
mirrors Radomir's experience _ a dramatic shift away from hard-line
attitudes. ``Nine months ago we came to Srebrenica and asked Serbs
if they wanted to go home,'' Littel said. ``They said, `Never.'
Now, in increasing numbers, they're saying yes.''
</P>
<P>
   But such sentiments are clearly not held by Srebrenica's Bosnian
Serb nationalist leaders, and many Bosnian Serbs in the town have
no desire to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by Bosnian Muslims to win back control of the town by
democratic means have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Voting by absentee ballot in municipal elections last September,
Bosnian Muslims won most of the seats on the Town Council. But
efforts by the new council to take control of the town have proved
futile. A rock-throwing mob spurred on by the town's leaders turned
back the newly elected Muslim officials and American troops in
January, Littel said. Meetings between the two sides ensued, but
the new council has yet to meet and Srebrenica has no functioning
government.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Szulc, a spokeswoman for the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe, which organized the elections, said that
if the two sides do not agree soon, the organization would appoint
a five-member council led by an American diplomat to run the town.
``We always knew Srebrenica was going to be toughest one, and it
is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little progress in bringing the perpetrators of
the massacres to justice, which survivors say would go a long way
toward reducing the urge for revenge. While the United States and
NATO have taken a more aggressive stance on arresting low-level
war-crimes suspects, Karadzic and his military commander, Gen.
Ratko Mladic, who have been charged with genocide at Srebrenica by
the International War Crimes Tribunal at The Hague, remain free.
Both men are out of power; their whereabouts are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Most galling to survivors is that three years after the town's
fall to the Serbs, only 1,000 bodies of the 7,300 missing have been
found. Only about 15 bodies have been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Hajra Catic, a director of Women of Srebrenica who lives in
Tuzla, in the Muslim-Croat part of Bosnia, said thousands of
corpses litter the hills of eastern Bosnia, exposed to the
elements, looters and wildlife. ``It hurts so much,'' said Ms.
Catic, whose son and husband have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors complain that despite assurances from American
officials that the mass graves around Srebrenica would be monitored
by U.S. spy satellites and planes, the Bosnian Serbs have
systematically tampered with the graves. Officials of the War
Crimes Tribunal seeking evidence of atrocities say Bosnian Serbs
dug up almost all the original mass graves and reburied the bodies
in hidden locations.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of how chaotic the process of finding graves
remains, a NATO bulldozer widening a road 40 miles north of
Srebrenica this spring dug up human bones. Tribunal investigators
said they believe the area, near Hodzici, holds at least five mass
graves of bodies that were moved from their original sites.
</P>
<P>
   With so many Muslims missing, Serbian nationalists are able to
deny executions took place, or contend that Muslims were killed
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In Sarajevo, Tuzla and other Muslim-Croat areas, Srebrenica's
Muslims have become a political force, organizing regular protests
over the last year that have increased pressure on Western and
Bosnian officials for arrests and exhumations. At a commemoration
of the third anniversary of the fall of the town, women from
Srebrenica covered a field in Staric Ravni, near the front line,
with pieces of cloth, each denoting one of the presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the peace accords ever take effect in Srebrenica may
depend on how average Bosnians respond to awkward reunions of
neighbors who became enemies.
</P>
<P>
   One person who would seem to be prone to revenge is Mevludin
Oric, 29, a Muslim who survived a mass execution three years ago by
hiding under his cousin's corpse. His father, his cousin and half
the men from his village are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking beer with friends in a suburb of Sarajevo in May, Oric
said, he was stunned to see Bosnian Serb women walking toward him.
The women were making a graveyard visit of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Oric confronted them. ``How dare you come here when I can't
return to Srebrenica?'' he hissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about it,'' replied one of the Serbian
women, visibly shaken. ``I'm an old woman,'' she blurted out. ``If
you want, you can kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   Oric and his friends berated the women, one of whom insisted
that they were not responsible for whatever occurred in Srebrenica.
Their conversation continued, and soon they were trading stories of
joblessness, complaining about leaders on all sides who profited
from the war and expressing gloom about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Oric calmed down.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the encounter days later, Oric and one of the
women said they were fairly optimistic _ assuming war criminals are
arrested and exhumations continue and nationalists are removed from
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that in two years we will live as we used to live
before the war,'' Oric said. ``I don't want revenge on all the
Serbs. They are not all guilty.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
