<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-BUSINESSES-ART-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPLACED COMPANIES WORK FROM HOTELS AND HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By LESLIE EATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While people all over Manhattan have been
inconvenienced by the collapse at the Conde Nast construction site
in Times Square, few have been as sorely tried as its neighbors at
1500 Broadway. Ever since the evacuation of the 37-story
black-glass tower on Tuesday, the 64 tenants _ scores of lawyers,
accountants, salesmen, public relations people, and the staffs of
two magazines _ have struggled to create offices in exile.
</P>
<P>
   They have coped with missing files, vanishing mail, and
overwhelmed voice-mail systems while worrying about the little
things, like exactly what was happening to the fruit and pastries
left in the conference room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fruit flies,'' said Allison Wye, a senior vice president of
the financial division of Edelman Public Relations Worldwide. ``Fat
mice,'' said Carol Ruth, chief executive of the company.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, both women were standing in a small
conference room in the Renaissance Hotel on Seventh Avenue, four
blocks north of their usual offices. The room was buzzing with
about 20 young people talking on cellular phones and peering at
laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   With almost 300 employees at 1500 Broadway, Edelman was the
largest tenant in the building. Now it has people scattered all
over the region. Some groups are working from their bosses' homes.
Some are working in a building borrowed from a client, NCR Corp.,
just off the Lincoln Tunnel in New Jersey (shuttle buses run into
Manhattan every 90 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Almost as elaborate were the logistics at BAR/BRI Bar Review,
that is coaching 7,000 fledgling lawyers to pass the state
licensing test next week. Anxious law graduates are pelting the
company with questions about everything from how to take the exam
with a broken finger to the rule against perpetuities, said Erica
Fine, an associate director of BAR/BRI.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fine and her team of legal experts are answering the
questions, she said, but not from the office. ``We're at my
mother's house on Long Island,'' she said. Students call the bar
review's Boston office, and their queries are faxed to the house in
Plainview, where a dozen lawyers page through reference books and
call the students back.
</P>
<P>
   The tutoring concern was also able to have some of its own
research material and lecture notes retrieved from the office by
the handful of building workers the city allowed to stay in the
tower. The owner of 1500 Broadway, Intertech Development Corp. of
Washington, kept these six people in the property's management
office answering phones and collecting things from offices for
tenants of the building, said Orna Shulman, executive vice
president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   That service probably saved the day for the magazine Essence,
which was closing its October issue Friday so that it could be in
subscribers' hands Sept. 10, said Barbara Britton, the magazine's
vice president for advertising. The magazine, which has a
circulation of 1 million, was able to get the material it needed
out of the office, and it will be printed on time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some of Essence's 100 employees moved into the Manhattan offices
of its printers, Brown Printing, at 46th and Broadway, she said,
while the rest ``are telecommuting, electronically and
psychically.''
</P>
<P>
   The building's owners say it will reopen as soon as the police
open the streets, which could be as early as this weekend, though
it remains unclear whether the offices facing 43rd Street can be
used.
</P>
<P>
   For some tenants, however, the latest shutdown has been the last
straw. In January the building was hit by the boom of a
construction crane from the Conde Nast site. No one was injured,
but the building was slightly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lazarus, who works with her father at a small public
relations company at 1500 Broadway, said the construction, along
with rising rents and congested streets, has prompted her to look
elsewhere for office space. In the meantime, she said, she had come
to the same conclusion as a number of other tenants: ``We've all
decided we're not walking on 43rd Street anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
