<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-TOURISTS-BOS &LR;      07-24 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-TOURISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TOURISTS, SENSE OF SECURITY SHATTERS AMID GUNFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Barbara Majewska was standing by the souvenir shop,
having just finished a tour of the Capitol with her husband and two
kids when she heard the shots. The echo stayed with her, mingling
with the screams of her 4-year-old daughter, Danika.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone scattered, running, shouting, crying, except for
Majewska, who thought it wiser to hide. Maternal instinct kicked
in, overrunning her own terror and inclination to bolt as she
directed her 15-year-old son to lie down flat behind a statue.
Majewska piled Danika between, and she lay on top, forming a human
shield.
</P>
<P>
   Her long, thin arms, she recalls thinking, couldn't be much of a
shield for her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe it,'' Majewska exclaimed, after reuniting
with her husband, Lee, who was swept up and lost in the commotion.
``I never thought this would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Majewska, who lives in Poland, didn't yet know that four people
were hit by those bullets _ the assailant, two fatally wounded
officers, and a tourist like herself. All she knew is that she and
her husband, after searching frantically for one another outside
the Capitol amid a crowd thick with cameras, Popsicles, American
flags and a half-dozen accents from far away places, had found each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many millions of parents, toddlers, tourists, and
foreigners, Majewska and her husband were here to visit the US
Capitol, seat of the largest democracy in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is, even with security guards posted at every entrance and a
swirl of plainclothes officers partrolling the Capitol grounds, one
of the most open and public viewings of government at work
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the Capitol building itself, visitors congregate. They
come as part of their social studies class, to learn the difference
between a bill and an amendment. They come to buy T-shirts, flags
and cups boasting logos of the Capitol dome. They come to curry
favor with their representatives. They come in the hope of rubbing
elbows with important people they see on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands pass every day under the Capitol dome, through
Statuary Hall, where history is embodied in the marbled forms of
suffragettes and military heroes, and into the crypt, where the
shooting happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting in line and this bang went off, and one lady
said, `Oh, it must be construction,' and the other said, `No way,
that is gunfire,' '' said 14-year-old Derek Zalewski, of
Stevenspoint, Wis. ``This guard came running up to us in
plainclothes with a badge and a gun out and put us up against the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   What Zalewski witnessed next _ a woman running out of the
capitol in blood-soaked clothes as panicked people poured down the
capitol steps _ was made that much more shocking by the way it
confliced with the ``pretty'' mental picture he had formed of the
Capitol. Visitors repeatedly pointed out that they considered the
Capitol extremely safe and well-policed when they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to map out a route for my high school students,''
said Jillian Simon, a 23-year-old English teacher from Wilmington,
N.C. ``It's ironic. I went through the detectors and thought, only
minutes before I heard the shots, how safe it is here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm a little shaken,'' she cried, her hands
trembling. ``I just saw my whole life in front of me. There's
something extremely wrong in this country. The security doesn't
work. The gun laws don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people milled about after the shooting on the shaded
lawn in front of the Capitol, which had been transformed into a
parking lot filled with police cars, ambulances and a large fleet
of black sedans. Among the cars roamed Secret Service agents,
public safety officers and plainclothes police.
</P>
<P>
   Some saw the scene as less extraordinary than as a sad reminder
of the pervasiveness of violence in our culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is typical,'' said Donna Peterson, a 26-year-old
stationed with her husband at Fort Campbell, Ky. ``It's nothing
abnormal. If you have kids shooting their teachers, this is bound
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an observation voiced by more than one visitor and
contrasted with a prayer offered by a group of clergy, who voiced
hope that what had passed would not be repeated again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray that there could be healing words that go forth, that
sanity be restored, that violence be negated,'' intoned the Rev.
Jim Pitt from Pittsburg, who knelt in prayer with other clergymen
under the shade of an oak tree near the Capitol after the shooting.
``We unite in great sorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
