<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cooperstown, here they come!
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Skip Caray has brought some extra scorecards. The
substitutes are coming in a day early for orientation. The cars and
planes are all arranged. The Braves radio crew is ready for a day
of hooky.
</P>
<P>
   The car leaves the William Penn Hotel 9 a.m. Sunday to take Skip
Caray, Pete Van Wieren, Joe Simpson and WSB engineer Dave Baker to
a TBS corporate jet, where they will fly to Utica, N.Y., and then
on to Cooperstown, where as invited guests, they will witness
broadcast partner Don Sutton's induction into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Pete if we all had a rope with knots in it that we all
had to hold on to,'' said Simpson. ``He said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In their absense, WSB has brought in University of Georgia radio
voice Larry Munson and Hawks play-by-play man Steve Holman to
handle Sunday's Braves-Pirates game. Munson was an original member
of the Braves radio crew after the club moved from Milwaukee.
Holman's baseball experience stems primarily from watching the
Boston Red Sox in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   The TV schedule was arranged that Fox Sports South (with Bob
Rathbun and Ernie Johnson) will handle Sunday, freeing up the
entire crew. They will return by company jet and catch up with the
club in Cincinnati Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I sometimes get in trouble when I say things about
management,'' Caray said, ``but they have been great about this.
They didn't have to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez still absent
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez did not rejoin the club Friday as anticipated,
remaining in Atlanta another day while his wife, Marisol, is
treated for a gall bladder condition. The reserve catcher called
the club earlier in the day to inform manager Bobby Cox he was
waiting for his mother to arrive from Venezuela to help take care
of the couple's two children.
</P>
<P>
   While Perez is expected back for tonight's game, second baseman
Tony Graffanino has found a new hobby. He caught a Greg Maddux
bullpen session Thursday in his first work ever as a catcher and
found himself better for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had on the mask and shinnies and everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off
</P>
<P>
   Facing Pittsburgh left-hander Chris Peters, Cox used Gerald
Williams as his lead-off man for the fourth time this season. While
he has been modestly successful when used in the role _ 2-for-12,
two walks, two runs, two stolen bases _ Williams has seen enough in
his nearly four months as a Brave to know leading off in Atlanta
can be a more significant job than in some other ports-of-call.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you understand what the identity of the team is, it's
important to get on and get into position to score,'' said
Williams, who came into the game hitting .300 (6-for-20) since the
All-Star break. ``With the pitching staff we have, it's very
important that we score first. That gives the guys a chance to get
into the rhythm and flow of the game easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves came into the game at 51-11 when they score first.
</P>
<P>
   Medical update
</P>
<P>
   Cox's bench remains thin due to injury. Shortstop Walt Weiss
(strained left quadricep) reports he is much better but has not
attempted to run in five days and may not play this entire road
trip. Michael Tucker (jammed left ankle) was available for
pinch-hitting again Friday but has been able to stay off his foot
while the Braves have faced the left-handed Peters. If the Pirates
had started a righty Friday night? ``I started and gone deep
twice,'' said Tucker, who was lying.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
