<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz gets 3-hitter as Braves roll
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The question may no longer be: When will John
Smoltz get well?
</P>
<P>
   At least Friday night, it became: When was John Smoltz better?
</P>
<P>
   With Andres Galarraga's 33rd homer serving to sway the night,
the Braves dropped Pittsburgh 3-0 in the first game of a weekend
series at Three Rivers Stadium, Atlanta winning its first three of
the current nine-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   But another strong start by Smoltz (9-2) in what is becoming a
midseason crescendo left the Pirates helpless. Since returning from
the DL June 20, Smoltz is now 5-2 and has won four consecutive
starts since the All-Star break. In 1997, Smoltz did not win his
ninth game until his 23rd start. He did so Friday in his 15th
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   It was Smoltz's first complete game and shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves tonight send out Denny Neagle (10-8) against Pirates
right-hander Francisco Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga gave Atlanta a 3-0 lead in the fifth with his homer,
coming with Chipper Jones on base. The homer, which carried into a
table-and-chairs area in the Bullpen Lounge above the left-field
wall, was Galarraga's third in his last 11 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   It also left him the leader among active players for most homers
hit in Three Rivers. With three this season, Galarraga has hit 21
career homers in Pittsburgh, just four fewer than Hall of Famer
Mike Schmidt, whose 25 is the most all-time by opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz received outstanding defensive help. Gerald Williams
crashed the wall in right field to take away a double from Kevin
Young in the fourth inning. Play was delayed for stadium workers to
replace a section of padding Williams knocked loose in the
collision.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga later saved a run in the fifth when, with Al Martin on
second, Lou Collier sent a ball into the hole to Galarraga's right.
The first baseman made a rolling stop and flipped to Smoltz
covering the base to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves put men on base in each of the first four innings but
could only cash in during the first, when Tony Graffanino sent an
opposite-field double into the right-field corner. Chipper Jones
singled him to third and Galarraga brought him in on a fielder's
choice for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four innings, Pirates starter Chris Peters allowed
five hits while his infield made two errors behind him and still
the Braves could score just once, stranding five men, three of them
in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
