<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2239 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SCENE-1STLD-W     07-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SCENE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNFIRE SEEMED TO COME OUT OF NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: SUBS for add-at-end. Text below optional trim is new;
refinements in top half. No pickup.)  (See CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-OFFICERS, CAPITOL-TOURIST,
CAPITOL-GUNMAN, CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He wore khaki pants and a green fedora with a
feather, witnesses said Friday, as any tourist might. But he was
armed with a six-shot Smith &AMP; Wesson revolver, and almost as soon
as he traded the July heat for the cool of the Capitol, the
authorities said, he opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses and the authorities described a sudden and shocking
burst of shots after Officer Jacob Chestnut asked Russell Eugene
Weston Jr. to pass through a metal detector, like every other
visitor.
</P>
<P>
   As tourists screamed and stampeded, Weston left Chestnut
mortally wounded on the floor, the authorities said. His path into
the Capitol was blocked by other officers, they said, so he turned
left toward a door marked private that opens onto the ``rabbit
warren,'' as insiders call the maze of offices belonging to Rep.
Tom DeLay, the majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the door, Special Agent John Gibson of the Capitol police
force was shouting at staff members to hit the floor. Witnesses and
the authorities offered conflicting versions of what came next. The
authorities said Gibson and Weston traded shots that cut each other
down, but not before Weston reached the first office of DeLay's
extensive suite.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later some 10 officers surrounded Weston, their guns
trained at his head, said two of DeLay's aides. The office carpet
was soaked in blood.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in the echoing marble hallways of the Capitol's first
floor, the visitors' blend of boredom, curiosity and awe had turned
to bedlam as shell casings scattered across the stone floor and
officers shouted at them to get out. In the fusillade, one
bystander, Angela Dickerson, had been wounded in the face and
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Some people took refuge behind pillars; others simply crouched
where they stood.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Beamish, a 69-year-old tourist from England, said that he
bent over a wounded police officer _ it must have been Chestnut _
feeling for a pulse as the officer muttered words he could not make
out. ``I yelled, get a stretcher,'' said Beamish, whose khaki pants
were stained with blood. ``There was blood coming from his head,
and one eye looked as if it was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone had had the presence of mind to summon Sen. Bill Frist
of Tennessee off the floor of the Senate. The senator, a heart
surgeon, checked the pulse of one of the wounded, then helped
resuscitate Weston and rode with him to the hospital.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was a typical lazy July afternoon, and Capitol Hill like the
rest of Washington was easing into the weekend. The last vote had
been taken in the House chamber, and though Congress was still in
session many representatives had already streamed down the broad,
steep steps into the sunshine to their waiting cars.
</P>
<P>
   In DeLay's office, some 50 members had gathered to celebrate the
passage of health care legislation with champagne brought by Rep.
Mark Foley of Florida. Across the hallway, Rep. John Boehner,
another member of the House leadership, was in his hideaway office
performing a ritual that marks the approaching weekend in official
Washington the way margaritas might in the rest of the country:
They were discussing what was likely to be debated on the Sunday
television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at about 3:40 p.m., the gunfire and the screaming started.
Boehner's staff called the Capitol Police immediately and were told
to lock their door and stay put. In DeLay's suite, some dove under
their desks or ran to the backs of their offices. Staff members
gathered with the congressmen and said a prayer. Many of the aides
would later credit Gibson with saving their lives. Tearful
congressmen would pay the same tribute to both slain officers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in the main entrance hallway, Tyvon Crawford, 20, was
working at the small gift shop _ a kiosk, really _ run by the
Capitol Historical Society. ``Someone was making a purchase, and I
heard shots to my right,'' he said. With a co-worker, his manager,
and a passing tourist, he crowded into the booth for shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Brown, another worker in the souvenir shop, said that the
first thing he thought to do was duck. ``There was a guy running,
just shooting at anybody he could hit,'' he said. ``When I looked
up, I saw the officer with a hole in his chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tourists and staff heard just three or four shots; others
heard 20 reverberating through the halls. Officers, their weapons
drawn, pushed tourists to the ground to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Ottotta, a radio technician from Rockford, Ill., was
touring the Capitol with his wife, three sons, and mother-in-law
when he heard a sound that he thought was an exhibit crashing to
the floor. He lost track of all his family members in the chaos,
glimpsing one son as he darted off, leaping down stairs into the
crowd. He found all of them safe later.
</P>
<P>
   Judson Threlkeld with his wife, Rachel, was touring the crypt, a
vaulted space on the first floor beneath the House chamber. Four
years ago, he was at the southwest gate of the White House when he
heard what sounded like fireworks; he later learned that a man had
opened fire on the building. This time, upon hearing a bang, his
wife dropped to the floor, and he lay on top of her. ``There was a
pause, and we were afraid he was going to come into the open space
and start firing,'' Threlkeld said. They got up and dashed to hide
behind a pillar. Then, when the Capitol Police ordered them out,
they ran for an exit.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Cleary, the chief legislative aide to Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., was giving a tour of the Capitol to a group of
children including an 11-year-old girl from Belfast, Northern
Ireland, who was visiting the United States as part of a program to
take Irish children away from violence. ``We were trying to isolate
her from this kind of thing, not letting her watch the news,'' Ms.
Cleary said, ``and then this happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
