<HEADLINE>
BOOKSTORE FOR SERIOUS CATHOLIC READERS CONFRONTS ITS WEAKNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.) (jw) 
 By PETER STEINFELS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A month ago, when the financial storm clouds hanging
over the Paraclete Book Center in Manhattan grew particularly
menacing, Mary Butler called a meeting. Although Ms. Butler owns
the bookstore, on 74th Street just east of Lexington Avenue, she
believes that it belongs to a larger, amorphous community of
people, some in New York, some spread around the world.
</P>
<P>
   They are the people who have been turning to the Paraclete for
years as a source of serious books on Christian, especially Roman
Catholic, theology and history. And they ought to have a voice, Ms.
Butler thought, in whether the bookstore lived or died.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bit surprising that in a city that has a population
roughly 40 percent Catholic and that is a center of intellectual
life, the Paraclete should stand out so sharply. In the five
boroughs, there are dozens of religious bookstores, and, New York
being New York, they include ones specializing in Judaism, Islam,
Zen and Tibetan Buddhism, Hinduism, Yoga, New Age, astrology and
diverse species of witchcraft. They include quite serviceable
Christian bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   But where else but the Paraclete would there be the pile of
books that stood among the outgoing orders last Tuesday? A volume
about the German social theorist Max Horkheimer rested on a book by
Hans Urs von Balthasar, a giant of 20th-century Catholic theology,
on top of a volume by Plotinus, the third-century Neoplatonist, on
top of a work by Edith Stein, the philosopher, Catholic convert
from Judaism, Nazi victim and candidate for sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   Religion and spirituality constitute a growing sector of the
book market. But that does not necessarily help a store that gains
customers by stocking Thomas Aquinas rather than ``Chicken Soup for
the Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Flourishing Christian bookstores are likely to feature
inspirational CDs, greeting cards, church supplies _ and what Bob
Anderson, president of the evangelical Christian Booksellers
Association, described as state-of-the-art ``ambience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anchor Room, for example, is an evangelical bookstore in
Fort Wayne, Ind. Books occupy only a fraction of its 20,000 square
feet, with other sections devoted to music, video rentals, choir
robes and other apparel, Sunday school teaching aids, wedding
items, children's books and toys, and the Higher Grounds Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the 750-square-foot Paraclete has bad fluorescent
lighting, worn red tile, a patchwork of mismatched shelves and a
system of categories relying heavily on Ms. Butler's impressive
knowledge of virtually every book in the store. It also has a
selection of books that the Anchor Room would not touch, and the
opportunity for hands-on browsing that Internet-based booksellers
still cannot provide. At least that is how one recent visitor
explained why he was carrying home $129 worth of purchases in
religious history.
</P>
<P>
   The Paraclete opened almost a half-century ago. Elizabeth
Sullivan, its founding owner, made the Paraclete an outpost of the
new Catholic thinking that culminated in the Second Vatican
Council. In the 1960s, during and after the council, the business
``grew and grew and grew and grew,'' Ms. Butler recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The serious ups and downs started in 1984,'' said Ms. Butler,
who began working at the store in 1961. She became the owner after
Ms. Sullivan died in 1978. She borrowed money and repaid the loans
as the cash flow fluctuated. But this spring the store found itself
in arrears with publishers and with the landlord.
</P>
<P>
   Independent religious bookstores face the same challenges as all
independent booksellers, said Lynn Garrett, the religion editor for
Publishers Weekly. ``There's just a proliferation of competition,
from chains, from the Web, from other non-bookstore outlets, like
Wal-Mart or Kmart,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the best-run stores that do everything right'' have
difficulties, Ms. Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Butler does not pretend that the Paraclete has been doing
everything right. It has not advertised sufficiently. It has a Web
site but has not developed extensive links from other religious
sites. And ``maybe we have not addressed adequately the people in
the parishes for whom our stock of books might be forbidding,'' Ms.
Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   At last month's meeting with old friends of the Paraclete, a
plan was drafted to confront the store's weaknesses. Now the
question is whether there is enough time. Ms. Butler, who is
nearing 59, would love to put in a couple more years and turn the
Paraclete over in good financial shape to younger owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the difficulties, there is a real sense that we are
doing something that needs to be done and that no one else is
doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently others think so as well. July sales have been strong,
and recently, Ms. Butler received a gift of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel optimistic,'' she said, ``possibly more than I
should.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
