<HEADLINE>
GREEKS BEAR GIFTS FOR A U.N. SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ How much is a two-year seat on the Security
Council worth?
</P>
<P>
   For the Greeks, a couple of Aegean cruises is not too high a
price.
</P>
<P>
   Greece, competing against the Netherlands and Canada for a
``Western Europe and other'' seat, has been entertaining New
York-based diplomats from several dozen countries _ along with
their families _ with trips to Greece and a sea cruise. According
to the diplomatic grapevine, more than 200 people have signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats have been told that the ``get to know Greece'' tour is
a private venture connected to a coming commemoration of the
Olympic Games, not a campaign pitch. Greek diplomats were not
available to discuss the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say countries curry favor with the 185 members of the
United Nations every year before rotating seats are filled.
Dinners, entertainment and gifts are not unusual, and go largely
unremarked. But an audible buzz surrounds the Greek offering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
