<HEADLINE>
NAVY BOOTS MALE, FEMALE SAILORS FOR GROUP SEXUAL INCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Three female and seven male sailors from the aircraft
carrier USS Abraham Lincoln are being kicked out of the Navy after
a group sexual incident in a Hong Kong hotel room two weeks ago,
Navy officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   An eleventh sailor is facing more serious charges that could
result in a military court-martial for sexual assault, said Navy
Lt. Dave Oates, a spokesman for the Pacific Fleet Naval Air Forces
headquarters in San Diego. The assault investigation is continuing
and the sailor has not been formally charged, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident comes as Secretary of Defense William Cohen and his
aides are grappling with how to deal with sexual activity in the
military. Cohen has proposed decriminalizing adultery by revising
the military legal code. That change came in response to the highly
publicized Air Force case of Lt. Kelly Flynn, who faced a
court-martial for adultery and accusations of disobeying orders.
The proposal to lessen the penalties for adultery has sparked some
resistance in the military leadership, particularly the Marine
Corps, out of fears that it may inadvertently weaken military
discipline and order.
</P>
<P>
   The incident on the night of July 6 occurred as the aircraft
carrier was on a six-day port visit to Hong Kong. The ship, which
left Everett, Wash., on June 11 for a six-month deployment to the
western Pacific and Middle East, entered the Persian Gulf on
Thursday, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   All 11 remain on board the carrier for now.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 sailors were involved in what another Navy official
described as an off-duty party in the Hong Kong hotel that
degenerated into ``multiple sex acts.'' There were three female and
eight male crew from the carrier in the room. No civilians were
involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, one of the female sailors reported to the
Lincoln's security office that she had been sexually assaulted. The
carrier's commander, Capt. J.J. Quinn, ordered an immediate
investigation by the Naval Criminal Investigative Service, Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the three female and 10 of the 11 male sailors were
brought to a ``Captain's Mast'' hearing for nonjudicial punishment
where they were found guilty on charges of adultery, sodomy and
fraternization, Oates said. The 11th sailor is still being
investigated on a more serious charge of alleged sexual assault
which could result in a military court-martial, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The female sailor who disclosed the incident by accusing the
shipmate of sexual assault is one of the three females being kicked
out of the Navy ``based on illicit sexual acts prior to the alleged
sexual assault'' the same night, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was determined the sailor who reported the sexual assault
had also engaged in inappropriate behavior prior to the alleged
assault,'' said Lincoln public affairs officer Lt. Cmdr. Scott
Harris, in an e-mail message to the Puget Sound Navy News, which
published an account of the incident Friday.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 sailors at the Captain's Mast were reduced in rank one
grade, restricted to the ship for 60 days, and fined 50 percent of
their salary for two months, Oates said. In addition, all 10
sailors are being processed for administrative separation from the
service which, if approved on appeal, could result in them being
discharged with general or other-than-honorable discharges.
</P>
<P>
   All of the sailors involved are described as junior enlisted
personnel with the ranks of seaman or petty officer 3rd class.
</P>
<P>
   The names and ranks of the sailors have been withheld under
terms of the Uniformed Code of Military Justice and federal Privacy
Act which protect the identities of military personnel in
administrative disciplinary hearings. The name of the 11th sailor,
who has not yet been formally charged, likewise is being withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Navy believes it has recovered from the 1991
Tailhook Association scandal where several dozen females were
groped and harassed during the naval aviation convention in Las
Vegas, the latest incident put Navy officials on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   (The Tailhook scandal rocked the Navy and resulted in the
disciplining of 40 officers, including three admirals. The Navy and
Marine Corps pursued 140 harassment cases, but none led to a
court-martial.)
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials yesterday described the Hong Kong incident as an
isolated occurrence in the service, which has had women serving on
combat warships since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other 4,607 sailors who weren't involved in this incident
represented our country with pride and dignity during our port
visit in Hong Kong,'' said Quinn, the Lincoln's commander. ``They
are an awesome group of young men and women dedicated to serving
their country and I am proud to be their commanding officer.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Navy's personnel command in Washington,
D.C., declined to enumerate any other similar incidents involving
male and female sailors. ``We don't have those (records),'' said
Cmdr. Terry McCreary. ``Nobody collects NJPs (nonjudicial
punishment records). It's a local matter, kept administrative at a
local level.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Navy officer, who discussed the incident on grounds his
name not be used, said, ``It's a shame that the actions of 10
sailors are highlighted over the more than 4,500 sailors who are
performing an outstanding and professional job while on
deployment.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 400 female officers and enlisted personnel
assigned to the Lincoln, about 9 percent of the total roster of
4,600 in the ship's crew and embarked carrier air wing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
