<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-DRIFTER-NYT &LR;      07-24 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-DRIFTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LIFE WITH A SECOND ACT AND A TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never mind that Jack Ryan was dead. Everyone agreed
he looked sharp. ``This is the best dressed Jack's been in a long
time,'' said Keith Haskins, who helps run a center for the elderly
on Delancey Street where John D. Ryan used to pass his days. ``He
wouldn't spend a penny on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   That got a small, knowing laugh from some of the 40 other
mourners who were at the Guidetti Funeral Home, on Spring Street,
the other morning. They knew Ryan better in an old shirt and even
older pants, forever wearing a red baseball cap that now hung near
his coffin. But he looked grand, they said, in the unfamiliar black
suit and tie, clasping a rosary to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   There is no particular reason why you should have heard of Jack
Ryan, who was 83 when he breathed his last on July 11. ``There
isn't really anything outstanding about me,'' he once told Cal
Hedigan, who was in charge of the house where he lived on East
Fourth Street, a residence for poor elderly people run by a
nonprofit group called the Bowery Residents' Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never committed any terrible crime,'' he told her. ``Never
did anything great. I just sort of survived, more or less.''
</P>
<P>
   Even to those who thought they knew him, much of Ryan's past was
lost in a haze. He was born in Manhattan and grew up here. He
worked here and there. He had a wife, but no children. He drank too
much after his wife died in 1961. And he found himself on the
Bowery. These days, people would say he was homeless. The word back
then was more direct, if less kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you might have thought of him as a traditional _ what
should I say? _ bum,'' said Bill Kavanagh, a friend and a
down-and-outer himself once, not from the drink but from a ruinous
inability to stay away from slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few of Ryan's mourners were white-haired men who
also had landed on the Bowery when it was a synonym for skid row.
Now the homeless are everywhere, and the Bowery is on the
gentrifiers' map.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there is much point in getting sloppy-sentimental about
the old days of hard-drinking men who filled countless flophouses.
Still, there was a wispy, end-of-an-era feel to this funeral as the
old-timers shuffled into Guidetti's, down the block from benches
where young people were sitting outside Balthazar and having
breakfasts of coffee and brioches.
</P>
<P>
   As they waited for the service to begin, some of the mourners
talked quietly. ``I saw Jack one day, and we were talking about
drinking,'' one elderly man said to a friend. ``I asked him, `When
was the last time you had a good time drinking?' And then I thought
to myself, `Jeez, when was the last time I had a good time
drinking?'''
</P>
<P>
   But this is not really about the drinking life. It is about how
Jack Ryan touched his last drop of booze in 1974, about how he read
a lot and studied French. He picked up money changing beds at a
hotel on the Lower East Side, but he never seemed to spend any of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1985, he got interested in art; he was lured, someone
recalled, by an art therapist with a soft voice and a pretty face.
In time, this interest blossomed into a passion, and he would paint
away most days at the center on Delancey. He worked in pastels and
favored seascapes, some of which Susan Pustilnik, an artist friend,
placed next to his coffin.
</P>
<P>
   He was not a man of many words. ``He wouldn't let you get too
close,'' Haskins said. All the same, he connected with people in
interesting ways. One man stood up at the funeral to say that Ryan
had taught him about painting. Bill Kavanagh said that painting
alongside Ryan at the center ``gave me back my self-respect.'' Yet
another man said of Ryan, ``I managed to stay sober on the Bowery
for many years, and he helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he died, officials at the Bowery Residents' Committee
discovered to their amazement that he was not broke. He had managed
to save about $70,000, presumably money earned at the hotel, and he
left word that it should all go to the committee. ``He just socked
everything away,'' said Joan Malin, the group's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   You may read any lesson you want in this tale, or none at all.
But the amazing ability of people to reinvent themselves, and
surprise you, is not a bad thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows that if you have a little faith in people ...''
Kavanagh said, and his voice trailed off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
