<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-O725     07-24 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-O7252NDLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: in 9th graf, corrects to read 'Weston' sted of 'Chestnut'
 &HT;    GUNMAN SHOOTS, KILLS TWO POLICEMEN, WOUNDS TOURIST IN CAPITOL
 &HT;    With SHOOTING-TOURISTS-0725; SHOOTING-SCENE-0725;
SHOOTING-SECURITY-0725; SHOOTING-HISTORY-0725.
 &HT;    By BOB DART, EUNICE MOSCOSO and JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lone gunman shot his way into the Capitol Friday,
killing two policemen and scattering terrified tourists who hid
behind statues and fled down historic corridors in the world's
best-known symbol of Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-year-old female bystander was seriously injured with
gunshot wounds in the face and shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Identified by Washington police as Russell E. Weston, 42, a
native of Valmeyer, Ill., the gunman was recovering at a Washington
hospital from gunshot wounds in his chest and legs.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said he was known to the U.S. Secret
Service because of reported threats to President Clinton two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The slain policemen were Jacob Chestnut, a uniformed member of
the Capitol police force assigned to the door through which Weston
allegedly entered, and John Gibson, a security specialist assigned
to House Majority Whip Tom Delay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The woman bystander was identified by officials at George
Washington University Medical Center as Angela Dickerson,
apparently a tourist.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress who had been briefed on the incident by
police said Weston, who the Associated Press said now lives in
Missoula, Mont., had parked his car several blocks from the
Capitol, walked to a front entrance and walked around a metal
detector.
</P>
<P>
   When Officer Chestnut attempted to stop him, Weston turned and
shot him, said Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman then went a few feet further into the Capitol where
he was confronted by Gibson. Seconds later, members of DeLay's
staff said they could hear the exchange of shots between Gibson and
Weston.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William H. Frist, R-Tenn., a heart surgeon, rushed to the
Capitol after seeing a television report on the shootings and began
giving victims first aid.
</P>
<P>
   He then accompanied the ambulance that transported Weston to a
Washington, D.C. General Hospital, helping paramedics resuscitate
the gunman, who had been shot three times.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokeswoman later said Weston was in recovery
following surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before the shooting, Frist had presided over the Senate
and recessed it for the week.
</P>
<P>
   The House had finished its business for the day and was in a
period traditionally reserved for members to make one-minute
speeches on topics of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the staff of Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, said the
explosion of gunfire outside Boehner's Capitol hideaway office
echoed through the marble corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Holt, a Boehner staffer, described hearing, ``Bang! Bang!
Bang! Scream!''
</P>
<P>
   Members of DeLay's staff said after the first gunfire, Gibson
pushed them into the office and closed the door before turning to
confront the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists who had been making their way through the statue- and
portrait-lined corridor, screamed and scrambled for exits.
</P>
<P>
   One man said he crouched behind a pillar and called to members
of his family, trying to determine if they were all right.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders deplored the tragedy in the Capitol,
traditionally known as ``the People's House'' and Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., canceled a weekend trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress and representatives of the Capitol police
force emphasized that the Capitol security system was sound and
noted that the gunman was unable to advance more than a few feet
beyond the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the People's House and I deplore the action of the
person who brought violence within these sacred halls,'' Gingrich
said in a statement. He noted that without the two officers'
actions many more persons in the Capitol could have been shot.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton expressed sadness at the incident and called
Gingrich from Camp David, where he had gone for the weekend, to
express condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the word came down that two of their comrades had
died, two uniformed policemen walked out on the roof of the Capitol
and lowered the flapping American flag to half mast.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., said he was talking to a Capitol
policeman across Independence Avenue from the Capitol when he heard
the call for help on the officer's radio and the report that two
guards were down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very sad. I know most of these officers. We see them
every day that we're in session,'' said Lewis. Asked what questions
were running through his mind, Lewis said, ``How did this happen,
and why? Was the person acting alone? How did this happen to a
building as secure as the United States Capitol?''
</P>
<P>
   There will have to be a review about what happened, Lewis said,
but he added that the Capitol can't be sealed off from the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best symbol of democracy in the world,'' he said.
``You can't lock it down. It has to be accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the Capitol is ``very, very secure. It's probably one
of the most secure buildings not only in the country but in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting occurred, the Davis family from Hamilton,
Texas, were inside the Capitol being given a tour by a staffer of
Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tense,'' said Brad Davis, describing how his
wife, Karen, 11-year-old daughter, Laura, and 13-year-old son,
Barry, were ``rounded up'' and shuffled from room to room for about
an hour as the investigation was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for all of us, not only here in Washington but
across the country,'' said Assistant District Police Chief Charles
Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Beamish, a native of England, stood on the Senate side of
the Capitol's front steps, his gray slacks spattered with blood and
described one of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just big bangs _ just like fireworks, really,'' Beamish
said, describing the fatal shots. ``Loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Beamish did not know which of the two slain officers he saw
being shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the officer fall to the ground. He was shot in the head.
I wanted to help him but many officers went to him. His lips moved
and he was trying to say something,'' Beamish said, his voice
softening.
</P>
<P>
   Jillian Simon, 23, of Wilmington, N.C., said she hid by a window
and was afraid to move after she heard the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Still trembling an hour after the incident, she said that she
had been in the immediate area of the shooting ``10 seconds''
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I just had some angels around me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As emergency room personnel at George Washington University
Medical Center attempted to save the life of Officer Gibson, police
squad cars periodically arrived, bringing family members who were
escorted into the hospital by the officers.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox News Service correspondents Christi Harlan, Scott
Montgomery, Samar Abulhassan and Danielle Shook also contributed to
this report.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
