<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-SCENE-0725-     07-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-SCENE-0725-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALE FROM SHOOTING SCENE: A BRAVE OFFICER GAVE HIS LIFE TO SAVE
OTHERS
 &HT;    With CAPITOL-SHOOTINGS-0725-2NDLD.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first burst of noise was loud, ``as if you had
a platter of silverware that was 500 pounds, and it all spilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Then somebody opened the door, and the noise was inside _ inside
an office suite in a building where things like this don't happen,
where bullets don't smash into walls above your head and where you
don't wonder if you're going to die while you hide under your desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dove under my desk during the second round of shots, and I
was there like five seconds, and I decided if this guy is coming
through picking people off, I'm going to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Rudy, policy advisor to House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of
Texas, jumped up in time to see his boss headed toward the noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled at him to get back,'' Rudy said. ``At that point, you
don't know if there was a hit on him or if there was another person
or what.''
</P>
<P>
   There was just one person: a man who brought a gun into the U.S.
Capitol on a summery Friday afternoon and shot the first Capitol
Police officer who challenged him. Steps away, inside the secret
door to DeLay's office suite, officer John Gibson was on duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the guy opened the door, or our officer opened the
door,'' Rudy said. Gunfire erupted as staffers dove for cover. The
last exchange of bullets downed the gunman and cost Gibson his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved our lives,'' Rudy said of the officer. ``He saved our
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty people work in DeLay's office on the first floor of the
Capitol, handling the business of the No. 3 Republican in the House
and rounding up the votes to pass legislation. Friday's big vote _
on health-care reform _ had been a squeaker, passing by a mere six
votes.
</P>
<P>
   The last vote was cast at 3:13 p.m. Friday, Washington time,
early enough for most House members to hustle past the tourists
crowding the Capitol hallways and beat it to the airport for a
quick weekend visit to their home districts.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:40 p.m., 27 minutes after the House vote, at a door mere
feet from DeLay's office, a man pushed past the blaring metal
detector and shot Officer Jacob Chestnut, who later died of his
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy, a former press officer for DeLay, was on the phone with a
reporter when the first shots rang out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was gunfire, but you don't know,'' he said. ``I
was on the phone, and I said, 'Oh, my God, gunfire,' then, 'holy
----, it's in here.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was when Officer Gibson, a member of DeLay's personal
security detail, met the man with the gun.
</P>
<P>
   From his carpeted office on the opposite side of the suite,
DeLay ran toward the noise, pausing to push two or three staffers
to safety in his own office. Rudy shouted him back, and he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally, twenty seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how long Rudy counted from the first noise inside the
office until Officer Gibson was mortally wounded, and the gunman
was down on the carpet next to the office systems manager. Other
officers rushed to Gibson's aid, while one straddled the
unconscious gunman, pointing a sidearm at his head and screaming at
him to drop his gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, if it wasn't for Officer Gibson, numerous
members of the staff would have been killed,'' Rudy said. ``The guy
wouldn't have stopped until he ran out of bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson died after a helicopter carried him to a Washington
trauma center.
</P>
<P>
   To DeLay's staff, he was still alive early Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has been with us since the beginning,'' Rudy said, unable
to shake the present tense. ``He's part of the family . . . . He
comes up asking for the Boston papers, because he's a big U. Mass.
fan and a Red Sox fan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox played in Boston last night. At least they got to be
at home.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
