<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2272 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-SPARKSADV-LADN     07-24 0229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKSADV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS TRAVEL TO DETROIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Sparks begin a three-game road trip today at 11
when they play the Detroit Shock for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' 6-foot-5 center Lisa Leslie, who did not play in the
Sparks' 70-68 victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Thursday, remains
listed as day-to-day. She injured her right wrist, ankle and groin
in a 92-77 loss to the New York Liberty on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Van Emrbricqs, who replaced Leslie, clinched the victory
over the Mercury with two free throws with 1:06 remaining. Tamecka
Dixon, the Sparks' second-leading scorer (15.9) behind Leslie
(19.1), scored a season-high 23 points and Penny Toler added 21,
one below her career-high. The Sparks are 6-11.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, coached by Nancy Lieberman-Cline who played for Phoenix
last season, is 10-9 after defeating the Washington Mystics, 76-61,
Wednesday. Carla Porter had a season-high 19 points. The Mystics
are led by Korie Hlede (14.3 points, 5.2 rebounds), Sandy Brondello
(13.2, 4.0), and former Long Beach State All-American Cindy Brown
(11.5, 9.6).
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks continue their road trip at Cleveland on Monday and
Washington on Wednesday before returning home for a final meeting
against Phoenix on July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
