<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/24/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 24, 1998 -- NY-COLLAPSE-BUSINESSES,
7-24 -- Unable to use their offices at 1500 Broadway because of the
collapse at the Conde Nast construction site in Times Square,
employees from Edelman Public Relations are working in a suite at
the Renaissance Hotel. From left, Rosemary Otero, Carol Ruth, David
Carey and Ty Kaliski. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHERRY HILL, N.J. -- July 24, 1998 --
TVDINNER-TRANSFORM-2, 7-24 -- A Swanson TV dinner from 1953
features ``Quick Frozen'' turkey. After decades of inertia, the
Swanson TV dinner, the archetypal frozen meal, is getting an
overhaul. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHERRY HILL, N.J. -- July 24, 1998 --
TVDINNER-TRANSFORM, 7-24 -- Bob Bernstock, Vlasic's chief
executive, in his office; boxes of Swanson TV dinners, foreground.
Vlasic, which was spun off from Campbell Soup a year ago, is trying
to revitalize a group of food businesses that its old parent
company decided it did not need. Some analysts think the effort
could produce healthy profits. ``The whole goal was to do something
significant and symbolic of how we could operate as a company,''
Bernstock says of the changes. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) DALLAS -- July 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 26 --
PIZZA-MANAGE, 7-24 -- Offering stock options called ``Yum Bucks,''
Michael Rawlings, president of Pizza Hut, aims to reduce turnover
among restaurant managers. ``If we can unleash the power of the
folks working in the restaurants, we're going to be light-years
ahead,'' he says. Americans' consumption of pizza is at a record
high, market researchers say, trailing only soft drinks, burgers
and fries among foods ordered in restaurants. Even chicken can't
keep up. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- July 24, 1998 --
SUB-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP-2, 7-24 -- An injured tourist, Angela
Dickerson, is tended to on the Capitol steps Friday. Two police
officers and the tourist, who was hospitalized for her injuries,
were shot Friday afternoon around 3:40 p.m. when a man opened fire
inside the Capitol. The officers were killed and the suspect
wounded in a furious exchange of gunfire with Capitol police. The
gunman, Russell Weston, 42, a native of Valmeyer, Ill., and a
resident of Missoula, Mont., was then arrested, officials say.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- July 24, 1998 -- CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP-1,
7-24 -- An injured person, possibly a Capitol Hill policeman, is
loaded aboard a Park Police helicopter Friday for transport to a
local hospital. Two police officers and a tourist were shot Friday
afternoon around 3:40 p.m. when a man opened fire inside the
Capitol. The officers were killed and the suspect wounded in a
furious exchange of gunfire with Capitol police. The gunman was
then arrested, officials say. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 26 --
RESTAURANTS-SOFT-OPENINGS, 7-24 -- The Mercer Kitchen won't open to
the public before mid-August, but that hasn't stopped the
heat-seeking crowd from flocking to previews, eager to be among the
first to experience a highly anticipated new destination. They have
been invited to preview the food - or in some cases, simply to
check out the space during a cocktail party for a book or a movie -
weeks and even months before the official opening. (Miles Ladin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- July 24, 1998 -- BKO-BAGLEY-BOS, 7-24 -- Former
Boston College basketball star John Bagley returned to the Boston
College campus in order to finish his degree following his NBA
career. He left in 1982 after his junior year, 12 courses shy of a
sociology degree. ``To me, if I was going to go back to school,
this is where I wanted to go,'' says Bagley, 38, who deliberately
reentered academia at a slow pace, knowing it would take him a
while to get reacquainted with its rhythms. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- July 24, 1998 -- LOBSTER-DEPLETE-BOS, 7-24 --
Fisherman Chuck Houghton repairs lobster traps before leaving the
dock to head out to sea. Lobster, New England's most valuable
seafood, has been a godsend to depressed fishing communities,
providing record catches at a time when overfishing has decimated
other fish populations. Now, biologists warn that the lobster trap
``arms race'' has pushed the lobster population to the brink of
collapse. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- July 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 26 --
ABOUT-CARS-ELECTRIC-2, 7-24 -- The Honda EV Plus remote offers a
battery check, left; filling the Honda at a public charger. The
four-seat hatchback looks like a small minivan and leases for $455
a month. (Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- July 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 26 --
ABOUT-CARS-ELECTRIC-1, 7-24 -- From top, the Honda EV Plus offers a
utilitarian body with the look of a small mini-van (Jill
Connelly/New York Times Photo); the Toyota RAV4-EV possesses a
range of 100 miles and top speed of 78 mph; the General Motors EV1
has the lowest range and the highest profile.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON, Mass. -- July 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 26
-- MUTFUND-ASIA, 7-24 -- ``We almost seek out areas of high
perceived risk,'' says Mark Madden, the manager of the Pioneer
Emerging Markets fund. Despite the financial crisis in Asia, 49
percent of the fund is in Asian stocks. (Ed Quinn/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
