<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLAPSE-RDP-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS IN COLLAPSE FOCUS ON SUPPORT BEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI and JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investigators looking into the causes of the buckling
of a giant construction scaffold in Times Square on Tuesday are
focusing on whether critical support beams at the 21st floor were
disconnected by workers just days before the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Because the scaffolding is so unstable, investigators have been
able to look at it only from a distance, so they have yet to
determine the status of the beams. But they say their absence,
coupled with the stress from a rising construction elevator, could
have caused the buckling of the section of the 48-story scaffold at
the Conde Nast building.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of that section sent part of a steel elevator tower
across West 43rd Street and through the roof of a nearby hotel,
killing an elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not unusual for such beams to be disconnected to
allow access to a building's facade, they must be replaced before
the elevator can be used at their level.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse, which city officials have called the worst
construction accident in more than a decade, has forced officials
to close several streets and numerous buildings around Times
Square, forcing out hundreds of businesses, residents and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening, emergency workers were trying to install a
heavy nylon curtain around the 700-foot-high scaffolding on 43rd
Street and binding the broken elevator tower to the building.
</P>
<P>
   New York's buildings commissioner, Gaston Silva, said the city
planned to reopen Broadway and Seventh Avenue by midday Saturday
and 43rd Street by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Silva said that by early Saturday morning, workers expected to
have stabilized the broken scaffold, removing the danger that all
of it would fall. Construction workers inside the building drove
tremendous steel beams through the open sides of the structure and
into the scaffolding. Silva said the beams are expected to support
the latticework.
</P>
<P>
   But with the damaged scaffolding hanging 300 feet above the
pavement, any mistake could end in disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like pickup sticks,'' said Michael Mazzucca, vice
president of Regional Scaffolding and Hoisting Co. ``Move the wrong
stick and maybe the whole thing comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzucca was part of a team of experts that the city assembled
to recommend how to remove the scaffolding safely. His company
operates the concrete hoist inside the skyscraper that is being
used to ferry workers and materials to the top. In an interview
Friday, he said the metal scaffolding was tilting above 43rd Street
with little support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be a complete separation between the bottom
and the top,'' he said. ``That's why it is not a molehill. It is a
real mountain. It's thousands of pounds of aluminum that can
literally fall down to the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the scaffolding is stabilized, city officials said,
forensic engineers will use bucket hoists to examine the damage in
hopes of pinpointing a cause for the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Construction executives and city engineers and inspectors have
already discarded one theory, saying they no longer believe that a
heavy crane atop the 48-story building had struck the scaffolding
and knocked loose the elevator tower.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are concentrating on the possibility that workers
had disconnected support beams on the 21st floor that tied the
scaffolding to the building, to install a window panel, a senior
investigator said. Without the beams in place, the construction
elevator could have jarred the scaffolding when it rose above the
21st floor, causing the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   A construction executive who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said that the contractor for the scaffolding, United Builders
Supply, and the facade contractors had been working on the 21st
floor the weekend before the accident.
</P>
<P>
   It is a common procedure during the construction of a high-rise
building to disconnect the support beams temporarily to gain access
to the face of the structure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard Kielar, senior vice president with Tishman Realty and
Construction Co., whose unit is the building's construction
manager, said that for the last several months workers from
Universal Builders Supply had been removing connecting beams so
that another contractor could install facade panels. He said the
work was done only on weekends and at night, when the construction
elevator was not in use.
</P>
<P>
   The workers are supposed to reconnect the beams when the work is
done, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzucca said that removing a support beam usually would not
cause a problem. But he said, ``You shouldn't use a hoist beyond
where a tie has been removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal, a highly regarded company that erected the
scaffolding for the renovation of the Statue of Liberty and Grand
Central Terminal, did not return calls requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   As workers continued to shore up the scaffolding, the American
Red Cross said it had helped about 450 people evacuated from their
homes in the neighborhood in obtaining temporary housing. The
developer of the building, Douglas Durst, and his construction
manager, Tishman Construction Corp., established a center at 1120
Ave. of the Americas to aid people with insurance claims.
</P>
<P>
   All four theaters closed by the accident remained dark Friday,
but theater officials were hopeful that three would open as early
as Saturday night. But there is no indication when the fourth, the
Kit Kat Klub that is home of the revival ``Cabaret,'' would be able
to reopen. The club is on 43rd Street, in the shadow of the damaged
scaffolding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
