<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-OFFICERS-1STL     07-24 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-OFFICERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST CAPITOL POLICE OFFICERS EVER KILLED IN LINE OF DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for additions; text from graf 9 on is new. Corrects the
number of children in graf 5.)  (See CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-SCENE, CAPITOL-TOURIST,
CAPITOL-GUNMAN, CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO) 
(lh) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After 18 years in the Capitol Police force, Jacob
Chestnut was looking forward to his retirement. But the 58-year-old
officer remained so ebullient and outgoing with tourists that one
senator said he seemed like the Capitol's official greeter.
</P>
<P>
   John Gibson, an eight-year veteran of the force, worked in the
plainclothes division, assigned to guard Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas,
the third-ranking member of the House Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, both men gave their lives to stop a gunman who barged
into the Capitol and opened fire. The Senate historian said it was
the first time on record that Capitol Police officers had been shot
to death in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers who were killed, and those who apprehended the
gunman, are true heroes of democracy and every American owes them a
deep debt of gratitude,'' said Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that both men were married and that Gibson had
three children. Chestnut had two children, members of his family
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were members of the Capitol's own police force,
formed shortly after an 1828 incident in which a journalist slapped
President John Quincy Adams' son, who was on official business for
his father at the Capitol. Now the force comprises about 1,200
officers who guard the doors and entrances on Capitol Hill,
investigate threats against members of Congress and provide them
with personal protection.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he knew the two men, Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., said,
``We passed them multiple times during a day. And you exchange, you
know, `How are you?' You don't expect an answer. And they're there
every day. And no one expects this to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, members of Congress said, was shot in the chest when
he stopped the gunman and told him to go through the metal detector
at the entrance that he guarded.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was at his post at the unmarked back entrance to the
suite of offices used by DeLay and the whip staff. He ordered staff
members, who were celebrating the House's passage of health care
legislation, to get farther back in the room and to get down on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   He was killed as he exchanged gunfire with the intruder.
</P>
<P>
   ``John gave his life to protect me and members of my staff,''
DeLay said. ``There is no doubt that if John had not acted quickly
and with great bravery as he did, others would have been killed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chestnut's neighbors in the Maryland suburb of Fort Washington
and lawmakers who knew him described him as a cheerful man who was
looking forward to his retirement in another year or so. ``He was a
very outgoing guy,'' said Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D. ``He acted
almost like an official greeter; he was so good with tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome R. Goldring, a neighbor, said Chestnut was ``wonderful
and cheerful, and I wish I had more neighbors like him. I remember,
a few years ago, there was a kind of sickly neighbor, and he would
go up there and cut her lawn. He was a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn E. Gravely-Moss, another neighbor, described how the
officer loved to jog around the neighborhood. ``He and my husband
would talk about retirement. What they would do,'' she said. In
fact, Conrad said that another Capitol police officer told him that
Chestnut had been talking just a day earlier about how much he
looked forward to retiring, perhaps as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Gingrich stopped at the Chestnut home to see the
officers' wife, Wenling, and family.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, who lived in the Virginia suburbs, had worked as one of
the plainclothes officers in the Senate before being transferred to
protect DeLay. ``He loved the protection detail,'' said Virgil
VanFleet, a 28-year veteran of the Capitol Police who had once
worked in a scout car as Gibson's partner.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago, the two men had joked about the days when
they used to ticket cab drivers on Capitol grounds. ``That was the
last conversation I had with him,'' he said. ``John was a very good
man, very conscientious. It's obvious that when he died, he died a
hero.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
