<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHOOTING-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THERE WAS CHAOS AND PANDEMONIUM,' SAYS TOURIST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The tourists were snaking through the Byzantine
hallways and milling about the massive marble Rotunda of the
Capitol as they normally do during the busy summer season.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians were finishing up business for the week, still
giving speeches while they and their staffs prepared to head home
for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And then suddenly, nothing was routine. Gunfire erupted near a
first-floor entrance close to the area known as the Crypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was chaos and pandemonium,'' said Laurie Curcio, a
tourist from Long Island, who was on a tour on the floor above when
the shooting started at about 3:40 p.m., EDT., Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Those near the gunfire ducked and reached for their kids, while
tourists in other parts of the building who heard the rapid
succession of shots rushed for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Curcio said that at first no one in her group moved, behaving as
if they couldn't believe what they were hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, the tour guide yelled, ``Oh my God, that was a
gunshot,'' and people began heading for the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, Justin Brown was working in the gift shop when he
saw a man with a gun ``running through and shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just ran right through the metal detectors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Brown said he did not get a good look at the gunman, he
did notice that a police officer was down, as did tourist Ronald
Beamish from England, who went over to try to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the officer hit the floor. I went over to him, felt his
palm. I yelled, `Get a stretcher,''' said Beamish.
</P>
<P>
   Beamish said the police officer appeared to be hit in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``His left eye seemed to be gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Addotta of Rockford, Ill., was looking at the displays in
the Crypt with his family when he said he suddenly saw a flash of
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled, `Get down and out of the building,''' he said to his
wife, three sons and mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The family became separated in the chaotic aftermath but was
later reunited outside.
</P>
<P>
   Addotta, who was in Washington for a cookie convention, said
this was his family's first visit to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would come again, he replied, ``Probably. But I
don't know if my kids will.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the tourist assumed the Capitol was a safe place
considering the impressive show of security to anyone entering the
building. Police officers are stationed at each entrance where
everyone must pass through metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed well guarded. We felt safe going in,'' said Brad
Davis, who was visiting with his wife and two children from
Hamilton, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis family was being taken on a tour of the Capitol by an
aide to their Texas congressman, Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Although they did not hear the shots, they were about to go into
the Sam Rayburn room when they saw two guards coming toward them,
who ordered them to go the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scarey,'' said Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanie Mamo, a spokeswoman for Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, heard
the noise as she was conducting a tour of the Capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if you were at a construction site and heard blocks
falling,''she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mamo said she didn't realize what had happened until ``tourists
came flying down the steps. Some were shouting, `He's got a gun.
He's got a gun.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Amber Simas said she and a friend were walking on the second
floor near the Rotunda when she heard three shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone started picking up their kids and running,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Simas said that her first reaction was to get away. ``My second
reaction was to see what happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Simas said that right before the incident, she had asked her
friend when the last time someone was shot in the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, two police officers, one tourist and the
gunman lay wounded. The two officers later died.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the tourists and staff made it out of the
building, others were sequestered there for several hours as police
blocked off major hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers had just left the building because the House had
completed its major business of the day: voting on a bill to
regulated managed care.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of members, including Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Texas,
had remained behind to make short speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Lampson said he was giving his speech on missing and exploited
children when he saw guards rush in and lock the doors of the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lampson said that the lawmakers who remained in the
chamber either wandered into the cloakroom to watch events
unfolding on Cable News Network, or continued making speeches on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floor business continued as usual,'' he said. ``With
people giving presentations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
