<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, JULY 25
</HEADLINE>
  Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-VATICAN-BISHOPS-NYT (moved on Thursday, July 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, July 23,
about an apostolic letter by Pope John Paul II tightening Rome's
control over bishops' conferences misstated the kind of document
that must be sent to Rome for approval even if it is passed by an
overwhelming majority. The ruling applies to documents on doctrinal
matters, not nondoctrinal matters.
</P>
<P>
   BC-RUSSIA-CZAR-NYT (moved on Thursday, July 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, July 16,
about President Boris N. Yeltsin's decision to attend the burial of
Czar Nicholas II and his family in St. Petersburg misstated the age
of the fortress of Peter and Paul, build by Nicholas's ancestor,
Peter the Great. It was built some 250 years ago, not 350.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, July 22)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July
22, about diplomatic activity in the Middle East reversed the
position of Israel's Third Way party. The party has threatened to
quit Prime Minster Benjamin Net-anyahu's coalition if he does not
reach an accord with the Palestinians. The party did not threaten
to quit if Mr. Netanyahu does reach an accord.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BILINGUAL-EDUC-NYT (moved on Wednesday, July 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July
15, about a Federal judge's refusal to block the statewide ballot
measure that ended most bilingual education programs in the
California public schools referred incorrectly to the role of the
state Attorney General, Dan Lungren. Mr. Lungren has not recused
himself or the Attorney General's office in the lawsuit challenging
the measure. The State Board of Education, which is defending the
measure, retained its own lawyers with the Attorney General's
permission because it wanted to advance different legal arguments.
</P>
</TEXT>
