<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Slip.Net's Hack-Attack Suit Has Turned Into a Federal Case   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
It may have started out as a beef between a software engineer and
his boss, but now it has become a federal case.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Nicholas Middleton stood in District Judge Charles Legge's
San Francisco courtroom yesterday to defend himself against felony
charges that he hacked into a computer at Slip.Net, a San
Francisco-based Internet service provider, and wrought electronic
mischief that cost $40,000 to correct.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged hack was discovered on a Sunday morning in March, a
few weeks after Middleton, who had been Slip.Net's system
administrator, sent a take-this-job-and-shove-it e-mail to company
President Ted Glenwright.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Bert Glenn is now prepared to argue that
a miffed Middleton was the cyberintruder who used a program called
PC Anywhere to access Slip.Net's main computer via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the system, the hacker _ whoever he or she might be
_ allegedly changed all the passwords of Slip.Net's employees,
locking them out of their own Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   The intruder also uninstalled the SQL Server database that
Slip.Net used in its business.
</P>
<P>
   The government will seek to prove not only that Middleton caused
this mischief, but that it cost Slip.Net $40,000 in labor to set
its systems right.
</P>
<P>
   If the government can prove both assertions _ that Middleton did
the hack and, in the process, caused at least $5,000 in damages _
then the 34-year-old San Francisco man will face a maximum sentence
of five years in jail and $250,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Middleton's attorney, David Cohen, said his client, who has
never before been in trouble with the law, has pleaded not guilty
to the hacking charges and would vigorously dispute the supposed
costs of repairing the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Middleton and the FBI, which investigated the
charges, discussed a plea bargain but that the talks came to naught
because the feds wanted the him to reimburse Slip.Net for the
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now a federal jury will have to decide whether this was a stupid
prank or a costly crime _ and whether Middleton was involved.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Big spenders? &LR;  Silicon Valley millionaires have a reputation
for being cheap with charities, but venture capitalist Gib Myers
plans to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, a 28-year venture veteran, recently started a nonprofit
group called the Entrepreneur's Foundation. Its mission is to get
entrepreneurs in the habit of donating time _ and stock _ long
before they normally would get old and generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like you have to teach a child values, we're trying to
get companies to think about philanthropy from the outset,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation director Patty Burness said that altruism aside,
young firms benefit from supporting employees in volunteering at
food banks or doing blood drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great way to build team spirit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to writing volunteerism into their corporate DNA,
startups that join the Foundation will be required to donate some
stock. These donations will create a fund to support existing
nonprofits that specialize in education or youth development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the stock isn't worth much now, but if we get one
or two Yahoos ...,'' Myers said, letting the thought dangle.
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation won't just give money to nonprofits. It also will
place high-tech execs on their boards. The idea is to pollinate
charities with capitalistic management skills.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this cross-breeding will work remains to be seen, but
the new practice comes with a buzzword: venture philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Ten startups, including Know Med Systems of Berkeley and Aptia
Inc. of San Jose, have already joined. Myers hopes to get 25 this
year and 500 in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out to change the culture of the Valley with respect to
philanthropy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a tall order, and to get peer pressure working on his
side, Myers has recruited an all-star board including venture
capitalist Brook Byers, banker John Dean and lawyer Larry Sonsini &LR; 
(see http://the-ef.org) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Charitable trend? &LR;  Bud Colligan, the software guy turned
venture capitalist, has raised $3 million toward his goal of
creating a $10 million nonprofit fund to invest in companies that
create entry-level jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Colligan said he was motivated by concern that there might not
be enough entry-level jobs for the 500,000 people expected to lose
public assistance as a result of welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be administered by the newly formed Silicon
Valley Community Ventures  &LR; (www.svcv.org) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Colligan has lined up a board of directors that includes noted
entrepreneurs, such as attorney Gordie Davidson, and experts in the
nonprofit world, such as Eric Weaver, executive director of Lenders
for Community Development in San Jose, and Anita Stephens, who runs
a Fremont-based job-training program, Opportunity Capital Partners.
</P>
<P>
   By January, Colligan expects SVCV to have raised its $10 million
so that it can start investing in businesses _ be they factories or
service firms _ that employ mainly unskilled or semi-skilled
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate in being able to grow a company and make
money myself,'' said Colligan, best known as co-founder of
Macromedia, the San Francisco-based multimedia firm. ``This is an
opportunity to give back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail  &LR; (abate(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
