<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Advertisers Take a Swing at Golf   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
It's enough to tee a golfer off.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditionally, golf courses and driving ranges have been
sanctuaries of greenery and sand, disrupted only by the occasional
plaid trouser. But like bus shelters and taxi trunks before them,
golf venues are seeing the slow encroachment of advertising
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Posters hawking PCS phones and credit cards are popping up on
tee dividers at driving ranges, and billboard-style ads soon might
appear on range targets.
</P>
<P>
   At some golf courses, navigation computers on golf carts display
digital ads along with driving distances, and marketers are
plotting to wrap the carts in vinyl ads like those on city buses.
</P>
<P>
   Logos and signs also are appearing on golf balls, driving range
mats, score cards and golf-ball vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   Like most trends in advertising, demographics explain the drive
toward putting ads on golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sport is shedding its image as a pastime of the
country club set, the average annual household income of a golfer,
at $57,000, is significantly higher than the US average.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Golfers' expenditures on goods such as fine jewelry, stock,
travel, cigars and wireless telephones are well above those of
nongolfers, according to MRI Doublebase.
</P>
<P>
   Golf also is a growing sport, in part due to the appeal of
rising young stars such as Tiger Woods and Se Ri Pak.
</P>
<P>
   About 26.5 million Americans played at least one round of golf
in 1997, up from 25 million in 1996, according to the National Golf
Foundation. The number of core players, who play 25 or more rounds
per year, increased 30 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Those people represent a captive audience every time they step
onto a golf course or driving range. And golf venues contain
relatively unexploited spaces in a world where virtually every bus
shelter, Web site, newspaper and dirigible is already backed by
corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   While the profit potential is obvious, marketers should be wary
about overdoing advertising on golf courses, which serve as ``a
physical and mental retreat'' for golfers, said Keith Bruce,
director of sports marketing at the advertising agency Foote, Cone
&AMP; Belding/San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely the chance that you will offend some
people with an advertising message in an area where there used to
not be advertising,'' Bruce said. ``When they're entertaining and
nonintrusive, they will be viewed in a positive light. The question
is what is intrusive and what is not.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Ads located discreetly inside the cart, such as on a score
card or a navigation computer screen, are acceptable, Bruce said.
``Once advertising starts to intrude on the visual sight lines of
players, they're going to have problems with that.''
</P>
<P>
   At driving ranges, where golfers stand in rows and practice
hitting buckets of balls, golfers will be more forgiving of
advertising messages than on the course because serenity isn't as
important at ranges, Bruce said .
</P>
<P>
   That is why Pinpoint Golf Marketing, a San Francisco company
that is at the forefront of golf venue marketing, is focusing on
selling ad space at practice ranges _ though it is starting to move
onto courses, too.
</P>
<P>
   Pinpoint has put together a network of 175 driving ranges across
the country that have agreed to display signs on tee dividers _ the
vertical grids separating each tee area to protect golfers from
wayward balls.
</P>
<P>
   The company is looking for funding to expand to 1,000 ranges
during the next two years, said Ben Tresser, Pinpoint's vice
president of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers such as Visa, which markets a Jack Nicklaus credit
card, are paying $1,500 to $6,000 to post signs on half of the tee
dividers at a given range for three months. The price level depends
on the amount of tees and the number of customers who visit the
range.
</P>
<P>
   Many advertisers are pairing the signs with other promotions.
Titanium Sports Technologies, for example, posted signs at five
Chicago-area driving ranges telling visitors that they could &LR; 
 &LR; test-drive a club with a titanium shaft at the pro shop.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being annoyed by the ads, customers were pleased to
have a chance to try the expensive clubs, which are not widely
available, said Sandra Gladstone, vice president, marketing, with
Titanium.
</P>
<P>
   Titanium, based in Kennewick, Wash., also used the promotion to
collect names and addresses of golfers for its marketing database,
Gladstone said.
</P>
<P>
   The signs ``can't help but have an impact,'' she said. ``A lot
of the facilities have 50 or 60 tee dividers, and people are out
there for a half-hour to an hour. We think it's an excellent value,
and we're feeling quite confident that this will be beneficial for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many range managers who have been approached by Pinpoint
have opted not to post the signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call this Puritanism, but we don't like to overcommercialize
what we're doing,'' said Mike Santin, Western regional manager for
Family Golf Centers, which runs 100 driving ranges in 20 states.
``People come out here to hit balls, not to look at ads all over
the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Even driving ranges that display Pinpoint's tee-divider ads seem
leery of another, more in-your-face project in development _ ads on
range targets, the billboard-type signs on a driving range that
mark how far a ball has been hit.
</P>
<P>
   Pinpoint has spoken to advertisers such as Absolut, for example,
about making a 250-yard target in the shape of a vodka bottle,
Tresser said. So far, no advertisers have signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons of the driving range at Mission Bay Golf Center in San
Francisco don't seem to mind the tee-divider signs, said Dennis
Duden, general manager of the range. But Duden doesn't think that
his customers will stomach ads on targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe at our range in Sacramento we could get away with that,
but San Francisco has an image of itself as quite urbane, so we try
and stay away from gimmicky types of things,'' Duden said.
</P>
<P>
   To reach golfers on the green, Pinpoint is behind the move to
run digital ads on navigation computers in golf carts. The idea is
to run an ad between each of 18 holes while the cart is being
driven around the green.
</P>
<P>
   Along with tips such as ``There is a bunker 150 yards to the
left,'' the computers, which use satellite tracking technology,
would flash ads for the local BMW dealer or for a power drink being
served at the club house.
</P>
<P>
   ProShot Golf Inc. of Newport Beach (Orange County) charges about
$200 per month for each of the 18 ad slots, said John Seymour, vice
president of sales and marketing for the company, which develops
and markets the computers.
</P>
<P>
   Testing at the first three courses has gone well, and the
program soon will be expanded to 12 more, including the Presidio
Golf Course, Seymour said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinpoint's next plan for golf-cart marketing is far less subtle
than digital ads. Tresser said he is talking with a company that
makes vinyl signs for wrapping buses about creating similar
dressings for golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to wrap it with Budweiser ads or whatever,'' Tresser
said. ``That's the natural next step as we head into courses.''
</P>
<P>
   But cart wraps raise a red flag for Bruce, the proponent of
``nonintrusive'' advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want their golf course to look like a Nascar,''
he said. ``People won't be horrified by commercial messages, but
they have to be done in a tasteful, understated, almost covert
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but it could be so much worse. ``We've had much more
atrocious ideas,'' Tresser said. ``We've talked with some
advertisers about burning a corporate logo in the middle of the
field, like a Rosebowl Game,'' but decided that idea wouldn't fly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
