<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 26,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICIANS-ARTS (Washington) _ Today as yesterday and the day
before, with Republicans as well as Democrats in control of the
White House, with Democratic as well as Republican majorities on
Capitol Hill, the arts and intellectual activity in general are
often bashed and seldom boosted by political Washington, left or
right. By R.W. Apple Jr. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   REAL-WAR-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ If we post World War II children
had been cleared-eyed, we would have noticed that the close-lipped
veterans who oversaw our lives really didn't resemble those
full-of-moxie, hell-for-leather fighting Joes on the screen. The
men we boys knew, the ones working 9 to 5, mowing lawns and
coaching Little League, had little of John Wayne's swagger. They
were just regular guys. But small boys aren't built to notice such
disparities, let alone reconcile them. Small boys, as a rule,
aren't realists. Distinguishing reality from fantasy is a
grown-up's task, and Steven Spielberg, another son of the postwar
generation, has fairly risen to it. There is, of course, some irony
in saying this of a filmmaker who has imagined 20th-century
dinosaurs and cuddly extraterrestrials. But in ``Saving Private
Ryan'' he is, as he was in ``Schindler's List,'' a realist. By
William McDonald. &UR; ( &LR; Moved).
 &UR;  &LR; 
 &UR; FILMS and VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  POIRIER-FILMS &UR;  &LR; (Paris) _ Manuel Poirier's movie career got off
to a slow start. He was 40 by the time his first film was released,
and even then, forced to act as his own producer, he could afford
only one print. Yet, somehow, the right people saw it and liked it
and the doors that Poirier had been knocking on for years suddenly
opened. Within two years he had made three more movies, and the
last of these, ``Western,'' won the Grand Jury Prize at the 1997
Cannes International Film Festival. By Alan Riding. (Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GRAY-NEGOTIATOR-FILM (Los Angeles) _ An interview with the film
director, F. Gary Gray, 28, and his new movie ``The Negotiator.''
Gray, who grew up in tough South-Central Los Angeles came to
feature films through his directing of music videos for rap
artists. By Bernard Weinraub. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PARENT-TRAP-FILM (Undated) _ At a recent advance screening of
Disney's remake of its classic 1961 film ``The Parent Trap,'' a
girl about 7 or 8 years old was overheard to say: ``You know what I
like about this movie? This is a family movie kids will like.''
This pint-size critic had put her thumb squarely on something that
has been tormenting Hollywood of late: how to create films that
will appeal to young moviegoers without alienating their parents.
By James Ryan. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (London) _ Theater reviews of ``Twelfth Night'';
``Village''; ``Adam Resurrected'' and ``The Street of Crocodiles.''
By Vincent Canby. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY-HERMAN-THEATER (Los Angeles) _ Jerry Herman is returning
to Broadway this week on a deeply personal note. The 66-year-old
composer-lyricist for such huge successes as ``Hello, Dolly!,''
``Mame'' and ``La Cage Aux Folles'' _ a Broadway figure who is both
a symbol of a golden era and an undervalued songwriter _ was
diagnosed with HIV 13 years ago and watched his health decline.
Since then with the help of protease inhibitors, which he takes
after every meal, the outgoing and perennially smiling composer
said his restored health _ he also had a triple heart bypass last
year _ energized him for the first time in a decade and has led to
``An Evening With Jerry Herman,'' starring Lee Roy Reams, Florence
Lacey and Herman himself at the Booth Theater for a two-month run
that opens on Tuesday. By Bernard Weinraub. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   JENKINS-SEATTLE-OPERA (Seattle) _ No one else runs an opera
company, or talks about opera, with the fervor of Speight Jenkins.
``You see, in `Tristan und Isolde,' Wagner wanted everyone in the
audience to experience his frustration in not being able to
consummate his love for Mathilde Wesendonck,'' Jenkins, the general
director of the Seattle Opera, said recently, warming to his
favorite topic. The Seattle Opera's new production of ``Tristan und
Isolde,'' which opens on Saturday evening, brings together the
hottest Wagner singers of the moment, the Canadian tenor Ben
Heppner and the English soprano Jane Eaglen, for the first time in
the title roles. By David Schiff. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MAD-ARTISTS (Undated) _ In recent years there has been a lot of
interest, not least from composers, in the artistic productions of
people who would have once been called mad. By Paul Griffiths.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-VOICES (subslug) (Undated) _ A Favorite stump-the-panel
segment on the Texaco Opera Quiz during the Saturday afternoon
radio broadcasts of the Metropolitan Opera is the ``singer ID.''
Recordings of, say, five unidentified tenors singing the same
phrase of a particular aria are played in a row, and the panelists
are asked to name them. It's amazing how difficult it can be to
recognize the voices of even famous tenors like Carlo Bergonzi or
Alfredo Kraus. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   EAGLEN/SCHAFER-ALBUMS (Undated) _ Singers are forever trying to
create inventive programs, balancing art songs with arias, serious
material with lighter fare, the familiar with the novel. On
records, the challenge is perhaps even greater than in the concert
hall, for the choices must stand the tests of time and repeated
listening. How gratifying, then, to encounter two new cleverly
assembled vocal disks. Ostensibly these albums are similar, each
featuring a rising soprano singing music by Mozart and Richard
Strauss. By David Mermelstein. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Brief reviews of classical music
CDs. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PALMER-ROCK-FAME (Undated) _ When the Hall of Fame announces its
14th annual class of inductees this fall _ the selection process
began earlier this month _ it's a sure bet that Earl Palmer won't
be among them. Who? Though few people have heard of Palmer, this
73-year-old has had a greater impact on rock than many a Hall of
Fame shoo-in. By Tony Scherman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PULITZER-PRIZE-JAZZ (Undated) _ Trivia question: who was the
first jazz musician to win the Pulitzer Prize for music? Hint: it
wasn't Wynton Marsalis. The honor belongs to Mel Powell, who won in
1990 for a two-piano concerto called ``Duplicates.'' By Terry
Teachout. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUMPER-CARS-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ A look at Peter Foster, a
collector of bumper cars. Bumper cars were designed to operate
using electric power supplied from a metal-mesh ceiling, but
Foster's cars have been converted to 12-volt battery power, which
enables them to run on any hard, flat surface. By Seth Gussow.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PA-LANCASTER-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ The Lancaster sanctuary is
getting smaller, thanks in part to the car that conveys you into a
part of the world that retained its serenity until the postwar
years. In the last three years, more than 1,000 acres of farmland
in Lancaster County have vanished. The car culture has gulped down
big chunks of a landscape long associated with the horse-drawn
carriage. Open land has been turned into sites for suburban
subdivisions, big-box discount outlets and strip malls. By Herbert
Muschamp. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CITY-BALLET (New York) _ The New York City Ballet is 50 years
old this year. So let's rejoice. The company and its affiliated
School of American Ballet are remarkable institutions, and George
Balanchine and Lincoln Kirstein, their founders, are heroic
figures. By Jack Anderson. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
