<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-CLOSURE-240&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
18-MONTH RENOVATION FOR SUBWAY SHUTTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long considered one of the most run-down and
neglected parts of New York City's sprawling transit network, the
five-station Franklin Avenue shuttle, which cuts 1.4 miles across
central Brooklyn, began the final stages of a badly needed overhaul
Friday that will leave it out of service for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting off attempts to close the elevated line _ which
has not seen a healthy ridership since 1957, when the Dodgers last
played nearby, in Ebbets Field _ community leaders were finally
able to secure money for the $74 million rehabilitation project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Franklin Avenue Shuttle is a great project, and we worked
hard to get this for 10 years,'' said Lewis Watkins, an official
with Community Board 3 in Bedford-Stuyvesant. ``The transit
authority wanted to close the line or use the money for something
else, but we are finally getting a much-needed renovation.''
</P>
<P>
   While the line is legendary among subway buffs for its decrepit
condition, for some riders it plays an important role, serving as a
link between the A and C lines, which go to eastern Brooklyn, and
the D and Q lines, which go to southern Brooklyn. The shuttle draws
an average of 10,000 riders a day.
</P>
<P>
   To serve riders affected by the shutdown, transit officials will
operate free shuttle-bus service between Lincoln Road and Fulton
Street. City officials say the rehabilitation project will also
cause sporadic rerouting of traffic on busy Fulton Street over the
next 18 months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The project is not universally supported, even in Brooklyn. Some
residents complain that the Metropolitan Transportation Authority's
decision to use buses to transport riders will create a safety
hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is good that the new line is being constructed,''
said Bernice Moses, a frequent shuttle user. ``But the street that
they are temporarily putting the buses on is not equipped to handle
that type of traffic _ it's residential.''
</P>
<P>
   Transit agency officials brushed off the criticism. ``We have
been coordinating it with the community for two years,'' said
Melissa Farley, a spokeswoman for New York City Transit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the poor condition of the shuttle line, with its old
trains and deteriorating stations topped by rusty roofs, community
leaders have worked vigorously to keep it running, saying that it
was held hostage to political squabbling while much newer lines
were receiving repairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the project repeatedly ended up on the MTA's list
of needed restorations. In 1996, the Brooklyn borough president,
Howard Golden, and Assemblyman Albert Vann successfully lobbied the
state Legislature to budget money for the repairs. Construction
workers have been on the job since May, and demolition work has
already begun.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's shutdown of the line represents the beginning of the
second phase of the project. New tracks, signals, lights, signs,
platforms and a public address system, closed-circuit television
and even artwork are to be installed.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Russianoff, a lawyer for the Straphangers Campaign, the
subway riders advocacy group that lobbied for the renovations,
called the start of the project ``a great moment for the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   MTA officials said the project would have cost more and taken
months longer if they had chosen to shut down the line
sector-by-sector, as some community leaders had suggested, instead
of doing it all at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an old line, and it does need to be rehabilitated,''
said Ms. Farley, the MTA spokeswoman. ``And to do that, it needs to
be totally reconstructed. It's a pretty big job.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
