<SLUG> BC-BKN--US </SLUG>
 TEAM-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
It's no Roman holiday as bus men prepare for tuneup game with Italy
<TEXT>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ROME _ Traversing foreign countries with an entourage of 12
players, numerous coaches, support personnel and dignitaries from
various American basketball organizations, an international
incident is never more than an unintentional bump or impolite
gesture away.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as they found out Friday, it doesn't even have to
involve one of the Americans preparing for the FIBA World
Championship of Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team members were aboard a bus heading to their first
practice at the Palaeur on the outskirts of Rome when their driver
came to a sudden stop. In Rome, this is not news. Drivers, whether
they are operating a taxi, bus or moped, treat the roads as an
Indy-car driver would treat the racetrack. The lane is wherever the
driver wants it to be.
</P>
<P>
   New York cabbies are Rome cabbie wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after the bus driver for the Americans was cut off by a
man on a scooter, prompting the quick brake, there was a long
exchange between the two vehicularly charged gentlemen, complete
with many arm-waving gestures and, supposedly, the Italian
equivalent of four-letter words.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the bus lurched forward and bumped the back end
of the scooter. It was sort of like Shaquille O'Neal delivering a
message to Spud Webb: The bus driver only did it because he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy rammed him and then he stopped the bus and wanted to
go out and get a piece of the guy on the scooter,'' coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``It was a crazy scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Not something Ralph Kramden would have put on his rsum, but
standard stuff for the Romans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do that in LA or New York,'' said forward David
Wood. ``Someone will pull out a gun and pop a cap in you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those little mopeds are the way to get where you want to go
really quick,'' Wood said. ``But one time out of 100, you're not
going to get there. It's great 99 times out of 100. But that other
time, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as these things can, it could have escalated in Rome, too.
Were it not for the police escort that was with the U.S. bus,
things might have gotten nasty. But authorities calmed the driver
and things proceeded normally as the Americans made it to the arena
and had a lively practice.
</P>
<P>
   But you never know when something might happen to put people
representing America in a compromising position.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the team has escaped relatively unharmed after 10 days
overseas. Hopefully, the players can say the same thing after
tonight's final exhibition tuneup before the World Championship of
Basketball opens Wednesday in Athens, Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team will take on the Italian national team at the
Palaeur, one of the biggest and best arenas in Europe with seating
for about 12,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy will be the best team we've played so far and it will be
our last game before the tournament, and we feel that with each
game, we've played a tougher team,'' Tomjanovich said. ``So that
helps in our development.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Americans has a good working knowledge of the Italian
team. Forward Bill Edwards played for Calze Pompea Roma last
season; the Palaeur is that team's home court.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he believes the Italians will give the United
States a fitting final tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know just about all of them,'' he said of the Italian
players. ``I've actually played on the same teams with about seven
or eight of them the past few years. They're young and athletic.
(Guard) Carlton Myers is tough and (Andrea) Meneghin is the other
guy who can really play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gianmarco) Pozzecco is playing the point for them and you
love him as a player, but you hate him as a coach. He's a flashy
player who tries to get the crowd involved. And he'll have about
six or seven turnovers at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians lost to the same French team the United States beat
by 30 points in an exhibition last weekend. But Edwards says that's
not a sign of Italy's true team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised they lost to the French team,'' he said. ``But
generally, the Italian teams play better at home. They can play
terrible on the road and great at home. And we're on their home
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice, Edwards says, if the Americans became involved
in a tight game. Their first two exhibitions were blowout wins and
before the tournament begins, it would be good for the U.S. team to
be pushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two teams didn't really push us,'' Edwards said.
``I'd like to see us really get tested down to the wire so we can
get used to it and see how it's really going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards isn't the only American familiar with the Palaeur. Wood
had one of his fondest basketball memories on the same court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played the best game of my whole European career in this
building,'' Wood said. ``I had 27 points, 17 in the first half. We
had a $1,000 bonus on the game because it gave us home-court
advantage in the playoffs. So it was a big game for us and we
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, just winning will be enough for the Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
