<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY PLAYERS INUNDATE CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE ALLEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, Conn. _ The usual Friday beach backup on Interstate
95 turned into a Powerball jam Friday as New Yorkers sat in traffic
for hours so they could buy a dream of $195 million, a dollar at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic into Connecticut is routinely slow on a Friday night in
the summer, state police officials said. But the lottery jackpot
made things worse: traffic was backed up from New Haven, through
New York and even across the George Washington Bridge. A state
police dispatcher estimated that a 20-mile trip on Interstate 95
took two and a half hours during Friday night's rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy and hopeful, the out-of-staters lined up for blocks around
Connecticut gas stations, cigar stores and newsstands to buy
tickets for the Powerball lottery, which is sold in 20 states and
the District of Columbia but not in New York or New Jersey. The
jackpot for Saturday night's drawing is estimated at $195 million,
tying a Powerball record set in May.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Fernando, 36, a courier from Flatbush, Brooklyn, had made
the trip during a previous outbreak of Powerball fever. This time
he drove his motorcycle, so he could weave in and out of traffic on
his way to buy 60 tickets for himself and eight friends.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, fueled by the run from the New York border, is
expected to have more sales for this drawing than any other
Powerball state, according to the Multi-State Lottery Association,
which runs the game. About 122 million tickets will be sold for the
drawing, which will be held at 10:59 p.m. The odds of hitting the
jackpot are 80 million to 1.
</P>
<P>
   At the Putnam Shell gas station in Greenwich, a few dozen
customers slept in their cars after the lottery machine shut down
at 11 Thursday night so that they wouldn't have to wait so long
Friday morning. During the day, station employees ushered three or
four people at a time into the tiny shop, and at 7:30 p.m. there
was still a four-hour wait to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Christine McElduff, 35, a licensed practical nurse from Rye,
N.Y, was sunburned after waiting four hours to buy about 40 tickets
for herself and family members. ``My legs are about to give out,
but you never know if it's your lucky day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The lines in Greenwich were so long that police added five
officers to the evening shift's usual complement of 15. State
troopers were helping out in some traffic-clogged towns near the
state line.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Fernandez, 18, of Queens, skipped his biology class at the
end of summer school Friday so he could head for Cove Variety in
Stamford. Fernandez had more than two hours in traffic to think
about his lucky numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked around and all I saw were New York and New Jersey
license plates,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
