<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHOOTING-DELAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
DeLAY PRAISES OFFICER WHO GAVE HIS LIFE TO PROTECT OTHERS 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Friday's fatal Capitol shootout ended in a hail of
bullets just inside a private entrance to House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay's office.
</P>
<P>
   Killed in the confrontation was John Gibson, a plainclothes
police officer assigned to provide security for DeLay, the Sugar
Land Republican who is No. 3 man on the leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was fatally wounded, Gibson disabled the gunman who
had shot past security, killing another Capitol police officer and
wounding a tourist.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who was in the office at the time, was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``John gave his life to protect me and the members of my
staff,'' DeLay said. ``There is no doubt that if John had not acted
quickly and with great bravery as he did, others would have been
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   To DeLay and his staff, the first shots were faint. The lawmaker
emerged from his office, aides recalled. Then, the next shots were
louder and closer. DeLay ordered nearby staff members and interns
into his office where they shut, bolted the large oak door and
began praying.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, we heard a loud popping noise. You assume being in
the Capitol this isn't gunfire,'' said Tony Rudy, who is policy
director for DeLay. ``Four seconds later, we heard them again and
they were more pronounced, and I was absolutely sure they were
gunshots. Everyone took a nosedive under their desks.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said he grabbed two women in the outside office ``and we
went back into the bathroom off my office.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he used a cell phone to call the Capitol police and
stayed in the bathroom for about 10 minutes until they were told it
was safe to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite a gruesome scene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the congressman and his aides took cover, Gibson was
confronting the gunman in a small room at the head of a hallway
leading into the warren of offices that make up the majority whip's
complex.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman had come through an unmarked door about 20 feet from
the metal detector, turned a corner and came face-to-face with
Gibson. He ``was trying to run away from the other officers
outside,'' said Mike Scanlon, DeLay's press secretary. ``The guy
picked the wrong door.''
</P>
<P>
   Weston and Gibson began firing at almost point-blank range, some
bullets finding their mark, others nicking walls and desks that
lined the hallway. At one of the desks was Joe Connelly, a computer
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullets must have been flying past his head,'' Rudy said.
``He was right there, three or four feet from the firefight.''
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting stopped, Rudy and other staff members eased
down the hallway and heard Connelly, 21, shouting that Gibson had
been shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this guy, laying there bleeding on our rug. A police
officer was standing over him with a gun pointed at his head
telling him to drop his gun and yelling `you shot one of my
officers,''' Rudy said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman, wounded in the stomach and legs, was wearing khaki
pants and a T-shirt. His broad-brimmed hat, with a feather in the
band, had been knocked from his head during the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Gibson lay mortally wounded. The 42-year-old officer,
who grew up in Waltham, Mass., near Boston had been assigned to
DeLay's security detail a little more than three years ago.
Wherever DeLay went _ except for the House floor _ Gibson was at
his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Gibson is a hero. We all believe he saved our lives,''
Rudy said. He was ``more than a security guard. He was like a
member of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gibson was being flown by helicopter to the hospital, DeLay
gathered staff members and led a prayer for the officer.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Capitol police urged DeLay to leave the building
and, once they learned he had planned to fly home for the weekend,
suggested he not change his plans.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in Houston, DeLay said: ``It was one of the
longest plane rides of my life. I guess these things happen when
you've got so many crazies out there.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said he did not know whether he was a target of the
gunman. ``It was one of the closest doors. But he had to go through
two doors to get there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Gibson was one of the finest men I knew,'' DeLay said,
his eyes tearing. ``And he was a damned good Democrat. He was one
tough law officer because he took some bullets and still brought
the shooter down. It's very humbling when somebody gives their life
protecting yours.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman and his wife, Christine, returned to Washington
via chartered aircraft late Friday and were planning to meet with
Gibson's family Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the most professional men in the world. Just
yesterday we were laughing about the fact that he had a CD in my
car, `Macho Man,''' said DeLay. ``John was the most macho man I've
ever known. ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
