<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2326 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-GIBSON-BOS &LR;      07-24 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-GIBSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER WHO GAVE HIS LIFE CREDITED WITH SAVING OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY   AND ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seconds after the gunshots echoed down the Capitol
hallway Friday afternoon and the door to his office burst open,
Capitol Police Officer John Gibson stared into the face of danger
and refused to flinch.
</P>
<P>
   The face he saw was that of Russell E. Weston. Wielding a gun,
Weston stormed into the outer office of Republican Rep. Tom DeLay
of Texas, a senior member of the House leadership. Gibson, a Boston
native, nephew by marriage to Rep. Joseph Moakley, and a personal
bodyguard to DeLay, bolted up and hollered for Weston to freeze,
according to eyewitness accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drop the gun,'' Gibson yelled. Weston instead began firing.
</P>
<P>
   What followed, the witnesses said, was a frantic, seconds-long
shootout between Gibson and Weston while they stood no more than
several feet apart. It was a shootout that left Gibson dead and
Weston wounded. Others in the office, including DeLay, said Gibson
saved their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was shot first, but fired repeatedly at the suspect until
he wounded him to the point where he could no longer move,
according to Tony Rudy, a senior aide to DeLay who was hiding in a
nearby office at the time. Within 30 seconds, other Capitol Police
raced into the office. One held a gun to Weston's face as several
others pleaded in a loud voice for Gibson to hold on and stay
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officer Gibson ordered him to put his gun down,'' said Rudy.
``The guy didn't. He fired at Officer Gibson, and they had an
exchange of gunfire, and luckily the officer was able to knock the
gunman down.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy added: ``John Gibson is a hero. If it wasn't for John
Gibson, this would have been a tragedy of multiple proportions. If
it wasn't for him, the gunman would have walked through this office
and picked us off one by one. He saved our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   They were an unlikely pair, DeLay and Gibson, the former a
conservative Republican from a place called Sugar Land, Texas, the
latter a plaintalking 42-year-old Bostonian with a thick accent, a
love of sports, and a driving desire to work as a cop.
</P>
<P>
   From the crack of dawn until the last vote was cast and the last
event attended at night, Gibson, an eight-year veteran of the
Capitol Police, shadowed DeLay wherever he went. The two were so
close that some DeLay aides likened their relationship to that of
father and son.
</P>
<P>
   ``John was a very nice guy, friendly and outgoing,'' Moakley
said. ``The guy was into the job, loved the job. He had the job he
always wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley said he had not yet been able to reach Lynn, his niece
and Gibson's wife. She is the daughter of his brother Robert. He
said he called the hospital, and was told that she was too
distraught to speak to anyone, even a close relative. Gibson left
behind three children: Kristen, 17, John, 14, and Daniel, 12.
</P>
<P>
   In the office, Gibson was best known for his soaring spirits and
his sense of playfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take the guy out of Boston, but you can't take Boston
out of the guy,'' said Rudy. ``He frequently asked for the local
papers. He always liked to talk about UMass basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson had tried to join the Boston Police department, could not
secure a position, and came to Washington to work on Capitol Hill.
He started as an officer, rising through the ranks to that of the
Diplomatic Protection Service, which is part of the US Capitol
Police. For the last three and a half years, he has been assigned
to DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, he followed DeLay across the Hill and the city. When
DeLay worked in his suite of offices in the Capitol, Gibson sat at
a desk just a few feet from the door. At the time of Friday's
shootout, DeLay was in a back office about 40 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been with me for several years and I consider him a
member of my staff, my family,'' DeLay said in a statement. ``John
gave his life to protect me and the members of my staff. There is
no doubt that if John had not acted quickly and with great bravery
as he did, others would have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot say enough about John or the work he did,'' DeLay
said. ``I cannot express the depth of my sorrow for this loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley, shaken, said Gibson had died the way he would have
wanted to, sacrificing himself for the sake of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fellow came in shooting and encountered John and they had
a little battle,'' Moakley said. ``From what we've been told, if it
hadn't been for John, a lot more people would have been killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley, whose office is about 20 feet from DeLay's in the
Capitol, said he left the building shortly before the shootings,
rushing to make a flight home to Boston. He learned of Gibson's
death when he touched down in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In DeLay's office, just moments after EMTs raced out the door
with Gibson and Weston on stretchers, the staff bowed their heads
in prayer for the man they believed had saved them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ann Scales of the Globe staff also contributed to this report
from Washington. Adrian Walker reported from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
