<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANT SIGN FAILS STATION'S TASTE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The battle line between old Grand Central and new
Grand Central was drawn shortly after dawn Friday. It was 12 feet
long.
</P>
<P>
   About 5:30 a.m., a contractor for the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, which runs Grand Central Terminal,
unbolted a 12-foot-long, 1970s-style, multicolored, illuminated
sign for the Oyster Bar, covered it in bubble wrap and returned it
to the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, a gleaming metal beaux-arts light fixture was
in its place.
</P>
<P>
   The Oyster Bar installed the sign two weeks ago, hanging it from
the tiled ceiling of the vaulted public space outside its entrance
on the lower level of the terminal. A similar sign had hung in the
same spot from 1974 until June 1997, when the restaurant and
surrounding areas were damaged by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's removal of the sign is a signal to other commercial
tenants that the authority intends to enforce aesthetic standards.
Under a $196 million renovation that is nearing completion, the
architectural features of the beaux-arts landmark terminal are
re-emerging after being eclipsed for decades by visual clutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment we bend the rules for one tenant, we've got 90
other tenants right behind,'' said Forrest Taylor, deputy executive
director for operations and chief of staff of the MTA. ``Once that
floodgate opens, you're on your way back to a hodgepodge.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Brody, the owner of the Oyster Bar, said the sign was
necessary because of the restaurant's deeply recessed entrance.
Both new and old signs were the work of Rudolph de Harak, a
well-known designer, and they featured the word ``Oyster'' in
angular letters of bright primary colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how people are going to find us, except our old
customers,'' Brody said. ``Since something was hanging there for 24
years, it didn't occur to us that it was hanging without permission
for that whole period and would need new permission now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's essential,'' Brody said. ``We'd like to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign was in place when the interior of the terminal was
given landmark status in 1980 and could theoretically have remained
forever _ had it been untouched. But once the sign was destroyed,
permission to recreate it was required from the Landmarks
Preservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sign was installed without a permit,'' said Jennifer Raab,
the chairwoman of the commission. ``In our opinion, it was
inappropriate. And we are happy that the MTA had it removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially nameless, the vaulted space outside the restaurant is
known as a ``whispering gallery.'' Unusual acoustics permit two
people standing at opposite corners and facing the wall to hear
each another speaking softly across a distance of 40 feet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
