<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIMPING STRAWBERRY USES HOMER TROT, TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre does not often ask Darryl Strawberry how
his left knee feels, and Strawberry probably would never tell his
manager if what he's feeling in his joint is pain or weakness or
both. Don't ask, don't tell. Ignore the worsening limp, watch the
ball fly off his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry smashed his 14th and 15th home runs Friday night,
propelling the Yankees' to a 5-4 victory over the Chicago White
Sox. The Yankees have won four consecutive games, running their
record to 72-25, which matches the second-best 97-game record in
the 20th century. The 1902 Pittsburgh Pirates won 73 of their first
97 games.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte pitched seven innings, allowing eight hits, four
runs (two earned), two walks, and struck out six, to improve his
record to 13-6. Mariano Rivera pitched the ninth inning for his
26th save.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry probably wouldn't have batted in the bottom of the
sixth inning had Tim Raines not strained a groin earlier in the
game. With Chad Curtis at first base and two out in the sixth,
Strawberry was due to bat with the Yankees trailing, 4-3, having
already hit a home run off John Snyder earlier in the game. Jerry
Manuel, the Chicago manager, charged out of the dugout and called
for reliever Bryan Ward, a left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry almost never faces left-handers in late-inning
situations, and under normal circumstances, Curtis would have been
available to pinch-hit for Strawberry. But Curtis had replaced
Raines in the fifth inning, leaving Torre with few viable options
on his bench. So Strawberry hit against Ward, whose elaborate
sideburns make him seem more suited to the 1860s than 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry got ahead in the count two balls and no strikes,
before the count ran to 3-2. Ward, throwing with a three-quarter
motion, fired a fastball to the outside corner. Strawberry's
contact was perfect; through the lens of the center field camera,
it appeared he had hit a line drive single over second base, the
ball's trajectory low. But this line drive kept going and going,
beyond the leap and reach of the Mike Cameron, Chicago's center
fielder, beyond the center field wall, 422 feet away. Members of
the crowd rose to their feet, as Strawberry shuffled around the
bases, with the Yankees swiftly and suddenly in the lead again.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis waited for Strawberry at the plate, pointing a finger at
his 6-foot-6 teammate, and Strawberry paused for a moment before
wading into a dugout of happy teammates. Even before his head
disappeared from sight, a rolling cry began in the crowd: They
wanted to honor Strawberry one more time, and he obliged them,
stepping out and waving his left hand. He is 36 now, and after
being left for dead last year, in the baseball sense, he has far
exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, however, it is his home run trot that provides
evidence that Strawberry is ailing, that his surgically repaired
left knee is bothering him. Hitting against Snyder in the fourth
inning, Strawberry reached out to hit a changeup, driving the pitch
with most of his weight shifted onto his right leg, the ball
landing in the lower deck of the right field stands.
</P>
<P>
   As Strawberry moved toward first base, he stepped mechanically,
awkwardly, limping heavily. He steadied as he rounded first, the
limp hidden, but it was there again as he crossed home plate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Strawberry has been playing like this for more than two weeks
now, the spring training gracefulness gone. On July 14, Torre
summoned Strawberry and asked him about his knee, and Strawberry
admitted it felt weakened at times, and Torre considered placing
Strawberry on the disabled list. But the team trainers assured
Torre that playing cannot worsen Strawberry's knee; time seems to
be doing that on its own. There doesn't seem to be much chance of
the knee improving, either.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said earlier this week that there is no way he could play
Strawberry in left field, given his current condition. Rather, the
manager inserts him in the lineup as a designated hitter and will
continue to do this, hoping Strawberry's knee will hold up.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in August, the Yankees believe Chili Davis will be back
and ready to serve as the designated hitter, and Torre is committed
to playing Davis on a regular basis. If Strawberry cannot play left
field, the Yankees' leading home run hitter will be left out.
</P>
<P>
   But he and Torre don't worry about that now. Torre doesn't ask,
Strawberry doesn't tell. Ignore the limp. Watch the ball fly, so
long as Strawberry lasts.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Drew Henson is going to play football at the University of
Michigan, and there is the chance, as a top rated quarterback, that
he could move on to the National Football League. Despite all that,
the Yankees signed the infielder Friday to a $2 million signing
bonus, the most money ever given to a third-round draft pick.
Henson's obligation to the Yankees is only to play in the summer,
between spring and fall training camps with the Wolverines. He can
walk away from baseball after finishing college and keep the
Yankees' money, no strings attached, making him a significant risk
for the Yankees. Henson, a 6-foot-2 inch, 220-pound third baseman,
worked out with the Yankees' major-league team in Tampa July 9 and
met with George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, the
next day. According to a person involved in the negotiations, the
Yankees offered Henson $1 million, and when he rejected that, they
doubled their offer, at Steinbrenner's prodding. Henson, who
reported to the Gulf Coast League Friday and played in his first
game, will receive the bonus over a five-year period. ... David
Wells was supposed to start Saturday, but after suffering a
recurrence of gout in inside part of his right foot, Wells is
scheduled to start Sunday, instead, and Hideki Irabu will start
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
