<SLUG> BC-SOC-SANCHEZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S SANCHEZ SOLD TO MEXICAN CLUB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. -- Wellington Sanchez, who joined the Los
Angeles Galaxy to great fanfare back in April, saw his stint with
Major League Soccer brought to an end Friday, sold to Mexico's
Morelia in a deal that didn't particularly bother anyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecuadoran midfielder, acquired from New York/New Jersey in
exchange for Eduardo Hurtado, had seen limited success in L.A., and
his departure does little to weaken what might be MLS's best
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   It was an economic move made by the league, which won't discuss
economics, one geared to recoup the investment made to sign the
overpriced Sanchez in the spring. He departs for Morelia
immediately and will miss the Galaxy's showdown tonight at the Rose
Bowl with Eastern Conference leader D.C. United (17-5, 41 points).
</P>
<P>
   The move leaves the Galaxy (16-4, 46) with an open foreigner
slot, one that General Manager Danny Villanueva acknowledged could
be used should Juergen Klinsmann decide to play in MLS. Villanueva
said his desire for the German striker ``has not wavered one bit,''
that he ``wants him in L.A.'' and that the Galaxy has made that
clear to the league.
</P>
<P>
   More likely is defensive aid; the Galaxy has asked MLS to
inquire about two defenders, both from the Americas, Villanueva
said; MLS Deputy Commissioner Sunil Gulati said it was possible the
Galaxy would not receive an additional player this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Klinsmann is a realistic option because we have
so many players up front,'' Coach Octavio Zambrano said. ``Before
Carlos (Hermosillo's acquisition), he was a great option, but with
Carlos here, I don't think there's something there. ... The
position we've got to be looking for is in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinsmann hasn't determined what path he'll next follow, and
Gulati said the earliest he'd join an MLS team was next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez played in 11 of 18 games after joining the Galaxy,
starting in nine and scoring a goal and four assists, but he
struggled with the speed and physical play of the American game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just beginning to show what he could do,'' said
Zambrano. ``For a kid 23 years old, who had never been out of
Ecuador, he had a tough time (but) was just starting to feel at
ease, starting to show his true value.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva said the Galaxy wasn't disappointed in Sanchez's
production, that he ``did as much as he could do in the time he was
here. ... It's an interesting situation, really. He's usually the
playmaker on whatever squad he plays for, but we already had a
mainstay in Mauricio Cienfuegos. Since day one we asked him to play
a position supporting Mauricio, and it was foreign to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was a luxury in the Galaxy's deep midfield, and his
departure should provide additional playing time for rookie Clint
Mathis. The most likely foursome is Cienfuegos, Cobi Jones, Martin
Machon and Danny Pena, with Mathis, Daniel Hernandez and
wing-defender Ezra Hendrickson providing Zambrano more options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
