<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN KILLS TWO IN CAPITOL SHOOTING SPREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER   AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two police officers were killed and a woman
seriously wounded Friday when a lone gunman opened fire in the US
Capitol, as scores of terrified tourists scrambled for cover.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, identified as Russell E. Weston, 42, of Missoula,
Mont., was shot three times and arrested after ``he tried to blast
his way into the Capitol,'' as one congressman described the event,
in a seemingly senseless midafternoon attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service had listed Weston as a ``low-level'' threat
to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the slain officers likely saved lives with their
swift response after the suspect, brandishing a .38 caliber
handgun, broke past guards at an entrance to the Capitol to the
horror of onlookers, including many children.
</P>
<P>
   As authorities searched for a motive for the assault, the
tragedy struck many in Washington like a death in the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Capitol is the people's house, a place where visitors and
workers should not have to fear violence,'' Clinton said. ``Every
American appreciates the bravery of the Capitol police that
prevented further injury through their courageous actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident marked the worst violence in the Capitol since five
lawmakers were shot in the House chamber by Puerto Rican
nationalists in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Killed were Officer Jacob ``J.J.'' Chestnut of Fort Washington,
Md., an 18-year veteran of the US Capitol Police, and Special Agent
John Gibson, a Waltham, Mass. native who had served eight years on
the force. Both men leave three children, who were at their sides
in separate Washington hospitals when they were declared dead soon
after the gun battle erupted at about 3:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A tourist, Angela Dickerson, 24, was shot in the head and
shoulder and was listed in serious condition at a Washington
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Weston is expected to survive his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Weston was seen Thursday at his family's home in Valymeyer,
Ill., the Miami Herald reported on its Web site Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that Weston, who believed the government
had planted mines on his property in Montana, argued with his
father, Russell E. Weston Sr., after he used his father's shotgun
to kill more than a dozen cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shot a bunch of cats and I made him get out. I got mad,
told him, `You gonna have to leave,''' said the man who identified
himself as Weston's father, according to the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   The paper said Weston drifted between his family home and a
half-acre plot in Montana that he used to mine gold.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, authorities said Weston began the shooting spree
after walking several blocks to the Capitol from a vehicle that was
stocked with a large amount of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the gunman burst into the Capitol through the
``document door,'' an entrance on the building's east side that is
not far from the rotunda where leaders such as President John F.
Kennedy have lain in state.
</P>
<P>
   It was about 3:40 p.m., as many House and Senate members were
heading home for the weekend and hundreds of tourists were viewing
the halls where laws are made.
</P>
<P>
   The chronology of the violence is sketchy. But authorities said
the assailant shot Chestnut in the head after darting around a
metal detector at an entrace near a crowded souvenir stand. They
said the suspect fired immediately after Chestnut asked him to go
through the metal detector before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all ducked,'' said Justin Brown, who works at the souvenir
stand. ``When I looked up, I saw the officer was down.''
</P>
<P>
   As the gunman charged onward, Ronald Beamish, 69, a visitor from
Gloucester, England, tended to the stricken Chestnut, cradling him
on the cold floor. ``He was trying to talk,'' Beamish said. ``His
lips moved. ... He was barely alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, ``You'll be all right, you'll be all right,'' said
Beamish, whose khaki pants were stained with blood as he recounted
the incident on the Capitol lawn. ``But there was nothing I could
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspect charged into the Crypt, a circular room with stately
pillars and walls adorned with historical displays. There, he
turned left toward the House side of the Capitol and down a hallway
where the office of Representative Tom DeLay of Texas, the House
majority whip, is located.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, a member of DeLay's personal security detail, was
outside DeLay's office. Although it was not clear how or where
Dickerson was wounded, witnesses said Gibson and the suspect were
struck in a hail of bullets outside DeLay's office. Gibson was shot
several times.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses said the suspect was mostly expressionless and
said nothing they could hear throughout the episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just boom, boom, boom, and people yelling, `Take cover,
take cover!''' said Diane Markley, who was in the Crypt while
touring the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trapped, with nowhere to run,'' said Catherine
Whinery, of Gorham, Maine, who was with Markley and 10 other
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   As the drama unfolded, many tourists were directed into
restrooms by security officers, who locked them in until the threat
had passed. Others were rushed out of the building. Lawmakers and
their staffs were cautioned to lock themselves in their offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from walking through this historic place, feeling
patriotic, to feeling just stunned,'' Markley said. ``Why would
some nut do this?''
</P>
<P>
   No evidence surfaced that the suspect had targeted DeLay or his
staff. But the proximity of the bloody encounter and Gibson's final
stand deeply affected DeLay and his aides, as it did many other
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers who were killed _ and those who apprehended the
gunman _ are true heroes of democracy and every American owes them
a deep debt of gratitude,'' said House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour before the tragedy, the House had been roiled
in a rancorous, partisan debate over health care. But in the hours
afterward, many returned tearfully to the Capitol to mourn the
slain officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``John gave his life to protect me and the members of my
staff,'' DeLay said. ``There is no doubt that if John had not acted
quickly and with great bravery as he did, others would have been
killed. I cannot express the depth of my sorrow for this loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's wife, Lynn, is the daughter of Robert Moakley, the
brother of Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a South Boston
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bill Frist, a Tennessee Republican and heart surgeon,
performed CPR on Gibson and rode with him to Washington's D.C.
General Hospital. He also treated Chestnut and helped carry him to
an anbulance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really just focused on keeping their hearts and lungs
moving,'' said Frist, a graduate of Harvard Medical School. He
called the shootings ``a very serious catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, ``Whoever kills or attempts to kill an
officer or employee of the United States while such officer is
engaged in ... his official duties'' faces the punishment of
``death or imprisonment for life.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the official word of the officers' death was made
public, flags throughout the nation's capital were lowered to half
staff.
</P>
<P>
   A federal law enforcement official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the alleged gunman was listed in the Secret Service
computer database as a potential threat to the president because of
an incident that occured more than two years ago. He declined to
elaborate on that incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Service has had contact with him,'' the official
said. ``If anyone is in the system, it is because of a threat or a
comment or an unusual statement. But there hasn't been any contact
with him in more than two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers said they expected the House and Senate to
investigate security procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises serious concerns,'' said Representative Elijah
Cummings, a Maryland Democrat. ``It's a reminder of what kind of
world we're living in today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ann Scales, Brian McGrory and Michael Kranish of the Globe
staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
