u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VAUGHN-BOS &LR;      07-24 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGER FEELS HE'S FINISHED WITH RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three months before he will have the right to walk away
of his own volition as a free agent, Mo Vaughn all but declared
that his career with the Red Sox is over.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Steve Burton of WBZ-TV (Channel 4) whether he has seen
his last days in Boston, Vaughn said Friday:
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I think I have. And it's a shame to say, but I think
I have. I think I have for the wrong reasons, but sometimes, you
know, things don't go the way you want to go, either.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, general manager Dan Duquette said Friday
night, the team is prepared to move on. But Duquette added it was
``doubtful'' the club would attempt to deal Vaughn before next
Friday's trading deadline. But if Vaughn leaves as a free agent,
Duquette said, the money the club would have spent to re-sign him
will be used to sign other productive hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Roger) Clemens left, and it took a while to replace him, but
we did with Pedro Martinez,'' said Duquette, who took the unusual
step of appearing in the middle of the team's TV broadcast Friday
night to answer questions about Vaughn's situation. ``If (Vaughn)
doesn't want to stay here, the Red Sox organization is prepared to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette acknowledged, as he has in the past, that the team
asked Vaughn to submit to an alcohol evaluation after he was
charged with drunken driving last January in connection with an
accident on Interstate 95, charges of which Vaughn was later
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   But Duquette denied claims made by Vaughn Friday that the team
has had him followed by private investigators, or that they ever
raised the issue of drug use with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not personal,'' Duquette said. ``We made several
efforts to re-sign him. He's looking for more money. There isn't
anything personal about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To accuse the organization of (using) a private investigator?
No one in the organization has ever considered that. And an
insinuation of drugs? We've never done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's regrettable he has seen a need, that he feels compelled
to discuss his contract at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, asked Friday about published comments that he would
prefer to play for the Toronto Blue Jays over returning to the Red
Sox next season, had said, ``What would you do if you played for an
organization that tried to get you to take an alcoholic evaluation?
What would you do if they had a private investigator following you
around? What would you do if they brought up the issue of
narcotics? That's not my style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got these kids to deal with,'' added Vaughn, referring to
his status as a community role model. ``It's not about the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, there's many, many things that go along with this
contract situation besides just the dollar amount. There's a lot of
bad blood, and that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that bad blood spilled into the stands, where a sellout
crowd in Fenway Park greeted Vaughn with the loudest booing he has
heard in his six years with the team. The atmosphere was not
improved by the 10-6 beating inflicted on the Red Sox by the Blue
Jays, Vaughn's self-identified team of choice for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn expanded on his comments in a pregame interview with
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you play if there had been people talking about
narcotics use and, you know, affiliations with crack houses and all
different types of things?'' he said. ``Would you play under those
circumstances? If it were for $25 million a year?''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Vaughn said he was on the verge of signing a
three-year deal with the team worth close to $30 million, but talks
broke off when the Red Sox signed newcomer Martinez to a six-year,
$75 million deal. Negotiations took an ugly turn after the drunken
driving charges.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox asked him to submit to an alcohol evaluation as
a condition of renewing negotiations, he angrily rejected the
proposal. The club reacted by offering him just a two-year deal in
spring training, which was immediately turned down.
</P>
<P>
   At the All-Star Game in Denver, Duquette made another offer,
this one for four years and $37 million.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's agents had no comment Friday night, but sources
familiar with the year-long negotiations said that at no time did
the Red Sox raise the issue of drugs with Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, who talked to reporters before the TV interview, shook
his head when asked if he would trade Vaughn before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams responded tersely to questions about
Vaughn's status. ``Mo's a professional,'' Williams said. ``He'll go
play and he'll try to win a game tonight. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Vaughn's teammates declined comment on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he didn't say anything,'' said veteran reliever Jim
Corsi. ``Don't even talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's just throwing the bait up there,'' said reliever
Dennis Eckersley. ``But it doesn't matter one way or the other to
me. He's here to win, like all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who Friday morning gave a $150,000 grant to the Mo
Vaughn Youth Development in Boston, said at that time it was only
speculation whether he would leave Boston after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn will have 15 days after the season to file for free
agency. The Sox then would have about another month to negotiate
with him before losing that right. The Clemens negotiations went
down to the December deadline before the righthander announced he
had signed with the Blue Jays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
