<HEADLINE>
PATAKI AND GIULIANI START SPREADING THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.H.)  (jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In back-to-back presentations brimming with unspoken
rivalry and national ambition, New York Gov. George Pataki and New
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani went before an audience of
national Republican leaders Friday and sought to claim credit for
the recent rise in New York's fortunes, which each man would like
to ride to higher office.
</P>
<P>
   The paths of the two never crossed at Manhattan's Plaza Hotel
and, as is fitting at such events, neither directly discussed his
own ambitions _ or, for that matter, each other.
</P>
<P>
   But their influential audience _ members of the Republican
National Committee, in town for a summer meeting _ clearly
appreciated the preliminary face-off between two politicians who
are less than friends and whose national ambitions seem to be in
conflict as they seek to lay claim to the same governmental legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The committee members clapped and chuckled as Pataki, sounding
as if he were speaking at the Iowa State Fair, described the
decline in crime in New York and boasted, ``Our approach works for
the people of this city, this state, and will work for the people
of America as well.''
</P>
<P>
   And they murmured in interest as Giuliani advised the party to
embrace a Republican version of Bill Clinton's strategy of 1992 by
agreeing that the main interest in 2000 is electing a Republican to
the White House, even if it means sacrificing certain ideological
beliefs to produce a candidate who can win.
</P>
<P>
   That strategic framework would be of particular benefit to
Giuliani, considered part of his party's moderate wing, much like
Clinton in his party.
</P>
<P>
   Still, great skepticism remains among Republicans that either
New Yorker, Giuliani in particular, could win significant support
among conservative primary voters. Realistically, several
Republicans said, their best hope is that they would be considered
in 2000 as vice-presidential prospects to run with a more
conservative presidential nominee from another part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken competition provided an entertaining backdrop for
the annual session. ``This was so clearly an
each-guy-trying-to-outdo-the-other-guy thing,'' said Thomas Rath, a
national committee member from New Hampshire. ``It was just great
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Giuliani and Pataki crossed political paths was at
the New York Republican Convention in June. That day was devoted to
nominating Pataki to a second term, but Giuliani, with a dramatic
speech intended to restore his uneasy relations with the party,
nearly overshadowed the governor, to the annoyance of Pataki's
allies.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, before a more significant audience of national
leaders, it was Pataki who came out ahead, several committee
members said. The governor, who is not known for his speaking
abilities, gave a spirited speech peppered with statistics, as he
held up his own record in New York _ reducing crime, welfare rolls
and taxes _ as a validation of Republican policies. He earned a
loud, prolonged standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a Republican Party are very different than the
Democratic Party,'' he said. ``We believe in people; they believe
in government. We believe in responsibility; they believe in
dependence. We believe in opportunity; they believe in
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani used his speech to hail the condition of the city and
present his record as a tribute to the success of Republican
policies, a familiar refrain during his national travels. But he
went on to offer political advice to Republicans that he said was
intended to assure the party's return to power in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani noted approvingly how Clinton, in 1992, maneuvered the
Democratic Party to the center on several issues, a
primary-election strategy that produced a strong challenge to Bush.
The Democrats, Giuliani said, decided that ``it would be better to
have a Democrat in the White House than to have George Bush
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``And they stuck together as a party and they
accomplished that and allowed Bill Clinton to make a move to the
middle, which he later rejected after he became president, in order
to get elected president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who supports abortion rights and gay rights, declined
to give examples of issues that Republicans might need to shelve to
avoid damaging primary fights. He refused even to comment on the
observation by many Republicans that the party would not nominate a
candidate who supports abortion rights for national office. ``I
don't think that should be the question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several delegates said they found a measure of self-protection
in Giuliani's remarks. Tim Lambert, a committee member from Texas,
suggested that the mayor was looking for a way to ensure that
Republicans overlook that Giuliani's views are ``far outside the
Republican mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   The sparring between the mayor and governor continued into the
evening. At Gracie Mansion, the mayor's residence, Giuliani treated
the Republicans to an extravagant three-course supper served by
waiters in white gloves under an air-conditioned tent overlooking
the East River. Pataki's aides said he was not invited to the
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment included a videotape selling New York as a
place for the Republican National Convention in 2000. Giuliani was
a constant presence on the tape. It included one scene in which he
was reading to schoolchildren, a snippet recognizable to anyone who
had seen his television ads in his re-election campaign last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
