<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-SHOPS-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS SPAR OVER DETAILS OF LAW CURBING SEX SHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It came down to a battle over T-shirts and bikinis,
how to measure 500 feet, and the difference between ``Lady
Chatterley's Lover'' and a magazine like Hustler.
</P>
<P>
   These unusual issues were at the center of the latest skirmish
between lawyers for sex shops and the administration of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani over just how city officials intend to enforce the
new zoning law against X-rated businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, lawyers for both sides told Judge Miriam Goldman
Cedarbaum at a hearing in U.S. District Court in Manhattan that
they had resolved one dispute, over whether the law was too vague.
</P>
<P>
   The city told the judge that in recent days it had issued a
series of new guidelines for building inspectors on such matters as
how to measure the distance between a strip club and a church and
what proportion of videos on a store shelf could be sexually
explicit.
</P>
<P>
   But they continued to fight behind the scenes, in letters and
phone calls, about whether the city should give sex shops notice
before they are shut down. That dispute is still simmering.
</P>
<P>
   All this occurred as the U. S. Supreme Court failed to announce
Friday whether it would grant the sex shops a stay they have sought
against enforcement of the law. Lawyers said they now expect a
ruling on Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Giuliani seems to be getting what he wants. With
uncertainty about how the Supreme Court will act and when the city
will move aggressively to enforce the law, a lawyer for the shops,
Herald Price Fahringer, said he was advising his clients to bring
their shops into compliance immediately, to avoid shutdowns as well
as criminal misdemeanor charges.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, the city may seek to padlock shops and
prosecute their owners under a provision that includes a jail term
of up to 90 days and a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor mentioned the criminal provision briefly last week,
but city officials have refused to provide any details of their
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Fahringer said the situation was particularly urgent for his
clients, who are owners of 107 sexually oriented businesses
affected by the law, in light of Giuliani's suggestion last Sunday
that merely covering up nude dancers with bikinis would not be not
enough to comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Fahringer said that the mayor's comments only reinforced his
view that the law was too ambiguous to be enforced fairly, leading
him to ask Cedarbaum for another stay on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He asserted in court papers filed on Wednesday that the law
violates the First Amendment because it is too vague, and does not
provide enough guidance to owners on how they can come into
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   But the city told Cedarbaum in papers filed on Thursday that the
shops would be ``easily able to tell'' whether their conduct is
illegal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To give further guidance, the city told the judge that the
Department of Buildings had issued new guidelines this week on how
to comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   One notice issued this week, for example, says the shops must
reduce their sexually oriented books or videos to less than 40
percent of their stock and floor area. Although a 40-60 ratio has
been discussed before, Fahringer said Friday that this was the
first time city lawyers had said explicitly that it was to be
considered part of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Another notice offers different factors that a building
inspector must consider in determining whether a topless theater or
club is showing sexually oriented entertainment on a ``regular''
basis, a legal standard contained in the law.
</P>
<P>
   A third notice offers instructions about how to measure the
500-foot distance the law requires to separate sex shops from each
other, as well as from places of worship or schools. The
measurement should be taken from the center line of the door
considered the ``principal entrance'' of the business, the notice
says.
</P>
<P>
   Fahringer told Cedarbaum Friday that he was satisfied with the
city's guidelines, and withdrew his request for the stay.
</P>
<P>
   In the one matter over which both sides clashed out of court,
Fahringer said that he wrote to city lawyers earlier this week,
asking that they inform him before they went to court to enforce
the law against any of his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Taussig, a senior lawyer in the Corporation Counsel's
office, said Friday by phone that he told Fahringer that he did not
have to inform him of such action, and would not. Under the law,
Taussig said, the city may go to a judge unilaterally if it
believes it has enough evidence to seek an order forcing a store to
close.
</P>
<P>
   Fahringer said he sent a copy of his letter to judges in all
five boroughs in hopes that if the city appears before them, they
will be sympathetic to his concerns about notice. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
