<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COMMENTARY-BOS &LR;      07-24 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENTARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMINENT PARTING POOR REFLECTION ON FRANCHISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Next year is already impossible. He'll be far from
Boston by then. The only No. 42 we'll see in Fenway Park on July
25, 1999, is the one that now hovers above right field, a
blue-and-white tribute to Jackie Robinson. No, Mo Vaughn will not
call this park home next year. He may not even make it to next
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The only glimmer in the bizarre tale of Red Sox vs. Mo is that
we will never have to read about another contract squabble between
Vaughn and Dan Duquette-John Harrington. There will be no more
squabbles because there will be no more offers. This relationship
is finished. That alone makes Friday night one of the most somber
in Sox history. Unfortunately, there are others.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the first-inning boos during the 10-6 loss to the
Blue Jays. You knew they were going to cling to Vaughn as soon as
he approached the batter's box. And forget about Vaughn waving at a
Juan Guzman sinker, simultaneously striking out and raising the
anger of 33,159 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox should be concerned that their best player stood in a
hallway, teary-eyed, and told Steve Burton, of WBZ-TV (Channel 4)
that the club has accused him of associating with crack dealers;
that he feels he is being followed by private investigators hired
by the team; that he is still angered by management's request that
he take alcohol evaluation tests; and, yes, that he told a reporter
from Toronto that he wants to play there next season.
</P>
<P>
   And you. You should be terrified that Duquette, in the middle of
a playoff run, said the Sox are prepared to go on without their
best power hitter. He said the team can make good use of the draft
picks that will come if Vaughn walks away. He said the team has
done its research on possible trades (the deadline is next Friday).
He also remarked, sarcastically, that $10 million can get you a
pretty good hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Dan. You're right. Ten million dollars can get you a good
hitter. But since when is build-and-destroy the sanest route to
general managing? The Sox like to tell you they got Pedro Martinez
when they lost Roger Clemens. I say: Why did it have to be
either/or? Wouldn't both of them be nice? Championship teams don't
``replace'' players to get better; they add to the players they
already have. But that's the least of the problems on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   I have always maintained that Duquette would be haunted by his
quote _ ``The Red Sox are back in business'' _ after Martinez's
signing. What kind of business is this? Three years ago, Vaughn was
the model of what a professional athlete is supposed to be. After
he won the American League's Most Valuable Player Award, the team
held a press conference at Vaughn's youth center. How many pro
athletes spend time on Blue Hill Avenue, in Boston's predominantly
black Roxbury neighborhood, talking with children? But now he
suddenly has problems with alcohol and is obsessed with money?
That's odd.
</P>
<P>
   It will not surprise me if Vaughn announces at his Toronto press
conference that he has signed a four-year contract worth $37
million, the same numbers the Sox offered him earlier this month.
In Boston, he wanted respect before he wanted market value. The Sox
have given him neither. Because of this, they have put themselves
in a dangerous position: They will forever be known as the
organization that has a problem with black players.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn came to town in 1991 and said he was willing to face a
city with a tough racial reputation and an organization plagued by
racial warts. There was the rejection of Robinson in 1945. There
were no black players here until 1959 as the Sox became the last
team in the majors to integrate. There were negative comments from
Reggie Smith and Tommy Harper. Only one black player early in '91
(Ellis Burks). And now a man who was willing to say he loved Boston
is run out of town, feeling his employers think he associates with
crack dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. Now ask yourself: If you were a black major
leaguer, would you come to Boston after seeing what happened to
Vaughn? Not only wouldn't I do it, I would tell other players to
stay away, too. Thirty-seven million or one hundred thirty-seven
million; it wouldn't matter. Not many respectable people will sell
their souls for the right to be disrespected?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me ask you this,'' Vaughn said early Friday, ``what would
you do if they brought up the issue of narcotics? That's not my
style. I've got these kids to deal with (as far as his reputation).
It's not about the money.''
</P>
<P>
   For once, it's not about the money. And it's not completely
about race. Take all sentiment aside and ask yourself: How do you
feel about losing a hitter capable of batting .300-plus
(lefthanded) with 35 home runs and 125 RBIs?
</P>
<P>
   It's sad. Mo Vaughn will be gone soon, leaving two No. 42s as
Fenway memories. The Sox are back in business. And it's a sad day
in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
