<HEADER>
A2367 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-GUNMAN-NYT &LR;      07-24 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-GUNMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHOOTING SUSPECT: A LONER WITH A DEADLY GRUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mont.)  (See also CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-SCENE, CAPITOL-OFFICERS,
CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO) 
(hlw) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1993, the Mississippi River surged past its
levees and drowned Valmeyer, Ill., population 900, under 20 feet of
water. One of the people made homeless in the flood was Russell
Eugene Weston Jr., the 41-year-old suspect in Friday's killings in
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The town was lost. For three years, its people lived in an
emergency settlement, packed into trailers. Some of them derisively
called their temporary town Femaville, for the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, the government service that promised to help
them.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, a blue-eyed, blond-haired man who never settled down,
began drifting away, neighbors in Valmeyer said on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy relocated to Montana,'' said one, Denise Fisher, who
lived about a quarter-mile from where Weston and his parents had
their home. He left town in a 13-year-old Chevrolet pickup,
although he returned from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rusty was a loner; he didn't have many, if any, friends,''
said a neighbor from Valmeyer, who identified herself as Mrs. Henry
Rahe and said that she attended church with Weston's parents and
that the community was devastated by the shootings at the Capitol
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, months before the government finished building a new
Valmeyer, Weston was questioned by law-enforcement authorities in
Illinois and in Montana, where he owned a small plot of land where
he panned for gold, about having made threatening statements about
government officials, including President Clinton, federal
officials said on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Those statements included a variety of paranoid ramblings about
the power of the government, fantasies about the CIA and an
accusation that federal officials had planted land mines on his
Montana property, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The statements were strong enough to attract the attention of
the Secret Service, they said. Weston was questioned by the Secret
Service in April 1996, they said, and the agency's Presidential
Protective Detail has maintained a file on him ever since.
</P>
<P>
   That May, the Secret Service classified him as a probably
harmless but potentially dangerous man, law-enforcement officials
said on Friday night. The Secret Service made that assessment after
reviewing interviews with Weston conducted by local mental-health
authorities, they said.
</P>
<P>
   So Weston was filed away as one among thousands of Americans who
have delusions about the government, its power and its nature, they
said. If he ever showed up in Washington in any way that registered
officially, the Secret Service would take notice.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Weston left Valmeyer, heading east and carrying his
father's old .38-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson, government officials said
on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he drove to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``He parked off to one side, and he came through the Capitol,''
said Rep. Bill Thomas, a California Republican who heads the House
Oversight Committee, which oversees House security and works with
the Capitol Police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Weston went around the magnetometer,'' the metal detector,
Thomas said. ``There was an exchange of gunfire'' in which Officer
Jacob Chestnut was fatally shot.
</P>
<P>
   He approached ``a door that says, `Private. Do Not Enter,' a
door that goes to the back hallway of Majority Whip Tom DeLay's
office,'' Thomas said. Then he shot Officer John Gibson, also
fatally, and was shot in return, apparently four times. Sen. Bill
Frist of Tennessee, a heart surgeon, massaged his heart and pumped
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Not three hours later, as the sun was setting over the
Mississippi, a police car drove up to the Weston family home in
Valmeyer, near a set of railroad tracks with grain and coal cars
rumbling by.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Monroe County sheriff was talking with the father on the
front porch to break the news to him,'' Mrs. Fisher said. The
father, Russell Sr., is 66, and looked ``elderly,'' she said. ``He
had his head drooped, and walking toward the police he looked kind
of sad.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
