<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REALNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLING MICROSOFT TAKES TOLL ON STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Testifying against Microsoft Corp. can be costly. For Real
Networks Inc., the price seems to have been about $240 million, or
25 percent of its stock-market value, in two days.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the day before the chairman of Real Networks
appeared before the Senate Judiciary Committee, shares of the
company closed at $44.25. On Friday, they closed at $33.25, down
about 25 percent in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Glaser, the chairman of Real Networks, based in Seattle,
testified that a new Microsoft program crippled his company's
recent products. Real Networks is a leader in software used for
transmitting audio and video programming over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At the Senate hearing on Thursday, Glaser demonstrated how
Microsoft's new multimedia viewing software disabled his company's
technology. By the end of the day, Microsoft declared that the
problem was a bug in Real Networks' software instead of a nefarious
Microsoft ploy.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Glaser stood by his testimony and his software
demonstration at the Senate hearing. In a late-afternoon conference
call, he was joined by representatives of two smaller multimedia
companies, Xing and Digital Bitstreaming, who said they had similar
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was sticking to its guns as well. In its camp was a
specialist from PC magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised a broader industry issue,'' Glaser said. ``We've
been out front on this issue, and we've taken some arrows in the
last day or two. But hey, that's life in the big city.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
