<SLUG> BC-NJ-FAKE-TERRORIST-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WITH FAKE DYNAMITE SPREADS PANIC IN NEWARK BEFORE ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A man dressed partly in military fatigues carried
what appeared to be seven sticks of dynamite attached to a timer
into a downtown office building Friday morning, causing widespread
panic and confusion. Although the device turned out to be fake, it
was so realistic that it fooled police dogs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people were evacuated from the building at 18
Rector St., which houses several local and federal government
agencies, and from about 15 nearby buildings. There were no
injuries, but traffic in downtown Newark was tangled for several
hours as tense bomb squad technicians used a water cannon to break
the device apart and defuse it.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the seven red tubes marked ``dynamite'' turned out
to be filled with some other substance, possibly clay, Newark's
police director, Joseph Santiago, said. The man who carried it,
identified by the police as Gregory James, 43, of Irvington, N.J.,
was arrested and charged with possessing an explosive device,
making terroristic threats and other related crimes, Santiago said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's events began to unfold shortly before 11 a.m. when
James rode into downtown Newark on a public bus. He wore camouflage
pants and a matching cap, and carried two black shoulder bags,
witnesses told the police. He got off the bus at Market and Broad
Streets, Newark's busiest intersection, witnesses and the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   A man who had been riding on the bus with James and who, the
police said, might have known him learned of the bomb and,
believing it to be real, began to follow James, signaling for help
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   By chance, as James walked toward 18 Rector St., a police bomb
truck drove by. The man following James hailed the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a one-in-a-million chance,'' said Detective
William Tartis, a bomb squad expert who was in the truck. Moments
later, Tartis and other officers arrested James in the lobby of 18
Rector St.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After James was detained, the police evacuated the building,
diverted traffic and brought in police dogs. After sniffing the
device that James had been carrying, both dogs signaled to
investigators that they had detected explosives. The bomb squad
then used a water cannon to break the device apart.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago and other investigators said tests were being conducted
to determine the contents of the device.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they knew little about James other than that he had
served in the U. S.Marines and had been discharged in the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
