<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHERS GRUMBLE, BUT NOT FLOYD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You could still hear the groans and wails through
the eucalyptus and sycamores of Riviera Country Club during
Friday's second round of the U.S. Senior Open.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't because of wind whipping through the historic Pacific
Palisades course, but the result of another day of players trying
to cope with how the U.S. Golf Association set up this week's age
50-over national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Long rough, no-roll fairways, and hard, quickening greens
combined to produce a second straight day of dreadful scoring, with
just seven of 155 players shooting as low as par.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Morgan, a winner of two senior majors this year, called it a
``goofy'' setup that left players ``between a rock and a hard
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't land the ball short of the green and let it run up
because the fairways are so soft,'' Morgan said. ``And if you carry
it on to the green, the ball runs clear to the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibby Gilbert declared the setup ``unfair,'' saying he had never
seen rough so difficult and expressing surprise it hadn't resulted
in a run of injuries from trying to hit out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played 16 L.A. Opens at Riviera and one PGA
Championship,'' Gilbert said, ``but I've (begin ital)never(end
ital) played this course.''
</P>
<P>
   Against that prevailing attitude, midway leader Raymond Floyd
stood firm and in the distinct minority _ not just because he was
the only player under par, but because he (begin ital)approved(end
ital) of the difficult conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, if you put it in perspective, more golf tournaments
should have a little more of that philosophy,'' Floyd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more to this game than standing there and drilling a
driver and hitting the next shot and making a putt and going to the
next hole. There is a whole lot more to this game than that. I
think that has been lost through the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd especially likes that major tournaments demand the best of
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to separate those that are better,'' he said.
``It's not just the physical part of the game _ there is a lot of
the mental part that plays. And the U.S. Open tests that side to
the max.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd also likes the fact that he's in the lead on a tough
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tremendous edge for me,'' he said. ``If I can keep
playing solidly and keep the ball in the fairway and on the green,
I know nobody's going to go out there and light it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said he has thrived at Riviera because, in addition to
hitting good shots, he has played patiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't hit good shots, I don't care what kind of a game
plan you have, you can't play to it. But fortunately I've played
pretty close to my game plan, and that's why I've had success
through two rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, he said, shooting par equals success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all must remember that par is a fantastic score on each and
every hole in a U.S. Open. If you leave with a par you've done
well. You might be a little discouraged that you didn't make a
birdie, but par is a good score.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a stonemason chipping away on a block of granite, Floyd
found results starting to show near the end of his work both days.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied three of the last four holes Thursday, then two of
the last three Friday _ always with the same approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just patience and hitting a good shot and finally
making a putt somewhere,'' he said. ``I don't see that I played
those holes any differently... I could have made a lot of birdies
today that I didn't, but I didn't give in _ I just kept trying and
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently loving the conditions every step of the way.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
