<SLUG> BC-SHORT-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCOVERED SHORT POSITIONS ARE 3.7 PERCENT HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open positions of short sales on the Nasdaq market
rose 3.7 percent in the most recent month, the National Association
of Securities Dealers reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the month ended July 15, uncovered short positions totaled
2.17 billion shares, compared with 2.09 billion in the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
   In a short sale, an investor borrows shares from a brokerage
firm and sells them, hoping to buy them back at lower prices and
make a profit. If the shares rise in price, the short-seller faces
a loss. Uncovered short sales, or those with open positions, are
those shares that have been borrowed and sold but not yet covered
by repurchase.
</P>
<P>
   For the third month, Worldcom had the largest short position on
the Nasdaq and the largest increase in short positions. Short
positions in Worldcom totaled 137.2 million shares, up 20.2 million
shares. Worldcom is awaiting final government approval to acquire
MCI Communications.
</P>
<P>
   In acquisitions in which the buyer will exchange its stock for
the shares of the seller, as in the Worldcom-MCI deal, speculators
often buy shares in the target and sell short the stock of the
buyer. This guarantees them a profit if the deal is completed but
subjects them to a possible loss if it is not. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
