<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEP FOR METS COMES AT THE RIGHT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In the first game, a 32-year-old right-hander who had
not pitched in the major leagues in over a year tossed eight
shutout innings. In the second one, the Mets rallied for seven runs
in the final four innings to erase a pair of one-run deficits.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, the Mets had swept a doubleheader from the Chicago
Cubs at Wrigley Field, 5-0 and 7-3. And they had done so behind
Armando Reynoso's pitching and Brian McRae's hitting in the opener
and with an entire team effort in the second game, all of which
pulled the Mets to within one and one-half games of the Cubs in the
National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It far exceeded anything I could have possibly dreamed of,''
Bob Apodaca, the pitching coach, said after Reynoso's first-game
performance helped halt a five-game Chicago winning streak. ``Eight
shutout innings? Five hits? I couldn't fathom anything like that
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not long ago the same could have been said of the chances
that the Mets would be back in the thick of a playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, it seems, is the best day of the season for the Mets
(54-46), who have won six games in a row, including two
doubleheader sweeps on the road in the last three days. Two weeks
ago, the Mets seemed in danger of falling out of the postseason
chase. But after winning eight of their last 10 games, four of them
by shutout, the Mets are not only very much alive, they have a
chance to return to New York ahead in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are two more months to go. And no, this was not 1969,
when the Mets overtook the Cubs in September on their way to their
first playoff appearance. But Friday afternoon had all the feel _
and emotion _ of a pennant race, something many of the Mets players
later said they felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to that point,'' said Dennis Cook, who won a
World Series ring with the Florida Marlins last fall and who Friday
convinced Manager Bobby Valentine that he could pitch in both
games, before picking up the Game 2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Before 40,684 fans, the biggest crowd of the season at Wrigley,
there was Reynoso, in his first major-league start in 373 days,
nearly pitching a complete-game shutout in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   That the stakes were higher than usual was evident in the
reactions of the players.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley, who narrowly missed three homers on the day,
kicking the dirt after just missing first-game home run. Brian
McRae, who had four hits in all, running full-speed toward the ivy
in left center field to make a sensational catch against his old
team. Carlos Baerga clapping his hands and pumping his fist in the
second game after driving in two key runs apiece with two
right-handed swings. Chicago's Glenallen Hill styling and posturing
after hitting a game-tying homer onto Waveland Avenue in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Lenny Harris pumping his fist up the first-base
line after giving the Mets the lead for good with his run-scoring
single in the top of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   If anything demonstrated the difference between going good and
going bad, it was Hundley losing a ball in left in the first game
and then dropping one in left in the second _ and neither mistake
hurting the Mets. Even Mel Rojas, who had been buried in the
bullpen for nearly a month, contributed a scoreless eighth inning
in the second game with the Mets clinging to a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard it from me before,'' Valentine said. ``The worst
is yet to come. Tomorrow's our biggest game. However, this is a
very tough stretch. And I'm very, very proud that everyone came to
the ballpark ready to play. We played well. The guys played like it
was a big game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starting first and foremost with Reynoso. The Mets were hoping
for 100 pitches from their first-game starter. He gave them 108 _
and so much more.
</P>
<P>
   How could anyone have possibly expected such a performance from
someone whose last major-league start was last July 16? Reynoso had
been 6-1 with a 2.80 earned run average over his first 13 starts
with the Mets a year ago. But his arm troubles began when he took
the mound after a rain delay here on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso eventually underwent arthroscopic procedures on both his
elbow and shoulder. And then he came up with tightness in the elbow
in a spring training start in March.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Mets took their time easing Reynoso back to the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like a long time,'' Reynoso said with a little laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's rested,'' Valentine had joked before Friday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   And how. The Mets now have six viable candidates for five
starting slots. Afterward, Reynoso credited his breaking ball for
keeping the Cubs off balance. His biggest test came in the third,
when Sammy Sosa came to the plate with the bases loaded and two men
out. Sosa, who has 37 homers this season, has never hit a grand
slam. And after Reynoso retired him on a fielder's choice grounder
to short, the Mets' 4-0 lead was still intact.
</P>
<P>
   From there on, no Chicago runner made it past first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any better than that,'' Valentine said. ``He
made sure he was right before he came back. And he was definitely
right. He made adjustments, changed speeds. He as everything and
more that we could have hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, Bobby Jones picked up right where Reynoso
left off. But after Lance Johnson singled home Kevin Orie off Cook
with two out in the seventh, four batters after Hill's game-tying
home run, the Mets were down 3-2 one inning after they had rallied
for a 2-1 lead on Baerga's two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied right back in the top of the eighth on a
one-out double by Butch Huskey and Mike Piazza's game-tying single.
Three batters later, Harris drove Piazza home with what proved to
be the winning run. And then Baerga capped a three-run ninth with a
two-run single for his third and fourth runs batted in of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially on the road, when you get a lead and then give it
right back up, it's a tough thing to strike up the band again,''
Valentine said. ``But they did.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets are right back in the race.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Steve Phillips phoned John Franco's agent, Dan
Horwits, earlier this week, and the two are thought to have
discussed for the first time the parameters of a contract extension
for Franco, who is in the final season of a two-year deal that will
pay him a base salary of $2.6 million this year. Franco, 37, has 20
saves in 23 opportunities this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
