<HEADLINE>
JUREVICIUS IS A NO-SHOW AND FASSEL IS TROUBLED
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Acquiring a tall, physical wide receiver to boost
an anemic offense was a priority of the Giants during the off
season. It is the reason they used their second-round draft pick to
take 6-foot-5-inch, 230-pound Joe Jurevicius, a wide receiver from
Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Now they just need to get Jurevicius to come to practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants open training camp Saturday on the campus of the
State University of New York at Albany, but Jurevicius, who has not
agreed to a contract with the Giants, is not expected to work out
with the team. On Friday afternoon, Jurevicius failed to report for
the first meeting of players.
</P>
<P>
   Jurevicius' absence irritated Giants Coach Jim Fassel, who did
not have a contract holdout during his first camp as head coach
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed based on the circumstances,'' Fassel
said. ``We have put a proposal on the table and we have called his
agent and we've gotten no response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jurevicius needs to be here. He has a lot of things to learn.
He has good football instincts but he made mistakes in our
minicamps, too. This is the time when we can work on that and
incorporate him into our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurevicius' agent, Neil Cornrich, said that he would not address
any of the issues of his client's contract, including whether he
has returned the Giants' calls or whether he plans to talk to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe would like to be in camp,'' Cornrich said. ``We'll wait
and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have offered Jurevicius a four-year contract valued
at about $1.98 million. Tight end Rod Rutledge, drafted by the New
England Patriots just before Jurevicius, signed a four-year deal
worth $1.996 million. Jets defensive end Dorian Boose, taken right
after Jurevicius, received a four-year, $1.928 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Teams generally use the contract values of players selected
around a draft pick to slot their contract offers. Occasionally, as
in Jurevicius' case, players and agents resist such slotting.
</P>
<P>
   Jurevicius may not be the only player missing Saturday. Tackle
Toby Myles, the team's fifth-round pick, also has yet to come to
contract terms. That deal is reportedly close to being made final,
although Myles did not attend the players meeting Friday. There
were no other no-shows.
</P>
<P>
   Jurevicius' unresolved contract status _ and Fassel's annoyance
with it _ was the lone moment of acrimony during a day when
Albany-area officials gave the Giants a lavish welcome. This is the
third season the team has brought its training camp practices to
Albany and the first year of a new agreement that will have the
team training here until the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, who arrived in Albany last year a virtual unknown,
seemed to particularly enjoy returning to camp as the 1997 coach of
the year and as the coach of the defending National Football
Conference East champions. At the team's reception luncheon, he was
surrounded by well-wishers, autograph-seekers and the local news
media.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Fassel said the theme of his first speech to the team
would be about putting last season in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year is over and nobody is picking us to repeat as
champions,'' he said. ``We have to prove ourselves to people all
over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel added that he expected an improvement on last season's
10-5-1 record, despite a more difficult schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule is a great challenge,'' he said. ``But I won't be
satisfied if we don't have a better record.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
