<HEADLINE>
IRWIN SIZZLES ON, OFF COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A nine-stroke turnaround vaulted Hale Irwin from
oblivion to contention in the U.S. Senior Open on Friday. But even
though his performance placed Irwin's familiar name back on the
leaderboard, it did little to improve his demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   After refusing to speak to anyone following his unexpected 77 on
Thursday at Riviera Country Club, Irwin was only slightly more
talkative Friday and tried to restrict the topics he would address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to talk about today, not tomorrow or yesterday,''
Irwin said after shooting a 68 in the second round, the best
18-hole score posted during the Senior Open's first two days.
</P>
<P>
   Several questions later, Irwin was eventually asked about why he
disappeared so quietly after his opening-round 77 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did I say? I didn't want to talk about... yesterday,''
Irwin said sternfully. ``The reason being that it is a round I am
trying to forget. And I am going to speak to this only one time.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin then proceeded to break his rule by referring to
``yesterday'' nine different times while answering ensuing
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin moved into a tie for fifth place, about the position he
was expected to occupy as one of the pre-tournament favorites along
with Gil Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to pay attention to that,'' Irwin said. ``If we, the
players, get hung up in all the hype, then you might start
believing your clippings.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was U.S. Senior Open defending champion Graham
Marsh who labeled Irwin and Morgan as the pre-tournament favorites,
but who's keeping track?
</P>
<P>
   This is about as surly as it gets on the player-friendly seniors
tour. Irwin's cranky behavior made no difference on the course,
however, and that's where he has been looking like a genius lately.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has been the hottest player on the senior tour, winning
four tournaments and finishing no worse than fifth in any of the 13
events he has participated in this year.
</P>
<P>
   He demonstrated exactly why he was considered a pre-tournament
favorite during Friday's round, when he recorded three birdies and,
more impressively, avoided a single bogey. His 68 left him
three-over par through 36 holes, just five shots behind leader
Raymond Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great round and I needed it badly,'' Irwin said. ``I
didn't do anything last night. I left here and tried to forget
about my problems. Yesterday was just a bad day. My irons were not
real crisp and my putting was atrocious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really just a fairly solid round (Friday). And it was
not mistake-free. I did have some errors out there that fortunately
I was able to salvage the pars.'' &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
