<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MICKEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCK MICKEL, 72, EXECUTIVE WHO AIDED EXPANSION OF FLUOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Ga., N.C.)   (bl)  
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buck Mickel, who helped bring about the corporate marriage that
created the modern Fluor Corp. in 1977, died on July 23 at his home
in Greenville, S.C. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   A Fluor spokesman said that Mickel, who had seemed in good
health, had apparently died in his sleep. No cause of death has
been determined, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mickel was chairman of Daniel International Corp., a large
construction company based in Greenville, when Fluor became
interested in the company in 1977. At the time, Fluor was
principally a maker of industrial equipment for the petroleum
industry.
</P>
<P>
   When Fluor sought to acquire Daniel, Mickel held out through
polite negotiations until Fluor increased the price it was willing
to pay. He neither urged nor discouraged the deal, telling
reporters that shareholders should decide on their own but that a
majority of the Daniel board had decided to accept Fluor's offer.
</P>
<P>
   From that deal grew Fluor Daniel, the principal subsidiary of
today's Fluor Corp., an international engineering, construction and
diversified services company listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Mickel was appointed chairman of Fluor's engineering and
construction group in 1982 and was named vice chairman and
president of the parent company in 1984. He retired from his
executive positions in March 1987 but remained a director of the
company until early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Elberton, Ga., Mickel graduated from the Georgia
Institute of Technology in 1947 after serving in the military
during World War II. He also served for three years during the
Korean War as a first lieutenant in the Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   He began his professional career in 1948 at Daniel Construction
Co., advancing through several management positions. In 1965, he
was named president of the company after the death of its founder,
Charles E. Daniel. He was elected chairman of the board in 1974,
just three years before the Fluor deal.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Mickel was chairman and chief
executive of RSI Corp., a small company he operated from offices in
Greenville, and was a director of several corporations, including
Duke Power Co.
</P>
<P>
   He was a life trustee of Clemson University and Converse College
and chairman of the Daniel/Mickel Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Mickel is survived by his wife of 52 years, Minor Herndon
Mickel; two sons, Buck Alston Mickel and Charles Clark Mickel, and
a daughter, Minor Mickel Shaw, all of Greenville; and six
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
