<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 26, will move Saturday in the `a' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-MURDER-REVIEW _ There are sharp regional differences in
homicide, with the South having by far the highest murder rate,
almost double that of the Northeast, a divergence that has
persisted for as long as records have been kept, starting in the
19th century. By Fox Butterfield. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALISTS-REVIEW _ Businesses, feeling the pressure of
stepped-up financial reporting over the last decade, are becoming
bolder about attacking journalists, both publicly and with
lawsuits. And reporters and editors, thrust into the spotlight, are
forced to articulate ethical distinctions that may not be easy to
defend. By Felicity Barringer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-COUPS-REVIEW _ In the 12 months since the Thai baht fell
against the United States dollar and touched off currency
devaluations and a slump in every major East Asian country, at
least one of the region's stubborn old ghosts has been exorcised.
There have been no military coups. By Joseph Kahn. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM-REVIEW _ A quarter-century of shrinking market share and
periodic financial crises at GM have fed a popular image of the
auto maker as being a shadow of its former self. Yet GM remains the
world's largest company in sales and share of global economic
output, and is immense by any standard. By Keith Bradsher. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-CULTURE-REVIEW _ More and more these days, there is
talk about the cultural chasm between the military and the rest of
society, what most people consider the ``real world.'' Some people
want to narrow that divide, as though it is something new, and bad.
By David Stout. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ADVOCACY-GROUPS-REVIEW _ From both the left and right of the
political spectrum come dark assessments and dire warnings from
advocacy groups about the current racial, moral, financial or
social climate even as the country enjoys peace and prosperity and
is arguably less sexist, less racist, less dangerous, less polluted
and less regulated by government than it has been in decades _ and
perhaps, ever. By Steven A. Holmes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY-REVIEW _ For many years, Social Security cards
carried an admonition that they were to be used ``for Social
Security and tax purposes _ not for identification.'' That
assurance rings hollow today. Congress has authorized so many uses
of the nine-digit number, and Americans use it for so many
unauthorized purposes, that it has become the closest thing to a
national identifier. By Robert Pear. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-PRIVACY-REVIEW _ The Clinton administration, following a
1996 congressional mandate, is considering assigning every American
a health-care identification number that could be used to create a
giant electronic data base capable of tracking everyone's medical
records from cradle to grave. Suddenly, the public is up in arms
about medical privacy. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-DRUGS-TREATMENT-REVIEW _ Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's
pronouncement last week that New York City should abolish methadone
treatment for heroin addicts by the year 2000 drew fire from many
drug abuse experts. They insisted that methadone is the best tool
they have to help addicts reduce heroin use, stay out of jail and
get back to work. By Denise Grady. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-ENDOW-REVIEW _ For an agency that spends less than .01
percent of the federal budget, the National Endowment for the Arts
gets a lot of attention from Congress, particularly negative
attacks from conservatives. But last week the House of
Representatives overwhelmingly approved the agency's money for next
year. By Irvin Molotsky. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
</P>
</TEXT>
