<HEADER>
A2502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-UPDA     07-24 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-UPDATE-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Following is a list of stories related to the shooting
in the Capitol Building that are planned tonight for the New York
Times News Service report. Stories will move in ``w'' news file.
For more information, please call (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP (Washington) _ A gunman who had been
investigated by the Secret Service burst into the Capitol on Friday
afternoon and killed two police officers in a corridor shootout
that left a tourist and the gunman lying wounded as terrified
bystanders darted for cover. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (PHOTO AND GRAPHIC ADVISOR: a map and a diagram of the shooting
scene are being sent to NYT graphics clients. In addition, we call
your attention to a New York Times photo of a wounded victim
minutes after the shooting at the Capitol on Friday. Paul Hosfros
of the New York Times staff was the first photographer on the scene
and his image of the bleeding tourist, Angela Dickerson, will
appear on the front page of Saturday's New York Times. The photo is
available to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-GUNMAN (Washington) _ A profile of Russell Eugene
Weston, the man who went on a shooting spree at the Capitol
Building. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SCENE (Washington) _ He wore khaki pants and a green
fedora with a feather, witnesses said Friday, as any tourist might.
But he was armed with a six-shot Smith &AMP; Wesson revolver, and
almost as soon as he traded the July heat for the cool of the
Capitol, the authorities said, he opened fire. Witnesses and the
authorities described a sudden and shocking burst of shots after
Officer Jacob Chestnut asked Russell Eugene Weston Jr. to pass
through a metal detector, like every other visitor. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-OFFICERS (Washington) _ After 18 years in the Capitol
Police force, Jacob Chestnut was looking forward to his retirement.
But the 58-year-old officer remained so ebullient and outgoing with
tourists that one senator said he seemed like the Capitol's
official greeter. John Gibson, an eight-year veteran of the force,
worked in the plainclothes division, assigned to guard Rep. Tom
DeLay of Texas, the third-ranking member of the House Republican
leadership. Friday, both men gave their lives to stop a gunman. By
Alison Mitchell. (Replaces CAPITOL-VICTIMS slug.)
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SECURITY (Washington) _ History of the security measures
and violence at the Capitol building, with perhaps the most
notorious being the incident involving Puerto Rican nationals.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO _ A chronology of violence in the
Capitol and security measures taken in the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
