<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2514 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVEY-ANIMATION-LADN     07-24 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVEY-ANIMATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASPER, RICHIE RICH AIM FOR VIDEO HITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Harvey Entertainment Co., best known as home to
Casper the Friendly Ghost, has announced aggressive expansion plans
into the direct-to-video market.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey unveiled plans Friday to release a dozen live-action
titles starting next year through 2001 based on its characters such
as Casper, Richie Rich, Baby Huey, Wendy, Little Audrey and Hot
Stuff. It also plans to develop one new television show per year.
</P>
<P>
   To finance the projects, it plans to seek funds through
distribution deals, banks and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement underscores the growing appeal of producing
direct-to-video versions of easy-to-recognize properties for
families, a trend spurred by Walt Disney Co.'s successful sequels
to ``Aladdin'' and ``Beauty and the Beast.'' Direct-to-video
production and promotion costs usually don't top $15 million, while
the average movie's tab went past $75 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's first direct-to-video title, ``Casper, A Spirited
Beginning,'' sold more than 5 million copies through 20th Century
Fox. Two more Harvey titles will hit shelves this fall with Warner
handling ``Richie Rich's Christmas Wish'' and Fox distributing
``Casper Meets Wendy.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-24-98 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
