<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE DONALD TURNS TASTEFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 25:
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the Trump Plaza casino in Atlantic City,
N.J., stands a handsome three-story home owned by a widow named
Vera Coking. She wants to keep it, rather than have it torn down to
provide a parking lot for limousines.
</P>
<P>
   This week she won her case, as a judge in New Jersey blocked a
state authority's effort to condemn the property and turn it over
to the Trump organization. The judge noted that the casino would be
under no obligation to use the land for trees and parking, as
promised, but could use it to expand the casino. An appeal is
possible, but for now, Mrs. Coking has prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Donald Trump tell it, his effort to take over the
property is pure civic duty: ``Everybody coming into Atlantic City
sees that property and it's not fair to Atlantic City and the
people,'' he told an ABC interviewer. ``They're staring at this
terrible house instead of staring at beautiful fountains and
beautiful other things that would be good.'' Such as, we presume,
parked limos.
</P>
</TEXT>
