<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS REPELS ROOKIE'S BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Dean Wells remembers Draft Day '98 with the
emotion most people reserve for birthdays and anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
   April 18 was the day the Seahawks used their first-round draft
choice to select middle linebacker Anthony Simmons, a player who is
supposed to take the position Wells has worked so hard to earn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously when you're the starting middle linebacker and your
team uses the 15th pick overall to draft a middle linebacker,
you're kind of like, `Wow,' '' Wells said Friday. ``It makes you
realize the NFL is a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells vs. Simmons was supposed to be the hottest battle of what
has been a very hot training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons has displayed the talents that first attracted the
Seahawks _ startling speed; an explosive burst; a knack for making
plays all over the field.
</P>
<P>
   But, so far, it is Wells who has been taking care of business
during the team's first week at Eastern Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, to be very honest, Dean Wells is having an
excellent camp,'' said Jim Johnson, the Seahawks' new linebackers
coach and a 12-year NFL assistant whose last stint was as defensive
coordinator of the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like the way Dean is playing and, right now, he's
still the No. 1 guy,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells has been the starter since 1995. He led the club in
tackles with 107 the following season and finished third with 92
last year despite the fact that Wells is replaced by an extra
cornerback in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Simmons was a challenge, and the coaches were
eager to see how Wells would react.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dean Wells has gotten a lot better, a lot better,'' coach
Dennis Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Johnson what he likes best about Wells and the answer is
immediate: ``He's a smart linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart enough to realize why Simmons was the team's top draft
pick and outside linebacker DeShone Myles was added in the fourth
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the last year of my contract. We need depth at
linebacker. We need guys who can run and play on special teams,''
Wells said. ``So while you might be a little ticked off about it at
first, you realize it's probably a smart decision on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Simmons doesn't say a lot. He is the epitome of
that old Chuck Knox platitude: Your actions speak so loud, there's
no need to hear what you say.
</P>
<P>
   A bit undersized for a middle linebacker at 6-foot-1, 230
pounds, Simmons has grown weary of questions about whether outside
linebacker might be his natural position.
</P>
<P>
   ``My natural position is just on the field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no pressure on Simmons to be something he's not ready
to be. He can make an immediate impact on special teams, help out
in the nickel defense and be spotted in the new three-man line that
Johnson brought with him from Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a plus for me because I can take my time, relax
and just learn the system,'' Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, will change. Simmons was expected to become the
starter since the day the Seahawks drafted him, and Wells is
expected to assist by helping Simmons learn how to play the
position at this level and also by playing the position until the
rookie is ready.
</P>
<P>
   Lay this scenario in front of Wells and he laughs before
offering, ``Sure, whenever Anthony has a question I'm going to do
whatever I can to help him out. My primary goal is, I want to go to
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells laughs again before adding, ``I want to be the starter on
that team, but the bottom line is, I really want to go to the
playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
