<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-SCENE-2NDLD-W     07-24 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SCENE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNFIRE SEEMED TO COME OUT OF NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: SUBS for refinements and to add more details.)  (See CAPITOL-SHOOTING-RDP, CAPITOL-OFFICERS, CAPITOL-TOURIST,
CAPITOL-GUNMAN, CAPITOL-VIOLENCE-CHRONO) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He wore khaki pants and a green fedora with a
feather, witnesses said, as any tourist might. But he was armed
with a six-shot Smith &AMP; Wesson revolver, and almost as soon as he
traded the July heat for the cool of the Capitol, the authorities
said, he opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses and the authorities described a sudden and shocking
burst of shots, after Officer Jacob Chestnut of the Capitol Police
force asked Russell Euguene Weston Jr. to pass through a metal
detector, like every other visitor.
</P>
<P>
   As tourists stampeded, Weston left Chestnut mortally wounded on
the floor, the authorities said. His path into the Capitol blocked
by other officers, they said, Weston turned left toward a door
marked private that opens onto the ``rabbit warren,'' as insiders
call the maze of offices belonging to Representative Tom DeLay of
Texas, the majority whip.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the door, Special Agent John Gibson was shouting at staff
members to hit the floor. Witnesses and the authorities offered
conflicting versions of what came next. What is clear, according to
both, is that Gibson and Weston traded shots that cut each other
down, but not before Weston reached an office in DeLay's extensive
suite.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later some 10 officers surrounded Weston, their guns
trained at his head, said two of DeLay's aides. The office carpet
was soaked in blood.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in the echoing marble hallways of the Capitol's first
floor, the visitors' blend of boredom, curiosity and awe had turned
to bedlam as shell casings scattered across the stone floor and
officers shouted to get out, get out. In the fusillade, one
bystander, Angela Dickerson, had been wounded in the face and
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Some people took refuge behind columns; others crouched where
they stood; still others ran through the elegant hallways, scooping
children into their arms.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Beamish, a 69-year-old tourist from England, said that he
bent over a wounded police officer, feeling for a pulse as the
officer muttered words he could not make out.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had had the presence of mind to summon Sen. Bill Frist
of Tennessee off the floor of the Senate. The senator, a heart
surgeon, checked the pulse of one of the wounded, then helped
resuscitate Weston and rode with him to the hospital.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was a lazy July afternoon, and Capitol Hill, like the rest of
Washington, was easing into the weekend. The last vote had been
taken in the House chamber. Although Congress was still in session,
with some members addressing cameras in the emptying galleries,
many representatives had already streamed down the broad, steep
steps into the sunshine and their waiting cars.
</P>
<P>
   In DeLay's office, some 50 members had gathered to celebrate the
passage of health care legislation with champagne brought by Rep.
Mark Foley of Florida. Across the hallway, Rep. John Boehner,
another member of the House leadership, was in his hideaway office
with about eight staff members performing a ritual that marks the
approaching weekend in official Washington the way margaritas might
in the rest of the country: They were discussing what was likely to
be debated on the Sunday television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at about 3:40, the gunfire and the screaming started.
Members of Boehner's staff called the Capitol police immediately
and were told to lock their door and stay put. In DeLay's suite,
some people dived under their desks or ran to the back of their
offices. Staff members gathered with the congressman and said a
prayer. Many of the aides would later credit Gibson with saving
their lives. Tearful congressmen paid the same tribute to both
slain officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We passed them multiple times during a day,'' Rep. Bill Thomas
said later, his voice breaking. ``And you exchange _ you know, `How
are you?' You don't expect an answer. And they're there every day.
And no one expects this to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tourists and staff members heard just three or four shots;
others heard 20 reverberating through the halls. Some heard two
bursts of gunfire, others a long shot followed by two bursts.
Officers, their weapons drawn, pushed tourists to the ground to
protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Brown, who was working in the small gift shop run by the
Capitol Historical Society, said that the first thing he thought to
do was to duck. ``There was a guy running, just shooting at anybody
he could hit,'' Brown said. ``When I looked up, I saw the officer
with a hole in his chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Ottotta, a radio technician from Rockford, Ill., was
touring the Capitol with his wife, three sons and mother-in-law
when he heard a sound that he thought was an exhibit crashing to
the floor. He lost track of his family in the chaos, glimpsing one
son as he darted off, leaping down stairs into the crowd. He found
all of them safe later.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Emmerick, of Evergreen, Colo., was already at an exit when
he heard the shots. He looked up to see the crowd racing toward
him. ``They were running toward me, screaming,'' he said. ``Women
and kids. Two adults were crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, unaware of the pandemonium, April Adams of Atlanta, was
entering the Capitol for a tour when she looked ahead and saw a
flock of children, age 5 or 6 come flying out the building. The
children were screaming, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Judson Threlkeld, with his wife, Rachel, was touring the crypt,
a vaulted space on the first floor beneath the Great Rotunda. Four
years ago, he was at the southwest gate of the White House when he
heard what sounded like fireworks; he learned only later that a man
had opened fire on the building. This time, on hearing a bang, his
wife dropped to the floor, and he lay on top of her.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Cleary, the chief legislative aide to Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., was giving a tour of the Capitol to a group of
children. Among them was an 11-year-old girl from Belfast, Northern
Ireland, who was visiting the United States as part of a program to
take Irish children away from violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to isolate her from this kind of thing, not
letting her watch the news,'' Ms. Cleary said, ``and then this
happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
