u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-N     07-24 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEED CEDING WIDOW'S HOUSE TO SUSPECTS IS FOUND, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Utah, Calif., Fla., Nev.) (jw) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police investigating the disappearance of Irene
Silverman discovered a notarized deed Friday transferring ownership
of Mrs. Silverman's East Side town house for a fraction of its
value to a corporation registered in the names of the prime
suspects in the case, according to law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   The deed, police said, was found in a large gym bag belonging to
Sante Kimes and her son, Kenneth. The bag also contained a
.22-caliber handgun, a set of plastic handcuffs and an array of
passports and driver's licenses, as well as other financial
documents, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
findings supported their suspicion that the Kimeses were planning
to defraud Mrs. Silverman of her East 65th Street town house. They
said the papers could help them establish a motive if they decide
to charge them with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators say they have no forensic evidence
linking the Kimeses to Mrs. Silverman's disappearance and have not
found her body, they believe she is dead and have considered the
Kimeses suspects since she was reported missing on July 5.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said that the two suspects checked the bag
with a bellhop at the Plaza Hotel before their arrest on July 5 on
a warrant relating to a bad check in Utah. The police obtained a
subpoena for the bag after it was picked up at the Plaza by
Lawrence Frost, a private detective working for the Kimeses'
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Two law enforcement officials who examined the contents of the
bag, and spoke on condition of anonymity, said it contained a trove
of documents and personal items that could help detectives paint a
more complete portrait of the Kimeses' activities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to documents related to the sale of Mrs. Silverman's
home, the bag contained a rental agreement for a storage room in
California, two Florida driver's license in Kenneth Kimes' name,
Sante Kimes' birth certificate and numerous pieces of
identification in several names.
</P>
<P>
   According to three people who reviewed the contents of the bag,
the deed transfers Mrs. Silverman's home to the Trans Atlantic
Corp. for $390,000, less than 10 percent of its market value.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they had found other documents in the last
few weeks indicating that the Kimeses had set up Trans Atlantic and
used it in several financial deals.
</P>
<P>
   But they also said that the bag did not contain any items that
appeared to be evidence of Mrs. Silverman's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to lead them to the body,'' one person familiar
with its contents said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives in New York and California are intrigued, however, by
the .22-caliber handgun and plan to conduct ballistics tests on
whether it was involved in the slaying of David Kazdin, a former
business partner of the Kimeses.
</P>
<P>
   Kazdin's body was found on March 14 in a garbage bin in Venice,
Calif., with a single .22-caliber gunshot wound in the head. The
Los Angeles police have called the Kimeses suspects in the killing,
saying that they used Kazdin's name and property in Las Vegas to
obtain a fraudulent $280,000 loan.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Muniz, Ms. Kimes' lawyer, said the Kimeses told him they
had stored a bag at the Plaza Hotel and asked him to retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz said the private investigator working for him picked up
the bag on Thursday and held it overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz added that the Kimeses had steadfastly said that they knew
nothing about Mrs. Silverman's disappearance, Kazdin's death or the
1996 disappearance of a bank auditor in the Bahamas while he was
reviewing some of their offshore accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also want to question the Kimeses in those other
disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They categorically deny any wrongdoing, and there's nothing in
the bags that will change any of that,'' Muniz said.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Sachs, Kenneth Kimes' lawyer, said prosecutors were informed
of the bag's existence early Friday. Sachs said no items were
removed from the bag. Officials at the Manhattan District
Attorney's office said they had no objection to the defense
lawyers' holding the bag overnight.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with prosecutors and State Supreme Court Justice
Herbert Adlerberg, the two lawyers delivered the bag at 7:15 p.m.
Friday to the Manhattan District Attorney's office, where it was
inventoried.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said he expected to challenge the admissibility of some of
the items in court next week.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure of the bag came as the Manhattan District Attorney's
office called in a dozen witnesses to determine whether they could
identify Kimes and his mother in a lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they hoped to charge the Kimeses with a crime
before Aug. 6, when they might otherwise be extradited to Utah to
face possible charges for passing a bad check.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hammer, a real estate agent on the Upper East Side, said
that prosecutors asked him to choose Kenneth Kimes out of a lineup.
Hammer said that Kimes, 23, came into his office in late June and
identified himself as a businessman from West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes told him he was interested in renting a corporate
apartment at 3 E. 65th St., which the real estate agent said is
across the street from Mrs. Silverman's town house.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said his company performed a credit check and discovered
that Kimes was using the name of a West Palm Beach businessman
without the man's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman called up and said, `Hey, my husband's in the
hospital, he's not renting any apartment in New York,' '' Hammer
said. ``We knew it was phony.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said he correctly picked Kimes out of a lineup.
</P>
<P>
   A notary public whom Kimes reportedly asked to notarize
documents regarding the sale of Mrs. Silverman's house was also
seen leaving the District Attorney's office Friday afternoon but
declined to speak with reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
