<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2544 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SHOOTING-1ST     07-24 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN TERRORIZES CAPITOL, KILLS 2 OFFICERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (updates throughout) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lone gunman with a history of threats against the
government stormed into the U.S. Capitol Friday, igniting a gun
battle that killed two police officers and came to a bloody end
inside the offices of House Majority Whip Tom DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran Texas lawmaker escaped unharmed after herding his
staff into his office and bolting an oak door against the fierce
gunfire that shattered a routine afternoon at the nation's capital
and sent hundreds of tourists fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's bodyguard, Capitol police officer John Gibson, who
rushed to stop the gunman as he burst into the Sugar Land
Republican's suite, was killed. Police officer Jacob Chestnut, who
first attempted to stop the assailant when he walked past metal
detectors at an east-side door of the Capitol, also was slain.
</P>
<P>
   A tourist, Angela Dickerson, 24, was shot in the face and
shoulder before the gunman was critically wounded by police.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman was identified as Russell E. Weston, 41, a native of
Valmeyer, Ill., living in Montana who was known to the Secret
Service for making threats against the president and the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   He had parked his pickup a few blocks from the Capitol and armed
himself with a .38-caliber handgun, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, hit in the stomach and legs, underwent surgery and was
in stable condition late Friday at D.C. General Hospital. Dickerson
was in stable condition at George Washington University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, indeed, a sad day for the United States Capitol
Police, the United States Congress and the nation as a whole,''
said a somber Sgt. Dan Nichols, the Capitol Police spokesman who
announced the officers' deaths to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol flags were placed at half-staff and parts of the
building will be closed Saturday while police investigate.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who was hustled out of the Capitol and onto an airplane
bound for Houston, said in a statement, ``I cannot express the
depth of my sorrow for this loss.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, No. 3 in the Republican leadership, did not appear to be
a target of the assault, but the suite of first-floor offices he
occupies are closest to the entryway where the shootout began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he (Weston) chose a route that he thought was open
to him because other routes were closed,'' said Rep. Bill Thomas,
R-Calif., chairman of the House committee that oversees the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of Gibson and Chestnut were the first in the Capitol
building, which has been a terrorist target in the past but remains
an open symbol of the nation's democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers who were killed, and those who apprehended the
gunman, are true heroes of democracy, and every American owes them
a deep debt of gratitude. They gave their lives to protect the
lives of hundreds of tourists, staff and members of Congress,''
said House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, taking a brief respite at Camp David, called Gingrich
to offer assistance. The president received briefings throughout
the afternoon. Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, said there had
been a slight upgrade in security around the White House after the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary and I were deeply disturbed to hear of the shootings
this afternoon at the United States Capitol,'' Clinton said in a
statement. ``The Capitol is the people's house, a place where
visitors and workers should not have to fear violence.'' Clinton
will make another statement today.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's motive remained unclear but the shootout was being
investigated by Capitol Police, D.C. Metropolitan Police, the FBI,
the Secret Service and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
Charges against him were pending.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Herald reported that Weston's father said in an
interview that his son believed the government had planted
landmines on his Montana property.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives had just completed its work for the
day, passing a Republican version of a bill to give patients more
rights in managed health care operations. Most members were heading
home.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of members, including Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Texas,
remained on the floor to participate in special orders, the time of
day in which any member can speak on any subject.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols reported that at 3:40 p.m., EDT, a gunman entered the
Document Door, the first floor public entrance in the middle of the
Capitol on the east side that faces the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses reported hearing a series of sharp reports as Weston
forced his way past metal detectors and opened fire on guards who
attempted to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists caught in the gunbattle fled for safety and fell atop
children to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, an 18-year veteran and father of three children, was
the first officer to be shot, suffering head wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, also wounded, stumbled into a hallway 10 feet away and
opened a private door, an unmarked side entrance to the dozen or so
tiny offices that comprise DeLay's Whip operation, said Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, an eight-year veteran and the father of three, usually
sat at a desk just inside the door. Gibson and Weston engaged in a
furious gunbattle less than 10 feet apart.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gibson and Weston fell wounded in the hallway inside
DeLay's offices. Gibson died after a helicopter ride to the
hospital. Weston underwent four hours of surgery and was expected
to recover, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, a Tennessee Republican and a heart surgeon,
rushed from his office to the shooting scene where he helped with
resuscitation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   When the gunfight started, tourist Linda Addotta was seated on a
bench just inside the Capitol with her youngest son, Jacob, leaning
against her napping. Her husband and two other children were
standing nearby. She threw Jacob under a table and lay atop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't look up. You could hear the guns going off. It was
like a nightmare,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a guy just running, just shooting at anybody he
could hit,'' said Justin Brown, an employee in a Capitol gift shop.
``The first thing I thought was, `Duck!'''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists fled down the massive steps that adorn the west and
east front as word of the shooting spread. Police huddled tourists
into hallways and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Officers locked all the doors leading into the House floor and
the House gallery, with members and tourists trapped inside, for
more than an hour after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a fault of security. It was an individual who was
determined to blast his way into the Capitol,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
