<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-24 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2547 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON     07-24 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUDEN'S FIRST LESSON: IT'S A TEAM GAME 
BY C.W. NEVIUS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No sooner had Jon Gruden become head coach of the Raiders than
he laid down the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called us together,'' said offensive lineman Lincoln
Kennedy, ``and he said there was a golf outing _ and it was
mandatory.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `How are you going to make golf mandatory?''' Kennedy
said. ``I mean, I had never picked up a golf club in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   No knock on Kennedy, who may be the team's most easy-going and
approachable player, but doesn't that summarize the mind-set of
last year's Raiders perfectly? They couldn't even agree to play a
free round of golf together.
</P>
<P>
   Which was exactly Gruden's point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to play together,'' Gruden said this week in Napa
as camp opened. ``That's the most important thing this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruden is working the theme hard. After playing in Kennedy's
foursome and offering up a huge ration of abuse to the big tackle,
he scheduled a second mandatory outing in a sport Kennedy knew he
could do _ bowling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen some of these guys,'' Gruden said. ``They
didn't exactly have bowling shoes to fit all of us. And Lincoln
looked like Twinkletoes out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah?'' said Kennedy happily. ``I don't know what I scored,
but I know I doubled his score. I'm not saying I'm ready for the
PBA, but I can play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems there's always a new tone at Raider camp, but you have
to admit that this is one we haven't seen before _ family fun.
Gruden, sometimes with his cap turned backwards, is all over the
field, barking out orders, getting into the drills himself and
working the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, our coaches have been sort of like father
figures,'' Kennedy said. ``He's almost like a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe not an older brother, either. At some point, everyone
wants to do the math. How many players are older than Gruden, who
is 34?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (reserve quarterback) Wade Wilson is (he's 39) because
I remind him of it every night. '' said Gruden, who also is younger
than defensive back Albert Lewis (37). ``People say you look so
young. What do you expect, for my hair to turn gray and fall out?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it has happened, you know, Jon.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you'd have to say right now _ although a ball has yet to
be kicked in anger _ that Gruden provides just the dose of
enthusiasm and go-gettum that the Raiders needed. There's lots of
talk about whether the veterans will listen to a young buck like
Gruden, but although he may look like the quarterback of his
fraternity's flag football team, he's already shaking things up.
</P>
<P>
   The move of Lewis from cornerback to free safety, for example,
is overdue. Lewis, who can still pulverize receivers, was willing
to make the switch last year, but he wanted to do it right from the
start of camp, not after the season began. Gruden came in and
announced the change before Lewis officially reported. Is that
early enough for you, Albert?
</P>
<P>
   Gruden also has just the right mix of smarts and sass to deal
not only with the media but with the looming shadow of Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I interviewed,'' Gruden said, ``Al Davis told me that if
things get tough, `you can always blame me.' I remembered that
because I take pretty careful notes.''
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure Davis appreciated Gruden's savvy, as well as his
attitude. And, although the feeling is mutual, Gruden isn't just
listening to Davis because he's kissing up to the team owner.
Gruden has bounced around the league, but no one will ever say he
wasn't paying attention at every stop. He's a sponge for ideas.
</P>
<P>
   49ers offensive line coach Bobb McKittrick tells the story of
finding Gruden sitting in the hall outside his line meetings,
taking notes like crazy. Even now, Gruden calls McKittrick ``the
best coach in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruden said he also has observed Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren,
49ers coach George Seifert and Philadelphia's Ray Rhodes, who had
so much faith in the kid that he made him offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The experience with the Eagles was invaluable, but it doesn't
take an offensive guru to figure out that he has much more talent
here. In Philadelphia, for example, Gruden was crafting a passing
game out of Bobby Hoying at quarterback and an aging Irving Fryar
at wide receiver. He must have run his finger down the Raiders'
roster and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a pure pocket passer in Jeff George,'' he said. ``We
have blinding speed at the split ends, our tight end is a helluva
talent, and we know what Tim Brown can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of those players were here last year, and the
team was 4-12. By the end, this was a fractured group with everyone
looking out for himself. As cynics said, there is no ``I'' in team,
but there is one in Tim Brown. So what is the difference going to
be?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play in concert with each other,'' Gruden said.
``We might tell someone you are going to have to clear out for Tim
Brown on this play, and you are going to have to bust it because
later it is going to be your play.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea in theory, everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business,'' said Kennedy, ``there is no place for
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, it seemed like there was last year _ the Raiders' locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
